<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Vietnam-Rats </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
More than 47 million rats killed this year
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HANOI, Vietnam (AP) _ More than 47 million rats have been killed
in Vietnam this year in a campaign to keep the voracious rodents
from destroying the rice crop, a government official said Tuesday.
	   Dam Quoc Tru, deputy director of the Agriculture Ministry's
Plants Protection Department, said rats have damaged nearly 230,000
hectares (568,000 acres) of paddy fields with more than 12,000
hectares (30,000 acres) seriously damaged.
	   Tru said there was no immediate financial estimate of the damage
for the first five months of 1998, but last year rats damaged
375,000 hectares (926,000 acres) of paddy fields and rice worth
dlrs 6 million.
	   Tru said the damage caused by rats increased dramatically over
the past three years due to the shrinking population of traditional
predators, cats and snakes, which are being served at restaurants
or are sold to China for traditional medicine.
	   Earlier this year, Prime Minister Phan Van Khai ordered
restaurants serving cat meat to close and banned the export of cats
and snakes.
	   In rural areas home to 80 percent of Vietnam's 76 million
people, local governments have launched a campaign urging villagers
to kill rats. In some places, one rat tail fetches a reward of 500
dong (4 cents).
	   Tru said in some provinces, villagers were given 30,000 dong
(dlrs 2.30) per family to raise cats.
	   However, the anti-rat fight has taken a toll. Reports have
emerged of people being killed by stepping on electric traps and of
children dying from eating cakes or candies laced with rat poison.
	   Last year, some 55 million rats were killed by trapping, hunting
or poisoning. 	   
</TEXT>
