w2306 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Nigeria-Abacha-WorldR 1stLd-Wrtitethru   06-09 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Abacha-World Reax, 1st Ld-Wrtitethru,0738 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dissident: Abacha's death `incredible opportunity' for Nigeria
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with quotes from son of executed Nigeria playwright,
Commonwealth minister, Clinton spokesman. &QL; 
 &UR; With Nigeria-Abacha &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo JRL111 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   Lagos, Nigeria (AP) _ Nigerian dictator Gen. Sani Abacha's death
Monday is an ``incredible opportunity'' for the West African nation
to return to democracy, a leading dissident in exile said _ a hope
echoed by Western powers.
	   Playwright Wole Soyinka, winner of the 1986 Nobel Prize in
literature and an outspoken opponent of military rule, fled Nigeria
in 1994. Abacha's military regime charged him with treason, a crime
punishable by death.
	   Speaking to reporters in Jerusalem, where he was lecturing at
Hebrew University, Soyinka called Abacha's death ``an opportunity
for Nigerian civic society, an opportunity for the Nigerian
military, and an opportunity for the international community.''
	   In a predawn ceremony Tuesday, Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakara, a
major general in the army and defense chief of staff, was sworn in
as Abacha's successor.
	   Even while Abacha was still in power, Nigerians were struggling
to restore democracy, Soyinka said.
	   ``The people were sick of military dictatorship,'' he said. ``So
it's up to the military to recognize this _ and up to the
international community to say that we're sick and tired of the
degeneration of a potentially great society.''
	   The United States, Britain and New Zealand urged a quick
transition to democracy in Nigeria, a former British colony.
	   ``We hope that following the death of Gen. Abacha, there will be
an opening for a stable transition to an early return to democracy,
with the election of an accountable civilian government which will
restore and respect human rights,'' Britain's Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook said in a statement.
	   White House spokesman Mike McCurry said the U.S. government
``acknowledges the death'' of Abacha, and is interested in seeing
his successor embark upon democratic rule.
	   ``There have been freely and democratically elected figures
throughout Africa that were formerly involved in the military,''
McCurry said. ``Our hope, among others, would be, at this moment of
transition, that an accountable civilian government ... will emerge
from what has been a very horrific episode in which basic
fundamental rights have been suspended.''
	   The 53-nation Commonwealth of Britain and its former colonies
suspended Nigeria after it executed playwright Ken Saro-Wiwa and
eight other dissidents in 1995.
	   Nigerian Chief Emeka Anyaoku, head of the Commonwealth, told BBC
TV: ``The Commonwealth would hope and would expect that the
Nigerians will decide to go back to the way of democracy and in so
doing will gain re-admission to the Commonwealth.''
	   The international community should now press for elections in
Nigeria this year, said New Zealand's foreign minister, Don
McKinnon.
	   ``Nigeria was one of the leaders in democracy in Africa back in
the 1960s and there's no reason why they can't return to it. But
it's very much up to (those there) to do something about it,'' he
said.
	   Former U.S. President Jimmy Carter, who had met with Abacha to
persuade him to relinquish power peacefully, said he hoped ``that
the new head of state will move toward a democratic transition of
government in a timely manner.''
	   Nigeria's next leader could hardly be any worse than Abacha,
Saro-Wiwa's son said in Britain.
	   ``In Nigeria, the thinking has always been that every successive
dictator is worse than the previous one, so one hopes that we don't
get another dictator because he will have quite a record to better
Abacha's appalling record,'' said Ken Wiwa.
	   Soyinka urged the military to release all political prisoners,
including Moshood Abiola, the apparent winner of Nigeria's aborted
1993 presidential elections, and name Abiola head of a transitional
national unity government.
	   ``There's only one choice for Nigeria _ that's a democratic
option,'' he said. ``And the structure is there. The
president-elect is waiting.''
	   Until that happens, the international community should increase
pressure and sanctions on the military government, Soyinka said.
	   ``They have an incredible opportunity to bow out gracefully,''
Soyinka said of the military. ``Let us pray that they take it.''
</TEXT>
