r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Baseball-USRou 1stAdd   06-09 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-US Roundup, 1st Add,0539 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTA: Darrin Winston (2-2).
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Rangers 3, Rockies 1 &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   In Denver, Domingo Cedeno homered and drove in all three Texas
runs, and Aaron Sele became the majors' second nine-game winner.
	   Sele (9-3) went eight innings, limiting Colorado to five hits
and a first-inning run, to join Atlanta's Greg Maddux with nine
victories. He struck out six and walked four.
	   John Wetteland pitched the ninth for his 17th save in 18
chances. The Rangers have won seven of their last 10, while the
Rockies have lost four straight.
 &UR; Marlins 4, Blue Jays 3, 17 innings &QC; 
	   In Miami, Todd Zeile singled home the winning run to cap a
bizarre 17th inning, and the Florida Marlins snapped an 11-game
losing streak.
	   Toronto appeared to take a 4-3 lead in the 17th when Felipe
Crespo scored from first on a two-out double by Carlos Delgado. But
the Marlins argued that Crespo had missed third base, and plate
umpire Tom Hallion upheld the appeal and ruled him out, ending the
inning.
	   Television replays showed that Crespo appeared to touch the
inside of third base on his way to the plate.
	   The game was the longest in the Marlins' six-year history, and
matched the longest in Toronto's 22-year history.
 &UR; Padres 4, Reds 2 &QC; 
	   In San Diego, Joey Hamilton allowed two runs in eight innings to
break his career-worst six-game losing streak.
	   The Padres broke a 2-2 tie in the seventh inning by scoring two
runs on two singles, two walks, a sacrifice fly by Ken Caminiti and
Wally Joyner's bases-loaded RBI groundout.
	   It was enough to give Hamilton (4-7) his first victory since May
2.
 &UR; Athletics 7, Dodgers 3 &QC; 
	   In Los Angeles, Blake Stein, making just his sixth big-league
start, allowed five hits and struck out 10 in 8 1-3 innings as
Oakland beat the Dodgers.
	   Stein (2-3) gave way to reliever Billy Taylor after giving up a
two-run homer to Eric Karros in the ninth.
	   Jason Giambi hit a three-run homer in the seventh off Ramon
Martinez (7-3) to put Oakland up 7-1.
 &UR; Giants 4, Mariners 3 &QC; 
	   In San Francisco, Danny Darwin kept the majors' best home
run-hitting team in the yard and Rich Aurilia homered in his first
at-bat against Randy Johnson as the Giants won their 10th straight.
	   It is San Francisco's longest winning streak since an 11-game
run in 1991. Seattle lost for the eighth time in nine interleague
games at NL parks.
	   The 42-year-old Darwin (6-3) allowed three runs in 6 1-3 innings
against the slumping Mariners, who fell to a season-low nine-games
below .500 (27-36). Johnson (5-5) allowed four runs and six hits in
seven innings. He struck out 10 and walked three.
 &UR; Padres 4, Reds 2
	   In San Diego, Joey Hamilton allowed two runs in eight innings to
break his career-worst six-game losing streak as the Padres beat
the Cincinnati Reds 4-2.
	   The Padres broke a 2-2 tie in the seventh inning by scoring two
runs off Scott Sullivan (1-3) on two singles, two walks, a
sacrifice fly by Ken Caminiti and Wally Joyner's bases-loaded RBI
groundout.
	   It was enough to give Hamilton (4-7) his first win since May 2.
He allowed seven hits, three walks and struck out five. Trevor
Hoffman pitched the ninth for his 17th save.
	    &UR; END
</TEXT>
