r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Singapore-Taiwan-Viru     06-09 0230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Taiwan-Virus </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore alerting doctors to watch for viral infection
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Singapore announced Tuesday that it is alerting
medical practitioners in the health conscious city-state to watch
out for possible cases of a virus that has infected thousands of
children in Taiwan.
	   A joint statement from the Ministry of Health and Ministry of
Environment said that Singapore's ``surveillance system has shown
no unusual occurrence'' of the viral infection here, but that the
two ministries were continuing to monitor the situation closely.
	   The enterovirus 71 epidemic in Taiwan has been blamed for
afflicting about 7,500 children, of whom 29 have died.
	   Usually spread by physical contact, the virus breaks down
immunity and can leave infants susceptible to encephalitis,
meningitis, and acute inflammation of the heart muscle. Early
symptoms are similar to the flu, including fever, headache and
vomiting.
	   The two Singapore ministries said that the epidemic appears to
be confined to Taiwan, and that there was no need for travel
restrictions between the two countries.
	   But the statement added that ``people travelling to Taiwan are
advised to take simple precautions such as avoiding crowded places,
observing a high standard of personal hygiene and avoiding sharing
personal items that are likely to be contaminated.'' 	   
</TEXT>
