<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Airline Strike </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine Airlines holds emergency board meeting to discuss
</HEADLINE>
pilots' strike
 &UR; AP Photos Staffing
 &UR; By JIM GOMEZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Cash-strapped Philippine Airlines
called an emergency board meeting Tuesday to decide its response to
a crippling 4-day-old strike by most of its pilots.
	   ``They are discussing the fate of our airline,'' a PAL official
said.
	   The strike by the 625 members of the pilots' union has forced
the cancellation of most of the airline's domestic and
international flights.
	   Only 25 management pilots _ senior pilots who train other pilots
_ are flying a limited number of flights, said PAL senior vice
president Avelino Zapanta.
	   When those pilots tire, the airline will have to halt its
operations, he said.
	   The strike has scared off a prospective buyer, Northwest
Airlines, which was in negotiations to purchase a portion of the
financially troubled company, Zapanta said.
	   The union is protesting a new management policy of ordering
pilots to retire who have reached 20 years of service or flown
20,000 hours, regardless of age. The policy puts about 200 pilots
in danger of forced retirement, the union said.
	   The policy threatens ``the very survival our profession and our
security of tenure,'' union spokesman Capt. Florendo Umali said.
	   The airline earlier announced plans to slash its work force, cut
expenses by as much as 40 percent, and reduce flights to overcome
its financial crisis.
	   PAL says the strike is causing daily losses of 150 million to
200 million pesos (dlrs 3.8 million to 5.1 million) in lost
revenue, pushing it ``closer to the brink of insolvency.''
	   It fired all the striking pilots on Sunday, calling their action
illegal, except for a handful who had complied with an airline
order to return to work.
	   The pilots have refused to accept a separate government order to
return to work, and Zapanta said the airline would not follow a
government order to accept them back.
	   PAL said Monday it lost 8 billion pesos (dlrs 205 million) in
the last fiscal year _ three times more than the previous year.
	   Labor Secretary Cresenciano Trajano called a meeting Monday to
try to resolve the strike but the talks broke down after the two
union representatives said they had no decision-making authority.
	   PAL tried to recover from its spiraling losses with an ambitious
dlrs 4 billion modernization program in 1996, ordering 36 new
aircraft. But Asia's currency crisis sharply reduced passenger
numbers and bloated the airline's debt in local currency terms,
forcing it to delay many of the orders.
	   PAL, Asia's first airline, is controlled by Chinese Filipino
tycoon Lucio Tan. It had been completely owned by the Philippine
government from 1941 until it was partly sold in 1992. 	   
</TEXT>
