r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Eritrea-Ethiopia 1stLd   06-09 0436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Eritrea-Ethiopia, 1st Ld,0435 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ethiopia threatens more military action, Eritrea urges talks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS lede and ADDS Eritrean president's quotes, grafs
8-10. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos ASM101-104 of June 8 &QL; 
 &UR; By KARIN DAVIES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) _ With Ethiopia threatening to attack
Eritrea again unless its neighbor withdraws from disputed
territory, the U.S. government made plans to evacuate Americans,
Germans, Egyptians and some Ethiopians on Tuesday.
	   The American planes would carry at least another 120 of U.S.
citizens.
	   The Eritrean government on Monday called for direct talks
between the two Horn of Africa countries in the presence of
high-level mediators ``to ensure a speedy resolution of the
crisis.''
	   President Isaias Afwerki's spokesman said Ethiopia had
effectively declared war on Eritrea and was using the threat of
renewed air strikes to blockade air and seaports.
	   ``They won't compromise,'' Yemane Gebremeskel said. ``These are
not the actions of a nation that wants peace.''
	   In Addis Ababa, Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi accused
the Eritreans of ``a pattern of prevarication, a pattern of trying
to draw out the process and consolidate their hold on our
territory.
	   ``If that's the case _ and it appears to be the case _ then the
opportunities for resolving this problem peacefully could be fast
disappearing,'' he told The Associated Press.
	   Eritrea claims its forces are within internationally recognized
borders drawn by Italy in the late 19th century. Eritrea, an
Italian colony from 1885 to 1941, was annexed in 1962 by Ethiopia,
against whom it later fought a 30-year war for independence.
	   With per-capita annual incomes of less than dlrs 300 a year,
Ethiopia and Eritrea are among the world's poorest countries.
	   Isaias indicated pride was an obstacle to resolving the
conflict, underscoring diplomats' concerns that the alliance
between Isaias' Eritrean People's Liberation Front and Meles'
Tigray People's Liberation Front to end 17 years of military rule
in Ethiopia in 1991 has soured.
	   ``We might be more concerned about pride, integrity, respect and
all that kind of thing _ trust, confidence. When you lose that it
becomes a big problem for us in this region _ it's not always money
and resources,'' Isaias said late Monday.
	   ``If we can find a lasting, sustainable solution, then we will
have to think of reversing the process, building confidence again
and trying to work together but it will take time and it will take
a lot of effort, in my opinion,'' he said.
 &UR; African leaders, graf 10 pvs 	   
</TEXT>
