<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Exodus </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: More than 150,000 fled Indonesian riots
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING to restore slug designator &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: SUBSTITUTES for item slugged BC-Indonesia promised on 0000 GMT
world digest

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ More than 150,000 Indonesians and
foreigners fled the country during a six-day period when riots
broke out last month, a news report said Tuesday.
	   The riots lead to the downfall of ex-President Suharto. Many of
those who fled were frightened ethnic Chinese who were targeted as
scapegoats for the worst economic crisis in 30 years.
	   Almost 1,200 people died in the violence, the worst to hit the
capital Jakarta and other cities in decades.
	   The Jakarta Post newspaper quoted Director General of
Immigration Pranowo as saying 70,837 Indonesian citizens and 81,526
foreigners left between May 14 and May 20 from airports and
seaports on the islands of Java, Bali and Sumatra.
	   The paper said many foreign airlines provided extra services to
cope with the exodus. Several multinational companies and foreign
governments arranged evacuation charter flights.
	   Violence erupted after four students were shot dead by security
forces at an anti-government rally at Jakarta's Trisakti University
on May 12.
	   It stopped after ex-president Suharto resigned on May 21, ending
a 32-year authoritarian grip on power.
	   Pranowo said 51,160 people returned in subsequent days,
including 27,616 Indonesians and 23,544 foreigners.
	   He did not say how many had returned to date.
	   Many observers fear the violence could flare again unless
rampant inflation and soaring unemployment are brought under
control.
	   Many Chinese business people have reportedly moved assets
offshore and have kept their families overseas as a precaution.
	   Justice Minister Muladi expressed concern that Indonesians of
Chinese descent were singled out by rioting mobs.
	   The ethnic Chinese community makes up only about 4 percent of
Indonesia's 202 million people, but dominates commerce and
industry. Many are Christians or Buddhists in what is the world's
most populous Muslim nation.
	   As such they have been blamed by some for the rising prices and
mass unemployment that have come with Asia's financial meltdown.
	   Muladi said hundreds of Chinese people had complained that
identity documents such as passports and citizenship papers were
burned or destroyed in the riots, in which 1,188 people are known
to have died.
	   Muladi said the documents would be replaced. He warned
bureaucrats not to take advantage of the situation by trying to
extort bribes from people needing new documents.
	   Over the weekend, President B.J. Habibie, who replaced Suharto,
called on Indonesians to end discrimination against the Chinese
minority.
	   Although many Chinese families have lived in Indonesia for
generations, some indigenous people, referred to as ``pribumi'' or
``sons of the soil,'' still regard them as outsiders. 	   
</TEXT>
