<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Flooding </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Three die in Taiwan floods
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ While much of Asia withers under a
devastating drought, torrential rains in Taiwan have lead to the
deaths of three people.
	   Up to 353 millimeters (14.12 inches) of rain have fallen in
parts of the island over the past two days, overfilling rivers and
reservoirs, the Central Weather Bureau reported. In the island's
mountainous center, rain washed rocks and mud down creeks, knocking
out at least one bridge.
	   In Pingtung county at Taiwan's southern tip, two men drowned
Monday when flood waters swept their pickup truck off the road and
into a drainage ditch. Another man also was killed Monday in
Kaohsiung county when his car aquaplaned into a road divider.
	   Damage to crops has been estimated at 640 million Taiwan dollars
(U.S. dlrs 18 million), with Yunlin county, 175 kilometers (108
miles) south of Taipei, the hardest hit. Agriculture authorities
have offered farmers subsidies of 6,000 Taiwan dollars (U.S. dlrs
242) per hectare (acre) for emergency replanting.
	   The rains preceding the summer typhoon season have been the
hardest in recent years, catching officials and flood control
systems off guard. The sogginess contrasts strongly with parched
conditions in Southeast Asia brought on by the El Nino weather
phenomenon.
	   Dozens of villages were stranded Tuesday by flood waters that
were two stories high. Supplies were brought in by boat and
helicopter.
	   Waters also inundated the construction site for the island's
second major high technology industrial park in Tainan county.
	   Forecasters said they expect the weather to dry up gradually
over the week. 	   
</TEXT>
