<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Philippines-Centennial Woes,0760 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Apathy, neglected monuments, squabbles hamper Philippine
</HEADLINE>
centennial &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo MLA105 &QL; 
 &UR; By JIM GOMEZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ A bronze mural of Philippine hero
Andres Bonifacio being erected in Manila's filthy Divisoria market
provides the only hint that the area is actually a hallowed
historic site.
	   Squalid shops stand today where Bonifacio and other nationalists
founded in 1892 the Katipunan, a secret society that led a revolt
to liberate the Philippines from 333 years of Spanish colonial
rule.
	   In place of the house where the Katipunan was born stands a
building owned by a Chinese merchant. Officials built a wall with
the mural in front of the building to memorialize the site, drawing
the owner's ire.
	   Decades of neglect have ruined many such historical landmarks,
compounding the woes of officials preparing for the country's June
12 centennial of its declaration of independence from Spain.
	   ``It's a disgrace,'' National Centennial Commission chairman
Salvador Laurel said of the destruction of many historical sites.
	   Other shrines or markers have been buried under garbage,
destroyed by vandals, thieves or termites, or encircled by
shantytowns. Historic buildings were turned into malls, warehouses,
even a noodle house.
	   The government, helped by private companies, is spending 3.5
billion pesos (dlrs 92 million) on celebrations that will include a
trade and historical exposition at the Clark Special Economic Zone,
a former U.S. air base in Pampanga province.
	   One-third of the money is being used to renovate 16 historic
shrines and construct historical markers and monuments along the
``freedom trail,'' areas where Filipinos put up resistance against
Spain.
	   President Fidel Ramos, who helped revive the nation's economy
after years of stagnancy, calls the centennial the ``main event''
of his six years in power.
	   Dignitaries from 24 countries have been invited, and Filipinos
working abroad are being urged to head home for the party, which
includes a beauty pageant, a native sports festival, musicals and
plays, a grand parade, and a centennial ball.
	   But many doubt whether multitudes will attend.
	   For one, the government has failed to aggressively promote the
fiesta abroad, said Arnaldo Bayag of the Philippine Travel Agencies
Association, a group of more than 400 tour companies. Asia's
financial crisis will also have a negative effect.
	   While Laurel hoped the centennial would unify traditionally
fractious Filipinos, squabbles have threatened to pull officials
further apart.
	   A major contractor had a widely publicized spat with Laurel that
ended with its withdrawal from the project at the former air base,
delaying construction of a 148-acre (60-hectare) historical theme
park by at least four months.
	   A major event _ a grand parade along a seaside boulevard in
Manila _ has triggered the resignations of some centennial
commission officials because Laurel chose to focus on events in
1898 and downplay subsequent history, officials said.
	   The U.S. and Japanese occupations of the Philippines and the
1986 ``people power'' revolt that ousted strongman Ferdinand Marcos
will receive little prominence. The number of floats was cut to
about 40 from more than 100, shutting out many groups, an official
said.
	   Laurel said a very long parade would bore people and be
prohibitively expensive.
	   Even the date is the subject of dispute, with some saying 1898
should not be celebrated as the country's centennial.
	   Gen. Emilio Aguinaldo, a former mayor who became the republic's
first president, declared Philippine independence from Spain on
June 12, 1898, at a house in Cavite province, south of Manila.
	   Before the Philippines could gain independence, however, the
United States acquired it after defeating Spain in the 1898
Spanish-American War. It brutally suppressed the independence
movement.
	   At least the celebration may arouse the interest of many
Filipinos with low historical awareness, said Samuel Tan, chairman
of the National Historical Institute. There will be a new national
archive, a new museum, spruced up shrines and about 100 new
monuments, many depicting lesser-known heroes.
	   The celebration also has revived such historical debates as the
proper shade of blue in the national flag and provided a chance to
correct errors in history books written from a foreign perspective,
he said.
</TEXT>
