<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar touches new 7-year high, Tokyo stocks rise
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with closing stock, mid-afternoon currency and bond
prices; ADDS trader comment in 6th graf

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar touched a new seven-year high
against the yen Tuesday in Tokyo before receding ahead of a key
meeting of the G-7 major industrialized nations. Tokyo stocks
finished sharply higher.
	   The dollar bought 140.79 yen at mid-afternoon, up 0.23 yen from
late Monday in Tokyo and above its New York level overnight of
140.71 yen. During Tokyo trading, the dollar rose as high as 141.11
yen, a level not seen since June 1991.
	   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
rose 235.46 points, or 1.52 percent, to close at 15,530.17. On
Monday, the average shed 28.72 points, or 0.19 percent.
	   The dollar slipped back below the 141-yen level amid speculation
deputy finance ministers from the Group of Seven largest economies
meeting later Tuesday in Paris may announce a joint effort to prop
up the Japanese currency.
	   A growing number of officials from the G-7 have expressed
concern over the declining yen. On Monday, German central bank
chief Hans Tietmeyer said he hopes ``the yen won't depreciate
excessively.''
	   ``Judging from Tietmeyer's remark, we can't completely rule out
the possibility of a surprise announcement from the G-7 that
expresses, for instance, concerted efforts to defend the yen,''
said Ryuichi Takami, a senior currency trader at Sanwa Bank Ltd.
	   Meanwhile, the main cause of the yen's recent weakness _ Japan's
ailing domestic economy _ remains unchanged. On Tuesday, a Japanese
government report warned that key sectors of the economy such as
employment and production would likely worsen in June.
	   And with no economic turnaround in sight, Japan's central bank
has been forced to take steps that have the effect of undermining
the yen even further.
	   To reinflate the economy, the Bank of Japan has kept interest
rates at a historic low. But that's forced investors to sell yen to
shift funds overseas in search of better returns.
	   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, stock prices rose amid optimism the
strengthening dollar will boost profits at the country's vaunted
exporters.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was up 10.32 points, or 0.86 percent, to 1,208.68.
The TOPIX closed down 3.58 points, or 0.30 percent, the day before.
	   For every yen the dollar gains in value, Toyota Motor Corp. sees
its revenues jump 10 billion yen (dlrs 71 million) and Sony Corp.
earns an additional 6 billion yen (dlrs 43 million), Japan's NHK
television said.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond rose to 1.200 percent from Monday's close of 1.145
percent, driving its price down to 112.04 yen from Monday's 112.46
yen. 	   
</TEXT>
