<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-2002 World Cup-Koreas </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Korean officials to contact northern counterpart for 2002
</HEADLINE>
World Cup

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ South Korean soccer officials said
Tuesday they have obtained government approval to discuss sharing
some matches of the 2002 World Cup finals with rival North Korea.
	   South Korea and Japan will co-host the games, but South Korea
hopes to share some of its 32 matches with North Korea to promote
peace on the peninsula.
	   Officials at the Korea Football Association said they will send
a letter to North Korea soon to arrange a meeting on the
match-sharing idea or even forming a unified Korean team for the
competition.
	   They also said the contact, if held, could take up the issue of
promoting regular sports exchanges between the two sides.
	   South Korean soccer officials needed government approval for the
move. The two Koreas are technically at war, with no peace treaty
signed at the end of the 1950-53 Korean War.
	   A high-ranking North Korean soccer official in Paris said in a
published interview Tuesday that the communist country could
consider sharing World Cup matches if such a proposal is made.
	   ``We are not in a stage to discuss details yet, but in
principle, it is very desirable to form a single team and for North
Korea to hold some games,'' Choi Pyong Joo, vice president of North
Korea's soccer association said in an interview with South Korea's
Sports Seoul newspaper.
	   Choi was in Paris attending various functions of FIFA, soccer's
world governing body, ahead of the 1998 World Cup finals.
	   In the early 1990s, the two Koreas formed single soccer and
table tennis teams for international tournaments. 	   
</TEXT>
