<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Arrest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Head of government statistics agency arrested for rigging
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The head of the government's statistics service
was arrested Tuesday on charges of helping tax-dodgers and selling
confidential data, according to news reports.
	   Yuri Yurkov, head of the State Statistics Committee, was
arrested along with an unspecified number of senior workers in
charge of data processing, the Interfax and ITAR-Tass news agencies
reported.
	   They were charged with ``systematic distortion of statistical
data on big companies which allowed them to evade taxes,'' the
reports quoted government officials as saying.
	   Tax evasion is a major problem in Russia with many big companies
and businessmen not paying. Government efforts to boost the economy
have been hobbled by a lack of revenues because of tax evasion.
	   Spokesmen for the government headquarters, Prosecutor General's
office and the Federal Security Service declined to comment on the
reports.
	   The reports said Yurkov and his alleged accomplices were accused
of manipulating economic data to hide the real output of companies
and reduce their tax liability and with selling classified
information about rival companies' performance.
	   Yurkov, who has served as the statistics agency chief since
1993, would be one of the highest-ranking Russian officials
arrested for alleged wrongdoing in recent years.
	   (vi/ren)
</TEXT>
