w2391 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SriLanka-CivilWar     06-09 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sri Lanka-Civil War,0388 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rebels claim to have repulsed attack, at least 56 dead
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ Guerrillas fighting for an ethnic
homeland in Sri Lanka said they fought off a government attack in
the north, and at least 56 fighters from both sides were killed
Tuesday in the seven-hour battle.
	   The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, in a statement faxed to
news agencies in the Indian capital from their London headquarters,
said government forces retreated, leaving behind the bodies of 30
of their soldiers, after encountering heavy rebel resistance at
Kilinochchi, 275 kilometers (170 miles) north of the Sri Lankan
capital of Colombo.
	   The Tigers said they lost 26 fighters.
	   Kilinochchi was also the scene of heavy fighting last Thursday,
with government forces attacking it and nearby Mankulam in a
two-pronged effort to capture the region's main highway from
guerrilla control.
	   In Sri Lanka, the defense ministry said Tuesday that government
troops destroyed a rebel fortification near Mankulam and advanced
north. The ministry statement made no mention of casualties.
	   The government has been battling since May 1997 to capture the
highway connecting the Jaffna Peninsula with the rest of Sri Lanka.
The army captured the 1,000-square-kilometer (400-square-mile)
peninsula in 1996 from the Tamil rebels, who had run the area like
a mini-state for five years.
	   Because the government does not control the highway, Jaffna's
half million people rely on air and sea deliveries of food and
other supplies.
	   So far, the troops have captured about two-thirds of the
highway, with another 27 kilometers (17 miles) to go. The military
admits having lost nearly 1,000 soldiers and claims to have killed
3,200 guerrillas in the highway campaign. The rebels have not given
their total casualty figures.
	   No independent assessment of the battle situation was possible
as the government bars journalists from visiting the war theater on
their own. The government also has imposed censorship on reports
about the fighting emanating from Sri Lanka.
	   The rebels want a separate homeland carved from this island off
India's southeastern tip, accusing the Sinhalese majority of
oppressing the Tamil minority. The war began in 1983 and has so far
claimed 52,000 lives.
</TEXT>
