<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bangladesh-Long March,0360 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bangladesh opposition begins long march amid tight security
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos DHA101-102 &QL; 
 &UR; By HASAN SAEED &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) _ Hundreds of thousands of Bangladeshis
began a 400-kilometer (250-mile) protest Tuesday on foot and by car
to underscore their opposition to a peace accord they say gives
away too much to southeastern hill tribes.
	   The ``long march'' protest is seen as a test of strength for
former Prime Minister Khaleda Zia's strength. Zia has campaigned
against the government of Sheikh Hasina since she lost power in
elections two years ago. In recent years, Bangladesh has been
plagued by almost daily strikes and political protests that often
erupt into violence.
	   Fearing unrest, drivers kept buses, trucks and private cars off
the roads in the capital of Dhaka and the southern city of
Chittagong. Across the country, some 50,000 police and paramilitary
troops have been put on alert, The Nation daily reported.
	   Hasina struck a peace accord in December 1997 giving autonomy to
tribes in the Chittagong Hill Tracts and ending two decades of
guerrilla war by Chakma separatists. The fighting over an area rich
in timber and minerals left more than 20,000 people dead.
	   Hasina has ``left the Chittagong Hill Tracts to the
terrorists,'' Zia said at a kickoff rally for the march in a Dhaka
sports stadium.
	   Hundreds of thousands of Zia's supporters chanted
anti-government slogans as they set off, with Zia accusing the
government of trying to block the march.
	   The government tried to disrupt the march by urging gas stations
to close, opposition activists said. Police detained at least 100
opposition activists under local laws that give authorities the
right to hold people without charge.
	   Police searched buses, trains and river boat ferries and pulled
out people they believed were planning to join the march, the
opposition said.
	   Although Hasina has promised to let the protesters reach their
destination, her supporters set up road blocks along its route,
witnesses said. It was unclear if they were acting on their own.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Bangladesh-Long March; CT:i; 
