w2400 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-France-Fashion     06-09 0190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Fashion </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Saint-Laurent turns over women's ready to wear to U.S. designer
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo PAR101 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Fashion giant Yves Saint Laurent has named American
designer Alber Elbaz, 38, to be the artistic director of his
women's ready to wear collection.
	   Elbaz will present his first ready-to-wear clothes for Yves
Saint Laurent during the 1999 fall collections, said a communique
issued Monday.
	   It was the first time Saint Laurent has named an artistic
director for one of his lines. The legendary French designer will
continue to create his haute couture clothes.
	   Many of the top fashion lines in Paris are now being designed by
foreigners, and Elbaz's nomination could put him in line to take
over should Saint Laurent, 62, step down some day.
	   In 1996, Elbaz, took over as the new creator for luxury
ready-to-wear for Guy Laroche. Until then, he had designed for
Geoffrey Beene for seven years.
	   His first collection in 1997 for Guy Laroche was a hit.
	   Born in Morocco, Elbaz is a graduate of Israel's prestigious
Shenkar College School of Fashion in Tel Aviv.
	   (parf-dgs) 	   
</TEXT>
