<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Tourists </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesia asks other governments to drop tourist travel warnings
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By HARIS SYAMAUN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Indonesia asked other governments
Tuesday to drop official warnings against tourists visiting
Indonesia in the wake of riots last month.
	   ``There is no reason to restrict tourists from visiting
Indonesia now. There is nothing to worry about,'' said Foreign
Minister Ali Alatas.
	   Alatas said neighboring Australia, a major source of foreign
tourists, had revoked an earlier tourist warning.
	   However, other countries, such as the United States and Japan,
were maintaining their warnings.
	   On June 4, the U.S. Department of State issued an advisory
warning U.S. citizens against non-essential travel to Indonesia.
	   Recently the Indonesian government said foreign tourist arrivals
had dropped dramatically following the riots, in which 1,188 people
were killed and thousands of buildings were burned or ransacked.
	   Violence erupted after four students were shot dead by security
forces at an anti-government rally at Jakarta's Trisakti University
on May 12.
	   It stopped after ex-president Suharto resigned on May 21, ending
a 32-year authoritarian grip on power.
	   Indonesia is battling its worst economic crisis in decades and
some fear violence could return unless rampant inflation and
soaring unemployment are controlled.
</TEXT>
