<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Obscene Tabloids </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police scold two newspapers for publishing obscene material
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MARI YAMAGUCHI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Accusing Japan's ribald tabloids of going too far,
police have issued warnings to two newspapers for publishing
pornographic color photos, police said Tuesday.
	   The Tokyo Metropolitan Police Department said it has questioned
the tabloid Nikkan Gendai and sports daily Tokyo Sports separately
on suspicion of illegally selling obscene material.
	   The police said, however, that the papers would not be charged
with any crime this time since the publishers pledged _ in writing
_ not to release such photographs again.
	   The warnings, made separately in recent months, were the first
in decades in which police took exception to material published in
Japan's often risque daily tabloids, said a police official in
charge of public safety.
	   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the two
photos _ which displayed genitals _ went beyond the socially
accepted limits of nudity. He refused to describe on what criteria
the judgment was made.
	   Though a ban on photographs of pubic hair is widely flaunted,
publications for the most part refrain from clearly showing
genitals. Police periodically crack down on pornographers who break
the law too brazenly.
	   On March 9, Tokyo Sports published a photo downloaded from the
Internet showing female genitalia that _ according to police _ was
insufficiently blurred out.
	   On May 9, Nikkan Gendai printed a color photo of a couple having
sexual intercourse, with their genitals only slightly blurred.
	   In both cases, police warnings shortly after the photos
appeared.
	   The two newspapers, which often feature color centerfolds, sexy
stories and pornography ads, submitted a statement pledging that
they would not publish similar photographs again.
	   ``But we will not stop publishing sex-related materials,'' said
Yasuo Sakurai, chief editor of Tokyo Sports. ``Sex is a universal
interest of human beings, and we believe many readers like to read
what we publish.''
	   Nikkan Gendai's chief editor Shuji Uragami was quoted by the
major newspaper Asahi as saying that pornography is only part of
general news it covers ``to meet readers' demand.''
	   There are growing calls from women's and human rights' groups
for tighter restrictions on widespread pornography as a way of
curbing sexism and protecting children from the sex business.
	   ``Such materials treat women as a sex toy,'' said Kazue
Takahashi, director of New Japan Women's Association. ``They
violate human rights of women.''
	   Still, pornography is widely accepted in Japan. Men have no
qualms about purusing centerfolds and obscene comics while riding
subways. Every video shop is well-stocked with porn tapes, which
are openly displayed.
 &UR; (may-jc)
</TEXT>
