<SLUG> BC-Russia-Japan </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia, Japan to hold naval exercise
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia and Japan will hold naval exercises for the
first time in the Pacific Ocean next month as part of efforts to
improve relations between the two forces, the Interfax news agency
reported Tuesday.
	   Two Russian warships and two helicopters will take part in
exercises with two Japanese destroyers, a training ship and five
aircraft, the report said. The exercise, to be held 400 kms (250
miles) east of the Russian port of Vladivostok, will simulate
searching for a ship in distress.
	   Five decades after World War II, the two nations have yet to
sign a treaty, mainly because of a territorial dispute over four
tiny islands in the southern Kuril chain that Soviet troops seized
from Japan in the closing days of the war.
	   (ren)
