r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Malaysia-Opposition     06-09 0377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Opposition </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dozens of groups, parties, band on civil liberties
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ In a rare show of unity, nearly 30
volunteer and consumer organizations, opposition parties and the
country's largest trade union on Tuesday demanded more civil
liberties and free speech.
	   Protesting the cancellations of public meetings in recent weeks,
the groups accused Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad's government of
violating basic human rights.
	   ``People must be free to express, discuss, engage in dialogue
and release their frustrations and tensions,'' said a one-page
declaration by the group.
	   Last week, the police banned a consumer rights group from
organizing a meeting to discuss the severe water rationing in the
capital, where nearly 2 million people have suffered dry faucets
for three months.
	   The previous Sunday, more than 50 police officers in riot gear
broke up a gathering organized by the the nation's main opposition
group, the Democratic Action Party.
	   The party's leader, Lim Kit Siang and his son, Lim Guan Eng,
both opposition members of Parliament, were to speak at that
meeting about the younger Lim's 18-month prison sentence for
printing a pamphlet that criticized the government.
	   Another party meeting was also subsequently broken up and the
permit revoked.
	   ``There is clearly a clampdown on public meetings,'' Lim told a
news conference Tuesday. ``We can eat, but we can't talk.''
	   While Lim demanded a meeting of opposition leaders with Mahathir
to seek explanations for the police actions, one consumer group
said it was planning to sue local authorities for failing to
provide water to residents.
	   ``We will show that it is a crisis of negligence,'' said A.
Jayseelan, director of the Selangor and Federal Territory Consumer
Association.
	   Stepping out of political neutrality, the Malaysian Trades Union
Congress _ which claims a half-million members _ said it was
plunging into an alliance with the opposition parties and civil
liberties groups.
	   The rumblings of political discontent come amid Malaysia's worst
economic crisis since the mid-1980s. The government recently
announced that the economy had shrunk by 1.8 percent in the first
three months of 1998.
</TEXT>
