<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Cyprus-Missiles </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Russian missiles already on Cyprus
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russian air defense missiles have been delivered
to Cyprus despite vows by Turkey to stop the weapons reaching the
island, a newspaper reported on Tuesday.
	   The Russian Foreign Ministry refused to confirm or deny the
report by the respected Segodnya daily.
	   While declining to comment on whether the S-300 missiles were
already on Cyprus, ministry spokesman Valery Nesterushkin
reiterated the long-held Russian argument that the missiles would
threaten no one.
	   ``We have been giving repeated explanations that the missiles
are a defensive weapon,'' Nesterushkin said in a telephone
interview. ``The presence of weapons on the island is the outcome
of the unsettled conflict between the Turkish and Greek population
on the island.''
	   Russia's Rosvooruzheniye arms trading monopoly denied that the
delivery had taken place and said the missiles will be sent to
Cyprus in mid-August as earlier planned, the Interfax news agency
reported.
	   The S-300, capable of shooting down aircraft and missiles, is a
Russian equivalent of the U.S. Patriot missiles which gained fame
during the Gulf War.
	   Turkey has threatened to use force to prevent the missiles'
deployment.
	   Greece has said it will come to the aid of Cyprus if it is
attacked by Turkey, raising fears of a military conflict between
two NATO allies.
	   Turkey maintains some 30,000 troops on Cyprus since it invaded
the island in 1974, following a failed coup by supporters of union
with Greece.
	   Cyprus has said it is ready to cancel the dlrs 200 million
missile deal if there is substantial progress toward the
reunification of the island and if Turkey accepts its proposal for
demilitarization.
	   The latest attempt to restart talks to reunify the Mediterranean
island by U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke failed earlier last month.
	   (vi/ren)
</TEXT>
