<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar falls after hitting new 7-year high, Tokyo stocks rise
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS; UPDATES with closing bond, late afternoon currency
prices &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Tokyo stocks ended sharply higher Tuesday as a
stronger dollar stoked optimism about earnings at Japan's
exporters. The U.S. currency gave up some gains after reaching a
new seven-year against the yen.
	   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 235.46 points, or 1.52
percent, to close at 15,530.17. On Monday, the average shed 28.72
points, or 0.19 percent.
	   On Tokyo's foreign exchange market, the dollar bought 140.36 yen
at late afternoon, down 0.20 yen from late Monday in Tokyo and
below its New York level overnight of 140.71 yen. During Tokyo
trading, the dollar rose as high as 141.11 yen, a level not seen
since June 1991.
	   Exporters such as Sony Corp., Canon Inc. and Toyota Motor Corp.
led the benchmark average higher. A stronger dollar is good news
for these companies because it boosts the yen value of dollar-based
profits and allows them to cut prices overseas.
	   The Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan Ltd. was the most actively
traded stock Tuesday. It plunged 77 percent as a rumor spread its
tie-up with Swiss Bank had come undone _ and then bounced right
back when the bank denied the speculation.
	   Trading was sparse, with an estimated 314 million shares
changing hands on the first section. Gaining issues outnumbered
decliners 6-to-5.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was up 10.32 points, or 0.86 percent, to 1,208.68.
The TOPIX closed down 3.58 points, or 0.30 percent, the day before.
	   On the currency market, the dollar surrendered early gains amid
speculation deputy finance ministers from the Group of Seven
largest economies meeting later Tuesday in Paris may announce a
joint effort to prop up the Japanese currency.
	   A growing number of officials from the G-7 have expressed
concern over the declining yen. On Monday, German central bank
chief Hans Tietmeyer said he hopes ``the yen won't depreciate
excessively.''
	   ``Judging from Tietmeyer's remark, we can't completely rule out
the possibility of a surprise announcement from the G-7 that
expresses, for instance, concerted efforts to defend the yen,''
said Ryuichi Takami, a senior currency trader at Sanwa Bank Ltd.
	   Still, the main cause of the yen's recent weakness _ Japan's
ailing domestic economy _ remains unchanged. On Tuesday, a Japanese
government report warned that key sectors of the economy such as
employment and production would likely worsen in June.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond rose to 1.210 percent from Monday's close of 1.145
percent, driving its price down to 111.96 yen from 112.46 yen.
</TEXT>
