<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Russia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yeltsin, Kohl meet on Russia's financial troubles, Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS pvs. To be updated after 0915 GMT news conference &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos expected &QL; 
 &UR; By IAN MADER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ Russian President Boris Yeltsin and his
ministers met with German officials Tuesday on how to prevent
escalating violence in the Serbian province of Kosovo.
	   The talks also focused on Russia's market collapse last month
following an oil-price drop. But Yeltsin and other Russian
officials have insisted publicly that they are not looking for any
new aid or funding.
	   The two-day talks, the first in a series of periodic
German-Russian consultations agreed to by Yeltsin and Chancellor
Helmut Kohl last year, also focused on nuclear tests in Pakistan
and India and on whether to jointly build a military transport
plane.
	   ``New problems keep emerging which need to be solved quickly and
energetically, and the both of us, Helmut and I, will solve these
problems this way,'' Yeltsin said after arriving Monday evening.
	   Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel said he would try to get Russia to
back the European Union's decision Monday to punish Serbia with
economic sanctions for its attacks on its separatist region of
Kosovo.
	   But asked whether Russia would support the ban on investment in
Serbia and a freeze of its foreign assets, Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov said Monday night: ``No, I don't think so.''
	   Kremlin spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembski said Russia and other
European nations need to address the Kosovo conflict ``as a team''
to prevent other nations from being drawn into the conflict.
	   German government spokesman Otto Hauser said Germany would
provide no direct aid to Russia. But Germany left open the
possibility of participating in a loan package put together by the
International Monetary Fund.
	   Stanley Fischer, an IMF official based in Washington, said in
Washington that the organization didn't see any immediate reason to
boost an existing dlrs 9.2 billion credit arrangement with Russia.
	   Yeltsin and Kohl made no statements after meeting late Monday,
but were to hold a news conference later Tuesday following a
meeting with their ministers.
	   Ministers of finance, economics, foreign affairs, defense and
atomic energy met separately with their counterparts Tuesday
morning on a broad range of security and trade issues. Yeltsin also
met with opposition chancellor candidate Gerhard Schroeder.
	   Shortly after arriving in Bonn, Russian and German ministers
signed two agreements dealing with cooperation in the nuclear power
industry.
	   Cooperation in the defense industry also was on the agenda.
Ukraine has been trying to enlist Germany, Russia and France to
help build a new Ukrainian version of the Antonov An-70 aircraft.
	   Since the fall of communism, Germany has become Russia's most
important trade partner outside the former Soviet Union, and a key
source of aid and credit.
	   Kohl and Yeltsin agreed to periodic consultations during an
April 1997 meeting in Baden-Baden, when Kohl helped negotiate
Russia's acquiescence to the eastward expansion of the NATO
military alliance.
	   (im/cb) 	   
</TEXT>
