<HEADLINE>
VATICAN CITY: Soviet bloc.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   The Polish-born pope and some other churchmen were said to have
had differences with Casaroli's cautious approach to diplomacy,
preferring a more uncompromising stance.
	   But John Paul promoted Casaroli to secretary of state less than
a year after becoming pontiff.
	   Casaroli was considered as consummate diplomat and an extremely
loyal official. He and the pope clearly had reconciled any
differences as the years went on.
	   In the Vatican hierarchy, the secretary of state is the most
important post under the pope, a position equivalent to premier.
	   Casaroli was considered an architect of the Vatican's diplomacy
that aimed to gain at least some freedom for the Roman Catholic
Church after open persecution by Communist nations.
	   The policy toward Eastern Europe, known as the Vatican's
Ostpolitik, was the inspiration of Pope John XXIII after the hard
line taken by Pope Pius XII during the years of Stalinist
repression.
	   Pope Paul VI, who took over in 1963, implemented the policy,
working closely with Casaroli, sending the prelate on frequent
missions to Communist capitals.
	   Casaroli was given credit for the tough language on human rights
and religious liberty in the 1975 Helsinki accords.
	   Beyond the diplomatic field, Casaroli kept the Vatican running
smoothly after the pope was wounded by a Turkish gunman in 1981.
	   (vls-fd)
