w2447 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Israel-Palestinians     06-09 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinians </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Netanyahu may be leaning toward referendum on troop withdrawal
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DINA KRAFT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu signalled
Tuesday that he might support a nationwide referendum on a pending
Israeli troop pullback from the West Bank, saying public input was
important on such a crucial question.
	   ``It is obligatory, above all, that there be broad public
support so the rifts in the nation will heal and we have domestic
peace, not just external peace,'' Netanyahu said in an interview
with Israel Radio.
	   But the prime minister added he was not yet committed to the
referendum route.
	   A show of public support for the withdrawal could help Netanyahu
weather the political storm that authorizing it would bring.
Right-wing members of his coalition have threatened to bring down
his government if he goes ahead with a pullback.
	   After much wrangling and delay, Israel's Cabinet is expected to
vote by the end of the week on a U.S. initiative to pull back from
13 percent of the West Bank, which Israel seized from Jordan in the
1967 Mideast war.
	   According to Israeli media reports, U.S. President Bill Clinton
urged Israel on Monday to quickly overcome internal disputes on the
pullback and move ahead to so-called final-status talks with the
Palestinians, in which thorny issues including Jerusalem's future
are to be decided.
	   The reports said Clinton made the remarks during an unexpected
encounter with Israel's U.N. ambassador, Dore Gold.
	   Netanyahu says security considerations, not internal disputes,
are holding up a vote.
	   ``My considerations are over what is the best agreement from the
point of view of security, settlement and the national interest,''
he told Israel radio. ``And of course that there will be
reciprocity _ that the Palestinians will fulfill their
commitments.''
	   The Palestinians, who currently have full control over 3 percent
of the West Bank and partial control over another 24 percent, have
accepted the American initiative.
	   Under the American plan _ which has been widely reported but
never formally unveiled _ a second Israeli redeployment would take
place in three stages over 12 weeks. It would bring full and
partial Palestinian control over the West Bank to 40 percent.
	   Peace talks between the two sides have been deadlocked for more
than 15 months. They stalled after groundbreaking on a Jewish
neighborhood in traditionally Arab east Jerusalem.
	   Palestinians want the city's eastern sector as their future
capital, but Israel claims jurisdiction over all Jerusalem.
	   Bitter disputes have broken out in recent weeks over Jewish
settlers' moves into Arab parts of town, which Palestinians view as
land grabs in advance of any settlement of Jerusalem's status.
	   Before dawn on Monday, Jewish settlers took over five apartments
in two buildings in the Arab neighborhood of Silwan, setting off
angry confrontations with residents.
 &UR; (dk-lk) 	   
</TEXT>
