<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Impeachment </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Communist move to impeach Yeltsin face hurdles
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A Communist-backed impeachment motion against
President Boris Yeltsin hit a snag on Tuesday when lawnmakers
failed to agree on setting up a panel to draw up formal charges.
	   The parliament's lower house, the State Duma, must create a
commission made up of representatives of all factions to prepare an
indictment. The Duma will then have to vote by a two-thirds
majority to launch impeachment proceedings.
	   When the Communists called for the commission's creation
Tuesday, the pro-government Our Home Is Russia faction said it
didn't want to take part, bringing the move to a grinding halt.
	   Previous impeachment motions against Yeltsin have all fizzled
without reaching the floor mostly because Russia's Constitution
gives the president the upper hand in confrontations with
parliament.
	   Even if the Duma finally votes to start the impeachment
proceedings, the motion will then go to the upper chamber
consisting of regional officials many of whom are loyal to Yeltsin.
The charges will also have to win confirmation from both
Constitutional and Supreme courts _ a highly unlikely development.
	   The Communists and their allies have accused Yeltsin of a range
of transgressions, including instigating the Soviet collapse,
launching the botched war in Chechnya and ruining the country's
economy which led to a population decrease.
	   (vi/ren)
</TEXT>
