<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Romania Media,0360 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Soccer team boycotts Romanian media
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By VIOREL URMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ALBI, France (AP) _ The national soccer team is refusing all
interviews with Romanian media in France for the World Cup,
following news reports of the goalkeeper's bad behavior during a
warmup game against Paraguay last week.
	   ``The players said they will talk only to foreign reporters,''
coach Anghel Iordanescu told a news conference Monday night,
attended by foreign and Romanian reporters.
	   Asked if he could intervene with the players to change their
mind, Iordanescu said, ``I can't do anything if they don't want to
talk to Romanian journalists. Perhaps FIFA can do something.''
	   He said he hoped that the situation will change in the next
couple of days.
	   Afterwards, the players met only with foreign reporters, while
ignoring their compatriots. Frustrated Romanian reporters, whose
dailies and magazines paid up to dlrs 10,000 each for their
accreditation, transportation and living costs, looked upset.
	   The scandal followed a row about obscene gestures by goalkeeper
Bogdan Stelea during the game against Paraguay, a World Cup
qualifier, last week in Bucharest. Romania struggled to defeat the
South Americans 3-2 on a penalty kick.
	   Stelea conceded an easy goal from Paraguay's Roberto Acuna in
the 64th minute, angering Romanian fans. The goalkeeper later
defused another Paraguayan attack, earning applause from
spectators. But Stelea then pulled down his shorts to expose part
of his backside and made a vulgar gesture at the crowd.
	   Romanian media headlined the incident. ``Stelea _ Be Ashamed,''
said one report.
	   Teammates defended Stelea. ``We are deeply grieved by some
dailies and TV stations' attitude regarding us,'' the players said
in a statement released after the game.
	   The statement said the team wants to keep calm during the
tournament, without distractions from Romanian media comments.
	   ``Because of you, the public is cursing us,'' star player
Gheorghe Hagi told journalists before their departure for France.
</TEXT>
