<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Vietnamese </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hong Kong repatriates more than 100 Vietnamese
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Another group of 154 Vietnamese was deported
back to their Communist homeland Tuesday, two weeks after the Hong
Kong government closed the last remaining camp for such
asylum-seekers.
	   This brought to 12,758 the number of Vietnamese deported under
the government's forced repatriation policy that was introduced in
1991.
	   Last month, the government shut down the High Island Detention
Center, the last remaining camp for the Vietnamese.
	   The territory still harbors about 2,500 Vietnamese
asylum-seekers. More than 1,100 of them have been granted refugee
status and are awaiting resettlement. The rest are in jail and will
be deported.
	   In January, six months after Hong Kong reverted to Chinese rule,
the government abolished its 23-year-old policy of offering
temporary asylum to the Vietnamese.
	   Vietnamese who arrive illegally now are simply held in detention
until arrangements can be made to send them back.
	   Since communist North Vietnam defeated the U.S.-backed South in
1975, ending the Vietnam war, nearly 223,000 Vietnamese have passed
through Hong Kong, most of them arriving penniless by boat.
	   The government said just 178 Vietnamese arrived in the first
five months of this year, compared to 1,024 over the same period
last year.
</TEXT>
