<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asia Business Briefs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Australia. Some of these stories also moved earlier today as
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items from Japan, Singapore, Philippines and
separates.

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Housing construction, employment and import figures
have worsened over the past month, but consumer spending shows
signs of a recovery, according to a closely watched government
report Tuesday.
	   The Economic Planning Agency assessed the overall economy as
``stagnant,'' unchanged in June from its report in May.
	   But the report slightly upgraded its view of personal
consumption because of hopes that spending will accelerate from
next month.
	   ``Consumption trends are showing signs of recovery,'' the
carefully worded report said. It added, however, that spending
remains weak due to poor employment conditions and other factors.
	   It also said housing construction and import statistics
worsened.
	   Japan's unemployment rate has steadily worsened, climbing to an
all-time high of 4.1 percent in April, its highest level in more
than four decades.
	   Japan's economy has been sluggish for most of the decade,
despite numerous government attempts to revive it via fiscal
stimulus and tax cuts.
	   ___
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Japanese electronics giant Hitachi is shifting
much of its production of dynamic random access memory chips, or
DRAM, from its plants in Germany and Japan to Singapore, a
newspaper reported Tuesday.
	   A Hitachi spokesman in Tokyo said that ultimately more than half
of the company's output of 64-megabit DRAM chips could come from
Singapore, according to The Business Times.
	   No timetable for the completed shift was given.
	   Hitachi is one of the world's largest producers of DRAM chips, a
key component in personal computers and a bellwether for the global
electronics industry.
	   The Singapore plant, Hitachi Nippon Steel Semiconductor
Singapore, currently accounts for about 10 percent of total DRAM
chip production.
	   Hitachi said the plan is to consolidate its DRAM output from
various German, Japanese, and Singapore fabrication plants to two
bases.
	   Hitachi's Naka plant in Japan will produce mostly
future-generation 256-megabit DRAM chips, while the Singapore plant
will concentrate on the more commonly-used 64-megabit DRAMs, the
spokesman told the newspaper.
	   ___
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan Ltd., a major
Japanese credit bank, denied a rumor Tuesday that it would dissolve
its tie-up with Swiss Bank Corp.
	   ``This is completely false, and there is no truth in it,'' the
Japanese bank said in a statement.
	   Long-Term Credit Bank's share prices moved sharply lower on the
rumor, falling by 14 percent from Monday's finish to 155 yen (dlrs
1.10) per share at the end of Tuesday's morning session on the
Tokyo Stock Exchange.
	   Long-Term Credit Bank Vice President Masami Suda told a news
conference that the bank had asked the Securities and Exchange
Surveillance Commission, Japan's securities watchdog, to
investigate the rumor.
	   Last year, Long-Term Credit Bank and Swiss Bank agreed to form a
strategic alliance to take advantage of Japan's ``Big Bang''
financial deregulation effort.
	   In the statement, Long-Term Credit Bank said that the securities
joint venture created by the alliance, LTCB Warburg Securities
Ltd., had already started operations, and said other joint
operations _ private banking and investment trusts _ will soon be
launched.
	   ___
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Non-performing loans in the
Philippine banking sector rose to 7.6 percent of total loans as of
March 31, the central bank said Tuesday.
	   The central bank's treasury director, Amando Tetangco, said the
rise from 5 percent at the end of 1997 wasn't surprising given the
impact of the region's financial crisis. He called the level
manageable.
	   The central bank has forecast that the ratio of non-performing
loans will rise to about 8 percent by the end of the year.
	   He said those banks that are experiencing financial difficulties
are smaller institutions.
	   Central bank officials earlier Tuesday denied a report in a
local newspaper saying that monetary authorities have put 17
allegedly ailing banks on a watch list.
	   ``We have no such list,'' central bank deputy governor Alberto
Reyes told a radio station.
	   The report came a day after the central bank announced the
closure of a small Manila thrift bank, Commonwealth Savings and
Loan Bank, which was placed in receivership.
	   The central bank has said two other small banks _ Richmond Bank
and Fortune Savings and Loan Association _ have problems, but are
preparing rehabilitation programs.
	   Reyes said the country's larger banks are well capitalized and
in sound financial health.
	   Tetangco said the regional currency crisis has prompted the
central bank to set up a special monitoring team to scrutinize
various aspects of the banking system in addition to existing
oversight in areas such as foreign exchange and bank deposit
movements.
	   ``But there is no watch list of banks,'' he reiterated.
	   ___
	   TOKYO (AP) _ In another sign of deflation in the Japanese
economy, Japan's central bank said Tuesday wholesales prices fell
1.7 percent in May from the same month last year.
	   That follows a 2.7-percent drop by the Bank of Japan's monthly
index of wholesale prices in April.
	   In breaking down this month's figure, the bank said prices of
goods produced domestically fell 2.3 percent from last year.
	   Meanwhile, the effects of a weakening yen made themselves felt
on the price of imports. The Bank of Japan said import prices rose
1.2 percent as a stronger dollar boosted the cost of oil and other
imports.
	   Deflation can be devastating because falling prices mean
companies don't earn enough to pay for production, throwing the
economy into a vicious cycle of factory shutdowns, declining
consumption and still lower prices.
	   ___
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ The long-awaited departure of the El
Nino weather pattern will boost Australia's winter crops, including
wheat, the government's chief commodity forecaster said Tuesday.
	   But widespread rain in April and early May was too late to stop
the summer crop production forecast for the 12 months to June 1998
being cut to 3.9 million (metric) tons from about 4.1 million tons,
the Australian Bureau of Agricultural and Resource Economics said
in its June crop report.
	   However, Australian wheat production was forecast to increase to
19.3 million tons in the 12 months to June 30, 1999, up four
percent on the previous year and exceeding the bureau's earlier
18.4 million ton forecast.
</TEXT>
