<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Iran </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iran could have missile capable of hitting Israel within year
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JACK KATZENELL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Within a year, Iran will have a missile capable
of reaching Israel _ unless Russian aid for the Iranian nuclear
program stops, an Israeli defense source said Tuesday.
	   Western experts believe that Iran is making strenuous efforts to
develop nuclear weapons and ballistic missiles capable of
delivering them.
	   At a recent high-level meeting, Israeli defense officials warned
that a prototype for Iran's Shihad-3 missile, with a range of 1,300
kilometers (1,625 miles), will be ready for launching in about a
year if Russia continues to supply missile technology to Teheran,
the source said.
	   ``Without Russian knowhow, the Shihad-3 will never take off,''
said the source, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
	   According to Western estimates it will take Iran about five
years to acquire or devcelop nuclear warheads.
	   During a visit to Israel in October 1997, Russian Foreign
Minister Yevgeny Primakov denied that Russia was supplying Iran
with weapons or military technology, but this assertion was
received with skepticism in Israel and the United States.
	   Israeli media reports have said Russia is helping Iran develop
missile navigational and delivery systems as well as the knowhow to
produce nuclear warheads, and that thousands of Russian scientists
and technicians were involved in various Iranian military projects.
	   In the past three months, Russia has begun cutting back its aid
to Iran, in response to the economic sanctions imposed by the U.S.
Congress, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said Monday.
	   ``The Russians were shocked by the sanctions imposed by the
Congress,'' Netanyahu told the parliamentary foreign affairs and
defense committee. ``There is a change on the ground. It's not
enough, but this time it's genuine.''
	   Congress voted May 22 by an overwhelming majority to impose
sanctions on governments or companies supplying ballistic-missile
technology to Iran. In the Senate the vote was 90-4 in favor. The
sanctions would range from denial of U.S. aid to denial of arms
licenses.
	   Officials of Iran's Islamic regime regularly declare their
ambition to destroy Israel.
	   Israeli foreign ministry Director General Eitan Bentsur arrived
in Moscow Monday night for talks with Russian Deputy Foreign
Minister Viktor Posovalyuk.
	   High on their agenda was the issue of Russian aid for the
Iranian missile program, said an Israeli official, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
 &UR; (jk-lk) 	   
</TEXT>
