<HEADLINE>
Thailand offers bonds to bail out rescue fund
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Thailand will issue 50 billion baht
(dlrs 1.2 billion) in one-year bonds this week to help replenish
the country's bank rescue fund, a senior ministry official said
Tuesday.
	   The bonds will be issued via the central bank to Thai financial
institutions and will carry a coupon rate of 12.5 percent, said
Kamol Juntima, ministry comptroller-general.
	   They are the first installment of a planned 500 billion baht
(dlrs 12 billion) domestic bond offering to help refinance the
debts of the Financial Institutions Development Fund.
	   The fund is an arm of the Bank of Thailand responsible for
bailing out troubled financial institutions reeling under bad debts
and the Asian currency crisis.
