w2501 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HongKong-Economy     06-09 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Politicians step up pressure on government to stimulate shrinking
</HEADLINE>
economy
 &UR; By PRISCILLA CHEUNG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Pressure mounted on the government Tuesday to
stimulate Hong Kong's troubled economy, with some legislators
threatening to stop cooperating with the authorities if it turns
down their economic proposals.
	   The warning came ahead of Financial Secretary Donald Tsang's
scheduled meeting later Tuesday with political party leaders.
	   ``We would withhold cooperation with the government to force
them to the negotiation table,'' said Lee Cheuk-yan of the populist
Frontier goup.
	   ``We want to send the government a message that there will be a
constitutional crisis if it ignore our demands,'' he added.
	   Impatient with the government, seven political parties from
across the political spectrum agreed at a rare summit last week on
a six-measure stimulus package, which includes cuts in taxes and
government fees and a refund of prepaid taxes to boost consumer
spending spending.
	   They also demanded that the govenment push forward
infrastructure plans and expand social services to create jobs,
review the interest rate system, and give support to medium and
small enterprises, the backbone of Hong Kong's economy.
	   The government's own job creation and economic stimulus packages
announced in recent weeks are generally seen as inadequate.
	   Joined by seven other independent legislators, the seven-party
coalition formed an overwhelming majority in the 60-seat
legislature that was elected last month.
	   This is the first meaningful political opposition Chief
Executive Tung Chee-hwa has faced since he came to power after Hong
Kong's handover to Chinese rule last July.
	   A handpicked legislature Beijing installed after the handover
was dominated by generally cooperative, conservative government
supporters.
	   Analysts have said the record voter turnout at the May 24
legislative election was a show of public dissatisfaction with the
government over the economic downturn.
	   Although Hong Kong has weathered the region's economic turmoil
better than most other Asian countries, slumping property prices,
dwindling tourist arrivals and high interest rates have pushed the
territory into the first economic contraction in 13 years.
	   The economy shrank by 2 percent in the first quarter this year,
and umemployment is at a 14-year high of 3.9 percent.
	   The weakening yen also is putting more pressure on the Hong Kong
dollar's fixed exchange rate with the U.S. dollar.
	   Allen Lee, chairman of the business-oriented Liberal Party and
leader of the political coalition, said the government needed to do
``more than just sitting there, doing nothing.''
	   ``What we don't want is a Japanese situation,'' he told the
government-owned Radio Hong Kong. ``Ten years ago, the Japanese
government thinks ... the market will correct itself. They think
the government does not need to do anything. Look at what's
happening 10 years later today?''
</TEXT>
