<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Air France-Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Air France pilots' strike on collision course with World Cup
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with criticism of pilots, strike in 9th day, bus
strike, changes byline
 &UR; AP Photos Planned
 &UR; By DEBORAH SEWARD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Criticism of striking French pilots mounted Tuesday
as their walkout entered its ninth day, and Air France arranged to
transport soccer teams on special flights for the World Cup.
	   No new talks have been planned between Air France management and
the pilots, who are increasingly seen as the spoilers of French
efforts to stage the World Cup.
	   Air France is the official carrier of the World Cup, which opens
Wednesday, and the airline has arranged 110 special flights to
transport the teams to their destinations throughout the
tournament.
	   The strike did not appear to be wrecking the party atmosphere in
the French capital on the eve of the World Cup.
	   Preparations for parades in Paris later Tuesday were in full
gear. The Champs-Elysees was decorated with the flags of competing
nations, and hotels strung up banners.
	   In the skies, only one in four Air France planes were expected
to fly Tuesday.
	   Overseas, the strike appeared to have had little affect on fans
trying to get to France for the World Cup.
	   Kazuyoshi Sakamaki, a spokesman for the Narita International
Airport Authority, which manages Tokyo's main international
airport, said the strike had caused no problems or confusion.
	   Japan Travel Bureau, a major travel agency, said that so far it
hasn't received any complaints or requests for reservations on
other airlines from passengers holding tickets on Air France.
	   The main pilots' union offered Sunday to work for free to fly
World Cup ticket holders to the 10 game sites, but on Tuesday said
Air France had rejected the proposal.
	   Air France President Jean-Cyril Spinetta called an extraordinary
board meeting for Wednesday or Thursday, amid French media reports
of a major change in strategy.
	   No new negotiations have been set since an all-night session
ended Saturday morning, and bitterness appeared to gradually
replace the initial embarrassment caused by the strike.
	   Trade union leaders joined politicians in accusing the pilots of
being selfish.
	   Alain Deleu, president of the French Confederation of Christian
Workers, said Tuesday on Radio Monte Carlo that ``nobody can
understand'' how the pilots' grievances could ``be allowed to
disrupt the welcome of foreigners for a world event.''
	   French President Jacques Chirac said he hoped for a speedy
resolution, but said it would not impact the country's reception of
visitors.
	   The pilots are protesting (500 million francs) dlrs 83 million
in salary cuts Air France says are needed to modernize the airline
that was saved from bankruptcy in 1993. It has since reported
profits for 1996 and 1997.
	   Air France has offered to compensate the pilots by giving them
stock in exchange for the pay cuts.
	   (parf-dgs-ip)
</TEXT>
