<SLUG> BC-Caribbean-Summary,1271 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
An overnight summary of Caribbean news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 
 &UR; ST. LUCIA: Defeated party brings veteran leader out of retirement &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   CASTRIES, St. Lucia (AP) _ Hoping to reclaim some of its former
power, the St. Lucia United Workers Party announced Monday it is
bringing former Prime Minister John Compton out of retirement to
lead the party again.
	   The 72-year-old Compton, who was prime minister for 29 years
until he retired in 1996, was elected unopposed Sunday night, the
party announced Monday.
	   Compton was nominated in April by party leaders worried by
increasing divisions in the party and a huge defeat in May 1997
elections. The rival Labor Party won all but one of the 17
legislative seats.
	   Compton had said he would accept the job only if the vote was
unchallenged. His successor as prime minister, Vaughn Lewis, had
been running against Compton for the party leadership but withdrew
his candidacy Sunday.
 &UR; PUERTO RICO: Poll says residents split on statehood
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ Puerto Ricans are deeply split on
whether to become the 51st state, despite a relentless lobby by
their pro-statehood governor, a poll published Monday showed.
	   The poll in The San Juan Star daily showed statehood supported
by 40.9 percent, while 40.2 percent favored retaining the unusual
``commonwealth'' status worked out in 1952.
	   Under commonwealth, Puerto Rico's 3.8 million residents are U.S.
citizens but don't pay federal taxes, don't vote for president and
are represented in Congress only by a non-voting delegate.
	   In a non-binding 1993 referendum on the Caribbean island's
political status, continued commonwealth edged out statehood by two
percentage points.
 &UR; JAMAICA: Indian doctor falls to death at hospital
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ A medical intern from India fell four
stories to his death at Kingston Public Hospital Monday morning,
police said. They suspect it may have been a suicide.
	   Jasti K. Saigal, 29, had finished his morning rounds when
security staff and nurses saw him fall from a roof near the
interns' quarters at the hospital.
	   He was rushed to the hospital's emergency room, but doctors were
unable to save him, said Trevor McCartney, the hospital's chief
medical officer.
	   Saigal was from Andhra Pradesh, a province in southeastern
India, and had recently joined the hospital staff, McCartney said.
	   His roommate, Rao Srinvias, said Saigal had been ``quite
anxious'' Monday morning and said he missed India. He had asked
Srinvias to pick up some antidepressant pills for him.
 &UR; DOMINICAN REPUBLIC: Probe into lottery scandal bogs down
	   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) _ A months-old probe into
a dlrs 6.5 million scandal at the Dominican National Lottery has
bogged down, and some vendors say their sales have yet to recover.
	   When the scandal broke in September, several people were
arrested, including top officials in the government of former
President Joaquin Balaguer. All have been released since, however.
	   Prosecutors say the investigation is continuing.
	   Now Dominican officials want a Haitian citizen, Frederick
Mazourca, who was convicted of defrauding the lottery of dlrs
460,000, only to escape and later appear on television to claim a
``mafia'' ran the state-sponsored game.
	   Authorities say Mazourca, who allegedly acted with officials at
the lottery to rig numbers, fled last year to Miami.
 &UR; UNITED NATIONS: Caribbean, Latin American leaders blame drug
consumers
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Despite President Clinton's appeal to
avoid ``finger-pointing,'' leaders of the world's drug-producing
nations showed no hesitation Monday in blaming consumers for the
global narcotics problem.
	   Their message: if rich countries such as the United States want
our help in fighting against drugs, show us the money.
	   ``The illicit drug trade is demand-driven,'' the prime minister
of the tiny Caribbean nation of St. Kitts and Nevis told the
opening session of the U.N. General Assembly special session on
drugs.
	   ``How can we truly expect small, poor countries such as mine to
defeat the wealthy drug lords if the rich countries, with their
wealth of resources, are unsuccessful in limiting the demand,''
said the prime minister, Denzil Douglas.
 &UR; DOMINICAN REPUBLIC: Retired lottery official wins lottery
	   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) _ Nobody knows the
daunting odds of winning the lottery better than Luis Didiez, who
for years administered the official lottery in the Netherlands
Antilles.
	   But a few weeks after retiring and moving to the Dominican
Republic, Didiez bought a ticket anyway _ and struck it rich.
	   On Monday, he claimed his 22 million pesos (dlrs 1.5 million)
win from Saturday's draw in Santo Domingo.
	   The winner said he earned about dlrs 2,000 a month as head of
the lottery in Curacao.
 &UR; UNITED STATES: Dominican president sees no change in peso rate
	   NEW YORK (AP) - There will be no devaluation of the Dominican
Republic's official peso rate to bring it more in line with weaker
market rates, says President Leonel Fernandez.
	   ``There are no technical reasons for this movement in the
currency. Perhaps, the electoral period has an impact and (since)
the elections things will stabilize again,'' Fernandez said Sunday
in New York, on a visit for a U.N. drug conference.
	   He said the Dominican economy is ``booming, especially in
construction, tourism and free-trade zones ... All our
macroeconomic indicators are very stable.''
	   The Dominican economy grew 8.3 percent last year and is expected
to grow by more than 7 percent this year, he said.
 &UR; UNITED STATES: Dominican leader stumps in New York
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ The Dominican presidential elections are in
2000. But hours after reaching New York for a U.N. drug meeting,
President Leonel Fernandez was stumping in the Dominican stronghold
in northern Manhattan.
	   Extolling ``Companero Leonel'' in ritualistic political
speeches, the expatriate faithful of Fernandez's Dominican
Liberation Party on Sunday packed a middle-school auditorium,
festooned in the party purple and yellow in the city where he spent
much of his childhood.
	   Dominicans, who number 1 million to 2 million in the United
States, can't even vote abroad. But Fernandez, a minority president
struggling to press through economic reforms, takes his support
where he finds it.
	   In a bizarre twist, his party lost its bid for a badly needed
congressional majority in May 16 elections after a charismatic
opponent, Jose Francisco Pena Gomez, died days before, producing a
sweeping sympathy vote for his party.
 &UR; PUERTO RICO: KIWI International Air Lines begins Newark-San Juan
flights
	   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) _ KIWI International Air Lines will
begin once-a-week flights between Newark, New Jersey and San Juan,
Puerto Rico on June 26, the company said Monday.
	   The airline said service will be on Boeing 727-200s. Flights to
Newark will depart on Fridays at 6:45 p.m., and flights to San Juan
on Fridays at 2:20 p.m. Fares will be dlrs 119 until June 24.
	   The Newark airport is in northern New Jersey, about 10 miles
west of New York.
	   KIWI will also add a third flight between Orlando, Florida and
San Juan on Wednesdays beginning June 22. Flights to San Juan will
leave at 7:10 p.m., and flights to Orlando will leave at 2:30 p.m.
</TEXT>
