<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Saudi Nurses-Money </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Murdered nurse's brother donates most money from convicted nurses
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ADELAIDE, Australia (AP) _ The brother of an Australian nurse
murdered in Saudi Arabia donated on Tuesday U.S. dlrs 620,000
(Australian dollars 1.035 million) of the money he received to
waive the death penalty for her accused killers.
	   Frank Gilford handed over a check to the Adelaide Women's and
Children's Hospital to help pay for a new day surgery unit which
will be named in memory of his murdered sister, Yvonne Gilford.
	   Gilford received U.S. dlrs 1 million (Australian dollars 1.7
million) compensation for waiving his right to call for the death
penalty for British nurse Deborah Parry, who was convicted by a
Saudi court of the murder.
	   Yvonne Gifford was killed at a hospital in Saudi Arabia in
December 1996.
	   Gilford will keep about U.S. dlrs 30,000 (Australian dollars
50,000) of the payout, about U.S. dlrs 5,400 (Australian dollars
9,000) will go to his mother and the rest will pay legal fees.
	   ``As a nurse, Yvonne cared for people,'' Gilford said at the
presentation ceremony. ``She would be pleased, as I am, that some
good has come from her terrible murder.''
	   He said he hoped the donation towards the unit would help many
people to live comfortably.
	   Gilford's lawyer Michael Abbott said Gilford's only wish during
the 18-months murder trial had been to see the establishment of a
memorial to his sister.
	   A second British nurse, Lucille McLauchlan, was convicted of
being an accessory to the murder and was sentenced to eight years
jail and 500 lashes.
	   Parry and McLauchlan were released last month after the Saudi
King Fahd commuted their sentences to the 17 months already served
in prison.
</TEXT>
