<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Cambodia-Khmer Rouge Peace,0759 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Peace with the Khmer Rouge filled with bloody ironies
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos PHN101-103 &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBIN McDOWELL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ANLONG VENG, Cambodia (AP) _ His makeshift limb, a piece of
metal capped with a scrap of car tire, thuds as he walks through an
abandoned schoolhouse in this former Khmer Rouge stronghold.
	   Each step reminds Teng Sokun _ who lost his left leg in 1989 to
a land mine _ of the heavy price he and other guerrillas had to pay
for decades of civil war against Cambodian governments before they
made peace earlier this year.
	   Looking over the landscape from the third floor, Teng Sokun
said: ``The land is fertile, there's plenty of water. I hope now
people like me can focus on farming instead of fighting.''
	   Integrating former Khmer Rouge like Teng Sokun into society
poses a challenge to the government: It is trying to bring peace by
letting members of a movement that killed as many as 2 million
people start new lives.
	   The Khmer Rouge proved over the past 30 years to be one of the
world's toughest guerrilla forces, surviving in the jungles to wage
war even after their genocidal regime was overthrown by a military
invasion from Vietnam in 1979.
	   But since 1996, Khmer Rouge bastions have fallen one by one
under government control as thousands of veterans like Teng Sokun
grew fed up with war and defected to the Phnom Penh government.
	   In March, the last stronghold of Anlong Veng, near the northern
border with Thailand, came under government control when guerrillas
mutinied against hard-line members loyal to Ta Mok, the tough and
wily successor to the notorious Pol Pot.
	   As a rebel force, the Khmer Rouge is now believed near
extinction, with Ta Mok and an estimated few hundred loyalists
pressed against the Thai border.
	   In Anlong Veng, thousands of guerrillas and their families
officially joined the government Friday, changing out of
Maoist-style garb into royal army uniforms. A day later, they were
registering to vote in upcoming elections.
	   In exchange, they were promised help to develop the area _ home
to about 15,000 former fighters and their families _ and build
schools, roads, pagodas and markets.
	   Now, they have nothing.
	   The hospital can provide rudimentary amputations to land mine
victims, but the seriously ill are sent to the provincial capital
of Siem Reap. The local school is closed. Most houses are empty.
There is no electricity and no market.
	   Anlong Veng's new chieftain, Yim Phanna, a former Khmer Rouge
division commander, said that after years of isolation from the
rest of the world, the former guerrillas need international
assistance.
	   Many are land mine victims. Their best years behind them, they
still hope to build a future for their families through
agricultural development and small-scale trade.
	   That would be a departure from the past, when trade and profit
were considered heresies punishable by death.
	   Before, youngsters spent season after season making poisoned
bamboo spikes to use against government soldiers and education to
make model revolutionaries.
	   Lesson number one: Cambodia is beset by historic foe Vietnam and
Hun Sen, the country's chief leader for the past 13 years, is the
puppet of Hanoi.
	   Now, the guerrillas are accepting Hun Sen's leadership. But no
one has bothered to take down a sign in the schoolyard calling him
a ``mass criminal.''
	   The irony runs both ways. Hun Sen, a former Khmer Rouge official
who escaped to Vietnam in 1977 to escape bloody purges, has built
his career by declaring them his number-one enemy.
	   But unable to defeat them, he has now had to embrace them in the
name of national reconciliation.
	   As result, killers are likely to get away with mass murder, no
matter how many calls are issued for international tribunals to
press charges of crimes against humanity.
	   One is Ke Pauk, who played a major part in the purges Hun Sen
escaped. He strolls freely through Anlong Veng or kills time in a
hammock with little fear of punishment.
	   Ke Pauk brushes off allegations that he is responsible for the
killings of more than 100,000 people. He knows Hun Sen can't touch
people like him if he wants to end the war.
	   The death of Pol Pot of a reported heart attack April 15 gives
killers like Ke Pauk a scapegoat for their crimes.
	   ``This is a Pol Pot issue, it has nothing to do with me,'' says
Ke Pauk, who has even received a post in the government army. ``I
never did anything directly.''
</TEXT>
