<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-World Labor-Union Repression,0365 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Study condemns China, Colombia for union repression
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ Colombia and China were singled out for criticism
over abuses of labor union rights in a report published Tuesday to
coincide with a U.N. labor conference.
	   Worldwide, 299 activists were killed last year, according to the
142-page report of the International Confederation of Free Trade
Unions, the world's biggest umbrella organization of labor unions.
	   Highlighting 156 killings of union leaders and members in
Colombia, the report complained that ``the violence was rarely if
ever investigated'' in the South American nation.
	   Although paramilitary organizations were mostly to blame for the
violence in Colombia, ``union activists continue to be stigmatized
as enemies of the state,'' it said.
	   It said hundreds of unionists had to leave their homes because
of death threats.
	   Deregulation of Colombian labor laws has made it ``impossible in
practice for many workers to belong to unions and to be covered by
collective agreements,'' the report claimed.
	   In China, ``the unions in foreign-owned and joint venture
companies are largely symbolic,'' according to the Brussels-based
confederation.
	   Such unions in China are controlled either by the Communist
Party or plant management, the report said.
	   The group also criticized U.S. labor law for ``double standards
with respect to the rights of employers and of workers,'' claiming
that at least one in 10 activists campaigning to form a union is
illegally fired.
	   This year's International Labor Organization conference is aimed
at getting countries to commit to work toward collective bargaining
and eliminating forced labor.
	   It is also considering a new world convention aimed at
abolishing the most extreme forms of child labor.
	   In an address to delegates, Venezuelan President Rafael Caldera
warned of the dangers of competitiveness and productivity becoming
the only focus of increasingly liberal markets.
	   Newly freed Indonesian labor leader Muchtar Pakpahan promised
support for other repressed activists.
	   ``Do not be afraid. Persevere,'' he said.
</TEXT>
