w2537 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Belarus-US 1stLd-Writethru   06-09 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Belarus-US, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Officials defend plan to evict ambassadors, apologize for
</HEADLINE>
`inconvenience' &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: ADDS final graf with Russian foreign ministry's reaction. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo MIN101-2 &QL; 
 &UR; By MARINA BABKINA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MINSK, Belarus (AP) _ The U.S. ambassador and other envoys were
refusing Tuesday to budge after the Belarusian government said they
had to leave their residences to allow repairs and renovations.
	   The Foreign Ministry expressed regret for the ``inconvenience,''
but said 22 ambassadors would have to leave their homes in the
diplomatic complex on the outskirts of the capital, Minsk, for long
overdue repairs.
	   A long statement said the homes built just after the World War
II were in very poor condition, the water supply was no longer safe
and the sewage system was polluting the environment.
	   Diplomatic missions had been offered apartments in downtown
Minsk to accommodate staff while those willing to build their own
residences would be offered plots, the ministry said late Monday.
	   The Belarusian government served notice in April that it wanted
to overhaul water and sewage pipes in the diplomatic complex.
Diplomats protested, saying they would prefer to make arrangements
to remain in the complex during the repairs.
	   U.S. Ambassador Daniel Speckhard said at a news conference on
Monday that he and a number of other ambassadors are refusing to
vacate the complex, and appealed to President Alexander Lukashenko
to rescind the order.
	   But when he came home after the news conference accompanied by
camera crews and photographers willing to make footage of the
compound, they found a team of workers and a policeman trying to
weld shut the side gate.
	   A small American flag was lying on the ground. The workers left
when Speckhard protested.
	   ``To lock ambassadors into their residences and weld their door
shut is not becoming to the dignity of your country,'' Speckhard
told Belarusian reporters.
	   He called the incident the most serious violation of the Vienna
Convention on embassy operations since the end of the Cold War.
	   Speckhard said that he doesn't doubt that some repairs are
needed on the pipes leading to the complex, built to house the
Communist Party elite. But he insisted that the government must
reach agreements with the foreign missions and cannot simply evict
them.
	   Under international law, ambassadors' residences are considered
sovereign territory and governments have no right to enter without
permission or insist that diplomats leave.
	   Speckhard said the United States has had a lease on the
residence since 1992, the year after Belarus gained independence
with the collapse of the Soviet Union, and has spent dlrs 800,000
on repairs. The lease does not expire until 2001.
	   If the government forcibly evicts the ambassadors, it would be
the first violation of the Vienna Convention since Iranian
militants seized the U.S. Embassy in Tehran in 1979, an embassy
spokeswoman said.
	   Russian foreign ministry on Tuesday also protested the planned
eviction of the Russian ambassador and other envoys and voiced
``deep concern'' over Belarusian officials' action.
	   (mb/vi/ren)
</TEXT>
