</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Arrest, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Head of government statistics agency arrested for rigging
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with comments from tax enforcment chief &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The head of the government's statistics service
was arrested Tuesday on charges of helping tax dodgers and selling
confidential data, officials said. Investigators said they found
over dlrs 1 million in cash at his apartment.
	   Yuri Yurkov, head of the State Statistics Committee, was
arrested along with an unspecified number of senior workers in
charge of data processing, government spokesman Alexei Volin said.
	   They were charged with ``systematic distortion of statistical
data on big companies which allowed them to evade taxes,'' Volin
said.
	   Tax evasion is a major problem in Russia with many big companies
and business executives not paying. Government efforts to boost the
economy have been hobbled by a lack of revenues because of tax
evasion.
	   The country's new tax enforcement chief, Boris Fyodorov, said he
had no information about Yurkov's arrest. At a news conference
Tuesday, Fyodorov pledged once again to enforce the law equally
against all tax dodgers.
	   ``I've been told to collect taxes.'' he said. Because he intends
to do so, he added, ``People are hysterical. It's like 1937, the
year of the Stalin purges.''
	   His first targets will be rich Russians and foreigners, Fyodorov
said. Noting that Western bankers in Russia have advised the
government on how to establish a tax system, he said, ``Our good
friends who help us collect taxes don't always pay themselves.''
	   Yurkov and his alleged accomplices were accused of manipulating
economic data to hide the real output of companies and reduce their
tax liability, and with selling classified information about rival
companies' performance.
	   Yurkov, who has served as the statistics agency chief since
1993, is one of the highest-ranking Russian officials to be
arrested in recent years.
	   (vi/ren/ml)
</TEXT>
