<HEADLINE>
Cyclone hits India's western coast, 3 dead
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with storm hitting land. No pickup. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BOMBAY, India (AP) _ A cyclone hit the coast of India's western
Gujarat state Tuesday, leaving three people dead when high winds
toppled a wall that fell on them.
	   Meteorologist Kamaljeet, speaking by telephone from Ahmedabad,
465 kilometers (290 miles) north of Bombay, said the storm quickly
moved 50 kilometers (30 miles) inland and was expected to weaken
soon. It first struck land at Porbunder, 450 kilometers (280 miles)
northwest of Bombay.
	   Gujarat state officials said the three deaths occurred in
Junagadh, a rural district near Porbunder.
	   Forecasters had earlier predicted the storm would pack wind
speeds of 120 kilometers (72 miles) per hour, but it did not gain
such strength. The storm, with winds up to 80 kilometers (50 miles)
per hour, is expected to move north, said Kamaljeet, who uses one
name only.
	   Indian officials had moved 5,000 people in small towns and
villages bordering the Arabian Sea to safety, state government
officials said.
	   Authorities asked fishermen not to venture out into the sea.
Heavy rains in the area snapped power lines and forced traffic off
the road, Press Trust of India said.
