<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Carless Sundays </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Swiss initiative calls for one auto-free Sunday per season
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BERN, Switzerland (AP) _ Swiss voters are to be called on to
decide whether to ban cars from their country's roads on four
Sundays per year, the government said Tuesday.
	   The initiative ``for one car-free Sunday per season'' calls for
private motor vehicles to be banned from Switzerland's roads
between 4 a.m. and midnight on the days in question.
	   Public transport would continue to operate under the plan, which
would initially be introduced for a four-year trial period and then
resubmitted for approval by the people.
	   Under Switzerland's unique system of direct democracy, any
proposal that gathers 100,000 signatures is voted on in a national
referendum.
	   More than 110,000 people backed this initiative, the government
said. No date was given for the vote.
	   The Swiss go to the polls around three times a year to vote on
various national issues.
	   In the latest vote Sunday, Swiss voters firmly rejected a
proposal to impose tough restrictions on genetic engineering.
 &UR; (gm)
</TEXT>
