</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Airline Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government to allow Philippine Airlines to hire new pilots if
</HEADLINE>
strike continues
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with labor department ordering pilots to
return to work
 &UR; AP Photos Staffing
 &UR; By JIM GOMEZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Labor officials ordered about 600
striking Philippine Airlines pilots to return to work Tuesday,
warning they would authorize the troubled airline to hire
replacements if the strike continues.
	   The pilots' union, however, refused the labor department's
attempts to formally deliver the back-to-work order and said it
would continue the walkout.
	   PAL president Jose Antonio Garcia said the airline agreed to
take the strikers back if they complied with the new Tuesday
deadline. On Sunday it had fired all the striking pilots, calling
their action illegal.
	   Garcia said the 4-day-old strike caused several potential
foreign buyers of the airline, including Northwest Airlines, to
break off talks and could force the airline to shut down.
	   ``Closing PAL is an option. If there are no pilots and
operations, what work can we do?'' Garcia said to reporters after
attending an emergency meeting of PAL's board of directors called
to discuss the strike.
	   The union is protesting a new management policy of ordering
pilots to retire who have reached 20 years of service or flown
20,000 hours, regardless of age. The policy puts about 200 pilots
in danger of forced retirement, the union said.
	   PAL, however, said it was not a unilateral management policy but
a provision in a collective bargaining agreement signed by airline
and union officials.
	   The airline earlier announced plans to reduce staff, slash costs
and cut flights to survive a financial crisis.
	   The strike began Friday, forcing cancellations of most
international and domestic flights and affecting thousands of
passengers.
	   PAL says the strike is causing daily losses of 150 million to
200 million pesos (dlrs 3.8 million to 5.1 million) in lost
revenue, pushing it ``closer to the brink of insolvency.''
	   President Fidel Ramos urged both sides to follow the labor
department's order and resume negotiations.
	   PAL said Monday it lost 8 billion pesos (dlrs 205 million) in
the last fiscal year _ three times more than the previous year.
	   PAL tried to recover from its spiraling losses with an ambitious
dlrs 4 billion modernization program in 1996, ordering 36 new
aircraft. But Asia's currency crisis sharply reduced passenger
numbers and bloated the airline's debt in local currency terms,
forcing it to delay many of the orders.
	   PAL, Asia's first airline, is controlled by Chinese Filipino
tycoon Lucio Tan. It had been completely owned by the Philippine
government from 1941 until it was partly sold in 1992.
</TEXT>
