r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Malaysia-OfficialChar     06-09 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Official Charged </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police serve summons on official charged with corruption
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ On the heels of his acquittal on
currency violations by an Australia court, a top Malaysian
politician was ordered Tuesday to appear in court to face new
corruption charges at home.
	   Former chief minister of the central state of Selangor, Muhammad
Muhammad Taib, was served the summons Tuesday after eluding police
Monday night, Malaysia's Anti-Corruption Agency said in a
statement.
	   Police had stood watch throughout the night at Muhammad's two
homes in the suburbs of the capital, according to the national news
agency Bernama.
	   Muhammad will be charged in a district court Wednesday for
failing to declare all his assets. If convicted, he could face one
year in jail and a 2,000 ringgit (dlrs 500) fine.
	   On Monday, Malaysia's Attorney General Mohtar Abdullah said
there was strong evidence against Muhammad after studying the
investigation by the Anti-Corruption Agency.
	   Muhammad, 52, was found innocent on May 29 by a court in
Brisbane, Australia, of charges of carrying more than a million
dollars in foreign currency in his hand luggage during a trip to
Australia in December 1996.
	   Muhammad said he had been unaware that he had to declare any
cash in excess of U.S. dlrs 3,100 (5,000 Australian dollars) while
traveling in the country.
	   At the time, Taib was chief minister of Selangor. He resigned
his post and has also taken leave from his position of vice
president of Malaysia's ruling United Malays National Organization
party.
	   During the trial, he revealed he had purchased a farm, houses
and several pieces of land valued in Australia and New Zealand
under the name of his wife, Asbi Rohani Asnan.
	   Since Muhammad's arrest, the opposition in Parliament has been
calling on Malaysia's prime minister to investigate the former
chief minister.
	   ``This is a test case as to whether there is a newfound
political will against corruption in Malaysia,'' said Lim Kit
Siang, the leader of the nation's main opposition group, the
Democratic Action Party.
	   On Sunday, the outspoken UMNO youth chief Ahmad Zahid Hamidi
told the government to put its house in order by eliminating
nepotism and corruption in the administration.
	   ``Practices of corruption, power abuse must be curbed,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
