<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Nigeria,0318 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Africa sends condolences on Abacha's death
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ South Africa saluted the role
played by the late Nigerian Gen. Sani Abacha in supporting
democracy outside its own borders, but pointed out political
shortcomings at home in the West African country.
	   ``It is our hope that ... the path to democracy in Nigeria will
be pursued to its full conclusion,'' said a statement late Monday
from the Department of Foreign Affairs.
	   Abacha, 54, died Monday of a heart attack. He seized power in
Nigeria in 1993 after canceling presidential elections and
suspending the country's constitution.
	   The South African statement was issued from the Organization of
African Unity summit in Burkina Faso by Foreign Affairs Minister
Alfred Nzo, who expressed the government's condolences to Abacha's
family and nation.
	   ``The South African government, as indeed the rest of the
continent, pays tribute to the positive contribution which General
Abacha ... recently made towards the return of democracy in Sierra
Leone,'' the statement said.
	   The Nigerian-led west African intervention force, ECOMOG,
restored Sierra Leone president Tejan Kabbah to power in March
after he was ousted in a coup.
	   Relations between South Africa and Nigeria have been strained
since the execution of environmental activist Ken Saro-Wiwa and
eight other Ogoni activists prompted Mandela to call for sanctions
against Nigeria during a 1995 summit in New Zealand of the
Commonwealth of Britain and former colonies.
	   Although Abacha pledged to hand the government over to an
elected civilian administration, Abacha in April became the only
nominated candidate for the presidency in upcoming elections.
	   Last week, Nigeria accused South Africa, Ghana and the United
States of trying to destabilize his country and disrupt the August
elections.
</TEXT>
