<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rocks thrown during student protest in Indonesia
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING to restore dropped word in lede &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS to ADD some shops damaged
 &UR; By IRWAN FIRDAUS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Mobs threw rocks and smashed the
windows of banks and shops at the end of a student protest against
local government corruption Tuesday, witnesses said.
	   Police said there were no reports of injuries in Tegal, a
coastal town about 300 kilometers (185 miles) east of Jakarta.
	   One man was arrested.
	   Sri Wulandari, a Tegal resident, said more than 100 students
demonstrated in the streets against corruption and collusion in the
local government.
	   Stores closed their doors after other groups joined the protests
and began throwing rocks.
	   ``Stores were shut because some were afraid a riot might
start,'' she said.
	   The failure of many banks has resulted from the worst economic
crisis in 30 years.
	   Several shops, including those owned members of the Chinese and
Arabic minorities, were damaged.
	   In Jakarta about a dozen protesters demonstrated peacefully
outside the U.S. embassy, demanding Washington speed up a 43 dlrs
billion IMF bailout plan by the International Monetary Fund.
	   Protests have been held almost daily outside the embassy since
last week.
	   Also in Jakarta, about 200 supporters of opposition figure
Megawati Sukarnoputri marched about five kilometers (3 miles) from
the Justice Ministry to the offices of the opposition Indonesian
Democratic Party.
	   They demanded control over the building that serves as the
headquarters of the opposition party.
	   Megawati, the daughter of Indonesia's first president, Sukarno,
was ousted as party leader by rivals in 1996. She maintains the act
was illegal and was sponsored by the government of former President
Suharto after she called for democratic reform.
	   Suharto stepped down last month following riots and protests
triggered by rising prices and mass unemployment.
	   In a third protest in the capital, about 100 students
demonstrated outside the parliament demanding the government speed
up reform.
	   About 30 people were injured when police and strikers clashed
during a street march in the second city of Surabaya, police said
Tuesday.
	   Violence erupted when a line of riot police halted a
10-kilometer (six-mile) long march by striking factory workers
Monday, setting off a spate of stone-throwing in Indonesia's
biggest protest since the new president eased restrictions on
labor.
	   At least five police and three protesters were hospitalized as a
result of violence during the march in Surabaya, about 650
kilometers (400 miles) east of Jakarta.
	   Police estimated Monday's crowd at 10,000. However, the Jakarta
Post newspaper said about 25,000 took part.
	   Feeling the effects of Indonesia's worst economic crisis in 30
years, the workers went on strike a week ago to demand higher
salaries.
	   Meanwhile, all 46 members of the provincial legislature of the
tourist island of Bali have promised to resign after thousands of
protesters accused them of corruption and collusion.
</TEXT>
