<HEADLINE>
Report: Australian casino may sue Malaysian lawmaker
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ An Australian casino is
threatening to sue a Malaysian lawmaker who has failed to settle a
three-year-old gambling debt of 4.8 million ringgit (dlrs 1.2
million), a newspaper reported Tuesday.
	   Private investigators representing the casino in Perth were
preparing to file the papers in a Malaysian court after they failed
to persuade the member of parliament to pay up, the Malay Mail
said.
	   The report did not give the name of the legislator or of the
casino.
	   The lawmaker was among eight Malaysians who may be sued by the
casino because they had not settled debts incurred since 1994, the
daily said.
	   More than 100 Malaysian gamblers ran up debts totaling 60
million ringgit (dlrs 15 million) over the last four years in 10
casinos in Australia, a popular destination for rich Malaysians,
the daily said.
	   There is just one holiday resort in Malaysia that boasts of a
casino.
	   In 1995, a Las Vegas casino sued a Malaysian businessman to
recover a dlrs 1.3 million gambling debt.
</TEXT>
