<SLUG> BC-Bangladesh-Long March, 1st Ld-Writethru,0448 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bangladesh opposition begins long march amid tight security
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with march stalled, CLARIFIES that tens of
thousands, sted hundreds of thousands, were marching. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos DHA101-102 &QL; 
 &UR; By HASAN SAEED &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) _ A huge antigovernment protest was
stalled Tuesday on the outskirts of the Bangladeshi capital by a
road block of 100 trucks set up by supporters of Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina.
	   Some in the angry crowd of tens of thousands set fire to several
of the trucks that had been used to block the road, the protest
could not advance. Hasina had said she would let the march go ahead
_ it was not clear if she had ordered her supporters to put up the
barricade.
	   Former Prime Minister Khaleda Zia was leading the ``long march''
protest, scheduled over two days, to underscore opposition to a
peace accord she says gives away too much to tribal people in the
country's southeastern Chittagong Hill Tracts. The protesters were
headed mostly by car and truck 400 kilometers (250 miles) south to
the Chittagong region.
	   Zia has campaigned against the Hasina government since she lost
power in elections two years ago. In recent years, Bangladesh has
been plagued by almost daily strikes and political protests that
often erupt into violence.
	   Tuesday's standoff was potentially explosive, but there were no
immediate reports of violence beyond the burning of the trucks. It
was not clear how many government supporters were at the road
block, facing opponents shouting ``down with Sheikh Hasina!''
	   Protester Ashgar Ali, who owns a small business, said it could
take more than a day to clear the blockade. Many of the trucks had
deflated tires or no tires at all, and drivers of several trucks
had run away with the keys, he said.
	   Fearing unrest, drivers kept buses, trucks and private cars
stayed off the roads in the capital of Dhaka and the major southern
city of Chittagong. Across Bangladesh, some 50,000 police and
paramilitary troops have been put on alert, The Nation daily
reported.
	   Hasina reached a peace accord in December 1997, giving autonomy
to tribes in the Chittagong hills and ending two decades of
guerrilla war by Chakma separatists. The fighting over an area rich
in timber and minerals left more than 20,000 people dead.
	   Hasina has ``left the Chittagong Hill Tracts to the
terrorists,'' Zia said at a kickoff rally for the march in a Dhaka
sports stadium.
	   Zia's marchers had earlier been estimated at hundreds of
thousands, but it later became clear that it was closer to tens of
thousands
</TEXT>
