<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Abubakar Profile, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Abubakar, career serviceman, assumes power in Nigeria
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with details, background; CORRECTS day to Tuesday in
6th graf. ADDS byline. Edits throughout. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; With Nigeria-Abacha, Nigeria-Abacha-Reax &QL; 
 &UR; By GILBERT DA COSTA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) _ Hand-picked to be the latest in a long
line of army rulers in Nigeria, Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar is a
product of a military that rewards its own and honors unflagging
loyalty.
	   First as defense minister under military leader Gen. Ibrahim
Babangida and later chief of staff for the late Gen. Sani Abacha,
Abubakar, 55, emerges as first among equals in Nigeria's military
establishment.
	   A career serviceman, Abubakar became Nigeria's ninth military
ruler since independence from British colonial rule in 1960.
	   Even his first public words as head of state rang like a
military order.
	   ``All hands must be on deck to move this nation forward. I will
address the nation in due course,'' he said.
	   Promoted from major general to the full rank of general during a
predawn ceremony Tuesday, he was sworn in as head of state to
appoint him Nigeria's new head of state by chief justice Mohammed
Uwais.
	   Effectively the second ranking member of Nigeria's military
Provisional Ruling Council, Abubakar led the charge against the
former deputy leader Gen. Oladipyo Diya, who awaits his execution
after being found guilty in April of plotting a coup against
Abacha.
	   Abubakar oversaw the investigation into the alleged coup
charges.
	   Bespeckled and described as quiet, but friendly, he was often
pictured with Abacha, before the late leader's death of a heart
attack Monday.
	   Born June 13, 1942, in the town of Minna near the capital,
Abuja, and later sent off for schooling from 1957 to 1962 in the
nearby town of Bida.
	   Growing up during the heady buildup toward independence from
British rule in 1960, Abubakar later graduated from secondary
school and went on to study at the Kaduna Technical Institute
before joining the air force.
	   In the mid-1970s, he switched services and joined the army,
which sent him to the United States for formal training. Details of
his U.S. training weren't immediately known.
	   In 1981, Abubakar was appointed commander of a Nigerian
contingent attached to a U.N. peacekeeping force in Lebanon.
	   Through much of the 1980s, he served on routine domestic
military assignments until joining the Babangida's staff.
	   Abubakar is married and has two sons and three daughters.
 &UR; (var/ad/ids)
</TEXT>
