<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Malaria Death </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
First Singapore malaria death this year, dengue fever rises
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ A teenager became the first Singaporean to die
of malaria this year, while dengue fever, caused by a different
type of mosquito, also continues to rise, according to reports
Tuesday quoting the Environment Ministry.
	   The 15-year-old who died Saturday had contracted malaria while
visiting family members on the nearby Indonesian island of Batam.
	   One-third of the 27 malaria cases reported in Singapore from May
18 to June 7 were contracted in the Indonesian resort islands of
Batam or Bintan, according to statistics reported by The Straits
Times.
	   The total number of malaria cases this year has reached 147,
seven more than last year, and the teenager's death brought the
death toll to seven since last year. There were no deaths in
1995-96, the newspaper said.
	   Dengue fever cases continue to rise. The total reached 2,079 for
the first five months of this year, up from 1,285 in the same
period last year. Some types of dengue fever can be fatal.
 &UR; (lak) 	   
</TEXT>
