<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Unemployment, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede NUREMBERG
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; German unemployment rate drops for May &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: ADDS breakdown for east and west; RECASTS lead with
unemployment rate; ADDS byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By ANNE THOMPSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ Germany's jobless rate sank to 10.9
percent in May, the first drop below 11 percent since 1996, the
Federal Labor Office said Tuesday.
	   A total 4.2 million people were still unemployed, but 223,400
more people had jobs in May than in April, when the unemployment
rate was 11.1 percent.
	   ``We can't ignore the fact that 4.2 million people in Germany
are still looking for work,'' Labor Office President Bernhard
Jagoda said. ``The positive jobless development in May doesn't
allow us to sit back. It's only a nice intermediate goal which we
achieved.''
	   Compared to May of last year, 58,300 more people had jobs,
making it the first time since 1995 that unemployment figures have
improved on the year.
	   But the labor office, in Nuremberg, attributed the May jobless
decline in part to a usual economic upturn in the spring. When
adjusted for seasonal factors, such as bad weather that hinders
construction work, only 60,000 more people had jobs.
	   The labor office also said Germany had reached a turnaround in
joblessness in the western states, where unemployment dropped to
9.1 percent in May from 9.5 percent in April.
	   Jagoda noted some improvement in the former East Germany, where
unemployment has been twice that of the west. The May rate was 18.1
percent compared to 19.4 percent in April, although eastern states
still struggle in their transition from communism to capitalism.
	   Unemployment protests were planned for Tuesday around the
country, but smaller numbers were expected than in recent months.
Since January, protesters have been rallying outside unemployment
offices on the day labor numbers are announced.
	   Joblessness is the key issue in national elections Sept. 27.
Last week, Chancellor Helmut Kohl revealed the unemployment figures
early, saying the main goal of his political platform was ``to give
people who want to work the chance to work.''
	   (aet/cb) 	   
</TEXT>
