r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EU-China-Economy     06-09 0230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-China-Economy ,0230 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chinese trade minister: impact of Asian crisis ``far from over''
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ China's Foreign Trade Minister said
Tuesday the impact of the Asian economic crisis is ``far from
over,'' but insisted China would uphold the value of its currency
despite the regional turbulence.
	   ``The crisis does have inestimable implications for China that
have already resulted in a sharp decrease in exports to Southeast
Asia, Japan and South Korea,'' Shi Guangsheng told a China-European
Union trade seminar.
	   He said currency devaluations in Southeast Asian countries had
weakened China's export competitiveness, but stressed China would
not devalue its currency, the yuan.
	   He said China's policy of maintaining the yuan's value
``effectively prevented further deterioration of the Southeast
Asian economy.''
	   Shi said the Asian economic turmoil would not slow reforms to
open up China's economy. He said China will make ``all efforts'' to
achieve 8 percent economic growth this year, control inflation at
below 3 percent and hold the yuan steady.
	   ``We firmly believe the Asian crisis is only a transient
phenomenon and the affected countries will overcome the economic
hardships through efforts made by themselves and the region, and
with assistance from the world community,'' he added.
</TEXT>
