<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine peso strengthens; stocks dip on higher interest rates
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Late gains in the Japanese yen lifted
the Philippine peso and other Asian currencies higher against the
U.S. dollar Tuesday, dealers said.
	   Stocks, meanwhile, were pushed down by rising interest rates,
traders said.
	   The dollar averaged 39.470 pesos for the day, down from 39.649
pesos on Monday.
	   Dealers said the peso wasn't heavily affected in early trading
by the doll.
	   Commercial demand for dollars has been slack for several weeks
now. However, dealers say there is relatively heavy pent up demand
for the dollar at the 38.80-38.90 peso level.
	   In stock trading, the 30-share Philippine Stock Exchange Index
fell 6.10 points, or 0.3 percent, to 1,924.49 after losing 27.17
points Monday.
	   Yields of treasury bills rose Monday because of higher inflation
in May. The bellwether 91-day treasury bill increased to 13.953
percent after falling to a 10-month low of 13.798 percent last
week. Increases in longer-term bills were higher.
	   Securities 2000 analyst Erwin Balita said the rise in the
treasury bill rate has renewed worries over the prospects of
property companies, and the possibility that banks may face more
loan collection problems.
	   Sun Hung Kai research head Raul Ruiz said if the increase in
treasury rates proves to be a trend it could spell problems for the
economy.
	   ``If the uptrend in interest rates resumes, borrowers will once
again face rising financing costs, stalling any recovery in
investments and the economy in general,'' Ruiz said.
</TEXT>
