w2608 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AsianMarkets     06-09 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asian Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Asian stock markets close mostly lower
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Most Asian stock markets closed lower Tuesday,
but share prices in Tokyo rose because of optimism that Japanese
exports would rise in the face of a falling yen.
	   Tokyo's 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 235.46 points, or
1.52 percent, to close at 15,530.17. On Monday, the average shed
28.72 points, or 0.19 percent.
	   Exporters such as Sony Corp., Canon Inc. and Toyota Motor Corp.
led the rise in the Nikkei index.
	   In currency trading, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 140.36 yen,
down 0.20 yen from late Monday in Tokyo and below its New York
level overnight of 140.71 yen. During Tokyo trading, the dollar
rose as high as 141.11 yen, a level not seen since June 1991.
	   The dollar surrendered early gains amid speculation deputy
finance ministers from the Group of Seven largest economies meeting
later Tuesday in Paris may announce a joint effort to prop up the
Japanese currency.
	   In Hong Kong, share prices slumped as torrential rains forced
trading to be suspended for the morning session on the stock
exchange.
	   The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key indicator of
blue chips, fell 195.17 points, or 2.3 percent, to 8,391.46. On
Monday, the index had gained 17.16 points.
	   Brokers attributed the slump to worries about the weakening
Japanese currency, which investors feared could lead to a
devaluation of the Chinese yuan.
	   They said investors kept dumping red-chips, which are Hong
Kong-listed companies controlled by Chinese state-owned
enterprises.
	   Thai shares fell 1.3 percent to a new 11-year low amid growing
worries about the health of Thai financial institutions.
	   The Stock Exchange of Thailand index fell 4.12 points to 308.25
points, its lowest level since 1987.
	   Shares on the Taipei exchange also tumbled as the Taiwan dollar
fell to a new 11-year low of 34.715 to the U.S. dollar.
	   The Taiwan market's key Weighted Stock Price Index fell 135.64
points, or 1.8 percent, to 7,455.63.
	   Elsewhere:
	   SEOUL: Share prices closed lower on worries that the continued
depreciation of the Japanese yen may cause another financial crisis
in Asia. The Korea Composite Stock Price Index fell 6.66 points, or
1.9 percent, to 339.22.
	   KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian share prices closed higher on a
technical rebound following recent sharp losses. The Composite
Index, which tracks share prices of 100 key stocks, closed at
505.64 points, up 7.85 points, or 1.6 percent.
	   SINGAPORE: Share prices closed lower on selling by foreign
investors, who were unimpressed by banking reforms announced late
Monday. The Straits Times Industrials Index fell 1 percent, or
11.36 points, to 1,117.21.
	   WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed lower for the eighth
consecutive session. The NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 6.26 points, or
0.2 percent, to 2,098.14.
	   MANILA: Philippine shares closed slightly lower, pushed down by
by an uptrend in interest rates. The Philippine Stock Exchange
index of 30 selected stocks fell 6.10 points, or 0.3 percent, to
1,924.49.
	   SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed lower, with overseas
investors thought to be hanging back in case the weakened local
currency becomes cheaper still. The All Ordinaries Index fell 18.9
points, or 0.7 percent, to 2,623.9.
	   JAKARTA: Share prices closed generally lower, but late buying in
state-owned companies pushed the key index into positive territory.
The Composite index rose 1.653 points to 411.072. 	   
</TEXT>
