<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Eritrea-Ethiopia, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Erirea says Ethiopia attacks border town, Eritrea urges talks
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS lede to include Ethiopian denial that it attacked
first on Tuesday; CORRECTS style to Isaias on second reference to
Eritrean president; TRIMS; no pickup &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos ASM101-104 of June 8 &QL; 
 &UR; By KARIN DAVIES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) _ Eritrea claimed Tuesday that Ethiopia had
delivered on its threat to attack Eritrea again unless it withdrew
from disputed territory.
	   But an Ethiopian official said it was the Eritreans who struck
first at Ethiopian defensive lines south of the border town of Zala
Ambessa, 600 kilometers (372 miles) north of the Ethiopian capital,
Addis Ababa.
	   ``They came to attack in the morning, three times, regrouping
and attacking, regrouping and attacking,'' said Foreign Ministry
spokesman Yemane Kidane. He said the Eritreans suffered heavy
casualties.
	   With hostilities between the two Horn of Africa neighbors
escalating, the U.S. government prepared Tuesday to evacuate at
least another 120 of its citizens, along with Germans, Egyptians
and some Ethiopians.
	   Eritrea said the Ethiopians attacked Eritrean positions at dawn
with tanks and artillery in a bid to recapture Zala Ambessa, 105
kilometers (65 miles) southeast of Asmara. Eritrea took the town of
15,000 in a June 2-4 battle.
	   Eritrea on Monday called for direct talks in the presence of
high-level mediators ``so as to ensure a speedy resolution of the
crisis.''
	   President Isaias Afwerki's spokesman said Ethiopia had
effectively declared war on Eritrea and was using the threat of
renewed air strikes to blockade air and seaports.
	   Eritrea claims its forces are within internationally recognized
borders drawn by Italy in the late 19th century. Eritrea, an
Italian colony from 1885 to 1941, was annexed in 1962 by Ethiopia,
against whom it later fought a 30-year war for independence.
	   In Addis Ababa, Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi accused
the Eritreans of stalling to consolidate their positions inside
Ethiopia.
	   ``If that's the case _ and it appears to be the case _ then the
opportunities for resolving this problem peacefully could be fast
disappearing,'' he told The Associated Press.
	   Eritrea's Isaias indicated pride was an obstacle to resolving
the conflict, underscoring diplomats' concerns that the alliance
between his Eritrean People's Liberation Front and Meles' Tigray
People's Liberation Front to end 17 years of military rule in
Ethiopia in 1991 has soured.
	   ``We might be more concerned about pride, integrity, respect and
all that kind of thing _ trust, confidence. When you lose that, it
becomes a big problem for us in this region _ it's not always money
and resources,'' Isaias told The Associated Press late Monday.
	   ``If we can find a lasting, sustainable solution, then we will
have to think of reversing the process, building confidence again
and trying to work together, but it will take time and it will take
a lot of effort, in my opinion,'' he said.
	   With per-capita annual incomes of less than dlrs 300 a year,
Ethiopia and Eritrea are among the world's poorest countries.
	   African leaders deplored the Horn of Africa conflict at an
Organization of African Unity summit Monday in the West African
nation of Burkina Faso.
	   An Italian envoy at the OAU meeting talked with the foreign
ministers of Ethiopia and Eritrea and asked for a halt to further
bombing raids.
	   ``There's reason to believe that this will be heeded,'' the
Italian Foreign Affairs Ministry said.
	   The envoy, undersecretary of state for foreign affairs Rino
Serri, was expected to visit Asmara and Addis Ababa imminently, it
said.
	   The United States and Rwanda have crafted a four-point peace
proposal that would require Eritrea withdraw to positions it
occupied prior to May 6, when border skirmishes broke out. Ethiopia
has accepted the plan, but Eritrea says it needs more work.
	   Eritrea has vehemently denied Ethiopian charges that its attack
Friday on the Ethiopian town of Mekele provoked Ethiopian air
strikes on Asmara's military airport.
	   Eritrean Air Force Cmdr. Habtezion Hadgu said Ethiopia bombed
the Asmara airport first. ``This is tit for tat _ one to 100,
that's the exchange rate. They hit us, I hit them harder.''
	   Asmara-based diplomats confirmed the commander's version, saying
the airport attack occurred shortly after 2 p.m. (1100 GMT) Friday,
and 50 minutes later two Eritrean warplanes took off and headed
south.
	   (kjd/dc/sl)	   
</TEXT>
