w2621 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-EastTimor     06-09 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-East Timor </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesia prepared to grant special status to East Timor: report
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Indonesian President B.J. Habibie said
Tuesday he's prepared to grant special status within Indonesia to
the disputed territory of East Timor, the British Broadcasting
Corp. reported.
	   Giving details of an interview with Habibie, the BBC said the
new Indonesian president also said he's ready to release 10
Timorese fighters jailed by Indonesia, which invaded the former
Portuguese colony.
	   But Habibie made clear that the releases would not include the
jailed East Timorese leader Xanana Gusmao, the BBC reported.
	   Indonesia's regards Gusmao as a criminal, saying he has
committed violent acts in his fight against Indonesian rule in East
Timor. Gusmao is currently serving a 20-year prison term.
	   Other parts of Indonesia to enjoy special status include the
capital Jakarta, the deeply Muslim province of Aceh in north
Sumatra Island and the sultanate of Yogyakarta in Central Java.
	   The special status they enjoy gives their local government a few
privileges and powers ahead of other parts of the country.
	   Nevertheless, Habibie's comments appear to represent a softening
in policy toward East Timor following the resignation last month of
ex-Present Suharto.
	   Indonesian troops, under Suharto's orders, invaded the former
East Timor in 1975 after the Portuguese withdrew ending about 400
years of colonial rule.
	   In 1976 Suharto declared East Timor the 27th province of
Indonesia _ an act not recognized by the United Nations.
	   The United Nations does not recognize Indonesia's claim to
sovereignty. It has been sponsoring talks between Indonesia and
Portugal over the territory's future, but with little progress.
	   Under Suharto, Indonesia steadfastly refused to consider the
granting any special status or any form of local autonomy to East
Timor.
	   Suharto quit office last month and was replaced by Habibie,
raising hopes of a possible change in policy.
	   Last week U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan wrote to Habibie
asking that Gusmao be released.
	   Other foreign leaders, including South African President Nelson
Mandela have done the same.
	   Habibie, sworn in on May 21, has already released four other
political prisoners and has signalled that more will be released
soon.
	   Earlier on Tuesday Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said
Suharto's departure from politics has provided an opportunity for
Portugal, East Timorese separatists and Indonesia to resolve
conflicts over the disputed territory.
	   ``I think now is a good time to resolve our disagreement under
the auspices of the United Nations secretary general who has taken
the initiative over the years,'' Alatas said after a meeting with
Habibie.
	   In the past, Alatas has accused Portugal and the East Timorese
separatists, led by Nobel peace prize winner Jose Ramos-Horta, of
being inflexible.
</TEXT>
