<SLUG> BC-Finland-Baby Leave </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
It's official: prime minister to take time off for baby's birth
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HELSINKI, Finland (AP) _ Prime Minister Paavo Lipponen will
become the first Finnish government minister to take parental leave
for the birth of a child, officials said Tuesday.
	   The prime minister's office granted Lipponen six days father's
leave. His wife, Paivi Hertzberg, is due to give birth in several
months. The dates of Lipponen's leave were to be disclosed later.
	   During his leave, Lipponen will receive a paternity allowance
instead of his normal salary, as stipulated in the social security
act.
	   Lipponen, 56, married history teacher Hertzberg, 30, in January
after they lived together for more than a year.
	   Their wedding was the first by an incumbent prime minister since
Finland gained independence in 1917.
	   Finnish fathers are entitled to up to 18 days off from work
after a baby is born. Women are entitled to 105 paid days of
maternity leave.
	   (mhh-ewm)
</TEXT>
