<HEADLINE>
Chairmen of four ethnic parties send letter to Myanmar government
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   YANGON, Myanmar (AP) _ The chairmen of four ethnic minority
political parties have asked the head of Myanmar's military
government to begin a dialogue with the opposition and convene a
parliament elected in 1990.
	   The call was made in a letter to Gen. Than Shwe, chairman of the
ruling State Peace and Development Council, a copy of which was
received by The Associated Press on Tuesday.
	   It follows a resolution calling for the convening of parliament
passed nine days ago by Myanmar's main opposition party, the
National League for Democracy, led by Nobel Peace Prize winner Aung
San Suu Kyi.
	   Suu Kyi's party won a landslide victory in the 1990 election,
but the military never allowed those elected to parliament to meet
and take up their duties.
	   The largest party signing the letter to Than Shwe was the Shan
National League for Democracy. The other three parties represent
the Rakhine, Mon and Zomi ethnic groups.
	   Those three parties have officially been dissolved for reasons
that remain unclear, but their representatives elected in 1990
still claim status as members of parliament and regard themselves
as independents.
