<SLUG> BC-Uganda-Students killed </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rebels kill at least 60 students, abduct eight in western Uganda
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) _ Rebels killed at least 60 students and
abducted eight others in an attack at technical training school in
western Uganda, newspapers reported Tuesday.
	   The rebels from the Allied Democratic Forces rebels attacked
Kicwamba Technical College early Monday, locked the students in
dormitories and then set the buildings ablaze, the independent
daily Monitor said.
	   The attack occurred near the district headquarters of Kabarole,
about 316 kilometers (195 miles) west of Kampala.
	   ``The rebels' goal was to abduct all the students to bolster
their manpower,'' Monitor said. ``When some of them tried to resist
the abduction, the rebels set their dormitories on fire.''
	   The daily New Vision said seven people from the training college
were hospitalized after the attack, but it did not say whether they
were all students.
	   The government-owned newspaper quoted military spokesman Maj.
Shaban Bantariza as saying the rebels outnumbered the 40 government
soldiers stationed near the college.
	   The ADF appears to have no known political agenda other than
wanting to oust President Yoweri Museveni, himself a former rebel
leader.
	   The group has its base in the foothills of the Rwanzori
Mountains that former the border between Uganda and the Democratic
Republic of the Congo. They stage frequent attacks on Uganda's
western districts along the border. Some of the rebels are members
of former armies or groups defeated by Museveni's National
Resistance Movement in 1986.
	   The government is also fighting rebels from the West Nile Bank
Front in the northwest and from the Lord's Resistance Army in the
north.
