<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China studying U.S. invitation to observe military exercises
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ China is considering an invitation from the
United States to observe military exercises, a Chinese Foreign
Ministry spokesman said Tuesday.
	   The United States has asked China to attend naval exercises in
Hawaii or mock air force operations in Alaska next month.
	   ``The two sides are still in discussion on this matter,''
Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said at a routine media
briefing. He did not elaborate on the substance of the talks.
	   U.S. Embassy spokesman Bill Palmer called the invitation part of
an effort to improve communication between the Chinese and U.S.
militaries and not part of the discussions to prepare for the late
June summit in Beijing between presidents Bill Clinton and Jiang
Zemin.
	   The exercises are part of a series the U.S. military
periodically conducts jointly with other Pacific Rim nations,
Palmer said. He did not know what other nations would be
participating but said China would only attend as observers.
	   At their last meeting in Washington in October, Clinton and
Jiang agreed to procedures to avoid accidents or conflicts between
the U.S. and Chinese navies.
	   Allegations that a Chinese military officer donated money to
Clinton's Democrats and that Beijing may have acquired sensitive
missile information by launching U.S. satellites have raised doubts
about the president's China policy among members of Congress and
marred the atmosphere ahead of the visit.
	   Some members of Congress have called on him to cancel the trip,
the first by a U.S. president in nine years. The House of
Representatives has sought to confine Clinton's dealings with China
by passing amendments that would ban future launches and restrict
technology transfer to China.
	   Although Trent Lott, leader of the Senate's Republican majority,
has not endorsed the restrictions, on Monday he called the Clinton
administration's explanations of possible satellite technology
transfers inadequate.
	   Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu reiterated Tuesday that China did
not acquire any sensitive technology through its low-cost,
11-year-old commercial satellite launching program.
	   ``Such cooperation (with foreign companies) is in conformity
with international practices of formal business conduct,'' Zhu
said. ``There's no such problem of acquisition of technology during
the launching of satellites.''
</TEXT>
