<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Mir </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cash shortage could force Russia to abandon Mir this fall
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia may have to discard the Mir space station a
year ahead of schedule and send it crashing back to Earth this fall
unless the cash-strapped government comes up with more money,
officials said Tuesday.
	   ``We can't work with our bills unpaid,'' said Yuri Semyonov,
head of the state-run RKK Energia corporation, which built Mir and
has been running it since it was put in orbit in early 1986.
	   Semyonov said the government still owes Energia 440 million
rubles (dlrs 70 million) for station operations last year and
hasn't yet paid any bills this year, the ITAR-Tass news agency
reported.
	   The money shortage already threatens to stall the arrival of the
station's next crew, currently scheduled to blast off in August, he
said. If the trouble continues, space officials may decide to bring
down the station by the end of the year.
	   Russian space officials had planned to keep the 12-year-old Mir
flying until the end of 1999, after the first parts of the
international space station were placed in orbit.
	   Andrew Thomas, the last of seven American astronauts to live on
Mir, left the station on Monday. Following his departure, Russia
had hoped to earn more cash by hosting French and Slovak
astronauts, but that cooperation program is now in doubt, Semyonov
said.
	   Ironically, discarding Mir would cost more in the short run than
leaving it in orbit, the officials said. To control the station's
descent to Earth, Russia would have to launch several cargo ships
over a short period to dock with the station and direct it into
lower orbits.
	   ``Now we don't know what to do,'' Semyonov said.
	   According to an earlier plan, several Progress cargo ships,
docked one at a time, would fire their engines to gradually lower
the Mir's orbit from 400 kilometers (250 miles) now to 120
kilometers (75 miles), before it burns up in the atmosphere. A few
large fragments would be aimed to fall into the ocean.
	   If Mir's orbit isn't controlled, the 130-ton station will fall
back to Earth within two years on its own and pieces could land in
populated areas, space officials warned.
	   The government's cash shortage has also jeopardized Russia's
contribution to the new international space station and caused
several delays in the program already.
	   On Monday, Anatoly Kiselyov, director of the Khrunichev Company,
said the government has not paid the 1.3 billion rubles (dlrs 211
million) needed to prepare the critical service module for launch.
The service module contains the living quarters for the station's
crew.
	   The station's components are to be assembled in orbit and, if
everything goes as planned, the first American-led crew is expected
to board the station in July 1999, more than a year later than
originally planned.
	   The dlrs 21 billion space station is a joint project of Russia,
the United States, the European Space Agency, Canada and Japan.
	   (vi/mr) 	   
</TEXT>
