<HEADLINE>
Philippine car sales fall nearly 50 percent in first five months
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Sales of passenger cars in the
Philippines plunged nearly 50 percent in the first five months of
the year to 17,111 from the same period last year, an industry
association said Tuesday.
	   The Chamber of Automotive Manufacturers of the Philippines Inc.
attributed the sharp decline to higher prices resulting from the
peso's depreciation, larger down payment requirements, and stricter
financing rules.
	   The association said sales in May totaled only 2,951 cars, down
4 percent from April's 3,075 and 55 percent less than the 6,603
sold in the same month last year.
	   Honda Cars Philippines Inc., the local unit of the Japanese car
maker, led all other car assemblers, capturing nearly 26 percent of
the market.
	   Honda and other Japanese car makers _ Toyota, Mitsubishi and
Nissan _ together hold about 78 percent of the Philippine passenger
car market.
