<HEADLINE>
Albanian weapons depots: targets of looters and smugglers
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TIRANA, Albania (AP) _ Albanian soldiers opened fire and threw
hand grenades against a group of unidentified men who tried to loot
two army depots in northern Albania on Sunday, a Defense Ministry
spokesman said Tuesday.
	   In another incident, about 280 anti-tank missiles were stolen in
the town of Lezha, and police arrested two officers allegedly
involved in the robbery, local media reported Tuesday.
	   The armed clash started at 3 a.m. (0100 GMT) on Sunday when a
group of unidentified men attacked the depots in the villages of
Gjegjan and Gojan, 75 kilometers (47 miles) north of the capital
Tirana in the Fushe-Arrez area.
	   ``We were informed about the attack, and we sent more troops to
the area,'' said Albert Mullai, spokesman for the Defense Ministry.
	   He said hand grenades were used to keep the attackers away from
the depots. No one was wounded and police were still searching for
those who attacked.
	   On Sunday, few hours after the attack, Prime Minister Fatos Nano
told his National Security Council he had reports of more planned
attacks on army depots.
	   Albanian officials are concerned that while ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo are demanding more weapons to resist the Serb offensive,
Albania's army depots again have become targets of looters and
smugglers.
	   They have warned the Albanians that the areas of 70 depots were
mined last year after a million guns were looted by angry
protesters who lost their savings in collapsed pyramid schemes.
	   ``Any attempt to attack those depots would threaten the life of
about 35,000 people'' said Nano.
	   Sources at the Defense Ministry said that the guards of the army
depots have been orders to shoot anyone who tries to break in.
	   (md/rp) 	   
