<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Defense Debt </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai Defense Ministry struggling with huge foreign debt
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ With the Thai economy battered on all
fronts, the country's Defense Ministry is battling to pay off
millions of dollars in foreign debt for weapons purchases, a
ministry official said Tuesday.
	   The ministry owes between 4 billion and 5 billion baht (dlrs 95
million and dlrs 120 million) for imported weapons, and because of
budget cuts, doesn't have the means to pay, said the official who
spoke only condition of anonymity.
	   High-ranking Defense Ministry officials will meet with Finance
Ministry officials on Wednesday to try and devise a strategy for
solvency.
	   Lenders have already agreed to roll over between and 5 billion
and 10 billion baht (dlrs 120 million and 240 million) in debt held
by the ministry, The Bangkok Post reported.
	   Thailand is in the midst of its worst economic crisis in
decades, and that has forced the military to accept deep budget
cuts.
	   In the past, legislators feared asking the armed forces to scale
back expenditures because of its history of launching coup d'etats.
Thailand has had more than a dozen coups since the end of World War
II.
	   But the military has accepted the cuts without protest in light
of the economic crisis.
	   The budget difficulties of the armed forces were highlighted
earlier this year when the Thai government asked the United States
to let it out of a dlrs 392 million contract to buy eight F-18 jet
fighters because it could not afford to purchase them.
	   The United States agreed as long as Thailand could find another
buyer for the planes. So far, the Thais have been unable to do so.
</TEXT>
