<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Newspapers </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Major Chinese newspapers announce new media groups
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Mirroring trends in other industries, two of
China's state-run newspapers have announced they are setting up
media conglomerates, state media reported Tuesday.
	   The government is encouraging formation of such corporate groups
in a wide range of industries as part of its effort to make
state-ownedups enterprises profitable.
	   Newspapers, which are owned and controlled by the government,
are following suit.
	   The Guangming Daily is a Beijing-based Communist Party
enterprise that publishes newspapers, magazines and books and also
has various information industry businesses. The Economic Daily,
founded in 1983, likewise publishes newspapers and magazines
focused on business and financial news, the Beijing Youth Daily
reported.
	   Last month, another newspaper, the Southern Daily, based in
southern Guangdong province across the border from Hong Kong,
announced it was setting up a conglomerate.
	   The first newspaper to do so, the Guangzhou Daily, based in the
Guangdong provincial capital Guangzhou, set up its media group in
1995.
</TEXT>
