<SLUG> BC-AP Top Financial News,0772 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 1100 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Most Asian stock markets closed lower Tuesday,
but share prices in Tokyo rose on optimism that Japanese exports
would rise in the face of a falling yen. Tokyo's 225-issue Nikkei
Stock Average rose 235.46 points, or 1.52 percent, to close at
15,530.17. Exporters such as Sony Corp., Canon Inc. and Toyota
Motor Corp. led the rise in the Nikkei index. In Hong Kong, share
prices slumped as torrential rains forced trading to be suspended
for the morning session on the stock exchange. The Hang Seng Index,
the Hong Kong market's key indicator of blue chips, fell 195.17
points, or 2.3 percent, to 8,391.46. Brokers attributed the slump
to worries about the weakening Japanese currency, which investors
feared could lead to a devaluation of the Chinese yuan. They said
investors kept dumping red-chips, which are Hong Kong-listed
companies controlled by Chinese state-owned enterprises. (ASIAN
MARKETS)
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ In a potent sign of Asia's economic
crisis, Thailand's largest conglomerate _ which has more
investments in China than any other firm in the world _ has
announced a major restructuring. Charoen Pokphand Group revealed
late Monday it would consolidate 12 core agribusiness companies
into a single entity listed on the Stock Exchange of Thailand. The
move reflects the start of a back-to-basics strategy by a company
that over 70 years has became an Asian business empire and even
surfaced in the campaign contribution scandal that touched U.S.
President Bill Clinton. CP Group expanded during the Asian economic
boom into everything from chicken and shrimp farming to beer,
motorcycles and pharmaceuticals. Founded by Chinese immigrants to
Thailand, it is has plowed money back into the old country and is
the No. 1 investor in China in terms of projects. But analysts say
the expansion left the company overextended and heavily in debt
once the Asian boom went bust last year. (THAILAND-CP STRUGGLES)
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Pressure mounted on the government Tuesday to
stimulate Hong Kong's troubled economy, with some legislators
threatening to stop cooperating with the authorities if it turns
down their economic proposals. The warning came ahead of Financial
Secretary Donald Tsang's scheduled meeting later Tuesday with
political party leaders. ``We would withhold cooperation with the
government to force them to the negotiation table,'' said Lee
Cheuk-yan of the populist Frontier goup. ``We want to send the
government a message that there will be a constitutional crisis if
it ignore our demands.'' Impatient with the government, seven
political parties from across the political spectrum agreed at a
rare summit last week on a six-measure stimulus package, which
includes cuts in taxes and government fees and a refund of prepaid
taxes to boost consumer spending spending. (HONG KONG-ECONOMY)
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Labor officials ordered about 600
striking Philippine Airlines pilots to return to work Tuesday,
warning they would authorize the troubled airline to hire
replacements if the strike continues. The pilots' union, however,
refused the labor department's attempts to formally deliver the
back-to-work order and said it would continue the walkout. PAL
President Jose Antonio Garcia said the airline agreed to take the
strikers back if they complied with the new Tuesday deadline. On
Sunday it had fired all the striking pilots, calling their action
illegal. Garcia said the 4-day-old strike caused several potential
foreign buyers of the airline, including Northwest Airlines, to
break off talks and could force the airline to shut down.
(PHILIPPINES-AIRLINE STRIKE)
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Thailand will issue 50 billion baht
(dlrs 1.2 billion) in one-year bonds this week to help replenish
the country's bank rescue fund, a senior ministry official said
Tuesday. The bonds will be issued via the central bank to Thai
financial institutions and will carry a coupon rate of 12.5
percent, said Kamol Juntima, ministry comptroller-general. They are
the first installment of a planned 500 billion baht (dlrs 12
billion) domestic bond offering to help refinance the debts of the
Financial Institutions Development Fund. The fund is an arm of the
Bank of Thailand responsible for bailing out troubled financial
institutions reeling under bad debts and the Asian currency crisis.
(THAILAND-BONDS)
</TEXT>
