<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0637 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Scrambling to avoid a power vacuum in the
wake of Gen. Sani Abacha's unexpected death, the ruling military
moved quickly Tuesday to appoint another general as Nigeria's new
head of state. Abdulsalam Abubakar, wearing a beret and army green,
was sworn into office during a predawn ceremony, becoming the ninth
military leader in oil-rich Nigeria, Africa's most populous nation.
Although the immediate question of succession was answered, many
Nigerians were waiting to see if Abubakar would push forward with
some form of political transition to democratic rule this year.
Abacha in the final months of his life appeared again to be moving
away from his pledge to hand power over to an elected civilian
government. (NIGERIA-ABACHA)
	   ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) _ Ethiopia kept its promise Tuesday to
attack if Eritrea failed to withdraw its troops, launching a fresh
offensive to recapture a town on the border of the former allies.
The Ethiopian army attacked Eritrean positions in a bid to take
Zala Ambessa, 100 kilometers (65 miles) southeast of Asmara, the
Eritrean government said. Eritrea captured the town earlier this
month. The two East African nations are engaged in a battle over
their border. Ethiopia is resisting its smaller neighbor's attempts
to control territory it says is wrongly held by Ethiopia. The
Eritrean government on Monday called for direct talks between the
two countries in the presence of high-level mediators to find ``a
speedy resolution of the crisis.'' (ERITREA-ETHIOPIA)
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ Russian President Boris Yeltsin and his
ministers met with German officials Tuesday on how to prevent
escalating violence in the Serbian province of Kosovo. The talks
also focused on Russia's market collapse last month following an
oil-price drop. But Yeltsin and other Russian officials have
insisted publicly that they are not looking for any new aid or
funding. The two-day talks, the first in a series of periodic
German-Russian consultations agreed to by Yeltsin and Chancellor
Helmut Kohl last year, also focused on nuclear tests in Pakistan
and India and on whether to jointly build a military transport
plane. (GERMANY-RUSSIA)
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ South Korean President Kim Dae-jung is making
a triumphant return visit to the country that received him years
ago when he was down and out, barely escaping execution for his
dissident views in his native land. Almost 18 years ago, Kim was
under death sentence from the military government that ruled South
Korea at the time. The outgoing Carter and incoming Reagan
administrations interceded to save his life. On Tuesday night, Kim
will sit down with President Bill Clinton at a lavish White House
state dinner following a morning meeting with the president and a
State Department luncheon hosted by Vice President Al Gore. Once
considered a dangerous radical back home, Kim demonstrated his
comeback skills, not to mention endurance, by winning the
presidency in December. He was inaugurated at age 74 in February.
(US-KOREA)
	   PARIS (AP) _ Criticism of striking French pilots mounted Tuesday
as their walkout entered its ninth day, and Air France arranged to
transport soccer teams on special flights for the World Cup. No new
talks have been planned between Air France management and the
pilots, who are increasingly seen as the spoilers of French efforts
to stage the World Cup. Air France is the official carrier of the
World Cup, which opens Wednesday, and the airline has arranged 110
special flights to transport the teams to their destinations
throughout the tournament. (FRANCE-AIR FRANCE-STRIKE)
</TEXT>
