<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Russia, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yeltsin, Kohl meet on Russia's financial troubles, Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: New throughout with quotes from news conference &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos expected &QL; 
 &UR; By IAN MADER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ Russian President Boris Yeltsin said
Tuesday he was counting on ``personal support'' from Chancellor
Helmut Kohl, not direct aid, to help Russia recover from its latest
financial market turbulence.
	   Talks between the two leaders, which Kohl described as ``very
open,'' also touched on issues ranging from trade and security to
the crisis in the Serbian province of Kosovo.
	   At a joint news conference, Kohl quoted Yeltsin as saying he
would use his influence with Serbia to put a stop to the escalating
violence in the separatist region. Serbia and Russia are
traditional allies.
	   ``Everything has to be done to stop the bloodshed as soon as
possible,'' Kohl said.
	   German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel was also seeking Russian
backing for the European Union's decision Monday to punish Serbia
with economic sanctions for its attacks on villages in Kosovo.
	   But asked Monday night whether Moscow would support the ban on
investment in Serbia and a freeze of its foreign assets, Russian
Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov said: ``No, I don't think so.''
	   Kremlin spokesman Sergei Yastrzhembski said Russia and other
European nations need to address the Kosovo conflict ``as a team''
to prevent other nations from being drawn into the fighting.
	   The main focus of the two-day talks, however, was last month's
market collapse in Russia following an oil-price drop. The crisis
had raised speculation that Germany, Russia's most important
trading partner outside the former Soviet Union, might offer
financial assistance, although Russian officials have insisted
publicly that they are not looking for any new aid.
	   Asked at the news conference whether German aid was discussed,
Yeltsin said it was most important to obtain ``personal support
from Helmut Kohl as a great political figure'' to support Russia's
reform policies.
	   ``On this basis, international investors won't leave our
country,'' he added.
	   Kohl said Germany plans to continue its support for Russia
within an international framework, in particular with the
International Monetary Fund.
	   An IMF official in Washington, Stanley Fischer, said that the
organization didn't see any immediate reason to boost an existing
dlrs 9.2 billion credit arrangement with Russia.
	   The talks were the first in a series of periodic German-Russian
consultations agreed to by Yeltsin and Kohl last year, when Kohl
helped negotiate Russia's acquiescence to the eastward expansion of
the NATO military alliance.
	   Ministers of finance, economics, foreign affairs, defense and
nuclear energy met separately with their counterparts on a broad
range of security and trade issues. Yeltsin also met with German
opposition chancellor candidate Gerhard Schroeder.
	   Shortly after arriving in Bonn, Russian and German ministers
signed two agreements dealing with cooperation in the nuclear power
industry.
	   Cooperation in the defense industry also was on the agenda.
Ukraine has been trying to enlist Germany, Russia and France to
help build a new Ukrainian version of the Antonov An-70 aircraft.
 &UR; (im/cb/pfg)
</TEXT>
