<HEADER>
w2663 &Cx1f; wstm-
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Soccer-Koreas     06-09 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Koreas,0612 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: South Korean chief organizer hopeful about joint team,
</HEADLINE>
North role in 2002 &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: INCORPORATES material from Seoul-dated
Sports-Soccer-2002-World Cup &QL; 
 &UR; By LARRY SIDDONS &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ The chief South Korean organizer of the 2002 World
Cup said Tuesday he was optimistic that a host role for North Korea
and a joint team for the tournament could be worked out.
	   Park Seh-jik, chairman of the Korean Organizing Committee, said
a recent lessening of tensions between the capitalist south and
communist north on the divided peninsula have improved the chances
of agreement on World Cup involvement.
	   Park was president of the organizing committee for the 1988
Olympics in Seoul and was involved in years of frustrating and
ultimately unsuccessful efforts to meet North Korean demands to
stage some part of the Summer Games. He said things have changed
drastically, even though the two nations remain technically at war.
	   ``The situations in 1988 and now are quite different,'' Park
said. ``The tensions are very much reduced. We are looking for a
positive answer from North Korea.''
	   A high-ranking North Korean soccer official, meanwhile, said in
a published interview that his country could consider sharing World
Cup matches.
	   ``We are not in a stage to discuss details yet, but in
principle, it is very desirable to form a single team and for North
Korea to hold some games,'' Choi Pyong Joo, vice president of North
Korea's soccer association, said in an interview with South Korea's
Sports Seoul newspaper.
	   In Seoul, officials of the Korean Football Association said they
had received government approval to discuss sharing some matches in
2002 with the north and forming a unified team. They said a letter
would be sent soon to Pyongyang asking for a meeting where
negotiations could begin.
	   Such contact also could take up the issue of promoting regular
sports exchanges between the two sides, they said.
	   Choi and Park were both in Paris a day before the start of the
World Cup, where South Korea is playing for the fourth straight
tournament. North Korea did not qualify.
	   At a news conference Saturday, Joao Havelange, the outgoing
president of the international soccer federation FIFA, said he
would like to see a joint Korean team and some matches of the 2002
tournament staged in Pyongyang's 100,000-seat stadium. A joint
Korean team played in the last under-16 world championships in
Portugal and FIFA said it was ready to follow that path again.
	   ``There is precedence for that, although, of course, there is a
huge difference between youth soccer championships and the World
Cup,'' federation spokesman Keith Cooper said. ``That is strictly a
matter for the two national (soccer) associations to decide.''
	   The 2002 World Cup already has to deal with logistical problems,
since it's being shared by South Korea and Japan _ the first time
the world's biggest single sports event will be split between
countries.
	   South Korea will play host to half the games, 32 in all, and any
games in Pyongyang would come from that batch.
	   Because of the existing limits, Park said, it was imperative
that any negotiations with the north not drag out as they did a
decade ago.
	   ``It is very complicated, so the sooner, the better,'' he said.
	   At the same time, Park said, there was enough time to work out
details of the north's role and bring facilities in the
impoverished country up to international standards.
	   ``We still have a full five years, so any complications could be
solved,'' he said.
</TEXT>
