<SLUG> BC-China-Yugoslavia-Kosovo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China calls Kosovo Yugoslavia's problem but urges dialogue
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ While calling the fighting between Serb forces
and ethnic Albanian separatists in Yugoslavia's Kosovo province a
domestic matter, China urged both sides Tuesday to negotiate a
settlement.
	   ``The Kosovo problem is the internal affair of Yugoslavia. It
should be addressed by relevant authorities in Yugoslavia through
political means,'' Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao
said.
	   Zhu said efforts by Albanians in Kosovo to open a dialogue with
the government were in the best interests of stability and should
be supported by the international community.
	   After E.U. diplomats got a glimpse of the devastation over the
weekend, the United States and European Union both tightened
sanctions against Serb-dominated Yugoslavia Monday, freezing its
assets and banning investments.
	   China has steadfastly resisted imposing sanctions on other
countries. As one of five permanent members of the U.N. Security
Council, China sought to limit the body's response to punishing
Yugoslavia, a Cold War ally, during its earlier conflicts with the
former provinces of Croatia and Bosnia.
</TEXT>
