<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Military </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Taiwan to inaugurate electronic warfare force
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ Seeking to plug a hole in its defenses,
Taiwan's air force will inaugurate a flight wing dedicated to
electronic warfare in July, a senior officer said Tuesday.
	   Tang Ting, the air force's deputy chief of planning announced
the formation of the wing at a weekly Defense Ministry news
conference, but provided no other details.
	   The move follows repeated public fretting by the military over
what it says is China's advantage in using electromagnetic
interference to scramble missile targeting and communications
between fighting units.
	   Defense Minister Chiang Chung-ling told legislators last month
that China could disrupt Taiwan's communications during a conflict
and win control of the electronic battlefield over the Taiwan
Strait.
	   Major Chinese military units are capable of electronic
surveillance and interference, while its air force has more than 10
electronic warfare planes and navy vessels have also been outfitted
for such missions, Chiang said.
	   Though they've been united for just four of the last 100 years,
China claims sovereignty over Taiwan and threatens to use its
massive military to bring the island back into the fold.
	   The United Evening News reported the air force this year
received a second Lockheed C-130H converted to C-130HE electronic
warfare specifications. Another of the converted planes is likely
to be added to the wing, the paper said.
	   It said the Defense Ministry's Chungshan Institute of Science
and Technology carried out the conversions.
	   Newspapers have also reported Taiwan plans to further upgrade
the planes' signal interception and jamming capabilities.
	   Those reports said the air force's four Grumman E-2T Hawkeye
early-warning planes will also be more closely linked to military
information networks.
	   Aged RF-104 Starfighter reconnaissance planes have also been
replaced by RF-5Es, former jet fighters converted by the air force.
</TEXT>
