<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Malaysia-Pirates </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Malaysia to seek Indonesian pirates' extradition from China
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Malaysia is seeking to extradite 12 Indonesians
held by China in connection with the April hijacking of the Petro
Ranger, a Malaysian-registered oil tanker, a newspaper reported
Tuesday.
	   Malaysia and China have an extradition treaty, and the Malaysian
government has notified Beijing that the Indonesians are being
sought on charges or armed robbery, The Business Times quoted an
official of the International Maritime Bureau in Kuala Lumpur as
saying.
	   ``This will be the first test case involving an action by a flag
state against crimes committed by such hijackers on the high seas
in which a coastal state was powerless to act,'' the maritime
bureau's director, P. Mukundun, was quoted as telling Lloyd's List.
	   As the coastal state, where the hijacked ship and its crew were
discovered on April 26, China has the first option of trying the 12
Indonesians who were taken into custody.
	   The ship and its crew of 21 were released on May 30 after a
Chinese investigation, but there has been no word about charging
the Indonesians.
	   They are alleged to have hijacked the Petro Ranger as it sailed
from Singapore to Ho Chi Minh City on April 17, and offloaded most
of its 10,000 tons of gas oil and kerosene, worth 2.4 million
Singapore dollars (dlrs 1.4 million) to another vessel in Chinese
waters, according to various news reports.
	   Neither the ship's agents in Singapore nor the Chinese
authorities have said what happened to the cargo.
	   Chinese maritime authorities escorted the tanker to the port of
Haikou, holding it and the crew for more than a month.
</TEXT>
