w2694 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Rwanda-Tribunal     06-09 0381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Rwanda-Tribunal </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rwanda tribunal adopts procedures to speed up genocide trials
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ Judges at the International Criminal
Tribunal for Rwanda have adopted new procedures to speed up trials
of defendants charged in the 1994 genocide in Rwanda, the court
said Tuesday.
	   The measures were adopted after a plenary session of the six
judges sitting on the tribunal in the northern Tanzanian town of
Arusha and an additional five visiting from the Appeals Chamber of
the International War Crimes Tribunal on the former Yugoslavia in
The Hague.
	   Procedures adopted include pre-trial discussion between the
prosecution and the defense to decide which issues are uncontested.
	   This would enable judges to shorten the time needed for
questioning witnesses or to dispense with them altogether, a
statement from the tribunal said.
	   Judges will also have more power to control the questioning and
cross-examination of witnesses and to receive written testimony if
neither the defense nor the prosecution objects.
	   The judges also decided that defense attorneys should have at
least 10 years experience in order to provide the defendants with
adequate legal representation.
	   The U.N. tribunal has been criticized, especially by Rwandan
authorities, for being too slow.
	   The tribunal was established in November 1994 and won its first
conviction May 1 when former Rwandan Prime Minister Jean Kambanda
pleaded guilty and offered to testify against ringleaders of the
three-month slaughter. At least 500,000 people, mostly minority
Tutsis, were stabbed, shot, bludgeoned or hacked to death.
	   The first verdict is expected this month. The tribunal has
indicted 35 people and is holding 24 defendants in custody.
	   There are 130,000 genocide suspects imprisoned in Rwanda. Many
have not been formally charged. Rwandan began trying the suspects
in December 1996, and to date, 350 people have been convicted of
varying degrees of crimes against humanity and genocide.
	   A third were sentenced to death, most others received prison
sentences and a small number have been acquitted. The first 22
convicts were executed by firing squad on April 24.
	   The heaviest penalty the Arusha tribunal can impose is life in
prison.
	    &UR; (HO-cm)	   
</TEXT>
