r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-Centennia     06-09 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Centennial Guests </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Only one head of government to attend Philippine centennial
</HEADLINE>
celebration &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Only one foreign head of government
will join the foreign dignitaries at the centennial of the
Philippines' declaration of independence from Spanish rule,
officials said Tuesday.
	   Limited overseas publicity and a strike by Philippine Airlines
pilots will mean that the number of foreign tourists and overseas
Filipinos attending Friday's celebrations will also be lower than
hoped.
	   Governor General Silas Atopare of Papua New Guinea will be the
only head of government among the representatives of 32 countries,
the Department of Foreign Affairs said.
	   The Philippines was a Spanish possession for 333 years, from
1565 to 1898.
	   On June 12, 1898, Gen. Emilio Aguinaldo, a former mayor who
became the republic's first president, declared the Philippines'
independence from Spain at a house in Cavite province, south of
Manila.
	   Before the Philippines could gain independence, however, the
United States acquired it after defeating Spain in the 1898
Spanish-American War.
	   The Philippine government, helped by private companies, is
spending at least 3.5 billion pesos (dlrs 92 million) on the
centennial celebrations, which are to be highlighted by a trade and
historical exposition at the Clark Special Economic Zone, a former
U.S. air base in northern Pampanga province.
	   The United Nations will send Undersecretary General Adrianus
Mooy while the United States will be represented by its former
ambassador to Manila, Nicholas Platt, the department said.
	   Most countries in the Association of Southeast Asian Nations, of
which the Philippines is a member, will send a representative,
along with Spain, Cuba, China, Libya, Nicaragua, Britain and
Australia. Many will be Cabinet members.
	   The dignitaries are expected to attend ceremonies in Cavite,
visit trade exhibits in Clark and watch a parade and fireworks
display in Manila. President Fidel Ramos will host a dinner for the
guests Friday.
	   Police plan to tightly guard the government parade and other
centennial activities, which are expected to draw large crowds of
people.
</TEXT>
