<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai stocks at new 11-year low on financial fears; baht rises
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Thai stock prices dipped 1.3 percent to
a new 11-year low Tuesday amid growing worries about the health of
Thai financial institutions as the economy shrinks.
	   The Stock Exchange of Thailand index fell 4.12 points from
Monday to 308.25 points, its lowest level since 1987 and nearing
the psychological threshold of 300 points.
	   The baht meanwhile ended stronger against the U.S. dollar at
42.95, compared to 43.35 on Monday, as foreign funds holding long
positions on the dollar sold to take profit.
	   Dealers attributed the shares slump to investor gloom about
prospects for Thailand's financial markets in the medium term. The
government so far has shown little alarm about the decline of the
currency in recent weeks.
	   ``There are a lot of fears over the health of the finance
industry and over the implementation of new guidelines of the Bank
of Thailand for debt restructuring,'' said Stuart Matthews, head of
research at Deutsche Morgan Grenfell Securities.
	   Foreign investors are reluctant to buy stocks given the
likelihood the Thai currency may continue to decline, Matthews
said.
	   The Thai central-bank governor said last week he considers 43 to
45 baht to dlr 1 an acceptable range, leading investors to worry
the baht may be allowed to drop to 45.
</TEXT>
