<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Yen </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Official: Weakening yen bad for China but no devaluation ahead
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Although the weakening Japanese yen is
complicating Chinese economic growth prospects, China's central
banker vowed Tuesday not to devalue the Chinese yuan.
	   The depreciating yen ``is having a very negative impact on
Chinese imports and exports and the utilization of foreign
capital,'' People's Bank of China governor Dai Xianglong said in a
speech at a symposium on Asia's financial crisis.
	   Slacker exports and less hard currency coming in will make it
more difficult for China to get protected state industries to
compete in the market, Dai admitted. The Chinese government says it
needs the economy to grow by 8 percent this year to help generate
jobs for millions of laid-off state workers.
	   Despite the added difficulties, Dai said China would keep to a
pledge not to devalue. Made after financial turmoil began hammering
Asian currencies nearly a year ago, the pledge has been praised
worldwide as a stabilizing factor.
	   Dai also reiterated that the 8 percent growth target was still
attainable, despite a relatively strong currency. He projected that
fixed-asset investment will grow more than 15 percent this year,
five percentage points higher than last year and a rate many
economists say is crucial to revive flagging growth.
	   The State Statistical Bureau on Tuesday said China's value-added
output for the first five months climbed 7.9 percent from the same
period a year ago _ well below the 10.5 percent level some
officials have said China must maintain to reach the growth target.
</TEXT>
