<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Chemical Warfare,0332 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Apartheid scientist made ecstasy
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By PAUL HARRIS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ A former apartheid scientist
confessed Tuesday to running a secret government program that made
912 kilograms of the drug ecstasy with a street value of up to 1
billion rand (dlrs 200 million).
	   Testifying before a panel probing apartheid abuses, Dr. Johan
Koekemoer described working in 1992 for an army front company and
being asked to make the drug as part of a chemical warfare project.
	   The Truth and Reconciliation Commission is holding a weeklong
session on chemical and biological warfare projects set up by the
South African Defense Force during apartheid.
	   Koekemoer told the panel that he suspected his superiors might
be dealing privately in the drug after telling him it was to be
used to incapacitate enemies of the white-run state. Ecstasy has a
reputation for giving users a feeling of bliss and happiness.
	   Koekemoer said he confronted his superiors with his doubts, but
they assured him the drug was to be used for military purposes.
	   ``I was just a bit suspicious,'' he said. ``I would not like to
kiss my enemy, but rather work on his central nervous system so he
can't operate properly.''
	   Aiming to shed light on the murky world of espionage and secret
weapons projects, the hearings are focused on the activities of Dr.
Wouter Basson, who headed the army's Seventh Medical Battalion,
which ran biological and chemical weapons programs through a
sophisticated network of front companies.
	   Basson was forced to resign from the army in 1993 after a
government report accused him of making poisons and chemical bombs.
He is being investigated on charges of making and possessing
ecstasy and mandrax drugs. Basson is expected to testify later this
week.
	   The commission was set up by President Nelson Mandela in 1995 to
uncover the truth about apartheid crimes and promote racial
healing. 	   
</TEXT>
