w2718 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Italy-Politics-NATO     06-09 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Politics-NATO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Opposition says it won't support government on NATO vote
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By VANIA GRANDI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Silvio Berlusconi's main ally in the center-right
opposition confirmed Tuesday that the alliance won't bail out
Premier Romano Prodi's government on a crucial vote later this
month on NATO.
	   Without the support of the media mogul's Freedom Alliance,
Prodi's center-left coalition risks losing the vote and thus facing
a vote of confidence.
	   While Berlusconi and his allies support NATO's eastward
expansion, they have announced their refusal to come to the rescue
of the government yet again in the face of the governing
coalition's difficulties with its troublesome Communist allies.
	   Fausto Bertinotti's Communist Refoundation party which Prodi
counts on for a majority in the Chamber of Deputies, where a vote
on NATO is planned the week of June 22, has repeatedly said it will
vote against the military alliance's expansion.
	   Boosted by a strong showing for the center-right in scattered
local elections last weekend, Berlusconi said Monday he wanted to
``send Prodi and his government home.''
	   ``We don't want to bail Prodi out in any way,'' Gianfranco Fini,
leader of the rightwing National Alliance, a key ally in
Berlusconi's coalition, told reporters.
	   However, both opposition leaders have said they support NATO
expansion in principle, and it is unlikely they will ultimately
stop Italy from approving the addition of new countries.
	   Among the options to the opposition is one in which Berlusconi's
alliance would vote against Prodi's bill but propose another
version that changes only minor points while approving NATO
expansion.
	   Bertinotti pushed the government to the brink of collapse last
year when it voted against Italy's plans to send peacekeeping
troops to Albania, but Berlusconi's coalition bailed out Prodi
then.
	   A top Prodi aide, Enrico Micheli, asserted that the government
would be capable of ``defending themselves against this attack'' by
the center-right.
	   ``If this government must be sent packing, it won't be decided
by this thing or that. It will be the country, and it seems to me
that Italians are far from taking such a decision,'' Micheli said.
	   Prodi's coalition suffered a setback Tuesday with the formal end
of parliamentary efforts on political reform, a key plank of the
government.
	   ``It's not a happy day,'' said Sen. Cesare Salvi, a former
Communist, about the failure of a two-chamber commission on reform
to produce results.
	   Refusal by Berlusconi to back the government's proposal for
changing the powers of the Italian president brought collapse of
the reforms.
	   (fd)
</TEXT>
