w2720 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Belarus-US 2ndLd-Writethru   06-09 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Belarus-US, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Officials defend plan to evict ambassadors, apologize for
</HEADLINE>
`inconvenience' &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Lithuania recalling ambassador, EDITS. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo MIN101-2 &QL; 
 &UR; By MARINA BABKINA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MINSK, Belarus (AP) _ The U.S. ambassador and other envoys were
refusing Tuesday to budge after the Belarusian government said they
had to leave their residences to allow repairs and renovations.
	   The Foreign Ministry expressed regret for the ``inconvenience,''
but said 22 ambassadors have to vacate their homes in a diplomatic
complex on the outskirts of the capital, Minsk, for long overdue
repairs.
	   A long statement said the homes built just after the World War
II were in poor condition, the water supply was no longer safe and
the sewage system was polluting the environment.
	   Diplomatic missions had been offered apartments in downtown
Minsk to accommodate staff while those willing to build their own
residences would be offered plots, the ministry said late Monday.
	   The Belarusian government served notice in April that it wanted
to overhaul water and sewage pipes in the diplomatic complex and
gave the ambassadors until June to leave.
	   Diplomats protested, saying they would prefer to make
arrangements to remain in the complex during the repairs. They
noted that the government's decision was sudden, and that some
embassies had signed new multi-year leases just the month before.
	   Under international law, ambassadors' residences are considered
sovereign territory and governments have no right to enter without
permission or insist that diplomats leave.
	   U.S. Ambassador Daniel Speckhard called a news conference Monday
and said he and a number of other ambassadors would not leave their
homes, and appealed to President Alexander Lukashenko to rescind
the order.
	   When he returned home after the news conference accompanied by
camera crews, he found a team of workers and a policeman trying to
weld shut the side gate. The workers left when Speckhard protested.
	   ``To lock ambassadors into their residences and weld their door
shut is not becoming to the dignity of your country,'' Speckhard
said.
	   He called the incident the most serious violation of the Vienna
Convention on diplomatic relations since the end of the Cold War.
	   Speckhard said that he doesn't doubt that some repairs are
needed, but insisted that the government must reach agreements with
the foreign missions and cannot simply evict them.
	   Speckhard said the United States has had a lease on the
residence since 1992, the year after Belarus gained independence
with the collapse of the Soviet Union. The lease does not expire
until 2001.
	   If the government forcibly evicts the ambassadors, it would be
the first violation of the Vienna Convention since Iranian
militants seized the U.S. Embassy in Tehran in 1979, an embassy
spokeswoman said.
	   Russia and Lithuania also protested the planned eviction on
Tuesday. Russia's Foreign Ministry voiced ``deep concern'' over the
incident, and Lithuania recalled its envoy in protest, according to
the Interfax news agency.
	   (mb/mr)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Belarus-US, 2nd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
