<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Jordan-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
King Hussein to meet President Clinton in Washington on Monday
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ King Hussein left Tuesday on a tour of
Britain and the United States, including a stop in Washington for
talks with President Clinton on the stalled Middle East peace
process.
	   A Royal Palace official said Hussein's first stop will be
Washington, where he is scheduled to meet with President Clinton in
the White House next Monday. But before that, he's expected to have
a series of discussions with Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
and other administration officials.
	   ``The Washington meetings will focus on ways to push forward the
peace process and prevent it from collapsing,'' said the palace
official, who spoke on customary condition of anonymity.
	   King Hussein, Israel's closest Arab friend since the 1994
Jordanian-Israeli peace treaty, has become increasingly critical of
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's tough stance with the
Arabs.
	   Hussein is eager to see an Israeli-Palestinian settlement to
ease opposition among his predominantly Palestinian population to
his own peace treaty with Israel.
	   The Palace official said after Washington, Hussein will go to
Boston to attend the high school graduation of his 16-year-old
daughter Iman.
	   He will later travel to Rochester, Minn., for routine medical
checkups he has been undergoing since a 1992 cancer surgery.
	   Hussein will later go on a private visit to England, where he
has residence in Ascot outside London.
