w2737 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WorldCourt-FisheryDis     06-09 0449
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-World Court-Fishery Dispute </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Spain demands compensation from Canada in fishery dispute before
</HEADLINE>
World Court &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ In a long-running fishery dispute,
Spain Tuesday demanded compensation from Canada for the 1995
seizure of a Spanish trawler and backed the World Court's
jurisdiction to rule in their conflict.
	   Spain presented its arguments on the opening day of hearings to
examine whether the U.N. court has jurisdiction to hear the case.
	   Spain took Canada to court in March, 1995 after the
highly-publicized seizure of the Spanish trawler Estai in
international waters by Canadian officials. The Estai's captain was
also arrested.
	   Canada claimed the boat was fishing endangered turbot and using
small-mesh gear, as well as underreporting its catch.
	   Canadian officials made the arrest based on a national law which
allowed its authorities to seize ships in international waters if
they believe vessels are overfishing.
	   But Spain claims Canada violated international laws protecting
freedom of navigation and freedom of fishing on the high seas.
	   Spain's sovereignty was also under attack since the Estai was
sailing under its flag, said Spain's agent Jose Antonio Pastor
Ridruejo, who described Canada's actions as ``armed coercion.''
	   ``It is Canada's legislation which is attacking us,'' said
Ridruejo, in his opening statement. ``It is infringing on the
sovereignty of Spain because it is attacking our flag.''
	   ``We ask Canada to stop repeating its acts ... and provide us
with proper compensations,'' added Ridruejo.
	   He did not specify what kind of compensation Spain is seeking.
	   The incident, which occurred on March 9, 1995 in international
waters in the Grand Banks off Newfoundland, wrecked relations
between the two countries, but Canada claimed the dispute has long
been resolved through an agreement with the European Union on fish
stock conservation and management.
	   But Spain insists the court, the U.N.'s highest judicial organ,
must ``look at the wrongfulness of the actions of Canada.''
	   ``Canada has no legal international title to act in such a way
on the high seas as regard to a vessel flying a Spanish flag,''
said Ridruejo.
	   Representatives of Canada's legal team declined comment ahead of
their presentations on Thursday. They are expected to challenge the
court's authority to rule in the matter.
	   The current round of hearings, which will last six days, deals
only with the court's jurisdiction and not on the actual merits of
the case.
	   The World Court, officially known as the International Court of
Justice, has no enforcement powers.
	   (jc/mc)
</TEXT>
