<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-RugbyU-Australian Barbarians-Scotland </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Scotland loses to Barbarians
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Scotland lost its first match on the
Australian leg of its southern rugby tour when beaten 39-34 by
Australian Barbarians at Penrith on Tuesday.
	   The Barbarians, made up of Super 12 regulars but with no current
test players, scored six tries to five with Ricky Nalatu getting a
brace.
	   Scotland fielded a mostly second string side as test fullback
Derrick Lee scored a double.
	   Queensland's Shane Drahm made a significant contribution after
coming on as a substitute, scoring a try, two conversions and a
penalty.
	   With the scores at 32-22 and 10 minutes left, fly-half Drahm,
who replaced Elton Flatley, closed out the match with a spectacular
solo 70-meter try.
	   The Scots scored two late tries to set up a nervous last two
minutes and they nearly stole the match when the ball was kicked
through but went dead just as referee Wayne Erickson blew
full-time.
	   The match was the last for the tourists before Saturday's first
test against Australia in Sydney. Scotland's only other test so far
on tour was a 51-26 loss to Fiji in Suva.
	   Scorers: Australian Barbarians 39 (Ricky Nalatu 2, Pat Howard,
John Langford, Ipolito Fenukitau, Shane Drahm tries; Shane Drahm 2
goals, Elton Flatley 1 goal, 1 pen goal) def. Scotland 34 (Derrick
Lee 2, Jamie Mayer, Ian Jardine, Adam Roxburgh tries; Duncan Hodge
3 goals, 1 penalty goal).
 &UR; (tjh)
</TEXT>
