w2746 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Guinea-Bissau     06-09 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Guinea-Bissau </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rebel general urges president to step down, calls for transition
</HEADLINE>
government, elections &QL; 
 &UR; By BARRY HATTON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ The leader of renegade soldiers locked
in battle Tuesday with government troops in the West African nation
of Guinea-Bissau urged President Joao Bernardo Vieira to step down.
	   Former armed forces chief Brig. Gen. Ansumane Mane, in a
handwritten statement sent to the Portuguese news agency Lusa, said
a transition government should be installed to prepare for
elections in July.
	   Mane, describing himself as head of a military junta, said he
had no intention of seizing power himself.
	   Mane's statement came after government troops launched an
unsuccessful pre-dawn attack aimed at dislodging rebel forces from
positions they held in the capital.
	   The general, fired six months ago during an investigation into
arms trafficking with the separatist rebels of Casamansa, a
Senegalese province that borders Guinea-Bissau to the north, had
waited until Saturday to officially step down.
	   There was no immediate reaction available from the president,
who had vowed Sunday to ``use all possible means'' to quash the
revolt swiftly.
	   But Foreign Minister Fernando Delfim da Silva called Mane's
appeal for July elections ``a joke.'' Da Silva was interviewed by
phone in Lisbon, where he was stuck because of flight cancellations
to Guinea-Bissau.
	   Delfim da Silva said the two military sides were ``deadlocked.''
	   ``The rebels are hemmed in. They're not advancing, but we can't
get them out either,'' he said.
	   Heavy fighting could be heard at two military installations in
the Bissau suburb of Bra and around the army headquarters in the
suburb of Queije, U.S. embassy spokesman Bryan Hunt said in a
telephone interview with the Lisbon bureau of The Associated Press.
	   The fighting began at 5.30 a.m. (0530 GMT) and lasted about 30
minutes, Hunt said.
	   ``The major offensive by government troops ... was unsuccessful
as far as we can tell. The situation is very unsettled,'' Hunt
said.
	   Guinea Bissau's ambassador in Lisbon said the military situation
was ``deadlocked.''
	   ``The rebels are entrenched in Bra. Loyalist troops have been
trying to dislodge them but they haven't been successful so far,''
Ambassador Jose Baptista said in an interview.
	   Streets around the two areas, which were seized by an unknown
number of rebel soldiers early Sunday, were blocked off. However,
diplomats housed nearby reported that the two sides used mortars
and automatic weapons in the battles.
	   Hunt said it was not clear which side held the army
headquarters, nor were there any credible figures for the number
killed in the fighting.
	   A reporter for Guinea-Bissau national radio, interviewed by
Lisbon radio TSF on Tuesday, said he counted 30 bodies scattered
around the bases at Bra.
	   The Bra military installation, which includes a barracks and an
arms depot, is 15 kilometers (10 miles) outside the capital.
	   The nearby international airport remained closed. Peace Corps
representatives and U.S. citizens around the country reported there
was no fighting elsewhere.
	   In downtown Bissau, streets were quiet and people shopped at
grocery stores. However, police and troops ordered people to return
home by noon (1200 GMT), according to Hunt.
	   The city power supply was working normally, he said.
	   The ruling PAIGC party said in a statement broadcast on national
radio Tuesday that the government remained in control.
	   ``Legislative elections are scheduled for this year and
presidential elections are scheduled for next year,'' the foreign
minister said.
	   ``That is when the mandates for Parliament and the president end
and that's when the ballots will be held. We won't be given orders
by the head of a military junta,'' he said.
	   The PAIGC _ the Portuguese initials for the African Party for
the Independence of Guinea and Cape Verde _ won the 1994 general
election and has 60 lawmakers in the 100-seat National Assembly,
the country's parliament.
	   Guinea-Bissau, a former Portuguese colony, has 1 million people.
Most of them live from farming and fishing.
	   (bh/krt)
</TEXT>
