<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Nigeria-Injuries,0403 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Amokachi injures knee in practice; Shakpoke ruled out with broken
</HEADLINE>
collarbone &QL; 
 &UR; By HOWARD FENDRICH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   RESSONS, France (AP) _ Nigeria's World Cup team, already
battered by injuries and distracted by the death of the country's
leader, was hit twice more Tuesday when starting defender Jero
Shakpoke was lost for the tournament with a broken left collarbone
and striker Daniel Amokachi twisted his right knee.
	   The status of Amokachi, a possible starter, for Saturday's
opener against Spain in Nantes should be known within 24 hours,
officials said.
	   Shakpoke was ruled out of the tournament after doctors in Italy
diagnosed his shoulder injury as a fracture, team spokesman Austin
Mgbolu said. Shakpoke had flown to Reggiana to be examined by his
club doctor.
	   He sustained the injury during the first half of Nigeria's 5-1
loss to the Netherlands in a warmup match last Friday.
	   Mgbolu said Nigeria would ask FIFA, the international soccer
federation, for permission to replace Shakpoke on the roster.
	   Amokachi hurt himself about an hour into Tuesday's training
session when his foot got caught in the damp turf as he attempted a
shot. He was helped off the field by trainers with his right knee
heavily bandaged.
	   An assistant team trainer said it would be about 24 hours before
the extent of the injury was known.
	   ``He told me he had the same injury six months ago, and after 24
hours he was fine. I hope it's the same this time,'' coach Bora
Milutinovic said.
	   A member of Nigeria's 1994 World Cup squad and 1996 Olympic
championship team, Amokachi provides a creative element for the
attack. His injury is another blow for a team that was already
without injured forward Emanuel Ammunike and has leader Nwankwo
Kanu playing at less than 100 percent.
	   Kanu, a forward who underwent heart surgery 18 months ago, has
skipped all of the team's workouts in France because of a bad left
ankle.
	   The players were also dealing with the death of their country's
ruler, gathering for a moment of silence for Gen. San Abacha before
the morning training session.
	   Players learned of Abacha's death Monday night, and team captain
Uche Okechukwu said the team was considering wearing black armbands
on their jerseys during World Cup matches.
	   (str/jw) 	   
</TEXT>
