<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Thai Airways </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai government trims stake in Thai Airways
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Thailand's Cabinet decided Tuesday to
trim the government's stake in Thai Airways by authorizing the
Finance Ministry to sell 235 million shares in the national
carrier.
	   The sale would reduce the Finance Ministry's stake in Thai
Airways from 80 percent to 72 percent.
	   In the past, various government-appointed panels have
recommended the Finance Ministry reduce its ownership in the
carrier to a maximum of 49 percent as part of an aggressive
privatization program.
	   The reduction to 72 percent was a commitment made by the
government to the International Monetary Fund. The IMF has demanded
reforms and privatization procedures at state enterprises as part
of the dlrs 17.2 billion economic bailout package its is overseeing
for Thailand.
	   The Cabinet also approved the issuance by the airline of 100
million new shares in a capital-raising exercise, said Supachai
Pisitvanich, the ministry's permanent secretary.
	   Supachai said funds raised from the sale of the ministry's 235
shares would be used to pay off debts incurred by the country's
bank-rescue fund.
	   That fund, an arm of the Thai central bank known as the
Financial Institutions Development Fund, depleted its resources by
spending about 1 trillion baht (dlrs 23 billion) to prop up
troubled financial institutions last year.
	   The FIDF had borrowed most of its own funds from strong Thai
financial institutions, paying steep interest rates for the money.
	   The Cabinet said that the 335 million Thai Airways shares that
will enter the market _ the government's shares plus the new shares
_ may be sold both to individuals and institutions.
	   Some government officials have said the shares should be sold to
foreign airlines to help improve the efficiency of Thai Airways. A
company spokeswoman said Tuesday no foreign carrier had formally
approached Thai Airways to buy its shares.
	   In a statement, the cabinet said it ``asks Thai Airways to speed
up improvement of its operations to attract investors to buy its
shares so the state will get the best price possible.''
	   The cabinet asked the company to increase revenue, cut spending
and adjust its investment plans.
	   Thai Airways previously reported that its earnings for the six
months that ended March 31 dropped 55 percent year-on-year to 1.32
billion baht (dlrs 30 million).
</TEXT>
