<SLUG> BC-Russia-Arrest, 4th Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Head of Russia's government statistics agency arrested for faking
</HEADLINE>
data &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with details, arrests made late Monday sted early
Tuesday, CLARIFIES that officials found dlrs 1 million in Yurkov's
apartment alone, minor editing, UPGRADES attribution. &QL; 
 &UR; By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The head of Russia's government statistics service
has been arrested on charges of helping tax dodgers and selling
confidential data, officials said Tuesday. Investigators said they
found over dlrs 1 million in cash at his apartment.
	   Yuri Yurkov, head of the State Statistics Committee, was
arrested late on Monday along with several other senior workers,
government spokesman Alexei Volin said.
	   They were charged with ``systematic distortion of statistical
data on big companies which allowed them to evade taxes,'' Volin
said.
	   The arrests could have far-reaching economic implications for
Russia if it turns out that data government officials rely on to
make policy and collect taxes was in fact manipulated.
	   Volin said that investigators had found over dlrs 1 million in
cash during a search at Yurkov's apartment.
	   Russian Prosecutor's General office later said that Yurkov's
deputy Valery Dalin and the head of the agency's data processing
center Boris Saakyan were among those arrested. The authorities
have seized more than dlrs 1.5 million in cash and a large amount
of jewelry pieces from Yurkov and others, it said in a statement
released to the media.
	   Altogether, over 20 people were involved in the scheme, the
prosecutor's office said. ``They have distributed roles among
themselves making every member of the criminal group earn money,''
it said.
	   Yurkov and Saakyan made statements pleading guilty to the
charges, the statement said.
