<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Freighter Fire </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Greek freighter catches fire after crossing Bosporus strait
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) _ A fire broke out on a Greek freighter
Tuesday after it crossed the Bosporus Strait.
	   There were no immediate reports of casualties or injuries.
	   A thick gray smoke, rising from the ``Marianna'' off Istanbul,
hung over parts of this metropolis. Firefighters on boats rushed to
battle the blaze.
	   It was not clear what caused the fire in the cargo section of
the ship, carrying sheet iron from a Black Sea port, the Anatolia
news agency said.
	   The ship's destination was not clear.
	   The incident comes only two days after Turkish activists staged
a protest pointing out to the danger of heavy traffic posed to this
city of 10 million people.
	   The narrow waterway has been the site of nearly 200 accidents,
many of them fatal, in the past decade.
	   The stakes are rising since Russia proposes to carry Caspian oil
from a Black Sea port through the Bosporus, which Turkey ardently
opposes.
	   (sh-ms-fd)
</TEXT>
