<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Missing Tickets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Scotland fans bought tickets that didn't exist
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   GLASGOW, Scotland (AP) _ Scottish soccer fans who bought tickets
from unofficial outlets for Scotland's World Cup opener against
Brazil in Paris may have paid for tickets which don't exist and
could be refused entry to the match.
	   The Independent newspaper reported Tuesday that hundreds of
Scottish fans who had paid for package deals including World Cup
tickets had paid for tickets which did not exist.
	   And travel agents who sold the tickets in good faith fear that
the majority of fans have already arrived in France for Wednesday's
match.
	   The Independent said those affected were those who decided,
against Scottish Football Association recommendations, to buy
tickets from unofficial outlets.
	   The official SFA allocation for the Scotland versus Brazil game
was 5,000 of the 80,000 seats in the stadium.
	   The Independent said a U.S. company thought to be responsible
for supplying the tickets to unofficial outlets has not delivered
them.
	   Glasgow-based travel agent Kelvin Travel reportedly admitted
that it is having to cancel 640 of the 960 World Cup packages it
sold to fans.
	   Scotland fan Jim Dixon, who paid 640 pounds (dlrs 1,043) for
such a package, said staff at Kelvin Travel told him the company
had set up an office in Paris to buy some of the 15,000 tickets
released Monday.
	   Last week the government closed down a company which had
allegedly made 2.4 million pounds (dlrs 3.9 million) by selling
40,000 World Cup seats, but failed to deliver all the tickets.
	   (jp/sw) 	   
</TEXT>
