<SLUG> BC-Germany-Russia, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yeltsin, Kohl meet on Russia's financial troubles, Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with Yeltsin saying he'll seek meeting with
Milosevic to try to end Kosovo conflict, details. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos expected &QL; 
 &UR; By IAN MADER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ Russian President Boris Yeltsin said
Tuesday he would seek a meeting with Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic to persuade him to end escalating violence in that
country's Kosovo region.
	   But Yeltsin wouldn't say what kind of leverage he might use to
get Milosevic to stop Yugoslav attacks on separatist Kosovo
Albanians, or enter peace talks with them.
	   ``The more softly I speak the better the chances of a meeting,''
Yeltsin said at a news conference following two days of
broad-ranging talks with German officials.
	   ``We will meet and discuss the question of how to get out of
this situation without getting into a big war,'' Yeltsin said,
adding that any deployment of foreign troops in Kosovo would be
``very dangerous.''
	   Chancellor Helmut Kohl said Yeltsin was prepared to ``use his
big influence in Belgrade so that the bloodshed ends as quickly as
possible.''
	   Germany was hoping to get Russia behind the European Union's ban
on investment in the main Yugoslav republic of Serbia. But Russian
Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov said Russia probably wouldn't
join the sanctions, announced Monday and aimed at persuading
Belgrade to negotiate peace in Kosovo.
	   Another focus of the discussion was Russia's market collapse and
fiscal crisis last month following an oil-price drop.
	   The crisis had raised speculation that Germany, Russia's most
important trading partner outside the former Soviet Union, might
offer financial assistance. But the leaders announced no new aid.
	   Kohl said Germany was satisfied with Russian measures taken so
far to deal with the crisis, but did not elaborate. ``We trust that
the Russian government will go further with these reforms,'' Kohl
said.
	   Yeltsin, who has announced a vigorous new tax collection
program, said he was not seeking any new aid or loans. But he said
it was important to have Kohl's ``personal support'' while his
country negotiates loans with the International Monetary Fund.
	   ``On this basis, international investors won't leave our
country,'' he added.
	   The talks were the first in a series of periodic German-Russian
consultations agreed to by Yeltsin and Kohl last year in an effort
to ease Russian concerns over the eastward expansion of NATO.
	   Ministers of finance, economics, foreign affairs, defense,
interior and nuclear energy met with their counterparts on a broad
range of security and trade issues. Yeltsin also met with German
opposition chancellor candidate Gerhard Schroeder.
	   Kohl noted it was the first time the two country's interior
ministers had met, underscoring their increasingly ``friendly''
relations.
	   Shortly after arriving in Bonn, Russian and German ministers
signed two agreements dealing with cooperation in the nuclear power
industry.
	    &UR; (im/cb/pfg)
</TEXT>
