r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Ireland-Nuclear     06-09 0458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ireland-Nuclear </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Eight states demand that nuclear powers disarm within a few years
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) _ Eight nations joined Tuesday in pressing
the world's nuclear powers to take immediate steps to dispose of
their arsenals within a few years.
	   ``We are jointly resolved to achieve the goal of a world free
from nuclear weapons,'' said the declaration by the Republic of
Ireland, New Zealand, Sweden, South Africa, Brazil, Egypt, Mexico
and Slovenia.
	   The declaration called on India and Pakistan to sign up to the
Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty, and for the five nuclear powers _
the United States, Russia, China, France and Britain _ to act on
that treaty's commitments to rid the world of nuclear weapons.
	   Irish Foreign Ministry David Andrews said consultations among
the eight began at the start of the year, before the recent round
of nuclear tests by India and Pakistan.
	   ``The collapse of the Berlin Wall and the end of the Cold War
provided opportunities for the final thrust leading to the
elimination of nuclear weapons,'' Andrews told a news conference.
	   ``These opportunities have sadly been squandered in the decade
since then by the international community. The nuclear weapon
states have found new justifications where none exist for the
indefinite retention of their nuclear weapons,'' Andrews said.
	   Andrews said the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty obliged
signatories to move toward disarming.
	   ``The failure of the nuclear weapon states to fulfill their
legally binding obligations under the treaty is not the result of
any inadequacy in the treaty itself. It is the result of the lack
of political will,'' Andrews said.
	   ``Today's initiative is about securing that political will so
that in a few short years we will have consigned nuclear weapons to
history.''
	   The Ministry of Foreign Affairs said the eight nations would be
pursuing their initiative through the United Nations General
Assembly later this year.
	   In their declaration, the eight said: ``We can no longer remain
complacent at the reluctance of the nuclear-weapon states and the
three nuclear-weapons-capable states to take that fundamental and
requisite step, namely a clear commitment to the speedy, final and
total elimination of their nuclear weapons and nuclear weapons
capability, and we urge them to take that step now.''
	   The nuclear-capable states referred to India, Pakistan and
Israel.
	   The declaration called on the nuclear powers to ``abandon
present hair-trigger postures'' by taking weapons off alert and by
deactivating them; to develop measure to ban the production of
fissionable materials, and to engage in pledges not to be the first
to use nuclear weapons.
	   (rb)
</TEXT>
