<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-France,0502 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Wordl Cup: Zidane juggles ball like never before; France looking up
</HEADLINE>
for 1st match &QL; 
 &UR; By RAF CASERT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer

<TEXT>
	   CLAIREFONTAINE, France (AP) _ Zinedine Zidane juggled the ball
like never before Tuesday, easing fears an ankle injury would keep
the star playmaker out of France's opening match against South
Africa.
	   The Juventus Turin ace felt little discomfort from his tender
right ankle that was hurt in Finland last weekend and coach Aime
Jacquet stuck to his plans to build the strategic concept for
Friday's first game around Zidane.
	   At the end of a two-hour training session, Zidane put on a big
smile, happy that three days of uncertainty were behind him.
	   ``I'm OK, I didn't feel any pain,'' said Zidane. ``Now we have
to prepare the match. We're ready.''
	   France is the overwhelming favorite to win the first round Group
C, which also includes Denmark and Saudi Arabia.
	   Jacquet has no illusions whatsoever that the underdog will chose
open and fluent play. The coach knows he will need all the
offensive prowess of Zidane if France is to break down the wall of
11 South Africans in front of their goal.
	   ``It will be something like that. And it is logical,'' he said.
	   He expects little else from Saudi Arabia.
	   Despite criticism for lackluster play over the last three
preparation games, Zidane is confident France will show its true
face in his hometown of Marseille Friday.
	   ``That first match will liberate us. I'm convinced we can do
great things. There is no alternative,'' he said.
	   And he realized it was of no use crying over the tough marking
during the preparation games. It will be the same Friday. ``I'll
always have someone on my back. That is the way it is,'' he said.
	   France's backbone is set, build around a strong and experienced
defense, a solid midfield anchored around captain Didier Deschamps
and creative sparkplugs Zidane and Youri Djorkaeff.
	   The central striker and the second forward remain the main
worry.
	   Based on the team that edged Finland 1-0 last Friday, Jacquet is
expected to start Christophe Dugarry, a tireless worker that weighs
on any defense, before replacing the Marseille forward with a young
challenger like David Trezeguet of Monaco.
	   Even though South Africa is just a rank outsider, the
realization that fireworks won't necessarily be set off is taking
hold.
	   ``All games will be tough. We won't see too many 3-0, 4-0
matches. The important thing is to win them,'' said Zidane.
	   Les Bleus, as the French team is known, will stay for another
two days at its chilly training camp here in the woods southwest of
Paris before heading to the Mediterranean warmth of Marseille on
Thursday, ready for their Coupe du Monde.
	   Training in a strong breeze and temperatures that barely reached
14 C (57 F), many kept their full training gear on, hardly the
ideal conditions to prepare for a summer of soccer.
</TEXT>
