With Sports-Soccer-World Cup 2006
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Mandela applauds Blatter's election

<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ President Nelson Mandela
Tuesday applauded the election of Sepp Blatter to head
international soccer, lauding his commitment to take the World Cup
to South Africa in 2006.
	   ``I speak not only for ... the people of South Africa, but for
the entire African continent and the people of the developing and
underdeveloped countries,'' Mandela said in a statement released in
Johannesburg.
	   Blatter was elected Monday as president of FIFA, defeating UEFA
president Lennart Johansson for the most powerful post in soccer.
	   During a visit to South Africa last month, Blatter promised to
back South Africa's bid for the 2006 World Cup. England, Germany
and possibly Brazil and Argentina are also bidding for the
tournament.
	   ``I am heartened by (this) remarkable display of foresight and
commitment to development of all people around the globe,'' Mandela
said.
