<SLUG> BC-Japan-Intel-FTC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Intel says FTC complaint to have no effect on business
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The president of Intel Corp. on Tuesday said the
U.S. Federal Trade Commission's anti-monopoly complaint against the
computer chip giant will not have any impact on its business, a
news report said.
	   Intel President Craig Barrett was quoted by Kyodo News agency as
telling reporters in Tokyo that he expects the FTC's complaint to
have ``no impact'' on Intel's business performance, including
development of new products.
	   Barrett said the FTC's administrative complaint before an FTC
Administrative Law judge is based on a mistaken interpretation of
the law and the facts, adding Intel has never committed itself to
any action that could hamper fair competition.
	   The Federal Trade Commission moved Monday to rein in Intel,
claiming it misused its position as the world's leading producer of
chips for personal computers to punish competitors and customers.
	   The FTC antitrust complaint also charged that Intel, which
controls up to 90 percent of the world market for personal computer
chips, abused companies that need its help to develop new products.
	   (jc)
</TEXT>
