<SLUG> BC-India-Rupee,0192 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rupee hits closing low
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BOMBAY, India (AP) _ The demand for dollars _ increasing since
dealers deemed the new Indian budget lackluster _ pushed the rupee
to a new low at the end of trading Tuesday.
	   The Indian currency closed at 42.24 rupees to the dollar, down
from the previous close of 41.80. The rupee touched a low during
the day of 42.25.
	   The demand for dollars increased after the Indian budget last
week didn't taken any special measures to encourage foreign direct
or portfolio investments. Even before that, the rupee had been
plummeting.
	   Since the budget was announced last Monday, the State Bank had
been selling dollars to prevent the rupee from falling below 41.80.
But the partly state-owned institution that is India's largest
commercial bank did not sell Tuesday.
	   Shortly before presenting his budget, Finance Minister Jaswant
Sinha said the rupee slide, which traders have linked to
international sanctions imposed following India's five nuclear
tests, was a welcome and orderly devaluation. He added the central
bank, which owns 68 percent of State Bank, had no plans to
intervene. 	   
