<SLUG> BC-Iran-Iraq </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former foes exchange bodies of soldiers
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ Iran and Iraq on Tuesday exchanged the
remains of 187 soldiers killed during their 1980-99 war, the
Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
	   Iran handed over the remains of 134 Iraqi soldiers killed during
the eight-year conflict and Iraq delivered the bodies of 53 Iranian
soldiers, the agency said.
	   The exchange of remains took place on the Iran-Iraq border in
the southwestern Khuzestan province in the presence of Iranian and
Iraqi military officials.
	   The war, which killed or wounded at least 1 million people from
both sides, ended with a U.N. brokered cease-fire but animosity has
persisted over the issue of prisoners.
	   Iran has suggested a plan to launch joint search operations in
border areas to locate the remains of soldiers killed during the
war, IRNA said.
	   The two countries are currently carrying such operations in
Shalamcheh in southwest Iran, the agency said.
	   The two countries recently exchanged thousands of prisoners of
war. According to the International Committee of the Red Cross,
some 75,000 POWs on both sides have been freed since the war ended.
 &UR; ti-sf
</TEXT>
