<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Reform Bills </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan's Parliament approves administrative reform bills
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan's Parliament on Tuesday approved an
administrative reform bill to streamline the country's bloated
bureaucracy by cutting the number of ministries and government
agencies.
	   The bill was passed by the upper house of Parliament with the
backing of Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto's ruling coalition. The
measure had already been approved by Parliament's more powerful
lower house.
	   A key policy objective of Hashimoto's administration, the law
will cut the number of Japan's ministries and other government
agencies from 22 to 13 within five years.
	   It will also bolster the power of the prime minister in
policy-making and require any new public corporations to adopt
accounting techniques used in the private sector.
	   Critics, however, charge that the changes will be largely
cosmetic. The bill, they say, will only merge existing ministries
without significant downsizing.
	   The government will now move to set up an administrative reform
headquarters later this month, to be headed by Hashimoto.
	   A key aspect of the new bill will be to allow the prime minister
to propose the agenda at Cabinet meetings. Up to now, bureaucrats
have been dictating what ministers discuss at the meetings.
	   Under the new law, the number of government employees also is
expected to be cut by 10 percent over the next decade.
 &UR; (js)	   
</TEXT>
