<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup-Italy,0471 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Del Piero glad about recovery, looking forward to comeback
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By PIERO VALSECCHI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SENLIS, France (AP) _ Alessandro Del Piero, delighted to be off
the injury list, said he does not feel disappointed over his
expected exclusion from Italy's World Cup opener against Chile.
	   The young striker will be replaced by his former Juventus
teammate Roberto Baggio in Thursday's match at Bordeaux but is
looking forward to regain his place on the starting 11 in the next
game against Cameroon.
	   ``I'm happy to be here, recovered, after fearing to miss the
World Cup,'' Del Piero said at Italy's training camp Tuesday. ``I
am optimistic now and I think to be ready for the match against
Cameroon.''
	   Italy, a three-time World Champion, plays the African team on
June 17 in its second match of Group B.
	   Considered the jewel of the Italian team and a key to the
``Azzurri'' fortunes in the World Cup, Del Piero healed a right
thigh strain suffered in the Champions Cup final against Real
Madrid but still is questionable form following ten days of light
training.
	   His exclusion from Thursday's match with Chile had been
suggested by coach Cesare Maldini on Sunday when he tested the
offensive duo of Baggio and Christian Vieri in a tuneup against an
amateur team while Del Piero trained on his own.
	   Del Piero, who replaced Baggio at Juventus and on the national
team, said he could not see any sign of doom or rivalry in the fact
that his older teammate is going to substitute him, this time.
	   ``There is no rivalry with Roberto. We are good friends. I hope
he plays a great match against Chile. It would be better for coach
Maldini to chose between two fit, good players for the match
against Cameroon,'' Del Piero explained.
	   Baggio, 31, also defused controversy saying he traveled to
France as Del Piero's substitute and that he was ready to sit on
the substitutes bench once the ``Golden Boy'' is ruled fit.
	   Baggio, Italy's Word Cup hero in 1994, earned a last-minute
place on the Italian team scoring 22 goals in league matches with
low-ranked Bologna, following a lackluster season with AC Milan.
	   Del Piero had one of his best seasons ever with Juventus this
year scoring 21 goals in league matches and becoming the highest
scorer in the history of the Champions League, with 10 goals.
	   Del Piero said he could feel the psychological pressure of being
in the World Cup ``and I'm sure it's going to grow day after day.''
	   ``We all are prepared to face it. It's a great experience for
me. I have a true passion for soccer. I want to take revenge with
the national team for the bitter defeat suffered with La Juve in
the Champions Cup final,'' Del Piero said.
	   (pv-sl)
</TEXT>
