<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-World Cup Fever </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bewildered Parisians look on as World Cup fever strikes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos PAR103/104 &QL; 
 &UR; By IAN PHILLIPS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Suddenly, the cuisine consists mainly of cheap
supermarket beer. The latest fashion accessory in the city of chic?
A polyester soccer shirt with your hero's name on the back.
	   World Cup fever finally gripped Paris Tuesday as thousands of
soccer fans, mainly Scots in kilts and Brazilians in yellow,
arrived on the eve of their countries' opening game Wednesday.
	   For some, it was a fascinating mix of fans from across the
world. For others, a rude culture shock.
	   ``Are they really going to drink all that?'' said middle-aged
Parisian Betty Teyssier as she watched a dozen Scots tucking into
crates of beer off the Champs Elysees. ``How long does this last? I
need to leave the city.''
	   Near the Place de la Concorde, where tens of thousands were to
gather later Tuesday for World Cup parades, a bemused police
officer looked on as Heimo Harma, from Finland, waved the flag of
his local team, Rovaniemi, in his face.
	   ``I have a ticket for the game! Brazil, Brazil!'' he shouted,
grinning. ``I've come from the Arctic Circle. Brazil, Brazil!''
	   After five years of planning, French organizers are lamenting
that World Cup fever hasn't caught on among the French.
	   Jacques Lambert, director of the World Cup organizing committee,
said Tuesday that with hindsight he would seek ``to mobilize France
and the French from the very beginning.''
	   Former soccer great Michel Platini accused authorities of
turning their back on the tournament, and ``not giving a damn.'' He
says authorities will realize their mistake once all the fans
arrive.
	   The spirit was certainly there Tuesday, although most was
imported. Many of the fans didn't have tickets, and were just
soaking up the atmosphere.
	   Roberto Rosenthal, his Argentine shirt carrying the name of
striker Gabriel Batistuta, had taken a dlrs 7,000 loan to get to
the World Cup, and had no idea when he'd be able to pay it back.
	   ``It's expensive, but a once-in-a-life-time,'' he said. ``And I
know we'll win.''
	   Derek Christie, a Scot, was planning his day ahead of
Wednesday's match for which he had a precious ticket.
	   ``Aye, it's a fine city, but expensive. I need to find a
supermarket for beer, and a place where I can barter prices down so
I can return home with affordable perfumes and aftershave.''
	   Christie, camping on the outskirts of Paris for dlrs 7 a night,
said he fancied Scotland to beat the world champions.
	   ``It's about time we had something to cheer,'' he said.
	   Towering above him was an orange giant depicting one of the many
nationalities participating in the World Cup.
	   On a city bridge earlier Tuesday, workers frantically tried to
patch up diaper-like shorts on a yellow Asian giant damaged by
overnight rain and wind. Traffic had been cut off all around.
	   ``What a pain!'' shouted a woman passing on a bicycle, almost
falling into traffic as she gesticulated at the yellow blob.
	   (ip-dgs) 	   
</TEXT>
