<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yugoslavia assails renewed Kosovo sanctions
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Kosovo Serbs meeting U.S. diplomat, reaction by
Montenegrin premier, Albanians collecting funds for their cause. &QL; 
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Yugoslavia on Tuesday denounced new
international sanctions over its offensive in Kosovo, where a
western strip of the separatist province has been turned into a war
zone of burned houses and deserted villages.
	   In a statement issued on the official Tanjug news agency,
Yugoslav officials called the imposition of sanctions a ``strange
and unreasonable decision.''
	   The comment came in response to decisions made by the European
Union and the United States within hours of each other on Monday,
banning new investments in Serbia and freezing its assets abroad.
	   ``It's cynical to demand from Yugoslavia to withdraw troops from
its own province and leave it to the mercy of Albanian
terrorists,'' said the Tanjug commentary.
	   Official Belgrade also was offended that the punishment is only
against Serbia. Its lone partner in the Yugoslav federation,
Montenegro, is exempted because of its pro-Western leadership.
	   ``This is the first case that EU has made a decision about a
sovereign state that applies to only one of its federal units,''
the Tanjug commentary said.
	   Montenegro's Premier Filip Vujanovic said that exempting
Montenegro would be difficult in practice as that would require ``a
border'' between the two republics and that is ``out of the
question.''
	   A prominent Kosovo Albanian, Nekibe Kelmendi, had welcomed the
new sanctions on Monday but said they were only a ``small step''
compared to the situation on the ground.
	   Ethnic Albanians form a 90 percent majority living in Serbia's
southern province. More than 250 have died this year in clashes
between government forces and the pro-independence Albanian
militants, known as Kosovo Liberation Army.
	   The international community has ruled out any change of borders
but wants Serbia to restore the autonomy Kosovo once enjoyed.
	   There were no immediate reports of new clashes Tuesday in
Kosovo.
	   The destruction in the southern Serb province has increased the
international outcry for Serbia to stop using its police and army
against ethnic Albanians. NATO is considering military
intervention.
	   Exiled Kosovo Albanian political leaders on Tuesday announced
they would collect an extra tax from an estimated 400,000 Kosovo
Albanians living in the west to finance the ``defense of our
people'' from attacks by government forces. They didn't say how
they would do this.
	   In 1993 Kosovo Albanians established a parallel system of
administration involving collecting taxes and financing education
and health care for Albanians.
	   The announcement made by the Germany-based Kosovo Albanian
government-in-exile was published Tuesday in Albanian-language
papers in Kosovo, saying every Albanian working in the West would
have to contribute to the ``obligatory financial mobilization''
with an equivalent of dlrs 300-600.
	   Also on Tuesday, a group of Serbs living in Kosovo and
dissatisfied with Milosevic's policy in the province met with
Richard Miles, the most senior U.S. diplomat in Yugoslavia.
	   A source close to the talks, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Miles told them the United States want to see meaningful
negotiations between the sides and will ``apply a form of pressure
on the government, and also on the Albanian side.''
	   In Washington, State Department spokesman James Rubin said
Monday the United States has not ruled out military options to stop
violence in Kosovo.
	   Carl Bildt, formerly the European Union's high representative in
Bosnia and still an influential figure regarding policy on former
Yugoslavia, harshly criticized Western officials in a commentary
published Tuesday for being indecisive and slow. He warned of a
``huge humanitarian and political disaster'' if swift actions
aren't taken.
	   He urged that troops be deployed to northern Albania to close
the border, that NATO impose a no-fly zone over Kosovo and threaten
air strikes against remaining Serb forces, and that the Kosovo
Liberation Army's sponsors in Europe and the United States be
pressured to get the KLA to halt military operations.
	   ``Kosovo is a testing ground,'' Bildt wrote in the Financial
Times of London. ``Here we will see if the lessons of the wars in
Croatia and Bosnia have been learned. So far, there are only faint
signs that this has been the case.''
	   (ih/ms/dc/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
