<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-South Africa,0469 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Troussier puts positive spin on South African chances
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By TOM COHEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VICHY, France (AP) _ Facing long odds and crushing pressure,
South African coach Philippe Troussier wants his players to believe
they can overcome any World Cup challenge.
	   So when asked Tuesday to assess Bafana Bafana's chances against
favored France in their opening Group C match Friday, he shrugged
his shoulders and said: ``100 percent.''
	   For Troussier, it was another opportunity to deliver the
unexpected by putting positive spin on his situation _ a new coach
of a team making its first World Cup appearance against the host
nation.
	   He wasn't predicting South Africa would beat France, but instead
saying his players must believe they can do so for it to happen.
	   ``Some times the match is not about potential,'' said Troussier,
who took over as coach in March. ``It's about playing under much
pressure.''
	   A Frenchman who has coached in Africa for a decade, Troussier
knows the French mentality, particularly how the crowd can turn if
the home team fails to start well. He wants South Africa to stymie
the French attack early to quiet the fans in Marseilles, all the
while looking for attacking opportunities.
	   ``Sometimes the best defense is a good attack,'' he said.
	   Attacker Shaun Bartlett said Troussier is telling his players to
think to concentrate on winning the first half.
	   ``His idea is that if you can compress and contain a team for
one half and score a goal, that's good enough,'' Bartlett
explained. ``He says he has more players on the bench to help out
in the next half. He doesn't want us running ourselves ragged for
90 minutes.''
	   To remove some of the pressure from the opening match, Troussier
constantly reminds players and journalists that the other two Group
C opponents _ Denmark and Saudi Arabia _ are equally important.
	   Stressing discipline, he has warned his players that promised
red cards for tackling from behind would devastate South Africa's
chances of achieving its main goal _ advancing to the second round.
	   ``For sure, it will be a rough game physically,'' he said about
France.
	   Troussier's positive spin also surfaced when he was asked about
injuries, particularly the bruised heel that kept captain Lucas
Radebe of Leeds United from practicing Monday and Tuesday.
	   ``For us nobody is injured. Everything is okay,'' Troussier
said, adding that Radebe simply needed 48 hours of rest after the
long English season and his South African commitments.
	   But Troussier also downplayed the possible loss of the captain,
saying all his players were capable of filling the role if Radebe
missed Friday's match.
	   (tsc-sl)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
