	   Editors: The following stories have moved or will move on the
European circuits of The Associated Press by 1500 GMT, unless
otherwise noted.
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Yugoslavia on Tuesday denounced new
international sanctions imposed for its offensive in the separatist
province of Kosovo, calling it a ``strange and unreasonable
decision.'' YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO.
	   WITH:
	   _GERMANY-RUSSIA. Russian President Boris Yeltsin said Tuesday he
would try to meet with the Yugoslav leader to persuade him to end
escalating violence.
	   _NATO-KOSOVO. Events in Kosovo are unfolding almost faster than
NATO military planners can handle. Just a few days ago, the
generals focused on dispatching troops to deal with refugees and
patrol its borders. Now, one official said Tuesday, intervention
could be on the agenda.
	   LAGOS, Nigeria _ Scrambling to avoid a power vacuum in the wake
of Gen. Sani Abacha's unexpected death, the ruling military moved
quickly to appoint a new leader, Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar, who was
sworn in before dawn Tuesday.
	   WITH:
	   _ NIGERIA-ABACHA-WORLD REAX. Sani Abacha's death is an
``incredible opportunity'' for the West African nation to return to
democracy, a leading dissident in exile said _ a hope echoed by
Western powers.
	   _ NIGERIA-ABUBAKAR PROFILE _ Career serviceman Abdulsalam
Abubakar is the ninth military of oil-rich Nigeria, Africa's most
populous nation.
	   PARIS _ Criticism of striking French pilots mounted Tuesday as
their walkout entered its ninth day on the eve of the World Cup,
and a top trade union leader ruled out a negotiated settlement.
FRANCE-AIR FRANCE STRIKE.
	   WITH:
	   _BRITAIN-FRENCH STRIKE FALLOUT. For Air France's rivals, the
timing couldn't have been better. A strike by pilots has severely
crippled the French flag carrier just as thousands of people are
going to France for the World Cup games, and competitors are
cashing in with millions in windfall profits.
	   MOSCOW _ Russia may have to discard the Mir space station a year
ahead of schedule and send it crashing back to Earth this fall
unless the cash-strapped government comes up with more money,
officials said Tuesday. RUSSIA-MIR.
	   ROME _ Silvio Berlusconi's main ally in the center-right
opposition confirmed Tuesday that the alliance won't bail out
Premier Romano Prodi's government on a crucial vote later this
month on NATO. ITALY-POLITICS-NATO.
