<HEADLINE>
Parties bracing for showdown in Expo spending battle, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Parties bracing for showdown in Expo spending battle, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE government is bracing for a head-on collision with Executive
Councillors and political parties over the controversial Expo 2001.
	   It is believed that the Economic Services Bureau is reluctant to
approve the exposition because it may not be cost-effective.
	   But a number of Executive Councillors and political parties are
pushing for the project in the hopes of reviving the tourism
industry.
	   A spokeswoman for the Economic Services Bureau said bureau
officials were still reviewing the proposal.
	   ``After the bureau decides, it has to go through the Exco so we
are not expecting any announcement until next month,'' she said.
	   Outbound Travel Agents Association president Ronnie Ho Pak-ting
said it had already rejected the idea.
	   ``I think the government is not convinced that the project will
attract enough tourists and it could be a waste of taxpayers
money,'' he said.
	   Mr Ho said his association and a number of key players in the
industry shared the government's view.
	   ``We would prefer the government to concentrate on projects
which have long-term impact in attracting tourists rather than
funding ad hoc projects.'' Mr Ho said the government could use the
$2 billion injection into the project to build new facilities with
long-term impact.
	   ``There may be disagreements between the government and
politicians on this issue but I hope the government will consider
what is good for the community,'' he said.
	   It is believed that most Executive Councillors, including Henry
Tang Ying-yen and Exco Convenor Chung Sze-yuen support the
exposition.
	   Like the Hong Kong Tourist Association, which proposed the
project, executive councillors believe the project will help
encourage tourists to visit Hong Kong and generate much needed
jobs.
	   Executive councillors believe that the government should inject
funds into the project because it will provide long-term benefits
for the community.
	   The proposal is for the exposition to be held at the southern
part of the West Kowloon Reclamation for a period of six months in
2001.
	   The 54.5 hectare area will feature various attractions including
theatres, public plazas and a waterfront promenade.
	   The project will aim at attracting an attendance level of 19.4
million.
	   At least three million tourists are expected to generate about
$29 billion.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
