<BODY>
<SLUG> DEFICIT-BUDGET-FORECAST sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Deficit budget forecast by Chung, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Deficit budget forecast by Chung, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   EXECUTIVE Council convenor Chung Sze-yuen has for the first time
publicly predicted the budget for this financial year will end in
the red.
	   This was due mainly to poor land sale receipts and advanced
infrastructure works to create jobs.
	   Mr Chung made the remarks after visiting the Equal Opportunities
Commission and was asked by reporters to comment on the growing
pressure from academics and politicians for a deficit budget for
the next financial year to fight the threat of an economic
recession.
	   ``The land sale revenue will definitely decrease following a
slide in the property market this year, and the public is demanding
the government delay freeing land to the market under its five-year
land sale program,'' he said.
	   ``But at the same time, the government has to create more jobs
this year by starting infrastructure works earlier than scheduled.
That will increase its expenditure.
	   ``Thus, government income will be less than budgeted and
expenses will increase and finally, a deficit will result.'' But Mr
Chung did not comment on whether the government should plan a
deficit budget for fiscal 1999-2000.
	   ``It still has nine months to go (for the new budget). It's too
early to decide whether we should have a deficit budget or not.''
Financial Secretary Sir Donald Tsang Yam-kuen said he would stick
to the Basic Law when drafting the budget next year.
	   Speaking after inaugurating the new Air Mail Centre at Chek Lap
Kok, Sir Donald said it was too early to say if the budget proposal
for next year would be a deficit one or not.
	   He said he would maintain the principle of controlling spending
in accordance with economic growth.
	   Sir Donald went on to say that a one-year deficit budget would
not be the answer to all the current problems.
	   ``The most important thing is how to improve Hong Kong's
business environment to increase job vacancies and attract
investment,'' he said.
	   In yet another ominous hint that Hong Kong's economy was
hurtling towards a recession, Joseph Yam Chi-kwong, chief executive
of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA), admitted that Hong
Kong's growth would remain slow through the third quarter of this
year.
	   Talking in Basle, Switzerland, where he is attending the annual
meeting of the Bank for International Settlements, Mr Yam said:
``My guess is that the second quarter would not be good, either,
because the first half of last year was quite buoyant and we are
talking about year-on-year comparisons.'' He added that the third
quarter may not be good either.
	   ``I have been saying that things may get worse before they get
better. One's got to be realistic about the sort of situation that
we are facing,'' Mr Yam said.
	   Meanwhile, Chief Executive Tung Chee-hwa told a visiting
European Parliament delegation that Hong Kong was experiencing a
credit crunch which has worsened because of the fear of an attack
on the dollar peg.
	   ``Hong Kong's economy needs to be corrected if we are to regain
our competitiveness.'' Mr Tung said it would take time for the
fiscal stimuli to take effect.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
