<SLUG> LONG-MARCH-TO-CHT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Long march to CHT begins today, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Long march to CHT begins today, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The two-day long march to the Chittagong Hill Tracts (CHT) by
the BNP-led 7-party alliance to press for scrapping the agreement
on the CHT begins from Dhaka city today morning.
	   Marchers from the northern and south-western districts started
arriving in Dhaka from yesterday afternoon in buses and other
transports. In Dhaka final touches were given to the preparations
to hold the march peacefully.
	   Reports of clashes between the supporters and opponents of the
march in different parts of the country reached Dhaka yesterday.
The administration was taking some undeclared precautionary
measures to discourage people from participating in the march. The
measures included requisitioning of heavy vehicles and microbuses
in Dhaka and house to house campaigning in Khagrachhari asking the
people not to participate in it.
	   While the government has termed the march a programme to
destabilise the CHT peace, the opposition termed it a rehearsal to
safeguard the country's independence and sovereignty.
	   Campaigning in favour of the march continued while posters and
leaflets were distributed in Dhaka city and other district towns
yesterday.
	   Amid speculations of violence with rival political workers along
the route, the National Standing Committee of the BNP had a meeting
last evening to take necessary precautions.
	   The long march of the BNP begins from the Paltan Maidan after a
rally to be addressed by BNP chief Begum Khaleda Zia. The programme
of Jamaat-e-Islami begins from Ramna Square.
	   Leaders and workers of five other parties of the 7-party
alliance will take part in the march with the BNP and the Jamaat.
	   The march is scheduled to reach Chittagong by this evening. On
the way more motor vehicles carrying long marchers from different
districts and thanas would join the convoy at different points.
There would be brief rallies at such points including Comilla and
Feni. Long marchers would make a night halt at Chittagong.
	   From there the long march of the BNP would proceed towards
Khagrachhari. Jamaat's long march will proceed towards Rangamati.
BNP's long march would end after the holding of a rally at
Khagrachhari early in the afternoon on Wednesday. Jamaat would end
its long march after holding a rally at Rangamati on the same day.
	   Meanwhile, the police administration in Dhaka requisitioned at
least 350 town service buses and mini-buses apparently in a bid to
prevent the marchers from hiring those for the programme.
	   By yesterday evening the streets of Dhaka city were almost
stripped of buses and mini-buses. Members of the travelling public
were seen crowding bus stops to take trips. They also had to take
alternative modes of transport. Office-goers were the worst
sufferers as they got stuck-up on their way back home late in the
afternoon.
	   Police also started searching the buses carrying the marchers to
the city at Aricha and Daulatdia ghats and at Manikganj. Police
said that they tried to make sure none carried weapons. At least
one hundred buses coming from the northern and south-western
districts drove to Dhaka city via Manikganj by 9-30 pm.
	   The BNP and its front organisations brought out processions in
different parts of Dhaka city to drum up support for the march.
Workers of Jamaat-e-Islami Bangladesh also brought out similar
processions.
	   To maintain discipline during the programme, the BNP issued
leaflets containing instructions to the marchers. About 2,000
stickers were prepared by yesterday evening as serial numbers for
the motor vehicles that would be taken to the long march.
	   The first 50 motor vehicles of the march would carry volunteers
who would be responsible for maintenance of discipline.
	   Cars carrying national leaders would be positioned after every
ten vehicles carrying the volunteers. There would be one ambulance
after every 20 motor vehicles to attend to the marchers who fell
sick.
	   One motor vehicle carrying volunteers would be positioned after
every 25 motor vehicles of the long march.
	   In another leaflet marchers have been advised about how to
protect themselves from the scorching heat and avoid getting
dehydrated. They also have been advised to carry dry food, water
and packets of oral saline.
	   The front organisations of BNP and its district and thana units
would use separate banners on motor vehicles for proper
identification.
	   Last night long marchers coming from northern and southern
districts were sheltered under a tarpaulin erected on the premises
of the Minto Road official residence of Begum Khaleda Zia, also the
leader of the opposition in Parliament.
	   To maintain law and order in the capital during the CHT Long
March programme, the government would deploy over 3000 law
enforcing agency personnel including Bangladesh Rifles (BDR).
	   Sources in Dhaka Metropolitan Police (DMP) told The Independent
last night that 166 police officers including 7 Deputy
Commissioners (DC) would supervise the operation.
	   DMP Commissioner Mahmud Al-Farid yesterday at a session briefed
the supervising officers about their duties. He directed them to
ensure safe passage to the marchers and maintain peace in the city,
the sources said.
	   The supervising officers include 9 ADCs, 5 Assistant
Commissioners (AC), 14 Inspectors, 82 Sub-Inspectors, 22 Sergeants
and 9 Assistant Sub-Inspectors.
	   Our Narayangonj Correspondent reported last night that the
district police administration would deploy a total 700 police
personnel at 13 sensitive spots on the Dhaka-Chittagong and
Dhaka-Sylhet highways as part of security measures.
	   Police sources said that of the total 700 personnel, 100 would
be members of the Armed Police Battalion.
	   Two of the 13 named spots have been identified as the ``most
sensitive points'' as the district unit of the ruling Awami League
(AL), is scheduled to hold ``peace- rally'' at Shimrail Crossing
near Muktee Smarani under Bandar thana and Mograpara under
Sonargaon thana. Other spots are - Munshirkhola and Panchabati
under Fatullah thana, Chashara at Narayangonj town, Thanarpar, Old
Demra Road, Galakata bridge and Madanpur under Bander thana,
Kanchpur Bridge under Sonargaon and Meghnaghat under Sonargaon,
Purinda under Araihazar and Bhulta under Rupgonj thana.
	   Additional Police Super Dr Abdur Rahman would coordinate the
duties while ASP (Headquarters) Abu Baker take position near
Kanchpur bridge round the clock.
	   Our Staff Reporter from Feni adds: The district administration
has doubled its police force and planned to deploy para-military
troops, to avert any violence here during today's long march while
the restive local activists of both, the ruling party and the main
opposition BNP have taken up respective programmes.
	   According to sources, local BNP leaders and activists will
receive the convoy of the long march at the Feni-Comilla border and
escort it to Mohipal where BNP chief and former prime minister
Begum Khaleda Zia is expected to address a rally on the way to
Khagrachhari.
	   The Local Awami League, however, vowed to resist it if there was
any untoward incident in the name of long march. Earlier at a
meeting ruling party leader Joynal Abedin Hajari MP also said that
his workers would resist any vandalism in the name of long march.
	   Sources said that the district administration had pointed out
nine vulnerable points in Feni, the ancestral home district of
Begum Zia along the highway to Chittagong.
	   The Deputy Commissioner Noor Mohammad said ``We have taken the
strongest precautionary measures to avert any untoward incident
during the long march programme''.
	   Sources in the local administration said that the most sensitive
points would include Mohipal, Mohammad Ali, Fatehpur, Dagon
Bhuiyan, Rampur, Lalpool, Mohoriganj and Shuvapur.
	   They said that at least one platoon of police force under a
magistrate would be deployed in each of the vulnerable points.
	   ``We have asked for additional forces and three platoons of
para-military force, BDR, which will be added to our local forces
to maintain law and order in the areas,'' said Superintendent of
Police Kazi Anwar Hossain.
	   Our Mirersarai correspondent adds: Thirteen persons were injured
in Mirersarai in Chittagong district today when the a procession
and miking when a group of the supporters of the long march came
under attack from the rivals. One person was missing. Six persons
were injured in the attack. Two persons were injured when a bomb
was hurled at a taxi engaged in miking in support of the long march
at about 3 pm.
	   Four persons were injured and another remained missing when a
procession of Jamaat-e-Islami came under attack near Abur hat at
about 3.30 pm.
	   Tension was prevailing in Mirersarai. Chhatra League workers
have held a rally and procession against the long march.
	   Our Bandarban Correspondent adds: A group of long marchers led
by seven-party alliance leader Kazi Zafar Ahmed would reach
Bandarban tomorrow (Tuesday) morning.
	   The Deputy Commissioner of Bandarban this morning held a meeting
with the leaders of 7-party alliance. Leaders of BNP, Jamaat and JP
(Z-M) attended the meeting.
	   The ruling party leader of Bandarban Bir Bahadur MP visited
different parts of the town yesterday. He said the people of
Bandarban want peace. He said the ruling party had no counter
programme in Bandarban against the march.
	   Our Chandpur Correspondent adds: A big procession organised by
the district units of BNP and JCD in support of the long march
paraded streets of the town yesterday afternoon. A roadside rally
was held later near Railway court Station. SA Sultan Titu presided
and local MPs and leaders of BNP spoke. The long march will start
from Hasan Ali High School at 8 am tomorrow (Tuesday), said
organisation sources.
	   
</TEXT>
