<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sweden-Nazi Gold </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jewish leader says Sweden must assess its World War II behavior
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JIM HEINTZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) _ In its investigation of whether
property of Holocaust victims remains in the country, a Swedish
commission should do a moral accounting as well as a tally of
tangible items, the secretary-general of the World Jewish Congress
said Tuesday.
	   ``We don't just want a bean-counting,'' Israel Singer said at a
news conference. ``That's the least interesting part of the
story.''
	   Singer spoke after meetings with Prime Minister Goeran Persson
and the government commission looking into Jewish property. The WJC
was a prime mover in encouraging Sweden to form the commission,
which is expected to present its report in December.
	   Sweden was neutral in World War II, during which it sold Nazi
Germany goods critical to the war effort, including steel and ball
bearings. Germany paid for the goods in gold, much of which was
returned by Sweden after the war to countries from which the Nazis
had looted it.
	   Despite the return, questions had hovered for decades about
whether other property belonging to Jews had ended up in Sweden and
the government formed the investigation commission last year.
	   Already, the commission has identified more than 600 bank
accounts that had been dormant since the war and that may have
belonged to Jews.
	   Singer said that such developments were welcome, but that he
believes the most important question for the commission to assess
is ``what did Sweden do in World War II and what does Sweden think
of this in 1998.''
	   That is an uncomfortable question for many in Sweden, which both
traded with Adolf Hitler's regime and rescued tens of thousands of
people from it.
	   The Wallenberg family _ often referred to as ``Sweden's
Rockefellers'' _ encompassed the two poles, with Raoul Wallenberg
lionized for his role in saving some 17,000 Hungarian Jews while
his cousins Jacob and Marcus led business dealings with Germany.
	   Singer said the commission's moral assessment should not be a
finger-pointing or an apology. ``I don't know anybody whose
behavior was impeccable'' during the war,'' he said. ``Basically in
Europe there are only gray figures.''
	   ``They don't owe us a `sorry.' They owe themselves the truth,''
he said.
	   (jh)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sweden-Nazi Gold; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
AP-NY-06-09-98 0915EDT
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19980609.0520 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 06/09/1998 09:18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2863 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-Kosovo     06-09 0585
</HEADER>
