<SLUG> BC-NATO-Kosovo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Events in Kosovo unfolding faster than NATO can plan
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JEFFREY ULBRICH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) - Military events in Kosovo are unfolding
almost faster than NATO military planners can plan.
	   Just a few days ago, the generals were focusing on military
exercises and dispatching troops to help Albania and Macedonia deal
with refugees and patrol borders. Now, as one senior NATO official
put it Tuesday, ``We are contemplating more challenging options,
which could include intervention.''
	   More than 250 people have died in Kosovo since Mar. 1 in
escalating clashes between government forces and the Kosovo
Liberation Army, armed wing of the Albanian independence movement.
Ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of the province's
population, are demanding independence from Serbia, the larger of
the two republics remaining in Yugoslavia.
	   The United States and its allies support autonomy for Kosovo but
oppose the rebels' demands for independence and condemn violence on
both sides.
	   In recent days entire villages in Kosovo have been flattened and
thousands of people driven from their homes, making the need for
action more urgent if the crisis is not to erupt into a wider
Balkan war.
	   Twelve days ago, NATO foreign ministers agreed to enhance
military exercises in Albania and Macedonia as a way of increasing
the military presence there. A NATO assessment team is still the
region looking at future options. But as a senior NATO official
said, speaking anonymously: ``With the events of the last week,
shoring up the periphery seems of secondary value.''
	   NATO defense ministers meet in Brussels Thursday and Friday for
discussions certain to be dominated by Kosovo. It is expected they
will order the military to start looking at direct intervention in
Kosovo.
	   Exactly what form such action might take is unclear. Some have
suggested air strikes against Serbian forces, or a no-fly zone. But
military moves that may deter the Serbs may not necessary work
against the insurgents.
	   Any significant move away from the current focus of preventive
deployment along the borders to active military intervention will
require, as one NATO official put it, ``significant political
guidance.''
	   ``We have to see what direction our governments want us to move
in,'' he said.
	   Another official said there is an ``emerging consensus'' toward
direct military action, if not on the specifics.
	   The British, backed by the Americans, are pushing for a U.N.
Security Council Resolution authorizing ``all necessary measures''
to deal with the situation in Kosovo, including intervention. This
would be a sufficient legal basis, but requires the Russians go
along.
	   Until now, Moscow has opposed any direct move against the
Belgrade government of Slobodan Milosevic.
	   NATO officials say there are other legal bases for conducting
such an operation, but are vague about exactly what they are.
	   ``If we can't get that resolution, we'll have to find another
legal basis to act, if action is necessary,'' said the senior
official.
	   The 15-nation European Union and the United States have slapped
a ban on all investments in Serbia and frozen Yugoslav assets
abroad, though Molosevic has not shown himself particularly
susceptible to sanctions in the past.
	   ``We have learned the Serbs don't respond to pressure unless it
is military pressure,'' said the senior official.
	   (ju-pa)
</TEXT>
