<SLUG> BC-Germany-Italy-NATO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Italy's prime minister confident about NATO vote
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi said
Tuesday that his government's stability will not be shaken by a
parliament vote later this month on NATO.
	   Italy's conservative opposition, which won a majority of
municipal elections last Sunday, has threatened to veto the NATO
bill in the lower house of parliament. The move could force a vote
of confidence.
	   ``We can't forget that the NATO proposal has passed in one
chamber of parliament,'' said Prodi during a visit to Germany. If
the opposition were to vote against the proposal, it would be ``the
opposition's problem, not mine.''
	   The Italian senate last month approved the enlargement of NATO
to include Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic, and Prodi's
center-left coalition received the support he needed from the
conservative opposition.
	   But in the lower house vote, expected June 23 or 24, Prodi's
coalition could need opposition support because its far-left ally,
the Rifondazione Comunista, is against NATO's expansion.
 &UR; (aet-pfg)
