<HEADLINE>
Future sound after correction, Tung tells MP's, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Future sound after correction, Tung tells MP's, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   CHIEF Executive Tung Chee-hwa yesterday met with a visiting
delegation from the European Parliament and briefed them on the
latest developments in Hong Kong.
	   The two sides also discussed issues ranging from the evolution
of democracy and the economy in Hong Kong since it returned to
Chinese rule in July last year and future links with the European
Community.
	   On the development of democracy Mr Tung said the process was
enshrined in the Basic Law, which sets a 10-year timetable leading
to full elections including for the post of chief executive.
	   ``The development of democracy must comply with the timetable
set out in the Basic Law. The Basic Law is our constitution and was
written after four years' consultation and should not be amended
lightly,'' he said.
	   Reiterating Hong Kong was going through a difficult period of
economic adjustment, Mr Tung said years of high property prices,
high wages and negative interest rates had built a bubble economy.
	   ``We are experiencing a credit crunch which has worsened because
of the fear of an attack on the linked rate (between the Hong Kong
dollar and the US dollar). Tourism and consumer spending have also
taken a downturn.
	   ``Hong Kong's economy needs to be corrected if we are to regain
our competitiveness.'' The government had foreseen difficulties
ahead when drawing up the 1998-99 budget early this year and
introduced tax reductions and expenditure increases totalling $53
billion or 4 per cent of GDP.
	   ``This has been done well within the principle of prudent
financial management,'' Mr Tung said, adding it would take time for
these efforts to take effect.
	   The chief executive expressed optimism about the future, saying
its economic fundamentals remain sound and economic development on
the mainland is going well.
	   Turning to Europe, Mr Tung said that he was impressed by the
achievements of the European Union in its convergence on the Euro
and in other areas.
	   
</TEXT>
