<HEADLINE>
Ctg preparing for receiving marchers, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Ctg preparing for receiving marchers, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Abdur RahmanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Preparations have been completed in the port city of Chittagong
to welcome thousands of people coming in a long march towards
Khagrachhari.
	   The big political showdown is being organised by the BNP and its
allies including Jamaat-e-Islami Bangladesh to register their
protest against the peace accord on CHT and the consequent passage
of law giving it a legal ever.
	   Briefing newsmen at the party office here at Nasimon Bhaban this
afternoon, Oli Ahmed, the convener of long march supervisory
committee, said the programme was going to be a historic event in
safeguarding the independence and sovereignty of the country.
	   The long marchers, are scheduled to reach Chittagong by tomorrow
evening, but the advance group of volunteers are active to make the
long march a grand success.
	   Two big pandals have been set up at the outer stadium and in
front of Nasimon Bhaban to accommodate the marchers. They will stay
overnight there and will be entertained by the JASAS and the JISAS
cultural groups with cultural function.
	   WASA and the city corporation have extended facilities to supply
drinking water to ten different points and the places of gathering.
Five thousand volunteers have also been deployed to look after the
marchers.
	   A media centre has been set up for the media personnel. The
centre earlier set up at Chittagong Club have been shifted to 33,
Mehedibag with telephone and fax facilities.
	   Leader of the Opposition Begum Khaleda Zia and senior leaders of
the party are expected to reach Chittagong by Tuesday evening. She
will stay at the Circuit House and make her brief address the
following morning before the long march resumes its journey towards
Khagrachhari.
	   Meanwhile, adequate security measures have been taken to keep
the law and order situation under control. Chittagong police have
mobilised additional force including armed police to deploy at
strategic points along the march route. BDR personnel will also be
deployed.
	   To counter the opposition long march, Chittagong city unit of
the ruling party and its front organisations held a joint meeting
on the court premises this afternoon and took out a procession
condemning the long march.
	   Addressing the rally, city Mayor ABM Mohiuddin Chowdhury, who is
also the general secretary of city Awami League, called upon the
long march organisers to shun politics of anarchy and work for the
economic prosperity of Chittagong.
	   He also called upon the people to organise peace committee in
each ward of the corporation to promote peace and development in
the port city.
	   Meanwhile, BNP city unit north and south district units held
rallies in different wards and at key points at thana sadar today
and took out processions there. According to BNP sources, some
pro-Awami League Chhatra League workers forcibly took away mikes
from the possession of the BNP workers at Baroier Hat area under
Mirsarai thana when the BNP activists were launching campaign on
behalf of long march.
	   Jamaat-e-Islami city unit held a rally at Chowkbazar area and
later brought out a procession in support of tomorrow's long march
at the rally, Jamaat leaders said that two Jamaat workers Ramjan
Ali and Farooq were allegedly kidnapped and another one Mohiuddin
Hassan was seriously injured by the Chhatra League activists at
Jorargonj area under Mirsarai thana today when they were miking for
long march programme. Chaired by the Ameer of city Jamaat Mowlana
Abu Taher, the rally was addressed among others by Shahjahan
Chowdhury, Afearuddin Chowdhury, Prof. Mofizur Rahman.
	   Giving his reaction on the long march, the acting president of
Chittagong Chamber of Commerce and Industries (CCCI) Saifuzzaman
Chowdhury said as commercial capital of the country, Chittagong
should be kept free from all trouble so that foreign investment was
not affected and business could be carried on smoothly.
	   According to report received from Khagrachhari, ruling Awami
League and its front organisations have organised a meeting and
procession in the district headquarters denouncing the opposition
long march. A good number of tribesmen attended the meeting.
	   The ruling party decided to show white flags to the opposition
at Khagrachhari where Begum Zia is scheduled to deliver her
concluding march on June 10.
	   The all party unity council also brought out a procession and
held a rally in support of long march. Police today made some
arrests and continued to keep pressure on opposition organisers.
	   Our Staff Correspondent adds: The convenor of long march
supervisory committee and member of the BNP Standing Committee Col
(rtd) Oli Ahmed MP urged the ruling party workers to refrain from
any provocative activities during long march towards CHT tomorrow
and day after tomorrow. If the ruling party workers did something
against long march, the people will deal with it properly he
warned. Oli Ahmed, MP was addressing a press conference here today
at the BNP city office at Nasimon Bhaban.
	   Regarding terrorism in CHT, Col (rtd) Oli Ahmed said during
Sheikh Mujib government in 1973, he was assigned by the government
as an army official to launch operation in CHT. ``All the
governments, from Sheikh Mujib period, were trying to resolve the
CHT crisis'', he added. The press conference was also addressed
among others by member secretary of long march supervisory
committee Abdullah-al-Noman, convenors of reception committee Meer
Md. Nasir Uddin, media committee Ameer Khusru Mahmud Chowdhury, MP,
and security committee Golum Akbar Khandakar. Meanwhile,
Jamaat-e-Islami city (north and south district) units jointly held
a press conference here at the local press club where they called
upon the people to join the long march to protect the sovereignty
and independence of the country. Jamaat will hold a grand rally on
old court building premises at Rangamati sadar on Wednesday where
party chief Prof. Golam Azam will address. About five hundred
vehicles will be arranged to carry the long march participants.
About eight spots including parade ground, Kazem Ali High School
ground, Mohshin College ground have been arranged to accommodate
the marchers. Jamaat chief Golum Azam will also address a meeting
at local Laldighi Maidan on June 10 morning before starting the
long march towards Rangamati.
	   The written statement at the press conference was read out by
the convenor of long march implementation committee Chittagong
Mowlana Mominul Hoq Chowdhury and it was attended among others by
Mowlana Abu Taher, Prof Mofizur Rahman, Shah Jahan Chowdhury,
Afearuddin Chowdhury.
	   
</TEXT>
