<HEADLINE>
Don't play foul games with CHT peace. Azad warns opposition, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Don't play foul games with CHT peace. Azad warns opposition, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad has urged the opposition not
to play foul games to destabilise the peace and harmony in the
Chittagong Hill Tracts.
	   He blamed the BNP and its allies of doing so in all possible
ways. ``They do not want peace to prevail in that area. Their long
march is the latest in the series of their plan to disturb peace
and harmony in the region,'' he added.
	   The Foreign Minister was addressing foreign diplomats at a
briefing session yesterday at state guest house Padma on the
situation arising out of the opposition's march scheduled for
today. Later he briefed newsmen at the same venue on the situation.
	   The briefing session was arranged hurriedly as the BNP leaders
had briefed the foreign diplomats on the long march issue and the
CHT peace process on Sunday.
	   The Foreign Minister accompanied by State Minister for Foreign
Affairs Abul Hasan Chowdhury and Acting Foreign Secretary Mohiuddin
Ahmed said that the opposition had the right to ventilate its
grievances, but, within the laws. ``We hope they are fully aware of
their obligations under the law, when undertaking these kinds of
activities,'' he added.
	   The Foreign Minister said that the government, as promise-bound,
did not have the slightest intention to create any obstacle. ``But
we are worried that some of their leaders have been making
provocative statements.'' He referred to a statement of Col (retd)
Akbar MP of BNP in Comilla in which the BNP MP urged the party
workers to carry licensed arms along with them and not to hesitate
to fire in case of any attack from any quarter on the participants
of the march.
	   Abdus Samad Azad said that they had information that the
opposition would like to deliberately create a law and order
problem. ``For this purpose, it has advised its armed cadres from
different places to join the march,'' he added.
	   Abdus Samad Azad feared that factional feuds within the BNP
itself might encourage some BNP leaders to deliberately create a
situation in which one faction would attack another. He pointed to
the fact that in Chittagong the BNP was sharply divided down the
middle with its two powerful leaders heading two rival factions.
	   He termed the long march a long drive', which he said was
targeted against peace and was a very expensive programme. He said
that the purpose of such an expensive long march was something else
but definitely not peace.
	   He said that he briefed the foreign diplomats about the possible
consequences of the march and the aggressive attitude of the BNP
leaders. When the whole world hailed the peace treaty the BNP was
staging long march against it and that was ridiculous, he added.
	   
</TEXT>
