<BODY>
<SLUG> KHAGRACHHARI-BRACES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Khagrachhari braces for show of strength, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Khagrachhari braces for show of strength, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Both the supporters and opponents of the long march against the
CHT agreement are making hectic preparations to demonstrate their
strength on June 10, when the BNP is scheduled to hold a massive
rally at the Khargrachhari stadium at the fag end of the two-day
long long march'.
	   The supporters of the long march apprehend violent clashes
during the programme. However, they are sharing no efforts to make
the long march programme a success.
	   The organisers of long march have alleged that the police have
already arrested seven persons who were working for the success of
the programme. But the police administration said that none had
been arrested so far.
	   The long march preparatory committee at a press conference
alleged that the police were frequently raiding the houses of the
activists of the BNP and the members of the All-Party Unity
Council. Hence no leader or worker of the BNP was staying at his
house far fear of arrest.
	   The administration has fixed June 10 as the day for ration card
checking for all Bengali settlers who are now staying at cluster
villages. The leaders of the long march preparatory committee
alleged that the arrangement was made to prevent the Bengalees from
attending the rally at the stadium.
	   They also alleged that though the administration had allowed the
organisers of long march to use the Khagrachhari Stadium, they were
asked not to use the bathrooms and toilets of the stadium.
	   Meanwhile the government has asked the Khagrachhari
administration to observe protocol during the stay of the Leader of
the Opposition in Parliament, Begum Khaleda Zia, in Khagrachhari.
	   The press conference was addressed among others by central
leaders Manjur Elahi, Belayet Hossein Bhuiyan, Shabauddin, Syed
Abdul Momen, Haroon or Rashid, Joynal Abedin and Ahasanuddin.
	   Manjur Elahi said that in case of any obstacle from the
administration in organising the long march peacefully , the BNP
would give a call for toppling the government.
	   Meanwhile the administration has kept 1,300, policemen and BDR
force on standby alert to tackle the situation. Twelve magistrates
have been stationed at various points of the town and adjacent
areas.
	   Meanwhile, convener of the Communication Committee on CHT
Hangshadhaj Chakma said that nothing would happen on the day of
long march. He said that the BNP was trying to a create problem in
the CHT. But the people in the region were totally in favour of the
agreement.
	   Chairman of Khagrachhari Pourashava Abul Quasem said that he
would welcome the Leader of the Opposition in Parliament who would
lead the long march procession.
	   Meanwhile activists of both BNP and the Awami League are going
from house to house separately to mobilise public opinion for and
against the long march.
	   The BNP and the Awami League also took out separate processions
in Khagrachhari.
	   Several gates have been erected to receive the Leader of the
Opposition in Khagrachhari by the organisers of the long march. The
main gate was erected in Manikchhari.
	   
</TEXT>
