<HEADLINE>
Deficit may be unlawful, says expert, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Deficit may be unlawful, says expert, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A DEFICIT budget for the next fiscal year might violate the
spirit of Article 107 of the Basic Law, a legal expert said
yesterday.
	   Political parties are demanding a budget deficit for the year
1999-2000 to stimulate the economy.
	   But associate professor of law at the University of Hong Kong
Johannes Chan Man-man said Article 107 was not clear in requiring
the Special Administrative Region government's expenditure to be
limited by its revenue receipts and economic growth.
	   According to Prof Chan there was no violation judging from the
written meaning of the article.
	   ``The written meaning is permissive rather than mandatory,'' he
said.
	   ``However, whether it (a deficit budget) might violate the
spirit of the article is questionable.'' He said a deficit budget
might only be needed and justified under exceptional circumstance
which leaves no option other than breaking the principle of the
article.
	   ``We are not talking about the deficiency of money of the
government but spending more to stimulate the economy,'' he said,
adding it was up to the courts to determine if a deficit was
justified.
	   Article 107 states: ``The SAR shall follow the principle of
keeping expenditure within the limits of revenues in drawing up its
budget, and strive to . . avoid deficits . . .'' 
</TEXT>
