<SLUG> ANTI-LIBERATION-FORCE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Anti-liberation force behind long march, says Nasim, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Anti-liberation force behind long march, says Nasim, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Telecommunications and Works Minister Mohammad Nasim has said
that the BNP and its allies have been making preparations for the
so-called long march programme towards the Chittagong Hill Tracts
(CHT) at the ``signal and with the support of a particular force ``
which opposed the birth of independent Bangladesh in 1971.
	   ``That force does not want political stability in Bangladesh ...
And the long march programme is designed to create disturbance in
Bangladesh so that we can't develop as a prosperous nation,''
Nasim, also the Organising Secretary of the Awami League, told
reporters at his Secretariat office yesterday.
	   Nasim did not identify the ``particular force'' but said that
the organisers of the long march were still opposing the spirit of
the liberation war.
	   The Minister said that the BNP was going to the CHT in the name
of long march spending crores of Taka. ``The only purpose of this
long drive is to create disturbance in the country,'' he said.
	   Referring to the BNP contention that the Bangalees would not be
allowed to live in the CHT and that area would become a part of
India with the signing of the peace accord, Nasim said:'' The BNP's
campaign has failed to confuse the people. A peaceful environment
has been prevailing in the CHT and the tribal and the non-tribal
people are living there in a peaceful environment. Local and
foreign investors are now showing interest in investing in the
CHT.''
	   Asked to comment on the remark of BNP leader Lt Col (retd) Akbar
Hossain, who had urged the BNP workers to join the long march
equipped with their licensed firearms, the Minister said: ``No sane
person can say so...Such persons should be admitted to the Pabna
Mental Hospital.''
	   However, Nasim said that the motive of the BNP's 'long drive' in
the name of a long march towards the CHT had become clear with the
remark of Akbar.
	   
</TEXT>
