<HEADLINE>
Forty workers sacked in Wing On cutbacks, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Forty workers sacked in Wing On cutbacks, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Antoine SoASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FOR the second time in a month, Wing On Department Store has
announced a staff lay off.
	   The company said in a statement yesterday that 40 more employees
would be laid off.
	   The statement said that compensation according to the law would
be offered along with a special gratuity based on the number of
years' service.
	   The 40 employees are from the receive and despatch department
which, according to Wing On, has been centralised to increase
efficiency.
	   The department store chain, one of the biggest in Hong Kong,
laid off 270 employees in May.
	   The company said it regretted the latest decision but added that
it was necessary since the company recorded a more than 30 per cent
drop in revenue in March compared to the same period last year.
	   Newly elected legislator Chan Yuen-han of the Hong Kong
Federation of Trade Unions, said the federation was unhappy over
the company's lack of consultation with staff.
	   ``All of the laid-off employees, including the previous 270,
were sacked suddenly. This is most unfair,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
