<SLUG> BC-Russia-Tchaikovsky </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tchaikovsky competition opens in Moscow
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia's prestigious Tchaikovsky competition
opened Tuesday, with nearly 500 young pianists, violinists,
cellists and vocalists hoping the contest will vault them into the
world's top concert halls.
	   ``This is truly an international musical holiday, which has no
equal anywhere in the world,'' President Boris Yeltsin said in a
greeting to contestants.
	   The competition has been held in Moscow every four years since
1958, when a young American, Van Cliburn, won the piano competition
and instantly became one of the world's best known pianists.
	   The competition runs for two weeks, and will be judged by juries
that include previous Tchaikovsky winners.
