<SLUG> BNP-PROTESTS-PM'S sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BNP protests PM's remark over possible clashes, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
BNP protests PM's remark over possible clashes, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The National Standing Committee of the Bangladesh Nationalist
Party (BNP) yesterday protested the Prime Minister's remark that
clashes in the long march might be the outcome of feuds between the
BNP's own terrorists. The turn of events would prove whether or not
the remark was part of a blueprint to attack the long march or a
cover-up for other conspiratorial activities, it said.
	   The Standing Committee had a meeting at the Minto Road official
residence of the Leader of the Opposition and said that the Prime
Minister's remark had created suspicion in the minds of the people
that it was motivated.
	   In a resolution the meeting also complained that the government
and the ruling party had announced peace processions' in an effort
to foil the long march through provocation and attack.
	   The meeting, presided over by BNP chief Begum Khaleda Zia, urged
the people to make the long march a success. It said that the
government would have to bear serious consequences' if it
obstructed the long march.
	   The BNP Standing Committee reiterated that the long march was a
peaceful political programme announced well in time to safeguard
national independence, sovereignty and integrity, and ensure equal
rights of all citizens.
	   It alleged that the government had been creating obstacles to
the long march programme in various ways as the programme had
attracted huge popular response and the government had become
isolated from the people.
	   The meeting complained that the publicity activities had been
obstructed, terrorist attacks were made, fabricated cases filed and
arrests made without cases. The government had continued to
obstruct the efforts to collect transports for the long march, it
said.
	   Referring to the Prime Minister's remark, the meeting said that
there was no intra-party feud in the BNP, and that the leaders,
workers and well-wishers at all levels had been working shoulder to
shoulder to make the programme a success.
	   The BNP Standing Committee warned that the people of the country
were prepared to give a befitting reply to conspiracies against the
long march.
	   The meeting said that the leaders, workers and volunteers of the
party would remain determined to make the long march a disciplined
and peaceful one. Allout preparations had been made for this. In
addition, cooperation had also been sought in black and white from
the Ministry of Home Affairs, the communications authorities and
others concerned to help keep the march peaceful.
	   The meeting felt assured that the long march would be peaceful
if the government refrained from provocation and attacking it.
	   
</TEXT>
