<SLUG> FOURTEEN-PAPERS-RECEIVED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fourteen papers received on common gas carrier system, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Fourteen papers received on common gas carrier system, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Antoine SoASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FOURTEEN replies have been received in the government's
consultation exercise on a common gas carrier system to make the
fuel supply market more competitive.
	   The market is currently monopolised by the Hong Kong and China
Gas Company.
	   An Economic Services Bureau spokesman yesterday said the 14
responses were from gas suppliers and the public.
	   Advice from the Energy Advisory Committee on the issue has also
been sought.
	   The spokesman described the current government position as being
``open'', pending a study by gas company on a series of related
issues including availability of natural gas, the economic benefits
to consumers and transportation costs.
	   The spokesman said the government wished to explore ways of
encouraging more competition in the gas supply market while
ensuring it was secure and reliable.
	   ``The government believes that the common carrier idea warrants
further consideration in view of its potential to introduce more
competition to the gas market.'' Political parties welcomed the
consultation, which began in June last year, which they said would
eventually benefit the public.
	   Both Democratic Party newly elected legislator Lee Wing-tat and
Democratic Alliance for the Betterment of Hong Kong's Miss Chan
Yuen-han applauded the study.
	   A common gas carrier system enables more than one gas supplier
to supply households.
	   In the long-term, customers would benefit from the increased
competition, although the final cost would be a little higher, both
legislators believed.
	   A spokesman for Hong Kong and China Gas also welcomed the study,
but added that the company was conscious of the ``uncertainties''
involving the issue, including the economic benefits to customers
and the availability of natural gas.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
