<SLUG> YAM-URGES-FLEXIBILITY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yam urges flexibility on land sales, housing, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Yam urges flexibility on land sales, housing, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Sam YungASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Chief Executive of the Monetary Authority, Joseph Yam
Chi-kwong, said efforts to boost the supply of accommodation in
Hong Kong should be applied in a ``flexible'' manner when dealing
with land sales and the building of flats.
	   Speaking in Basle, Switzerland, where he is attending the annual
meeting of the Bank for International Settlements, Mr Yam said the
administration was aware of the need to keep property prices from
falling further.
	   ``I think it would be in the interests of everybody if the
property market stabilises. Because if it continues to fall, then
nobody wants to buy,'' he said, adding further property price
declines could also hit sentiment throughout the rest of the
economy.
	   He said efforts to make more housing available were important.
``Of course this policy must have a long-term dimension, which is
that we ought really to be producing a lot more land and a lot more
housing.'' But he added: ``In the short-term, given what is going
on in the economy, given the deflation process and the fall in
property prices, some flexibility in this long-term policy is
called for, and I think the administration has indicated
willingness to be flexible.'' Meanwhile, Director of Lands Bob Pope
said yesterday he was worried about the difficulty developers were
having obtaining funds to bid for land.
	   Mr Pope acknowledged ``they have a lot of problems raising
finances''.
	   He revealed many developers had tried to negotiate lower
premiums when they modified the use of land.
	   Mr Pope said officials would assess the premium on the market
value. ``If prices are down, we will reflect that,'' he said.
	   Despite these worries, Mr Pope said it was too early to revise
downwards land sale revenue estimates of $50 billion for this
financial year.
	   ``We are fairly conservative in our estimates,'' he said.
``We've got a long time to go. It is just two months into the
financial year. Maybe I can be a little bit more certain in six
months' time.'' He said about $10 billion had been raised from land
sales so far.
	   ``Hopefully towards the end of the year, things will improve and
we will get the revenue expected.'' Mr Pope emphasised that the
land sale program was proceeding to schedule and no changes were
planned.
	   But he also said the government would be flexible when it came
to the program.
	   Several criteria would be taken into account if changes to the
land sale program were needed.
	   ``The aim is obviously to provide housing, that's by far the
most important aim. Revenue is secondary,'' he said.
	   ``Obviously because people in Hong Kong follow the property
market so closely, whatever happens in the property market has an
effect on the economy as a whole.'' He said smaller developers were
more active in bidding for land, either through public auction or
tendering.
	   But he pointed out that this did not mean major developers had
withdrawn from the market.
	   The wider range of developers bidding for land was positive for
Hong Kong, he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
