<HEADLINE>
Best bargains at hypermarts, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Best bargains at hypermarts, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Mon. - The hypermarkets offered the best bargains
for most items surveyed today.
	   For Nescafe (250 grammes) there was a RM2 price difference among
the 10 outlets surveyed. It was cheapest at Carrefour where it was
selling for RM15.90.
	   The good buys for the day included Milo (1kg) priced at RM11.20
at Giant, Naturel margarine (500g) at RM4.90 at Hankyu and Nestle
infant rice cereal at RM3.50 at UDA Ocean.
	   In Ipoh, prices of essential dry goods remained relatively
stable today, with marginal changes in only a few items at the
three major supermarkets here.
	   Nescafe was more expensive at Ocean at RM16.85 for 250g compared
with RM15.70 last week, while the price of a one kg tin of Milo was
higher by 35 sen at the same venue.
	   Meanwhile, a 50-bag box of Boh Superior Tea at Jaya Jusco was
selling at RM4.60, up 60 sen from last week, while retailing at
RM4.50 and RM4.90 respectively at Super Kinta and Ocean.
	   The prices of most other items remained unchanged.
	   In Penang, Everyday instant powdered milk (900g) was selling at
RM13.60 and RM14.10 at the Sui Wah and Super Komtar supermarkets
respectively.
	   F&AMP;N condensed milk (525g) was priced at RM1.95 at Sui Wah while
it was RM2.05 at Super Komtar.
	   Prices of most other items were the same as last week.
	   In Johor Baru, Carrefour offered some of the best prices for a
range of groceries. However, the more up-market Tops supermarket
offered an excellent variety of jams, cereals and cordials.
	   Their shelves were stocked with brands and goods which are not
easily available elsewhere.
	   
