<SLUG> BC-Sports-Auto Racing-Villeneuve-Schumacher </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Villeneuve says Schumacher a law unto himself
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Reigning Formula One champion Jacques Villeneuve
has made a scathing attack on Michael Schumacher following the
German driver's Canadian Grand Prix win Sunday.
	   Villeneuve, whose car was rammed by Schumacher in last year's
season-ending Grand Prix, wrote in his Daily Telegraph newspaper
column Tuesday that Schumacher had become a law unto himself.
	   Villeneuve accused Schumacher of producing several
``questionable maneuvers'' during the Canadian Grand Prix.
	   ``What planet is this guy on?'' Villeneuve said. ``On `Planet
Michael' it would seem, as he believes himself to be all alone on
the track.''
	   ``In Monaco he ran into Pedro Paolo Diniz for no other reason
than he was three laps behind him, and in Montreal he compounded
his errors,'' Villeneuve said. ``Before leaving the pits for the
grid he passed me on the left on the inside of the yellow line
where everyone was working. Why, I have no idea.
	   ``Then, leaving the pits during the race, he forced nz-Harald
Frentzen off the track before cutting across a chicane after
overtaking Damon Hill.''
	   Villeneuve said it was a shame such a talented driver had to
make so many ``blunders'' and questioned how he would be stopped.
	   Schumacher, a two-time world champion and leading Ferrari
driver, caused a furor during the European Formula One Grand Prix
in Jerez, Spain, in October last year when he collided with
Villeneuve.
	   Schumacher held a one-point lead in the drivers' championship
when he rammed into Villeneuve on the 48th lap. Schumacher slid off
the track and out of the race, while Villeneuve went on to win his
first Formula One title.
	   The Formula One world governing body, FIA, ruled the collision
was deliberate, but instead of suspending Schumacher or fining him,
merely voided his second-place finish in the season standings.
	   (jp/sw)	   
</TEXT>
