<SLUG> SWINDLED-$2M-VICTIMS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Firm `swindled $2m from victims', HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Firm `swindled $2m from victims', HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Lydia HoASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A FIRM established to cheat innocent companies and employees of
their money creamed more than $2 million from its victims, the
District Court heard yesterday.
	   Vista Industries, registered in the name of Kwok Wai-ming, 42,
was controlled by the manager who, ``used Vista to cheat people for
money'', prosecutor Isaac Tam said.
	   Between March 1994 and when the company closed down in October
1994, Vista swindled 26 companies with 49 bounced cheques amounting
to $2.3 million, Mr Tam said.
	   Although Kwok signed up two chequebooks for the company, he only
went to the Kwun Tong office a few times each month.
	   Vista employed three female clerks, and two male merchandisers,
Ho Kai-cheung and Tai Chui-ming who were the front men for the
fraudulent activities, having direct dealings with the victim
companies, it was alleged.
	   Both Ho and Tai claimed they were only employees and acted
according to instructions, ordering goods from the companies and
giving the companies Kwok's signed cheques.
	   The men denied any knowledge of the fraud, Mr Tam said.
	   In most cases Vista would conduct legitimate purchases of
electronic goods and present a cheque that would be honoured.
	   But subsequent cheques were dishonoured because the account had
closed, or the account had been overdrawn.
	   The company finally closed on 4 October 1994. Victims reported
their losses to police.
	   Kwok told police that although he ``did not know in the
beginning as to what sort of business the Vista manager was to do,
he knew right from the start when he let the man run his business
that they were doing illegal business to cheat people'', the court
was told.
	   Kwok admitted one count of conspiracy to defraud.
	   His co-defendant pleaded not guilty to the same charge.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
