<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Atlantic-Ship Sinks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South African fishing vessel sinks in South Atlantic
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ Twelve fishermen died and 21 were
rescued after a South African vessel sank in heavy seas near South
Georgia in the South Sandwich islands, the owners said Tuesday.
	   The 45-meter Sudurhavid sank in the Atlantic Saturday night
about 4,000 kilometers (2,600 miles) east of the Argentinean coast,
City Fishing Ltd. of Cape Town confirmed.
	   The survivors were rescued by the Isla Camilla, a South Sandwich
local ship that worked with aircraft from the British Royal Air
Force and the Argentinean Air Force. Four life rafts and an
inflatable boat were retrieved, the company said.
	   The survivors appeared to be in good health at a British
military base on South Georgia Island.
	   The British Royal Navy is expected to send a supply vessel to
transport the men about 2,400 kilometers (1,500 miles) to the
Falkland Islands, City Fishing said.
	   The men would then be flown via London back to Cape Town.
	   There was little chance that more survivors would be found, and
rescue efforts were stopped.
	   ``Given the temperature of the sea ... there is now no hope of
recovering any further crew members alive,'' City Fishing said.
	   (sapa-pr)	   
</TEXT>
