<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-East Timor-Reaction </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Flat reaction to offer of special status for troubled East Timor
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos DIL101-3
 &UR; With BC-Indonesia-East Timor
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER TORCHIA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DILI, Indonesia (AP) _ Indonesia's offer to grant special status
to East Timor to end a long running fight for independence seems to
have fallen flat among its troubled people.
	   Bishop Carlos Belo, Nobel peace prize winner and the spiritual
leader of the predominately Roman Catholic territory, refused to
comment. Instead, he attended a church concert in park adjacent to
his residence in the provincial capital, Dili.
	   Ordinary people said they were unaware of what President B.J.
Habibie's concession would mean for the former Portuguese
territory, invaded by Indonesia in 1975.
	   Community leaders were dismissive, saying that Habibie should
live up earlier promises to grant more democracy to all.
	   Habibie said Tuesday he's prepared to grant special status
within Indonesia to East Timor, but he did not explain exactly what
form the special status would take, the British Broadcasting Corp.
reported.
	   Outspoken former legislator Manuel Viegas Carrascalao said East
Timorese should be allowed to vote on their future through a free
and fair referendum.
	   ``He should respect our right to self determiniation,''
Carrascalao said of Habibie.
	   Students, who have consistently protested against Indonesian
rule while pro-independence rebels fight a guerrilla war, also
called for a referendum.
	   Student leader Jose Aparicio said the offer of special status
for East Timor meant little if East Timorese did not have a say on
whether they wanted to be part of Indonesia.
	   Aparicio also said that rebel leader Xanana Gusmao should be
freed from serving a 20-year prison sentence for leading the fight
against Indonesia's military.
	   Habibie on Tuesday specifically ruled out the possibility of an
amnesty for Gusmao, who is considered a violent criminal.
	   ``They still believe that Xanana is not political leader but
only a criminal. That shows the Indonesian government doesn't know
how to solve the East Timor problem,'' Aparicio said.
	   However, Florentio Sarmento, chairman of the East Timor Action
for Development and Progress, a non-governmental organization,
called for compromise.
	   A political moderate, he argued against a referendum, saying it
could cause more conflict among divided East Timorese.
	   ``We do not have any democratic tradition here. No one is ready
to lose in a referendum,'' he said.
</TEXT>
