<SLUG> BANGLADESH-BUDGET sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bangladesh budget likely to widen VAT, cut duties, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Bangladesh budget likely to widen VAT, cut duties, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Country's forthcoming budget is expected to increase revenue by
expanding the VAT net and to help spur economic growth through
subsidies to agriculture and reduced duties on the import of
industrial raw materials and machinery, business leaders said on
Monday, reports Reuters.
	   ``We want a budget that will support the development of domestic
industries,'' said Yusuf Abdullah Harun, president of the
Federation of Chamber of Commerce and Industries.
	   This in turn would help create employment and raise the
country's exports.
	   Finance Minister S.A.M.S. Kibria is expected to announce the new
revenue budget for 1998/99 (July-June) on Thursday.
	   ``The budget should encourage productivity in the industrial
sector and must protect it by discouraging imports of finished
goods,'' Sharif Afzal Hossain, president of Bangladesh Chamber of
Industries, said.
	   He said the tariff difference for imports of industrial raw
materials and finished goods should be substantial.
	   ``The tax on imports of industrial raw materials should not be
more than 15 per cent and that for finished goods not less than 30
per cent.''
	   Entrepreneurs said the budget was also likely to reduce
subsidies to exports of specialised textile products as the
industry, which annually makes nearly $3.0 billion, had sufficient
help in the past and now employs more than one million people.
	   The government, burdened with heavy recurrent expenditures due
to huge losses by public companies, may expand the value-added tax
net and simplify income tax procedures.
	   Atiur Rahman, a senior economist with Bangladesh Institute of
Development Studies, said he expected a pragmatic budget.
	   ``It may not raise taxes but may seek to expand VAT net and
simplify procedures on filing income tax returns to mobilise
increased revenue.''
	   He said the government might spend some 1.5 billion taka ($32.4
million) on agriculture to boost farm production. The money would
allow farmers to get fertiliser and pesticides at subsidised or
reduced rates.
	   Rahman also said the new budget should be crafted to control
inflation, which is now at an annualised eight per cent.
	   He said the government might fix the growth of gross domestic
product at 6.0 per cent for the new year against an expected 5.6
per cent in the current year.
	   Businessmen and investors are worried about Bangladesh's power
shortfall. The country is currently producing about 1,850 megawatts
of electricity against demand for more than 2,100 megawatts.
	   Rahman said the government ``should immediately put money on the
maintenance of existing power infrastructures and reduce pilferage
or theft of electricity.''
	   
</TEXT>
