<SLUG> SUMMER-OF-FIN-AHEAD sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Summer of fun ahead for tourists, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Summer of fun ahead for tourists, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE streets of Central and Tsim Sha Tsui will be illuminated
within the next two months as part of a package of measures to
attract tourists for the summer sale.
	   The brightening up of the renowned Golden Mile in Tsim Sha Tsui
and Central, organised by the Hong Kong Tourist Association (HKTA),
will be accompanied by the promotion of airlines, restaurants and
hotels.
	   The streets near Lan Kwai Fong will be decorated in July and
August and special menus will be prepared by bars and restaurants
in the area. Nightly special appearances of fringe entertainers
will be organised.
	   The lane of bars at Knutsford Terrace will be decorated and
illuminated during the promotion period and will feature strolling
musicians and entertainers as well as special features.
	   On weekends, a Harbour-front Fest will be organised outside the
Cultural Centre in Tsim Sha Tsui from next month.
	   Street performances, live bands and choirs will be featured.
	   The HKTA hopes the summer promotion will increase visitor
arrivals during July and August, capitalising on the first birthday
of the Special Administrative Region, the new airport and Airport
Express opening and the Hong Kong Food Festival.
	   The gimmicks are also expected to create awareness and
excitement over the summer sales.
	   The HKTA will also offer special packages for the Airport
Express and city rides which include tickets and admissions to the
new Museum of History.
	   Fashion shows, theme parties and instant lucky draws will be
launched by major shopping and retail outlets, including Shanghai
Tang, Lane Crawford, Times Square and Dutyfree Shoppers.
	   Two major trade shows _ the Asia Pacific International Marine
Exhibition and Asia Pacific International Motor Show _ will also be
held.
	   But president of the Outbound Travel Agents Association Ronnie
Ho Pak-ting said decorating the streets would be of little help in
attracting tourists.
	   ``You cannot expect tourists to come here just to see the street
activities and band performances,'' he said.
	   ``We need more permanent tourist attractions to win more
visitors.'' 
</TEXT>
