<SLUG> BC-India-Nuclear Protest,0304 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Anti-nuclear gatehring blasts India, Pakistan tests
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By HEMA SHUKLA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ In the country's largest anti-nuclear
gathering since India's five controversial underground tests last
month, more than 500 activists met Tuesday to condemn the
government's actions and urged it to pull back its nuclear weapons
program.
	   ``A global (nuclear arms) race may be renewed because of these
tests,'' sociologist Rajni Kothari said at a panel discussion that
included a former naval chief, the head of India's Communist party,
a senior judge and other prominent thinkers and academicians.
	   When India first conducted the tests, domestic reaction was
euphoric, with the tests portrayed as a reason for national pride.
But neighboring Pakistan's retaliatory tests and economic sanctions
imposed on India and Pakistan by the international community had a
sobering effect and enlivened the nuclear debate.
	   Admiral Ram Das, who retired as India's navy chief in the
mid-1990s, cautioned that several things could go wrong when
inexperienced and emotional leaders have control over nuclear
weapons.
	   ``We have been told we have a control and command system set up
.... This is all humbug. There is no safety measure built into the
system,'' Das said.
	   Ordinary Indians, he said, were unfamiliar with the horrors of
nuclear weapons and unaware how ill-equipped India and Pakistan
were to deal with a nuclear holocaust. The region had no civil
defense system and no underground shelters, he said.
	   Das said the three nuclear powers in the region _ China,
Pakistan and India _ should talk and agree to end their nuclear
weapon programs. He also said the cost of the weapons was too high
in a region desperate for hospitals and schools. 	   
</TEXT>
