<BODY>
<SLUG> BUDGET-WILL-BE-AS-USUAL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Budget will be as usual: 53pc city dwellers expect, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Budget will be as usual: 53pc city dwellers expect, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Fifty three per cent people of Dhaka City expect the third
budget of this government to follow the usual pattern. On the other
hand 47 per cent think the Finance Minister's recent series of
pre-budget discussion meeting with various organisations,
economists and other groups will enable him to present a budget
which is likely to reflect the general expectations of the people.
	   This has been revealed at the 19th Opinion Poll conducted by the
Centre for Sustainable Development (CFSD) from June 4 to June 6.
The poll sought opinions from 720 residents from different areas of
the city.
	   The respondents are aged from 18 and above. Of them 48.8 per
cent are from 18 to 29 years, 37.2 per cent from 30 to 44 years, 11
per cent from 45 to 59 years and 3.1 per cent from 60 plus age
groups.
	   The sample included people with education level SSC or
equivalent and above. All occupational classes and of both sexes.
The margin of error of the poll results is 1 out of 16. Professor
Ainun Nishat and Dr A K Enamul Haque supervised the poll using
standard polling techniques.
	   When asked to name five areas of expenditures where they want
the government to allocate more funds, primary and secondary
education topped the list with 84 per cent support, power and
electricity from 64.6 per cent, hospitals and health care from 53.1
per cent, transport sector from 31.7 per cent and higher education
from 29.4 per cent people.
	   At the same time, when asked to name five heads of expenditures
where they want the government to cut expenses, 78.4 per cent
favoured the military expenses, 29.6 per cent salary expenses of
the public servants, 22.6 per cent expenses on jute sector, 18.7
per cent in recently introduced old-age allowances and 15.1 per
cent in industry.
	   It has been reported in several newspapers that this budget may
extend the VAT net to increase revenue collections. Responding to
the question, 81.5 per cent think the government should rather try
to cut its own expenses than expanding the tax net. Only 18.5 per
cent think that government has no alternative but to expand the VAT
net to fund its expenses.
	   Government has been slow in deregulating public industries.
Responding to the question of privatisation, 65 per cent opined
that government should speed up the process while 35 per cent said
government should announce deadlines for the privatisation process
to be completed.
	   It has been alleged that tax collection is low due to corruption
in the taxation department. Responding to this question 72.5 per
cent think that the method of tax payment must be made easier to
attract more voluntary tax payment from the public while 27.5 per
cent think that government should lower the tax rate to attract
more payment of taxes.
	   Finance Ministers of Bangladesh on several occasions increased
tax rates, fuel prices, utility rates etc, after the budget was
passed by Parliament. Referring to this practice 87.9 per cent
wanted the Jatiya Sangsad to be called for discussing these before
making such unilateral announcements. At the same time only 12.1
per cent supported the actions of the Finance Minister and thought
that there is no alternative but to raise taxes to meet exigencies.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
