w2907 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx12;  BC-Sports-Soccer-Morocco     06-09 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Morocco-Norway,0618 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Norway heavily favored in their first-ever meeting
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By STEPHAN NASSTROM &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MONTPELLIER, France (AP) _ Perfect preparations, no injuries and
perhaps the most impressive warmup record of all World Cup teams.
	   Norway's ``Drillos'', fourth on FIFA's world rankings after
winning their last three exhibitions over fellow Cup teams Denmark,
Mexico and Saudi Arabia by a whopping combined score of 13-2, are
heavily favored to win their first-ever meeting against Morocco on
the opening day of the tournament Wednesday.
	   Norway scored only one goal in three games during a
disappointing 1994 World Cup in the United States. But it would be
much more disappointing should they fail to make the second round
this time.
	   Morocco's ``Atlas Lions'', also playing in the World Cup finals
for the third time, were eliminated in the first round during the
'94 Cup as well. But another early exit would not be a big
surprise. The Moroccans, coached by former French manager Henri
Michel, are clearly the underdogs in this group.
	   Eleven Norwegians are back, most of them with more experience
from some of the toughest leagues in the world. In fact, Norway
could line up a complete starting lineup of English-based players.
	   Coach Egil ``Drillo'' Olsen watched Morocco draw Chile 1-1 in a
lackluster tuneup in southern France last week.
	   ``Morocco did not play well,'' he said ``Yet I think they were
better than Chile.
	   ``There are no easy matches in the World Cup, but I think we
have a good schedule. If I had the chance to choose, I would never
have picked Brazil in the opening game.''
	   The Moroccans will face a disciplined Norwegian defense that
only allowed two goals in eight games in an unbeaten qualifying
campaign. Norway has played 14 straight games without defeat since
losing 1-0 with a B team away to Australia early last year.
	   Known for its somewhat boring long-ball attack and tireless
running, Olsen will probably stick to his 4-5-1 formation. Tore
Andre Flo, a Cup Winners' Cup champion last month in his first
season with Chelsea, would be the lone striker.
	   Aerial attacks are a Norwegian specialty. So Flo and his older
brother, Jostein, both 1.93 meters (6-foot-4), could be joined by
their cousin Havard Flo (1.85 meters - 6-foot-1) if Olsen decides
to launch an aerial war against the shorter Moroccans with a rare
combo of three relatives.
	   ``Morocco has two or there good players in the air, but that's
it,'' Olsen said.
	   A speedy counterattack is the main offensive weapon from a
defensively oriented Moroccan team. Its key players play together
for Deportivo La Coruna in Spain: defender Noureddine Naybet,
midfielder Mustapha Hadji and forward Salaheddine Bassir.
	   Hadji, a native of France, played eight years for French club
Nancy. Naybet, a sweeper with more than 90 caps, is one of eight
veterans back on the team from 1994.
	   In the 1994 World Cup, Morocco lost all three matches _ against
Poland (2-1), Belgium (1-0) and Saudi Arabia (2-1). Adding to the
team's frustration was its 1-0 quarterfinals loss to South Africa
in the 1998 African Nations Cup in Burkina Faso.
	   Michel, who has led the Atlas Lions since 1995 after coaching
France to the 1986 World Cup semifinals in Mexico, says the Nations
Cup defeat is a huge motivating factor.
	   The players ``want to prove that what happened in Burkina Faso
is not representative of their real abilities,'' Michel said.
	   ``The World Cup is the best chance for them to prove their
abilities.''
	   (sn-tet-jw)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-Morocco-Norway; CT:s; 
