<BODY>
<SLUG> TOP-DOCTOR-FLATTENS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Top doctor flattens fears over canvas shoes, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Top doctor flattens fears over canvas shoes, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Cynthia WanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A TOP chiropractor has disputed another doctor's claim that
wearing canvas shoes _ common among primary school children _ can
cause flat feet.
	   Hong Kong Chiropractors' Association president Dr Edward Lee
Tin-tak said there was no evidence to back the claim.
	   For people with healthy feet, built-in muscles were able to
support their bodies well, he said.
	   ``Wearing any kind of shoes can't really lead to serious
problems because human feet can adapt very well _ they are
themselves good shock absorbers,'' Dr Lee said.
	   ``Shoes are just a protective layer (from cuts).'' But Dr Tsang
Wing-hon, prosthetic and orthopaedics department manager at the
Pamela Youde Nethersole Eastern Hospital, had earlier warned that
playing sports in canvas shoes for a period of time could lead to
flat feet and urged schools to scrap them as a dress code.
	   He said canvas shoes were no better than slippers since they
could not prevent the feet from sliding inside the shoes.
	   Parents should choose shoes with more support on the ankles and
the arches, he said.
	   Children wearing canvas shoes to play sports could develop flat
feet as too much pressure was put on their feet, causing the arches
to lose their ability to spring back.
	   White canvas shoes _ with or without laces _ have been worn by
almost all school children in Hong Kong as sneakers during physical
education lessons at most public primary schools.
	   The compulsory dress code is aimed at standardising uniforms to
avoid brand-name competition among students.
	   The code will probably remain unchanged despite the medical
warning.
	   Chairman of the Subsidised Primary Schools Council Nelson Lau
Chi-keung said he had not noticed any problems with students
wearing canvas shoes during more than 30 years in the profession.
	   ``Pupils with flat feet are usually advised by doctors to wear a
special insole in their shoes, and they would be wearing the
orthopaedic shoes,'' Mr Lau.
	   ``Our school requires students to wear the all-white shoes for
economic reasons.'' But he would suggest parents not buy canvas
shoes without laces, nor those with a thin sole.
	   The Education Department said parents did not have to be
concerned as white canvas shoes were suitable for most sports
taught at schools, such as floor exercises, table tennis and
badminton.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
