<HEADLINE>
Demand for dollar high in forex market, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Demand for dollar high in forex market, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   In the local forex market, demand for US dollar was high on
Monday due to import payment and a three-day long virtual weekend
in both local and international markets and the exchange rate was
between Taka 46.45 and Taka 46.48. Call money rate was higher in
the morning due to the payment of T-bills worth of Taka 153.50
crore but it came down in the afternoon, says a Standard Chartered
market commentary.
	   International markets saw US dollar reaching its seven years
high against yen on Monday when US dollar broke through the
resistance level of 140 and reached 140.73 yen. Remoteness of G7's
support for yen and lingering Bank of Japan's intervention fuelled
US dollar to run this high against yen. Dollar-mark is expected to
remain steady as all are very concerned about dollar-yen.
	   At 1645 local time, dollar traded at 1.7736/41 DEM, 140.19/29
yen and GBP traded against 1.6335/40 US dollar.
	   
</TEXT>
