<SLUG> CAR-MAN-DISAPPEARS-$9M sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Car man disappears with $9m, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Car man disappears with $9m, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Cheung Chi-faiASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ANTI-FRAUD investigators are searching for a car dealer after he
disappeared with $9.6 million in deposits for discounted luxury
vehicles.
	   The Commercial Crime Bureau launched an investigation after
police received 154 complaints concerning the non-delivery of
luxury vehicles, mostly BMWs, which were offered at discounted
prices, since 16 May.
	   Police are appealing to people who have signed contracts to buy
cars from the dealer _ trading as Carboy in Wan Chai _ between
April 1997 and May 1998, as well as those who have received the
ordered vehicles, to contact the Commercial Crime Bureau at 2860
4971.
	   The dealer's showroom in Gloucester Road was found to be closed
down.
	   The latest alleged scam triggered a Consumer Council warning for
the public to beware of unauthorised car dealers who offer
discounts.
	   The council has received 80 complaints against authorised and
unauthorised car dealers in the first four months this year _ 43
complaints more than the same period in 1997.
	   Council spokesman Kenneth So Wai-sang advised consumers to
exercise caution if they wanted to buy vehicles from unauthorised
vehicle dealers.
	   ``It is better to pay on delivery. Consumers should be cautious
about paying a deposit, which should be as little as possible. And
if the delivery takes sometime, consumers should consider whether
they have confidence in the dealers,'' he said.
	   Mr So declined to reveal how many complaints were related to
Carboy or the nature of complaints.
	   Carboy had been offering discounts on its luxury vehicles in the
past year.
	   Authorised dealers have also published a notice in newspapers
warning buyers to be cautious.
	   But one authorised car dealer, a Mr Cheng, said the existence of
both types of dealers provided more choice for consumers.
	   ``The consumers have the freedom to purchase what they like,''
he said. But Mr Cheng warned consumers that the after-sales
services of unauthorised dealers, including maintenance and
provision of accessories, may not be as good as those provided by
authorised agents.
	   
</TEXT>
