<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Middle East Business Briefs </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Kuwait, Egypt, Jordan and UAE &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KUWAIT (Dow Jones) _ Kuwait will ``soon'' cut its oil production
further, Oil Minister Sheik Saud Nasser Al-Sabah said Tuesday.
	   ``I think everybody, for their own interest, has to take a
cut,'' the minister told a joint news conference with Saudi Oil
Minister Ali Naimi.
	   Naimi is touring the region to lobby fellow Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries members to trim output in a bid to
boost prices.
	   Last week Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and Mexico, the three
countries which cut back their production levels in March, pledged
to cut another 450,000 barrels of oil a day from world markets,
beginning July 1.
	   Sheik Saud said the Kuwaiti cuts would be announced following
consultations with the cabinet.
	   He said the cuts were likely to be in the range of 50,000
barrels a day to 100,000 barrels a day.
	   Venezuelan Oil Minister Erwin Arrieta said last week that Kuwait
and the United Arab Emirates would each trim their outputs by
75,000 barrels a day. The U.A.E. has not announced any cuts.
	   ____
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Revenue flowing from Egypt's three main
sources of income has fallen dramatically, the Central Bank said
Tuesday.
	   In its monthly report, the Bank said income from oil, tourism
and ships passing through the Suez Canal fell in April.
	   Income from oil sales was dlrs 69 million, down from dlrs 146
million in April last year, because of the fall in world prices.
	   Revenue from fees charged to ships in the Canal was dlrs 146.3,
down from 149.3 millions for the same period last year. Fewer ships
have been passing through the Canal.
	   As for tourism, the report said the number of tourists in April
was 170,000, down from 317.000 in April last year. It gave no
figure for the decline in revenue for the tourist industry.
	   Tourism has yet to recover from the attack by Islamic extremists
that killed 58 tourists in the southern city of Luxor last year.
	   The report, which is published as an indicator, gave no
prediction of the state's total revenue for 1998.
	   The number one source of hard currency is remittances sent by
Egyptian workers abroad. The report gave no figures for that in
April.
	   ____
	   DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) _ Dubai airport is to embark on
a dlrs 200 million expansion of its cargo facilities, the head of
its department of civil aviation said Tuesday.
	   The project will increase the annual handling capacity of the
airport's cargo village from 400,000 tons to nearly three million
tons by 2010, said Sheik Ahmed bin Saeed al-Maktoum.
	   The expansion will be carried out in three phases and will
include the construction of a mega terminal, capable of handling
2.7 million tons.
	   The Dubai Cargo Village, which was built in 1991, is the
region's busiest cargo hub. It was originally designed to handle
250,000 tons of cargo per year. Its capacity was increased to
350,000 tons in 1995, but it handled more than 400,000 tons in
1997.
	   Officials say the volume is expected to reach 1 million tons by
2005, 2 million tons by 2014 and 2.7 million by 2018.
	   ____
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Germany is to grant dlrs 1.8 million to the
U.N. Relief and Works Agency for the building and equipping of two
schools for Palestinian refugees in northern Jordan, a U.N.
official said Tuesday.
	   UNRWA spokesman Mattar Saqer told The Associated Press the
schools will replace five old ones which are currently attended by
5,000 students in a refugee camps in Irbid, Jordan's second largest
city which lies 88 kilometers (55 miles) north of Amman.
	   Saqer said the new premises will save UNRWA dlrs 140,000 per
year in money spent on maintenance and leasing. The agency faces a
budget deficit of dlrs 9 million,
	   UNRWA provides educational, health, relief and social services
to more than 3.4 million Palestinian refugees living in the Gaza
Strip, West Bank, Jordan, Syria and Lebanon.
	   In Jordan, the agency runs 198 schools which serve 142,000
students in 13 Palestinian refugee camps.
