<SLUG> BIRD-FLU-HEALTH-CHECKS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
90pc of stall owners may lose licences in bird flu health checks, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
90pc of stall owners may lose licences in bird flu health checks, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   UP TO 90 per cent of poultry stall owners face having their
business licences cancelled for failing to fully comply with new
hygiene requirements to combat avian flu.
	   The 15 June deadline is a week away for full compliance with the
new hygiene requirements imposed following the avian flu scare.
	   The new hygiene conditions were aimed at upgrading hygiene at
poultry stalls.
	   The measures include the installation of a refrigerator for
slaughtered poultry and a high pressure water jet cleaner, as well
as the use of durable and impervious cages for live poultry.
	   Steven Wong Wai-chuen, vice-chairman of the Poultry Retailers
Association, appealed for a three-month extension of the grace
period which ends next Monday.
	   He estimated only 10 per cent of poultry vendors had fully
complied with the government's new standards.
	   Mr Wong said many business owners were reluctant to further
invest in the stores due to the recent business slump. He estimated
the new facilities would cost around $100,000 for each stall.
	   Mr Wong said business had dropped 40 per cent due to the
economic slump aggravated by high chicken prices.
	   He said wholesale prices remained at the $14 to $18 per catty
level, compared to the $9 to $12 before the government ban on
chickens in December. The retail price is now between $22 and $24
per catty.
	   ``Many people see it as not worth spending about $80 on a
chicken, especially when the whole economy is in a slump,'' Mr Wong
said.
	   He added that many consumers were now choosing other meats such
as pork for their meals.
	   Meanwhile a spokeswoman for the Urban Services Department _ the
licensing authority for the 383 poultry market stalls and about 220
fresh provision shops in the urban area _ said the department was
unlikely to extend the deadline.
	   What it would do was consider the poultry stalls and meat shops
on a ``case-by-case'' basis when the 90-day-grace period was over
next Monday.
	   The spokeswoman said the department had been aware of the
situation where most vendors failed to use the high pressure water
jets to clean the shops and equipment on a daily basis.
	   The officials of the Regional Services Department could not be
reached for comment.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
