<HEADLINE>
Precede LAGOS
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Dissident: Abacha's death `incredible opportunity' for Nigeria
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS precede; UPDATES with comment from France, former
foreign minister &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Nigeria-Abacha &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo JRL111 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ The death of Nigeria's military ruler inspired
fresh hope among dissidents and governments that the nation could
now move rapidly toward democracy.
	   Some campaigners for democracy were cheered by the appointment
of a career military man to succeed Gen. Sani Abacha as head of the
government.
	   ``It's my belief, it is my hope that in the next few days, Gen.
Abdulsalam Abubakara, whom I know very well, is going to open
dialogue with the civilian opposition leaders in that country
towards redressing the issues that are on the table,'' former
Nigerian foreign minister Bolaji Akinyemi said Tuesday in an
interview with BBC radio.
	   Wole Soyinka, the Nigerian writer who won the 1986 Nobel Prize
in literature and an outspoken opponent of military rule, told
reporters in Jerusalem that Abacha's death presented ``an
opportunity for Nigerian civic society, an opportunity for the
Nigerian military, and an opportunity for the international
community.''
	   ``The people were sick of military dictatorship,'' Soyinka said.
``So it's up to the military to recognize this _ and up to the
international community to say that we're sick and tired of the
degeneration of a potentially great society.''
	   The United States, Britain and the Commonwealth of Britain and
its former colonies urged a quick transition to democracy in
Nigeria, a former British colony. France also urged Nigeria's new
leaders in that direction.
	   ``We hope that following the death of Gen. Abacha, there will be
an opening for a stable transition to an early return to democracy,
with the election of an accountable civilian government which will
restore and respect human rights,'' Britain's Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook said in a statement.
	   ``Our hope, among others, would be, at this moment of
transition, that an accountable civilian government ... will emerge
from what has been a very horrific episode in which basic
fundamental rights have been suspended,'' said White House
spokesman Mike McCurry said.
	   The 53-nation Commonwealth suspended Nigeria after playwright
Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other dissidents were executed in 1995.
	   Nigerian Chief Emeka Anyaoku, secretary-general of the
Commonwealth, told BBC TV: ``The Commonwealth would hope and would
expect that the Nigerians will decide to go back to the way of
democracy and in so doing will gain readmission to the
Commonwealth.''
	   The international community should now press for elections in
Nigeria this year, said New Zealand's foreign minister, Don
McKinnon, who is also vice-chairman of the Commonwealth Ministerial
Action Group on Nigeria.
	   ``Nigeria was one of the leaders in democracy in Africa back in
the 1960s and there's no reason why they can't return to it,''
McKinnon said.
	   In New York, a spokesman for U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
said Annan praised the contribution made by Nigeria under Abacha to
ending the civil war in nearby Liberia and to restoring the
democratically elected government of Sierra Leone.
	   ``It is our hope that the good relations that exist between our
two countries will persist and that the path to democracy in
Nigeria will be pursued to its full conclusion,'' read a statement
issued from the Organization of African Unity summit in Burkina
Faso.
	   Nigeria's next leader could hardly be worse than Abacha,
Saro-Wiwa's son said in Britain.
	   ``In Nigeria, the thinking has always been that every successive
dictator is worse than the previous one, so one hopes that we don't
get another dictator because he will have quite a record to better
Abacha's appalling record,'' said Ken Wiwa.
	   Soyinka urged the military to release all political prisoners,
including Moshood Abiola, the apparent winner of Nigeria's aborted
1993 presidential elections, and name Abiola head of a transitional
national unity government.
	   ``There's only one choice for Nigeria _ that's a democratic
option,'' he said. ``And the structure is there. The
president-elect is waiting,'' Soyinka said.
	   (buros-rb)
</TEXT>
