<HEADLINE>
DSE dips further, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
DSE dips further, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The all share price index in the Dhaka Stock Exchange (DSE)
further plummeted yesterday for the second consecutive day created
a fresh crisis in the market following a bullish business for the
last few days.
	   The DSE price index plunged by over 16 points yesterday to 672
points following a nose-dive of 89 points Sunday. The change in
capitalisation yesterday was 2.41 per cent over that of Sunday.
	   The downswing in the DSE came as a thunderbolt as the market had
been steadily gaining in the previous week, with a jump of over 81
points in share prices alone on Saturday, the first business day of
the current week.
	   Then came the abrupt nose-dive from Sunday that continued
yesterday. The Chittagong Stock Exchange (CSE) was also witnessing
similar decline in the share price index after an upswing last
week.
	   The CSE price index yesterday fell by 9.6 points to 303 points.
In terms of capitalisation it declined by 2.90 per cent over the
previous day's (Sunday) business turnover. On Saturday, the index
also fell by 11.32 points.
	   In all 133 issues were traded yesterday in the DSE of which 27
gained and 104 incurred loss, while in the CSE 38 issues were
traded yesterday of which three gained and 35 incurred loss.
	   The market analysts said yesterday's fall in the price index
both at Chittagong Stock Exchange and Dhaka Stock Exchange was in
conformity with the plunge the market suffered on Sunday. But they
were quite at a loss to explain why it was behaving so erratic
while the market fundamentals remained by and large poor.
	   The DSE sources were, however, unanimous on, one point -- that
is the short supply of shares and debentures to put investors money
from a wide range of choice.
	   A Kerb market trader said because there was a shortage of blue
chips, how long will the traders wait and keep away from investment
in anticipation that new issues were coming in the market?
	   He said there was no indication that fresh issues were coming,
so they were buying second rate shares and even the shares that
which had otherwise no appeal to the investors. It was a supply
crisis. But it was also a confidence of crisis at the same time.
	   He said investors were not ready to take risks, so everytime
there would be a rise in the share prices it would be followed by
rush for sale and cash the profit. The DSE officials also made
similar observations and said that in the present context even bad
chips had become good ones only to bridge the gap between the poor
supply and the increasing demand.
	   A section of dishonest traders had tried through the kerb market
to create a market warm up and thereby make whatever financial gain
was possible to exploit from the floor, some sources alleged.
	   That was what exactly happened in a wider scale before market
crash in December 1996. It could partly explain why the share
prices fell over the last two days after a bullish business over
the last few weeks.
	   The analysts said that the market indication was that the small
investors were prepared to put money in the stock market. But the
government failed to increase the number of new issues.
	   
</TEXT>
