<SLUG> ALLOWANCE-INCREASE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Councillors to seek common ground on allowance increase, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Councillors to seek common ground on allowance increase, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Simon NgASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PROVISIONAL Regional Councillors are searching for a consensus
over an expected pay rise proposed in a review on the allowance
system.
	   The review is said to have proposed a 16.3 per cent increase in
allowance, from $51,360 to $57,520 a month.
	   It will also introduce a new system to divide the allowance into
personal and administrative expenses.
	   Two-thirds of the proposed allowance will be earmarked for
office expenses.
	   Democrat Josephine Chan Shu-ying, a member of the interim
council's ad hoc committee on members' allowance, said the group
had yet to discuss the recommendation which was originally
scheduled for April.
	   ``Given the current economic situation, it is hard to justify
the rate of increase to the public,'' she said.
	   Ms Chan said either the allowance should be frozen or a ceiling
for the increase should be set.
	   ``The personal allowance should be revised according to the
civil service pay rise, but the office expenses can be revised
according to the inflation rate.'' She said councillors from the
Democratic Party would meet later to unify their stance.
	   Her colleague Lee Wing-tat said the party supported the new
system, but added members had yet to decide whether to agree to
freeze the increment.
	   Au Yeung Po-chun, of the Democratic Alliance for the Betterment
of Hong Kong, said her party agreed the new allowance should be
frozen for a year.
	   But she said they were still considering whether to endorse
dividing the allowance into two parts.
	   ``Take me as an example, I run two offices, so the new system
will not be an advantage,'' she said.
	   But she added that the debate on the new system should not be a
big problem _ she will support it if her party does.
	   Independent Ting Yin-wah is all for freezing the increase.
	   ``If the new system is implemented, an increase in allowance
will follow eventually, so it should be frozen together with the
allowance increase.'' 
</TEXT>
