<HEADLINE>
Plans should be drawn up to maintain ecological balance: PM, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Plans should be drawn up to maintain ecological balance: PM, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina yesterday directed the officials of
Water Resources Ministry for taking into consideration the natural
condition of the surroundings while making any plan.
	   ``All plans should be drawn up maintaining ecological balance,''
she said reviewing a high-level meeting at the Secretariat
yesterday.
	   She emphatically stated the need for land reclamation and
evolving domestic system for implementing water-related projects as
well as achieving self-reliance rather than dependence on donors.
	   Referring to the crying need for creating green belt in the
coastal region, Hasina called for coordination among Water
Resources Ministry, Forest and Environment Ministry and Bangladesh
Navy for afforestation programme in the region.
	   She also stressed on dredging of rivers to reclaim lands and
said country's water bodies and canals are being silted up which
should be redressed urgently.
	   The Prime Minister asked the officials for taking steps to
ensure navigability of the rivers and solve the waterlogging
problem.
	   Hasina directed the officials to make judicious use of land and
suggested appropriate measures for development of haor, baor and
beels.
	   She expressed her concern over the encroachment of rivers and
canals and suggested coordinated efforts to stop this.
	   While reviewing various projects of the ministry Hasina called
for speedy implementation of the projects and their proper
monitoring.
	   She was happy to know that the Water Resources Ministry has been
using mini machine for dredging purposes.
	   Earlier, Water Resources Minister Abdur Razzak said due to the
dynamic effort of the Prime Minister Water Sharing Treaty with
India has been signed and the Ganges Barrage Project will now be a
reality.
	   He listed several steps for streamlining the manpower and
resources of the ministry.
	   Razzak informed that the ministry has prepared a draft of
National Water Policy which will be placed for approval soon.
	   
</TEXT>
