<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Jordan-Press </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jordan endorses controversial draft press law
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ The government on Tuesday endorsed a
controversial draft press law that could considerably restrict
press freedoms.
	   The draft has to be approved by Parliament which will debate it
later this month, said a senior government official, speaking on
customary condition of anonymity.
	   The bill comes five months after the supreme court overturned a
government decree ordering 13 tabloids to cease publication for
allegedly violating the provisions of another draft press law that
was introduced in May 1997.
	   The January ruling invalidated the previous draft law. The court
said then that the government could not enforce the draft law
without parliament endorsement.
	   The current press law has been in force since 1993. But the
government says its flexible provisions has led to a freewheeling
media which it says violate the norms and ethics of professional
journalism.
	   King Hussein had said his patience was wearing thin with
Jordan's 22 weekly tabloids, which are largely affiliated with
Muslim fundamentalist and other hard-line groups opposed to his
1994 peace treaty with Israel and pro-Western style.
	   The king's warnings were often accompanied by a clampdown on the
media, including sporadic blackout on news events, newspaper and
magazine censorship and frequent arrests and imprisonment of
journalists.
	   The New York-based Committee to Protect Journalists named Prime
Minister Abdul-Salam Majali as one of 10 enemies of the press
worldwide in 1998.
	   Critics had warned the government against adopting the draft
press law.
	   ``Endorsing such a law will be a real massacre of public
freedoms in Jordan,'' wrote columnist Saleh Qalab recently in the
mass circulation al Arab al Yawm newspaper.
	   ``If it is endorsed, it will take Jordan back to the days of
martial law and it will impede its progress for a long time to
come,'' he added.
	   But King Hussein told a group of 150 journalists last Saturday
that the law will provide a ``more responsible press'' and increase
public freedoms.
	   A minimum fine of dlrs 50,000 _ a 30-fold hike _ will be slapped
on those who violate vaguely defined provisions of the state
security, said the government sources.
	   The draft law also forces journalists to divulge their sources
in court and gives the government more powers to censor the media.
 &UR; jjh-sf
</TEXT>
