<SLUG> DEMOCRATS-TO-FIGHT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Democrats to fight increase in class size, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Democrats to fight increase in class size, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Cynthia WanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Democratic Party will call for a motion in the new
Legislative Council to overturn the Education Department's decision
to place two more pupils in every classroom.
	   Backed by seven major education groups, Democrat Cheung
Man-kwong, chairman of the Hong Kong Professional Teachers' Union,
said yesterday he would ask fellow legislators to stop the
government from cramming classrooms.
	   Whatever the outcome, it will not be able to change the fact
that 30,518 kindergarten children were allocated primary one places
last Saturday.
	   They will register with the schools they have been assigned
today and tomorrow.
	   Any changes will only take place next year.
	   However, Yeung Yiu-chung of the Democratic Alliance for the
Betterment of Hong Kong does not see the necessity to freeze the
plan, provided more teachers are employed.
	   Mr Yeung, chairman of the Hong Kong Federation of Education
Workers, will meet officials from the Education and Manpower Bureau
to demand 182 more teachers be hired at a cost of $41 million to
cope with the inflated class size.
	   The government has refused to open about 1,961 vacant classrooms
to ease the overcrowding because they are either situated in remote
areas, scheduled for demolition or reserved for whole-day
schooling.
	   ``We do support whole-day schooling, but the resources saved (on
closed classrooms) should be spent on frontline educators,'' Mr
Yeung said.
	   In response to the pledge in the Policy Address for 60 per cent
of schools to operate on a whole-day basis by 2002/2003, the
Education Department has ordered the class size increases as a
temporary measure.
	   But the education groups argued whole-day schooling should be
achieved through building more schools and making use of vacant
classrooms.
	   They said the larger class sizes would reduce interaction
between teachers and pupils and increase teachers' workload.
	   At least 20,000 signatures have been collected from teachers and
school heads from primary and secondary schools to oppose the plan
with a second round of the campaign running currently under way.
	   From September, Primary One classes will be boosted from 35 to
37, while activity approach classes will increase from 30 to 32.
	   The reduction in class sizes in secondary schools is being
shelved.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
