<HEADLINE>
Editor of Iranian newspaper found guilty of libel and defamation
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ A court has convicted the editor of one of
Iran's most popular newspapers of libel and defamation.
	   The court handed down its verdict Monday against Hamid Reza
Jalaipur after hearing charges brought by the deputy public
prosecutor, the head of the Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps and
the State Prisons Organization, Iranian television reported
Tuesday.
	   The plaintiffs accused Jalaipur of printing ``insults, lies,
actions against public morality and publication of lies to agitate
public opinion,'' the television reported.
	   Last month, the revolutionary guard said reports published in
the newspaper accusing its commander of attacking growing
liberalism in the country were distorted and aimed at creating
tension.
	   Jalaipur's newspaper, Jameah, has been testing the limits of new
press freedoms introduced since moderate President Mohammad Khatami
took office in August. The afternoon daily, which started in
December with a circulation of 200,000, sells out within hours.
	   Khatami's reforms enjoy the support of most Iranians, but
hard-line elements in the government, particularly the powerful
judiciary, have resisted them.
	   Jalaipur's sentence was not made public.
