More budgetary allocation for northern zone demanded, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   North Bengal Lawyers Forum yesterday demanded that the
government make budgetary allocation in the next budget money for
North Bengal in proportion to its population.
	   President of the Forum Akram Hossain Amin and Secretary General
Md Abdus Salam Mondal made the demand while speaking at a press
conference at the Jatiya Press Club in the city yesterday. Vice
presidents of the Forum Alhaj Giasuddin Ahmed, Advocate Ayenuddin
and Alhaj Abdus Samad were also present.
	   The Forum secretary general read out its 16 point charter of
demands. He demanded appointment of justices in the High Court
division of the Supreme Court, law officers and law advisors to
different banks, insurance and corporations from the lawyers of
North Bengal on the basis of population.
	   The Forum's demands also included: gas connection to North
Bengal on an emergency basis, immediate construction of Teesta
Barrage, elevation of Rangpur Carmichael College into a
full-fledged university, establishment of a branch of National
University in North Bengal, immediate rail connection to Bogra,
announcement of Syedpur as a city, establishment of an
international airport at Bogra, a full-fledged TV centre at North
Bengal, a branch of Bangla Academy at Rajshahi and international
tourist centre at Panchagarh.
	   The Forum secretary general also demanded the holding of at
least one session of the Jatiya Sangsad and two meetings of the
cabinet at Uttara Ganobhaban every year.
	   
</TEXT>
