<SLUG> BC-Britain-French Strike Fallout </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
As World Cup begins, Air France strike lucrative for rivals
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DIRK BEVERIDGE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Business Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ For Air France's rivals, the timing couldn't be
better: A strike by pilots has crippled the French flagship carrier
just as thousands of people are heading to France for the World Cup
games.
	   Most Air France flights are grounded, but anybody watching the
runways in Paris can see that the other guys are landing with the
largest airplanes they can find.
	   British Airways said Tuesday it is replacing some short-haul
Boeing 757s with 747 jumbo jets on routes into France, adding more
than 200 seats per flight that it can sell to stranded soccer fans.
	   Switching to bigger airplanes _ British Airways is also
replacing some 757s with larger 767s _ will let the carrier fly up
to 2,400 extra people from London to Paris this week alone.
	   With sports enthusiasts from around the world forced to change
their plans, British Airways estimates it's bringing in an
additional 1 million pounds (dlrs 1.6 million) a day in unexpected
revenues.
	   Air France's misfortune is also creating a bonanza at the
Eurostar high-speed train services that take people between England
and France through the undersea Channel Tunnel.
	   Eurostar is bringing in tens of thousands of pounds (dollars)
daily in extra revenue, although the train bosses were bashful
about offering any precise estimates. A separate desk has been set
up to handle the flood of passengers transferring from Air France,
Eurostar said.
	   ``It's a few hundred coming our way each day,'' Eurostar
spokesman Roger Harrison said. With fares running up to 319 pounds
(dlrs 520) per passenger, that adds up quickly.
	   Airlines and train companies had counted on lots of extra
business from the World Cup matches that begin Wednesday and run
for a month in 10 French cities. But the walkout at Air France made
the business outlook even better.
	   Lufthansa German Airlines said demand was up on routes between
Germany and France, so Lufthansa, too, is rolling out bigger
aircraft when possible. Spokeswoman Gudrun Gorner could not say how
many seats will be added or how much extra money Germany's big
airline hopes to rack up.
	   At British Midland, executives said the Air France strike had
created a marginal improvement over business that was booming
anyway because of the World Cup.
	   How high will profits rise?
	   ``I would imagine it's going to be an extra 40 percent, but I
don't have a pound figure,'' spokeswoman Sarah Able said.
	   (db-kg)
</TEXT>
