<BODY>
<SLUG> BANK-REJECTED-CASH-ADVAN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`I lost RM1.5m deal after bank rejected cash advance', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`I lost RM1.5m deal after bank rejected cash advance', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ruslaini AbbasASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Mon. - Through no fault of his, a businessman
holding a Citibank Bhd Preferred Mastercard lost a RM1.5 million
contract when the bank rejected his application for a RM1,710 cash
advance, the Sessions Court heard today.
	   Businessman Kogelen Govindasamy said besides losing the
contract, he also had to pay RM150,000 to the other party for
failing to deliver the goods concerned.
	   Kogelen said the bank rejected his application for a purported
payment default, when in fact he had made the payment, but the
money was credited to someone else's account.
	   In his statement of claim, Kogelen, a card holder since 1994,
said he paid RM2,000 to the bank on Oct 15 and was told he could
use the card three days after payment was received.
	   On Oct 28, 1996 when he was in Madras, he applied from Citibank
Madras for an advance of Rs 25,000 (RM1,710), but his application
was rejected since he had purportedly failed to pay RM2,000.
	   Kogelen said although he appealed for his application to be
considered to avoid losing the contract to supply the anti-wrinkle
creme Liposol, the bank refused to entertain his appeal.
	   He found out later that due to Citibank's negligence, the Oct
15, 1996 payment was credited into the account of another
Mastercard holder on Oct 19, 1996. The money reverted to his
account only on Nov 12, 1996.
	   He is claiming RM150,000 in damages, interest, costs and other
relief.
	   Kogelen was represented by T. Kunan while K. Vijayaram appeared
for the bank.
	   In its defence, the bank denied telling Kogelen that he could
use the card after paying RM2,000.
	   It said at the material time Kogelen had passed the due date for
payment and had failed to settle within time.
	   The bank said it could suspend the card facilities if payment
was late.
	   Asked by his counsel, Kogelen said he could not buy his plane
ticket to Bangalore since he normally used his credit card when
abroad.
	   Moreover, there was a limit on the amount of rupees one could
take into India.
	   The bank's witness Calvin Chan said even if the money was
rightly credited, Kogelen was still not entitled to use the card
since he still had to pay another RM474 as the minimum payment was
RM2,474.
	   Hearing continues on June 15.
	   
</TEXT>
