<SLUG> PUBLIC-SALARIES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Call for freeze in public salaries, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Call for freeze in public salaries, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   May TamASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE pro-Beijing Hong Kong Progressive Alliance (HKPA) will
contribute towards reviving Hong Kong's economy by freezing any
salary increase for lawmakers and lobbying others to do the same.
	   Party chairman Ambrose Lau Hon-chuen hoped his austerity move
would also influence members of the two municipal councils and
district boards to freeze their salaries.
	   He and three other party members unveiled their proposal after
holding pre-budget talks yesterday with Financial Secretary Sir
Donald Tsang Yam-kuen.
	   Mr Lau also hoped the proposal would influence civil servants to
consent to lowering their proposed pay rise, which ranges from 5.79
per cent to 6.03 per cent.
	   He said the rate of increase was not in line with the spirit of
the government in sharing difficulties with the people.
	   But he did not confirm whether HKPA members in the first SAR
legislature would go for the freeze alone if other parties refuse
to follow suit.
	   The next pay rise for the legislature is scheduled for October.
	   ``We will consider what we should do. It is not fair if only you
are frugal and others not,'' Mr Lau said.
	   ``We are willing to take the lead to freeze our members' salary
in the legislature which may produce a catalytic effect to share
the economic hardship with Hong Kong citizens.'' He proposed
keeping the salary at $57,330, the same level as before last
October.
	   In February, 52 of the 60 provisional legislators decided not to
implement a salary increase to $60,830 backdated to October.
	   On the next budget, Mr Lau told Sir Donald a deficit budget
would be acceptable if the government needed large expenses to
maintain basic social services and stimulate the economy.
	   Mr Lau did not think a deficit budget would violate the Basic
Law.
	   
</TEXT>
