<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-US-International Callback,0762 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Virginia company sells cheap phone calls to Russia
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING to restore cycle designator &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo NY138 &QL; 
 &UR; By JAN CIENSKI &QC; 
 &UR; AP Business Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   RICHMOND, Virginia (AP) _ Want to make a call from Yakutsk _
Russia's Siberian diamond and gold capital _ to Moscow? Route the
call through the United States, then back to Russia, and you could
save a lot of rubles.
	   A small Virginia company, Applied Information Technologies, has
found a niche by supplying cheaper and clearer phone connections to
Russians, even if those calls have to travel thousands of extra
kilometers (miles).
	   Russia's primary phone company, Rostelcom, charges about dlrs
2.50 a minute for a call from Yakutsk to Moscow during peak hours.
AIT can do the same for dlrs 1.30, said Kim Kerns, owner of the
husband-and-wife operation based in the Richmond suburb of
Midlothian.
	   Discount or ``callback'' telephone systems allow callers
overseas to save a bundle by using an American phone line, skirting
the much higher prices charged by government-owned phone companies
in other countries.
	   To use a callback service, a subscriber dials an American phone
number provided by the service, lets it ring once and hangs up.
Since no one picks up on the other end, the caller is not charged.
The service's computer then calls the user back and gives a dial
tone, allowing the subscriber to make the call back overseas, but
billed as a call originating from the United States.
	   The callback computer wizardry is done by specialized
telecommunications companies that sell phone numbers to smaller
resellers such as the Kerns, who in turn market them around the
world.
	   ``What you're ... trying to do is circumvent the telephone
monopolies and everything that goes along with that, including high
rates and virtually nonexistent service,'' Trevor Gunnd said.
	   Gunnd is deputy director of Business Information Service for the
Newly Independent States, a branch of the U.S. Commerce Department
that tries to help companies like AIT do business in the former
Soviet Union.
	   ``Obviously callback is inconvenient but people use it to save
money,'' said Stacy Oh, director of marketing for Encino,
California-based Cross Communications Inc., an international
callback provider.
	   The callback industry started in the early 1990s and is worth
about dlrs 1.4 billion this year, said Cathleen Woodall, director
of marketing for M.J. Scheele and Associates, a San Francisco-based
telecommunications consulting company. The services have become
popular among expatriates living in countries like Japan that have
steep long-distance phone rates.
	   Ms. Woodall said there are about 170 callback providers, most
based in the United States.
	   Fifty-seven countries ban callback services, including the
Bahamas, India, China and Venezuela, according to a survey
conducted by the International Telecommunications Union in Geneva.
The services are legal in the United States.
	   While some countries try to block callback companies, others
embrace the new technology.
	   ``There are countries like Russia that support and encourage the
use of callback because it allows business to flourish and their
infrastructure is bad and they know it,'' Kerns said.
	   Kerns has about 140 customers, most in Russia and Ukraine, and
he has sales agents in Moscow and Yakutsk with about 500 additional
clients. He also has customers scattered around other countries
including India, Pakistan and Brazil. He would not say how much his
company earns.
	   Kerns has never been to Russia. He uses the Internet to find
salespeople and advertise his service. He requires most of his
customers to pay up front so people a world away don't stick him
with unpaid bills.
	   His agent in Yakutsk found him by trolling the World Wide Web
for a company offering cheap phone service. The agent runs a travel
business and his customers were complaining that they needed a
reliable and inexpensive way to call their home offices in St.
Petersburg on the other side of Russia.
	   Small callback resale businesses like Kerns' face a tough
future, Ms. Woodall said. Foreign phone companies are lowering
their rates in response to competition, cutting the callback
providers' profits.
	   ``We are definitely seeing a dropoff in callback service because
the margins are being squeezed so extremely,'' she said. ``I'd say
growth is going to be kind of flat. Staying the same for the next
year and maybe dropping of a little the year after that.''
	   Kerns has noticed that it's more difficult to make money.
</TEXT>
