<HEADLINE>
$566m airport post office, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
$566m airport post office, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Ceri WilliamsASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE new airport was given a stamp of approval with the launch of
a $566 million postal centre yesterday.
	   Organisers said the 24-hour operating Hongkong Post Air Mail
Centre at Hong Kong International Airport, Chek Lap Kok, will
handle around 548,000 letters daily.
	   Postmaster General Robert Footman said it would be operated by a
staff of 250 and open on 6 July when the new airport was launched.
	   ``The air-mail centre will meet postal needs well into the next
millenium and help us to offer superb postal services to the
community,'' he said.
	   ``It is equipped with the latest state-of-the-art technology
capable of handling rapidly growing air- mail traffic.'' Letters
and parcels will be sorted by special processing machines instead
of by hand. And a container storage system will process mail that
will then be put onboard planes.
	   Financial Secretary Sir Donald Tsang Yam-kuen praised
organisations such as government department Architectural Services,
who were the building managers and designers behind the new centre,
for launching the project.
	   British Postal Consultancy Service was the project consultant
and Yau Lee Construction was the building contractor. Siemens
ElectroCom of Germany was the main contractor for supplying postal
automation equipment.
	   ``The new centre will bring our postal services into a new era.
The state-of-the-art system will ensure that our postal services
will be efficient and one of the most advanced in the world,'' Sir
Donald said.
	   Other facilities at the new postal centre include an Elevating
Transfer Vehicle which handles bags of post for outgoing airmail.
	   
</TEXT>
