<HEADLINE>
Install larger tanks, restaurant owners urged, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Install larger tanks, restaurant owners urged, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Mon. - Restaurant owners who complain of
insufficient water supply in their areas should check whether they
have tanks big enough to store water for their consumption.
	   Selangor Waterworks Department deputy director V. Subramaniam
said many restaurants might have tanks which are too small to store
sufficient water for their daily use.
	   He said this was often true in the case of restaurant owners who
had renovated their premises to cater to more customers, resulting
in an increased use for water.
	   ``When an average restaurant with a tank big enough to store
sufficient water for its use is renovated to cater to more
customers, owners should also installbigger tanks.''
	   Meanwhile, the water level at the Sungai Semenyih, Sungai
Langat, Klang Gates and Tasik Subang dams remained relatively
stable today compared to yesterday.
	   As of noon today, the water level at Sungai Semenyih was
recorded at 99.74m, 205.61m at Sungai Langat, 89.53m at Klang Gates
and 36.45m at Tasik Subang.
	   However, there was a notable increase in the level of rainfall
at the catchment areas of the Sungai Semenyih and Sungai Langat
dams compared to yesterday.
	   At both dams, the level of rainfall was 14.3mm and 0.5mm
respectively compared to none at all yesterday.
	   Overall, the water output today was 82.3 per cent compared to
60.2 per cent yesterday at the Sungai Langat, Cheras and Ampang
Intake treatment plants.
	   
</TEXT>
