	   The High Court yesterday dismissed the writ petition that was
filed challenging the legality of the four bills on Chittagong Hill
Tracts.
	   BNP leader Barrister Rafiq filed the writ on behalf of one Aung
Yung Murong on June 1. He did not appear before the court on a
previous date fixed for hearing on June 2.
	   The case was dismissed as no lawyer appeared before the court
for the petition, which came up for hearing as motion in the
division bench yesterday.
	   Dismissing the case, the High Court bench, comprising Justice AM
Mahmudur Rahman and Justice Md Mozammel Hossain, gave ``dismissed
for default'' order.
	   It was reported that BNP Chairperson Begum Khaleda Zia directly
interfered to stop Barrister Rafiq from moving the writ.
	   However, during a recent press conference BNP leader Prof AQM
Badruddozza Chowdhury on a query told newsmen that the writ
petition filed by Barrister Rafiq was not a party decision.
	   
