<HEADER>
w2982 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  MORE-FUNDING-FOR-FILMSsk     06-09 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> MORE-FUNDING-FOR-FILMS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
More funding for films if Beijing eases rules, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
More funding for films if Beijing eases rules, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE mainland holds the key to reviving Hong Kong's film industry
which has been reeling from poor box-office receipts since the
early 90s.
	   Investors would put in up to 30 times the current $4 to $5
million backing for each Hong Kong film if Beijing eased
restrictions, said Crucindo Hung, the head of a 48-member industry
delegation visiting the mainland.
	   The delegation arrived in Beijing yesterday to discuss further
opening up the mainland market to Hong Kong films.
	   The delegation will meet Vice-Premier Li Lanqing and officials
of the Ministry of Radio, Film and Television, the Central
Propaganda Department and National Copyright Administration during
its four-day mission.
	   Mr Hung said that following the contraction of the Southeast
Asian market, the need to expand into the mainland had become more
important.
	   ``Without the mainland market, investors who are now willing to
put up $4-$5 million in a film will invest 20 to 30 times more if
the films can be shown in the mainland,'' he said.
	   Among the mission members are personalities such as singer-actor
Andy Lau Tak-wah, comic Eric Tsang Chi-wai and producer Michael Hui
Koon-man as well as legislator-elect Ma Fung-kwok.
	   They will seek to enhance co-operation with the mainland in film
production.
	   Mr Hung said the current restrictions on co-operative production
should be scrapped. The restrictions include pre-censoring the
script and requiring post-production work to be completed in the
mainland.
	   The delegation will also try to persuade Beijing to allow Hong
Kong films to have its own quota _ the mainland allows 10 foreign
films to be co-distributed each year with the overseas distributor
sharing the box-office gross.
	   Preventing the rampant copyright privacy will also be discussed.
	   
</TEXT>
