<HEADLINE>
Dr M to attend smart partnership dialogue, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Dr M to attend smart partnership dialogue, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Mon. - Fifteen heads of government, including
Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir Mohamad, are expected to
attend the Second Southern Africa Dialogue on Smart Partnership
which is to be held in Swakopmund, Namibia, from July 26 to 29.
	   Namibian High Commissioner to Malaysia Ndeutapo Amagulu said the
conference, themed ``The Generation of Wealth in Southern Africa'',
would provide an opportunity for participants to engage each other
with fresh ideas, propositions and plans that could translate into
successful business ventures.
	   He told a Press conference that apart from the 15 leaders,
Namibia also hoped to attract about 350 participants comprising
civil servants, business executives and labour leaders throughout
Africa.
	   Amagulu said the smart partnership concept was bound to gain
popularity as it harnessed the resources of the public and private
sectors for economic development and encouraged long-term
``win-win'' business alliances.
	   He said heads of government and businessmen should work in
unison to ensure the overall success of smart partnerships.
	   He said it was high time the leaders implemented smart
partnership and took the lead in their respective countries.
	   The smart partnership philosophy, he said, which was introduced
to southern Africa in May last year through the First Southern
Africa Dialogue, had proven to be a success as it had led to
incredible economic transformations in his country.
	   ``The concept has helped push our economies into high gear. In
fact, it had showed us the way forward not just in the field of
economics but also in the social and political sectors.''
	   
</TEXT>
