<SLUG> BC-France-Air France-Strike, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Air France pilots' strike on collision course with World Cup
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with French Transport Minister urging talks. Trims.
 &UR; AP Photos Planned
 &UR; By DEBORAH SEWARD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ On the eve of the World Cup, France's Transport
Minister on Tuesday urged pilots and Air France to return to the
negotiating table as the air strike entered its ninth day.
	   ``Each moment, each hour, each minute must be used for talks for
discussion and for negotiation,'' Jean-Claude Gayssot told the
French parliament during a question-and-answer session.
	   On strike since last Monday, the pilots are increasingly seen as
the spoilers of French efforts to stage the World Cup, the world's
biggest international sporting event.
	   ``Finding a solution to the conflict is essential,'' Gayssot
said.
	   Talks broke down Saturday and no new negotiations have been set.
	   Criticism of striking French pilots continued Tuesday.
	   Alain Deleu, president of the French Confederation of Christian
Workers, said Tuesday on Radio Monte Carlo that ``nobody can
understand'' how the pilots could ``be allowed to disrupt the
welcome of foreigners for a world event.''
	   Air France is the official carrier of the World Cup, and the
airline has arranged special flights to transport the teams to
their destinations throughout the tournament.
	   Air France President Jean-Cyril Spinetta called an extraordinary
board meeting for Saturday.
	   The strike did not appear to be wrecking the party atmosphere in
the French capital.
	   Preparations for parades in Paris later Tuesday were in full
gear. The Champs-Elysees was decorated with the flags of competing
nations, and hotels strung up banners.
	   In the skies, only one in four Air France planes was expected to
fly Tuesday.
	   Meanwhile, British Airways is cashing in on Air France's woes.
The company said Tuesday it was putting in service bigger planes to
fly an extra 2,400 people between London and Paris this week.
	   British Airways estimated it is bringing in an additional 1
million pounds (dlrs 1.6 million) in revenues daily as a result of
the Air France strike.
	   The French pilots are protesting 500 million francs (dlrs 83
million) in salary cuts Air France says are needed to modernize the
airline that was saved from bankruptcy in 1993. It reported profits
in 1996 and 1997.
	   Air France has offered to compensate the pilots by giving them
stock in exchange for the pay cuts.
	   Meanwhile, bus and subway service was reduced in Lyon, a World
Cup venue, on Tuesday following a drivers' strike there. A strike
by train conductors has been announced for Wednesday.
	   Another World Cup venue, Bordeaux, may also be hit with a
walkout by bus drivers on Thursday.
	   (parf-dgs-ip)
</TEXT>
