<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Queens </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Defending champion Philippoussis upset in first round
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Defending champion Mark Philippoussis slumped to a
first-round defeat at Queen's Club on Tuesday and then announced he
may not play at Wimbledon.
	   The ninth-seeded Australian, a power hitter with one of the
fastest serves in the game, was upset by Spanish grass-court novice
Jordi Burillo 7-6 (11-9), 7-5.
	   ``This year's been pathetic for me and I just haven't been there
at all,'' Philippoussis said. ``I'm just very confused at the
moment. I've tried to think about what's wrong, but I don't know
what it is. It's like I'm not hungry any more and it's not a good
feeling at all.''
	   In other matches, American qualifier Doug Flach, ranked 222,
surprised the Czech Republic's Daniel Vacek 4-6, 6-1, 6-3, and
12th-seeded Australian Todd Woodbridge advanced with a 6-2, 6-3 win
over Andre Sa of Brazil.
	   The 22nd-ranked Philippoussis double-faulted on set point to
hand Burillo the tiebreaker. In the second set, neither player
earned a break point until Burillo broke serve for the match when
Philippoussis sent a wild forehand long.
	   ``I believe I can play well on this surface,'' said the
92nd-ranked Burillo. ``It feels comfortable and is one of my
favorite surfaces. Mark wasn't playing badly, but I got my serves
in and was returning well, and that was the key.''
	   ``It is always an inspiration to play someone supposedly much
better than you,'' he said. ``That was an extra motivation for me,
although when I saw the draw I didn't think I could win the
match.''
	   A tournament victory in Memphis in February has proved to be the
only bright spot in a dismal year for the 21-year-old
Philippoussis. He has failed to advance beyond the opening round in
five of his 12 tournaments.
	   ``I'm actually deciding whether to play Wimbledon,'' he said.
``At the moment I'm not sure. I'm not sure what's going to happen.
I'll go to Florida and talk with my father about it.
	   ``On the court nothing's there for me. I haven't got the desire,
and I can't afford to go out there and give away matches like that.
It's better not going on the court at all.''
	   (str/sw)
</TEXT>
