<HEADLINE>
JS goes into budget session Wednesday, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
JS goes into budget session Wednesday, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Parliament goes into budget session at 10 am tomorrow amidst
stormy political and nagging economic situation of the country.
	   Finance Minister SAMS Kibria will place the national budget for
fiscal 1998-99 at 3 pm Thursday. His budget speech will be
broadcast live by Bangladesh Betar and Bangladesh Television from
Parliament.
	   Main opposition BNP, which abstained from the House during the
last few days of the last session, will take part in budget
deliberations.
	   However, the BNP and Jamaat lawmakers, who are busy with the
long march to CHT, will not be able to attend the opening session.
	   The shadow Finance Minister of BNP M Saifur Rahman, now in
London, is expected to return home on June 22.
	   Kibria, who already indicated he will not propose fresh taxes
but seek expansion of the tax net, is under pressure from different
lobbies to give them fiscal benefits, including tariff protection
to the domestic industry.
	   The national exchequer is already in the red reportedly with
heavy government borrowings from the bank in view of shortfall in
revenue income to the tune of about Tk 1500 crore.
	   The World Bank, which will finance half of the Tk 136 billion
ADP (Annual Development Plan) for 1998-99, has been insisting on
raising prices of gas, electricity, fertiliser, etc and further
liberalising the market.
	   Kibria is unlikely to take the risk of proposing price rise of
such essentials in his budget to deny the opposition any political
leverage. But he is likely to allow respective organisations to
give effect to a higher price after the budget.
	   Besides adoption of the national budget, the lengthy session
will also take up some legislative businesses, including the
Upazila Bill.
	   The session is likely to be stormy with the opposition taking on
the government for its alleged failure to resolve the electricity,
gas and water crises, and check the rising crimes.
	   
</TEXT>
