<HEADLINE>
Sunday meeting on Sungai Pencala Link, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Sunday meeting on Sungai Pencala Link, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Mon. - The Sungai Pencala Residents' Association
will hold a meeting to discuss the issue of the Sungai Pencala Link
at 2.30pm on Sunday at Dewan Masyarakat Sungai Pencala.
	   Association chairman Datuk Noor Azam said Works Minister Datuk
Seri S.
	   Samy Vellu and relevant heads of department had been invited to
brief residents of Sungai Pencala on the project.
	   He said the meeting would be important as the Government had yet
to inform residents and affected landowners about the project,
which is part of the Sprint Highway and built on Malay reserve
land.
	   Noor Azam said this had given rise to many questions as well as
suspicions about the project.
	   On June 1, it was reported that the Cabinet had approved the
construction of the Sungai Pencala Link on the Malay reserve land.
	   Samy Vellu had said although Sungai Pencala residents had
protested against the highway, the Government felt the area had to
be developed and should not remain as Malay reserve land forever.
	   However, Noor Azam said, ``a six-lane highway in the middle of a
kampung is not development. This is destruction''.
	   ``The Pencala Link is not a project for the people. It is a
commercial project and 200ha of land will disappear and hundreds
more will be destroyed.''
	   The meeting would enable the Works Minister to explain the
development that would take place in Sungai Pencala, he said.
	   
</TEXT>
