<BODY>
<SLUG> PDB-SEEKS-POLICE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PDB seeks police protection during World Cup, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
PDB seeks police protection during World Cup, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Apprehending attacks by soccer fans on power stations in case of
power failure during the World Cup, PDB has sought police
protection.
	   A decision to deploy police at every power station, supply unit
and residence of the PDB officials has already been taken, official
sources said.
	   Police protection has been sought for each and every electricity
supply centre and unit in all districts and thana headquarters of
the country, in addition to 55 power generating centres across the
country.
	   According to the sources, soccer fans are threatening the PDB
officials across the country of attacks if they fail to ensure
uninterrupted power supply during the World Cup matches to be
telecast by TV.
	   In the wake of frequent threats, they urged the police
administration to ensure their security.
	   Meanwhile, BTV has decided to telecast live 56 matches of the
France World Cup Football to be kicked off on Wednesday, leaving
the country's fans in great anxiety as erratic power supply has
been a common phenomenon.
	   A recent survey showed that 80.70 per cent soccer fans may react
sharply against the government if it fails to tackle the
load-shedding during the World Cup matches.
	   According to police, there is every possibility that the
political opponents will use the sentiment of the soccer fans
against the government.
	   If such a situation arises there is also possibility to deploy
BDR and army forces at the power generating centres to avert
possible attacks, the sources said.
	   PDB sources said the present shortfall of power generation in
the country stands at 500 megawatt everyday.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
