<SLUG> PLUMMETS-AGAINST-US sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hibor surges as yen plummets against US dollar, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Hibor surges as yen plummets against US dollar, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   S M YauASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HONG KONG Interbank Offered Rates (Hibor) shot up dramatically
at yesterday's fixing against last Friday's as the troubled yen
went beyond 140 against the United States dollar.
	   The benchmark three-month Hibor rate soared to 9.17434 per cent
yesterday morning from 8.36458 per cent last Friday, before closing
yesterday at 8.75 per cent.
	   One-month Hibor was at 8.96711 per cent against 7.65972 per cent
at Friday's fixing, with the closing rate at 8.5 per cent
yesterday.
	   Carlos Cheung, head of the spot market division at the Bank of
East Asia, said Asian currencies had been battered again as the yen
crumpled against the US dollar. The yen dived to as low as 140
against the US dollar in yesterday's trading, from 139.44 last
Friday.
	   The yen's plunge hit regional currencies, including the Thai
baht and Malaysian ringgit, and eventually exerted pressure on Hong
Kong's interbank rates.
	   Financial Secretary Sir Donald Tsang Yam-kuen, however, denied
there was any speculative attack on the Hong Kong dollar yesterday
even as he stressed the strength of the US dollar peg.
	   ``There is no sign of weakness. There is no sign of any attack
at all. I do not need to do any additional measure to defend the
link. It is very strong,'' he said.
	   Mr Cheung expects the latest round of volatility in the
interbank rates to last at least until end-1998.
	   ``The (interbank) rates won't drop in a large magnitude even if
the yen declines further,'' he said.
	   But he did not rule out the possibility that the yen would
continue to slide if the Group of Seven (G7) industrialised
countries failed to come up with any rescue plan to bolster the yen
in the near future.
	   The market is awaiting a G7 meeting next week.
	   Yesterday's six-month Hibor was at 9.73684 per cent versus
8.94444 per cent on Friday. The overnight rate was at 5.50-6.00 per
cent against 5.00-5.50 per cent on Friday.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
