r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UN-HumanRights-Kosovo     06-09 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Human Rights-Kosovo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. human rights chief ``deeply disturbed'' by Kosovo violence
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By PHILIP WALLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ U.N. human rights chief Mary Robinson Tuesday
urged warring Serbs and ethnic Albanian separatists to ``curb the
spiral of violence'' in the troubled Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
	   As the United States and other Western powers consider using
military means to try to stop the fighting, Robinson said in a
statement issued from U.N. European headquarters in Geneva the
violence was ``deeply disturbing.''
	   She said her staff in the region were reporting a ``grave and
worsening human rights and humanitarian situation.''
	   ``I urgently call on the authorities of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia and the Republic of Serbia, as well as leaders of the
Kosovo Albanian community, to curb the spiral of violence,''
Robinson said.
	   There were no immediate reports of new clashes Tuesday between
the Serbs and Albanian militants fighting for Kosovo's independence
from Serbia.
	   More than 250 people have died this year in fighting between
government forces and pro-independence Albanian guerrillas, known
as the Kosovo Liberation Army.
	   Robinson said reports of human rights violations, including
arbitrary arrests and abductions, were increasing daily.
	   The Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights had
received reports of arbitrary killings, shelling of villages by
police and attacks on the military and police by armed Albanian
groups.
	   ``I am concerned this violence is taking place in a region where
approximately 47 per cent of the population is under the age of
18,'' Robinson said.
	   She expressed concern the Serb authorities had not answered her
office's inquiries about the fate or whereabouts of people
allegedly held by Serb police, or about police officers themselves
reported as abducted.
	   ``Free and unimpeded access to information is essential'' to
address the causes and consequences of the human rights crisis,
Robinson said.
	   On Monday, the United States said it hadn't ruled out military
options to stop the violence.
	   Earlier Tuesday, U.N. children's agency spokesman Patrick
McCormick said UNICEF didn't advocate a military intervention. But
it favored peacekeeping operations or ``anything that will keep two
sides apart and save the lives of civilians, especially children
and women,'' he said.
	   The U.N. refugee agency supports ``vigorous action'' to stop the
fighting, said UNHCR spokeswoman Judith Kumin.
	   ``Our hope would be that any intervention would serve to
stabilize the situation so that civilians don't move,'' Kumin said.
	   UNHCR staff are traveling to eastern Albania Tuesday to check
unconfirmed reports of arrivals of refugees.
	   ``If true it would signal a shift in the refugee flow and
possibly a consequent shift in the fighting in Kosovo,'' Kumin
said.
	   UNHCR says information from various sources suggests more than
60,000 people are displaced in Kosovo, Montenegro and Albania.
	   NATO will transport humanitarian aid from UNHCR's depots in
Bosnia towards Tirana and then by shuttle operation to the north
using helicopters or small planes on Wednesday, Kumin added.
 &UR; (pw)
</TEXT>
