<SLUG> WARNING-OVER-DISCLOSURE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Warning over disclosure rule, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Warning over disclosure rule, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE stock exchange yesterday warned that it would not rule out
taking disciplinary action against companies that failed to
disclose information relating to their connected transactions.
	   Lawrence Fok, executive director of the stock exchange's listing
division, said the exchange has observed of late an upsurge of
cases of directors of listed firms failing to notify the exchange
of connected transactions.
	   For instance, Tingyi (Cayman Islands) Holdings and C P Pokphand
have not notified the exchange of loans obtained by their
respective directors.
	   Mr Fok warned that this practise comprised a breach of the
listing rules and culprits could be subjected by the exchange to
disciplinary actions.
	   ``Ignorance of the (listing) regulations is no excuse for
company directors,'' he said.
	   Mr Fok also urged company directors to read carefully paragraph
14 of the listing regulations which relate to connected
transactions.
	   He said the exchange was considering holding a series of
workshops to remind directors to comply with listing regulations.
	   The exchange is also considering whether to revise listing rules
enabling it to order companies whose shares have been suspended to
have trading of their shares resumed.
	   ``For those companies which are in a position to resume trading
but did not do so, the exchange at the moment is powerless to order
them to resume trading,'' he said.
	   ``We will see if this is feasible in the context of the law,''
Mr Fok said.
	   There are at least two companies in this situation at the
moment.
	   As for those companies which were still unable to resume trading
after a long suspension, Mr Fok said that trading of their shares
would only resume when they could produce a detailed update of
their financial position.
	   ``We want the market to understand that the stock exchange
certainly wants the companies to resume trading,'' he said.
	   Mr Fok also said that the decision of Cable &AMP; Wireless of
Britain to remove its secondary listing on the Hong Kong stock
exchange did not mean that the local exchange was losing its
attractiveness.
	   ``In the listing of some H shares, the volume of their
transactions in Hong Kong was much more than the volume of
transactions overseas,'' Mr Fok said.
	   ``Cable &AMP; Wireless has had a secondary listing in Hong Kong for
over ten years,'' Mr Fok said.
	   Its listing has been cancelled because there was very little
trading in the company's shares for a long time.
	   ``Only a handful of shareholders had used the trading services
in Hong Kong and the turnover level had remained low,'' according
to the company.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
