<HEADLINE>
Seminar on N blast ends in pandemonium, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Seminar on N blast ends in pandemonium, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A seminar organised in the city yesterday to protest the recent
nuclear explosions in South Asia was foiled when two groups of
participants clashed with each other resulting in injuries to some
of them.
	   The trouble erupted at about 5.10 PM at the seminar room of the
National Book Centre, when Mostafa Farouq, a leader of Bangladesher
Samajtantrik Dal (BSD), sought clarification from the leaders of
Shamyobadi Dal, as to why the name of the BSD Chief was mentioned
as a discussant without his prior knowledge.
	   BSD activists went berserk as Dilip Barua, General Secretary of
Shamyobadi Dal, the organiser of the seminar, tried to take control
of the microphone from Mostafa Farouq.
	   Witnesses said the clash lasted 20 minutes during which a
handmade bomb was also exploded. BSD leader Bazlur Rashid Firoj was
among the wounded.
	   Both BSD and Shamyobadi Dal are components of the Left
Democratic Front (LDF), an alliance of eight left-leaning parties.
	   Officials of the National Book Centre (NBC) said 30 chairs, the
microphone and flower-plant vases were also damaged during the
clash.
	   Shamyobadi Dal leader Shafiqur Rahman Majumder who was presiding
over function escaped unhurt along with journalist Ataus Samad
	   Dilip Barua who was manhandled by the BSD activists left the
scene immediately. However, he could not be contacted till the
filing of this report last night.
	   When contacted, Shafiqur Rahman Majumder regretted the behaviour
of the BSD activists. LDF leader Nirmal Sen said they did not do
the right thing.
	   The seminar was organised to protest the recent nuclear
explosions by India and Pakistan.
	   When contacted, Mostafa Faruoq defended their actions. ``We went
to lodge protest and there would have been no clash if I was
allowed to finish my speech.''
	   
</TEXT>
