<BODY>
<SLUG> CHANGES-TO-TOBACCO-LAWS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Changes to tobacco laws to curb teenage smoking, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Changes to tobacco laws to curb teenage smoking, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   DO you know that the Government amended the Control of Tobacco
Products Regulations 1993 (CTPR 1993) in April last year to check
the growing phenomenon of teenage smoking and to protect the public
from the dangers of passive smoking?
	   Acting on the Health Ministry's suggestions, the CTPR 1993's
stipulation of non-smoking areas and provisions for controlling the
advertisement of tobacco products, the distribution of free
cigarette samples, cigarette company sponsorship, the labelling of
cigarette packages and the sales of cigarettes to those under 18
were revised.
	   The eight general areas stipulated as strictly non-smoking zones
in the CTPR 1993 were entertainment centres (including cinemas and
theatres), hospitals and clinics, public lifts, public transport,
air-conditioned restaurants (in which no more than half of the
restaurant can be designated a smoking section), petrol stations,
the Esso Tower and the Island and Peninsular office buildings (both
of which are in Kuala Lumpur).
	   To ensure greater protection of non-smokers against passive
smoking, however, the designated areas were, in 1997, broadened to
include air- conditioned shops, airports (aside from the designated
smoking areas), government premises, public halls, institutions of
higher learning, kindergartens, day-care centres, public bus and
taxi stops, schools, banks, Telekom Malaysia Berhad, Tenaga
Nasional Berhad and Pos Malaysia Berhad counters; shopping
complexes, sports complexes and stadiums.
	   Aside from this, a subsection requiring owners of public
buildings and vehicles to place non-smoking signs on their premises
or vehicles was added to the CTPR 1993.
	   For buildings, the signs are to be 50cm by 40cm with the
non-smoking symbol measuring 30cm in diameter. In buses, taxis, the
LRT and trains, the signs are to be 18cm by 15cm with the
non-smoking symbol measuring 10cm in diameter.
	   Under the amended regulation, owners of public buildings and
vehicles are required to place non-smoking signs according to the
stipulated formats and numbers (in proportion to area size) in
readily visible areas by the June 30.
	   Should any owner of a public building or vehicle fail to do so
he/she can be issued a RM500 fine. Those who distribute packets of
cigarettes on which the tar and nicotine levels of the cigarettes
are not disclosed, on the other hand, can also be fined RM500.
	   A RM200 fine awaits those who sell tobacco products to persons
under 18 while a RM100 fine can be earned by smoking in a
non-smoking area. Persons below 18 caught smoking or chewing on
tobacco products face a RM50 fine.
	   The 1997 amendment of the CPTR 1993 also makes provisions for
exhaust grilles and fans to be placed in all smoking zones while
return air grilles are to be placed at non-smoking zones.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:CHANGES-TO-TOBACCO-LAWS sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
