</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> SYNDICATED-LOAN-MARKET sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Swire tipped to tap syndicated loan market, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Swire tipped to tap syndicated loan market, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Teresa LeeASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SWIRE Pacific is being tipped as the latest major corporate
likely to tap Hong Kong's syndicated loan market.
	   This emerged as United States ratings agency Moody's Investors
Service announced it had placed the debt ratings of Swire Pacific
and its subsidiaries under review for a possible downgrade.
	   Moody's said the review reflected concerns over Swire's changing
business profile from diversified conglomerate to a company mainly
reliant on property development.
	   About $7.8 billion of the group's securities stand to be
affected by the possible downgrade.
	   Banking sources said Swire Pacific executives had made inquiries
regarding a syndicated loan.
	   They said the group was seeking pricing lower than that obtained
by Cheung Kong for its recent $3.96 billion loan.
	   The loan, obtained in March, was priced at 53.5 basis points
over Hibor (Hong Kong interbank offered rate) for an average life
of four years.
	   In the past, Swire has obtained favourable loan terms. Its $3
billion Floating Rate Notes issue launched last April was priced at
32 basis points for three years and 39 basis points for five years.
	   Nikko Research Center chief analyst Steven Thompson said he
doubted that Moody's would downgrade Swire Pacific.
	   He said another ratings agency, Standard &AMP; Poor's, re-affirmed
its ratings for Swire some time ago.
	   Mr Thompson said there was no doubting Swire's financial
strength as the group's gearing ratio stood at 10 per cent at the
end of last year, but rentals for new tenancy agreements in its
properties were coming under pressure with the vacancy rate
currently standing at just 2 per cent.
	   An analyst with a Japanese brokerage house said that as at end
of fiscal 1997, some 54 per cent of Swire Pacific's debts had
fixed-rate interest.
	   He forecast the group's net debt-to-equity ratio at the end of
fiscal 1998 to be 17 per cent, with net debt amounting to $16
billion.
	   Swire Pacific had remained committed to its investment program,
with its projects expected to have an impact on profit growth over
the longer term. The analyst estimated Swire would earn about $1.5
billion in extra rental income by fiscal 2000 from new property
projects.
	   The group was also expected to benefit from completions of joint
venture projects from fiscal 2000, such as the third phase of the
Tung Chung Airport Railway project, and the redevelopment of the
Shiu Wing steel mill site in Tseung Kwan O.
	   Moody's said Swire Pacific's greater dependence on property
income, resulting from the weak performance of its aviation and
industrial businesses and reduction of ownership in Cathay Pacific,
might increase the volatility of its financial position.
	   It said the downturn in the local property market was a rating
concern.
	   
</TEXT>
