<HEADLINE>
BUETTA postpones strike, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
BUETTA postpones strike, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Bangladesh University of Engineering and Technology Teachers
Association (BUETTA) yesterday postponed its strike programmes.
	   The BUETTA enforced the strike fro May 5 to realise its demands
including the reinstatement of the Vice-Chancellor, Prof Iqbal
Mahmud, who resigned on May 4 protesting the government's alleged
interference with the affairs of the university. The VC's
resignation was followed by resignation of 70 other teachers from
key administrative posts.
	   The decision to postpone the strike was taken at a general
meeting of the BUETTA, held with its President, Prof Abdur Razzaq
Akhand, in the chair. About 200 teachers joined the meeting.
	   The strike has been postponed on three conditions which are: the
VC will have to be reinstated; no government interference with the
affairs of the BUET and no discrimination against the university,
said Prof Akhand while talking to The Independent yesterday.
	   When contacted Prof Iqbal Mahmud, who has been continuing his
routine work as the VC, told The Independent that the deans'
committee was scheduled to sit today to finalise the date for the
resumption of classes.
	   Prof Mahmud, who met the BUETTA on Sunday, urged the teachers to
call off the strike and resume classes.
	   According to a press release of the BUETTA, the general meeting
expressed resentment over the Chancellor's reported inaction' to
resolve the month-long BUET crisis despite the repeated requests
from the BUETTA. The association said Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina's ``indifference to BUET and reluctance to play her due role
as Chancellor has angered the teachers'', and urged the PM to
``stop interfering'' in the affairs of BUET.
	   
</TEXT>
