<SLUG> THE-HORNS-OF-A-DILEMMA sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
On the horns of a dilemma, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
On the horns of a dilemma, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Faezah IsmailASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MALAYSIA'S rhinoceros conservation programme has hit a major
snag. It is one more casualty of the regional economic crisis.
	   Unless funds are forthcoming, a major component of the
initiative to conserve the peninsula's critically endangered
Sumatran rhinoceros may not be effective, pushing the species
closer to extinction.
	   Malaysia's economic difficulties have severely cut the
Department of Wildlife and National Parks budget for rhinoceros
protection units this year.
	   That translates to fewer patrols of rhinoceros habitat
throughout the peninsula. Leaving the forest largely unattended
will result in more poaching and rhinoceros mortalities.
	   Department sources say there is some money for rhinoceros
conservation but the economic downturn has forced the department to
prioritise its activities.
	   ``In the case of rhinoceros, the department will work out a plan
using limited resources to cover Taman Negara, Ulu Selama and
Belum, the major rhinoceros areas in the peninsula. It doesn't mean
we will neglect the localities which harbour fragmented
populations, however. Once we get more funding we will step up
patrolling there,'' add the sources.
	   Wildlife conservationists describe the situation as ``just
absolutely tragic'' because Malaysia is not able to accord enough
priority to rhinoceros survival in the peninsula.
	   The shocking revelation that the Endau-Rompin rhinoceros
population is down to fewer than five animals from 20 to 25 five
years ago has sent shivers down the spine of wildlife
conservationists.
	   That seriously hampers Malaysia's plan to conserve the Sumatran
rhinoceros, one of the five living species of rhinoceros found in
the world.
	   ``It isn't looking good for the Sumatran rhinoceros,'' says
Asian Rhino Specialist Group chairman Mohamed Khan Momin Khan. ``If
we are not careful, we will lose the Sumatran rhinoceros by the
turn of the century. Remember, we lost the Javan rhinoceros in
1932,'' adds Mohamed Khan, who is also the former director-general
of the Department of Wildlife and National Parks.
	   ``With the loss of the Endau-Rompin population, the probability
of extinction of the rhinoceros in the peninsula has been increased
by at least 100 per cent,'' says International Rhino Foundation
(IRF) programme director Dr Thomas Foose, who was in Kuala Lumpur
two weeks ago for a short visit.
	   Except for Taman Negara which has 33 to 40 animals, Ulu Selama
and Belum have suffered major losses in recent years.
	   Recent patrolling showed that logging is increasing in Gunung
Bintang Hijau in Ulu Selama, a rhinoceros stronghold. Department of
Wildlife and National Parks rhinoceros conservation officer Dr
Zainal Zahari Zainuddin says the population there has been halved
to six animals.
	   Significant reduction in numbers is also seen in Belum which now
has 10 animals. The situation is aggravated because of the forest's
proximity to the Thai border, making it easy for poachers to come
and go.
	   Current estimates put the rhinoceros population in Peninsular
Malaysia at between 50 and 60 although Mohamed Khan believes
stragglers (one to three animals) are moving around several states.
	   Endau-Rompin had one of the two largest populations, the other
being in Taman Negara.
	   Rhinoceros protection units were created in 1987 by the
Department of Wildlife and National Parks to patrol rhinoceros
areas in the peninsula.
	   Each unit is made up of between four and five rangers including
a team leader. Its job is to give a precise report of any
encroachment into the forested areas, the population count of not
only rhinoceros but other animals as well, and their movement
patterns.
	   These units have proven to be very effective in maintaining
rhinoceros populations but occasional losses have occurred during
times when patrols were temporarily stopped due to the lack of
funds.
	   ``It is hard work for the wildlife rangers,'' says Mohamed Khan.
	   ``Sometimes, they have to spend 20 nights at a stretch in the
forest. For that reason, it is impossible to expect these men to do
the job without adequate rewards,'' he adds.
	   The rangers whom Mohamed Khan describes as ``extremely
dedicated'' must be paid their allowances which they have been
receiving but not adequately.
	   It costs RM400,000 a year to sustain the 10 rhinoceros
protection units which are spread over Taman Negara, Endau Rompin,
Ulu Selama and Belum.
	   The United States-based IRF is providing some support towards
rhinoceros conservation both in Malaysia and Indonesia (US$155,000
a year for four years) but most of the funds have been spent in
Indonesia to build a managed breeding centre in Way Kambas and
tourism facilities.
	   Malaysia has started receiving funds from the IRF (RM120,000 a
year for the next three years) to be spent on the rhinoceros
protection unit programme and the Rhinoceros Captive Breeding
Facility in Sungai Dusun, Selangor.
	   Besides that, the US$1 million grant from the Global
Environmental Facility (GEF) for rhinoceros conservation will
expire at the end of 1998.
	   Sadly, the funding scheme does not allow for Phase Two projects.
	   Says Foose: ``We currently have two grants for rhinoceros
protection units in Indonesia from the US Rhino and Tiger
Conservation Fund and we will probably be applying to that fund for
Malaysia in the future.''
	   A government department such as the Department of Wildlife and
National Parks should not have to appeal for funds from
international bodies for its activities but the financial crisis is
leaving it with no choice.
	   The IUCN - The World Conservation Union - has included the
Sumatran rhinoceros on its Red List Categories (IUCN 1994). Its
assessment is that the Sumatran rhinoceros is the most critically
endangered of all rhinoceros species with a population of 250-400
distributed fragmentarily in Sumatra, Peninsular Malaysia and
Sabah.
	   Remnants may survive in Sarawak, Thailand, Myanmar and Laos but
their existence is unconfirmed and the viability of any populations
unlikely.
	   The first written sighting of the Sumatran rhinoceros in Malaya
was by Raffles who described the species being killed in Malacca in
1820.
	   In the last century, Westerners had trapped and acquired more
than 60 known animals of this species and exported them to Europe
and America where they were exhibited in zoos and circuses.
	   The introduction of firearms in the peninsula by the colonial
masters led to big game hunting. The rhinoceros was also gunned
down by locals who believed the animal's body parts, especially the
horns, possess certain medicinal and supernatural value.
	   Rhinoceros hunting became so rampant that the Javan rhinoceros
became extinct in the peninsula in 1932.
	   Man remains the rhinoceros' chief enemy. Today, habitat
degradation and poaching conspire to drive the species to the edge
of extinction.
	   Loss of rhinoceros habitat has been especially serious in the
peninsula.
	   Logging, agricultural development, human settlement and shifting
cultivation are the main reasons for the dwindling numbers and this
has intensified over the last 10-15 years.
	   ``Deforestation, be it partial or complete, narrows the gap
between man and animal,'' says Zainal of the Department of Wildlife
and National Parks.
	   ``It gives easier access to poachers to wrest the rhinoceros
horns and people to set up snares.''
	   The goal of Malaysia's conservation strategy is to maintain or
recover viable populations of the Sumatran rhinoceros in the wild.
	   Essentially, the action plan calls for protecting and managing
the rhinoceros and its habitat. Constant surveillance of rhinoceros
localities is key.
	   Captive rearing and reintroduction is also part of the measure
to save the Sumatran rhinoceros. A managed breeding centre was set
up at the Sungai Dusun Wildlife Reserve in 1991 and earnest work is
now being carried out to breed rhinoceros in captivity. (See story
on Page 7).
	   Educating the public on conservation issues is also crucial and
a pilot project was introduced last year at Kampung Peta - one of
the major entry points to Endau-Rompin - to spread such awareness
among villagers living near rhinoceros habitats.
	   Every effort must be taken to ensure the Sumatran rhinoceros
does not end up like the Javan rhinoceros which many cannot
remember now.
	   Malaysia can eventually recover from the economic crisis but
without money the peninsula's mega species including the rhinoceros
may be lost forever.
	   Note: Those interested in contributing to the Wildlife Trust
Fund (Sumatran rhinoceros) can contact Department of Wildlife and
National Parks director-general Musa Nordin at 03-9052872.
	   Save the rhino, safeguard biodiversity THE uninformed are likely
to argue that pushing for rhinoceros conservation at a time when
Malaysia is facing an economic downturn seems trivial.
	   So what if a few rhinoceros disappear, they may say.
	   But they are missing the whole point of the biodiversity
argument.
	   Forest Research Institute Malaysia biodiversity division
director Dr N.
	   Manokaran says biodiversity is a hugely important concept that
stresses the interdependence of all forms of life on earth.
	   ``There must be a willingness to accept that interdependence
applies to every one of life's component parts and not just
humans,'' says the forest ecologist.
	   The interdependence of various life forms helps to maintain
ecological systems such as the tropical rainforest, acknowledged to
contain the greatest diversity of plants, animals and
microorganisms on earth.
	   Very simply, interactions between the flora and fauna through
the food web and especially through pollination of flowers and
dispersal of seeds help to regenerate the forest.
	   When you save the forest for rhinoceros, you are also saving it
for so many other species which live in it. Indeed, the Sumatran
rhinoceros is recognised as an umbrella species for the
conservation of biodiversity.
	   How would the world view Malaysia if it allowed the rhinoceros
to go extinct despite having ratified the Convention on
Biodiversity?
	   ``Badly,'' says Manokaran, one of the architects of the National
Biodiversity Policy which was endorsed by the Cabinet on Oct 22
last year, and launched by the Science, Technology and Environment
Minister on April 16.
	   ``When Malaysia makes serious attempts to safeguard the
rhinoceros, it is signalling to the world that it sees conservation
as a very important aspect of its diverse culture as outlined in
one of the principles of its biodiversity policy,'' he adds.
	   Conservation of Malaysia's wild populations can only begin when
there is a deep appreciation that man and animal need each other.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:THE-HORNS-OF-A-DILEMMA sked; CT:w; 
