<HEADLINE>
Speculators still wary of residential property, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Speculators still wary of residential property, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SPECULATORS have not yet returned to the mass residential
property market despite the massive turnout last weekend of
prospective buyers to view flats at Paliburg Holdings' Park Royale
development in Yuen Long.
	   Analysts yesterday said the general conditions in the mass
residential market were not yet ripe to lure speculators.
	   There were some indications though of speculation in the Tierra
Verde project in Tsing Yi with some 200 of the 1,700 units that
have already been sold being offered for sale in the secondary
market.
	   Analysts noted though an improvement in sentiment as reflected
by the fact that 30,000 prospective buyers flocked to Paliburg's
project to see what had been described as the cheapest flats in the
market at $2,834 per square foot.
	   Nan Fung Development's Nan Fung Plaza project also drew a strong
response from some 20,000 prospective homebuyers.
	   An analyst with an Asian brokerage house said despite the
government's recent lifting of the ban on the resale of uncompleted
flats before their titles were assigned to buyers, speculators were
not expected to return in the near future because market prospects
still looked grim.
	   While speculators could resell their ballot tickets and earn
some money quickly, the prospects of reselling their flats within a
year look very slim.
	   The analyst said the improved sentiment evidenced in the large
turnout of potential homebuyers last weekend would probably be
short-lived.
	   Prices were likely to remain depressed because major developers
are scheduled to release thousands of flats on the pre-sale market
in the second half of this year.
	   ``There is a risk that cash-strapped developers may now rush to
sell projects quickly which could put further pressure on prices by
boosting supply,'' the analyst said.
	   The managing director of Ricacorp Properties Group, Barry Law,
said the fact that a large number of people viewed flats over the
weekend did not necessarily reflect a return to the market of
speculators.
	   He said the atmosphere was good, but the secondary market was
still ``deadly quiet'' and there was hardly any sign of
speculation.
	   While developers are eager to cash in by releasing their
existing projects, soft prices in the primary market are expected
to continue to undercut price levels in the secondary market.
	   
</TEXT>
