<SLUG> POWER-CRISIS-IN-21-S sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Power crisis in 21 S-dists worsens, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Power crisis in 21 S-dists worsens, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Public life in and around the capital was in torment due to
frequent loadshedding amid an extreme hotspell, as severe power
shortage forced 11 substations to a grinding halt yesterday.
	   Officials said the Dhaka Electric Supply Authority was compelled
to suspend operation of its 11 substations of a 33-KV transmission
line at the instructions from the Load Despatch Centre at
Siddhirganj.
	   They said the DESA area faced a shortage of 250 megawatt power
yesterday as the supply was around 750 megawatts against the demand
for 1,000 MW.
	   ``Many people phoned power offices threatening to set fire to
the stations'', said one official, as life became unbearable due to
on-again, off-again power supply on the hot-and-humid summer day.
	   Because of generation shortfall, Power Development Board could
not also meet the demand across the country, causing public outrage
in other areas as well.
	   The power board, however, was trying to increase generation in
the Kaptai Hydroelectric Project which could not run up to its
capacity.
	   ``The situation may improve only after full resumption of power
supply from Kaptai,'' an official said.
	   The power substations under suspension are: Mirkadim, Tongi,
Tongi-1, Tejgaon, Zinjira, Narayanganj (Khanpur), Kaliganj,
Shyampur grid-2, Narsingdi, Nawabganj and Srinagar.
	   In Tejgaon Zone, one of the three 33-KV power substations
suspended supplying electricity to the area.
	   Tejgaon unit was able to maintain supply for two hours after
each one-hour loadshedding as the zone got 14 MW power against the
demand for 38 MW.
	   Due to power shortages, industrial production is being hampered
while people in offices and various establishments are facing
problems doing their work.
	   Our Staff Correspondent from Khulna adds: Power crisis in the
western grid comprising 21 districts has further worsened with the
closure of the 110 MW unit of Khulna Power Station (KPS) on Friday
due to mechanical problems.
	   The western grid which includes greater Khulna district has been
subjected to 50 to 60 per cent loadshedding on average in recent
weeks due to reduced generation of electricity in the country,
sources in PDB said.
	   According to PDB sources, the total peak hour demand for
electricity in the western grid has been assessed at between 320
and 340 megawatts on average, while the average available load was
160 MW on Friday (June 5), 169 MW on Saturday (June 6) and 163 MW
on Sunday (June 7) at 8 pm.
	   Power crisis has seriously affected industrial production in the
region, besides causing serious disruptions in the supply of water
by the municipalities.
	   Four out of six electricity generating units of Khulna Power
Station remain out of operation. The two units now in operation are
producing about 30 to 31 MW of power. The GT 35 unit which has an
installed capacity of 10.5 MW is yielding 8 MW while the other
running barge mounted power plant (Unit No-2) is generating 22 to
23 MW as against its installed capacity of 28 MW.
	   The four units of KPS which are now out of operation are 110-MW
unit, 60-MW unit, TG-14 unit and barge mounted power plant (Unit
No-1).
	   The 110-MW unit which was shut down on Friday for some emergency
repair and maintenance is expected to be operative in a couple of
days. The overhauling and major repair of the Czech-aided plant are
learnt to be overdue.
	   During the last two months, the 110-MW plant had remained
inoperative for a total of 15 days for occasional repair and
maintenance work. The 110-MW unit was generating 50 MW of power
before its closure on Friday.
	   The 60-MW unit of KPS has remained shut down for about seven
years. At present, the overhauling and major repair works of the
unit are now being undertaken by the Chinese experts and the unit
is officially scheduled to become ready for operation by the middle
of next year 1999.
	   The TG-14 unit which has an installed capacity of 12.75 MW is
remaining idle for over a month. The authorities are trying to
import some equipment from Italy to make it operative again.
	   The barge mounted power plant unit No-1, which suffered damages
following a fire in March this year, is yet to be made ready for
switching on.
	   
</TEXT>
