<HEADLINE>
Penang planning zone for higher education, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Penang planning zone for higher education, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Penang Development Corporation and State Government plan to
develop special education zones, similar to industrial parks, in a
move to turn Penang into a centre of educational excellence.
	   State Education Committee chairman Dr Toh Kin Woon yesterday
said the PDC had been asked to set up an education section to
promote educational services.
	   The plan was to establish special zones for education, develop
housing schemes for private college students with reasonable
rentals and public transport between the houses and colleges.
	   Toh (BN-Machang Bubok) said this in reply to points raised
during the debate on the motion of thanks to the Yang di-Pertua
Negeri Tun Hamdan Sheikh Tahir for his opening address at the State
Legislative Assembly last week.
	   He said the PDC should offer incentives such as joint-promotion
of Penang's 32 private colleges, especially within the
Indonesia-Malaysia- Thailand Growth Triangle.
	   The Penang Public Library would emphasise the needs of private
colleges by providing more reference and textbooks.
	   On the role of the Penang Island and Seberang Prai municipal
councils in private education, Toh said the municipalities should
relax procedures, and speed up the approval of plans to build
private colleges.
	   Meanwhile, the House was told that Penang aims to become the
overall champion in the biennial Malaysia Games (Sukma) in the year
2004.
	   In his winding-up speech on the motion of thanks to the Yang
di-Pertua Negeri State Youth and Sports Committee chairman Koay Kar
Huah (BN-Bukit Glugor) said the the target was based on the
performance of State athletes at Sukma '98 in Selangor.
	   Penang finished sixth with 12 golds, five silvers and 24 bronze
medals, up from 11th at Sukma '96.
	   Koay said the State aimed to finish third in the overall medal
standing at the next games which it will host in two years, with at
least 35 gold medals.
	   To a question by Syed Amiruddin Syed Ahmad (BN-Teluk Kumbar) on
programmes to reactivate interest in sports among youths, Koay
said: ``Assemblymen can arrange activities with the help of
district youth and sports councils and district officers.''
	   He said his committee would come up with a comprehensive policy
to revive ``dead'' youth clubs in the State.
	   
</TEXT>
