<SLUG> CHU-KONG-EYES-PROJECTS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chu Kong eyes new projects, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Chu Kong eyes new projects, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Patricia LeeASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   CHU Kong Shipping Development Co will continue to look for
opportunities to expand the market share of its core businesses on
the mainland despite the economic slowdown.
	   ``We are unable to change the macroeconomic conditions but we
would take the approach to further stabilise the core businesses _
river trade transportation and toll roads in the Pearl River Delta
Economic Zone,'' said managing director Huang Fianji.
	   Mr Huang said the company was always looking for opportunities
to acquire new assets, but added no substantial agreement had been
reached so far.
	   He also said they would not only focus on the Pearl River Delta
for new investment but also look at other mainland cities for
quality projects.
	   Income from toll roads accounted for about 30 per cent of total
net profit at the end of 1997.
	   ``We would not rule out the possibility of acquiring new toll
roads with the co-operation of other parties,'' he said.
	   For the first quarter of 1998, traffic volume of the toll road
Guangfo Expressway, of which the company holds a 25 per cent equity
interest, had a capacity of about 70,000 vehicles per day, an
increase from 69,000 vehicles per day in 1997.
	   The expansion plan for Guangfo Expressway has commenced and is
expected to be completed by the end of 1999. Chu Kong's investment
will be more than $50 million, which includes financing the design,
land acquisition and tender invitations for construction contracts.
	   For the first two months of 1998, the average volume of river
trade cargo direct shipment for the entire industry rose by 5 per
cent. Mr Huang did not disclose the actual amount but said the
company's figure would be comparable to the industry as a whole.
	   
</TEXT>
