<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Austria,0404 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPEATING to fix slug
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; World Cup: Practice canceled in favor of watching Cameroon-Denmark
video &QL; 
 &UR; By GEORGE JAHN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ARSAC, France (AP) _ With two days to go until their opening
game against Cameroon, the Austrians on Tuesday canceled a planned
practice session and replaced it with a favorite video _ the
African squad's drubbing of the Danes.
	   Morning practice went ahead as planned, with the Austrians
concentrating on offense and defense in front of the goal and free
kicks from behind a defensive wall. The atmosphere was relaxed,
with squad members squirting each other with fizzy mineral water
and coach Herbert Prohaska loudly cracking jokes with several
players.
	   But an afternoon session was canned in favor of watching the
Cameroon-Denmark game of Friday, with its surprise 2-1 win for the
Africans. And with Cameroon recently looking better than for a long
time, the Austrians were careful not to overestimate themselves.
	   ``Cameroon is a tough team,'' said Anton Pfeffer, as he wiped
the sweat off after training. ``And because it's our first game,
we'll have a tough time coming back if we lose against them.''
	   With the Austrians struggling in their pre-World Cup friendlies
_ winning only against low-ranked Tunisia and even less threatening
Liechtenstein _ players refused to be drawn on chances against
Italy, the team to beat in Group B, which also contains Chile.
	   ``We'll have to see that we get second place _ that will be
difficult enough,'' commented forward Anton Polster, the veteran
forward who plays for Cologne in Germany's top league. ``Italy is
definitely the favorite.''
	   Forward Andreas Herzog said the plan on Thursday was to play
offensively from the opening whistle _ at least until the first
goal.
	   ``We will try to score in the first few minutes,'' he said.
``Then things will be easier.''
	   Prohaska, the coach, refused to tip his cards on the lineup in
Toulouse on Thursday. But judging from the practice sessions since
the team's arrival on Friday, the following configuration was
likely:
	   Michael Konsel, goal; Wolfgang Feiersinger, sweeper; Peter
Schoettel, Pfeffer, defense; Harald Cerny, Dietmar Kuehbauer, Roman
Maehlich, Heimo Pfeiffenberger, midfield; Andreas Herzog, Arnold
Wetl and Polster, forwards.
	   (gj-sl)
</TEXT>
