<HEADLINE>
Dr Jinnah asked to surrender before court, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Dr Jinnah asked to surrender before court, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Appellate Division of the Supreme Court yesterday ordered Dr
Jinnah, the main accused in a rape case, to surrender before the
magistrate's court to comply with the High Court's directive.
	   The three-member bench of the Appellate Division comprising
Justice Latifur Rahman, Justice Mohammad Abdur Rouf and Justice
Bimalendu Bikash Roy Chowdhury also adjourned hearing of Jinnah's
application for stay of High Court's order to surrender before the
lower court till June 14.
	   Earlier, Dr Jinnah obtained rule and ad-interim anticipatory
bail from a HC Division Bench. But another HC bench, on the final
hearing of the anticipatory bail prayer, discharged the rule and
directed Jinnah to surrender before the lower court.
	   Dr Jinnah filed an application before the Appellate Division
seeking stay of the High Court's order, but the Appellate Division
ordered him to comply with the HC directive.
	   Senior Advocate Habibul Islam Bhuiyan moved the petition on
behalf of Dr Jinnah.
	   Additional Attorney General Abdul Wadud Bhuiyan along with
Assistant Attorney General Abdur Rouf on behalf of the state
opposed the stay application.
	   
