<HEADLINE>
Schoolboy rescued, one arrested, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Schoolboy rescued, one arrested, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A schoolboy was kidnapped yesterday from the city's Dhanmondi
area. The kidnapers demanded a ransom of Tk one lakh from the boy's
family members for his release. Police rescued the boy and arrested
one of the abductors from Hatirpool area in the afternoon.
	   According to sources, Nafiz Ibn Mannan Rusho (14), a class IX
student of Mohammadpur Government High School, was abducted from in
front of the Coffee House in the city at gun point while he was on
his way to his aunt's residence at Hatirpool at about 1 pm.
	   The kidnappers, reportedly two in number, took the boy to
Nilkhet from where he contacted his aunt on telephone asking her to
go to his residence at 70, Pisciculture Road, in Mohammadpur area
immediately.
	   Later, he again phoned his mother Rabeya Begum asking her to go
to Eastern Plaza with Tk one lakh for his release.
	   Receiving the call, Rabeya Begum contacted Dhanmondi police and
filed a case, sources said.
	   The police then laid an ambush at Eastern Plaza at 4 pm. When
Sohel, one of the abductors, asked Rabeya Begum whether she had
brought the money, the police arrested him and took him to Shahbagh
area where his other accomplice, Rana, was waiting with the victim,
Rusho.
	   But sensing the presence of police, Rana fled the scene
immediately and Rusho was rescued.
	   Police said Sohel belonged to a gang of child-lifters active in
the city.
	   
</TEXT>
