<HEADLINE>
Cathay plans Amsterdam cargo flight, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Cathay plans Amsterdam cargo flight, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Cyrus LiASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   CATHAY Pacific Airways is looking at the possibility of
launching an air cargo service to Amsterdam, an airline spokeswoman
said yesterday.
	   But corporate communications manager Diana Fong said the airline
was still studying the feasibility of such a service which could
include the Asian region, Europe and North America.
	   Ms Fong said no further details about the new service could be
disclosed since the proposal was at a preliminary stage.
	   However a source said Cathay Pacific planned to launch a
twice-weekly freight service to Amsterdam in August.
	   It is understood that the new service is being considered
because the airline's Asia operations had suffered due to the
regional financial crisis.
	   OCBC Securities transport analyst Patricia Yeung said overseas
demand would justify the setting up of the new service, judging by
the strong performance of the division in the last financial year.
	   Also, the load factor of the cargo division was around 73 per
cent last year, higher than the passenger load factor of 68 per
cent.
	   Ms Yeung said that although overseas markets could sustain
business growth for cargo services it could not compensate for the
slump in passenger numbers.
	   Last year, the cargo division accounted for only 30 per cent of
total revenue.
	   Ms Yeung said it was going to be hard for the airline to make a
profit this year because she anticipated that passenger load factor
would drop to 60 per cent due to the deterioration of Hong Kong's
tourism sector.
	   Meanwhile, Ms Fong said Cathay would launch a new service to
Istanbul on 8 August.
	   
</TEXT>
