	   People from all walks of life including the women took out a
procession carrying empty pitchers in the district town as a mark
of protest against continuous water crisis. The enraged people also
gheraoed the pourashava office and blocked the main road of the
town demanding regular water supply to the town dwellers. Acute
scarcity of drinking water has been prevailing in the district town
for a long time. The water supplied by the Barisal Pourashava
hardly meet only 10 per cent need of the consumers.
	   According to pourashava sources, there are 12,000 water
consumers in Barisal town. The authority concerned supplies 10 to
14 lakh gallons of water per day in the town against the demand of
over 80 lakh gallons. Most of the time, people procure water from
pond and ditches. In a press conference, chairman of Barisal
Pourashava Ahsan Habib Kamal said, water crisis in the town has
become acute due to irregular power supply and fall in underground
water level.
	   Faulty installation of new water pipeline, deep tubewells,
construction of overhead water tanks under the project and shortage
of manpower are some of the other causes of water crisis, he
alleged. Water Department of Barisal Pourashava said, the town is
divided into 18 water supply Pump areas. Of them, Sitlakhola,
Bottola and Police Line pump houses are totally out of order. Two
other pump houses may go out of order any moment.
	   Ten other pumps including south Amanatganj, Nazir Mohollah,
Sagardi, Zila School, Kaunia, Alamgir Hostel and Moelakhola cannot
supply more than 10 thousand gallons each whereas the capacity of
each is over 25,000 gallons per hour. Poura authority said if PDB
could ensure regular power supply the situation must improve.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
