<HEADLINE>
Citic `not hurt by threat to downgrade parent', HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Citic `not hurt by threat to downgrade parent', HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Karen ChanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   CITIC Pacific Ltd said yesterday the possibility of Moody's
Investors Service downgrading the debt rating of its parent, China
International Trust &AMP; Investment Corp, would not affect its ability
to raise funds from the market.
	   Citic Pacific shares came under tremendous pressure yesterday
amid a sell-off, which followed a 7.7 per cent fall in their value
last Friday.
	   Citic's shares were among the top 20 net losers, shedding 45
cents to close at $15.70 per share.
	   Tai Fook Securities analyst Frankie Szeto said he was puzzled by
the response of the investors.
	   He added that the investors still believed that there was a
close link between Citic Pacific and its parent in Beijing.
	   He noted that when Citic Beijing sold its shares to Citic
Pacific's management, Citic Pacific was believed to have severed
its connection with its parent.
	   As a result, Citic Pacific did not enjoy the same
price-to-earnings ratio rating as the other red chip stocks and
underperformed significantly in comparison to its peers during the
first half of 1997.
	   When Citic Beijing lost its status as being directly
administered by the Chinese State Council, people sold Citic
Pacific shares.
	   ``Now, the market reacted again to the possible downgrade
leaving Citic Pacific at its new low this year,'' Mr Szeto said.
	   ``The selling of Citic Pacific shares is overdone. While it is
true Citic Pacific is highly geared with net debt-to-equity ratio
at 53 per cent, we reckon Citic's operating cash flow is sufficient
to finance its expansion plan in fiscal 1998 and 1999.'' Copyright
1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
