<SLUG> BC-Russia-Religion </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian Orthodox Church cancels meeting by Presbyterian pastors
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ANNA DOLGOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The government of a Russian Far Eastern region has
canceled a conference by Presbyterian missionaries after the
Russian Orthodox Church complained, a Presbyterian church official
said Tuesday.
	   The annual meeting of Presbyterian missionaries and pastors in
the former Soviet Union was to be held later this month in the city
of Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk, on Sakhalin Island, said the Rev. Stephen
Park.
	   But local Russian Orthodox leaders said their church has been in
the region for centuries, and would not permit any other religion
to expand there. The government complied.
	   ``The local government is very, very sensitive about it, because
the Orthodox Church is behind them,'' Park, an American based in
Moscow, told The Associated Press.
	   Russian officials are eager to stay in the good graces of the
Orthodox Church, which has become a powerful political force since
the 1991 collapse of the officially atheist Soviet state.
	   The church has been assertively expanding its power, while
trying to curb the influence of other denominations. A recently
adopted law on religion enshrines the Russian Orthodox Church as
the country's predominant religion and sharply curtails the rights
of many other churches.
	   Sakhalin has a large community of ethnic Koreans, many of whom
practice Presbyterianism. Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk has only a half-dozen
Orthodox parishes, and twice as many Presbyterian ones, the
ITAR-Tass news agency said.
	   Between 25 and 30 pastors from the Nakhodka region, located on
the nearby mainland, plan to hold a conference anyway, but no one
from outside is expected to attend, Park said.
	   The cancellation of the Sakhalin meeting has ``made people very,
very frustrated,'' he said.
	   Presbyterian pastors from former Soviet republics have been
holding annual meetings for the past four years in Moscow, and this
was the first time it tried to gather outside of the Russian
capital.
	   (ad/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
