<SLUG> FISHERMEN-STOP-BARGE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fishermen stop barge from dumping muck, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Fishermen stop barge from dumping muck, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PASIR GUDANG, Mon. - A group of 47 fishermen today blocked off a
barge loaded with mud and sludge on its way to dump the muck at
their fishing grounds in Sungai Johor.
	   The dredging contractor has already dumped more than 8,000
tonnes of the slime, dug from Sime Sembawang Engineering Sdn Bhd's
harbour area at Pasir Gudang, into the fish-rich Sungai Johor.
	   The fishermen boarded the barge and demanded the contractor,
Dredgecon Engineering, stop polluting Sungai Johor.
	   The head of the fishermen's community, Zaili Chik, called on the
Department of Environment to halt the activities of the contractor
immediately.
	   Zaili said the contractor's dumping site at Tanjung Buai along
Sungai Johor, directly opposite Kong Kong Laut, a seafood haven,
was a threat to the area.
	   The muck, dug out of Sime Sembawang Engineering harbour area to
increase its depth, was toxic and should be disposed of somewhere
else.
	   The highly polluted Sungai Batu and a two-metre thick main
effluent pipe from the Pasir Gudang industrial estate empty their
contents into the harbour area.
	   Zaili said: ``We cannot understand how the DOE and Marine
Department could approve something like this.''
	   Zaili said checks indicated the Marine Department had approved
the operation.
	   State Marine Department director Rosnan Sathlal said the
department would issue a statement after a meeting with the parties
tomorrow.
	   State Department of Environment director Tengku Bakery Shah
Tengku Johan said the DOE had approved the operations on certain
conditions.
	   He said: ``The operator is required to constantly monitor the
water quality at the dredging and dumping sites to ensure that its
activities do not cause pollution.
	   ``The choice of dumping sites is the prerogative of the Marine
Department.''
	   Tengku Bakery said the DOE would investigate the allegations
that the muck was being dumped into Sungai Johor, as it was illegal
to dump at a river area.
	   If the contractor had contravened DOE conditions, it will advise
the Marine Department to withdraw the licence.
	   
</TEXT>
