<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0676 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yugoslavia assails renewed Kosovo sanctions
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Kosovo Serbs meeting U.S. diplomat, reaction by
Montenegrin premier, Albanians collecting funds for their cause. &QL; 
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Yugoslavia on Tuesday denounced new
international sanctions over its offensive in Kosovo, where a
western strip of the separatist province has been turned into a war
zone of burned houses and deserted villages.
	   In a statement issued on the official Tanjug news agency,
Yugoslav officials called the imposition of sanctions a ``strange
and unreasonable decision.'' The sanctions apply only to Serbia.
Montenegro, its lone partner in the Yugoslav federation, is exempt
because of its pro-Western leadership.
	   ``This is the first case that EU has made a decision about a
sovereign state that applies to only one of its federal units,''
the Tanjug commentary said.
	   The European Union and the United States imposed the sanctions
within hours Monday, banning new investments in Serbia and freezing
its assets abroad.
	   ``It's cynical to demand from Yugoslavia to withdraw troops from
its own province and leave it to the mercy of Albanian
terrorists,'' Tanjug said.
	   Montenegro's Premier Filip Vujanovic said exempting Montenegro
would be difficult because that would require ``a border'' between
the two republics and that is ``out of the question.''
	   A prominent Kosovo Albanian, Nekibe Kelmendi, welcomed the
sanctions Monday but said they were only a ``small step.''
	   There were no immediate reports of new clashes Tuesday between
Serbs and ethnic Albanian militants fighting for Kosovo's
independence.
	   International outcry has increased against Serbia to stop using
its police and army against ethnic Albanians, who make up 90
percent of the province's population. NATO is considering military
intervention.
	   Carl Bildt, formerly the European Union's high representative in
Bosnia and still an influential figure regarding policy on former
Yugoslavia, harshly criticized Western officials in a commentary
published Tuesday for being indecisive and slow. He warned of a
``huge humanitarian and political disaster.''
	   He urged that troops be deployed to northern Albania to close
the border, that NATO impose a no-fly zone over Kosovo and threaten
air strikes against remaining Serb forces, and that the Kosovo
Liberation Army's sponsors in Europe and the United States be
pressured to get the KLA to halt military operations.
	   ``Kosovo is a testing ground,'' Bildt wrote in the Financial
Times of London. ``Here, we will see if the lessons of the wars in
Croatia and Bosnia have been learned. So far, there are only faint
signs that this has been the case.''
	   More than 250 people are said to have died in Kosovo since March
1 in escalating clashes between government forces and the KLA.
	   Also Tuesday, exiled Kosovo Albanian political leaders announced
they would collect an extra tax from an estimated 400,000 Kosovo
Albanians living abroad to finance the ``defense of our people.''
They didn't say how.
	   In 1993, Kosovo Albanians established a parallel system of
administration involving collecting taxes and financing education
and health care for Albanians.
	   The announcement made by the Germany-based Kosovo Albanian
government-in-exile was published Tuesday in Albanian-language
papers in Kosovo, saying every Albanian working abroad would have
to contribute an equivalent of dlrs 300-600. The tax would be
collected from June 10 through July 10.
	   Also Tuesday, a group of Serbs living in Kosovo and dissatisfied
with Milosevic's policy in the province met with Richard Miles, the
most senior U.S. diplomat in Yugoslavia.
	   A source close to the talks, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Miles told them the United States wanted to see meaningful
negotiations between the sides and will ``apply a form of pressure
on the government, and also on the Albanian side.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 2nd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
