WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MUAR, Mon. - Less than six per cent of the factories in the
State referred their applications to renew licences to the State
Department of Environment, said State executive councillor Dr Chua
Soi Lek.
	   He said last year, only 117 factories out of the 2,000 factories
in Johor had referred to the State DOE when renewing their
licences. Of the 117, he said, the department only supported 66
applications.
	   Chua said the State DOE would come down hard on factories which
did not refer to the department before renewing their licences with
the local authorities.
	   ``This is one of the ways the DOE can check on the increasing
complaints of pollution by factories in Johor,'' he told reporters
after opening the annual general meeting of the Parent-Teacher
Association of SJK (C) Chung Hwa Presbyterian in Jalan Hashim last
night.
	   Menteri Besar Datuk Abdul Ghani Othman, in his l998 Budget
speech, had ordered local authorities to refer all factory licence
renewals to the DOE to check complaints of pollution.
	   Chua, who is also the State Environment and Consumer Affairs
committee chairman, said: ``We need to ensure effluents and smoke
emission do not cause pollution which is harmful to the health of
the workers and residents.''
	   
</TEXT>
