<HEADLINE>
Boro paddy on 40,000 hectares submerged in Kishoreganj, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Boro paddy on 40,000 hectares submerged in Kishoreganj, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Boro paddy on 40,000 hectares of land at Bara Haor' have gone
under water due to massive siltation of the 20-mile long canal from
Narasunda river in Karimganj thana to Ghurauttra river in Nikli
thana.It is gathered that due to siltation of the canal standing
Boro paddy on vast tracts of land at Bara Haor' go under water even
after a slight rainfall affecting 15 to 20 thousand farmers each
year.Incessant rainfall for the last few days has damaged Boro
paddy on more than 30,000 hectares of land at Bara Haor' this
season .
	   Chairman of Gundhar Union Parishad, Golap Mia told this
correspondent that every year Boro paddy on vast tracts of land at
Bara Haor' go under water due to siltation of the 20-mile long
canal. If the canal had been excavated the Boro crop on vast tracts
of land would not have been inundated, he added . Largescale damage
of crops every year due to overflowing of the canal water has
crippled hundreds of farmers economically . Farmers who borrow
money from the local money lenders at high rate of interest can not
repay the same .
	   The local people have appealed to the concerned authorities to
take initiative to re-excavate the canal as early as possible to
save the farmers from ruination.Meanwhile the government purchasing
centres are not purchasing paddy directly from the farmers on the
ground that the paddy brought by the farmers contain more than 15
per cent moisture. Farmers who are not aware of the moisture
content are forced to sell their produce to the farias' at cheaper
rate.
	   The farias' in collusion with some officials of the Food
Department sell the paddy to the government procurement centres at
higher rate depriving the farmers.It may be mentioned that
currently Boro paddy is selling at Taka 170 to Taka 190 per maund
in the markets of the district.
	   
</TEXT>
