<SLUG> RUBBER-COMPANIES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rubber companies under BFIDC incurring losses, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Rubber companies under BFIDC incurring losses, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The rubber companies under the Forest Industry Development
Corporation (BFIDC) in Sylhet zone, including Moulvibazar district
are incurring huge losses due to absence of buyers of their
products in both domestic and international markets. Development of
the rubber industry is being hampered due to fall in the demand for
rubber products which remained stockpiled and are gradually losing
quality. About 6,000 tonnes of rubber products worth about Tk 20
crore reportedly have remained unsold, BFIDC sources said.
	   The concerned authorities published a tender notice in all the
national dailies on February 22 last with schedule date on April 30
for dropping tenders for sale of the rubber products. But only one
tender was dropped, which was rejected for non-fulfilment of
conditions. The purchasers are showing reluctance to purchase
rubber at a price of Tk 40 per kg in the face of falling of its
price in the international market. According to sources, a ton of
rubber with tariff value at 850 dollars and 15 per cent import tax
could be sold below at Tk 50 per kg while the production cost is
above Tk 40 per kg with marginal profit.
	   The higher rubber growing countries of the world like Malaysia,
Indonesia and Thailand have lowered the export price of rubber from
Tk 40 to Tk 30 per kg for the last two years. The James Finlay,
Duncan Brothers and the owners of a few hundred small companies are
facing the problems. In the circumstances , the BFIDC authorities
sent a proposal to the government to take initiative for the
protection of the rubber industry of the country from the onslaught
of the foreign growers by raising tariff value of the imported
rubber goods and import tax.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
