<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Fire, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRECEDES: Jakarta
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Dozens feared dead in movie theater fire in Indonesia
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with 19 bodies found in 4th graf; Minor editing;
CHANGES dateline; Some Indonesians use only one name &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos pursuing &QL; 
 &UR; By ALI KOTARUMALOS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PALEMBANG, Indonesia (AP) _ Fire swept through a crowded movie
theater complex and shopping center and rescuers fear dozens of
people were killed, police said Tuesday.
	   Fire burned the Megahira shopping center, which contained the
cinema, on Monday night while hundreds were inside watching a film.
Dozens more were lined up to buy movie tickets and others were in
an adjacent amusement center.
	   Police in Palembang on the island of Sumatra said the exact
number of victims was unknown. The fire was still smoldering
Tuesday night, hampering rescue efforts.
	   Nineteen bodies had been founds in the ashes after one small
area of the building had been searched, police said, in the city
460 kilometers (285 miles) northwest of Jakarta.
	   Police spokesman Lt. Col. Sardjo Sadjat said 19 people were
injured, 14 of them hospitalized.
	   ``Dozens are believed trapped there, but we have not known what
exactly happened, because no one is able to enter the building so
far,'' he said.
	   The cause of fire, reported to have started on the second floor,
was still not known, Sadjat said.
	   He said the cinema was made up of three theaters, each with a
capacity of about 40.
	   ``I think no one can survive,'' said Djaieni, a fire department
official.
	   The newspaper Republika said most of those who died had been on
the top three floors of the five-story shopping center.
	   It said nine people escaped the flames by climbing down ropes of
a window washing platform on the outside of the building.
	   Three of the nine fell to the ground and were hospitalized with
serious injuries.
	   The newspaper said those who escaped claimed ``many people'' had
been trapped inside after panic broke out.
	   ``On the stairs we trampled over each other to get out,''
Republika quoted one survivor, identified by the single name of
Zukar, as saying.
	   The fire follows several shopping mall blazes that killed
hundreds of people during riots in the capital Jakarta last month.
	   Police say the Jakarta fires had been deliberately lit and most
of the dead had been looters.
</TEXT>
