<SLUG> SINOLINK-PRICE-DIVES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sinolink price dives 24pc in trade debut, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Sinolink price dives 24pc in trade debut, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Teresa LeeASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SHARES of Sinolink Worldwide Holdings dived 24 per cent to $0.87
a share in their first trading day yesterday amid the spreading
economic gloom.
	   Shares of the Shenzhen property developer and electricity
supplier made their trading debut at $1.10 per share yesterday,
compared with an issue price of $1.15.
	   The price quickly dropped to $1.02 per share in the first two
minutes of trading.
	   Sinolink chairman and managing director Thomas Ou Yaping said
the company's financial performance would be strengthened further
with the launch in July of new property projects in Shenzhen.
	   ``The property market in Shenzhen has a good potential,'' he
said.
	   The firm's share was trading between $0.81 and $1.10 a share
yesterday, posting a turnover of $97.24 million on a volume of
106.3 million.
	   The company issued 380 million shares at $1.15 a share,
representing a discount of about 36 per cent to its net asset value
of $1.80 a share.
	   Sinolink raised $406 million from its initial public offering.
	   Of the issue, 342 million shares were offered through an
international placement and was barely oversubscribed. The public
offer of 38 million shares in Hong Kong was 1.18 times subscribed.
	   Analysts said investors were cautious amid the turbulence in the
market and were unwilling to invest in big issues in the absence of
sufficient liquidity.
	   ``Companies which offer big issues will have very little chance
of success in today's gloomy market,'' said a corporate finance
director at HSBC investment Banking.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
