<HEADLINE>
NGOs implementing uplift schemes, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
NGOs implementing uplift schemes, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Two leading non-government organisations have taken up
programmes in the district for the welfare of the people.
Association for Social Advancement Programme has brought village
Bhadera in Tarail thana under sanitation and safe-drinking water
coverage to be completed by the end of the year. About 600 families
in the village have been brought under the purview of the
programme.
	   An awareness programme on the importance of the use of sanitary
latrines and safe drinking water has been started. Earlier, an
orientation course for the staff of ASAP was held at its office in
the town to impart training and to equip them with experience for
successful implementation of the programme. Deputy Speaker of the
Jatiya Sangsad, Advocate Abdul Hamid inaugurated the programme as
the chief guest.
	   Association for Rural Poor (ARP) has been implementing various
programmes for the alleviation of poverty through self-employment.
Under the programmes, many unemployed youths of Tarail areas have
been provided with soft-term house building loans. Loans were also
distributed among 126 rural poor women. Each woman was given Tk
2,000. Dr Paul Kestel, a former member of West German provincial
parliament distributed the loans as the chief guest.
	   
</TEXT>
