</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> MULTIMEDIA-CAMPAIGN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Multimedia campaign on endangered species, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Multimedia campaign on endangered species, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Esther TanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Mon. - A multimedia campaign was launched today to
create awareness about the possible extinction of endangered
species caused by consumption and buying of wildlife body parts.
	   Called the Asian Conservation Awareness Programme, the campaign
carries the message ``When the buying stops, the killing can too''.
It is depicted in a series of five printed advertisements and a
public service message to hit the local cinemas next month.
	   The message, an appeal to the people to stop eating and buying
body parts of endangered species, is by ACAP's international
ambassador, Hong Kong actor and stuntman Jackie Chan.
	   The message is targetted at those who knowingly or unknowingly
contribute to wildlife extinction.
	   Deputy Science, Technology and Environment Minister Datuk Abu
Bakar Daud launched the programme at his ministry.
	   ACAP was designed by three international wildlife organisations
namely the Global Survival Network (GSN) from the United States,
the David Shepherd Conservation Foundation and the Tusk Force, both
from the UK.
	   In Malaysia, ACAP is being run by the Malaysian Nature Society,
the Wildlife and National Parks Department and GSN.
	   It is supported by J. Walter Thompson Advertising Agency and
Hill &AMP; Knowlton (SEA) Sdn Bhd, an international public relations
firm.
	   MNS chief executive officer Dr Rizal Roy Sirimanne said the main
objective of the programme was to promote awareness about the
plight of some of the country's endangered species.
	   Five animals have been targetted for the programme namely the
Sumatran Rhinoceros, Indo-Chinese Tiger, Malayan Sun Bear, Asian
Elephant, and Sea Turtles.
	   ``These animals are endangered and their numbers are diminishing
because they are hunted for their body parts to be turned into
medicine, ornaments or jewellery.
	   ``The public must know that they have the power to stop the
killing of endangered animals when they stop buying,'' said Rizal.
	   Globally, it is estimated that the illegal wildlife trade is a
US$7 billion (about RM28 billion) a year industry, third only to
the drugs and black-market arms business.
	   ACAP's international director Tamara Gray said demand for
products and meat from endangered species was strongest in East
Asian countries and their overseas communities.
	   She said the main consumers were those from Korea, Japan, China
and the Chinese community in the US such as in San Francisco and
New York.
	   The trading in wildlife involves a huge network. Due to the high
profits obtained, curbing the illegal trade is almost impossible.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
