	   KUALA LUMPUR, Mon. - The Housing and Local Government Ministry
has set up a committee to look into ways of encouraging more people
to enrol as volunteer firemen.
	   Its Minister Datuk Dr Ting Chew Peh said today the step was
being taken due to a high number of fires over the past five years.
	   He said the committee, headed by his deputy Peter Chin Fah Kui,
was expected to submit its proposals to the Ministry soon.
	   ``There are currently only about 230 volunteer fire brigades in
the country and we need increase it to create public awareness of
the dangers of fire.
	   ``The primary objective of a volunteer fire brigade is not to
aid regular firemen in times of emergencies but to increase public
awareness of the dangers of fire and to make the public more
committed towards preventing such fires,'' he said.
	   Ting was speaking to reporters aft%
Chai Hock, City fire chief Leonard Athanasius and City police chief
Datuk Kamaruddin Ali.
	   ``We want more volunteer firemen, not just in urban areas, but
especially in high-risk areas in cities,'' Ting said.
	   Earlier, in his speech, Ting said the department received a
total of 24,350 emergency calls last year.
	   The Minister later launched the City Fire and Rescue
Department's fire hydrant hotline.
	   Members of the public who know if any of the city's 16,000 fire
hydrants are damaged or being misused can call the hotline at tel
2222994.
	   
