<HEADLINE>
First REIF-financed property launched, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
First REIF-financed property launched, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PROPERTY consultancy Brooke Hillier Parker yesterday launched
Avic Plaza in Shenzhen, the first in a series of property projects
on the mainland which will be financed through single-purpose Real
Estate Investment Funds (REIF).
	   Development of the US$370 million (HK$2.88 billion) project is
expected to be completed by late 2001.
	   The property project will be developed by a consortium
comprising Brooke Hillier Parker, Buoygues and China National
Aero-Technology Import &AMP; Export Corp (Catic).
	   Brooke Hillier Parker chairman Nicholas Brooke said Catic would
provide the land and REIF would contribute the capital for the
development of the whole project.
	   ``Despite the rapid pace of development, commercial rental
yields in China are still among the highest in the world,'' David
Faulkner, director of Brooke Hillier Parker, said yesterday.
	   Mr Faulkner said while over-supply was likely to cause a
downturn in the property markets in Shanghai and Beijing,
second-tier cities, such as Shenzhen, were emerging as attractive
options for investors.
	   ``Shenzhen, in particular is China's most developed and most
accessible economic zone,'' Mr Faulkner said.
	   He said commercial values and rents in Shenzhen had been stable
over the past year and were expected to rise during the second
half, while retail sales had increased by 9 per cent over the past
12 months and residential rents by 5 per cent.
	   The single purpose REIF established to finance the development
is the first of its kind for a mainland project.
	   Investors will be sought in Britain, continental Europe, and the
United States, said Mr Brooke.
	   
</TEXT>
