<HEADLINE>
Now you can afford a Jeeves', THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Now you can afford a Jeeves', THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Towheed FerozeASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Have got a twenty person sitting dinner? Can't decide what to
serve or how to manage the monumental task of organising the feast?
Well, don't get flustered. The solution is here, courtesy to Pan
Pacific Sonargaon Hotel. The ideal butler is now not just a
character in P.G Wodehouse's novel. Jeeves' can also be at your
disposal ever ready to salvage you from the hopeless situations
that often plague the modern households. Traditionally, the butler
was a British institution who worked his way up from humble junior
footman to head the male household staff and take charge of the
wine cellar and the valuable articles of daily use. He carved and
served at meals, assisted the male servants, made sure everything
was done according to protocol.
	   The role of the butler however surfaced with multifaceted
dimensions in P.G Wodehouse's Jeeves - the gentleman's gentleman
who epitomised the word perfection. Jeeves was the answer to the
prayers of the indolent, asinine wealthy fop Wooster, who was
incapable of taking care of his life and its twists. From rescuing
Wooster from social embarrassments to setting out his clothes -
Jeeves was the saviour as well as his associate. A true gentleman's
gentleman Jeeves set the trend: To overlook all the master's fault,
to keep a stiff upper lip at the sight of an unknown woman on the
master's bed, to solve all the problems (household or others), to
iron the master's newspaper and to manage large parties (often mind
boggling), The impeccable appearance of Jeeves as well as his
immaculate English also set the outline for the perfect servant.
	   The conclusion of the Second World War brought tough economic
times for Britain and the institution of the butler was on the
wane. Now-a-days this custom is restricted among the extremely
wealthy people and the well-off aristocrats. The job now also
involves the role of a personal manager. Here in Dhaka, where
having servants is an accepted and an affordable feature of city
life, the institution of Butler has multifarious prospects. It is
better service for comparatively cheaper price. The residents of
the affluent parts of the city have bearers who usually do all the
household chores. Given a butler training they can become twice as
good and three times as efficient. This was the view that prompted
the Sonargaon Hotel to introduce the butler training programme,
designed to produce certified household managers ``Why have a
bearer when you can afford a butler'' - is the slogan that has
inspired this novel inclusion to many of their laudable steps.
	   A few days ago the first batch of butlers received their
certificates of household mastery. ``This programme has made us
confident and has improved our services'', remarked a graduate
wearing a dark suit and a bow tie. ``I believe that this course
will also be helpful to the housewives as it will give them a
thorough insight into household management'', said, the owner of a
reputed restaurant. The guests present were also optimistic as they
underlined the necessity of discipline, courtesy, efficiency and
confidence in the services of waiters or bearers. ``This programme
will root out the crudity from the nature and infuse a refined air.
Shoulders straight, no grins, heads up, no rocking walk with ten
filled glasses on a tray-that's one of the things that go into
making an expert butler'. said Mr. Tanveer . Who knows this butler
programme might turn out to be as famous as Ivor Spencer's school
of Butlery - and Sheikhs and tycoons just might change their route
and start coming here to recruit their gentleman's, A bit too
imaginative, is it?
	   
</TEXT>
