<HEADLINE>
Alco investors want answers, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Alco investors want answers, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ALCO Holdings' decision not to adjourn a Special General Meeting
today to approve connected transactions that were not disclosed for
more than five years, has angered a group of minority shareholders
who had called for the meeting to be cancelled.
	   The row was sparked by the revelation that the company has been
supplying telephones and other consumer products in the past five
years to three Venturer Group companies, Venturer Electronics,
Venturer Electronics UK and Venturer Electronics De Chile, which
are wholly or partly owned by David Leung, the son of Alco's
substantial shareholder and chairman, Leung Kai-ching.
	   According to Anthony Fox, chairman of Managing Partners Ltd, who
is acting as spokesperson for certain minority shareholders, the
Alco board had failed to satisfactorily comment on the matter.
	   ``In the absence of comment from the board, the minority group
is unable to satisfy itself that past connected transactions with
Venturer were conducted on terms comparable to those extended to
other customers or were fair and reasonable to independent
shareholders,'' Mr Fox said.
	   Because of the board's decision not to adjourn the meeting, the
minority group is urging other minority shareholders to attend the
SGM in person.
	   ``Minority shareholders should support a call for a vote on a
poll,'' Mr Fox said.
	   ``They should also vote against the resolution ratifying the
past connected transactions and approving future dealings with
Venturer Group.'' The minority had demanded a full explanation from
Alco's directors for its failure to disclose the transactions in a
timely manner.
	   The transactions started in November 1992, but were only
disclosed in the company's annual report for last year.
	   Sales to Venturer represented 4.3 per cent of Alco's turnover
for the year ended 31 March 1997 and amounts due from Venturer for
the same period represented about 36 per cent of the Alco Group's
accounts receivable.
	   The minority group is considering lobbying the Hong Kong Stock
Exchange to probe the matter.
	   
