<HEADLINE>
Bernas denies it caused rice price increase, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Bernas denies it caused rice price increase, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Mon. - Padiberas Nasional Bhd (Bernas) refuted
allegations that it is the cause of the price increase in super
grade rice and instead put the blame on wholesalers and retailers.
	   Its managing director Mohd Ibrahim Nor said the higher price of
rice was caused by wholesalers and retailers who took advantage of
the demand to mark up the price.
	   At present, he said, there were 37,000 retail outlets inclusive
of supermarkets, which were being served by a network of 1,500
wholesalers which give Bernas a wholesale to retail ratio of less
than 1:25 (25 retail shops per wholesaler.) ``How can we be
responsible for the price increase? The figures quoted by Fomca
(Federation of Malaysian Consumers Association) are grossly
wrong,''he told a Press conference.
	   While admitting that there was not more than a 30 per cent price
increase, he denied allegations by Fomca that Bernas sold 80 per
cent import cheaper to its subsidiaries which in turn sell higher
to other wholesalers.
	   Bernas, he said, represents between 25 and 30 per cent of the
supply of local rice or 16.7 per cent of the total market in
Malaysia at pre- wholesaling level.
	   Mohd Ibrahim said that with the present structure of rice
distribution, up to April only 38.6 per cent of imported rice was
sold to its subsidiaries while the rest was sold to others.
	   ``Sales to other subsidiaries are at the same price as to other
wholesalers,'' he said.
	   He added that studies showed that some wholesalers sold the
Super grade rice AAA at RM3.80 per kg compared to the RM2.85 per kg
sold at Bernas outlets and by its subsidiaries.
	   On controlling the price of Super grade rice, he said if the
Government were to regulate its price, the rice industry would go
back to its position years ago where wholesalers could be blending
or mixing super grade rice to reduce costs and increase their
profit margin.
	   On recent complaints of a shortage in controlled grades of rice
(standard and premium grades), he said Bernas has not received any
complaints from consumers, and suggested that the complaints come
from wholesalers.
	   
</TEXT>
