	   Nepal, the beautiful country which is known as the daughter of
the Himalayas, always attracts the travellers. The tiny Himalayan
kingdom is a place of excitement and fun for them who come to visit
Nepal for its dreamy fairytale-like scenery.This mythical kingdom
of Himalayas was off limits to foreigners until the early 1950's.
The country became Shangri-La for hippies in the 1960's and 1970's
and a haven in the 1980's and 1990's for the new breed of adventure
travellers in trekking, rafting and mountain climbing. And at the
heart of Nepal, Kathmandu, the home of seven world-heritage sights
- more than any other location on earth, offers a fascinating mix
of the old and the new.
	   Nepal offers variety of entertainment stuffs to the travellers
interested in visiting Nepal. Modern TV satellite dishes and modern
stupas crowd the skyline. Cows, elephant and turbo-injected
four-wheel drive vehicles share the same narrow side streets. The
country also offers the travellers interesting shopping
opportunity. Young priests sporting Tom Cruise-style sunglasses
mingle with tourists wearing Nepali dress. Shops sell the latest CD
system alongside antique carpets. Medieval buildings nestle next to
modern five-star hotels. Colourfully decorated bicycle rickshaws
and luxurious foreign taxis compete for fares. Despite the
influence of the West in this ancient city, the centuries-old
temples, palaces and pagodas are yet to be replaced by modern
skyscrapers. And in the background of this atmospheric place lies
the mighty Himalayas - the abode of the Gods - that makes anyone
feel that he is on the roof of the world. Biman started operating
their regular flights to the capital city of Himalayan kingdom from
February 8, 1974.
	   At present Biman operates 4 flights a week to Kathmandu. The
national flag carrier uses F-28 aircraft in its flights to
Kathmandu.A table showing comparative revenue earning on
Dhaka-Katmandu and Kathmandu-Dhaka route from 1991 to 1997 is given
below:`(Takas in lakh)1991-92483.841992-93 479.651993-94
