<HEADLINE>
Laser to the aid of bad skin, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Laser to the aid of bad skin, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ng Peng SengASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IF you, or your child, have disfiguring pigmentation or
unsightly birthmarks, help is at hand. With laser technology, you
don't have to be the butt of jokes or comments.
	   Lasers designed to treat skin conditions were introduced into
Malaysia last year. It is thus now possible to treat many hitherto
untreatable skin conditions locally, a boon for those in the
low-income group.
	   Consultant dermatologist Dr K.C. Yee says the excitement came
from the discovery in 1980, by scientists Anderson and Parish, that
lasers could be developed to target specific tissues.
	   ``The principle is simple. Every tissue absorbs light of a
certain colour or wavelength. For example, abnormal blood vessels
contain blood pigment (haemoglobin) which absorbs yellow light
best. Hence, a yellow light laser such as the Pulsed Dye laser,
which emits short bursts of laser energy, can destroy abnormal
blood vessels without harming surrounding tissues.''
	   This thus is the concept of ``selective photothermolyis''.
``Selective'', as Dr Yee explains, means the laser can be designed
to hit a specific target whilst ``photo'' means light and
``thermo'' heat, with the term ``lysis'' meaning destruction.
	   ``Thus we have selective destruction of a chosen target by a
specific wavelength of light. Light engery is transformed into heat
which destroys the target. This is akin to some sort of magic
light,'' he muses.
	   What birthmarks and blemishes can skin lasers treat?
	   Dr Yee says a variety of conditions are amenable to laser
treatment.
	   Basically, they are vascular blemishes (related to the veins)
like birthmarks, pigmented blemishes (due to skin diseases or
tattoo pigments, and scars and wrinkles (which can be smoothened by
``laser resurfacing'').
	   All the treatments are approved by the US Food and Drug
Administration.
	   Vascular blemishes or red birthmarks cause a great deal of
anguish and guilt in parents of affected children and often
stigmatises the child for life, says Dr Yee.
	   The villain of this group of birthmarks is the port-wine stain
(PWS).
	   Prior to the advent of ``designer'' skin lasers, various
therapies had been tried with poor results and scarring, he says.
	   PWS birthmarks occur in three out of 1,000 births, often on the
face.
	   The case for treatment is compelling. Left alone, the abnormal
blood vessels grow larger and the pink stain becomes darker,
eventually becoming purplish with irregularities which can bleed.
	   Apart from the physical aspects, affected children suffer
considerable psychosocial disturbances, he says.
	   ``By age seven, children can distinguish between pleasing and
unpleasant appearances and are often brutally frank about it.
Results are best if treatment is started before four years of age.
This also avoids school- related stresses.''
	   In fact, adds Dr Yee, treatment is safe enough to be used on
children as young as four weeks, he says, with scarring very rare
and complications minimal in the right hands.
	   One important area that emerged over the past 10 years overseas
is the treatment of hypertrophic scars or keloids with the Pulsed
Dye laser.
	   These scars are lumpy, discoloured, unsightly and often itchy or
painful.
	   For these, treatment is difficult, admits Dr Yee. A significant
proportion of patients fail to respond to conventional treatment.
	   Nevertheless, Pulsed Dye laser may work in 50 to 80 per cent of
the cases by a t undetermined mechanism (possible by stimulating
collagen absorption and interfering with the blood supply to the
scar tissue.) Dr Yee points out another area of interest - the
treatment of stretch marks using Pulsed Dye laser. Stretch marks
are due to hormonal (pregnancy/puberty) and other factors,
frequently occuring after pregnancy over the stomach, thighs,
buttocks and breasts. He quotes two recent studies in the US that
show how low-energy Pulsed Dye laser treatment improves the
appearance of stretch marks. Skin biopsy reveals restoration of the
elastin content in the treated areas.
	   ``Apart from the vascular blemishes, pigmented skin blemishes
that respond to skin lasers are also common. Some of them are
birthmarks such as Nevus of Ota, occurring in 1-2 per cent of
Japanese and other Orientals.''
	   Other pigmented skin blemishes, such as freckles and lentigines,
occur later on in life. Both are induced by exposure to sunlight.
Still others are artificial pigment, for example, tattoo pigment
placed deep in the skin, or caused by damage due to materials like
glass fragments in accidents.
	   Another useful application of pigment lasers is in the removal
of tattoos.
	   Now we come to conventional lasers (CO2 laser, Erbium laser)
which are not selective lasers like what we have talked about
earlier. But they have their own uses. They are used in ``laser
resurfacing'' of the skin - the precise removal of a very thin
layer of skin without causing significant heat injury to the
underlying tissue.
	   In the West, dramatic results have been obtained in the
treatment of wrinkles using the conventional CO2 laser with a
scanner that allows the laser to dwell very briefly on the skin
surface. However, even in lightly pigmented Caucasian skin, the
skin becomes reddened and more pigmented for months. These post
operative complications are even more commom in Asian and darker
skin types, says Dr Yee. Thus, it limited its application in Asia.
	   Not to lose hope, he says, for recently, another laser was
introduced for laser resurfacing which appeared to cause less
redness and pigmentation even among Asian and Hispanic skin types.
This is the Erbium: YAG laser which causes five to 10 times less
heat injury to the underlying tissues. This refinement results in
faster healing time.
	   It would appear to be the best laser for treating soft acne
scars and wrinkles. The results are perhaps slightly less dramatic
than with the CO2 laser resurfacing but the advantages would appear
to outweigh the inherent risks of the CO2 technique. Dr Yee is
optimistic this treatment is likely to be available in the Klang
Valley in the near future.
	   The Persatuan Dermatologi Malaysia is now formulating criteria
for the credentialling of skin laser practitioners to prevent the
abuse of lasers by untrained operators. Ideally, says Dr Yee, laser
practitioners should have dermatological training. This would
prevent the treatment of potentially cancerous pigmented and
vascular lesions by non-dermatologigal practitioners, as this may
disguise the cancer till it is too late.
	   Dr Yee says: ``I've also seen patients with tattoos who
developed scarring after being treated by an unregistered
practitioner with a CO2 laser. This is a totally inappropriate
laser for this treatment in this day and age when pigment lasers
are now available.''
	   Skin lasers, the product of great scientific advances can
alleviate the suffering of many, but like all powerful tools, they
can cut or they can heal.
	   So, patients are advised to see qualified dermatologists (skin
doctors) who can give a diagnosis and then give the right
treatment. And you can get it here. Choose medical doctors who have
grounding in laser physics, a good understanding of the structure
and functioning of the skin and have proper credentials of laser
training.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:LASER-TO-THE-AID sked; CT:w; 
