<BODY>
<SLUG> PILOTS'-STRIKE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pilots' strike embarrasses Air France management, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Pilots' strike embarrasses Air France management, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Mahbub Husain KhanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   As the quadrennial event of the World Cup approached, the pilots
of Air France decided to go for at least a week-long strike upto
14th June. It was particularly embarrassing for the airline
management as it is the official carrier for the World Cup and had
promised to provide flights for all the teams in this year's
32-nation World Cup tournament. While Air France may very well
bring in all the teams on time for their matches through lease or
charter operations, this will not hold true for the thousands of
fans and tourists flocking to France this year, in June. The French
public have mostly been sympathetic with striking workers and
professionals throughout the ages. Where else in the world will you
find restaurant and family hotel owners going off on holidays of
their own each August with no protests from locals or tourists who
are the clients?
	   This country has always been philosophically in favour of the
workers and professionals at least from the first Bastille Day. But
now public opinion and that of soccer fans and French officials
have been heavily against the pilots, who are among the best paid
in the world despite the national airline's having run up years of
losses. This industrial action by the pilot's union is being
considered by the majority of the concerned public as an act of
blackmail on the eve of the World Cup. The origins of Air France
are in the brilliant French tradition of innovation in the air in
the eighteenth century balloons (the interested reader should
re-read Jules Verne's Five Weeks in a Balloon.), and their role in
aviation is commemorated by words like fuselage, aileron,
helicopter , aeroplane.
	   One of the first international airlines, the Farman company,
which made planes in Paris, was flying its Goliath bi-planes in
1919 between London and Paris and Brussels and Paris. By l923 three
other French airlines had merged to form Air Union, which
concentrated on the cross-channel flights, with connections through
France. Another merger in 1930 created Air Orient, which the next
year began flying regularly to Saigon, via Beirut, Damascus,
Karachi, Calcutta, Rangoon, and Bangkok. The most famous of the
French airlines was the little company set up in 1919 by a French
arms manufacturer, Pierre Latecoere, to fly to North America and if
possible to Latin America. It became known simply as The Line,
immortalised by the writings of the daring young pilot, Antoine de
St-Expury, who brilliantly expressed the conflict between the sense
of liberation among the stars and the stern discipline of The Line.
	   But The Line was suddenly undermined by financial scandals, the
company went into liquidation, and was sold to Air Orient. The
French Government intervened and in 1933 forced the merger of all
the airlines into a single company, with Ernest Rhoume as
president, called Air France. It was a name - imitated by many of
the national airlines that followed - which left no doubt that it
was carrying the flag. The French were determined to catch up after
the wreckage of Second World War with all the force of their
diplomacy: they still had their network of overseas colonies, and
their lack of colour prejudice made them better than the British at
negotiating with the newly independent countries. In 1948, the
French government had bought a majority share of the old private
company Air France, and put all the power of the state behind it,
with a succession of French civil servants in charge.
	   By 1952 Air France could claim to be the world's biggest airline
in terms of its unduplicated mileage, flying all through French
West Africa, the French West Indies and as far as the remote
outpost of New Caledonia between Australia and New Guinea. The
Francophone routes by which passengers could fly round the world
without ever speaking English were a striking achievement of Air
France. I had been flying Air France, fairly regularly in the
eighties, and encountered timely flights, efficient cabin service,
and good food. For example, in First Class on the Paris-Bombay
sector the lunch menu used to be: Fresh caviar, Lobster, Rack of
Lamb with mustard, Pigeon with olives, Cepes mushrooms, Aubergines
and tomatoes sweet and sour, seasonal salad, French cheese, Ice
cream and fresh fruit, with Colombian coffee.
	   This was Michelin Star quality food. At present the General
Sales Agent for Air France in Dhaka is Bengal Airlift, with its
offices in the Landmark building in Gulshan Second Circle and a
branch office in Motijheel, opposite the Federation of Chambers of
Commerce and Industries' building. (Speaking of GSA's, I must
apologise to the readers for giving them outdated information about
the GSA of Dragonair. At present it is Omni-Trans International, a
sister company of Enem Enterprises, with its recent location at 53
Kazi Nazrul Islam Avenue, atop the Kawran Bazaar branch of ANZ
Grindlay's Bank).
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
