w1098 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-WorldCup-Yugos     06-09 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-World Cup-Yugoslavia,0510 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yugoslavs arrive in France with optimism and trouble
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DUSAN STOJANOVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAINT GALMIER, France (AP) _ The Yugoslav soccer team arrived at
the World Cup Tuesday in an atmosphere of optimism about their
prospects, but clearly troubled by the ethnic turmoil back home.
	   ``Of course we cannot ignore what is happening in our county,''
said midfielder Vladimir Jugovic as he and his teammates unloaded
luggage from a bus that they took from Switzerland, their previous
training site.
	   ``But we'll try to ignore it,'' Jugovic said, referring to newly
imposed international economic sanctions against Serb-led
Yugoslavia for ethnic clashes in the troubled Kosovo province that
claimed more than 250 lives over the past 3 months.
	   ``I fight against it by not watching TV or reading newspapers,''
said Jugovic of Lazio in Italy. ``After all, we are just sportsmen
and not politicians.''
	   Yugoslavia and Germany are favored to qualify to the next round
of the World Cup from preliminary Group F that also includes the
United States and Iran.
	   As they arrived in this picturesque village just outside Saint
Etienne, players were surrounded by security police, bomb-sniffing
dogs, and dozens of local children waving Yugoslav flags and
carrying banners ``Welcome Yugoslavia.''
	   Defender Sinisa Mihajlovic said the first match against Iran on
June 14th could be crucial for Yugoslavia's hopes of reaching at
least the quarterfinals.
	   ``We simply have to beat the Iranians,'' Mihajlovic, who
recently transferred from Sampdoria to Lazio in the first Italian
division, said.
	   ``With a victory against the Iranians, we'll be relaxed playing
against the much-favored Germans,'' Mihajlovic said. ``And then,
the game against the Americans could decide which team advances to
the next round.''
	   ``But the Americans shouldn't be underestimated,'' Jugovic
added.
	   Asked whether the match against the U.S. would be a grudge match
because the United States was in instrumental in imposing sanctions
against Yugoslavia for the Kosovo troubles, the head of the
Yugoslav Soccer Federation Miljan Miljanic said:
	   ``We don't want a political match against the Americans. We are
not politicians but sports friends.''
	   Banned under U.N. sanctions from soccer in 1992 for Serb
government's fomenting of wars in Bosnia and Croatia, the Yugoslav
team returns to the World Cup stronger than ever, led by such
talents as Real Madrid's high-scoring forward Predrag Mijatovic and
longtime AC Milan star midfielder Dejan Savicevic.
	   Savicevic, who has been suffering with a string of injuries, is
likely to be ready only for Yugoslavia's second match at the
championships against Germany on June 21.
	   ``We have a very good team, maybe the best ever for
Yugoslavia,'' said assistant coach Vujadin Boskov. ``With a bit of
luck, we can reach the top. But only if we forget politics and
concentrate on soccer instead.''
	   (ds-sl)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-World Cup-Yugoslavia; CT:s; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:ASIA;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
