</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> SHARE-TURNOVER-TUMBLES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Share turnover tumbles, HONGKONG STANDARD
</HEADLINE>
Share turnover tumbles, HONGKONG STANDARD &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   HONGKONG STANDARD
   HONG KONG
   ENGLISH
   Dennis NgASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   TURNOVER on the Hong Kong stock market has been falling steadily
since February as the economy continues to contract.
	   Stock exchange data show May turnover was $115.7 billion a 0.5
per cent drop from the April turnover of $116.3 billion.
	   The number of trades has also fallen 6.8 per cent to 71,705 from
77,156 in April.
	   But a heftier 33.2 per cent fall was recorded in the volume of
turnover between the March level of $174.2 billion and the April
level of $116.3 billion.
	   Stock exchange statistics showed that the volume of turnover was
steadily rising from $398.9 billion in June last year before a
sharp fall was recorded in September, when volume reached $424.6
billion from $637 billion in the previous month.
	   The global stock market crash in October last year saw the Hong
Kong stock exchange volume crash to $375.7 billion from the
previous month's level of $424.6 billion.
	   The statistics also showed market activities declining sharply
up to last month following the Asian turmoil.
	   The only break from the falling trend since August last year was
February this year when total turnover and the total number of
trades were $212.8 billion and 2.3 million respectively, compared
to the figures of $159.5 billion and 1.4 million for January this
year.
	   The statistics also showed a continuing decline in the
importance of the first computer network terminal.
	   The percentage of trades handled by the first network terminal
dropped from 45 per cent in July last year to only 31.3 per cent
last month.
	   However, the figure for the second terminal rose from 55 per
cent to 62.1 per cent for the same period.
	   The Stock Exchange of Hong Kong also started the operation of
its third computer network terminal from 9 January this year.
	   The turnover handled by the third terminal for May this year was
$7.64 billion, while the total number of trades for May fell 6.84
per cent over the previous month.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 HONGKONG STANDARD all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
