<HEADLINE>
Muhammad Taib to be charged with corruption, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Muhammad Taib to be charged with corruption, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Carolyn HongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Mon. - Former Selangor Menteri Besar Tan Sri
Muhammad Muhammad Taib will be charged in the Sessions Court on
Wednesday with failing to declare all his assets as required under
the Prevention of Corruption Act 1961.
	   Public Prosecutor Tan Sri Mohtar Abdullah, who is also
Attorney-General, today gave his consent to prosecute after being
satisfied there was prima facie evidence obtained by the
Anti-Corruption Agency in its investigations.
	   The summons has been obtained from the court to be served on
Muhammad.
	   The case will be mentioned at 9am.
	   A statement signed by the A-G's special officer Shamsuddin
Hassan stated that Muhammad will be charged under section 25(2) of
the Prevention of Corruption Act.
	   The charge carries a maximum fine of RM2,000 or a year's jail,
or both.
	   Under the section, the Public Prosecutor may, in the course of
investigations, request a person to declare all assets belonging to
him, his agent, trustee, spouse, sons or daughters; the date and
how each property was acquired.
	   The person can also be asked to give a sworn statement of any
money or property sent out of Malaysia, during a specified period.
	   ``Tan Sri Mohtar Abdullah, the Attorney-General, in his capacity
as the Public Prosecutor of Malaysia, has studied and scrutinised
all evidence obtained from investigations by the Anti-Corruption
Agency and is satisfied that there is prima facie evidence,''
Shamsuddin said.
	   The investigation papers, received on June 1 by the head of
prosecution in the A-G's Chambers, were the result of the first
part of ACA's investigations after a police report was lodged
against Muhammad at the Sentul police station on June 28 last year.
	   The investigations concerned his failure to declare all his
assets as required by section 25(2) of the Act.
	   The second part of the investigations concerns offences under
the new Anti-Corruption Act 1998 which came into force on June 8
this year.
	   On Sunday, ACA director-general Datuk Shafee Yahaya said
investigations were still ongoing regardless of Muhammad's
acquittal in an Australian court.
	   He said the ACA had completed the first part of its
investigations which started when Muhammad was detained for failing
to declare more than A$1.2 million (RM2.95 million) when he left
Brisbane International Airport on Dec 26, 1996.
	   ``We are still investigating the second part of it, and once
it's completed, we will forward the papers to the A-G's Chambers,''
he said.
	   The Brisbane District Court on May 29 acquitted Muhammad on two
charges of falsely declaring the money he took into Australia in
December 1996 and failing to declare more than A$1.2 million when
he left the country.
	   The money was seized by the Australian police following his
arrest and was released the day after his acquittal.
	   During his trial, Muhammad told the court that he had used his
wife's name, Puan Sri Asbi Rohani Hasnan, to buy assets in
Australia and New Zealand.
	   This included a plot of land valued at A$460,000 and a A$460,000
bungalow at Sovereign Island, Gold Coast; a farm in Currajong
valued at A$3.7 million, a NZ$500,000 house (RM1.05 million) and
two plots of land valued at about NZ$4 million in New Zealand.
	   FULL text of statement released by the Attorney-General's
Chambers A REPORT was lodged at the Sentul Police Station No:
7031/97 on 28.6.1997 against former Selangor Menteri Besar, Y.B.
Tan Sri Muhammad bin Muhammad Taib on the suspicion of committing
an offence under the Prevention of Corruption Act. Part One of the
investigations is linked to the offence of failing to declare all
his properties as provided for under Section 25(2) of the
Prevention of Corruption Act 1961 (Laws of Malaysia Act 57) and
Part Two of the investigation focuses on offences linked to the
Anti- Corruption Act 1998 (Laws of Malaysia Act 575) recently
enforced on 8th June 1998.
	   2. On 1st June 1998 the Head of Prosecution, Attorney General's
Chambers, Malaysia, had received the Part One Investigation Papers
on the investigations connected to this case.
	   3. Y.B. Tan Sri Dato' Mohtar bin Abdullah, Attorney-General, as
the Public Prosecutor, Malaysia, has studied and scrutinised all
evidence obtained from investigations by the Anti-Corruption Agency
and he is satisfied there is ``prima facie'' evidence and as a
result, on this day which is also 8th June 1998 Y.B. Tan Sri Dato'
Attorney-General, as the Public Prosecutor of Malaysia has already
given permission to charge Y.B.
	   Tan Sri Muhammad bin Muhammad Taib under section 25(2)
Prevention of Corruption Act 1961 (Laws of Malaysia Act 57).
	   4. The summons has already been obtained from the Court to be
served on Y.B. Tan Sri Muhammad bin Muhammad Taib and henceforth
this case will be mentioned at the Kuala Lumpur Sessions Court on
Wednesday, which is 10th June 1998, at 9.00am.
	   Shamsuddin Hassan Special Officer to the Attorney-General, on
behalf of the Attorney-General, Malaysia.
	   
</TEXT>
