<HEADLINE>
Pioneer status company that paved the road to wealth of opportunity, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Pioneer status company that paved the road to wealth of opportunity, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Valerie NgASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   COLOURFUL HARVEST ... Aquarium fish entrepreneurs Raymond Cheah
(left) and Jalil Tumirin gather varieties of fancy carp,
scientifically known as cyprinus carpio, at their farm in the Senai
Industrial Estate in Johor.
	   Jalil is company executive chairman and Cheah the managing
director of Technofish Sdn Bhd which has proven that the aquarium
fish business is lucrative and probably yields the fastest returns
in pisciculture activities.
	   The company is now exporting 98 per cent of its fish to
countries like Singapore, the United States, Japan, the United
Kingdom, Germany, France, Italy, the Netherlands, Spain, Belgium,
Taiwan and South Korea.
	   Technofish, which started 12 years ago as a pioneer status
company, breeds and sells wholesale about 40 species and 60
varieties of aquarium fish commercially on its eight-hectare farm.
	   It invested between RM50,000 and RM100,000 in each 0.4-ha of the
farm.
	   Each of this 0.4ha consists of about 20 to 200 earth ponds,
areas for hatchery, nursery, growout, grading, quarantine and
packing.
	   ``The sales value for every hectare ranges from between RM5,000
and RM20,000 per month,'' Cheah said.
	   Besides fancy carp, the other fish include ramirez (apistogramma
ramirezi), tiger barb (barbodes tetrazona), goldfish (carrassius
auratus), managuense cichlid (cichlasoma managuense), dwarf gourami
(colisa lalia), kissing gourami (helostoma temmincki) and angel
fish (pterophyllum scalare).
	   Cheah said among the best selling fishes were the tetras such as
penguin tetra (thayeria obliqua) and glowlight tetra (hemigrammus
erythrozonus), barbs and gouramis.
	   The company breeds its own fry from imported parent stock from
countries in Southeast Asia, Australia, China, India, Mexico,
Colombia, Brazil, Argentina, Congo, Zambia and Madagascar.
	   Technofish also prepares its own fish feed, carries out
in-breeding, experiment and hatchery and supplies fry to other fish
farms.
	   Cheah, who is also the Johor Aquarium Fish Breeders Association
vice- president, said Technofish provides training for Fisheries
Department staff and Universiti Putra Malaysia students.
	   
</TEXT>
