<SLUG> GREEN-GARDEN-PROGRAMME sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Successful Green Garden programme to be expanded, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Successful Green Garden programme to be expanded, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE State's Green Garden programme is becoming a success and the
State is expected to produce nearly 370,000 kilogrammes of various
vegetable products by the end of this year, the House was told
yesterday.
	   The Green Garden programme emphasises utilisation of idle land,
usage of hydroponic farming sets and public involvement in planting
vegetables at home.
	   State Agriculture and Environment Committee chairman Datuk Abdul
Rashid Abdullah (BN-Sungai Acheh) said under the programme, the
State Agricultural Department had provided technical assistance to
40 groups of collective farmers to work on a variety of vegetables.
	   The State Government also plans to expand the collective farming
scheme from the present 700ha land area to increase vegetable
output.
	   He said a 195ha land had been identified for such development.
	   In replying to points raised during the debate on a motion of
thanks to the Yang di-Pertua Negeri Tun Hamdan Sheikh Tahir for his
opening address, Abdul Rashid said since the hydroponic farming
system was launched in February, 11,700 sets had been sold to
households by the State Agricultural Department with the help of
other related agencies.
	   With this initial success, he said the State Government's aim to
reduce dependency on imported vegetables could be achieved faster
than expected.
	   He said through overtime work by staff of certain departments,
the recent drought and water shortage crisis that affected at least
50 per cent or 5,774ha of the State's padi fields had been
overcome.
	   He said only 220ha of padi fields, involving 145 farmers, could
not be worked on. However, he assured that the State Government
would help them once a study on their problem was completed.
	   He said the State Government planned to install new, and upgrade
existing, basic infrastructure systems especially the irrigation
canal lines to the State's 11,500ha of padi fields under the budget
of RM220 million announced three years ago.
	   Penang has the fifth largest area under padi in the country.
	   On the fate of fishermen affected by reclamation projects in
Tanjung Tokong and the Jelutong Expressway, Abdul Rashid said each
of the 86 registered boat owners in Tanjung Tokong had received
RM12,000 in the form of high-powered and fibre glass boats and
modern fishing equipment.
	   In Jelutong, each of the 232 registered fishermen will get
RM15,000. In addition two new jetties with a fishery complex would
be built for them, he added.
	   On open burning, he said 23 people had been compounded and eight
had been taken to court so far this year.
	   
</TEXT>
