<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Venables-Palace </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former England coach takes over at Crystal Palace
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Former England coach Terry Venables returned to
English club soccer Tuesday, taking over as manager of relegated
first division side Crystal Palace.
	   Venables was appointed following the completion of new chairman
Mark Goldberg's protracted 22-million-pound (dlrs 35.8 million)
takeover of the London club last week.
	   Venables finished his playing career at Palace and started in
management with the club in 1976. He guided the club to the old
First Division from the Third Division before taking charge at
Queens Park Rangers, Barcelona and Tottenham.
	   He guided England to the semifinals of Euro 96, coached the
Australian national team and bought and then sold control of first
division Portsmouth.
	   ``I've been involved in international football for the past four
years and I really enjoyed that,'' Venables said. ``Some of that I
will miss but at the same time I missed the day-to-day running of a
football club, and this was an opportunity that I wanted to take
up.''
	   ``The first aim is to try to get the club back up to the Premier
League. ... It's not going to be easy _ people at this club have
witnessed it going up and coming down again many times. We need to
go back up and to stay there.''
	   Venables and Goldberg will aim to hold onto stars such as Matt
Jansen and Italy's Attilio Lombardo and invest in new players.
	   Goldberg revealed he would be hold the 31-year-old Lombardo to
the two years remaining on his existing contract and offer him a
three-year extension to the deal.
	   Several players, such as fellow Italian Michele Padovano, are
likely to leave.
	   Goldberg said his restructuring plan is to transform Palace into
a club capable of competing in Europe within five years.
	   Venables' assistant will be existing coach Ray Lewington. Former
manager Steve Coppell was confirmed as the club's technical
director of football.
	   (sw)	   
</TEXT>
