<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Africa-Reax </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Africans praise Abacha the man, scorn the policies
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By AMBA DADSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) _ African leaders, diplomats and
dignitaries on Tuesday ignored late Sani Abacha's harsh domestic
politics, opting instead to praise the man who defended democracy
abroad while squelching liberty at home.
	   From the Ivory Coast to South Africa, carefully worded tributes
marked Abacha's death _ tributes that also carried a message
calling for change in Nigeria.
	   ``He was quick to recognize that prosperity in the region
depends on the capacity of countries in West Africa to foster peace
and stability,'' Ghana's Vice President John Atta Mills said.
	   At home Abacha crushed dissent, jailed opponents and refused his
people freedom and democracy.
	   But elsewhere in West Africa, Abacha's soldiers were ironically
welcomed by villagers as champions of democracy as they drove out
villains and despots to help restore elected governments.
	   Sierra Leone's President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah was returned to
power earlier this year as a direct result of Nigeria's military
intervention in his war-wracked country.
	   Kabbah was ousted in a May 1997 military coup by Lt. Col. Johnny
Paul Koroma, who was in turn driven from power by Abacha's troops
who were leading a West African coalition force.
	   Liberia's President Charles Taylor called for a national day of
mourning for Abacha. Again, Nigerian troops helped to implement
peace accords in Liberia to end seven years of civil war and clear
the way for presidential elections.
	   Organization of African Unity Secretary-General Salim Ahmed
Salim said he was struck with personal sorrow over Abacha's death.
	   ``He had his downside, but as far as Africa is concerned he will
be missed,'' Salim said.
	   He added, however, that Abacha had failed to move his country
toward democracy.
	   ``Stability, democracy in Nigeria is important not only for the
country but for all of Africa,'' Salim said.
	   In the Ivory Coast, President Henri Konan Bedie called Abacha
one of Africa's ``most ardent architects of economic integration.''
	   The government-backed newspaper Fraternite Matin _ the
editorials of which echo the official line _ criticized Abacha's
tight grip on power. A ``diabolical plan'' the editorial said.
	   ``Abacha died without loosening the noose which strangled
Nigeria's international image,'' the newspaper's editorial said.
 &UR; (ad/ids)
</TEXT>
