<SLUG> BC-France-Bomb, 1st Lst-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bomb explodes in office of French far right political party
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: UPDATES with two people injured, group claims responsibility
for blast, National Front leader condemns attack. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MARSEILLE, France (AP) _ An explosive device blew out the window
Tuesday of the office of the far right National Front in the
southern French port of Marseille, slightly injuring two people.
	   A group called ``Francs-tireurs Partisans,'' (Sniper Supporters)
has claimed responsibility for the attack, police said.
	   The explosion took place just hours before the trial of three
National Front activists, who are accused of having killed a youth
from the Comoros Islands in 1995, started in the nearby town of
Aix-en-Provence.
	   Ibrahim Ali, 17, was allegedly shot in the back by the National
Front activists while running for a bus with his friends. All three
of the accused claim to have been acting in self-defense, but
police did not find any arms or dangerous objects belonging to the
victim and his friends.
	   The ``Francs-Tireurs Partisans'' said there could be more
attacks before the end of the alleged killers' trial. The group has
already claimed responsibility for a February attack on another
National Front office, carried out in memory of the boy's death.
	   The National Front, led by Jean-Marie Le Pen, blames immigrants,
mainly from North Africa, for France's nearly 12 percent
unemployment rate. It has also been accused of anti-semitism.
	   Bruno Megret, the No. 2 in the National Front, condemned the
attack.
	   President Jacques Chirac has branded the party, which tallied
around 15 percent at recent regional elections, ``racist and
xenophobic.''
	   About a hundred anti-racism demonstrators stood outside court on
Tuesday, waving a banner that said ``Justice for Ibrahim.''
	   Demonstrations in Ibrahim Ali's honor have taken place since
Saturday in Marseille, a city with a large community from the
Comoros Islands, a former French territory in the Indian Ocean.
	   (parf-dgs) 	   
</TEXT>
