<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Romanian coach donates to charity, slams national soccer
</HEADLINE>
federation &QL; 
 &UR; By VIOREL URMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ALBI, France (AP) _ Anghel Iordanescu, who will end five years
as Romania's national coach after the World Cup finals, will pocket
only a modest sum for leading the east Europeans in France.
	   After the tournament, the 48-year-old general will become coach
of Greece, on a two-year contract said to be worth some dlrs
800,000.
	   But Iordanescu, who played for Steaua Bucharest army club, feels
he owes his country something after the national team's poor
showing at Euro '96 in England, where they lost all three of their
group matches and scored just once.
	   ``I donated a considerable amount to a charity foundation which
takes care of orphans and children with social problems,''
Iordanescu told The Associated Press in an interview.
	   Iordanescu's wife is a member of the ProVita charity foundation
in Bucharest, and the couple, who has three sons and a daughter,
also plans to pay for the construction of a church and a nursery to
raise orphans.
	   ``We hope that the good God will give us power and support to
achieve our plans,'' he said.
	   Iordanescu did not give a precise figure, but according to press
reports he will receive dlrs 100,000 from the Romanian federation
for taking the team to France. Most of that amount is said to go to
the ProVita foundation.
	   But the softspoken general has made himself an army of enemies
because of his outspoken stance against corruption and match-fixing
in Romania's premier division.
	   So fierce was his opposition that two years ago he resigned, but
Romanian officials refused to accept it and convinced him to
return.
	   In 1994 in the United States, Iordanescu led Romania to its best
ever World Cup performance, reaching the quarterfinals where they
fell to Sweden on penalties.
	   In the interview at the Romanians' base camp, Iordanescu accused
the soccer authorities of endangering the country's World Cup
chances by denying him money, facilities and competitive warmup
matches.
	   ``I wanted to organize a training camp in Switzerland, but the
federation president told me there wasn't even money to pay for the
flight.''
	   Federation President Mircea Sandu told a news conference in
Bucharest that he was at least dlrs 1 million short of what was
needed to prepare the team for the finals.
	   ``Then I asked the federation to find us strong teams for our
warmup games, like France, Italy and Germany. But in the end we had
to contend ourselves with Paraguay and Moldova.''
	   He said the federation rejected a friendly with Nigeria because
they offered dlrs 15,000 but the Nigerians wanted more.
	   As a player Iordanescu played 64 times for Romania, scoring 26
goals.
	   He first caught the eye in 1986, when as player-coach of Steaua
he came on as substitute to help the club beat Barcelona on
penalties to win the European Champions Cup.
	   He was promoted to the rank of army general after the '94 World
Cup.
	   In July he will pack his bags and take over the Greek national
team.
	   ``The contract with the Greek federation is better than that
with the Romanian federation,'' he said, no regrets in his voice.
</TEXT>
