<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Israel-Peace </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Egyptian, Israeli peace activists vow to advance peace
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Egyptian and Israeli peace activists pledged
Tuesday to work together to advance Middle East peace, a prospect
they said could only be realized through the creation of a
Palestinian state with Jerusalem as its capital.
	   The activists, who met Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in Cairo
on Tuesday, also blamed Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
for the deadlock in Israeli-Palestinian talks.
	   The activists represent Peace Now, Israel's largest peace
organization, and the Egyptian Peace Movement, a small group whose
members include prominent writers, lawyers and former officials.
	   On Monday, the activists backed the right of Palestinians to
establish an independent state. They said that while they support
Israel's position that Jerusalem should remain unified, a
Palestinian capital should be set up in the city's Arab areas.
	   Israel captured east Jerusalem from Jordan in 1967.
	   A statement by the two groups said they decided to join hands to
counter Netanyahu's hard-line policies, which they blamed for
bringing the talks to a ``virtual standstill.''
	   The statement said some Israeli settlements should be allowed to
remain within the boundaries of a Palestinian state but others must
be evacuated with the Israeli government paying compensation.
	   The proposal said the Palestinian state should be allowed to
absorb the 1948 refugees and displaced Palestinians from the 1967
Arab-Israeli war. The refugees should receive compensation from the
international community, it said.
	   The official Israeli-Palestinian talks have left the issue of
Jerusalem and the historical disputes to be resolved last, pending
a resolution of major issues such as Israeli troops pullout from
West Bank, the opening of an airport in Gaza and the free passage
of Palestinians between the West Bank and Gaza.
	   The peace talks between the two sides are currently stalled over
Israel's refusal to accept a U.S. proposal for a further 13.1
percent Israeli troop withdrawal from the West Bank.
 &UR; sn-as
</TEXT>
