<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANALYSIS-Nigeria-After Abacha,0684 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Impoverished Nigeria considers life without Abacha
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; An AP News Analysis &QC; 
 &UR; With BC-Nigeria-Abacha &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo NY191 &QL; 
 &UR; By IAN STEWART &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) _ Rich in resources, gifted with great
thinkers, Nigeria in its nascent independence 38 years ago was
energized with the promise of freedom in a modern Africa.
	   That was before the military entered the picture, with its
coups, corruption and mismanagement.
	   With his death from a heart attack Monday, Gen. Sani Abacha
leaves behind a country in disarray, its natural oil wealth
plundered by only the latest in a long line of dictators.
	   Under Abacha, Nigeria's dlrs 4.45 billion in oil export revenues
did little to ease the staggering poverty in a country where rural
villages go without electricity, clean water and medical clinics.
	   In contrast, Abacha lived in a world of obscene wealth in a
capital, Abuja, which he ordered built from nothing at a staggering
cost.
	   In a pre-dawn ceremony Tuesday, the military named a new
general, Abdulsalam Abubakar, to replace Abacha. Nigerians now must
watch and wait to see what's in store from their ninth army ruler.
	   Abacha's unfinished and divisive work will continue to haunt the
country unless Abubakar moves Nigeria away from army rule and
toward democratic reform as so often promised _ but never
fulfilled.
	   In the wake of Abacha's five years in power, Nigerian prisons
are crammed with political prisoners; the former deputy military
leader remains on death row on what are probably trumped-up coup
charges.
	   The president-elect of 1993, Moshood Abiola, likewise languishes
in prison.
	   And Nigeria's noted thinkers, like Nobel laureate Wole Soyinka,
live in exile. More ominously, others, like author and
environmentalist Ken Sara-Wiwa, are dead _ executed at Abacha's
whim.
	   ``Everything has been allowed to deteriorate,'' outspoken
Nigerian political analyst Auwalu Ilu said in a recent interview
before Abacha's death. ``The only way to recovery is for every
Nigerian to play a role.''
	   After Abacha's iron-fisted rule, however, most Nigerians have
learned that playing a role means risking time in jail, or worse.
Change must come from Abubakar.
	   Abacha jailed thousands of critics, opponents and pro-democracy
activists. Meanwhile, Nigerians watched in confusion as their
leader helped defend democracy away from home.
	   In Sierra Leone, Abacha was hailed as a friend to democracy when
his army helped restored that country's elected government.
	   But then, Nigerians are quick to point out with typical
street-wise self-deprecating humor, that theirs is a country that
imports what it has (oil) and exports what it doesn't have
(democracy).
	   For its faults, the army has been credited with holding
fractious Nigeria together _ particularly in the wake of the brutal
1967-70 Biafran civil war.
	   But under Abacha, the army bridged ethnic fault lines only to
rob the country of its riches.
	   The world's sixth-largest oil exporter, Nigeria is forced to
import refined fuel _ the country's refineries have all fallen idle
for disrepair.
	   Daily life in the cities has deteriorated into a grinding
routine of day-long queues for fuel and mandatory bribes to
underpaid police officers.
	   The promise of free enterprise and burgeoning new markets in the
Nigeria of the 1960s was soon hijacked by the military. With its
legacy of corruption fine-tuned under Abacha, fair business
competition has been all but obliterated.
	   Supply and demand be damned, currying favor with the military
was the means of corporate survival in Abacha's Nigeria.
	   Apart from robbing Nigeria of civil liberties and democracy,
Abacha has left a legacy of corruption that has permeated almost
every level of society, from jacket-and-tie bankers to the
street-corner shoeshine boy.
	    &UR; ___
	   EDITOR'S NOTE: Ian Stewart, The Associated Press chief of bureau
for West Africa, is based in Abidjan, Ivory Coast.
</TEXT>
