<SLUG> BC-Africa-Briefs </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items on South Africa, Kenya, Zimbabwe, Malawi &QL; 
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ------
	   BLANTYRE, Malawi (AP) _ One child was killed and three girls
were raped when pupils from two neighboring schools fought pitched
battles, police said.
	   Blantyre police spokesman Oliver Soko said the clashes started
after a soccer match Monday between the two high schools near the
southern town of Nsanje.
	   The losing team accused the winning team of attacking girl
pupils who jeered at the winners. Three of the girls were allegedly
raped and classmates retaliated by invading the other school and
smashing desks and property.
	   Soko said it was not clear how the pupil died and he had no
information on the dead child's identity.
	   He said five boys were arrested and will face proceedings in a
court for juveniles.
	   -----
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ Under military escort, the U.N. World Food
Program has begun a two-month emergency food distribution to more
than 100,000 displaced people in northwestern Rwanda, the agency
said Tuesday.
	   WFP Rwanda country director Gerard Van Dijk said until now, the
agency had
	   only been able to take small amounts of relief food into a few
areas because of insecurity and rebel attacks.
	   ``Now we hope to reach more remote villages where reports
indicate that displaced people are in urgent need of our help,''
Dijk said.
	   The U.N agency said the distribution began last week in a region
where 200 metric tons was provided to 25,000 people.
	   The agency plans to hand out a total of 1,200 tons of food aid
in the two prefectures of Gisenyi and Ruhengeri in northwest
Rwanda.
	   Thousands of people have fled the violence in the area.
	   UN and other aid agencies have had only partial and periodical
access to the two regions. This year, the majority of WFP
assistance has been food-for-work programs that support community
participation in agricultural rehabilitation.
	   -----
	   MUTARE, Zimbabwe (AP) _ Eleven people were killed when a bus
collided with
	   an 18-ton truck near Mutare, police said.
	   Police spokesman Assistant-Inspector Eddison Makacha said eight
passengers
	   died instantly in Monday's accident and another three died
afterwards.
	   The driver of the bus was among those who died.
	   ----
	   STUTTERHEIM, South Africa (AP) _ Stock theft cost Eastern Cape
farmers 29 million rand (dlrs 5.7 million) last year, according to
Stutterheim stock theft unit commander Capt. Theo Meyer.
	   Meyer was speaking Monday at the bail application of seven
alleged rustlers, who are charged with stealing 96 sheep worth
30,000 rand (dlrs 6,000) between April and May this year.
	   The men, who were arrested May 25, were denied bail.
	   ------
	   PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) _ A pick up truck carrying a
potentially life threatening radioactive device was hijacked in the
black township of Soweto, south of Johannesburg, on Tuesday, police
said.
	   Captain Johan Pelser of the Pretoria bomb disposal unit urged
anyone who found the device not to tamper with it.
	   ``Anyone within a certain radius will suffer radiation
(exposure) if the container is opened,'' he said. ``This could be
life-threatening.''
	   The heavy metal container in which an isotope was being
transported was marked with radioactive warning signs. It was red,
and measured about 250 by 300 millimeters (10 by 12 inches), said
Superintendent Dries van Sittert, commander of the Pretoria
explosives unit
	   He said the Toyota Hilux pickup truck was hijacked about noon.
	   (pr)
