<HEADLINE>
Nature walk on Environs Day, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Nature walk on Environs Day, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Angela RaoASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   WORLD Environment Day which fell on June 5 was celebrated on a
large scale by the Malaysian Nature Society and Universiti Malaya
at the Rimba Ilmu botanical garden recently.
	   Fittingly themed ``A Walk Down Enviro-Lane'', visitors were
given guided tours on the trails of the 80-hectare Rimba Ilmu which
is home to some of the most beautiful and rare species of tropical
plants.
	   Schoolchildren got a chance to show off their skills by taking
part in the nature art competition while the younger ones tried
their hand at the Koko Krunch colouring contest.
	   Visitors also got free Koko Krunch cereal and Milo drinks to
cool down during the walk which was held from 9am to 3pm.
	   The young ones were entertained with video shows such as A Troll
In The Park.
	   The event also saw hand-picked speakers giving lectures on
various subjects.
	   Legal adviser to the Third World Network Gurdial Singh Nijar
spoke on Genetic Engineering - Promises and Perils, Tan Siew Luang
on organic farming, Suja Uddin Yusof of MNS cave group on caves and
caving and Universiti Putra Malaysia's Azman Zainal Abidin on the
haze episodes in the country.
	   Young environmentalists got a chance to expand their knowledge
at the ``rainforest and our environment'' exhibition centre where
amazing photographs of the rainforest, caves and animals were on
display along with informative posters and brochures.
	   There were also a recycling drop-off point, recycling of paper,
and food stalls.
	   All donations and proceeds from the sale of items will go to the
Rimba Ilmu Environmental Educational Fund. The event was supported
by The Star, Nestle, McDonald's Malaysia, Clairol Herbal Essences,
Yves Rocher and Schwan Stabilo.
	   
