<HEADLINE>
Cyclone hits India's western coast, at least 21 dead
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS, UPDATES with 21 dead. EDITS to conform. Trims. No
pickup &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BOMBAY, India (AP) _ A cyclone spun onto India's western Gujarat
state Tuesday, whipping up high winds that toppled walls and a
communication tower, killing 21 people.
	   The storm hit land at Porbunder, 450 kilometers (280 miles)
northwest of Bombay, and gradually moved north, buffeting much of
western India with heavy rain and winds of up 80 kph (50 mph),
snapping power lines and making driving impossible.
	   Gujarat state officials said 12 of the deaths occurred in
Junagadh, Bhuj and Jamnagar, rural districts near Porbunder, where
walls collapsed in the storm.
	   Nine others died in Porbunder when a telecommunications tower
came crashing down.
	   Kamaljeet, a meteorologist who uses only one name, said by
telephone from Ahmedabad, the capital of Gujarat, that the storm
was expected to weaken soon.
	   Indian officials moved some 5,000 people in small towns and
villages bordering the Arabian Sea to safety on Monday, state
government officials said.
</TEXT>
