<HEADLINE>
Rubbish cleared but nuisance remains, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Rubbish cleared but nuisance remains, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   INEFFICIENT rubbish collection and disposal in Jalan Masjid
India by Alam Flora Sdn Bhd is now a thing of the past.
	   A check by the New Straits Times showed that all bin points were
cleared twice a day and bin sites thoroughly washed.
	   Drains in the Jalan Masjid India area were being cleared
regularly and one business owner, Maideen Razak, confirmed that
Alam Flora had indeed improved services.
	   The question of why crows are attracted to Jalan Masjid India is
something which Alam Flora and Kuala Lumpur City Hall will have to
ponder on.
	   Business operators and residents in Jalan Masjid India have been
crying foul over the crow menace for a long time and all this
while, uncollected rubbish was blamed as the cause.
	   Crows in Jalan Masjid India disappear during the day, only to
come back late in the evening to roost on the trees which have
become their home.
	   No crow was to be found feeding in the area.
	   
</TEXT>
