<HEADLINE>
Cuban leader sees Russian Communist chief
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Reaffirming strong ties between Russian and
Cuban communists, Cuban President Fidel Castro held a meeting with
Russian Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov in Havana, Cuban news
media reported Tuesday.
	   The government's Prensa Latina news agency said the Monday night
meeting saw ``a broad interchange of information about the activity
of both parties, the progress of political relations and the
continuance of the fraternal ties which for years characterized the
relations between Russia and Cuba.''
	   Castro _ who openly embraced communism two years after his 1959
revolution _ has frequently lamented the collapse of the Soviet
communist system and expressed gratitude for Soviet support of
Cuba's socialist government against U.S. efforts to topple it.
	   Russia's Interfax agency said Castro ``spoke about the
activities of the Cuban Communists, the reforms that are being
carried out in Cuba and the Cuban people's struggle against the
American blockade.''
	   The Russian politician arrived Monday in Havana as part of a
Latin American visit that also took him to Brazil and Argentina. 	   
