</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> WORSENING-BY-THE-DAY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Crow menace worsening by the day, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Crow menace worsening by the day, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Bhavani Krishna IyerASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   DESPITE having to battle with heavy congestion with the
implementation of the one-way street system, Jalan Masjid India
residents and business operators have another big problem to live
with for which no solution seems to be in sight.
	   Now, they have to put up with pesky crows whose numbers seem to
be increasing by the day.
	   Following a letter published in the New Straits Times by an
affected resident on May 21, a check confirmed that the Masjid
India area was indeed a sorry sight.
	   True to the writer's claims that the pedestrian malls and roads
were littered with crow droppings, the whole of Jalan Masjid India
looked ``unsafe'' for pedestrians.
	   Saras Maniam, an employee in a textile shop in the area, said
she had seen people walking along the stretch using umbrellas to
protect themselves from crow droppings, especially in the evenings.
	   She admitted that she herself had sometimes resorted to taking
such precautions.
	   The owner of a batik shop on the ground floor who lives with his
family on the second floor of the same building, said having his
car parked under the trees proved costly as he has to send his car
for washing everyday.
	   ``Carwash does not come cheap. If I allow the crow droppings to
settle on my car for a few days, I will have difficulty removing
the stains and have to then send the car for waxing and polishing
which is even costlier,'' he said.
	   Asked what had drawn the crows to the area, N. Kumar, who has an
office in Wisma Lal Doshi, said it could be due to the large number
of hawker stalls which have dirtied the surroundings.
	   ``There is a possibility that leftover food from the stalls is
not disposed of properly and is attracting the crows here,'' Kumar
said.
	   Most business owners interviewed echoed similar complaints. They
added that the crows were noisy and a nuisance in the mornings.
	   Alam Flora Sdn Bhd acting chief executive officer Mohammad Siraj
Abdul Razak said cleaning the pedestrian malls was done on a
regular basis in the mornings but the problem recurred and there
was nothing much they could do beyond that.
	   ``We flush the walkways with water every morning but the next
morning it is back to square one. I do not agree that rubbish is an
attraction here because our rubbish collection system is scheduled
in such a way that there is nothing left to attract crows,''
Mohammad Siraj said.
	   In response, passers-by interviewed said that although they have
seen Alam Flora cleaning the pedestrian malls, it was not done on a
daily basis and this was evident from the dry crow droppings on the
pedestrian malls, roads and even telephone booths.
	   Kuala Lumpur City Hall Press officer Zakaria Mohamed Lazim said
although crow shoots were carried out regularly around the city,
Jalan Masjid India was not ideal for such an exercise.
	   ``Residential blocks like the Razak and Malayan mansions are too
low and if we shoot in this area, there is a likelihood that the
buildings will be hit by stray bullets,'' Mohamed Lazim said.
	   He said crow shoots which had taken place in the vicinity of
Jalan Masjid India, like Jalan Raja Laut and Jalan Munsyi Abdullah,
had driven the birds to seek refuge in Jalan Masjid India.
	   ``Apart from that, the trees along Jalan Masjid India have thick
branches which are an ideal habitat for the birds,'' Mohamed Lazim
said.
	   He also denied claims that rubbish was an attraction for the
birds as they were not found in Jalan Masjid India during the day.
	   ``They only fly back to the place in the evening to roost on the
trees,''
	   Mohamed Lazim said, adding that City Hall would employ
contractors to trim the branches of the trees.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
