w1151 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Iraq-Telephones     06-09 0369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq-Telephones,0368 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iraq linked with outside world for the first time since Gulf War
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By LEON BARKHO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ For the first time since the 1991 Gulf War,
Iraqis can make direct international telephone calls without having
to go through the operator.
	   Calls into the country also had to go through the operator, and
Iraqis living abroad used to complain it took them days to get
through.
	   An official at the Post, Telegraph and Telephone department in
Baghdad said lines were overloaded as Iraqis tried to call
relatives abroad.
	   The direct lines that resumed Monday does not apply to Israel,
which remains Iraq's enemy.
	   Minister of Transport and Communications Ahmed Morteda was
quoted as saying in the London-based Asharq al-Awsat newspaper this
week that the decision to resume direct phones lines would help
business.
	   He said Iraq plans to ``improve its communications with the
outside world and upgrade its services in order to be of service to
businessmen and investors.''
	   Previously, only embassies and representatives of foreign media
were given free access to international dialing provided they paid
in U.S. dollars _ an average of dlrs 4 a minute.
	   The Baghdad weekly al-Ittihad said Tuesday that the decision to
resume direct lines was taken following assurances by the PTT that
it made ``all the necessary technical requirements for contact with
the outside world.'' It did not elaborate.
	   A direct one-minute call to London costs 1,250 dinars (about
dlrs 0.75) and less than 50 cents to Jordan, the PTT official said.
	   Iraq has earmarked dlrs 150 million under the fourth phase of
the U.N.-approved oil-for-food deal to revamp its
telecommunications systems, which were severely damaged during the
1991 Gulf War over Kuwait.
	   Representatives from France's Alcatel, a telecommunications
firm, are currently in Baghdad to strike deals to repair the
country's telecommunications infrastructure, the weekly al-Musawir
said.
	   Alcatel modernized Iraq's telecommunications systems in the
1980s and al-Musawir said the company is also conducting talks for
post-sanctions contracts with Iraq. 	   
</TEXT>
