<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Unemployment, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German unemployment rate drops for May
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Kohl reaction, quotes &QL; 
 &UR; By ANNE THOMPSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ Germany's jobless rate sank to 10.9
percent in May, the first drop below 11 percent since 1996, the
Federal Labor Office said Tuesday.
	   A total 4.2 million people were still unemployed, but 223,400
more people had jobs in May than in April, when the unemployment
rate was 11.1 percent.
	   ``We can't ignore the fact that 4.2 million people in Germany
are still looking for work,'' Labor Office President Bernhard
Jagoda said. ``The positive jobless development in May doesn't
allow us to sit back. It's only a nice intermediate goal which we
achieved.''
	   With joblessness the key issue in national elections Sept. 27,
Chancellor Helmut Kohl put an optimistic spin on the latest figures
as a sign of economic recovery. He linked them to strong economic
growth, which has been forecast for 1998 at 2.5 percent to 3
percent.
	   ``The economy is recovering with a clarity that no one can
overlook,'' Kohl said. ``But more important is that a recovery in
the jobs market has started and a turnaround has been achieved.''
	   The labor office, in Nuremberg, attributed the May jobless
decline in part to a usual economic upturn in the spring. When
adjusted for seasonal factors, such as bad weather that hinders
construction work, only 60,000 more people had jobs.
	   But compared to May of last year, 58,300 more people had jobs,
making it the first time since 1995 that unemployment figures have
improved on the year.
	   For the fifth month in a row, jobless protesters held rallies
nationwide to coincide with the announcement of the unemployment
numbers. Altogether, about 50,000 people protested in 300 towns and
cities around the country.
	   The biggest gathering, with 800 people, was in the city of
Weimar, located in the former communist East Germany where
unemployment has for months been double that in the western states.
	   The labor office noted some improvement in the former east
Germany. The May rate was 18.1 percent compared to 19.4 percent in
April, although the east is still struggling in their transition
from communism to capitalism.
	   For the western states, the labor office claimed Germany had
reached a turnaround in joblessness. Unemployment dropped to 9.1
percent in May from 9.5 percent in April.
 &UR; (aet/cb/pfg)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Germany-Unemployment, 2nd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
