<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Germany Training,0410 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Ziege, Helmer still miss training
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NESHA STARCEVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NICE, France (AP) _ Before getting a day off, the German team
practiced hard Tuesday on the heels of a lackluster 2-1 victory
over a Cote d'Azure selection of young professionals.
	   Still missing from the mid-morning practice were wing back
Christian Ziege and Thomas Helmer, a versatile defender who can
also play in the midfield. Ziege was spared after overcoming a
fever, while Helmer is suffering from a thigh injury.
	   The Germans were taken a little bit surprised by the seriousness
with which the local selection took the practice game Monday
evening in Nice.
	   ``We thought it was going to be a relaxed practice game,'' team
spokesman Wolfgang Niersbach said. ``But they weren't all that
young and they were very competitive.''
	   Coach Berti Vogts was angry because the game featured some
tackling harder than usual in such exhibition, charity games,
Niersbach said. ``Luckily no one was injured.''
	   The Germans won on goals by Olaf Marschall and Oliver Bierhoff.
	   ``We didn't know they would be professionals, but it was good
practice, I think we needed it,'' said team captain Juergen
Klinsmann.
	   While Ziege will resume training Wednesday, Helmer is unsure
whether he'll recover by the time Germany opens its campaign June
15 in Paris against the United States.
	   ``I'll do my best to help the team, whether it's on or off the
field,'' said Helmer, the 33-year-old captain of Bayern Munich and
one of the leaders on the team.
	   Helmer will be examined Tuesday evening by Bayer's physician
Hans-Willhelm Mueller-Wohlfahrt, who is also a doctor for the
national team and who arrived Tuesday at the team's headquarters in
the hills above this Mediterranean resort.
	   ``I don't think it's very serious and the whole atmosphere is
making me feel better already,'' Helmer said. ``It's a little
setback but I already feel more positive.''
	   The Germans are living at the four-star Mas d'Artigny, near
Saint-Paul-de-Vence, and the players have been praising the
secluded, wooded compound.
	   ``Our physiotherapists have a whole house to themselves,''
Helmer said.
	   After Tuesday's training, Vogts gave his players off until 11
a.m. Wednesday. The wives and girlfriends of the players are living
in hotels in the area.
	   (ns-sl)
</TEXT>
