<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Klinsmann's Role,0492 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Klinsmann not guaranteed but likely to start
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NESHA STARCEVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NICE, France (AP) _ Juergen Klinsmann is the captain of the
German team with 103 caps. This doesn't guarantee him a place in
the starting lineup, however, and Klinsmann is feeling the heat.
	   Perhaps never before has Germany come to a World Cup with four
strikers who can all make an equal claim on a place in the starting
11.
	   ``It's a healthy competition, we try very hard in practice and
we take it very seriously,'' Klinsmann said. ``We respect each
other a lot, but all of us want to show that we belong.''
	   Besides Klinsmann, there is Oliver Bierhoff, who topped the
Italian Serie A with 27 goals. Ulf Kirsten led the Bundesliga with
22, followed by Olaf Marschall, who notched 21 in 24 league
matches.
	   Compared to such feats, Klinsmann had a quiet season. He moved
in mid-season from Sampdoria Genoa to his former London club
Tottenham, and was kept on the sidelines with ankle and jaw
injuries that also forced him to miss several national team games.
	   But the 33-year-old German star bounced back strongly in the
late stage of the season, scoring four goals in one game to rescue
Tottenham from relegation.
	   His club future is uncertain. Klinsmann is leaving Tottenham but
has no new club. Reports have surfaced that he may be lured to
Major League Soccer in the United States. Klinsmann, a
well-traveled player whose wife is American, has said he would like
to play about two more years at club level.
	   His international career, however, will be over after this World
Cup, his third. Klinsmann was in the 1990 team in Italy that won
Germany's third World Cup title.
	   And Klinsmann wants to go out with a bang. Before that, he had
to convince Berti Vogts, Germany's coach, that he was still the
formidable striker that had produced 44 goals for the national
team.
	   In April, Klinsmann was benched for Germany's warmup game
against Nigeria, something that would have been unthinkable a year
ago.
	   Klinsmann did not react like a hurt diva. Instead, he earned
public praise from Vogts for his hard work in practice.
	   Vogts has a lot of loyalty for his long-serving players, but
Klinsmann still had to work his way back to the front.
	   In a scrimmage game against a local team Monday, Klinsmann
paired with Bierhoff. The same has been happening in practice,
prompting reporters to conclude that Klinsmann and Bierhoff will be
Germany's strikers against the United States in Paris on June 15.
	   But Klinsmann wasn't convinced. ``I don't think it's connected
to the starting lineup against the Americans,'' he said.
	   With the German team in headquartered near Nice, Klinsmann is on
familiar ground, having spent two seasons in nearby Monaco on the
Riviera between 1992 and 1994.
	   (ns-jw)
</TEXT>
