<SLUG> YOUTH-FORUM-DELEGATES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Youth forum delegates feted, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Youth forum delegates feted, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Rosnazura IdrusASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PAN Commonwealth Youth Forum delegates who were in Kuala Lumpur
last month were treated to a dinner at the Concorde Hotel.
	   Hosted by Youth and Sports Ministry Parliamentary Secretary
Datuk Shahrizat Abdul Jalil, the dinner saw the presence of some 40
delegates from 35 Commonwealth countries.
	   The dinner also saw the launch of Council for Asean Youth
Co-operation president Mustaffa Kamil Ayub's book entitled Youth
Renaissance. Mustaffa was also the forum's organising committee
chairman.
	   Among local youth leaders present were Asian Youth Council
secretary- general Datuk Fuad Hassan, Malaysian Youth Council
president Datuk Suhaimi Ibrahim and Young Malaysians Movement
national president Lim Joo Kiat.
	   Former MBM president Hassan Malek, who is also Juaseh State
Assemblyman, and former treasurer Sri Ram were also present.
	   Commonwealth Secretariat desk officer for NGOs, Sport and
Development and Ireland Terence R. Dormer, Sri Lanka's Ministry of
Sports and Rural Development permanent secretary Dr R.M.K.
Ratnayaka and Sri Lanka National Youth Services Council
director-general Dr Sunil Jayantha Nawaratne were also there.
	   Others included Commonwealth Youth Programme Caribbean Centre
regional director Dr Ivan Henry, CYP Africa Centre regional
director Dr Richard Mkandawire, Commonwealth Secretariat (London)
chief programme officer Janey Parris and Pan Commonwealth London
senior project officer Cristal de Saldanha.
	   Also seen were Botswana National Youth Council executive
director Mpho B.W. Moruakgomo, David Jones from British Youth
Council, Ntsekhe Ntsekhe from Lesotho and C. Matonga from Malawi.
	   
</TEXT>
