<SLUG> BC-Sports-Auto Racing-Acropolis Rally, 1st Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Colin McRae wins Acropolis Rally
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: UPDATES with number of cars finishing, ADDS details &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ Coming from behind, British driver Colin
McRae, driving a Subaru Impreza, won the 45th Acropolis Rally
Tuesday.
	   McRae beat France's Didier Auriol by 20 seconds in the last
stages, after Auriol, in his Toyota Corolla, had led the second day
of the three-day rally.
	   McRae, who won the gruelling Acropolis Rally in 1996, crossed
the finish line in 4 hours, 26 minutes and 31 seconds, against
Auriol's 4:26.51.
	   Auriol, a 1992 Acropolis Rally winner, won the first two of the
five scheduled special stages Tuesday. But he lost time in the
others following engine problems, giving McRae the chance to regain
lost ground.
	   Finnish driver Juha Kankkunen in a Ford Escort WRC came in third
in 4:27.15.
	   The victory set McRae atop the world driving championships
standings with 36 points. He replaced Spain's Carlos Sainz, who
dropped to second place with 31 points.
	   Of the 103 cars that started out from the foot of the Athens
Acropolis hill on Sunday, 59 managed to complete the rally's total
distance of 1,036 kilometers (647 miles) through Greece's best and
worst roads.
	   Unlike previous races, this year's rally ended in the western
town of Delphi. The ancient Greeks considered Delphi to be the
center of the world. It was also the site of the oracle that
ancient Greeks consulted for prophesies of the future.
	   Japan's Subaru took the lead in the manufacturer's standings
with 49 points, followed by Toyota with 47 and Mitsubishi with 45.
Ford of Britain was 4th with 33 points.
 &UR; kc
</TEXT>
