<HEADLINE>
Training women counsellors, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Training women counsellors, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   TWENTY-ONE female employees from eight companies in the Ulu
Klang Industrial Zone, Selangor received their certificates
recently after completing a five-day training programme on
counselling women workers.
	   Launched by National Unity and Social Development Minister Datin
Paduka Zaleha Ismail at the De Palma Hotel in Ampang, the programme
was organised by the Gombak district Women's Welfare Department of
the Ministry and sponsored by the companies.
	   The participating companies were Harris Advanced Technology,
Malaysia Transformer, Pernec, Royal Selangor Pewter, Sapura,
ShinEtsu, SmithKline Beecham and Texas Instruments.
	   The programme was aimed at creating a pool of counsellors to
assist and guide women factory workers to overcome economic,
emotional, family, work or social problems they might face and help
improve their welfare and quality of life.
	   Besides helping women workers in their place of employment, the
21 counsellors will provide counselling services to the local
community in the State at the Selangor Women's Counselling Centre.
	   The Ulu Klang Industrial Zone also boasts of the first private
sector single parents club in the country which was launched by
Harris Advanced Technology last year.
	   Its aim is to help members recognise, cope with and overcome the
economic, emotional, family, work and social problems working
single parents often face.
	   Apart from promoting women's welfare, UKIZ companies have also
been active in fostering esprit de corps among their workers by
organising the Workers' Run on May 1 and an inter-company badminton
competition hosted by Malaysia Transformers.
	   
</TEXT>
