<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Finland-Earns-Kemira </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chemicals group's profit up 6 percent to dlrs 74 million
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HELSINKI, Finland (AP) _ Finland's leading fertilizer and
chemicals company, Kemira, increased its four-month pretax profit
to 401 million markkaa (dlrs 74 million), up from 377 million
markkaa during the same period in 1997.
	   Net sales from January to April grew slightly to 5.3 billion
markkaa (dlrs 1 billion), from 5.1 billion markkaa for the same
period last year, Kemira said Tuesday.
	   Sales in the core businesses of chemicals and pigments grew
strongly, the company said. However, a fall in fertilizer prices
caused a sharp drop in operating profit of the group's largest
unit, Kemira Agro, to 174 million markkaa (dlrs 32 million) from
303 million markkaa in 1997.
	   Kemira group predicted that strong sales will continue in the
pigments and chemicals sectors, while the agro unit's performance
was expected to fall below last year's level.
	   ``Net financing expenses are expected to be roughly the same as
last year,'' the company said. ``Net income for the group is
expected to be at last year's record level.''
	   In 1997, Kemira had a record pretax profit of 864 million markka
(dlrs 160 million), with net sales of 14.4 billion markkaa (dlrs
2.6 billion).
	   In January, Kemira announced it had extended a major deal with
Rhone Poulenc Agro of France to manufacture corn herbicides worth 1
billion markkaa (dlrs 185 million).
	   Kemira also makes pharmaceuticals. It is 54-percent state-owned,
and employs 10,400 people in 25 countries.
	   (mhh-jh)
</TEXT>
