w1184 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SwissBanks-Nazis     06-09 0293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Swiss Banks-Nazis </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Volcker-led panel names banks under dormant accounts audit
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BASEL, Switzerland (AP) _ A U.S.-led panel looking for
Holocaust-era assets in Swiss banks said Tuesday it had chosen 27
banks to be examined thoroughly for any remaining dormant accounts.
	   Included are the three largest Swiss banks and 24 state and
private banks, said the panel headed by former U.S. Federal Reserve
chief Paul Volcker.
	   Some 200 auditors from four international firms have been
assigned to the latest phase of the search, a statement said.
	   The selection of the banks was ``based on size, geographic
location and the desire for representation of different types of
banks,'' the statement added.
	   The search was organized after complaints from Jewish
organizations that, more than 50 years after World War II, the
banks were still hiding assets deposited by Jews who were then
killed by the Nazis.
	   The panel stressed that the investigation would be
time-consuming because of the large quantity and incomplete nature
of the banks' wartime and prewar records.
	   But investigations at the smaller banks are expected to finish
faster ``with new banks added as the first audits are completed.''
	   The committee, charged with looking at any unclaimed possession
from the Nazi period, is one of a number of Swiss measures to
investigate and atone for any wrongdoing during World War II.
	   In addition, the three biggest banks _ Credit Suisse, Swiss Bank
Corp. and Union Bank of Switzerland _ are negotiating with Jewish
organizations and lawyers for class-action claimants on a global
settlement of claims by Holocaust victims. The settlement
reportedly could exceed dlrs 1 billion.
 &UR; (gm-agh)
</TEXT>
