<BODY>
<SLUG> LOCAL-VOLUNTEERS-SOUGHT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Local volunteers sought for girl's home, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Local volunteers sought for girl's home, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Rosnazura IdrusASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SHELTER Four Home for girls in Kajang not only need cash and
other donations, but also local volunteers.
	   To date, of the six volunteers who give the girls tuition on
school subjects and other skills, only one is local.
	   The rest are foreigners who will only be in the country for a
short while.
	   The home's ``mom'', Rajeswari George, said at the home's
fund-raising and awareness night recently, that the home needed
locals to give a helping hand.
	   After all, the 11 girls at the home, who were victims of abuse
and neglect, are also locals.
	   ``Who else if not for caring Malaysians, could the girls depend
on. The foreigners are volunteering their service, but they will
not stay in this country forever,'' she said.
	   Sadly, not many people turned up at the awareness night held at
the World Tennis Centre in Country Heights, Kajang, and those
present were mostly expatriates.
	   One of the volunteers, Mary Ann Schuerger, who teaches the girls
English, said she would probably go back to the United States in
September when her husband's contract with the KLIA project is
completed.
	   Schuerger, who was introduced to the home by a German social
worker by the name Dorethia, became attached to the girls whom she
knew about a year ago.
	   She was also seen busy attending to the guests that night,
answering their questions in the hope that more would come forward
to help and that someone would take her place when she leaves the
country.
	   Guests were given a briefing on what Shelter Four was all about,
the girls and their needs. Guests were even ``taken'' to the home
and introduced to all the 11 girls via a video presentation.
	   A friend of Shelter Four, artist Victor Chin, also nated four of
his painting prints of common flowers from his garden to be sold
that night.
	   ``I hope that this will encourage others to help Shelter Four in
whatever way they can,'' he said.
	   His association with Shelter Four goes back for about two years
when he went for lunch with Rajeswari and the girls.
	   Since then, he and his wife had organised frequent lunches for
the girls.
	   That night, the home had sales of Sarawak black pepper and
paintings by Washington Fine Arts, which donated 70 per cent of the
proceeds to the home.
	   Shelter Four which caters for abused and neglected teenage girls
was started in Oct 1996. It is the latest addition to the Shelter
Homes.
	   Rajeswari said apart from donating money, the public could also
help by paying the monthly electricity, water and telephone bills,
food, school bus fare, toiletries and pocket money for the girls.
	   ``The public can also pay for the girls' school projects
expenditure or be a volunteer to teach them school subjects or any
skills,'' she said.
	   Those interested can contact Rajeswari at 03-8345871.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
