</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Parliament </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ukrainian parliament fails to elect speaker _ again
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ Ukraine's new Communist-dominated
parliament failed again Tuesday to elect a speaker _ the sixth time
a vote was declared invalid.
	   As during the five previous attempts, several parliamentary
factions refused to take part, and the vote count was too low to be
valid.
	   Dozens have been nominated for the post. Of the two who competed
Tuesday, former parliament speaker Olexander Moroz, a socialist,
was far ahead of his rival, Olexander Pukhkal of the centrist
Hromada movement.
	   Various factions have proposed candidates for the post since the
new Verkhovna Rada, elected in March, started its work last month.
	   But the votes have been blocked by three centrist opposition
groups and the pro-government faction. These factions demand that
the entire parliament leadership be elected at once _ an idea
rejected by other lawmakers.
	   The infighting has been condemned as a political farce by the
Ukrainian media, which devised a special term _ ``speakeriade'' _
to describe it.
	   On Tuesday, newspapers said President Leonid Kuchma planned to
issue an appeal to parliament over its inability to get down to
business. Communists, a key force opposing Kuchma's attempts at
market reforms, hold 125 of the 450 seats in Verkhovna Rada.
	   (sms/mr) 	   
</TEXT>
