<SLUG> BC-Pakistan-Bhutto,0283 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bhutto files suit against Pakistan government
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ZAHID HUSSAIN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) _ Former Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto
filed a suit against the Pakistan government Tuesday to defend her
``dignity and respect,'' she said.
	   Ms. Bhutto said the Pakistan government fed Swiss authorities
``false statements,'' which resulted in that government freezing
her bank accounts, as well as those of her husband, Asif Ali
Zardari and her mother.
	   It wasn't immediately clear what damages Ms. Bhutto was seeking.
	   As a result of information received from the Pakistan
government, the Swiss authorities also have launched an
investigation into business dealings between Ms. Bhutto and Swiss
companies.
	   Ms. Bhutto's government was dismissed from power in November
1996 on charges of rampant corruption and economic mismanagement.
	   Her husband is in jail on charges of masterminding the shooting
death of Ms. Bhutto's estranged brother. Murtaza Bhutto was killed
barely three months before her government was dismissed.
	   In a news conference after filing the suit in the Sindh High
Court in her hometown of Karachi, Ms. Bhutto said the information
given to the Swiss authorities has done irreparable damage to her
reputation.
	   Ms. Bhutto also said the Pakistani government breached Pakistani
law when it gave the Swiss authorities the ``misstatements and
false statements''.
	   ``I have gone to the court to defend my dignity and respect,''
Ms. Bhutto told reporters.
	   The government alleges Ms. Bhutto and her husband robbed the
exchequer of millions of dollars, a charge she vehemently denies. 	   
</TEXT>
