<HEADLINE>
Tokyo: Down, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Tokyo: Down, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SHARE prices closed 0.2 per cent lower yesterday as the yen
broke through the 140-yen support to a seven-year low against the
US dollar, brokers said.
	   Light selling emerged at the outset due to the yen's tumble, but
this proved to be short-lived with the yen decline to this level
largely expected and public funds stepping into the market, dealers
said.
	   ``I think public funds were modest buyers because the Nikkei 225
index rebounded every time it fell by about 30 points,'' a Yamatane
Securities broker said.
	   The key Nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange fell 28.72 points to end at 15,294.71.
	   The Topix index of all issues on the first section dropped 3.58
points to 1,198.36.
	   The yen's drop sidelined buyers and left share prices exposed to
light selling, brokers said.
	   Turnover on the major board declined to 250 million shares from
Friday's 290.8 million shares.
	   At 3pm, the dollar was trading at 140.62-65 yen, after hitting a
seven- year high of 140.73 yen in early trade.
	   Tokyo dealers said the final straw was news that a meeting of
Deputy Finance Ministers from the Group of Seven industrialised
nations this week would not focus on the yen's weakness.
	   The main market focus was on select stocks such as Nikko
Securities and Nissan, which have been the subject of speculative
activity, dealers said.
	   Nissan gained six yen to 411, bought on news it was negotiating
with Car Max for a US franchise, which would give it additional
distribution in the US market, brokers said.
	   Turnover in Nikko Securities, Japan's third largest securities
firm, shot up after it announced last week a tie-up with US
financial services giant Travelers Group.
	   Nikko closed up 51 yen at 600, gaining a sharp 9.3 per cent,
with trading turning increasingly speculative, brokers said.
	   
</TEXT>
