<SLUG> DAP-MEN-OBJECT-TO-HEARIN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAP men object to hearing of their case by two, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
DAP men object to hearing of their case by two, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Alex ChoongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PETALING JAYA, Mon. - The three DAP leaders who have been
suspended and removed from their positions in the party's central
executive committee today objected to two members of the party's
disciplinary committee hearing their case.
	   They said the two members - State Assemblyman for Bukit Gasing
Teng Chang Kim and assistant organising secretary Ronnie Liew -
should not be in the panel as they were the ``judge, jury and
prosecutor'' in the case.
	   Their objection came on a day when Selangor DAP chairman Chua
Kow Eng joined in the chorus for a ``fair hearing'', urging the
party's leadership to stop hurling accusations against the three
(see story on P2).
	   ``Teng and Liew have taken part in the debate and voted in
favour of the resolution to remove and suspend us,'' said Wee Choo
Keong, who was removed as party national publicity secretary.
	   At a joint Press conference with suspended national
vice-chairman Liew Ah Kim and treasurer Fung Ket Wing, Wee said
Teng and Liew were also responsible for referring them to the
disciplinary committee for investigation.
	   Teng, Wee said, had spoken very vociferously against the three
of them during the debate.
	   ``Therefore, Teng and Liew have to disqualify themselves from
hearing our case,'' he said.
	   Wee said they also regretted that secretary-general Lim Kit
Siang had not responded to their request for an independent and
impartial committee to investigate the allegations against them.
	   On a personal issue, Wee also cautioned Kit Siang to stop making
defamatory statements against him.
	   ``He has alleged that I leaked information on these issues to a
certain foreign news network. I categorically deny this,'' he said.
	   Wee said Kit Siang had also differentiated the case involving
his son Lim Guan Eng with the one he (Wee) faced as one between a
criminal and civil case.
	   Wee said that in Guan Eng's case, he was sentenced to a jail
term and as a result would lose his Member of Parliament position
whereas he (Wee) was fined and disqualified by the Election Court
judge.
	   ``Why is it that there was no campaign launched by the party to
show the alleged injustice and undemocractic removal of an elected
MP?'' he asked.
	   Wee also recalled the occasion when together with his mother, he
had asked Kit Siang for assistance to post a RM100,000 court bail.
	   ``Kit Siang told us that the party had no money,'' he said,
adding that he was prepared to ask his mother to testify to the
event.
	   
</TEXT>
