<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-European Court-Britain-Nuclear Tests </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
British nuclear test veterans lose European court case
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   STRASBOURG, France (AP) _ Two Scottish ex-servicemen who say
their health was ruined by being ordered to attend nuclear bomb
tests in the 1950s lost their case Tuesday in the European Court of
Human Rights.
	   The ruling be a blow to thousands of former military and
civilian workers who allege they were exposed to radiation during
the British tests blasts in the Pacific. Many were hoping a
positive result would open the way to big compensation payments.
	   Edward Egan, 59, and Kenneth McGinley, 60, went to the European
rights court to claiming the Ministry of Defense covered up
documents which could have won them a compensation settlement or a
pension.
	   But a panel of nine judges ruled there had been no violation of
the European Human Rights Convention in regard to cover-up
allegations. The court further ruled it had no jurisdiction to
consider complaints over the alleged lack of protection offered
during the tests.
	   Egan serving in the Royal Navy and McGinley serving with the
British army witnessed the explosion of an eight-megaton nuclear
bomb during tests on Christmas Island in 1957.
	   They say servicemen were ordered to line up in the open, with no
protection against the blast, which they said was no more than 20
miles away.
	   Veterans of the blasts have formed the British Nuclear Tests
Veterans Association to fight their case. They allege they were
deliberately exposed to radiation to see how their bodies would
react.
	   Successive British governments have said the men were not
exposed to harmful levels of radiation because they were too far
from the center of the explosion.
	   McGinley says the effects of the explosion made him sterile and
caused arthritis and kidney and skin problems. Egan blames the
blast for his osteoporosis, lung failure and a heart attack.
	   ``It is very disappointing to hear this result today,'' Egan
told the Press Association, Britain's domestic news agency. ``It is
not only the end of the road for me, it is the end of the road for
thousands of other people who were hoping this would set a
precedent.''
 &UR; (pa)
</TEXT>
