<HEADER>
w1220 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EU-Summitletter     06-09 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-Summit letter </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU head office: Kohl, Chirac criticism unfair; vows written reply
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ The EU head office denied Tuesday it
meddled unnecessarily in the lives of Europeans and said comments
to that effect by French President Jacques Chirac and German
Chancellor Helmut Kohl were unfounded.
	   EU spokesman Thierry Daman said there ``will be a written
reply'' telling them the European Commission is not a power-hungry
outfit issuing edicts affecting 370 million EU nationals.
	   Kohl and Chirac insinuated that in a letter this week to British
Prime Minister Tony Blair.
	   They asked him to use next week's EU summit in Cardiff to
correct ``questionable developments (such as) a tendency of some
institutions to distance themselves from citizens.''
	   The EU must not replace national, regional and local
governments, they said. ``The aim of a European policy has never
been ... to build a central EU state.''
	   Germany and France believe it is urgent to reform the European
Commission, which runs the EU's day-to-day affairs, and Council of
Ministers, the EU decision-making body.
	   France has long been wary of the European Commission, which runs
the EU's day to day affairs, exceeding its powers. And Kohl was
upset recently by a EU Court of Justice ruling on reclaiming
medical costs incurred abroad.
	   The Kohl-Chirac letter has upset small EU states, such as the
Netherlands and Belgium, which traditionally see a powerful,
assertive European Commission as an ally in containing the
aspirations of big neighbors such as Germany and France.
	   Dutch Foreign Minister Hans van Mierlo said Kohl and Chirac made
``gratuitous criticisms'' and complained about their letter's
vagueness.
	   Last year, the 15 EU governments failed to reform EU
institutions, partly because Kohl resisted more decision-making by
majority voting.
	   The EU governments also failed to reform the European Commission
or re-allocate votes for big and small countries _ issues that must
be settled before a dozen newcomers join in the years ahead.
	   Daman said European Commission President Jacques Santer ``shares
the approach'' of Kohl and Chirac and is studying how the EU can
legislate less.
	   He said sometimes it has no choice as in the case of recent
legislation on sanitary conditions for animals in zoos.
	   The Commission wanted to stay away from that but EU governments
asked for a directive on hygiene conditions in EU zoos.
	   The Kohl-Chirac letter seemed motivated by a need for
reconciliation after their heated dispute at a May 2 summit over
the leadership of the European Central Bank, diplomats said.
	   The EU reform debate is closely linked to a discussion among EU
governments on new ways to fund the union.
	   Proposals call for cutbacks in agriculture spending and more
money for poor regions without raising EU membership fees. After
one year of debate, no perceptible progress has been made.
 &UR; (rw)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-EU-Summit letter; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
