<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Uncertain Spaniards,0436 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Ferrer's transfer ends uncertainty for at least one
</HEADLINE>
Spanish player &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Sports-Soccer-Chelsea-Ferrer &QL; 
 &UR; By CIARAN GILES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CHANTILLY, France _ Albert Ferrer's transfer to Chelsea has
sorted out his problems. But the club future of four other key
Spanish world cup players is still in the air and niggling away at
the squad's morale.
	   Ferrer's transfer came less than two weeks after he and fellow
internationals Juan Pizzi and Guillermo Amor were told abruptly by
FC Barcelona's Dutch coach Louis Van Gaal that he had no use for
them.
	   Not known for his sensitivity or tact, Van Gaal warned the
players that ``if they choose to stay out their contracts with
Barcelona they will have a terrible time.''
	   Meanwhile, Barcelona' emblematic defender and the Spanish side's
main man at the back, Miguel Angel Nadal, has spent more time on
the bench than on the pitch with Van Gaal and knows his remaining
days at the club are few.
	   Last month also saw the arrival of former Italian team coach
Arrigo Sacchi at Atletico de Madrid and rumors immediately spread
that popular striker Kiko Narvaez and long-time keeper Paco Molina
are out.
	   The sudden new-found uncertainty and the poor timing of the
reports, especially Van Gaal's comments, dealt a severe blow to the
Spanish squad and angered Clemente given that they came just prior
to France.
	   In one moving moment, midfielder Amor, one of the most liked
players in Spanish soccer, broke into tears before reporters
recently saying neither Barcelona nor Van Gaal had a right to just
dump him after nearly 19 years of service.
	   On Tuesday, Ferrer said he hoped ``to demonstrate with Chelsea
that I am still able to play at top level soccer.''
	   Curiously, barring Molina, who has only played once for Spain,
the players are all Clemente pets and have rarely been benched
since the Basque coach took over the national team in 1992.
	   Spanish press reports described them as those Van Gaal and
Sacchi may not want, but Clemente will never abandon.
	   Known for his fierce loyalty to his crew, Clemente has been
working hard to keep up a positive atmosphere at the Chantilly camp
and on Monday called on players and press to forget the club
problems.
	   Amor agreed.
	   ``I'm here trying to concentrate on winning the World Cup and
all the press wants to talk about are my problems with Barcelona,''
he said. ``I know nothing about my future and don't want to think
about it until after France.''
	   (cg-sl)
</TEXT>
