<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Czar's Burial </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian Orthodox patriarch will not participate in czar's burial
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The leader of the Russian Orthodox Church will not
participate in the burial ceremony for the country's last czar, the
church's Holy Synod ruled Tuesday.
	   The church has been skeptical about next month's ceremony,
saying that some believers still have doubts about the identity of
bones recovered from a pit in the Ural Mountains city of
Yekaterinburg in 1991.
	   The Synod's decision, reported by the Interfax news agency,
means it will be up to local church officials in St. Petersburg to
determine who will officiate at the burial in the Peter and Paul
Fortress.
	   Russian media have said that President Boris Yeltsin will not
take part unless Patriarch Alexy II does.
	   The nine skeletons recovered in Yekaterinburg have been examined
by genetics labs in Russia, Britain and the United States and
identified as those of Czar Nicholas II, his wife, three children
and four servants.
	   After six years of deliberations, a government commission
declared the remains authentic earlier this year and scheduled a
funeral for July 17, the 80th anniversary of the family's execution
by a Bolshevik firing squad. Hundreds of foreign representatives,
including many royals, have been invited to attend.
	   The ceremony will be held in the Peter and Paul Cathedral, the
traditional burial site of the Romanovs, who ruled Russia for 300
years and were related through intermarriage to many other royal
families in Europe.
	   The church has started proceedings to consider sainthood for the
royal family, which would make their bones holy relics.
	   The church has previously suggested that the bones, still held
in a police morgue, be interred in a temporary tomb until all
doubts about their identity have been removed.
	   (ad/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
