<HEADLINE>
Nigerian dissident: new military leader `more of the same'
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo NY189 &QL; 
 &UR; By HILARY APPELMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ The succession of a new military leader in
Nigeria is ``not a step forward,'' exiled playwright and dissident
Wole Soyinka said Tuesday.
	   In Jerusalem, where he was lecturing at Hebrew University,
Soyinka said the appointment of Maj. Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar
``augurs very badly for Nigeria,'' because it means the military
still believes it is in control of the country's fate.
	   ``This is just more of the same thing _ it's just a change of
baton,'' he said.
	   Abubakar was sworn in Tuesday as Nigeria's head of state one day
after Gen. Sani Abacha died of a heart attack. Abacha, 54, ruled
Nigeria for five years with an iron fist. In the final months of
his life, he appeared to be moving away from his pledge to hand
power over to an elected civilian government.
	   Soyinka said he knew little about Abubakar himself, but said he
was not hearing any encouraging signs.
	   ``I'm willing to give Abubakar a couple of days to listen to
what he actually has to say,'' he said. ``But I want to say from
the outset _ and I speak for the majority of the Nigerian people _
that they're sick and tired of the military continuing to believe
that they have the right to succeed.
	   Soyinka, winner of the 1986 Nobel Prize for literature, repeated
his call for the international community to put pressure on
Nigeria, and urged World Cup spectators to show disapproval of the
Nigerian regime _ by booing the Nigerian flag, for example.
	   If Abubakar tries to continue in Abacha's path, he said, it
spells disaster for Nigeria.
	   ``I'm afraid that if the military does not bow to the will of
the people, armed insurrection becomes inevitable,'' he said. ``The
signs of it are already there.''
	   ``If any future Nigerian leader acts in any manner that can be
held remotely parallel to Abacha's depravity, I swear to you, that
is the end of Nigeria,'' he added, speaking slowly and emphasizing
each word. ``The nation will not hold.''
	   Asked if he had a message for the Nigerian people, Soyinka, who
fled his country in 1994, said: ``Don't let down your guard. The
battle isn't over yet.'' 	   
</TEXT>
