<SLUG> BC-Kenya-Violence,HFR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLD FOR RELEASE until 0001GMT, June 10; embargoed by source
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Amnesty urges Kenyan government to end spiral of violence &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ Amnesty International urged President
Daniel arap Moi's government Wednesday to end a spiral of violence
in Kenya and to prosecute its perpetrators.
	   The London-based human rights organization said in a report that
more than 120 people have been killed, thousands displaced and
hundreds of homes destroyed in Moi's own Rift Valley province since
the violence erupted early this year.
	   The violence mostly pitted Moi's Kalenjin group against the
Kikuyu, Kenya's largest tribe. It came on the heels of December
general elections in which Moi, 74, who had governed Kenya for 19
years, won his fifth and, constitutionally, his last five-year
term.
	   Moi draws most of his support from the Kalenjin, while the
Kikuyu generally support the opposition.
	   The violence is similar to clashes before and after the 1992
general elections in which an estimated 1,500 people were killed
and hundreds of thousands were forced to flee their homes.
	   The report said the government's failure to act to stem the
violence forced citizens to defend themselves this time.
	   ``For the first time, members of the Kikuyu community retaliated
to the attacks in an organized fashion, following the failure of
security forces to act,'' the report said.
	   It urged the international community to increase pressure on
Moi's government to honor its national and international legal
obligations on human rights.
	   The report also urged Kenyan leaders to refrain from making
inflammatory statements that incite tribes against each other.
	   This was an apparent reference to violence among Kelenjin
sub-tribes in northwestern Kenya. They have clashed in recent weeks
after a local member of parliament urged his Pokot people to defend
their rights against the Marakwet.
	   Kenyan politicians, including members of Moi's ruling Kenya
African National Union party, human rights groups and the Law
Society of Kenya have urged the government to prosecute Francis
Lotodo, a Cabinet minister, for inciting the Pokots against the
Marakwet.
	   Since politically motivated ethnic violence erupted last August
at the Indian Ocean coast _ the heart of Kenya's tourist trade _
there have been ethnic clashes in various parts of the country.
	   The violence is blamed for the downward spiral in the tourism
industry, which had been the single most important source of
foreign currency earnins for the East African nation.
	   Government officials could not be reached for comment on the
report. But in the past, they have dismissed Amnesty's criticism as
interference in Kenya's internal affairs.
	    &UR; (HO-cm)	   
</TEXT>
