<SLUG> FINDING-WAYS-TO-UP sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Finding ways to up revenue is Osu's priority, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Finding ways to up revenue is Osu's priority, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KOTA KINABALU, Mon. - Identifying new sources of revenue to
strengthen the State's financial position is the priority of newly
appointed Deputy Chief Minister and Finance Minister Datuk Osu
Sukam.
	   Osu said although the State Government had sufficient funds to
implement projects under the 1998 State Budget, there was a need
further improve its finances.
	   ``I have directed officers in the Finance Ministry to look for
new sources of revenue to boost the State's financial position,''
he told a Press conference at the Finance Ministry today.
	   Earlier, Osu was sworn in as a member of the State Cabinet
before Yang di-Pertua Negeri Tun Sakaran Dandai at Istana Negeri,
witnessed by High Court Judge Datuk Charles Ho.
	   Also present were Sakaran's wife Toh Puan Rukaiyah Datuk
Panglima Abdullah, Chief Minister Tan Sri Bernard Dompok, State
Assembly Speaker Datuk Hassan Alban Sandukong and State Cabinet
ministers.
	   Osu, 49, replaced Datuk Abdul Ghapur Salleh, who declined to be
re- appointed.
	   Later, Osu was briefed by the ministry's permanent secretary
Datuk S.
	   Abdillah Hassan and other senior officers of the ministry about
the State's financial position.
	   ``I am confident that despite the current economic downturn we
will still be able to meet the aspirations of the people,'' he
said.
	   He also said the listing of the Sabah Land Development Board on
the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange, which is expected to bring a
revenue of RM500 million to the State, would take place this year.
	   Osu, who resigned as Federal Minister of Land and Co-operative
Development to take up the State posting, said one way to enhance
State revenue was to improve the collection of water bills.
	   ``We may have to introduce a new mechanism to improve the
collection of water bills.''
	   He also said priority would be given to the implementation of
rural development projects.
	   
</TEXT>
