<SLUG> BC-Moldova-Prostitution </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Moldova makes prostitution a crime
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KISHINEV, Moldova (AP) _ Parliament passed a law Tuesday making
prostitution a crime in Moldova and prohibiting advertisements for
what has become a growing problem in the former Soviet republic.
	   People convicted of prostitution will face three to seven years
in prison or a fine of 3,000 lei (almost dlrs 630) under the new
law.
	   Lawmaker Alexandru Muravschi said growing poverty in Moldova is
driving women to sell their bodies for as little as a bottle of
alcohol or a chocolate bar. Until now, prostitution has not been a
crime in the country.
	   Muravschi said it will be difficult to enforce the law. He noted
that some newspaper and television ads do not specifically offer
prostitutes, but promote massage parlors where prostitutes work.
	   Advertisers who violate the law will also be subject to prison
terms of three to seven years.
	   (str/ma/amb) 	   
</TEXT>
