<SLUG> RESTORE-CONFIDENCE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`We'll step up efforts to restore confidence', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`We'll step up efforts to restore confidence', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Sharif HaronASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MERSING, Mon. - Deputy Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim
said the Government would continue to step up efforts to restore
confidence in the economy among local and foreign investors.
	   He said this would include providing more funds - not to protect
the interests of only selected companies or certain individuals -
but to be mobilised in a manner that benefited everyone, including
the low-income group.
	   He also said that while Malaysia was clamouring for reforms and
greater transparency of the international financial system, the
country should at the same time overcome its domestic weaknesses
and avoid the pitfalls experienced by others which had to resort to
the International Monetary Fund.
	   He said this when opening the third Johor Umno Convention at the
Sibu Island Resort on Sibu island, off Mersing.
	   Anwar, who is also Finance Minister, noted that not all of the
country's financial institutions were being responsible, saying
that some had given out loans at too fast a rate, including to
non-productive sectors like property.
	   There were also others which had ceased disbursing loans and did
not do enough for the Bumiputera lot.
	   ``It does not mean that we protect the attitude of financial
instutions... I protect transparency but there should be no
political inteference in the giving of loans,'' he added.
``Secondly, we must take steps to restore the confidence of local
and foreign investors (in our economy).''
	   He said if it was necessary to ensure the financial institutions
were strong, the Government would ensure just that although it
might mean causing difficulties to some parties.
	   He added that not only the big businesses were facing problems
but the rural people had also not been spared because of rising
prices, for example.
	   Anwar said while calling for transparency and reforms of the
international financial system, the country should also check its
domestic weaknesses, including corporate governance.
	   He said the country should not deny the fact that it was facing
economic problems. These problems, he said, were caused by external
factors as well as a number of weaknesses within.
	   He said if the country did not accept that domestic weaknesses
also needed to be corrected, ``we will invite an even bigger
catastrophe''.
	   Anwar also said he did not stop companies from restructuring but
if such an exercise was meant to safeguard the interests of a few,
then the companies would bring more problems to the economy.
	   ``Also, we should take steps to contain inflation and stabilise
the ringgit.''
	   Anwar said the economic system in the country should defend the
good policies, so as not to deviate from the principle of justice
to be fair to all, including the rural poor.
	   On Umno, he said the party must be prepared to demand that
weaknesses in the domestic financial and other systems be overcome.
	   In this context, he said transparency, fair distribution of
wealth and the spirit of musyawarah (consultation) were consistent
with the party's struggles.
	   Thus, he said, if within Umno, democracy and the spirit of
consensus were neglected, if transparency did not exist,
opportunities were monopolised (by certain individuals) and bribery
left rampant, then the party's very existence would be questioned.
	   
</TEXT>
