<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-World Labor-Union Repression, 1st Ld-Writethru,0425 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Study condemns China, Colombia for union repression
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with U.S., Indian comment on child labor. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ Colombia and China were singled out for criticism
over abuses of labor union rights in a report published Tuesday to
coincide with a United Nations labor conference.
	   Worldwide, 299 activists were murdered last year, the 142-page
International Confederation of Free Trade Unions report said.
	   Highlighting 156 killings of union leaders and members in
Colombia, the report complained ``the violence was rarely if ever
investigated.''
	   Although paramilitary organizations were mostly to blame,
``union activists continue to be stigmatized as enemies of the
state,'' it said.
	   It said hundreds of unionists had to leave their homes because
of death threats.
	   Deregulation of Colombian labor laws has made it ``impossible in
practice for many workers to belong to unions and to be covered by
collective agreements,'' its said.
	   In China, ``the unions in foreign-owned and joint venture
companies are largely symbolic,'' according to the Brussels-based
ICFTU, the world's biggest umbrella organization of labor unions.
	   Such unions are controlled either by the Communist Party or
plant management, its report said.
	   The report also criticized U.S. labor law for ``double standards
with respect to the rights of employers and of workers,'' claiming
that at least 1 in 10 activists campaigning to form a union is
illegally fired.
	   This year's International Labor Organization conference is
working on a declaration committing countries to work toward
collective bargaining and the elimination of forced labor.
	   It is also considering a new world convention aimed at
abolishing the most extreme forms of child labor.
	   U.S. Labor Secretary Alexis Herman told delegates she had come
``with clear instructions ... to underline the United States'
strong support for the negotiation'' of that convention.
	   India was ``happy to note'' consideration of the new convention
and its ``sequential and gradual'' approach to the child labor
problem, Indian Labor Minister Satyanarayan Jatiya said.
	   Venezuelan President Rafael Caldera warned of the dangers of
competitiveness and productivity becoming the only focus of
increasingly liberal markets.
	   Newly freed Indonesian labor leader Muchtar Pakpahan promised
support for other repressed activists.
	   ``Do not be afraid. Persevere,'' he told an ICFTU gathering. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-World Labor-Union Repression, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
