<HEADLINE>
State DAP chief urges fair hearing, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
State DAP chief urges fair hearing, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KLANG, Mon. - Selangor DAP chairman Chua Kow Eng today urged the
party's leadership to stop hurling accusations against its national
vice-chairman Liew Ah Kim, treasurer Fung Ket Wing and national
publicity secretary Wee Choo Keong but instead grant them a ``fair
hearing'' and allow them to defend themselves. He said it was not
right for the party's Central Executive Committee to accuse,
suspend and remove the three senior leaders without first asking
them to explain and defend themselves of any charge of wrongdoings.
	   ``I am shocked and very unhappy with the decision taken by the
CEC.
	   ``Surely there are avenues within the party for criticism.
	   ``I believe that free flow of criticism within the party must
not only be allowed but encouraged so that we can improve to become
a stronger and better party,'' he said adding that any organisation
needed members and leaders who dared to criticise so that it would
know whether its policy or decision was right or wrong.
	   Chua said the recent development had forced him to speak out on
the matter as he felt that he could no longer keep quiet while
accusations were publicly hurled by the party's top leadership
against the three daily when they were not given the privilege to
defend themselves.
	   He said the party's CEC had cited vague reasons in suspending
Liew and Fung and removing Wee from his post without explaining the
real cause of the actions against them.
	   This, he said, has caused confusion among grass roots members
and many have expressed their displeasure at the way the matter was
handled and the decision taken by the party's CEC.
	   The party's leadership, he said, was accountable to members and
must explain how a two-hour meeting convened by the trio, which was
cited by the CEC as the reason for their suspension and removal
last Thursday, could have caused a havoc within the party that such
drastic action had to be taken.
	   
</TEXT>
