<HEADLINE>
Suspended trio maintain innocence, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Suspended trio maintain innocence, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PETALING JAYA, Mon. - DAP secretary-general Lim Kit Siang's
offer to the three suspended DAP leaders to return to party's
mainstream on the condition that they admit to their wrongdoings
has been spurned.
	   Suspended national vice-chairman Liew Ah Kim said Lim had in his
speech in Bagan, Penang, and reported in the vernacular newspapers
that he would ``re-admit'' them if they confessed that they had
been responsible for causing disunity and harmony in the party.
	   Speaking at a joint Press conference at a hotel here, he said:
``Wee Choo Keong, who has been removed as national publicity
secretary and suspended national treasurer Fung Ket Wing and myself
maintain our innocence and will not accept Lim's condition to
return to the party''.
	   He added that to accept Lim's condition would tantamount to an
admission of guilt.
	   Instead the three gave a four-point reply to Lim: Whether Lim
and other party leaders were aware of their actions in removing and
suspending us would cause serious damage to the party's image; The
party does not belong to an individual or a small group of people
but to all party members; Our preparedness to contribute to
``real'' collective leadership; and A preparedness by the party
leaders to have reforms that will create unity, new hope, dream and
environment for members.
	   He added that they could not return to the party if the serious
allegations against them could not be cleared.
	   
</TEXT>
