<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Teachers-Strike </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Talks reportedly on track to avert South African teachers strike
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ Government negotiators and a
teachers union appeared headed for a settlement Tuesday aimed at
averting a nationwide strike.
	   The negotiators said they were to compile a draft agreement,
indicating a breakthrough had been achieved. The draft would then
be formally tabled at a meeting of the full negotiating teams, and
the parties would then consult further.
	   Tuesday marked a work slowdown, with some teachers leaving
classrooms early. It was to have escalated into a full strike by
the three teachers unions, though the timing had not been set. The
unions threatened the strike over new regulations they claim will
result in layoffs of thousands of teachers.
	   Meeting on Tuesday, the second straight day of talks, were
officials from the government and from the South African Democratic
Teachers' Union, the biggest labor group with more than 170,000
members.
	   The smaller National Professional Teachers Organization and the
South African teachers Union had also served notice they planned to
strike.
	   The unions say new regulations could result in at least 50,000
teachers losing their jobs and an increase in student-teacher
ratios. The unions want the regulations rescinded.
	   (aos)
</TEXT>
