<HEADLINE>
Hong Kong: Up, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Hong Kong: Up, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SHARE prices rose 0.2 per cent on future-led buying yesterday
despite concerns over renewed regional currency weakness triggered
by the yen's fall, dealers said.
	   ``Obviously, it's related to future-led buying, a lot has to do
with HSBC shares,'' which investors believed had fallen to
attractively low levels, said Eugene Law, research head at Lippo
Securities.
	   ``The market is still short of momentum, because of the regional
currency weakness,'' said Law. The key Hang Seng index gained 17.16
points to close at 8,586.63, after a 4.1 per cent loss in the
previous week's trade.
	   The value of turnover amounted to HK$4.548 billion, up from
Friday's HK$3.47 billion.
	   The market opened on a strong note with the key barometer
gaining 11.84 points by the end of the morning session.
	   Dealers said regional currency weakness triggered by the yen's
fall through the psychologically important 140 level against the
dollar- dominated trading in morning session with the index falling
below the 8,500 point level at one stage.
	   
</TEXT>
