</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Kazakstan-Turkic Summit </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkic-speaking countries meet in new Kazak capital
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo available &QL; 
 &UR; By BIRGIT BRAUER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ASTANA, Kazakstan (AP) _ Leaders of six Turkic-speaking
countries expressed concern Tuesday about India and Pakistan's
nuclear capability and urged them to sign the Non-Proliferation
Treaty immediately.
	   ``We are very much concerned with peace in the region'' said
Kazak President Nursultan Nazarbayev, noting that ``we live in the
same region.''
	   The six Turkic-speaking countries _ the Central Asian nations of
Kazakstan, Turkmenistan, Uzbekistan and Kyrgyzstan, as well as
Azerbaijan and Turkey _ have been meeting annually since 1992.
	   This year's meeting coincides with celebrations formally
designating Astana the new capital of Kazakstan.
	   Leaders of the six countries also discussed the rise of Islamic
fundamentalism in some of the former Soviet republics.
	   ``We cannot allow the myth of spread that an ideological vacuum
has emerged in Central Asia in the wake of the Soviet Union's
disintegration and that Islamic or other undemocratic states can
appear in the region,'' said Uzbek President Islam Karimov.
	   Karimov and other leaders expressed special concern about the
Wahhabis, a fundamentalist sect that has been blamed for recent
violence in southern Russia and Central Asia.
	   Seven men who were said to be Wahhabis were recently found
guilty of stirring unrest in eastern Uzbekistan. Karimov has
accused Wahhabis of killing officials and destroying
food-processing plants, water reservoirs, power stations and other
strategic sites.
	   ``The fight against Wahhabism, as one of the most reactionary
movements of Islam, does not mean Uzbekistan is prosecuting Islam,
the religion'' said Karimov. ``We are not rejecting the religion of
our forefathers and fathers.''
	   Uzbekistan has enacted a new law on religions that appears
directed at the Wahhabis, who Karimov says are intent on replacing
him with an Islamic government.
	   Nazarbayev, the Kazak leader, also acknowledged the existence of
a problem and said that it should not be ignored.
	   Nazarbayev has chosen Astana _ formerly known as Akmola _ to be
the new capital of his country of 17 million, replacing Almaty,
1,125 kilometers (700 miles) away.
	   The official reasons for relocating are that Almaty is
overcrowded, too close to the Chinese border and prone to
earthquakes. One of the unofficial reasons is that Nazarbayev wants
to counter separatist tendencies in Kazakstan's north, which is
populated mostly by ethnic Russians.
	   The next Turkic summit is scheduled to be held next year in
Baku, the capital of Azerbaijan.
	   (str/ls/mr)
</TEXT>
