w1270 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Poland-GovernmentRefo 1stLd-Writethru   06-09 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-Government Reform, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Polish premier, president fail to agree on administrative reform
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Buzek-Kwasniewski meeting bringing no result. &QL; 
 &UR; By ANDRZEJ STYLINSKI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek failed Tuesday
to get the president to lift his threat to veto government plans
for consolidating the country's provinces as part of an
administrative reform.
	   President Aleksander Kwasniewski and Buzek declined to comment
after their 90-minute meeting, but presidential adviser Ryszard
Kalisz said afterwards that no agreement had been reached.
	   Following heated debates in parliament and protests across
Poland, the government revised its original plan of turning the 49
provinces into 12 big ones, adding three more provinces to make 15.
Residents of cities that would lose their status as provincial
capitals had protested because they fear losing prestige and
government funding.
	   President Aleksander Kwasniewski's aides have indicated he
supports the idea of creating 17 provinces and would veto any other
solution.
	   Kwasniewski seems to have joined forces with his former
ex-communist colleagues, who form the leftist opposition bloc in
parliament.
	   The leftists argue that a return to the 17 provinces that
functioned in Poland until 1975 is natural. They say the government
has failed to win public approval for the reform, which would do
away with the communist-era administration by transferring power to
municipalities. The plan would take effect Jan. 1.
	   Leaders of the rightist government coalition argue Poland needs
big and strong provinces and thus increasing the number only
weakens the plan.
	   The Solidarity-dominated Senate is meeting June 18 and is
expected to support the government plan.
	   Buzek said before his meeting with Kwasniewski that he was
surprised by the president's position because he ``has repeatedly
said during our previous conversations that any solution between 12
and 17 provinces is acceptable to him.''
	   Poles also are divided over the government reform. A survey by
the state-run CBOS agency in mid-April showed that only 24 percent
of Poles approve of consolidating the country's 49 provinces into
12 new ones. Some 29 percent preferred 17 provinces, and 27 percent
wanted to see the present 49 provinces remain.
	   The poll had a margin of error of about 3 percentage points.
	    &UR; (ajs-pfg)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Poland-Government Reform, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
