w1275 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  GOVT-SAYS-ARMY-INTERRUPE     06-09 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> GOVT-SAYS-ARMY-INTERRUPE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Gov't Says Army Interrupted Rebel Meeting In Ayutla, THE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
Gov't Says Army Interrupted Rebel Meeting In Ayutla, THE NEWS &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE NEWS
   MEXICO
   ENGLISH
LATIN AMERICA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E.,

<TEXT>
2nd Floor WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax:
202-546-4194 COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE
OF FDCH, INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS
CONTAINED HEREIN MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO
WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Sunday's violent gun battle between soldiers and rebels, which
killed 11, wounded five and led to 21 arrests, revealed the
possible existence of yet another armed rebel group in the Pacific
Coast state of Guerrero, authorities report.
	   Officials say the bloody gunfight broke up a meeting the EPR
(People's Revolutionary Army) was having with the People's
Revolutionary Indigenous Army (EPRI), Spanish news agency EFE
reported.
	   The Guerrero prosecutor's office said it had confiscated
documents in El Charco, a colonia in the town of Ayutla where the
battle was played out, that point to a meeting between the EPR and
the People's Revolutionary Indigenous Army (EPRI).
	   The EPR rose up on June 28, 1996, in Guerrero, but to date
nothing is known about the EPRI, which is mysterious even to the
Center of Historic Investigations of Armed Movements (CIHMA), the
think-tank that in December reported 14 guerrilla groups were
operating in Mexico.
	   On Sunday, Army soldiers fought for six hours against EPR rebels
in El Charco.
	   Official figures report 11 soldiers died in the battle, five
civilians were injured and 21 were arrested. Following the battle
the Party of the Democratic Revolution (PRD) mayor and city council
of the mainly Mixtec town of Ayutla blasted the Mexican Army for
not allowing Mayor Odilon Ramirez from entering El Charco, French
news agency AFP reported.
	   Arnulfo Meza, a Mixtec Indian campesino , told state officials
50 miles away in Chilpancingo the Army was throwing grenades and
rockets at the town's primary school.
	   El Charco Police Commissioner Panfilo Santiago Hernandez, who
fled Ayutla with 20 other Mixtec Indians early Sunday morning, said
that since Saturday ``there was a meeting of some people in the
primary school and when I was going out of the town in the dawn
Sunday I heard gunfire.''
	   The PRD municipal committee of Ayutla said that ``for the full
clarification of the acts and of the help of communities where the
actions occurred, the Army should permit access to our municipal
authorities, of the representatives of civil organizations and of
the defense of human rights.''
	   Federal senators lamented Sunday's gun battle and condemned the
ultra-left-wing EPR as a threat to national security.
	   In an interview with official news agency Notimex, Sen.
Guadalupe Gomez Maganda said lawlessness in that area of Guerrero
requires a military presence.
	   Fellow Guerrero senator, Porfirio Camareno Castro, opined that
the clandestine nature of the armed EPR demands a permanent
military presence in the region.
	   ``It is necessary that this vigilance is continued,'' said
Camarena.
	   Official figures say that since Aug. 28, 38 people, including
Sunday's 11, have been killed.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE NEWS all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
