<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Train Derails, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German railway restores service through scene of rail disaster
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: New throughout with search for remains ended, rail line
reopened; death toll lowered to 95 &QL; 
 &UR; By PAUL GEITNER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BERLIN (AP) _ Rescue workers ended their search for remains
Tuesday at the site of last week's high-speed train disaster, and
the German railway reopened the Hamburg-Hanover line to rail
traffic.
	   Illustrating just how gruesome the crash was, officials lowered
the death toll for a second time _ from 98 to 95 _ as forensic
experts continue to put body parts together to identify the dead.
	   Police spokesman Joachim Lindenberg said workers sifting through
the last bit of sand found a women's watch and small pieces of
flesh before the site was turned over to the railway Tuesday
afternoon.
	   ``Everything has been scoured that's there to be scoured,'' he
said.
	   An hour later, a regional train from Hamburg passed through at
70 kph (44 mph) _ a third the speed of the InterCity Express that
derailed June 3 and slammed into a concrete bridge, crumpling the
cars like tin cans.
	   The severity of the disaster has made it difficult for officials
to determine exactly how many people died. They now believe 90
people died at the scene; five died in hospitals.
	   All but one of the 95 victims had been identified, police said.
	   Meanwhile, the German national railway said it was investigating
a newspaper report that it had rejected an internal proposal in
1995 for an electronic monitoring system of the wheels on express
trains.
	   Authorities believe a broken wheel caused the wreck in the
northern village of Eschede, although they have yet to determine
what caused it to break.
	   The mass-market Bild newspaper said the railway rejected the
electronic monitors then as impractical and unreliable.
	   Railway chairman Johannes Ludewig told a news conference in
Frankfurt he could not comment before the railway conducts its own
review.
	   Twelve of the 59 original model express trains pulled out of
service for safety checks after the crash were back in service on
Tuesday. Rail officials said so far no defects have been found.
 &UR; (pfg-aet)
</TEXT>
