<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Crimea </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pro-Moscow lawmaker beaten in Ukraine's Crimea
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ Ethnic Russian leaders in Ukraine's restive
Crimean peninsula accused political foes Tuesday of beating a
regional lawmaker to punish him for an ``openly pro-Russia
stance.''
	   Legislator Oleg Rodivilov was beaten Monday night by
unidentified people at the entrance to his home in the Crimean town
of Yevpatoriya, police said.
	   Crimea's Russian community said in a statement that Rodivilov
was attacked because of his ``openly pro-Russia stance, honest
political activities'' and relentless fight against crime, the
Interfax news agency said.
	   Crimea, populated mostly by ethnic Russians, has been part of
Ukraine since Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev gave it to the
then-Soviet republic in 1954. It became part of independent Ukraine
in 1991, but many ethnic Russians in the region want it returned to
Kremlin rule.
	   Olexander Dombrovsky, spokesman for the Ukrainian Interior
Ministry's Crimean branch, said it was ``too early to speak of
political motives'' in the attack, which could be criminal or
domestic in nature.
	   (sms/mr) 	   
</TEXT>
