w1295 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Belarus-US 3rdLd-Writethru   06-09 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Belarus-US, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
American, other ambassadors resist Belarus eviction orders
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. Recasts and UPDATES throughout with protests from France
and Germany. &QL; 
 &UR; By MARINA BABKINA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MINSK, Belarus (AP) _ The U.S. ambassador refused Tuesday to
vacate his official residence and other countries threatened to
recall their envoys from Belarus to protest orders evicting them
from a diplomatic compound.
	   The Foreign Ministry of the former Soviet republic expressed
regret for the ``inconvenience,'' but insisted the ambassadors and
their families must leave their homes in the 50-year-old housing
complex to permit urgent repairs.
	   ``These measures are unacceptable and inadmissible,'' French
Foreign Minister spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret said in Paris.
``They are contrary to the Vienna Convention on diplomatic
privileges and immunity.''
	   The United States, Russia, France, Germany and Lithuania have
formally protested the planned eviction. France and Lithuania said
they will recall their ambassadors for consultations if Belarus
persists.
	   The dispute began in April when the government served notice
that the 22 ambassadors would have to vacate their homes in the
Drodzy compound on the outskirts of Minsk by June 10.
	   Under international law, including the 1948 Vienna Convention,
ambassadors' residences are considered sovereign territory and
governments have no right to enter without permission or insist
that diplomats leave.
	   Belarus says that the complex's water supply is no longer safe
and the sewage system is polluting the environment. The Foreign
Ministry has offered the ambassadors apartments in downtown Minsk
or plots on which to build new residences.
	   But U.S. Ambassador Daniel Speckhard said Monday that envoys
would prefer to make arrangements to remain in the complex during
the repairs, in part because the houses are frequently used for
diplomatic functions.
	   He noted that the government's decision appeared to have been
sudden, and that some embassies had signed new multi-year leases
the month before.
	   The diplomatic compound was built after World War II as dachas
for the Communist Party elite.
	   Since the collapse of the Soviet Union, the spacious homes
inside the walled complex have been the primary residences of
ambassadors from 22 countries. Most have extensive grounds and
reception facilities.
	   After discussing the dispute at a news conference Monday, the
U.S. ambassador returned home to find workers and a policeman
trying to weld shut the side gate. The workers left when Speckhard
protested.
	   The United States has had a lease on the ambassador's residence
since 1992, the year after Belarus gained independence with the
collapse of the Soviet Union, and it does not expire until 2001.
	   Speckhard called the dispute the most serious violation of the
Vienna Convention since the end of the Cold War.
	   (mb/mr/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
