</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> GOVERNMENT-VOWS-TO sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government Vows To Support Press Freedom, THE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
Government Vows To Support Press Freedom, THE NEWS &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE NEWS
   MEXICO
   ENGLISH
LATIN AMERICA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E.,

<TEXT>
2nd Floor WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax:
202-546-4194 COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE
OF FDCH, INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS
CONTAINED HEREIN MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO
WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The government absolutely supports freedom of expression and
freedom of the press, but reporters and editors should honor codes
of ethics, as well as respect ``private life, moral life and public
peace,'' Interior Secretary Francisco Labastida Ochoa said.
	   ``The president of the Republic established the promise to
respect the free demonstration of ideas and the liberty to write
and to publish whatever material, as well as not to restrict in any
way the liberty of the press, whose limits are respect for private
life, moral life and public peace,'' Labastida said Monday at a
luncheon honoring a newspaper group's 47th annual Freedom of the
Press Day.
	   He added good journalism can help the country move forward as a
democracy.
	   ``Mexico is living new realities. Its democratic life is growing
stronger. New forces and energies are making the country more
dynamic,'' he said at the luncheon sponsored by the Mexican Daily
Newspapers Editors' Association (Aedirmex). Labastida said he was
filling in for President Ernesto Zedillo, who was in New York at
the U.N. anti-drug conference.
	   Labastida told the audience of reporters, editors and newspaper
executives the government is doing more than talking about ensuring
freedom of the press. Authorities, he said, are in the process of
selling off the country's government newsprint provider, known as
PIPSA, to allow fair market access to paper.
	   Critics, such as Luis Rubio, a columnist with a major Mexico
City daily, however, charge the government with hampering freedom
of the press. At a Friday award ceremony where he received a prize
from Zedillo, Rubio blasted what he called the bribing of reporters
by government officials desiring favorable coverage.
	   Rubio told Reuters news agency that ``in all countries there is
some degree of (bribery), perhaps not many at such a public and
absurd level as in Mexico'' and that ``the practices of bribery and
intimidation persist in many (government) agencies.''
	   Labastida added that new information technology, especially in
radio, television and on the Internet, has brought more Mexicans in
touch with news faster.
	   ``We count today with information media that are more
influential in society, which all across the country exercise,
without any federal government restriction, freedom of
expression,'' Labastida said at the conference held at the Hotel
Nikko in the Polanco neighborhood.
	   ``The new plurality, the different Mexican reality, also
dictates a new relation to the government. The state is not the
omnipresent actor that decides all.
	   ``This determines that in the media the government is one of
many political actors, which also has a right to express its
opinion and defend its points of view,'' he said.
	   But though Labastida generally championed freedom of the press,
the Interior Secretary urged newsgatherers to be mindful of
individual liberties.
	   ``A common goal is to put the liberties guaranteed by freedom of
expression and freedom of the press in line with individual
rights,'' Labastida said. Aedirmex member Rodrigo Villasana Lopez,
who is the editor in chief of The Herald of San Luis Potosi,
introduced Labastida and said newspaper people have an important
responsibility to society at-large. He said reporters and editors
also should be law-abiding members of society.
	   ``We are respectful of our laws. We have followed them for many
years.
	   ``We are not anarchists of the pen. We are journalists, and we
are Mexicans - proudly Mexicans,''
	   Villasana said.
	   He added the print media need to work together to improve Mexico
for future generations.
	   ``In few words, this is not the country we want for our children
or for the children of our children,'' he said. ``The country is at
risk. Let us not leave it behind.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE NEWS all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
