<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Settlement </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israel approves new housing project for Jews in east Jerusalem
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DAFNA LINZER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) _ Israel's interior ministry gave the
go-ahead Tuesday for construction of 58 homes for Jews on east
Jerusalem land that had been slated for an Arab girls school.
	   The decision came a day after Israelis and Palestinians clashed
in another east Jerusalem neighborhood where Jewish settlers took
over two homes in the middle of the night.
	   Settlers have been stepping up their campaign to increase the
Jewish presence in traditionally Arab east Jerusalem, which the
Palestinians claim as a future capital.
	   The building proposal was submitted by the Beit Orot Jewish
seminary, run by extreme right-wing settler and lawmaker Benny
Elon. The houses would be built on land purchased by American
multi-millionaire Irving Moskowitz around the seminary's building
on the Mount of Olives.
	   The Jerusalem city spokesman's office said that if no objections
were filed to the project, the city would issue building permits
for the 58 homes in the near future.
	   The Israeli peace group Ir Shalem said it would file a formal
objection to the plan. Attorney Danny Seidemann said the group also
planned to file suit against the project in Israel's Supreme Court.
	   The building proposal was approved by the municipality four
years ago but had not received final approval from the interior
ministry.
	   In its decision Tuesday, the ministry backed a city plan to
cancel the construction of a junior high school for Arab girls on
the site, and to move it further down the hill to the Arab
neighborhood of A-Tur. The ministry also approved a plan to build
100 housing units for Palestinians in the same area.
	   Seidemann said the decision to cancel construction of the school
came after the Mount of Olives plot was purchased by Moskowitz, who
has been actively buying up land from Arabs and turning it over for
Jewish settlement.
	   ``The school was approved and Jerusalem mayor Ehud Olmert and
Moskowitz got it removed,'' Seidemann charged.
	   The United States has asked Israel for a time-out in settlement
construction to help restart Israeli-Palestinian peace talks,
stalled since Israel began another settlement project on a disputed
east Jerusalem hilltop in March 1997.
	   Israel captured east Jerusalem from Jordan in the 1967 Mideast
War and later annexed it.
	    &UR; dl-hla
</TEXT>
