<SLUG> BC-Fighter Jets-China </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China starts to assemble Sukhoi fighters from Russian kits
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ China has started to assemble Sukhoi fighter
aircraft from kits supplied by Russia, Jane's Defense Weekly
reported Tuesday.
	   The first two Su-27 fighters are expected to be delivered to the
Chinese military by the end of the year, the respected military
magazine said.
	   China's purchase of Russian Su-27s is part of a concerted drive
to modernize its military.
	   The Su-27 is set to become one of the Chinese air force's main
fighters from early next decade, serving primarily as a long-range
interceptor, Jane's said.
	   The magazine said there is little difference between the Su-27s
being assembled at the Shenyang Aircraft Corp. in China's northeast
Shenyang Province and the 48 Su-27s that Beijing purchased directly
from Russia in the early 1990s.
	   The Shenyang facility has an annual production target of 10 to
15 fighters, Jane's said. A clause in the sales contract stipulates
that Russia's Su-27 facility in Komsomolsk will provide substitute
aircraft if the Shenyang facility doesn't meet that target, it
said.
	   (eml-kg)
</TEXT>
