<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-India,0386 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
India defends nuclear tests, saying they reflect unique security
</HEADLINE>
situation &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT H. REID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ India tested nuclear weapons because the
collapse of the Soviet Union changed the balance of power in Asia
and left India outside the system of global nuclear umbrellas, the
Indian planning chief said Tuesday.
	   ``The nuclear security paradigm is really a club which extends
from Vancouver to Vladivostok,'' Jaswant Singh told reporters.
``The (security) vacuum that has come into existence is southern
Russia and parts of Africa.''
	   India, he said, was simply filling the vacuum in South Asia.
	   He said the collapse of the Soviet Union had led to a
``disequilibrium in the nuclear'' balance in Asia ``from which
India was excluded.'' The breakup of the Soviet Union left China as
the only nuclear state in the region.
	   Singh's remarks indicated that India, the world's second most
populous country, sees itself as a major regional power with a
right to take measures to guarantee its own defense.
	   ``Large parts of the world today enjoy the benefit of the
extended deterrence of nuclear weapons powers,'' he said. ``Missing
in the flood of comment on India's decision to test nuclear weapons
... are informed assessments of India's own security predicament.''
	   Last Saturday, the Security Council condemned nuclear tests by
India and neighboring Pakistan and called on them to halt further
weapons development.
	   The council also denied India and Pakistan formal status as
nuclear states under the 1970 Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.
That treaty recognizes the United States, Russia, China, France and
Britain as nuclear states and allows them to keep their arsenals.
	   India and Pakistan have denounced this system and called on the
nuclear states to agree to talks on dismantling their own nuclear
weapons.
	   ``No other country in the world has exercised the kind of
restraint that India has demonstrated (since its first test in
1974),'' Singh said.
	   He accused the nuclear states themselves of violating the spirit
of the nonproliferation agreement by secretly using ``nuclear
technology as commodities.''
	   Singh said it was time for the nuclear powers to move toward
global nuclear disarmament.
</TEXT>
