<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-ETA kidnap </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Trial for ETA's longest kidnapping to start Wednesday
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ Four alleged Basque separatists are due to
stand trial in Spain's National Court on Wednesday for holding a
prison official hostage for 18 months.
	   The prosecution is seeking 32-year prison sentences for the four
who were arrested last July, hours before police rescued the
captive from a hideout in the northern Basque region.
	   The armed Basque separatist group ETA abducted Jose Antonio
Ortega Lara in January 1996, conditioning his release on improved
conditions for 450 jailed members of the group.
	   Ortega Lara, who was kept in a 3-meter by 2.5-meter (9-foot by
7-foot) windowless room for 532 days, has asked the court to excuse
him from taking the witness stand because of his delicate mental
health. A decision on the petition is expected when the trial
begins.
	   A medical evaluation of Ortega Lara submitted on Tuesday
concluded that he now suffers from acute anxiety and depression
because of the ordeal, and that a court appearance could ``provoke
a serious worsening of his psychological condition,'' the national
news agency EFE said.
	   In the pretrial report prosecutor Ignacio Gordillo said the four
defendants followed Ortega Lara, an active member of the governing
Popular Party, for several months before kidnapping him on his way
home from work.
	   As well as kidnapping, Jesus Maria Uribechevarria Bolinaga,
Javier Ugarte Villar, Jose Luis Erostegui Bidaguren and Jose Miguel
Gaztelu are also facing charges of conspiracy to murder.
	   According to Gordillo's report they had instructions to kill
their captive or let him starve to death if the government did not
give in to the pressure.
	   ETA, an acronym for Basque Homeland and Liberty, began fighting
for the independence of northern Spain's Basque region in 1968.
Since then it has killed nearly 800 people and kidnapped 71.
	   Prosecutors are also seeking compensation of 65 million pesetas
(dlrs 424,836) for Ortega Lara, and the trial is expected to last
two days.
	   (mr/jt)
</TEXT>
