<BODY>
<SLUG> FOBAPROA-HINDERS-MEXICO sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fobaproa Hinders Mexico's Economic Forecast, THE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
Fobaproa Hinders Mexico's Economic Forecast, THE NEWS &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE NEWS
   MEXICO
   ENGLISH
LATIN AMERICA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E.,

<TEXT>
2nd Floor WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax:
202-546-4194 COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE
OF FDCH, INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS
CONTAINED HEREIN MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO
WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The bank bailout fund (Fobaproa) debate will not have a major
effect on the economy, though recent peso fluctuations and the
proposed congressional bill to overhaul Fobaproa stir analysts'
concern, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter (MSDW) brokerage said Monday.
	   MSDW visited a wide range of companies, economists, and
government officials in Mexico recently, to further align its
economic forecasts utilizing a wide array of sources.
	   MSDW said virtually everyone it met with agreed with its 15.8
billion-dollar current account deficit estimate.
	   MSDW, however, reset its foreign direct investment (FDI)
expectation at between 10 billion dollars and 12 billion dollars.
	   In regards to the foreign-exchange rate, MSDW forecasts 9.2
pesos to the dollar for the end of 1998, and projects a yearly
gross domestic product growth of 4.8 percent.
	   Ernest W. Brown, an analyst from MSDW, said the economy is
growing at a healthy pace although a slowdown is expected.
	   ``The firms visited expect an economic-growth slowdown in the
second half of the year, despite repeated stories of impressive
sales gains continuing throughout'' the first quarter, he said.
	   Despite the good economic news, Fobaproa still clouds the
horizon.
	   ``The Fobaproa issue is not going away any time soon,'' MSDW
said. ``It's this kind of unaccustomed political give-and-take
that's making many business leaders more cautious about the
economic outlook.''The opposition in Congress is using the
controversy surrounding Fobaproa to threaten blocking the passage
of the government's financial reform package.
	   The government, using Fobaproa as its instrument, has bought
about 63 billion dollars' worth of bad debt off banks, while only
seizing 25 billion dollars' worth of assets from companies that
have defaulted on debt repayments. Furthermore, the Finance
Secretariat says it only expects to recover 25 percent of the debt
--leaving taxpayers to foot the rest of the bill.
	   Financial legislation proposed by the Zedillo administration
include: Shifting exchange-rate management to the central bank
(Bank of Mexico).
	   Removing banking supervision from the Bank of Mexico.
	   Restructuring Fobaproa into 2 institutions - one solely with an
FDIC deposit insurance function, and the other BTC asset
divestiture function.
	   Limiting deposit insurance to 1 million pesos per account.
	   Eliminating restrictions on foreign capital ownership of
Mexico's largest banks.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE NEWS all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
