<HEADLINE>
PGR Confirms Arrest Of Two Suspected Top Cartel Leaders, THE NEWS
</HEADLINE>
PGR Confirms Arrest Of Two Suspected Top Cartel Leaders, THE NEWS &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE NEWS
   MEXICO
   ENGLISH
LATIN AMERICA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E.,

<TEXT>
2nd Floor WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax:
202-546-4194 COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE
OF FDCH, INC. AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS
CONTAINED HEREIN MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO
WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Attorney General's Office (PGR) confirmed Monday it had
captured two men suspected of being top capos in the
drug-trafficking organization known as the Gulf Cartel.
	   The PGR announced that Angel Salvador Gomez Herrera and Oziel
Cardenas Guillen were arrested in Tamaulipas on Friday and will be
investigated for a variety of offenses related to drug trafficking
and organized crime.
	   Arrested with the two alleged cartel members was an unnamed
Federal Highway patrolman who is believed to have been in the pay
of drug traffickers.
	   The PGR said federal agents and military personnel participated
in the capture of the suspects, but did not give further details.
	   The operation also resulted in the confiscation of 15,000
dollars in cash, several high-caliber arms and other items.
	   Several arrest warrants (on drug trafficking and murder charges)
for Gomez Herrera had been issued by Texas courts over the past
several years, the PGR said.
	   Gomez Herrera and Cardenas Guillen are believed to head a
prominent faction of the Gulf Cartel, succeeding Oscar Malherbe de
Leon (arrested late last year), who had himself succeeded Gulf
Cartel boss Juan Garcia Abrego (arrested and deported to the United
States in early 1997).
	   Newspaper accounts over the weekend described Salvador ``Chava''
Gomez Herrera as the ``acting head'' of the Gulf Cartel, referring
to Cardenas Guillen as Gomez Herrera's right-hand man.
	   With these arrests, the four principal drug cartels in Mexico
are in various stages of disarray.
	   The PGR began dismantling the Gulf Cartel in 1993 when it
arrested several of its top lieutenants; the Juarez Cartel has been
in disarray since the July 4, 1997 death of capo Amado Carrillo
Fuentes after botched plastic surgery; the Tijuana Cartel leaders,
Benjamin and Ramon Arellano Felix, reportedly have gone into deep
hiding since the PGR stepped up its pursuit of the siblings (plus
the FBI placed Ramon on its Top 10 Most Wanted list earlier this
year); and the PGR says it dismantled the Colima Cartel when it
arrested Jesus and Luis Amezcua Contreras, the chiefs of the
so-called ``Amphetamine Cartel.''The director of Mexico's Office of
the Special Prosecutor for Crimes Against Health, Mariano Herran
Salvatti, told Spanish news agency EFE last week before Friday's
arrests that government officials believe the Gulf Cartel is on the
point of disappearing. Herran Salvatti also asserted that the
Colima Cartel has been smashed by the arrests of the Amezcua
brothers.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE NEWS all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
