<SLUG> BC-Vatican-Obit Casaroli, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Vatican's former No. 2 official dies
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs; recasts, adds Casaroli quote, trims &QL; 
 &UR; By VICTOR L. SIMPSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VATICAN CITY (AP) _ Cardinal Agostino Casaroli, the onetime No.
2 Vatican official whose quiet diplomacy helped keep the church
alive behind the Iron Curtain during the Cold War, died Tuesday. He
was 83.
	   Casaroli was hospitalized Thursday and died of heart problems,
officials at a Rome hospital said.
	   In a condolence note, John Paul II praised the churchman for
``carrying out with refined diplomatic sensitivity courageous and
significant steps, in particular for improving the situation of the
church in eastern Europe.''
	   Casaroli was considered an architect of the Vatican's diplomatic
policy to gain more freedom for the Roman Catholic Church after
open persecution by Communist nations.
	   Casaroli served as secretary of state from 1979 to 1990. The
position is the most important after the pope, and is equivalent to
premier.
	   When Casaroli retired, Pope John Paul II expressed his gratitude
to the tailor's son from Piacenza in northern Italy and said it was
``providential'' to have worked with him during such ``historic
times.''
	   Casaroli was considered a consummate but cautious diplomat and
an extremely loyal official. He once said that ``the forces that
can truly guide humanity on the moral level are so weak.''
Therefore, it was up to the pope and the Vatican ``to impose their
moral authority.''
	   The Polish-born pope and some other churchmen were said to have
had differences with Casaroli's cautious approach to diplomacy,
preferring a more uncompromising stance.
	   But John Paul promoted Casaroli to secretary of state less than
a year after becoming pontiff. He and the pope clearly had
reconciled any differences as the years went on.
	   ``He leaves an unmistakable imprint not only on the life of the
church, but in contemporary history,'' said Giulio Andreotti, a
former Christian Democrat premier and foreign minister whose tenure
concided with much of Casaroli's.
	   ``He had extraordinary intuition about the possibility of
dialogue even with his opponents in the certainty that in the end
the right approaches would have prevailed. Not everybody understood
him at the time,'' Andreotti added.
	   The policy toward Eastern Europe was the inspiration of Pope
John XXIII after the hard line taken by Pope Pius XII during the
years of Stalinist repression.
	   Pope Paul VI, who took over in 1963, implemented the policy,
working closely with Casaroli and sending him on frequent missions
to Communist capitals.
	   Casaroli also was given credit for the tough language on human
rights and religious liberty in the 1975 Helsinki accords.
	   Beyond the diplomatic field, Casaroli kept the Vatican running
smoothly after the pope was wounded by a Turkish gunman in 1981.
	   The cardinal's funeral, to be celebrated by John Paul, was
scheduled for Friday in St. Peter's Basilica.
	   (vls-fd/djw)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Vatican-Obit Casaroli, 4th Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
