</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> PRIVATISATION-THEY-STILL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAI TALK: Privatisation: They still don't get it, NATION
</HEADLINE>
THAI TALK: Privatisation: They still don't get it, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   SUTHICHAI YOONASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The trouble-plagued privatisation drive, hailed only six months
ago as a major component of this government's economic rescue
package, appears to have stalled. The badly-needed political will
to implement this crucial, if not highly sensitive, project is
fading fast. The well-entrenched bureaucrats, it seems, have won
out again.
	   For all practical purposes, the so-called ''comprehensive''
national privatisation plan has been shelved. Each government unit
assigned to map out its plan is doing its own thing. Nobody is
quite sure what the other guy is doing and everybody seems to be
praying that its turn for the big change will never arrive.
	   Who is in charge? There was some mumbling a few weeks ago that
the Cabinet was considering putting the Finance Ministry in overall
control of all the privatisation schemes. Deputy Premier Supachai
Panitchpakdi, who should have fretted over the change, kept quiet.
He headed a national-level committee supposed to supervise the
overall privatisation process.
	   But when an uproar erupted over the proposed sale of a power
plant at the Electricity Generating Authority of Thailand (Egat),
the committee was conspicuous by its silence. It became a drawn-out
and noisy battle between Egat's board of directors on the one side
and the union and management on the other. The board lost and was
replaced through a face-saving mediation. The pros and cons of the
controversy were never seriously debated in an open forum. Dr
Supachai's committee was nowhere to be seen.
	   The government, instead of dealing with the privatisation issue,
shifted the focus to the question of personalities of the board of
directors to appease the union. Egat has a new board now but the
privatisation controversy remains unresolved. It's back to square
one.
	   The conflict has not disappeared. It has merely been shelved for
the time being. Sooner or later, it will explode into another
chaotic political mess -- because the hard, cold fact will have to
be faced: Policy makers are there to make policies, not simply
patch up quarrels in order to avoid making the difficult decisions.
	   The case of Thai Airways International will meet the same fate
this week if the Cabinet flinches from making a tough choice.
	   Bureaucrats will be raising legal and technical obstacles to
slow down, if not block, privatisation of the national airline. The
Finance Ministry says it plans to sell existing and new shares
through a private placement arrangement to member airlines in the
Star Alliance. But the National Economic and Social Development
Board (NESDB) and Budget Bureau propose that the offer should be
made to financial institutions and general investors to fetch a
better price.
	   Then, there will be the question of whether the move will be in
line with provisions of the 1954 Aviation Act which specifies that
at least 70 per cent of the equity must belong to Thai nationals or
else its aircraft cannot be registered as Thai. The move may also
run into a major stumbling block if a piece of 1992 legislation is
brought into the discussion. That law imposes a time-consuming
procedure for a state agency in selecting a private partner in any
substantial business joint venture.
	   The outcome isn't hard to predict. The Cabinet, which doesn't
seem to possess the necessary political will to carry out vital
economic reform, will just throw up its hands over these highly
entangled arguments -- and, keeping everyone in the room happy,
will just politely ask the opposing bureaucrats to ''review and
revise'' their respective proposals before submitting their new
findings (a new set of entangled arguments) to the Cabinet for
''future consideration.'' Back to square one yet again.
	   Bangchak Petroleum offers another classic case of a well-laid
privatisation plan gone awry. It's been turned into an ugly and
noisy confrontation between the shareholders and the managing
director, portrayed in some circles as a clash between hard, cold
economic realities against the noble cause of promoting rural
development -- or less charitably, a battle between greed and
charity, or much worse, foreign domination against nationalism.
	   The risk of a privatisation scheme creating the image of saint
and Satan among advocates and objectors is always there. But in
most cases, such an unfair division could be avoided with a
strong-minded government ready to resort to unpopular policies to
achieve the necessary goals. That means coming up with a
comprehensive privatisation plan, setting down clear-cut goals,
explaining the rationale behind each scheme and setting appropriate
deadlines, with effective action plans backed up by public hearings
for all projects under the scheme. Most important of all, make the
information public -- and ensure utmost transparency. In other
words, put it clearly and unequivocally on the public agenda.
	   Because this government has failed to communicate effectively
with a skeptical public over the issue, privatisation has been seen
only as a desperate way of raising funds to pay for mismanaged
private concerns. Privatisation, when it's done right and
responsibly, ensures a greater degree of professionalism,
transparency and sensitivity in the management of our state
enterprises, the majority of which leave much to be desired.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:PRIVATISATION-THEY-STILL sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
