<BODY>
<SLUG> BATTLE-FOR-INTHANOND sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Battle for Inthanond affects all parties, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Battle for Inthanond affects all parties, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   As elsewhere, the debate in Thailand regarding the relationship
between man and forest has become polarised, with the current
dispute between highlanders and lowlanders in the Doi Inthanond
National Park becoming the main battleground at a time when the
government is set to review a regulation which allows people to
live in sensitive forest areas.
	   The recent road blockade by thousands of lowland villagers in
Chiang Mai's Chom Thong district was the result of a two-decade
impasse between lowlanders and highlanders, an issue which is
further complicated by the existence of powerful NGOs on both sides
which have refused to settle for compromises and are constantly
appealing to our sense of humanity to serve their agenda.
	   To overcome this divide, one must first move away from the
politically correct tendency to describe hill tribes as indigenous
people, a term used by some NGOs in their bid to win public
sympathy and support. The hill tribes living in the highland area
of Inthanond are today normal Thai highlanders with as much
citizenship right as the lowland Thais.
	   The lowland villagers in Doi Inthanond are insisting that the
highlanders living in the park must be resettled as their
activities disturb the watershed forest, but proponents of highland
communities argue that they have the right to remain on the land
because they have lived there since before the forest was declared
protected.
	   The real issue, however, goes beyond the question of humanity,
if one can get away from the images, propaganda and distorted
information in the debate. At stake is the lack of water for both
sides following widespread fire in the area.
	   Without accurate information on the ground, it will be difficult
for decision-makers to give judgement. The technical aspect of
ecological impact is probably the best clue in the search for a
solution, but this is not to say that the historical and social
contexts of the problem should not be taken into account.
	   This must include not only the public perception of hill tribes
and local northern Thai communities but the involvement of NGOs on
both sides and whether their roles are based on hidden agenda such
as differing ideologies and even the cover-up of past errors in
ecological management.
	   But the immediate issue is how to ensure that there is water
available for everyone in Doi Inthanond. The government must step
in urgently to check the availability of water and its management
in the highland area. This, if done objectively, would inform
everyone involved in the dispute whether there is hope for
salvaging the situation and perhaps put an end to the threat of
protests which could easily turn violent.
	   Nithi Eawsriwong, a Chiang Mai University academic, has also
suggested a wide-ranging study of the pattern of water usage by
both highlanders and lowland farmers. Without such an assessment
any decision could easily be mistaken, he says. Nithi was once
accused as being ''biased'' towards the highlanders when he made a
recent comment on the forest-fire problem in Doi Inthanond and
nearby Doi Chiang Dao. Lowland villagers burnt him in effigy along
with a number of other CMU academics who were accused for
supporting the highlanders, but his useful advice should not be
ignored.
	   The conflict at Doi Inthanond should see a proper solution when
accurate information from a detailed study is made available. If
need be the cultivation of certain crops by both highland and
lowland farmers should be reassessed, taking in consideration their
demand for water. A team consisting of ecologists, hydrologists,
geologists, conservationists, social scientists, anthropologists,
well-informed forestry officials and villagers themselves who have
the trust of both sides should be set up to designate all the
aspects the study has to cover.
	   Hopefully a solution might be in sight after the completion of
such a study. The Doi Inthanond controversy could well serve as an
optional model for future solution of forest-land conflicts in
other areas. Indeed the issue of humanity should not blur our view
when resolving such disputes.
	   The Nation 
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
