<SLUG> SENIOR-HIGHWAY-POLICE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Senior highway police officers to be transferred, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Senior highway police officers to be transferred, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FOUR senior officers at the Highway Police Division are to be
transferred as part of the Police Department's efforts to improve
its image, sources said Monday.
	   Although the four, including division deputy chiefs, have not
been charged with any wrongdoing, they have been in their positions
for a long time reportedly due to their relationship with leading
politicians and prominent figures.
	   It has not yet been decided which positions they will be
transferred to, the sources said.
	   The planned transfer resulted from a policy by Central
Investigation Bureau chief Pol Lt Gen Seri Temiyavej who did not
want any senior officer in any position for too long, especially
within the division.
	   However, police chief Pol Gen Pracha Promnok said he had not yet
received the official order on the four officers' transfer, and
that Seri had told him earlier that it would take at least another
20 days for the CIB chief to make his decision on who should be
transferred.
	   The image of the police force has been tainted by several
scandals with highway police being accused of extorting money from
truck drivers.
	   Twenty-one officers of the Patrol and Special Operations
Division have been moved to inactive posts for their alleged
involvement in the gruesome murder of a fellow officer last month.
	   Pol Maj Gen Somsak Prasarnsuk, chief of the division, said the
transfers of all the 21, four of them commissioned officers, would
temporarily end their alleged activities or prevent their possible
interference in the ongoing investigation of the killing of Pol Sgt
Nukul Khongsuwan.
	   He said all of them, better known as 191 police, would
immediately face temporary suspension from service if more evidence
is found clearly implicating them in the killing.
	   On May 30, Nukul's body, with one of the three gunshot wounds on
his head, was found hanging out of a Mercedes with his right wrist
handcuffed to the vehicle. Police initially believed that the
motive for the murder was his involvement with many gambling dens
or several affairs he had with women.
	   Bangkok police chief Pol Lt Gen Thawee Thipphayarat, speaking
after approving Somsak's proposed transfer order, said all of them
would be anyway assigned to positions which are easy to control
should it be revealed eventually that they had nothing to do with
Nukul's murder.
	   A police source said the 21 officers, who mostly work as
plain-cloth officers, are members of an extortion ring which has
long collected protection money from all illegal businesses in
Bangkok area.
	   The source added that Nukul had also worked for the ring until
his relationship with them soured recently when he began to keep
part of the money with him instead of handing the whole amount to
the group.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
