<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Koreas, 1st Ld-Writethru,0631 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Decade later, Park involved in another plan for Koreas
</HEADLINE>
to join forces &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES thruout with new material, background, recasts &QL; 
 &UR; By LARRY SIDDONS &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ The road is familiar to Park Seh-jik, one he
traveled a decade ago without ever reaching the end.
	   As president of the committee that staged the 1988 Seoul
Olympics, Park knew the stress and frustration of trying _ and
failing _ to bring North and South Korea together through sports.
	   Now, he's about to try again. Different event this time.
Different political climate. Different _ he hopes _ outcome.
	   As chairman of the South Korean organizing committee for the
2002 World Cup, Park said Tuesday he was ready to see if some of
the 32 games could be staged north of the demilitarized zone that
divides the peninsula and underscores the fact that the neighbor
nations remain at war.
	   ``The Korean people are very anxious to have the games both
north and south,'' Park said. ``We are ready to share. ... This
would affirm an atmosphere of peace.''
	   Park, in Paris for the start of this year's World Cup, also said
there was a chance of having a single, united Korean team in 2002.
Initial reactions from North Korea were favorable.
	   ``We are not in a stage to discuss details yet, but in
principle, it is very desirable to form a single team and for North
Korea to hold some games,'' said Choi Pyong Joo, vice president of
North Korea's soccer association.
	   In Seoul, soccer officials said the government had approved
contacting the north about World Cup matters. If meetings are set
up, they said, more general sports exchanges might also be
discussed.
	   Seoul was awarded the Summer Games by the IOC in 1981, and calls
followed from the North Korean capital of Pyongyang that it wanted
some of the action, too.
	   From 1986 through the summer of '88, Park's committee and the
IOC tried to cut a deal with the north, offering to let it stage a
handful of sports and ceremonies. The offers always fell short.
	   That was another time, though. The Cold War had yet to thaw and
North Korea was on relatively stable economic ground. Now, as the
last Stalinist state left, it finds itself impoverished and
isolated. The government in Seoul recently called for an easing of
decades-old sanctions and attitudes by the United States and other
Western nations.
	   Such changes lead Park to think that a sports enterprise with
the north could work this time.
	   ``The situations in 1988 and now are quite different,'' Park
said. ``The tensions are very much reduced. We are looking for a
positive answer from North Korea.''
	   He stressed, however, that any deal with Pyongyang would also
have to be approved by the international soccer federation, FIFA,
as well as Japan, South Korea's co-host in 2002.
	   Because of that unprecedented sharing, Park said, it was
imperative that any negotiations with the north not drag out as
they did a decade ago.
	   ``It is very complicated, so the sooner, the better,'' he said.
	   At the same time, Park said, there was enough time to work out
details of the north's role and bring facilities there up to
international standards.
	   ``We still have a full four years, so any complications could be
solved,'' he said.
	   A joint Korean team played in the last under-16 world
championships in Portugal and FIFA said it was ready to try it
again.
	   ``There is precedence for that, although, of course, there is a
huge difference between youth soccer championships and the World
Cup,'' federation spokesman Keith Cooper said. ``That is strictly a
matter for the two national (soccer) associations to decide.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Soccer-Koreas, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:s; 
