<HEADLINE>
Investors in trust funds told to exercise patience, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Investors in trust funds told to exercise patience, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ALOR STAR, Sat. - Investors in trust funds should be patient and
wait for prices to recover, instead of hastily selling off their
shares, Deputy Finance Minister Datuk Affifuddin Omar said today.
	   Admitting that trust funds had suffered paper losses, he said
they were not spared the ill-effects of the economic downturn.
	   ``We are aware the market value of the funds has dropped
drastically but investors should be patient.
	   ``There is no point panicking and selling off their shares at
such low prices ... they should wait until things improve,'' he
said, adding that the Government understood the predicament of
those who had borrowed to buy units.
	   However, he said it was not only trust fund investors who were
suffering. Almost every investor in the share market had been
affected by the economic problems.
	   Affifudin was speaking to reporters after attending a seminar on
Kedah's economic development.
	   He was asked to comment on the problems faced by investors in
trust funds following the sharp fall in unit prices after the share
market was badly hit.
	   The country's trust funds include Amanah Saham Nasional and
Amanah Saham Wawasan. There are also six trust funds run by the
State Governments of Kedah, Selangor, Johor, Terengganu, Sabah and
Sarawak.
	   
</TEXT>
