<HEADLINE>
PM questions Phan, number of unemployed, NATION
</HEADLINE>
PM questions Phan, number of unemployed, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   PIYANART SRIVALOASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   LABOUR Permanent Secretary Phan Jantrapan Monday briefed the
Council of Economic Ministers, saying the number of unemployed had
reached 2,061,719, consisting of 1,322,379 jobless villagers,
250,340 laid-off workers and 489,000 workers new to the labour
force.
	   While informing the council of the measures to tackle the
problem, Phan was caught off guard when asked about the number of
Thai workers sent back from Brunei owing to the sluggish economy
there.
	   Deputy Prime Minister Panja Kesornthong voiced concern over
reports that 6,000 Thai workers had been laid off by Bruneian
employers and returned home, prompting Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
to ask for clarification on the situation of Thai workers in the
oil-rich sultanate.
	   Phan replied he had no updated information on the number of
returned Thai workers from Brunei, adding that the reports had come
in over the weekend when his office was closed.
	   Chuan rebuked the top labour bureaucrat, saying he could not use
office hours as an excuse for his failure to keep abreast of
important labour developments.
	   Chuan also instructed the National Statistics Office to review
its labour statistics and submit a report next week on how it had
arrived at the total of 2,800,000 unemployed, which differed
greatly from the Labour, Interior and National Economic and Social
Development Board reports.
	   Government deputy spokesman Pan Phuengsujarit, speaking after
the meeting, broke down assistance to the unemployed as follows: -
Job placement for 153,162 laid-off employees.
	   - Training to upgrade job skills for 85,639 workers.
	   - Preparations for the hiring of 3,008 workers.
	   - Terminating the contracts of 232,639 illegal alien workers and
securing replacement jobs for 95,149 Thai workers.
	   - Organising sales of essential consumers goods to benefit
1,012,950 consumers.
	   - Sending mobile teams to distribute bargain-price goods to
1,721,000 residents.
	   - Arranging venture capital for 9,587 laid-off workers to begin
independent careers.
	   - Disbursing Bt2.3 million for the hiring of 112,768 jobless
villagers.
	   - Prompting 8,870 rural families to join the Royal-initiated
''New Theory Agriculture'' project for self-reliance, of whom 870
have already put the knowledge to use.
	   - Providing job counselling and training for 21,600 workers.

</TEXT>
