Homepage to help get money for Amirul, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Homepage to help get money for Amirul, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MOTHERLY LOVE ... Johor State Executive Councillor Halimah
Mohamed Sadique cuddling neuro patient Mohd Amirul Hakeem Abmad
Nazri, two, while the child's parents Ahmad Nazri Mahmud and
Jamilah Ibrahim look on.
	   The boy has been suffering from brain complications after an
epileptic attack when he was eight months old.
	   He needs about US$75,000 (RM292,500) for treatment abroad.
Halimah launched a homepage at Plaza Angsana in Tampoi near Johor
Baru yesterday to collect funds in aid of him. The website address
is http://www.johor.net.my/amirul/ The Malaysian Islamic Welfare
and Missionary Organisation (Perkida) Johor Baru branch has also
launched the ``Mohd Amirul Hakeem Fund'' to collect donations to
finance the boy's treatment. To date, about RM62,000 has been
collected.
	   Ahmad Nazri, a former Utusan Malaysia journalist who now runs a
small carpet-cleaning business, said as the sole breadwinner of the
family he could not afford the treatment. He has four other
school-going children.
	   The family is now staying in a rented house, as they have sold
their house to finance Amirul's treatment.
	   He said doctors found that Amirul's brain had shrunk and become
inactive after the epileptic attack. As a result, the child became
very weak, has poor eyesight, cannot sit up, walk or even hold an
object. Amirul also has to be spoonfed.
	   ``I have spent more than a year seeking treatment locally for my
son including sending him to numerous medical specialists and also
going to Indonesia and Singapore several times, but to no avail.''
	   Ahmad Nazri said he hoped to raise enough funds to take his son
to the United States.
	   Contributions for the boy can be made by cheque, bank draft or
postal order under the name ``Mohd Amirul Hakeem Fund'' and posted
to Perkida, Johor Baru branch, 6A, Mara Building, Jalan Sekolah, Kg
Melayu Majidee, 81100 Johor Baru.
	   
</TEXT>
