<BODY>
<SLUG> OF-GANGS-RAIN-AND-EXAM sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Of gangs, rain and exam jitters, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Of gangs, rain and exam jitters, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ted MilesASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   OCTOBER 1956: When I went to the hospital to check up on Yit
Song this evening, I also visited Balbir Singh, Harbans Singh's
brother. He fell on the steps at school this evening and broke his
arm.
	   Munzir went with him to the hospital to have it set and was
still there when I arrived. First Harbans and his leg, now Balbir
and his arm. That family! On the way home from our football game
with the Sulaiman School this evening, I noticed that Razak was
about to have a fight with Sulaiman School's Rosli. They were
exchanging words, so I asked Razak to invite Rosli to the hostel
for a talk.
	   He came, and the three of us had a long talk before dinner. Two
names kept coming up - Manan and Safian of the ``Ketari gang''- so
I told Rosli to bring those boys to the hostel on Saturday night so
that we could have the whole thing out once and for all.
	   Meanwhile, the other boys were having study hours, and when I
went upstairs, Tengku Abdullah said that they had heard some boys
shouting as they cycled by: ``Hostel boys, come out and fight!''
	   I told the boys that if it ever happened again, to let me know
immediately; we'll take them up on the invitation! I don't want
anyone to think the hostel boys are cowards, and if fight we must,
fight we will.
	   Jalil, home from Kuala Lumpur on a week's leave, came with his
mother tonight ``to take Ghaffar home.''
	   ``What?'' was my response. According to them, the mother needs
him at home to take care of her, but I'm sure that Ghaffar had just
cooked up this excuse to get out of the control of the hostel.
	   He has good friends in the ``Ketari gang'', so I told the mother
that she would have to keep a very strict watch on her son's
activities. I said that once he moved out of the hostel, I would
wash my hands of all responsibility for him - except in school as
his headmaster.
	   ``If he gets into any `gang trouble','' I said, ``he'll be
expelled from school.'' The mother gave me the impression that she
knows her son better than I do, so he took his things (they were
already packed) and left. I was really sorry to see him go.
	   There were tears in my eyes when I left the hospital this
morning.
	   Beserah had just told me that Yit Song definitely has TB, and
the boy looked so pathetic when I talked to him. He will have to be
in hospital for a long time, and until we can get him admitted to
Lady Templer's, he'll stay in Raub.
	   Nyit Chin packed his things for him today, and it made me so sad
to think that he had to leave in this way.
	   The boys wanted to go see Sumpah Orang Minyak tonight as a
reward for winning the game yesterday with Sulaiman School. I said
``No,'' and that was that.
	   ``You can see Oliver Twist at school tomorrow night,'' I said.
The truth is that I don't want them roaming around town at night.
	   Ghaffar came along tonight with Manan, Rosli, and Safian for our
meeting. We gathered around the table in the library - Razak,
Zubir, Munzir, and Tengku Ahmad representing the hostel boys; the
others were upstairs looking at USIS films.
	   The meeting became heated a time or two, but we managed to have
a pretty sensible discussion. After it was all over and we were
weighing things, it seemed to add up to the fact that these
`outside' boys were simply jealous of the hostel boys. Their
charges were downright juvenile: Rosli said that he didn't like the
way Razak walked, and Manan said that some of the hostel boys
``stared'' at him and his friends.
	   The whole thing ended with handshakes, but Manan still had an
evil look in his eye, and Ghaffar was smilingly defiant, saying:
``If there should be trouble, and I'm not there, you can't do
anything to me.''
	   ``Ghaffar,'' I told him, ``If there's any trouble, I'll know
that you're behind it, and your name will be the first on the list
I send to the police.''
	   The Standard Six students began their central exam this morning.
Our candidates had to go to the Malay School centre, where Yeng Kee
was a proctor. Some of the students reported to Brian that it was a
``very easy,'' exam - so that's a bad sign.
	   The weather is ruling us these days. We managed to get through
our football game with the PWD this evening before the rain started
(we won 3- 1), but we didn't do so well in badminton (either way).
	   Our match with Karak began at 5.30, and we lost the first two
games; then the rain stopped the playing. We came home in a
downpour and were absolutely soaked when we were finally blown in
through the front door by the strong wind.
	   We had a late dinner, and then Munzir complained that his new
sarong didn't come back from the dhoby today. Rosli and Say Kuang,
who checked the clothes, reported that 22 sarongs were sent on
Saturday and 22 came back today - but Munzir's new one was not
among them.
	   We checked everyone's cupboard and bag tonight - which was a
good idea, because the bags had not been down from the tops of the
cupboards for weeks, and they were covered with dust and needed a
good cleaning.
	   Then we checked the shelves in the bedroom - which was a good
idea, too, for the same reason. But we didn't find the sarong.
	   Bakar and some of the others were chasing Syed Adanan around
upstairs this afternoon before study hours - with the aim of
pulling his sarong down - and they knocked over a tin of ink onto
Nyit Chin's mattress.
	   ``Starting tomorrow,'' I announced, ``study hours will start at
two instead of 2.30.'' That should do it.
	   The Poster Contest got underway this afternoon - with a hallful
of students from the Sulaiman School, the Khai Mun School, and
M.E.S. We can see that the quality of the posters is going to be
very high, and it will be extremely difficult to judge them.
	   The theme was Give to the Lady Templer Hospital Fund; the drive
had begun, and tomorrow they'll be selling flags in the school. The
Fun Fair had been cancelled for some reason or other, but there
will be a money- raising social at the Kwongsi Association tomorrow
night.
	   They're even selling tickets to tomorrow's football game - but I
wondered how they intend to control the crowd who haven't bought
tickets.
	   The main event of the day was the Poster Contest. We kept the
contestants strictly to the time limit and collected all the
posters, finished or not, at five.
	   Three teachers from Khai Mun School came to help with the
judging, but no one came from Sulaiman School.
	   First prize went to a boy from the Khai Mun School, but we took
second (Osman) and third (Johari); Tengku Ahmad and Lurn Kok Seng
both got Honourable Mentions.
	   After the judging, it was raining, and we had to wait quite
awhile before it slackened enough for us to take the posters to the
Kwongsi Association where we pinned them up on display for
tonight's social.
	   I didn't make it out tonight because it rained constantly, but
the boys who took their night out stopped by to see the display. No
one was more surprised at the results than Tengku Ahmad.
	   When the clothes came back from the dhoby this afternoon, the
boys doing the checking found several pieces that had no laundry
marks on them.
	   I distributed the clothes and asked each boy to take them
upstairs and mark them right then and there.
	   Alias was marking his, so I asked Sunny to borrow Alias' ink to
do his.
	   ``No,'' said Sunny, ``he's not my friend.''
	   I called them down and asked: ``Now what's this all about?'' It
seems they were having a spat because Alias had called Sunny
`kling'.
	   So we had a long talk, and in the end they shook hands.
	   I hope that's the end of it.
	   The boys in Forms Three and Four are beginning to get worried
about the approaching exams. Munzir and Murad had even gone so far
as to request permission to stay up late and/or get up early to
study.
	   They really are worried! Osman Sham spent his last day with us
and left for Ipoh this afternoon to take up his post as assistant
district officer.
	   He may not be stationed in Ipoh, but he had to report there for
his appointment.
	   We certainly hated to see him go because the Form Three and Four
students were just beginning to learn something about Geography,
Math, and Science - but we were happy for him.
	   We expect great things of Osman, and, as one of the boys said:
``Some day he'll be famous and we'll be proud that he was our
teacher.''
	   Inspector Niuh told me this morning that the police would be all
out to win their game with us this evening, and afterwards he
boasted: ``Well, we got our revenge.'' The score was 4-1 in favour
of the police, and there were several scratches and bruises to
doctor tonight.
	   I promised the boys that if we won the game we'd have Cha Cha
Cha Boom here at the hostel tonight. Needless to say, we spent the
evening studying.
	   Some of the LCE students are going to stay up until 11: and
Munzir tells me he has set his alarm for four in the morning. I
wonder if he'll hear it go off.
	   
</TEXT>
