<SLUG> BC-UN-Drug Blame, 1st Ld-Writethru,0579 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Drug producers point finger at U.S. and its drug users
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with Samper saying incentives must be
offered to drug farmers &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT H. REID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Taking issue with U.S. views, Colombia's
president said Tuesday that wiping out narcotic fields will be
ineffective in the long run without programs to encourage farmers
to grow alternate crops.
	   ``Our experience has been that forced eradication, if not
accompanied by crop substitution programs, we find illicit crops in
the very same fields,'' President Ernesto Samper told reporters
during the second day of the U.N. General Assembly special session
on drugs.
	   Samper said Colombia has been carrying out fumigation programs
to destroy illicit cocoa fields.
	   ``But once the field has been fumigated, if there is no program
to offer the peasant crop substitution, he has no other choice but
to resow cocoa,'' Samper added.
	   During the three-day conference, which began Monday, delegates
from 150 countries are considering a U.N. program to combat drugs
in the next century.
	   The plan calls for, among other things, offering Third World
farmers financial incentives to stop growing opium poppies, cocoa
and cannabis.
	   During his speech to the opening session, President Clinton
announced a dlrs 2 billion, five-year media campaign against drugs,
targeting young people with a message that drugs ``destroy young
lives.''
	   Only dlrs 175 million of the dlrs 2 billion would be federal
funds; the rest would be contributed by corporations and
philanthropic organizations.
	   But U.S. officials showed little enthusiasm for the U.N. crop
substitution program, which is also unpopular in the
Republican-dominated Congress. Critics consider the plan
ineffective and simply a move to pay off the very people at the
root of the global drug crisis.
	   ``It is not clear to me that resources will bulldoze the
solution,'' U.S. drug czar Barry McCaffrey told reporters Monday.
``It's a problem for regional community solutions, not just funding
for alternative economic development.''
	   But Samper said the issue is one of economic practicality.
Colombian farmers can earn 10 times as much money from growing
cocoa as from corn, he said.
	   ``So to ask (a farmer) to sow a crop he cannot sell when he's
got an option that's 10 times more profitable is impractical,''
Samper said. ``I hope the U.S. Congress understands this.''
	   During his speech, Clinton also urged world leaders to avoid
``pointing fingers'' and work together to combat drugs. But that
did not prevent speakers from the Caribbean and Latin America for
blaming drug-consuming nations like the United States for not doing
its share to reduce demand.
	   ``The illicit drug trade is demand-driven,'' Prime Minister
Denzil Douglas of the tiny Caribbean nation of St. Kitts and Nevis
said. ``How can we truly expect small, poor countries such as mine
to defeat the wealthy drug lords if the rich countries, with their
wealth of resources, are unsuccessful in limiting the demand.''
	   President Hugo Banzer of Bolivia said his government was
committed to eradicating illegal production of cocoa, which is used
to produce cocaine.
	   But Banzer said the program will cost dlrs 952 million over five
years. He appealed to the United States and other wealthy countries
to pick up 85 percent of the cost of the program.
</TEXT>
