<HEADLINE>
Making schoolbus travel safer, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Making schoolbus travel safer, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Hamidah AtanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MALACCA, Sat. - The Transport Ministry has called for a meeting
with the schoolbus operators' associations to discuss ways to
prevent accidents involving pupils.
	   Deputy Minister Datuk Wira Mohd Ali Rustam said the meeting
would be held at his office in Kuala Lumpur next week.
	   ``Since the beginning of this year, three kindergarten pupils
have been killed in accidents.
	   ``We hope to get input from association members on preventing
accidents,''
	   he said after visiting the family of P. Darsheni Dewi, six, who
was killed when she was run over by a schoolbus in front of her
house in Taman Bukit Sebukor on Monday.
	   She was alighting from the bus when she fell. Not realising she
had fallen, the driver drove off.
	   Mohd Ali said police are investigating.
	   ``The driver has been released on bail of RM5,000,'' he said.
	   Under section 41(1) of the Road Transport Act, offenders shall
be liable to imprisonment of up to five years or fines not
exceeding RM10,000 or both.
	   Mohd Ali said drivers and bus conductors must be responsible for
children's safety. ``They must always make sure that the children
reach their homes safely,'' he said.
	   
