<HEADLINE>
European Central Bank's governing board holds first meeting
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Duisenberg quotes on bank capital, gold reserves &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ The policymaking board of the new
European Central Bank held its first meeting Tuesday as part of
preparations for the launch of the continent's single currency next
year.
	   At a news conference afterward, bank president Wim Duisenberg
said the 11 central banks in the euro zone will pay around 4
billion euros into the ECB's base capital by July 1. One euro is
expected to be worth roughly the same as a dollar.
	   He also said there was a consensus among the central bankers
that between 10 percent and 15 percent of the total reserves to be
transferred to the ECB will be in gold.
	   But the meeting largely avoided monetary questions, focusing
instead on internal issues.
	   ``Some organizational decisions have been made,'' Luxembourg
central bank head Yves Mersch said. Spanish central bank head Luis
Angel Rojo said it entailed ``only procedures, and no decisions.''
	   Bank of France Governor Jean-Claude Trichet and his Portuguese
colleague, Antonio de Sousa, called the meeting ``historic,'' and
others also expressed satisfaction with it.
	   The bank's six-member executive board and the 11 heads of the
central banks of nations participating in European currency union
make up the governing council.
	   The bank, based in Frankfurt, will set monetary policy for the
11 inaugural members when monetary union begins Jan. 1.
 &UR; (pfg)
</TEXT>
