w1370 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  THE-WHEEZEsked     06-09 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> THE-WHEEZE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
What's behind the wheeze?, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
What's behind the wheeze?, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Luisa DillnerASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE UK has one of the highest rates of childhood asthma in the
world, 20 times higher than Romania and Indonesia, says a study in
the Lancet. No country wants to head the league table of a disease
and it's dismal, indeed, that the UK is not only the place where as
a woman you're most likely to die from breast cancer, but also to
have your children inconvenienced by wheezing.
	   A total of 463,801 children aged from 13-14 in 56 countries were
asked the same questions (such as, `have you had wheezing or
whistling in the chest in the last 12 months?') to ascertain the
level of, not only asthma, but other related allergic conditions.
	   The highest level of reported symptoms of asthma were in
English- speaking countries, specifically, the UK, New Zealand,
Australia and the Republic of Ireland. The other allergic
conditions were more widely distributed world-wide. Previous
studies have shown the same pattern, with such mysteries as why the
US has substantially lower rates of the disease compared with the
UK.
	   Over one million children in the UK have asthma, and the
incidence of the disease has risen ludicrously, doubling between
1964 and 1989. So far there are no clear leads. Increasing
awareness and better diagnosis by family doctors can only explain
part of the rise.
	   While pollution is an obvious candidate, the Lancet study
suggested that the global pattern showed that it was not a major
risk factor for developing the disease, although it may exacerbate
the condition.
	   China and Eastern Europe, which have some of the highest levels
of air pollutants generally had low rates of asthma, while New
Zealand, not known for its smog, had one of the highest levels.
Similarly, a study carried out by the UK part of ISAAC, published
earlier this year in the BMJ found that the incidence of asthma in
12-14-years-olds was higher in rural than in urban areas.
	   Apart from pollution, the other suspect has been the microscopic
but sinister house-dust mite, thought to have been encouraged by
the British's unhealthy penchant for wall to wall carpeting and
tropical levels of central heating. But house-dust mites on their
own, (although reducing levels does relieve symptoms) are not
responsible for the epidemic of asthma, Neither are pets, which
exacerbate symptoms but don't start them off.
	   Rather it is likely to be a concoction of things, many of which
researchers are already on to. The emphasis is moving towards
trying to prevent children from getting asthma, and some measures
involve taking action at a fetal level. You can't change your genes
(yet) and a strong family history of allergy or asthma can lead to
a 40 per cent chance of a child getting it. If your mother suffers
from allergies, your risk is higher than if your father does. Yet
environmental factors may be essential to trigger the switch.
	   This switch can mean the difference between developing an immune
system that responds appropriately to irritants or one that
produces the symptoms of asthma: wheezing, night-time cough,
breathlessness on exercise and chest tightness.
	   Poverty has been linked to asthma, the specific factors being
dampness and moulds. High salt diets, and junk food in particular
have been linked to an increase in asthma rates.
	   Breast feeding has long been thought to be protective but the
evidence is not clear cut, and it may need to be prolonged (for up
to a year) to be effective. It does reduce the risk of exzema and
food allergy and for a million other reasons is worth doing.
	   Children with older siblings are less likely to get asthma,
probably because they are exposed to infections very early in life,
which may overwhelm their immune system into behaving normally.
	   Cigarette smoke is consistently found to trigger symptoms of
asthma, and smoking in pregnancy is thought to increase the risk of
a child developing the disease. Maternal diet and exposure to
environmental triggers may also play a part.
	   While researchers are trying to detect why asthma rates vary so
much across the globe, there are worrying signs that the disease is
still undetected.
	   The ISAAC research found that up to 3 per cent of the over
27,000 children in the study had moderate to severe asthma symptoms
but had never been diagnosed or treated.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
