<BODY>
<SLUG> MEASURES-FOR-UNEMPLOYMEN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Measures for unemployment not enough, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Measures for unemployment not enough, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Kamol Sukin reports on the government's mishandling of the
country's labour problems.
	   The seven government measures to solve unemployment, officially
over two million Thais are unemployed, seem to be too little, too
late.
	   The measure seen as the most solid, so far, was when the
government forced out illegal foreign workers to increase
employment opportunities for Thais. However, the policy has been
called a misconception because foreign workers had been employed
for jobs that Thais had refused because they were too tiring or
paid too little.
	   This measure was aimed to make 300,000 jobs, held by illegal
foreign workers in 35 provinces, vacant. The latest report from the
Labour Department said that 120,000 workers had been repatriated
but only 80,000 of the vacancies had been filled by Thais.
	   The second measure was to create jobs, with cooperation from
construction contractors who had been asked to use manpower instead
of machines. This too was criticised because it was considered
short-term employment which would cover a very small number of the
unemployed.
	   The government also attempted to continue employment in the
industrial sector, however its implementation has been considered
unsystematic.
	   One of the few projects which have received widespread support
is the one initiated by His Majesty the King on integrated farming.
However, it has been considered a long-term project with no clear
target and therefore, impractical.
	   The other three projects -- the Thai-Help-Thai project which
sells cheap consumer goods to raise cash; the project through which
Thai labourers are sent to work overseas and the project to monitor
and asses all other measures -- are merely campaign measures rather
than an effective solution to the problem.
	   Most of the seven measures launched by the national unemployment
committee, headed by Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai, were not really
welcomed by groups, especially labour organisations. The projects
did not receive any applause mainly because they seem to provide
little help for the unemployed.
	   ''Only less than 15 per cent of all written in the paper was
implemented,'' head of the State Enterprise Labour Association
Somsak Kosaisuk said.
	   Prof Nikhom Chandrawitoon, social critic and government adviser
on labour affairs, said the measures were inefficient because their
bureaucratic process caused problems.
	   The lack of sufficient data is another problem which has brought
about the mishandling of the issue, Labour economist Lae
Dilokwattayarat said agreeing with critics and labour
organisations.
	   ''The best example is the data about amount of unemployment in
the country. The figure of two million was estimated based on the
figure collected from reports of bureaucrats. How unreliable could
it be?'' he said.
	   However, according to the latest report from the National
Statistics Office unemployment is as high as 2.8 million, which
does not include the 500,000 new graduates, or 8.8 per cent of the
country's total labour force, who are still jobless.
	   Vice president of Thailand's Development Research Institute
(TDRI) Niphon Phuaphongsathorn has recently suggested that the
government establish a labour information centre to make management
systematic, efficient and transparent.
	   The government's mismanagement of labour has been widely
criticised as one without vision. Critics say that the government's
window dressing is not enough and what's really needed are labour
protection laws and regulations.
	   The 1998 Labour Protection Act will finally be enforced on Aug
19 this year. However, the Low Income Labour Fund as well as the
Unemployment Fund, considered by labour organisations as the proper
tool, have received no response from the government over the past
six months. Labour-related funds as well as the urgent fund for the
unemployed, supported by Prof Nikhom, have hardly been able to
attract the government's attention.
	   ''Labour issues are the last priority when compared to financial
ones,'' concluded Prof Nikhom.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
