<SLUG> PEOPLE-WATCH sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
People Watch, NATION
</HEADLINE>
People Watch, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   They may have different lifestyles, but Ray McDonald, Yuenyong
Opakul and Amita Tata Young have one thing in common -- they have
decided to buy shares of Bangchak Petroleum Plc.
	   The celebrities said they did not want to see the Thai-owned
company taken over by foreigners.
	   ''If I can help, I will. It's time for Thai people to help each
other. Actually there are many people out there who can afford to
buy some shares. We should do it,'' said Ray, a popular actor.
	   Songs-for-life artist Yuenyong, better known as Ad Carabao, said
he would ask his fans to buy some shares.
	   ''I just want to sneer at the power brokers [who say Bangchak
should be sold]. I want to show them that people like us think
differently from them,'' he said.
	   Teen-idol Tata Young, meanwhile, said Bangchak should be run by
Thais and that Thai people should be its beneficiaries.
	   -------Having abandoned the political arena for two years to
farm and run a leadership training school in Kanchanaburi, former
Palang Dharma Party leader Chamlong Srimuang seems to have much
more time to reflect.
	   He says he prefers living an austere life to being a politician.
	   ''It doesn't mean that I want to avoid hard work [as a
politician]. Compared with my political career, I feel more
comfortable with my current job,'' he said.
	   He admitted that his life has dramatically changed -- from being
always in the limelight to living in a rural area.
	   ''Actually I didn't want to seek popularity. But fame is a
by-product [for people in politics]. At that time life was hectic
and I didn't have time for myself. But now I'm happier,'' he said.
	   His wife Sirilak Srimuang agreed.
	   ''We feel more relaxed than before. When he was a politician, I
was always concerned about him, especially about his security
during election campaigns,'' she said.
	   Although many supporters had asked Chamlong to return to
politics, Sirilak said she tried to persuade him to stay clear of
it.
	   -------Despite a busy schedule, particularly over a takeover
battle for a big Belgian bank, Jan Kalff, chairman of ABN Amro Bank
from The Netherlands, has confirmed his visit to Bangkok this week.
He is due to host a reception at The Oriental hotel Tuesday.
	   ABN Amro Bank is increasing its presence in Thailand with a new
office and the recent control of Bank of Asia.
	   In case he misses home, here is the lead report from the Wall
Street Journal Europe: ''Jan Kalff should have read his Julius
Caesar. In the Gallic War, the Roman emperor recounts how he nearly
lost the conquest of Europe to a rag-tag alliance of Belgian
tribes. Last weekend, a similar alliance all but dashed the hopes
of ABN Amro's chairman for conquering Europe's retail banking
market.'' 
</TEXT>
