<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OAU-Ethiopia-Eritrea, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
African leaders propose peace mission to Ethiopia, Eritrea
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with summit agreeing in principle to send mission;
reaction from Eritrea and Ethiopia; minor edits; no pickup &QL; 
 &UR; By GLENN MCKENZIE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   OUAGADOUGOU, Burkina Faso (AP) _ African leaders on Tuesday
agreed in principle to send a peace mission to the Horn of Africa
where Ethiopia and Eritrea showed no signs of abandoning their
deadly border dispute.
	   But rganization of African Unity spokesman Pascal Gayama said no
final decision was taken by the 29 heads of state and government
who debated the issue during a closed-door session devoted almost
entirely to the conflict.
	   Eritrean Foreign Minister Haile Woldetensae praised the idea,
but his Ethiopian counterpart Seyoum Mesfin downplayed the
proposal, saying his country did not favor ``a proliferation of
mediation attempts.''
	   Last week the United States and Rwanda presented both sides with
a four-point peace plan that included, among others, a
recommendation that Eritrea withdraw to positions held before May 6
when clashes first began.
	   Ethiopia accepted the plan, but Eritrea said it was incomplete.
	   A Burkina Faso diplomat, who asked not to be further identified,
said the delegation would likely be headed by Burkina President
Blaise Campaore in his current role as OAU chairman and would
include presidents from each of Africa's five major regions.
	   In a statement issued at the three-day summit, the Eritrean
Foreign Ministry warned that its infantry and heavy artillery were
preparing to retaliate following an Ethiopian air attack early
Tuesday on Eritrean troops near Zala Ambessa, 105 kilometers (65
miles), southeast of the Ertirean capital, Asmara.
	   Eritrean forces captured the Ethiopian border town in a June 2-4
battle. Ethiopia charged Tuesday that Eritrean troops had attacked
its defensive positions south of the town.
	   Fresh troops deployed to the area would ``confront these attacks
resolutely in order to defend (Eritrea's) sovereignty and
territorial integrity,'' the Foreign Ministry statement said.
	   Eritrea accused its opponents of launching a `` wave of
offensives,'' including ``indiscriminate attacks on civilians,''
but said Asmara remained hopeful that the solution to the dispute
``lies in peace and legality.''
	   Late Monday, the foreign ministers from both countries traded
accusations that each side was escalating the conflict which began
in mid-May. Ethiopian Foreign Minister Seyoum Mesfin threatened
that Eritrea faced ``full-scale war'' unless it accepted a peace
plan proposed by Rwandan and U.S. negotiators.
	   Eritrea ``has opted to escalate the conflict to a full-scale
war, for which it has to bear full responsibility for the
consequences,'' Seyoum said.
	   The Ethiopian minister urged the OAU to pressure Eritrea to
withdraw from disputed areas before entering talks. Eritrea says it
is inside its own territory and calls instead for an immediate
cease-fire and the start of direct talks ``in the presence of
high-level mediators.''
	   (gm/sl)	   
</TEXT>
