<BODY>
<SLUG> RESERVES-EXPECTED-HELP sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Reserves expected to help end crisis, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Reserves expected to help end crisis, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   PIYANART SRIVALOASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Interior Ministry will receive the biggest chunk from the
Bt30 billion the government plans to draw from fiscal reserves to
revive the economy through social safety-net programmes, a
well-informed source said Monday.
	   The Government House source said the Budget Bureau has finalised
how to divide the Bt30 billion and will propose additional
allocations for the Cabinet's approval Tuesday.
	   The Interior Ministry will receive Bt6.6 billion from the budget
increase, the source said. Earlier, the Interior Ministry's
proposed spending was cut by Bt33.5 billion.
	   On June 2, the Cabinet resolved to draw Bt30 billion from the
reserve for spending as part of the the 1998 fiscal year, which
ends in September.
	   According to the source, the Budget Bureau set Bt2 billion of
the amount as a central fund for maintaining baht stability and
dividing the rest among ministries for launching social safety-net
projects.
	   The second largest earner from the increased budget will be the
Communications Ministry, which will receive Bt5.794 billion. Its
budget has been cut by Bt23.549 billion. The Education Ministry
will receive Bt4.764 billion, making it the third largest earner
from the increase budget. Earlier its budget was cut by Bt9.628
billion.
	   The Agriculture Ministry will become the fourth largest earner
of the increased budget with Bt2.945 billion.
	   The Budget Bureau has allocated Bt2.7 billion from the increased
budget to the Public Health Ministry, making it the fifth largest
earner.
	   
</TEXT>
