w1390 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  WAR-OF-WORDS-WORSENSsked     06-09 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> WAR-OF-WORDS-WORSENS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
War of words worsens, NATION
</HEADLINE>
War of words worsens, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE wars of words between the Democrat Party and the New
Aspiration Party intensified Monday with the former threatening to
file a libel suit against its rival.
	   Prime Minister and Democrat leader Chuan Leekpai, meanwhile,
gave the greenlight for PM's deputy secretary general Nipon
Boonyapattharo to send a letter criticising NAP's Parliament
President Wan Mohammad Noor Matha for having attacked Chuan.
	   NAP leader Chavalit Yongchaiyudh also joined the fray Monday,
saying Chuan did not have anything to say except to attack other
politicians over alleged vote-buying.
	   The war of words originated from a satirical comment from Chuan
over the NAP's plan to make in-roads into the Democrat's stronghold
in the South. Chuan said the NAP can try to expand in the South but
it should not bring the scourge of vote-buying there.
	   Wan Noor retaliated by saying that the Democrats also bought
votes, especially in Phichit, which is the home province of
Democrat secretary-general Sanan Kachornprasart.
	   Without naming names, Wan Noor said a former NAP MP in Phichit,
who is now a Cabinet member and who defected to the Democrats, also
bought votes when he was with the NAP.
	   A Democrat source said the party's legal experts had considered
and believed that Democrat Deputy Commerce Minister Paitoon
Kaewthong could sue the Parliament president for defamation.
Paitoon, a Phichit MP, had defected from the NAP.
	   Reaffirming his statement, Wan Noor said he made the comment
during an internal party seminar and he could not help it if
newspapers played it up.
	   Wan Noor said he did not name names but the media could figure
out who it was ''so this is a fact''.
	   In his letter to the Parliament president, Nipon pointed out
that Chuan was simply making a general comment, asking the NAP to
''support'' the traditional political practice in the South, which
abhors vote-buying.
	   ''So, I would like to ask your excellency, Wan Mohammad Noor,
whether you came to the conclusion yourself. What did the prime
minister do to infuriate you so much that you lost control and
attacked the prime minister. Please explain,'' Nipon said in the
letter.
	   Nipon said he had informed Chuan about the letter and the prime
minister had not stopped him from submitting it to the Parliament
president.
	   Chavalit said Monday that it was no good getting angry with
Chuan about his vote-buying comment, ''because the prime minister
knows how to speak about only a few things -- principles, laws and
vote-buying''.
	   Later, Chuan confirmed that he had allowed Nipon to send the
letter and added that Democrat MPs would retaliate against any
criticism from the NAP.
	   
</TEXT>
