<SLUG> PRESSURE-PUTS-EXIM sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pressure puts Exim on defensive, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Pressure puts Exim on defensive, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Export-Import (Exim) Bank of Thailand's president Monday
defended the bank's lending policy following alleged political
pressure for his dismissal.
	   MR Pridiyathorn Devakula was blamed for failing to help ease the
liquidity crunch by providing more loans to cash-strapped
companies.
	   To boost companies' liquidity, the Exim bank received a Bt113
billion loan from local and foreign financial institutions. Of this
amount, Bt59.87 billion was allocated to exporters, leaving a
balance of Bt53.12 billion loan, or 53 per cent.
	   This facility of Bt113 billion included Bt33 billion packing
credit of the Bank of Thailand and $500 million from foreign banks.
	   It also included Bt12 billion from Japan's Exim bank and Bt40
billion loan from Asian Development Bank (ADB).
	   The Exim bank said it had allocated the ADB loan to 15 local
commercial banks. However, the money was still inaccessible to
exporters pending document approval to Exim by ADB.
	   Deputy Prime Minister and Commerce Minister Supachai
Panitchpakdi said there was a debate among economic ministers on
the role of the bank, but reasons given by the bank were
acceptable.
	   Supachai said there was no talk on the dismissal of the bank's
president.
	   The bank did not cause the problem as alleged, but companies
appeared not to be interested in borrowing the remainder.
	   For longer-term loan, the Exim bank is supposed to provide a
total of Bt3 billion for maritime and industry structural
adjustment. According to its plan, the Exim bank will grant a
5-year soft loan to the maritime business with Exim Bank
contributing another 50 per cent of the amount.
	   Another Bt1 billion from the central bank to exporters is for
change of machinery. Exim Bank will contribute another 75 per cent
of the amount.
	   A major problem is that Exim Bank borrowed in dollar term to
match the amount from Bank of Thailand since most borrowers wanted
dollar loans. Secondly, structural adjustment loan (SAL) in baht
(Bt1 billion) for maritime and machinery change has run into
problem since baht loan is not convenient for matching fund and
cost of this SAL is higher than other sources. Borrowers, who
wanted to borrow in baht, therefore, preferred baht loan from BOT
which is cheaper.
	   However, the Exim bank believed that private firms would turn to
borrow the SAL facility after the central bank used up its Bt3
billion. Currently, the Exim bank approved a Bt448 million SAL for
exporters to change its machinery.
	   In addition, US Exim has agreed to lend US$1 billion loan
(approx Bt4 billion) as a stand-by-guarantee through the Exim bank,
could not provide to the private firms because the loan agreement
has not been signed.
	   n Meanwhile, Exim Bank was also urged to increase packing credit
amounts lending to the sugar mills as liquidity-hit commercial
banks are expected to cut their lending to the sugar industry in
the upcoming sugarcane milling season.
	   In the last season, the Exim Bank and commercial banks had put
together Bt25 billion as packing credits to the sugar industry,
with the eximbank contributing Bt2.6 billion. According to an
official from the Industry Ministry, based on the projected 45
million tonnes of sugarcane output, the sugar industry would
require Bt27 billion of packing credit amounts in the 1998/99
upcoming season.
	   ''If the commercial banks reduce the packing credit amounts, the
eximbank will have to substitute the amounts unless it would affect
the capability of sugar mills in paying money to the cane
growers'', said the official. Sugar mills are usually bring in
their letter of credits from forward sugar sales contracts for
making the packing credits in Nov enabling them to have cash paying
to cane growers for the cane inputs.
	   Last week, the Bank for Agriculture and Agricultural
Cooperative, the Government Saving Bank, and the Bank of Thailand
have agreed in principal to extend Bt6 billion for sugar mills to
have the so-called kiew money borrowing to the cane planters. Kiew
money is an advance payment made to cane growers for them to have
funding for their cane plantations.
	   The office of Cane and Sugar Board is also negotiating with ABN
Amro Bank, Rabo Bank and ING Baring to choose one of them within
this month to lend US$80 million to the Thai cane and sugar
industry. According to the official, half of the offshore loan will
be allocated to sugar mills for fixing and maintenance of their
machineries and the other half for kiew money purpose.
	   The BAAC loan, amounted to Bt3 billion, will be available from
June 15.
	   
</TEXT>
