<SLUG> MECHAI-MAKES-TOT-ANNOUNC sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mechai makes TOT announce its board agenda, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Mechai makes TOT announce its board agenda, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   USANEE MONGKOLPORNASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Telephone Organisation of Thailand's (TOT) chairman Mechai
Viravaidya has started his new information-accessibility policy by
having the board disclose its agenda to the public Monday.
	   Mechai insists that TOT be transparent because the agency's
business has a great impact on public well-being.
	   ''TOT is an agency responsible for several public services.
Every step it takes has to be transparent. The meeting's agenda is
something which will tell the public what we are doing,'' Mechai
said.
	   It is the first time in 44 years, since it has been established,
that TOT has decided to release information considered
confidential. However, the other state telecom carrier, the
Communications Authority of Thailand (CAT) does not have such a
policy.
	   Since the TOT is preparing for its privatisation later this
year, public exposure is one of the many tasks it has to undertake
before it is listed on the stock market.
	   A state enterprise policy committee, chaired by Deputy Prime
Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi, will meet next week to discuss ways
to make the stock listing process for TOT and its neighbour CAT
successful.
	   Meanwhile Mechai also restructured the board's organisation by
making TOT's president work as the board secretary instead of
letting the executive vice president do the job.
	   The board secretary plays an important role in screening the
board's agenda and information, thus making him a target for
private lobbyists who seek special favours. Sometimes companies
even track inside information about a board meeting from the board
secretary. This gives the board secretary considerable power.
	   In the past some board secretaries have demanded secret
payments, for example a percentage of the value of the proposed
project, from private proponents, according to TOT sources.
	   ''Many international organisations have the top boss work as a
board secretary, so our president should do this job as well,''
Mechai said.
	   To create transparency in the organisation, Mechai has
instructed TOT to let employees' representatives attend every board
meeting to help create mutual understanding.
	   According to the agenda released Monday, the management will
report its business activities until the end of March, the second
quarter of TOT's fiscal year, which ends in September.
	   Also they will report the burden to be shouldered by TOT after
private concessionaire RadioPhone Co pulled out of the business,
leaving 7,719 trunk mobile-phone terminals in the state agency's
care.
	   RadioPhone terminated its contract on April 1, claiming that
business prospects were too low.
	   The cancellation of Ericsson's bid for supplying telephone
equipment for integrated services digital network (ISDN), the use
of digital switches to improve TOT's network and the agency's plans
with satellite mobile-phone service GlobalStar were some of the
agenda issues announced.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
