<BODY>
<SLUG> CP-CONSOLIDATES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CP consolidates for results, NATION
</HEADLINE>
CP consolidates for results, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Charoen Pokphand Group has taken a major step to consolidate
12 companies of the group through share swaps and warrants so that
its agro-industrial and aquaculture businesses are under one listed
vehicle -- Charoen Pokphand Feedmill Plc (CPF).
	   Monday, CPF said it will tender an offer to swap shares of the
three listed units -- Charoen Pokphond Northeastern Plc (CPNE),
Bangkok Agro-Industrial Products Plc (BAP), and Bangkok Produce
Merchandising Plc (BKP).
	   For the nine unlisted firms, CPF will issue warrants for CP
Group, major shareholders of these firms. The plan is subject to
shareholder resolution approval on July 14.
	   The nine unlisted companies are Bangkok Feedmill Co Ltd, Charoen
Pokphand Industry Co Ltd, Bangkok Livestock Processing Co Ltd,
Bangkok Farm Co Ltd, CP Agro Industry Co Ltd, BP Feedmill Co Ltd,
Ratchaburi Feedmill Co Ltd, CP Food Product Co Ltd, and CP Food
Industry Export Co Ltd.
	   Ratchaburi Feedmill is a subsidiary of Bangkok Feedmill. CP Food
Product is a subsidiary of Bangkok Livestock Processing, while CP
Food Industry Export is a subsidiary of Bangkok Livestock
Processing and Bangkok Farm.
	   ''The consolidation falls in line with market sentiment that if
the group's businesses are not doing well, joining the companies
that operates similar businesses into one might bring better
results. However, the share swap will not bring new money to CPF,''
said an analyst of a local brokerage house.
	   He said consolidation through such method is good because the
three companies can be delisted from the stock market without
suffering a loss of image. Also, they can later re-enter the
market.
	   Kongkiat Opaswongkarn, CEO of Asset Plus Securities Co Ltd, said
consolidation of listed and unlisted units is one way to
restructure CP's vast business empire.
	   He said creditors of CP will also have more alternatives in
negotiations with the group on debts.
	   CP previously diversified aggressively into non-core businesses
resulting in heavy foreign debts.
	   In the process of consolidation, CPF will raise registered
capital to Bt2.73 billion from Bt1.2 billion through the issuance
of 153.49 million new common shares. Moreover, CPF will also sell
50 million warrants with a maturity of four years valued at a total
of Bt1 billion to CP Group.
	   According to the CPF, about 43.49 million capital increase
shares will be used to pay for acquisition of the three companies
-- CPNE, BAP, and BKP. The three companies are altogether worth
about Bt2.35 billion.
	   About 6.45 million capital shares of CPF will be swapped for the
shares of CPNE at the ratio of 27 CPF shares to 54 CPNE shares. CPF
will pay CPNE Bt27 apiece. After the share swap, CPF will hold
94.07 per cent in CPNE against the current ownership of 57 per
cent.
	   Another 13.62 million CPF capital increase shares will be
exchanged for BAP shares at the ratio of 61 CPF shares to 54 BAP
shares. BAP will offer CPF Bt61 a share. After consolidation, CPF's
stake in BAP will rise from 59.82 per cent to 90.17 per cent. For
the BKP sale, shares will be set at Bt22 apiece. CPF will exchange
about 23.4 of its capital increase shares with BKP shareholders at
the ratio of 22 CPF shares for 54 BKP shares. After the
transaction, CPF's 67.93 per cent stake in BKP will increase to
72.1 per cent.
	   Another 60 million new common CPF shares will be offered to
investors via a private placement. The remaining 50 million shares
will be reserved for its warrants which can be converted to the
company's common share at the ratio of 1:1 for Bt80 apiece.
	   CPF said it will pay cash for the purchase of Bangkok Feedmill,
Charoen Pokphand Industry, Bangkok Livestock Processing, Bangkok
Farm, CP Agro Industry, and BP Feedmill to CP Group. The deal is
totally worth Bt4 billion.
	   CP Group and its subsidiaries have signed an agreement with CPF
to divest their BAP, BKP and CPNE shares which will enable CPF and
its subsidiaries to hold at least 94, 82 and 91 per cent in BAP,
BKP and CPNE respectively.
	   According to the company, the objective of the consolidation is
to have the entire group's agro-industry and aquaculture businesses
to be under CPF which is a reflection of CPF's corporate strategy
to invest solely in its core business activities.
	   The recapitalisation of CPF will expand CPF's common shares from
the current 120 million shares to 213.5 million shares excluding
the warrants. The post-consolidation shareholding structure will be
CPG and its subsidiaries (49 per cent), cross-holding by CPF
subsidiaries (8 per cent), and public (43 per cent).
	   In terms of market capitalisation, the consolidation will place
CPF in the top 20 list of companies on the Stock Exchange of
Thailand.
	   CPF has appointed Phatra Securities as its financial advisers.
Phatra and Merrill Lynch (Asia-Pacific) are mandated the
joint-underwriters of the private placement issue.
	   
</TEXT>
