<HEADLINE>
BBC looks to Bt15 bn injection, NATION
</HEADLINE>
BBC looks to Bt15 bn injection, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   ANOMA SRISUKKASEMASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SCANDAL-PLAGUED Bangkok Bank of Commerce (BBC) is planning to
raise Bt15 billion in new capital to complete its plan of raising a
total of Bt25 billion.
	   BBC president Aswin Kongsiri made the statement after submitting
the recapitalisation plan to the Bank of Thailand for
consideration.
	   ''We want to increase capital as planned earlier, but the
central bank asks us to wait for a privatisation study conducted by
JP Morgan,'' he said.
	   Since taking over the management of BBC in May 1996, Industrial
Finance Corp of Thailand has proposed the bank be recapitalised by
Bt25 billion. As the central bank's Financial Institution
Development Fund holds a majority stake in the bank, it plans to
inject more money in addition to the Bt10 billion given the bank in
early 1998.
	   The economic crisis has caused a suspension of the plan as the
FIDF, which extended more than Bt1 trillion to cash-strapped
financial institutions, cannot spend money without government
approval.
	   Aswin Monday met officials of JP Morgan, a US investment bank
tasked to complete privatisation plans for all four nationalised
banks -- BBC, First Bangkok City Bank, Siam City Bank and Bangkok
Metropolitan Bank.
	   Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda said earlier the
privatisation plans should be completed around the end of this
month.
	   Aswin Monday ruled out the possibility that his bank would be
merged with state-run Krung Thai Bank (KTB) as rumoured after BOT
Governor MR Chatu Mongol Sonakul said last week the financial
authorities planned to merge the three nationalised banks,
excluding BBC, to one or two entities to conserve banking licences
in the next few years.
	   He said IFCT has a clear plan for reviving the bank. Aswin said
he has submitted a rehabilitation plan to the central bank. Under
the plan, IFCT will eventually purchase a 10 per cent stake in BBC
every year until its stake reaches 50 per cent. Next year, when the
management period reaches three years, IFCT is allowed to hold a 11
per cent stake.
	   ''Thus, merger with KTB should not take place,'' Aswin said.
	   He said the bank is now tackling its rising non-performing loans
in the face of the country's deteriorating economy. Aswin also
believes loan restructuring regulations announced by the central
bank should help curb NPLs as well as the bankruptcy law.
	   Aswin told reporters BBC's credit growth is minimal due to
illiquidity. However, he predicted the economy will recover next
year and help reduce the bank's deposit costs. Moreover, the
further recapitalisation will help boost credit growth.
	   ''BBC will then extend more loans to [the real sector],'' he
added.
	   
</TEXT>
