<BODY>
<SLUG> CRISIS-HIT-CP-SHEDS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Crisis-hit CP sheds more assets, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Crisis-hit CP sheds more assets, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Charoen Pokphand Group will sell its non-core assets to
maintain the growth of its agro-business, telecommunications and
7-Eleven convenience store franchise, according to chairman Dhanin
Chearavanont.
	   One of Thailand's largest conglomerates, it will as a result of
the regional economic crisis sell or find partners for its
petrochemical and discount store operations as well as its non-core
activities in China such as the motorcycle operations and brewery,
he said.
	   CP Group recently sold part of its stake in 12 Lotus discount
stores nationwide to Tesco Co, a UK-based supermarket group, while
its motorcycle plant in Shanghai was sold to the local state
authorities.
	   Dhanin said Ford Motor Co of the US is interested in buying CP
Group's other motorcycle plant in China to use as a platform for an
engine production company there.
	   ''People still look for a partnership with us because we have
quality management in China,'' he said.
	   CP Group is also selling its brewery joint venture with Heineken
in China as well as the oil extraction plant and wheat flour plant
there. It recently sold its Chinese satellite operation.
	   ''Our aim is to secure the operation of the parent company in
Thailand,'' Dhanin admitted.
	   Dhanin said Thailand's economic freedom is, in a de facto sense,
at an end because foreigners have seized the country's financial
sector -- the lifeblood of businesses. But the CP Group chief noted
that while foreign investors and creditors have the money,
technology and manpower skill -- all of which Thailand lacks --
they must still operate or be made to abide by Thai laws.
	   CP Group has a foreign loan exposure through the parent company
and TelecomAsia Plc.
	   Other CP executives said the group's activities in Indonesia
have also been hit by the current economic trends, with the large
depreciation of the local currency causing costs of feed imports to
spiral.
	   Its shrimp farming operation located on Java was undermined by
rising feed costs, while demand for chicken fell by half.
	   Dhanin said the overall exports of the group were still bright.
CP will maintain and expand its agro-business operations because
''we have a comparative advantage on a global basis.'' He said the
group wants to expand into fish and non-toxic vegetable production
worldwide.
	   ''We want to move into processed food production to sell to
developed markets such as the US and to buy from them their fish
heads, pork legs, etc, which the Americans do not eat.'' CP Group
has also set sights on forging a partnership with Seattle-based
Microsoft Co, the world's largest computer software company, to
launch electronic money cards called ''Electronic Wallets'' for
customers of the nearly 1,000 7-Eleven convenience stores.
	   ''It is truly electronic and the customers do not need cash at
all. We can also facilitate insurance sales and coverage through
the cards,'' he said.
	   Each 7-Eleven store will have personal computers for customers
to use as a multimedia vehicle. The CP Group also plans to
introduce web-TV through a UTV cable operation with Microsoft.
	   
</TEXT>
