<HEADLINE>
20 real estate firms keen on joining hands with holiday time-share unit, NATION
</HEADLINE>
20 real estate firms keen on joining hands with holiday time-share unit, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   TWENTY real estate developers have expressed their interest in
joining local holiday time-share firm Multiple Travel Club Co's
(MTC) as the number of participants is expected to double this
year.
	   MTC, a leading operator of holiday time-shares in Thailand,
announced on June 1 and 2 that it was seeking new business partners
to join the company's time-share programme in Pattaya, Phuket and
Koh Samui. Between June 1 and 5, about 20 operators of hotels,
resorts or condominiums contacted MTC about joining the programme,
according to MTC president Vittayen Muttamara.
	   Five of the companies were from the North, including Chiang Mai,
Chiang Rai, and Lampang provinces. Seven were from the South, and
four each were from the East and Northeast.
	   MTC said only 11 of the 20 companies would qualify to join the
time-share programme.
	   With a significant number of real estate developers joining the
programme under the current economic situation, the holiday travel
management service has been shown to be effective in attracting
foreign money. And such business is also a good way for hotel and
resort operators to benefit from new cashflow sources.
	   The time-share business in Thailand has expanded rapidly and
there are now about 2,000 foreign members altogether through three
networks -- Quality Suite Airport Bangkok Hotel, Green Park
Pattaya, and Lanna Resort Chiang Mai.
	   The three networks might not be enough to serve the 200-per cent
expansion rate expected this year due to the Amazing Thailand
promotional and the depreciation of baht, according to MTC.
	   Vittayen said companies which join the time-share network would
reach their break-even point within two years. The companies would
also benefit from the membership and annual fees which would help
support their cash-flow positions, and the country as a whole would
collect more foreign funds.
	   The Vacation Ownership Association of Thailand (VOAT) also met
Monday to discuss legal issues relating to the protection of
members of the time-share programme.
	   The results of the VOAT discussion will also be proposed for
further discussion on June 12 at the meeting on ''Consumer
Protection Law and Tax Law on Time-Share Business'' organised by
the Tourism Authority of Thailand. Vittayen will represent the
time-share operators at the meeting.
	   The Nation 
</TEXT>
