<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Roundup, 1st Ld-Writethru,0640 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nigerian gloom as the rest of the France celebrates
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: NEW throughout &QL; 
 &UR; By JOSEPH WHITE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ A touch of lightning on a cold, wet morning served
only to make things even gloomier for Nigeria on the eve of the
World Cup.
	   Already battered by injuries, the team had to deal with the
distraction of the death of their country's leader, Gen. San
Abacha, and two more doses of bad news from hobbled players during
the Tuesday morning practice.
	   The team learned that starting defender Jero Shakpoke, who hurt
himself against the Netherlands in a warmup game last week, has a
broken left collarbone and is lost for the tournament. Meanwhile,
striker Daniel Amokachi twisted his right knee and his status will
be evaluated day-to-day.
	   ``Like I always say, I worry about the things I can change,''
coach Bora Milutinovic said. Abacha's death ``is not one of those.
Neither are the injuries.''
	   The players held a moment of silence for Abacha before practice
began, and captain Uche Okechukwu said the team was considering
wearing black armbands on their jerseys during World Cup matches.
In Jerusalem, a prominent Nigerian dissident urged spectators to
show disapproval of Abacha's military regime by jeering the
country's flag during games.
	   ``We didn't know he was sick,'' midfielder Sunday Oliseh said.
``It's like if you don't know a team is in the World Cup and then
you find out it has won it.''
	   There was a distinctly different mood in Paris, where the
arrival of thousands of fans and an opening parade made for a
festive atmosphere ahead of Wednesday's opening games _ defending
champion Brazil vs. Scotland and Morocco vs. Norway.
	   ``We want to show that football is accessible to everyone and
belongs to no one,'' said Jean-Pascal Levy-Trumet, who designed the
``Fete du Football'' show that featured four large giants
converging on central Paris from different directions. ``The grand
theme is universality in a single world.''
	   The Nigerians weren't the only team struggling with new
injuries. Dutch coach Guus Hiddink said team captain Frank de Boer
twisted his left ankle in practice and may miss the Netherlands'
first match against Belgium on Saturday.
	   The news was better for host France. Zinedine Zidane, the team's
creative midfielder, juggled the ball without problem Tuesday,
easing fears an ankle injury would keep him out of the opener
against South Africa on Friday.
	   ``I'm OK, I didn't feel any pain,'' Zidane said. ``Now we have
to prepare the match. We're ready.''
	   Italian striker Alessandro Del Piero was also running better on
his injured thigh, although he won't be ready for Italy's opener
against Chile on Thursday. Roberto Baggio will start in his place.
	   Germany, which faces the United States on Monday, practiced in
Nice again without wing back Christian Ziege, who had a fever, and
versatile defender Thomas Helmer, who was still dealing with a
thigh injury.
	   Among the teams arriving in France on Tuesday were England and
Yugoslavia. The Yugoslavs tried to focus on soccer as they took up
residence in Saint Galmier, but they were clearly troubled by the
ethnic turmoil back home.
	   ``Of course we cannot ignore what is happening in our county,''
midfielder Vladimir Jugovic said. ``But we'll try to ignore it.''
	   Many see Yugoslavia's June 25 match against the United States as
a grudge match because the Americans were in instrumental in
imposing sanctions against the Balkan country, both in 1992 and
again earlier this week.
	   ``We don't want a political match against the Americans,'' said
Miljan Miljanic, the head of the Yugoslav Football Association.
``We are not politicians but sports friends.''
</TEXT>
