</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0720 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kosovo Albanians prepare for longer war, set new `defense tax'
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES, RECASTS with comments by UNHCR head, Yeltsin, reports
of new attacks, Yugoslav army reinforcements, NATO, U.N. actions
considered, Yugoslav Defense Council convenes, other new material.
TRIMS. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By ISMET HAJDARI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ As the international outcry to halt
the bloodshed in Kosovo grew Tuesday, ethnic Albanian leaders took
steps to prepare for extended warfare against Serb forces in the
secessionist province.
	   Exiled Kosovo Albanian political leaders announced they would
collect an extra tax from an estimated 400,000 Kosovo Albanians
living abroad to finance the ``defense of our people.'' They did
not elaborate.
	   The announcement by the Germany-based Kosovo Albanian
government-in-exile underscored the apparently deepening commitment
of both sides to the conflict.
	   The Serb-led Yugoslav army shipped in a trainload of 46 armored
personnel carriers and about 1,000 soldiers to Kosovo's capital
Pristina in a fifth straight day of such reinforcements, ethnic
Albanian sources said.
	   There also was no sign of a letup in clashes between Serb police
and army forces and ethnic Albanian guerrillas in western Kosovo,
where the U.N. human rights chief described a ``grave and worsening
human rights and humanitarian situation.''
	   In Geneva, Mary Robinson urged warring Serbs and ethnic Albanian
separatists to ``curb the spiral of violence.''
	   Meantime, the West was debating stronger actions a day after the
United States and the European Union imposed new sanctions on
Serbia. NATO defense ministers are expected to discuss the
possibility of direct intervention at a meeting in Brussels on
Thursday and Friday. At the United Nations, diplomatic sources said
the United States and Britain plan to ask the Security Council to
approve the use of force against the Serbs.
	   In a statement issued to the official Tanjug news agency,
Yugoslavia denounced the imposition of new sanctions as a ``strange
and unreasonable decision.'' The sanctions banned new investments
in Serbia and froze its assets abroad.
	   Serbia's lone partner in the Yugoslav federation, Montenegro,
was exempt because of its pro-Western leadership.
	   Published in Kosovo newspapers Tuesday, an announcement by
exiled ethnic Albanian government said Kosovo Albanians working
abroad would have to contribute the equivalent of dlrs 300-600
(500-1,000 DM) to the ``obligatory financial mobilization.''
	   Majority ethnic Albanians in the southern Serbian province
formed their own government after their autonomy was revoked in
1989. But it is not recognized by Serbian authorities and many of
its officials live in Western Europe.
	   The parallel administration has been collecting taxes and
financing education and health care for Kosovo Albanians since
1993.
	   According to the pro-Albanian Kosovo Information Center, Serb
forces Tuesday were firing grenades on villages along the Albanian
border in southwestern Kosovo. Several other villages were attacked
in northwestern Kosovo, and three people were killed, the Albanian
center said.
	   Ethnic Albanians comprise 90 of the population in Serbia's
southern province. More than 250 have died this year in clashes
between government forces and the pro-independence Albanian
militants, known as the Kosovo Liberation Army.
	   Yugoslavia's Supreme Defense Council, the top commanding body
for the country's army, met Tuesday in Belgrade to discuss Kosovo
despite deep disputes between some of its members.
	   The panel, headed by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic,
``concluded that the Yugoslav army and the police entirely control
the state border and successfully take measures that guarantee the
safety of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia,'' Tanjug reported.
	   Among the council members present was Montenegro's President
Milo Djukanovic, a Milosevic rival _ apparently signifying that
Milosevic has accepted election results giving a victory to the
reformist Djukanovic's party.
	   In Germany, Russian President Boris Yeltsin said he would seek a
meeting with Milosevic to persuade him to end the violence in
Kosovo. Russia is a traditional Serb ally. 	   
</TEXT>
