<HEADLINE>
Naigai opens local office, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Naigai opens local office, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   JAPAN'S non-vessel operating common carrier, Naigai Trans Line
Co Ltd, has opened its representative office in Thailand with plans
to form a joint venture locally, Shigemori Hatano of the company's
Bangkok representative office said.
	   Under the plan, the company expects to expand its business in
Thailand in partnership with local transportation and logistic firm
Leo Transport Corp Ltd as well as to use Thailand as a centre to
expand its transportation services in the Southeast Asian region.
	   Kettivit Sittisootornwong, president of Leo Transport Corp Ltd,
said the company is studying the joint venture proposal with Naigai
Trans Line, which is expected to be concluded and formed in two
years. Under the joint venture agreement, Naigai Trans Line will
help Leo Transport Corp contact Japanese clients to transport their
products between Thailand and Japan and other markets.
	   Hatano said Naigai Trans Line's headquarters in Tokyo decided to
expand their business to Thailand, the second country with a
permanent office in the region after Singapore.
	   ''We expect Thailand to be the headquarters of Naigai Trans Line
Co to expand its non-vessel operating common carrier and related
transportation services in the region,'' said Hatano, adding that
Thailand's potential for transportation business is very big along
with the country's improving transportation system and
fundamentals, as well as the increasing number of Japanese firms
doing business locally.
	   
