<SLUG> BC-Russia-Cyprus-Missiles, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia has already sent missiles to Cyprus, newspaper says
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. Recasts and UPDATES with Russia denouncing report as part
of media campaign. &QL; 
 &UR; By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia expressed indignation Tuesday over a
newspaper report that it has already delivered powerful air-defense
missiles to Cyprus despite Turkey's threat to use force to stop
their deployment.
	   The Segodnya daily reported that Cyprus has already received the
S-300 missiles _ the Russian equivalent of the U.S. Patriot
missiles used in the Gulf War _ under a contract with the Russian
state arms exporter.
	   Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin denounced the
paper's report, saying it was part of a media campaign to discredit
Russia's foreign policy, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
	   Rakhmanin did not say whether the missiles have been delivered,
according to ITAR-Tass. However, Russia's Rosvooruzheniye arms
trading monopoly denied that delivery had taken place and said the
missiles will be sent to Cyprus in mid-August as planned, the
Interfax news agency reported.
	   Russia says the weapons are defensive.
	   But Turkish Defense Minister Ismet Sezgin reiterated Tuesday
that his country would not tolerate the missiles' deployment on the
divided Mediterranean island.
	   ``If the S-300 missiles are deployed on Cyprus, we will do
whatever is necessary,'' the Anatolia news agency quoted him as
saying.
	   Turkey has threatened to use force to prevent the missiles'
deployment. Turkey has maintained 30,000 troops on Cyprus since it
invaded the island in 1974, following a failed coup by supporters
of union with Greece.
	   In Nicosia, government spokesman Christos Stylianides refused to
comment on the newspaper report.
	   Greece has said it will come to the aid of Cyprus if it is
attacked by Turkey, raising fears of a military conflict between
two NATO allies.
	   Cyprus has said it is ready to cancel the dlrs 200 million
missile deal if there is substantial progress toward the
reunification of the island and if Turkey accepts its proposal for
demilitarization.
	   The Russian Foreign Ministry said Tuesday that demilitarization
of Cyprus is essential for solving the conflict and called for more
international efforts to help end the confrontation.
	   The latest attempt to restart talks to reunify Cyprus by U.S.
envoy Richard Holbrooke failed last month.
	   (pvs/mr/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
