<BODY>
<SLUG> MATTEL-SEES-ROSY-FUTURE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mattel sees rosy future for its subsidiary in Thailand, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Mattel sees rosy future for its subsidiary in Thailand, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   ACHARA PONGVUTITHAMASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MATTEL Bangkok Ltd, subsidiary of the US-based toy manufacturer
Mattel Inc, known best for Barbie, Winnie the Pooh and Sesame
Street dolls, plans to export toy cars worth Bt1.1 billion in its
first year of operation here.
	   President for Mattel Inc's operations Joseph Gandolfo said Thai
plants would most produce die-cast cars, small toy cars made with
zinc-alloy. The products will be produced under the Mattel
trademark of Hot Wheels and will be mainly exported to the US and
Europe.
	   Last week, the company completed its first stage plan to export
one million units. The production has been planned at 60 million
units a year. Export value is expected to reach Bt1.6 billion by
the year 2000 with the export of 110 million units. Mattel's
worldwide sales revenue, from toy cars, was US$700 million last
year.
	   Thailand's toy export industry should wake up again once foreign
investors foresee long-term investments. A few years ago, several
local toy companies had been forced to shut down some operations in
order to survive.
	   Gandolfo said the parent company had not yet planned to produce
a doll, like Barbie, in Thailand. This is because Mattel had
recently invested $60 million to complete its Indonesian production
plant, which currently produces 33 million dolls a year. The full
capacity of the plant is expected to increase to 55 million.
	   ''The plant in Indonesia did not have any interruptions during
the political and financial crisis. Moreover, the investment is
enough for its long-term expansion. We seek new potential countries
instead of injecting more capital there,'' Gandolfo said.
	   He added that Mattel still eyed Thailand for product line
expansion and for the production of dolls. An investment
feasibility study will be conducted within the next two or three
years.
	   ''Thailand has the most potential among Asean member countries
with strong facilities, a highly skilled workforce and stable
political concerns, which will help strengthen production and
export,'' Gandolfo noted.
	   Mattel's biggest plant is in China where the company produces
particular Barbie dolls and accessories. The other types of dolls
are produced in Malaysia.
	   The combined output from Mattel's plants in China, Malaysia and
Indonesia is 130 million dolls a year which suits the worldwide
market demand.
	   Gandolfo believes that the Asian economy will recover in the
near future, adding that Thailand was headed the right way in
solving the crisis.
	   In 1997, Mattel Inc acquired a majority stake in Tyco
Corporation, which in the same year took over Universal
International (Holding) Ltd. Universal International is the parent
company of Universal Matchbox (Thailand) which was renamed Mattel
Bangkok Ltd.
	   Mattel, with sales networks in more than 140 countries and
manufacturing plants in nine countries, has reached global sales
worth more than $5 billion.
	   The company invested $26 million in Mattel Bangkok to cover two
phases of manufacturing through to the year 2000. The first phase
has employed over 1,200 workers and the second phase is projected
to have additional 2,000 employees who would, in full capacity,
produce 110 units yearly.
	   
</TEXT>
