<HEADLINE>
European Central Bank's governing board holds first meeting
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ The policymaking board of the new
European Central Bank held its first meeting Tuesday to help it
prepare for the launch of the continent's single currency next
year.
	   Wim Duisenberg, the bank's newly named president, said the 11
central banks participating in the euro currency will pay the
equivalent of around 4 billion euros into the bank's capital base
by July 1. One euro is expected to be worth roughly dlrs1.
	   He also told a news conference that the central bankers were in
general agreement that between 10 percent and 15 percent of the
total reserves transferred to the ECB will be in gold.
	   The euro currency will debut on Jan. 1 as part of the European
Union's efforts to create an economic and monetary union. Eleven of
its 15 member nations will be in the initial wave of euro
participants.
	   The ECB, which will be based in Frankfurt, will be in charge of
setting monetary policy for the euro. Its governing council
includes the six members on the ECB's executive board and the 11
central bankers of the participating nations.
</TEXT>
