<HEADLINE>
PTT rejects Petro Asia offer on sale of 37 outlets, NATION
</HEADLINE>
PTT rejects Petro Asia offer on sale of 37 outlets, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Petroleum Authority of Thailand (PTT) has refused to buy 37
petrol stations offered by Petro Asia (Thailand) Co (PA), a PTT
executive said.
	   The source, who asked not to be named, said the decision to
refuse came from the fact that many PA stations are situated close
to PTT otlets and would compete with them. PA has 400 small outlets
in Thailand.
	   ''If PA sells all its stations, it will automatically have to
close down the company, possibly within two to five years'', said
the executive.
	   In addition, PTT does not have any money available for the
investment.
	   ''If PA cannot go further, it should close down operations,''
said the executive, adding that PTT would bring back staff who had
been moved to PA.
	   PA is owned by the Charoen Pokphand (CP) Group, PTT and a
Chinese state-owned firm, China Petrochemical Corp.
	   CP is also negotiating the sale of its 35-per-cent stake in PA
to US company Atlantic Richfields (Arco). The executive said PTT
would maintain its holding in PA if it could not be sold to Arco.
	   With regard to PA's Chinese ventures, PTT has decided to retain
its current holding even if CP pulls out because investment in
China's downstream industry has high potential, he said.
	   PTT is also helping PA with aspects like marketing and
cost-cutting.
	   The Commercial Registration Department had reported earlier that
the number of petrol outlets, as of the end of March, totalled
12,726, up 22 per cent from the same period last year.
	   PTT has retained its position as a leader with 1,526 outlets,
followed by Bangchak, Shell, Esso and Caltex.
	   Petrol outlets of Article 6-registered oil companies have grown
by only three per cent to 7,098 in the first quarter of this year.
	   BY WATCHARAPONG THONGRUNG The Nation 
</TEXT>
