</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> NEW-LABOUR-LAW-LACKS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New labour law lacks clarity, NATION
</HEADLINE>
New labour law lacks clarity, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   EMPLOYEES, particularly women and children, will benefit most
from Thailand's new labour-protection law, said Suriyong Tungsuwan,
a partner of international law firm Baker &AMP; McKenzie in an address
to the Singapore-Thai Chamber of Commerce.
	   Speaking on the impact and implications of the act which comes
into force on Aug 19, Suriyong said that while the new law would
provide better protection to employees, some provisions,
particularly those limiting daily working hours, might be too rigid
and impractical for some workplaces and that while the new law
cleared up some of the issues in the existing legislation it raised
many new aspects which would inevitably require clarification in
the courts.
	   ''The new act will certainly provide better protection to
employees,'' Suriyong said, ''but while the contents of the act are
pretty lengthy, it does not tell us everything. A lot of
implementing legislation will be necessary, and we will have to
wait and see what will come out after that. The Ministry of Labour
and Social Welfare is given a lot of flexibility in what it can put
in its ministerial regulations.'' Changes and new requirements will
prevail over the provisions of existing regulations in workplaces
as well as terms and conditions of existing employment contracts.
The new legislation is intented to meet standards set by the
International Labour Organisation (ILO).
	   Suriyong commented on the implications of the new law in the
workplace: ''The new law will make it necessary for every workplace
to take a look at its personnel-management policy and to amend all
existing documents relating to employment matters, including work
rules and regulations and employment contracts.'' He said some of
the highlights of the new law included prohibition of child labour
and sex discrimination, restrictions on the work of pregnant
employees, outlawing of sexual harassment, a ceiling on working
hours, new overtime regulations, compulsory welfare and provident
funds and increases in severance pay for some employees.
	   Addressing sex-discrimination laws, he said that while the law
required the equal treatment of men and women in the workplace, the
issue of whether this applied before employment, as in job
advertisements, and during the recruitment process would need to be
resolved. Similarly, the act does not specify how it interprets
sexual harassment and does not penalise sexual harassment against
male employees or by an employee against a fellow employee of equal
ranking.
	   While long-term employees are set to gain more from new
severance-pay regulations, this would, he said, given the current
economic crisis, probably trigger accelerated and more widespread
lay-offs before the new law comes into force. Also, Suriyong said,
a new stipulation requiring employers to make severance payments
and other outstanding mandatory payments within three days of the
termination date might create some problems for insolvent companies
or those in need of cash flow.
	   ''In effect, some companies may not be able to close down until
they have the cash to do so.'' he said.
	   ''Once in force, all employment relationships will be governed
by this act,'' Suriyong concluded. ''It is important that employers
and employees be aware of the new labour-protection law and
familiar with its implications and impacts on the
personnel-management policy of every workplace''.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
