<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Nigeria's Distraction,0634 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Nigeria deals with key injuries, Abacha death
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: incorporates copy from Sports-Soccer-Nigeria-Abacha Reaction
and Sports-Soccer-Nigeria-Injuries &QL; 
 &UR; By HOWARD FENDRICH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ELINCOURT-STE. MARGUERITE, France (AP) _ Another day, another
distraction.
	   From the death of its country's leader to mounting injuries,
from a string of poor outings to rumors about coach Bora
Milutinovic's job status, Nigeria had plenty to think about Tuesday
as its World Cup opener neared.
	   The team got word that starting defender Jero Shakpore is out
for the tournament with a broken collarbone. Just a few hours
before, striker Daniel Amokachi had to be helped off the practice
field with a heavily bandaged right knee.
	   ``Like I always say, I worry about the things I can change,''
Milutinovic said. Gen. Sani Abacha's death ``is not one of those.
Neither are the injuries.''
	   Nor is the speculation that his job is on the line. Team
officials denied Tuesday that Milutinovic _ a Yugoslav at the helm
of his fourth different World Cup side _ will be fired immediately
if Nigeria loses its first match.
	   That outing, against Spain on Saturday, will set the tone for
the tournament, several players said.
	   ``Spain is very strong, but we are not thinking about Spain,''
said forward Nwankwo Kanu, who's battling an ankle injury. ``We
have to be thinking about ourselves.''
	   Nigeria has lost three straight tuneup games against World Cup
participants. The defense has been lackadaisical, the attack
anemic.
	   Shakpore, 19, quickly became one of Milutinovic's prized pupils
and was hoped to provide consistency at the revolving-door right
back spot.
	   But he was injured in a warmup game against the Netherlands last
week. After days of uncertainty, he was examined in Italy by his
club doctor, who diagnosed a broken collarbone and told the team
the player would be sidelined for six weeks.
	   Nigeria has petitioned FIFA, the sport's governing body, to
allow a roster move to replace Shakpore, team spokesman Austin
Mgbolu said. If granted, Mobi Oparaku would take his spot on the
roster and in the starting lineup.
	   Heavy clouds, occasional lightning and sprinkles framed the
team's practice, which started with a moment of silence for Abacha.
	   ``We're trying to take it calmly,'' captain Uche Okechukwu said.
``Of course we are thinking about it.''
	   The leader died in Lagos on Monday and was replaced Tuesday by
another general. Okechukwu said the team may wear black armbands on
their uniforms during the World Cup.
	   ``It was shocking for the team,'' Oliseh said. ``We didn't know
he was sick. It's like if you don't know a team is in the World Cup
and then you find out it has won it.''
	   Milutinovic said he thought Abacha's death might actually help
the players.
	   ``I wouldn't want to say this is special motivation, but we do
need to be united,'' the coach said. ``Death is normally not
positive, but. ...''
	   Practice was less than perfect. Amokachi crumpled to the ground
after catching his cleat in the damp turf when trying to shoot
during a half-field scrimmage. A member of Nigeria's last World Cup
team and the Olympic gold medal team of 1996, Amokachi can provide
power and play-making skills.
	   Milutinovic is fast running out of options in attack, with
Emmanuele Amunike not even here because of a lingering knee injury
and Kanu at less than 100 percent.
	   Kanu has skipped all of the team's workouts at its training
ground, about 80 kilometers (50 miles) north of Paris. He did do
some light jogging and stretching for about 20 minutes with a
trainer.
	   (hjf-jw)
</TEXT>
