<BODY>
<SLUG> NEW-DEBT-RESTRUCTURING sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New debt restructuring body urged by council, NATION
</HEADLINE>
New debt restructuring body urged by council, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Council of Economic Ministers Monday suggested the Bank of
Thailand set up a central body to coordinate debt restructuring
between commercial banks and their borrowers in order to ensure
benefits to small companies, government spokesman Akapol
Sorasuchart said.
	   Akapol said normally banks agree to restructure loans extended
to large companies while ignoring small ones.
	   The BOT Monday submitted the regulations, announced on June 2,
to the council. The regulations are in accordance with the fourth
letter of intent to the International Monetary Fund. Corporate debt
restructuring is to be a means to reduce the liquidity shortage and
insolvencies.
	   Companies restructuring their debts will receive new loans and
their lenders need not reserve against problem loans, thereby
increasing their credit supply. Once credit supply rises, interest
rates will fall.
	   Although the authorities hope the loan restructuring process
will inject liquidity into the market, commercial banks are still
reluctant to lower their lending interest rates.
	   Twatchai Yongkittikul, secretary general of the Thai Bankers'
Association, admitted it is difficult to cut rates as the
repurchase rate is still high.
	   Bangkok Bank president Chartsiri Sophonpanich said the TBA will
soon discuss rate reductions. However, they might not take place
due to the current shaky economic conditions.
	   ''Commercial banks in fact don't want high rates. Yet, we
couldn't cut them and the best we can do is maintain the current
levels. At present, BBL rates are the lowest,'' he said.
	   Thai Farmers Bank president Banthoon Lamsam said his bank is
squeezing credit on fear new loans might turn bad and loan
restructuring might take quite some time after the regulations are
announced. TBA, the Federation of Thai Industries and the Board of
Trade are scheduled to convene on Friday to discuss tax and other
problems concerning the loan restructuring as urged by the
financial authorities, according to a TBA source.
	   Later, they will submit their conclusion to the Bank of
Thailand.
	   The TBA source said the meeting was originally scheduled to take
place Monday, but was delayed as the authorities wanted to hear the
private sector's proposals. Based on the BOT regulations, there are
13 items which must be taxed but the taxation process is rather
complicated, he said.
	   The Stock Exchange of Thailand also discussed tax issues with
the Finance Ministry.
	   Finance Ministry permanent secretary Supachai Phisitvanich said
the ministry is studying what tax privileges will be provided to
commercial banks which agree to restructure problem loans.
	   He said so far, the ministry has finalised 80 per cent of the
adjustment framework, mostly covering transaction tax, income tax
and appraisal tax.
	   ''We're considering some issues, such as the proposal to allow
banks to deduct income tax from the difference between loan
collateral and lending amounts in case the collateral value is
below the lending amount,'' he said.
	   He said the tax privileges could be issued in a Revenue
Department announcement or ministerial regulations. ''Anyway, we
try to fix all things [which will be effective for a few years]
before the end of the 1998 account year [December],'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
