<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Japan,0327 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Injured captain returns to intra-squad practice game
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By YURI KAGEYAMA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AIX-LES-BAINS, France (AP) _ Japan's captain is back. For the
first time since last week's injury, defender Masami Ihara
scampered about in the field in a loose intra-squad scrimmage
Tuesday.
	   Whether Ihara would recover by Japan's opener Sunday against
Argentina had been uncertain after a right knee injury prevented
him from playing in two recent warmup matches _ a 1-0 loss to
Yugoslavia in Switzerland, and a 1-0 victory over Gueugnon of the
French second division Sunday.
	   But Ihara, the most experienced player on Japan's World Cup
team, appeared back in form. And his return is sure to be a plus
for the tournament newcomers. Japan has been working on a tighter
defense system centered on Ihara.
	   Although he played with the reserves, rather than the starters,
Ihara moved about freely and kicked the ball in afternoon practice
here in this resort turned Japan's training camp.
	   Coach Takeshi Okada appeared satisfied.
	   ``The team doctor had expected him to recover in time,'' he
said. ``I wasn't that worried.''
	   In the morning, the team spent some time on shooting practice.
	   Okada has said repeatedly that his team has serious difficulty
scoring. He has also said he will play a more defensive game
against Argentina, with two defenders marking the opponent strikers
one-on-one, in addition to Ihara.
	   The team also practiced free kicks and corner kicks behind
closed doors, at a separate field surrounded by walls especially
for that purpose. Such set-pieces will be key for Japan's scoring
at the World Cup.
	   The problem is the high-rise housing right by the stadium. Many
people _ presumably residents and not the Argentine team _ can be
seen gazing out of their windows, getting a clear view of all
Japan's secrets.
</TEXT>
