<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Gucci </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Companion of slain scion testifies at Milan trial
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MILAN, Italy (AP) _ Maurizio Gucci's ex-wife once asked a lawyer
what would happen to her if she had the fashion scion killed, a
witness testified Tuesday at the trial for his slaying.
	   The ex-wife, Patrizia Reggiani Martinelli, is being tried here
along with her former psychic and three others for the fatal
shooting of Gucci in 1995.
	   Reggiani Martinelli sat impassively during testimony by Gucci's
companion, Paola Franchi.
	   She a Gucci family lawyer warned that Reggiani Martinelli
contacted a fellow attorney to ask what criminal penalties she
might risk.
	   ``Maurizio didn't give any weight to the matter, even though I
asked him to hire a bodyguard,'' Franchi testified. ``Evidently, he
was used to threats by his wife.''
	   After Franchi testified, Reggiani Martinelli asked to make a
statement to the court, her first words to the tribunal since trial
began two weeks ago.
	   In a low, nervous voice, Reggiani Martinelli reiterated earlier
assertions that she regretted making known that she wanted to see
her husband dead because, she contended, two of the other
defendants then schemed to kill Gucci on their own and hit her up
for hush money.
	   ``It was a desire that they later carried out, and they began to
blackmail me,'' she said of fellow defendants, psychic Giuseppina
Auriemma, and a Milan hotel doorman, Ivano Savioni, who prosecutors
contend found the trigger man.
	   Also on trial is a man who confessed to driving the getaway car
and the alleged hit man.
	   Italian courts allow defendants to make statements during trial.
Reggiani Martinelli is not expected to take the stand for several
weeks.
	   The prosecution says Reggiani Martinelli had Gucci killed
because she was obsessed with gaining control of his estate and he
would cut her alimony in half to dlrs 900,000 a year. She allegedly
paid her co-defendants dlrs 300,000 to carry out the killing.
	   The Guccis were married in 1972 and separated 12 years later.
Their two daughters, Alessandra and Allegra, are 21 and 16,
respectively.
	   Franchi testified that Reggiani Martinelli tried to set the
daughters against their father, and that Gucci wanted to set up a
trust for his daughters while they were still minors so that his
money wouldn't end up ``in the wrong hands.''
	   (fd/djw)	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Italy-Gucci; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
