w1445 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  PHATRA-BUY-MUTUALLYsked     06-09 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> PHATRA-BUY-MUTUALLY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Phatra buy mutually beneficial, say firms, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Phatra buy mutually beneficial, say firms, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   K I WooASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MERRILL Lynch's chief operating officer for the Asia-Pacific
region said his company's recent 51 per cent acquisition of Phatra
Securities should not be perceived as a situation where a huge
deep-pocketed foreign company is taking control of a Thai company
during an economic crisis.
	   Kevan Watts said Merrill's US$68 million purchase should be
viewed as a deal which satisfies the strategic needs of both
parties.
	   Merrill Lynch Phatra Securities will be headed by co-CEOs
Veravat Chutichetpong and Michael Unsworth, a Merrill Lynch
managing director who previously was regional head of research in
Hong Kong.
	   According to Watts, Merrill and Phatra officials, including
Viroj Nualkhair and Banyong Pongpanich, had discussed mutual
strategies in May last year.
	   ''Viroj and Banyong said that in a world where their business
was consolidating locally, they didn't think Phatra could retain
its niche in Thailand without partnering with an international
investment bank,'' Watts said.
	   Watts said Phatra realised the investment business was
consolidating around a limited number of international players who
were becoming more of a factor in local markets like Thailand. He
said Phatra told him they did not believe they had the
profitability to compete against the deep-pocketed global players.
''The UK firms couldn't do it,'' said Watts who is from Great
Britain.
	   At the same time, Watts told the Thai Farmers Bank which
controls Phatra that the difference between Merrill and other
international firms was that Merrill was willing to show an extra
level of commitment. ''Our strategy is to invest in local firms,
because we believe that after the consolidation is over, important
local clients will view the global players differently,'' he said.
	   Watts said US-based Merrill recognises it couldn't provide the
same quality of service it delivers in its home markets by merely
periodically parachuting in experts. ''Our strategy has been to
build up the local expertise in all of our overseas operations,''
he said.
	   While actual takeover discussions didn't commence until July
1997, Watts said a crucial element to the deal's success was
Merrill's understanding of TFB's core strategies prior to the
baht's devaluation and the subsequent economic downturn. Watts said
if the negotiations had commenced after the baht devaluation and
after the economy began going sour it would have been much more
difficult to complete the transaction. Both Merrill and TFB
officials were insisting the premise which cemented the deal had
nothing to do with the financial crisis. ''They believed they
needed to do a transaction for the strategic needs of their
business -- all before the Thai baht was floated. It was the
group's core concept,'' he said.
	   With the faltering Thai economy crushing financial institutions'
balance sheets, TFB's choice to recapitalise Phatra Thanakit Plc
and form a new debt-free Phatra Securities Co Ltd was also crucial
for the deal's success.
	   Watts told The Nation it would have been highly unlikely that
Merrill would have made the deal if Phatra Securities had not been
separated from Phatra Thanakit. ''We're very diversified, but we're
not a lending institution. We're not in that business,'' he said.
	   Several weeks ago, Banthoon Lamsam, TFB's CEO, said his group
put money into recapitalising Phatra Thanakit Plc because it saw
the value of Phatra Securities. The group had been criticised for
letting some of its other faltering finance company affiliates fall
by the wayside.
	   With Merrill paying $68 million, Bt2.72 billion, for the stake
in Merrill Lynch Phatra Securities which new co-CEO Veravat said
will have net assets of Bt2.7 billion, including cash of Bt2
billion deposited in financial institutions, some observers are
saying Banthoon realised value from the deal. The $68 million paid
by Merrill will not go into the new company's coffers. It will be
paid to Phatra Thanakit Plc which is selling 51 per cent of its
shares to Merrill.
	   Watts argues that the $68 billion is only a small part of the
deal.
	   ''I don't think Banthoon is realising value in this deal -- he's
helping it to create more value for the Thai Farmers group,'' he
said.
	   Banthoon, he said, was convinced that to take Phatra forward,
this alliance was needed. ''This is a positive alliance about the
future. Its about creating more value in the 49 per cent they
retain than from their previous 100 per cent holding,'' he said.
	   Watts added that TFB now has the opportunity of participating in
Merrill Lynch's global franchise as its supplier in Thailand.
''It's a very good transaction for the Thai Farmers Bank group,''
he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
