<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-Forza Italia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Incongruous alliance in European parliament
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ANNA SATHIAH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) - An incongruous alliance was formed
Tuesday when members of Italian opposition leader Silvio
Berlusconi's party joined a European Parliament group of which
Prime Minister Romano Prodi is a member.
	   The European People's Party, a coalition of center-right
political parties and the second largest faction in the EU
parliament, opened its arms Tuesday to 20 parliamentarians
belonging to Berlusconi's conservative Forza Italia party.
	   Altogether 136 of the EPP's 180 members took part in the vote. A
separate vote was issued for each of the 20 applicants, the EPP
group's leader Wilfried Martens told a news conference.
	   ``On average, 92 EPP members voted against the candidates, 37
voted in favor, there were four abstentions and three blank
votes,'' Martens said.
	   ``This was not Forza Italia applying for membership, these were
individual applications. The distinction must be made,'' he added,
in a bid to tone down the uncomfortable rapprochement between Prodi
and Berlusconi.
	   The candidates were told they can join the group if they adhere
to its rules. Martens said the 20 candidates had assured him in a
letter they will ``reject every form of extremism.''
	   ``They clearly underlined the principles of the EPP,'' Martens
said in an interview with the Belgian daily De Standaard.
	   Six EU prime ministers belong to the EPP coalition, including
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, Spanish Prime Minister Jose Maria
Aznar and Prodi.
	   The Socialist Party, the largest grouping in the parliament,
denounced the entry of Forza Italia's members into the EPP.
	   The EPP parties ``are about to take a momentous decision on a
realignment of Christian Democracy to the right of the political
spectrum in Europe,'' the Socialist group's leader Pauline Green
warned before the vote.
	   The ``marriage ... will cause a seismic shift in the political
map of Europe. It will put at risk two decades of agreement between
Socialists and the EPP ... on the core proposals of a developing
European integration.''
	   The entry of the Forza Italia candidates narrowed the gap
between the EPP - which now has 200 members - and the 213-member
Socialist group.
	   Berlusconi leads Italy's right-of-center coalition which is made
up of his Forza Italia party, the rightist National Alliance and
other groups.
	   Prodi heads the center-left Olive Tree coalition.
 &UR; (as)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-EU-Forza Italia; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
