<SLUG> BC-India-Cyclone, 4th Ld-Writethru,0286 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cyclone hits India's western coast, at least 75 dead
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with the death toll rising to 75, details. No pickup. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BOMBAY, India (AP) _ A cyclone spun onto India's western Gujarat
state Tuesday, whipping up high winds that toppled homes, trees,
walls and a communication tower, killing at least 75 people.
	   At Kandla, a 4-meter (13-feet)-high tidal wave swept away 20
port workers, said Praveen Lehri, a top official of Gujarat state
government.
	   The storm, the most severe in the past 25 years to batter the
western coast, hit land at Porbunder, 450 kilometers (280 miles)
northwest of Bombay. It gradually moved north, buffeting much of
western India with heavy rain and winds of up 80 kph (50 mph),
snapping power lines and making driving impossible.
	   Most of the other deaths were mainly caused by lightning and
house collapses in Junagadh, Bhuj, Valsad and Jamnagar, rural
districts near Porbunder, Lehri said.
	   Nine people died in Porbunder when a telecommunications tower
came crashing down.
	   Kamaljeet, a meteorologist who uses only one name, said by
telephone from Ahmedabad, the capital of Gujarat, that the storm
was expected to weaken soon.
	   State officials said the military was asked to stand by for
help, while air force helicopters rescued homeless people.
	   Indian officials moved some 5,000 people in small towns and
villages bordering the Arabian Sea to safety on Monday, state
government officials said.
	   A South American cargo ship, carrying cement to Gulf states from
India, was grounded on the Saurashtra coast, but its 27-member crew
was rescued by port authorities, United News of India news agency
said.
</TEXT>
