w1463 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  'PASSENGERS'-AIRPORTsked     06-09 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> 'PASSENGERS'-AIRPORT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`Passengers' face snags using Sepang airport, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`Passengers' face snags using Sepang airport, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SEPANG, Sat. - With the opening of the Kuala Lumpur
International Airport less than a month away, advance operation
trials have hit a snag as problems surfaced with its systems and
passenger flow procedures.
	   More than 3,000 Commonwealth Games volunteers today took part in
the largest operation trial so far to test the airport's passenger
and baggage-handling systems, aircraft control, kerbside and
carpark management, public transportation, passenger flow and
communication systems.
	   The trials, the first of which was held on Sept 16, are to
ensure smooth operations of the airport when it opens on June 30.
	   However, some passengers found themselves having to wait over an
hour at the check-in counters as the computers processing passenger
check-in `slowed down', causing a delay in passenger flow.
	   One volunteer, Chan Choon Tsz, from Taiping, said she was still
at the check-in counters when her simulated `flight' was scheduled
to depart in less than an hour.
	   She said several passengers found difficulty locating their
designated check-in counters as the information provided was
inadequate.
	   ``We know that there are Flight Information Display monitors
located all over the airport, but a new passenger who comes to the
airport would still need to be informed that he should look at the
monitors to find his check- in counter.
	   ``There are not enough instructions on this,'' she said.
	   Another passenger, Lee Peng Keong, said there were not enough
signages in the airport to direct passengers to, for example, their
aircraft boarding gates.
	   ``Some of the signages are too small to be seen and it's no
wonder that some people coming to KLIA for the first time get
lost,'' said Lee who has participated in previous trials.
	   Malaysia Airports Berhad general manager Muhammad Adnan Yahya
however said while there may have been some problems, the trial
went smoothly.
	   ``We will be having a post-mortem on Tuesday afternoon and only
then can we assess the success of the trial.''
	   He added that some of the problems were caused by volunteers not
following the instructions and signages properly.
	   On placing more signages for passenger convenience, Muhammad
Adnan said more were being installed.
	   ``But we cannot have signages which are too big, since it may
spoil the beauty of the airport.
	   ``We don't want this airport to be like the one in Subang, which
has been dubbed `The Forest of Signages'.''
	   Five airlines took part in the trial run with 15 departures and
15 arrivals.
	   Each flight carried 150 or more passengers who were left on
their own to find their way to the departure and arrival halls.
	   Adnan said the response from the public was overwhelming.
	   ``We expected about 2,500 people to turn up, but I think more
than twice that participated.''
	   He said more trials would be conducted on June 11, 18 and 25.
	   ``There will also be two rehearsals for the opening day ceremony
and two trials for the commencement of full commercial
operations.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
