<BODY>
<SLUG> MAS-TO-REVIEW-FARES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAS to review fares after shift, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
MAS to review fares after shift, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Azrani RustamASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SEPANG, Sat. - Malaysia Airlines will review its fares after it
moves into its new base at the Kuala Lumpur International Airport,
its chairman Tan Sri Tajudin Ramli said today.
	   He said currently in Malaysia, airlines generally needed to
increase their fares by as much as 80 per cent to break even.
	   ``This is mainly due to the cost increase on items such as spare
parts and fuel due to factors such as the depreciation of the
ringgit.
	   ``Malaysia Airlines has not made any application to the
Government for an increase, but we will study our cost structure
after moving into KLIA.
	   ``If our study tells us an increase is needed, we will make an
application.''
	   Speaking to the New Sunday Times after hosting a visit of senior
editorial staff of NST Sdn Bhd to the airline's facilities at KLIA,
Tajudin said MAS was ``completely ready'' to begin operations at
the RM10.5 billion airport.
	   The airport will commence full commercial operations on June 30.
	   Asked if Malaysia Airlines would retain some domestic flights in
Subang, he said the airline would operate all its flight from
Sepang as there would be a lot of confusion if flights were
operated simultaneously at two hubs.
	   ``It would be very expensive not only for us but also for
Malaysia Airports Berhad as we would need to have two sets of
employees at the airports.''
	   He added while passengers would need to get used to the idea of
having to travel to get to KLIA, they should also appreciate the
fact that the airport is not too far from the city compared with
major airports elsewhere.
	   ``Narita Airport is about two hours away from Tokyo city and
even the airport in Subang now takes longer than an hour to reach
at peak hours.''
	   On its employees' housing, Tajudin said the airline viewed the
issue as ``crucial''.
	   ``However, the airport is now accessible to our staff living in
Subang Jaya and Petaling Jaya with the NSE-Central Link expressway.
So there seems no need for staff to move nearer to KLIA.''
	   The airline will provide a RM200 travel allowance to staff who
have to travel from the capital to the new airport.
	   About 12,000 cabin crew and administrative personnel will be
posted at the KLIA. This constitutes about 95 per cent of the
airline's total labour force.
	   The airline's administrative offices in Subang will remain
operational when KLIA opens.
	   Tajudin said in the long-term, Malaysia Airlines will be
shifting all its employees closer to Sepang, with a new
headquarters at Putrajaya.
	   The visit today by seven senior NSTSB editorial staff was led by
group editor Datuk A. Kadir Jasin. Present were NST's Business and
Finance editor K.H. Lim, Malay Mail editor Fauzi Omar, Malaysian
Business editor Susan Tham, Investors' Digest editor Dr Harun
Derauh, Business Times acting editor Akhiruddin Atan and features
editor Aishah Ali.
	   
</TEXT>
