<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Briefs, 1st Ld-Writethru,0766 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Includes items on century dream team, World Cup odds, Nigerian
</HEADLINE>
dissident, Blatter, Italian team news. &QL; 
 &UR; EDS: UPDATES last item with Ravenelli taken for X-rays. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Pele, Platini and Beckenbauer on the same team.
With Maradona, Garrincha and Cruyff in support.
	   A dream team for the century was unveiled Tuesday when
MasterCard announced the FIFA World Football Team. The group of
all-time all-stars featured four Brazilians, two Argentines, a
German, a Frenchman, a Russian, an Englishman and a Dutchman.
	   ``It is a great honor to be included with such players, the best
of soccer,'' Pele said.
	   The team was chosen by a worldwide panel of journalists, who
first voted for the 11 best players of the century in different
confederations. A total of five confederation teams, from Europe,
Africa, South America, North and Central America and the Caribbean,
and Asia and Oceania, were selected.
	   From those squads, 55 finalists were picked for balloting on the
world team.
	   The team consisted of Brazil's Pele, Garrincha, Nilton Santos
and Carlos Alberto; Argentinas Diego Maradona and Alfredo Di
Stefano; West Germany's Franz Beckenbauer; France's Michel Platini,
the co-chairman of the 1998 World Cup; the Soviet Union's Lev
Yashin; England's Bobby Moore; and the Netherlands' Johan Cruyff.
	   Pele, Garrincha and Maradona were selected as forwards. In
midfield were Cruyff, Di Stefano and Platini. On defense were
Beckenbauer, Moore; Carlos Alberto and Nilton Santos. The
goalkeeper was Yashin.
	   On behalf of the 11 players, MasterCard is making a donation to
the SOC Children's Villages, FIFA's official charity.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   LONDON (AP) _ Despite the loss of Romario and coach Mario
Zagallo's worry about his defense, Brazil remained Britain
bookmaker Ladbrokes favorite to win the World Cup.
	   The defending champions were listed as 3-1 favorites, while
France was the second choice at 11-2. Italy was third at 6-1 with
both Argentina and Germany 7-1 picks.
	   England sliped to 9-1, its longest odds since qualifying while
the Netherlands and Spain were 10-1.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Exiled Nigerian dissident Wole Soyinka is
asking soccer fans to use the World Cup as a way to protest
Nigeria's military government.
	   Speaking Tuesday regarding the death of Gen. Sani Abacha, the
1986 Nobel Prize winner in literature urged World Cup fans to jeer
the Nigerian flag, wear black arm bands or distribute pictures and
leaflets about the regime's atrocities.
	   Nigeria plays its first match in France '98 Saturday against
Spain in Nantes, France.
	   Soyinka said that ideally Nigeria should be treated the same way
as South Africa was during apartheid, including having its teams
banned from sporting events.
	   Barring that, he said, ``What we ask is at least some gesture of
solidarity with the Nigerian people.''
	   ___ &QC; 
	   PARIS (AP) _ A day after he was elected president of FIFA, Sepp
Blatter kept a low profile Tuesday, quietly helping in preparations
for the start of the World Cup.
	   Blatter, who loves the spotlight, will undoubtedly be more
public as the tournament, which starts Wednesday, progresses. Among
other things, he's expected to make at least one appearance at the
daily news briefings FIFA and French organizers hold _ but not just
yet.
	   ``Mr. Blatter is very busy trying to figure out how to spell
`president,' and just what it means,'' FIFA spokesman Keith Cooper
said.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   SENLIS, France (AP) _ Italian striker Enrico Chiesa was
preparing to return home Tuesday with the health of Alessandro Del
Piero and Moreno Torricelli improving. But then again, he may stick
around to replace Fabrizio Ravanelli.
	   The Parma forward, taken to France as Italy's 23rd player, had
been put on alert as a possible substitute if case either Del Piero
or Torricelli were too hurt to play.
	   Del Piero has recovered from a right thigh strain and is
expected to return to action against Cameroon next week.
	   Torricelli, suffering from a bruised right foot, resumed
training Tuesday.
	   Neither player is expected to be ready for Italy's World Cup
opener against Chile on Thursday.
	   But late in the day, Fabrizio Ravanelli was taken for X-rays to
check for bronchitis. The Olympique Marseille striker was battling
a slight fever and cough earlier in the day. Teams can make changes
to their roster for injuries or illness up to kickoff of the
opening game, 1530 GMT Wednesday.
</TEXT>
