<HEADER>
w1467 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WorldCup-FinallyItSta 1stLd-Writethru   06-09 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-World Cup-Finally It Starts, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Parisians catch the spirit at ``Festival of Soccer''
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with start of parade; color. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By MORT ROSENBLUM &QC; 
 &UR; AP Special Correspondent &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Four jolly giants in assorted colors of humanity
strode through Paris like good-guy Godzillas Tuesday to symbolize a
World Cup that France hopes will loom large in history.
	   Blaring ethno-techno music and escorted by 4,500 costumed
extras, the 18-meter (60-foot) robots took separate routes toward
the Place de la Concorde, the heart of a kickoff party for 1
million people.
	   ``We want to show that football is accessible to everyone and
belongs to no one,'' said Jean-Pascal Levy-Trumet, who designed the
``Fete du Football'' show. ``The grand theme is universality in a
single world.''
	   Moussa, an African giant, was the first to awake at the Tuesday
evening kickoff, opening his eyes to enthusiastic applause. He was
accompanied by little kids on ostriches _ actually people on stilts
_ and dancing African baobab trees and termite hills.
	   The 38-ton giants were powered by small trucks hidden in their
shoes, which moved back and forth to make the giants look like they
were rocking.
	   Parisians awoke to find the giants at familiar monuments, along
with throngs of strangely dressed tourists from the 31 nations
joining France in the globe's biggest sports tournament.
	   Pablo, the American Indian giant, crouched under the Arc de
Triomphe, ready for his afternoon stroll down the Champs Elysees to
the animated trees and bugs that depict nature.
	   Moussa waited by the Eiffel Tower, to symbolically discover man
and the earth on his wheel-assisted walk past Napoleon's Tomb and
across the ornate Alexandre III bridge.
	   Romeo, the European, snoozed outside the Opera Garnier. His
theme was love, and along his route waited a sculptor's conception
of the Urban Woman, a mere 4.5 meters (15 feet) tall.
	   Ho, the Asian, camped overnight on the Pont Neuf, where he would
encounter flying fish, dragons and whimsical beasts illustrating
his themes of spirituality and fantasy.
	   Heavy overnight rains did not dampen the mood, but they washed
off Ho's loincloth, made of rubberized-plastic, exposing the
midriff of his articulated steel skeleton. Workmen pinned it back
on.
	   Among hard-to-impress Parisians, the four colossi received mixed
reviews. Along the city's grand boulevards, real characters seemed
to attract more attention. Clusters of soccer fans roamed the
streets in outlandish outfits and gaudy colors.
	   For once, passersby paid more attention to skirts on men rather
than women. Perhaps 20,000 Scots came across the Channel for the
opening game with Brazil on Wednesday. Most wore kilts.
	   Scott Wallace, a fishmonger, and his housepainter friend, Gerry
Shiels, sat behind tankards of lager at the Cafe Montecristo, each
with bare knees and Highland feathers towering above their hats.
	   ``I think we'll beat 'em, 2-1,'' Wallace said, a little
hopefully. ``Aye,'' Shiels agreed. ``And if we do, it'll be some
party.''
	   From the looks of things Tuesday, there'll be some party,
anyway. Still, transport strikes by Air France and ticket foulups
have left many fans furious.
	   Crowds pushed their way into the France 98 shop to buy World Cup
paraphernalia: polyster T-shirts, caps, crowd-parting cologne,
fuzzy stuffed versions of the goofy-looking rooster mascot named
Footix.
	   Visitors seemed to show more interest than the French. Jacques
Lambert, head of the organizing committee, complained of an evident
lack of fervor among the general public.
	   A block off the Champs Elysees, Jean-Pierre Arnal sat alone in
his little hardware store, wearing his usual white smock with his
dog at his feet.
	   ``Oouuff,'' he replied when asked about the World Cup, employing
a beloved French nonword that means the same thing as shrugged
shoulders. ``I suppose it's a good thing, economically.''
	   Around the corner, Emmannuel Delhomme painted a banner on the
awning of his bookshop, the Livre Sterling: ``Good news, ladies.
This store will be open during all of the games of the World Cup.''
	   Delhomme, no soccer fan, said he was a little wary of the
snarled traffic, the armed police and boisterous visitors.
	   ``But, after all,'' he concluded, ``it's a good thing. Parisians
are so sad, so stressed, and this is a change. All these people in
colors and a happy mood. It is something new to talk about.''
	   (mr-var)
</TEXT>
