<SLUG> DEPARTMENT-TAKING-FLOODS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Department taking measures to prevent floods, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Department taking measures to prevent floods, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Leong Shen-liASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sat. - The Drainage and Irrigation Department has
begun taking steps to prevent floods in view of the recent
increased rainfall.
	   Its director-general Keizrul Abdullah said the department's
staff, with the local authorities' co-operation, had carried out
more frequent river inspections and removed all obstructions
immediately.
	   ``Rubbish which gets trapped during the dry spell will obstruct
water flow once the rains come,'' he said in an interview.
	   In the medium term, Keizrul said his department was looking into
installing machines which automatically removed rubbish trapped in
rubbish screens erected in rivers.
	   ``These machines will have to operate automatically because we
cannot afford to have people running all over town to start them
when there is a downpour.''
	   He said several tests had been done but the results were not as
effective as expected.
	   Some of the machines had problems when operating during heavy
thunderstorms.
	   The machines, he said, were necessary because unremoved garbage
from the rubbish traps would cause the water to be dammed up and
the drains to overflow.
	   Besides rubbish, Keizrul explained that the inability of rivers
and drains to handle a high level of run-off also caused floods.
	   ``Although we ensure that the drains are properly designed when
a project is developed, projects are often built next to existing
developed areas.
	   There is no way for rainwater to be drained except through the
drains of the existing housing estates.''
	   Keizrul said it would be unfair to force the developer of the
existing housing estate to enlarge the drains to handle the
increased capacity.
	   In the long term, Keizrul said the DID was looking into managing
water flow rather than increasing the river's capacity.
	   ``Like roads, you cannot continuously widen it.''
	   Keizrul said laws were being drafted to provide for developers
to pay for excessive run-off from project sites.
	   This would encourage developers to look into alternative methods
of managing run-off such as diverting and retaining rainwater.
	   
</TEXT>
