<HEADLINE>
Woei Sheng's surgery a success, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Woei Sheng's surgery a success, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   JOHOR BARU, Sat. - Eight-month-old Chan Woei Sheng has undergone
a successful operation to correct a birth defect which had made it
difficult for him to defecate.
	   The seven-hour operation at the Puteri Specialist Hospital on
Wednesday has enabled him to lead a normal life.
	   The surgery was made possible by generous New Straits Times
readers who helped finance the operation.
	   They included businessman Datuk Sunny Choong of Kuala Lumpur and
his two brothers who donated RM7,500 for the surgery and
hospitalisation, after reading about his plight in the NST last
month.
	   Woei Sheng, due to his birth defect, had to use a catheter bag
to urinate and defecate.
	   ``Since his operation, he has been on drips. But the doctors
said he would be able to eat from tomorrow,'' said his mother, Chew
Sai Lan.
	   Woei Sheng of Senai, had been suffering from the defect,
clinically called Hirschprung's disease since birth.
	   This is his second surgery. He underwent his first surgery when
he was only six days old, to make an opening so that he could
defecate through it.
	   Chew thanked the NST for highlighting her son's plight and to
NST readers for their donations.
	   ``I cannot thank them enough. I can only pray that God will
reward them accordingly,'' she said.
	   
</TEXT>
