<BODY>
<SLUG> 'PRETTY-DAMN-QUICK' sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Making it's name `pretty damn quick', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Making it's name `pretty damn quick', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IN this age of reinventing ourselves to face the uncertainties
of the business climate, one agency has broken the rules and
re-engineered in a new way.
	   Apart from calling itself PDQ (an acronym for Pretty Damn
Quick), it expanded upon the many functions of an ad agency by
going the extra mile to offer other value-added services under one
roof.
	   Citing the realities of today's marketplace where clients demand
the best professional input at every step of their marketing plan,
the PDQ Group is geared to handle advertising and design, public
relations, event management, publishing, premium sourcing and even
production up to printing at its premises in Section 5, Petaling
Jaya.
	   Driven by a taskforce of 20 professionals, it is slowly gaining
momentum as a one-stop centre for clients who don't have the time
to oversee all facets of their business and marketing
communications needs.
	   I managed to track down Tony Heneberry Managing Director of the
PDQ Group for the inside story last week.
	   S: Who are the main players in the PDQ Group and where do their
expertise lie in the grand scheme of things?
	   H: There are four main people. I started my first company in
1985, and have run management consultancy businesses and
entertainment companies in Europe.
	   Errol de Cruz is an experienced journalist, editor, and
published author and has been with the newspapers for a long time.
He now runs the PR and Event Management businesses, under PDQ
Management.
	   Margaret Wing was with the Dunlop Slazenger Group, firstly in
the UK, then Malaysia as Worldwide Purchasing Director. She now
manages the operations of the PDQ Group and runs the Sourcing
division.
	   Finally, we have Y.K. Gan, who has worked in colour separation
and printing for over 10 years. He runs PDQ Production, doing
colour separation and printing.
	   S: Does an all-in-one concept like this demand a heavy capital
outlay?
	   H: The business was established and has subsequently grown on
the basis of the quality of its resources, both in terms of
equipment and people.
	   As a result, the business did require substantial capital
investment to get started.
	   Our current advantage is that all investment has been by way of
shareholders' capital, and no bank borrowings.
	   S: How do you juggle responsibilities on a given project?
	   H: Responsibilities and work load are allocated according to
individual strengths. Our flat company structure, and equity-based
management approach ensure that as a group we are driven to
deliver.
	   S: What sort of clients do you wish to attract in these tough
times?
	   H: We hope to attract clients who can pay on time! Actually, a
weak economy tends to be an opportunity for certain sectors, for
example, beer and cigarettes usually do very well.
	   In addition, low ticket discretionary purchases such as
fast-food, ice cream, and branded soft drinks can maintain good
sales.
	   In Europe and US, DIY and home improvement has always been a
good recession business, but this will probably not be as marked in
Malaysia/Asia. However, the superstores and hypermarkets should
benefit from the discount mentality which prevails in a weak
economy.
	   S: Which type of client will gain from your roster of services
and how?
	   H: A client who has traditionally relied upon advertising as
their main communication tool will certainly find our approach to
be more cost- effective.
	   The PDQ approach is not prejudiced in favour of one `tactic'
over another. We evaluate the most appropriate and cost-effective
use of PR, events, direct marketing, design, collaterals, premiums
and advertising.
	   In this market the client needs to squeeze much higher value out
of their marketing investment, and it is essential therefore for us
to be able to rationalise and recommend the most appropriate
solution.
	   S: Tell us about a recent project that benefited from the value
of all the offerings within the PDQ Group.
	   H: There's ASPAC - Malaysia's leading executive search company.
	   We developed a communications programme and provided a
specialised management resource, both to plan the programme and to
manage its execution.
	   We identified the best tools with which to achieve the
objectives - a low-cost advertising device, corporate events, a
press, radio and TV PR campaign plus a direct marketing effort.
	   After six months, we achieved greater market awareness and
understanding, and an increase in business activity, compared to
their main competitors who are on average experiencing a
contraction of between 20 per cent and 30 per cent.
	   We also have a supportive client! S: How do you manage the
planning and buying of media space for clients wanting such?
	   H: As a medium-sized business we cannot carry a full media
research, planning, and booking resource. As a result we work with
Carat Mediabase which is Malaysia's largest independent media
broker.
	   This ensures that we are able to offer our clients a research
and planning facility equivalent to that of the international
agencies.
	   S: Are you intending expanding your current services or forging
some smart partnerships?
	   H: Yes and yes! We are already in discussion with certain
companies and we would hope to be able to announce further
development of the PDQ Group in the near future.
	   S: With the high cost of media these days, do you see more
clients hoping for free publicity, ie. PR coverage, to compensate
for the drop in advertising exposure?
	   H: The traditional understanding of PR is that it is a cheap way
of getting your company or brand name into the media. And to that
extent there has been a growth in interest in PR as a low-cost
alternative to advertising.
	   However, the correct use of PR as a communications
device/tactic, should not be based on cost. It should be based upon
the particular and unique benefits it can deliver to the
company/brand, when compared to other communication tools.
	   S: Many agencies have been laying off staff recently to brace
for even tougher times. Do you expect any downsizing in your
organisation?
	   H: We are still a relatively small organisation, and we are
actually recruiting. But this should be kept in context. As a small
organisation, the opportunity for growth is enormous.
	   A large agency, on the other hand, can never have the same
opportunity in percentage terms. Unfortunately, in the current
market, retrenching is the only prudent and practical option for
many of them.
	   S: Are you witnessing an upsurge in client spending of late?
	   H: If anything, total spending is dropping on a per client
basis.
	   However, we are seeing a dramatic increase in client enquiries.
	   This is probably because we can help our clients to work through
the issues in a structured and disciplined way, and together
identify solutions which are affordable and which are not
prejudiced in favour of any one specialised service.
	   Even with the best will, this is very difficult for a pure
advertising agency to do for its clients.
	   
</TEXT>
