w1485 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  CAUGHT-OFF-GUARDsked     06-09 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> CAUGHT-OFF-GUARD sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Better to be aware of options than caught off guard, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Better to be aware of options than caught off guard, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HOW do you manage your finances if you receive a pay cut, or
worse, lose your job?
	   Although this is a thought most of us would rather not
entertain, it is important to plan if there is a chance you could
end up in this boat. We have narrowed the process down to six
simple steps that you should examine in terms of income crisis
management.
	   Before we get into the steps on how to manage this unfortunate
situation, you have to determine what exactly you may possibly be
facing.
	   Are you a dual income family or a single income family? Are you
looking at pay reduction or job loss?
	   It is a good idea to get a realistic handle on your possible
situation so you can determine potential solutions.
	   Analyse Spending USE the following chart to take a second and
figure out where your pay goes on a monthly basis.
	   Although this is incredibly boring it will determine what your
absolute minimum monthly expenses are. You need to find out what
you, or your family, can scrape by on if need be.
	   This means getting rid of the extras like the fancy meals out or
the weekend shopping sprees for the family. By eliminating the
luxury spending we will get a clear picture of your minimum
financial obligations.
	   This does not mean deferring payments to a later date, we want
to look at the average monthly costs. So if you have some lump sum
expenses, such as an insurance payment, spread it out over a period
to even the cash flow.
	   Defer Major Expenditures AT this point, you will have to behave
like the government in this area and postpone any major purchases.
	   This holds true especially if you are looking at buying a luxury
good that will improve your lifestyle and hurt your finances. What
we are talking about here is the new car or stylish new furniture
for the house.
	   However, if it is a necessary purchase you have to be realistic.
For example, although the roof has a slow leak now may not be the
time to have the entire roof redone.
	   Identify Short-Term Assets NOW to do this properly you really
need to take a quick snapshot of all your assets and determine
which are short term and which are long term.
	   For regular readers this will be very easy. For others we refer
to short term assets as anything that can be converted to cash
within 30 days without a risk of capital depreciation.
	   In other words current accounts, savings, and Fixed Deposit's.
You get the picture?
	   Long-term assets are not that easy to convert and we will
discuss them further down the list.
	   Now that you have figured out-how-much you have in short-term
money you can roughly determine how long you can live off of this
pool if you lose all your income.
	   Some may just be looking to subsidize living costs to a certain
level if you are anticipating a drop in household income, but not
an outright elimination.
	   Obviously, if you think you are going to be out of work in the
near future you will want to cut back on the spending very quickly
and build up short term reserves.
	   It is important to note that you should not be turning
everything possible into cash at this point. That may come later.
	   Career/Income Options NOW, Wise Moves is not a career
counselling column, but we do have a few words of advice when it
comes to planning your finances.
	   If you are out of work, you have to be very realistic about your
chances of regaining employment and at what level. This will help
you to prepare a worse case scenario in terms of financial
management.
	   If you paint a worst case scenario and are able to make your
finances work in that situation, then you will be fine if things
turn out for the better.
	   Once you look at your situation and how long you can last on
your short term reserves it may also affect what type of work you
will take in the future. You may decide that some income is better
than no income until the picture looks brighter in the area where
you used to work.
	   Having said this, this is not an area of black and white
finance. All we are doing is encouraging you to look in advance. We
have seen far too many people who try to ignore the situation and
then are generally left with very few options, of which most are
not that attractive.
	   Restructure Debt THIS is an option that ideally will help reduce
the amount of money flowing out of the house on a monthly basis.
	   As you can well imagine there are many options and
considerations for one to consider. As this is the case we will
devote next week's Wise Moves to the topic of restructuring
personal debts.
	   Long-Term Assets DON'T worry, we are not going to tell you to
start selling your long-term investments! But we are going to tell
you to start realistically looking at the options you have in this
area in case worst comes to worst. It is critical to have an idea
of what you would liquidate if you had no other choice.
	   The reason is that you do not want to be trying to panic sell
long-term assets at the last minute, since you will most likely get
a much lower price than you would like.
	   If you plan in advance at least you will be able to get a fair
price for some of these assets. This whole process is not one of
optimism. But many people are worried these days about the
stability of their future income.
	   Although it may be only a slight possibility being aware of your
options is better than being completely caught off guard.
	   
</TEXT>
