<HEADLINE>
Family meetings important, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Family meetings important, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Dr Edward ChanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   WE have learned that a parent's role has an enormous impact on
developing the problem-solving ability of a child, an ability which
has critical importance for him throughout the rest of his life.
	   This week, we will explore specific ways on how you can exercise
your role as good leaders in problem-solving situations.
	   Few parents would argue the importance of helping children learn
good problem-solving habits, but many do not make the time to do
this.
	   One way to guarantee that you have opportunities to model
problem- solving skills for your children is by scheduling weekly
family meetings.
	   Making attendance mandatory - for parents as well as children -
will give children the message that you take your role as a family
leader seriously and you are committed to helping them develop
emotional and social skills for success.
	   For optimum effect, these meetings should last for half an hour.
As the leader(s) of the meeting, the parent(s) should insist on the
following ground rules.
	   Begin and end on time.
	   Don't interrupt when someone else is talking.
	   Don't criticise someone else's opinions or feelings.
	   Give everyone a chance to participate, but don't force them.
About half of the meeting should be spent on individual concerns
and the other half on problems that affect the family as a group.
	   Each person should have the opportunity to discuss and `think
out' a problem that he or she is having. This is the opportunity
for you to bring up your own issues that are appropriate for
discussion in the family.
	   For example, Fatimah has been coming home every day from work
with a headache and was uncharacteristically snappish with her
children and her husband. In a family meeting the mother of three
explained that pressure at her job was making her stressed and
anxious.
	   She was a paralegal for a large law firm and two of the lawyers
she worked with had given her more work than she could handle. She
didn't want to complain because she was up for a promotion but both
lawyers wanted her to make their work a priority.
	   She tackled the problem using the five-step problem-solving
process.
	   Identify the problem - ``I have more work than I can manage.''
	   Think of alternative solutions - ``I could a) tell both lawyers
that I am overworked, b) bring work home and work weekends, or c)
recommend that they hire a temporary worker and supervise that
person.''
	   Compare each solution - ``The first just puts the problem on the
lawyers, giving them more stress. The second will make things
harder on me and my family. The last acknowledges the problem,
provides a reasonable solution, and doesn't make work harder for me
or anyone else.''
	   Pick the best solution - ``The third. In the short run, it will
cost the firm a little money but in the long run the work will get
done quicker and more effectively.''
	   It is easy to see how Fatimah's children could learn from
watching her solve her problem out loud. They might then apply this
process to their own problems and conflicts.
	   As an added benefit, Fatimah makes the time to reason out her
problem, sharing with her family why she has been irritable and
giving them an opportuity to give her emotional support.
	   Once you have modeled the problem-solving process, your children
should have the opportunity to discuss a problem if they wish.
Younger children will need guidance in going through each of the
steps, but you may be surprised at how quickly even five-year-olds
catch on.
	   Each person in the family may also ask for help from other
family members. Children like to be given the opportunity to help
their parents with important matters and their opinions should be
respected.
	   Remember that problem-solving is a process where there are not
always right or wrong answers. It is also an activity that not only
contributes to the emotional development of your children, but
builds a sense of family cohesiveness and support as well.
	   
</TEXT>
