<HEADLINE>
US-based ISPseeks licence for Thailand, NATION
</HEADLINE>
US-based ISPseeks licence for Thailand, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   JIRAPAN BOONNOONASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   UUNET, a US-based Internet Service Provider, is asking the
Communications Authority of Thailand (CAT) for a licence to provide
Internet services to corporate users in Thailand, according to an
executive source at CAT.
	   In the negotiations so far, CAT will hold 32 per cent of shares
while CAT staff will have 3 per cent of total stock. The remainder
will be held by UUNet and Thai partners. Negotiations are expected
to be finalised soon. UUNet will provide Internet services at
speeds of 64 KB to corporate users this year and plans to provide
electronic commerce facilities as well. The pricing strategy is
expected to be its strong point.
	   After UUNet starts operating, the source said, all local
Internet Service Providers (ISPs) will be affected. UUNet has own
its international link which helps it to be more competitive than
local ISPs who have to pay massive fees to CAT for international
links.
	   ''The international link represents around 40 per cent of an
ISP's costs and this has increased due to the devaluation of the
baht. Although UUNet will have to pay for a half circuit for
internal links, it will still be more competitive than local
ISPs,'' the source said.
	   Kanokwan Wongwatanasin, president of Internet KSC Group, a local
ISP, said that the influx of international ISPs will certainly
affect local ISPs since international ISPs will be more competitive
than local ISPs in terms of investment and international link
costs.
	   Support from CAT in the form of a reduction of international
link charges and increased internal link speeds are essential to
the survival of local ISPs.
	   Kanokwan suggested that CAT rent its huge bandwidth to local
ISPs. This will help reduce ISP's investment costs by 20 per cent.
In the meantime, it should encourage Internet use in Thailand as
well as increase link capacity by such mean as setting up ATM
technology (Asynchronous Transfer Mode) in telecommunications
infrastructure.
	   ''If CAT ignores the support of local ISPs, the Thai Internet
industry will be dominated by foreign investors, the same as has
happened with other industries,'' he said.
	   Kanokwan said the demand for Internet facilities in business has
fallen by 50 per cent due to the economic turmoil while competition
in the industry is still high. However, the impact of the arrival
of UUNet will depend on its service.
	   
</TEXT>
