<BODY>
<SLUG> TOURISM-INDUSTRIES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Promoting archaeo-tourism, industries, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Promoting archaeo-tourism, industries, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Mimi Syed Yusof; Zubaidah Abu BakarASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ASK anyone where Chenderoh is and they will give you a vague
answer, pointing in the direction of Grik, situated along the Kuala
Kangsar-Grik road.
	   Not much is known about the constituency historically, a
traditionally Barisan Nasional area, that encompasses Lenggong and
Lubok Merbau. Its population of about 40,000 is mainly made up of
farmers and fishermen.
	   Despite having been provided with basic amenities Chenderoh,
located some 90km from Ipoh, has still retained much of its
kampung-look.
	   Rubber trees and oil palm estates line the Kuala Kangsar-Grik
road leading to the constituency, lending a rustic atmosphere to
the area.
	   Upon approaching Lenggong, the road widens and the scenic Tasek
Raban comes into view.
	   Tasek Raban, an artificial lake, was formed when the Sungai
Raban was flooded by the impounding of the Chenderoh Dam along
Sungai Perak over half a century ago.
	   The lake, which covers a vast area on both sides of the main
road, supports a rich supply of quality riverine fish and provides
a livelihood for the full-time fishermen living on the fringes of
the lake.
	   Apart from a becoming a popular tourist destination, the lake is
also the centre of a budding aquaculture industry being tapped by
the State Government, State Fisheries Department and the Farmers'
Organisation Authority.
	   There are over 20 aquaculture projects undertaken by various
individuals and groups, including the ex-servicemen's association.
	   The shores of the lake are dotted with aquaculture platforms and
cages.
	   Among the fish being bred in cages are jelawat, patin, talapia,
lampam jawa and baung.
	   Some of the fish harvested from the lake are being supplied to
restaurants in various parts of the country.
	   Because of the tourism potential, the State Government has
developed Tasik Raban and its vicinity into a resort-like setting
with facilities for anglers and holiday-makers.
	   One of them is the RM1.1 million tourist complex on the shore
along the main road. It was opened two years ago and comprises
restaurants, a tourist information centre and stalls.
	   At the entrance of the complex stands a RM50,000 monument on how
Lenggong got its name. It shows a leaning timber (''terlanggung''
timber) after being felled by using the traditional Orang Asli axe.
	   Elsewhere, not much development seems apparent in the
constituency, though concerted efforts by the State Government have
been taken to promote industrial development.
	   These efforts, some of which have brought a measure of progress
to the more rural areas, are seen as a manifestation of the wakil
rakyats who are determined to bring Chenderoh out from the shadows.
	   Member of Parliament for Chenderoh is Deputy Minister in the
Prime Minister's Department Datuk Mohamed Nazri Abdul Aziz, while
State Assemblyman for Lubok Merbau is Jamal Nasir Rasdi, who is
also Perak Umno Youth chief, and Chenderoh Umno division chairman
Talha Ismail is Lenggong State Assemblyman.
	   A lot is expected to come out of this combination of
intellectual and idealistic trio.
	   For Mohamed Nazri, his goal, among others, is to transform the
constituency into a haven for people from all walks of life, for
Jamal Nasir his plans include setting up a consortium to boost
economic activities while for Talha, education is a priority,
particularly religious education.
	   In more ways than one, many of these goals and aspirations have
had the desired effect.
	   For example, efforts have been made to bring in more economic
activities to prevent the younger people from leaving the area to
seek greener pastures at factories in Ipoh and Penang.
	   The nearby Perak Hanjoong cement factory, for instance, has
provided many job opportunities for the locals, while the
aquaculture industry has managed to rope in young entrepreneurs.
	   Plans are also underway to establish an industrial estate for
small and medium industries which is expected to bring in 10,000
jobs for the constituents.
	   And once the Grik-Kuala Kangsar highway is open more development
and economic activities are expected.
	   To further boost tourism in the constituency, there are plans to
develop Lenggong into an ``archaeo-tourism'' destination because of
the discovery of various pre-historic artifacts, dating back to
more than 30,000 years.
	   An archaeology museum, costing RM1.9 million to be undertaken by
Muzium Negara, will be built on a eight-hectare sight in Kota
Tampan near Lenggong to store and display the artifacts found in
the area and its surroundings.
	   One of the most distinctive artifacts discovered was that of the
Perak Man unearthed in Gua Gunung Runtuh at Lenggong in June 1990.
	   It is said to be the oldest and most complete human fossil ever
found in Southeast Asia. The remains were discovered by an
archaeological team from Universiti Sains Malaysia led by Prof
Datuk Dr Zuraina Abdul Majid and had attracted worldwide attention.
	   Aged between 10,000 and 11,000 years old, the Perak Man was
between 40 and 45 years old. According to archaeological records,
he was buried in a foetal position following a ritual, with some
food and shells.
	   Apparently this was not the only finding. In August 1996,
researchers unearthed 1,500 artifacts in Bukit Jawa, also in
Lenggong, which dated back 50,000 to 100,000 years.
	   The area was believed to be the centre of activity in Peninsular
Malaysia in the palaeolithic (Old Stone Age) times.
	   Chenderoh has a voter population of 32,614, with Malays making
up the majority of 72.4 per cent, Chinese 21.39 per cent, Indian
5.97 per cent and others 5.97 per cent.
	   
</TEXT>
