<SLUG> SOFTWARE-PROJECT-AIMS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Software project aims to encouragelocal developers, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Software project aims to encouragelocal developers, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   To boost the Thai software industry, the National Electronics
and Computer Technology Centre (Nectec) plans to set a standard for
object-oriented, game and Thai language programmes developed under
the Small Software project. Sompit Potipattanakorn reports.
	   The Small Software project, started in 1996, aims to encourage
students from secondary to undergraduate level to develop Thai
software. Under the project, Nectec contributes Bt2 million a year
to establish a software development contest every year.
	   ''The major purpose of this project is to encourage Thai
software developers to serve the Thai software industry in the
future,'' said Nectec's chief researcher at the software and
language engineering laboratory, Chonchanok Viravan.
	   Although the major purpose of this project is to boost the
number of Thai software developers to resolve the lack of IT
personnel, the quality of software is the next concern.
	   Chonchanok said even though it was developed by students, some
software which won in the contest last year is of sufficient
quality to use.
	   However, to encourage as much software as possible to meet a
higher standard, the project committee plans to set a benchmark in
next year's event. The types of software which will have to meet
the standards include object-oriented software, game software and
Thai language software.
	   ''These three areas are very important for the Thai software
industry,'' she said.
	   Object-oriented software and game software are considered to
have huge potential in the worldwide market.
	   According to a survey, game software currently dominates the
total software market worldwide, while the global value of
object-oriented software is expected to rise from Bt44 trillion
this year to Bt220 trillion by 2001.
	   ''We don't dream of developing software to compete with big
software developers such as Microsoft, but we hope that Thai
software developers can develop small or object-oriented software
to sell to big developers. Therefore we have to set a standard,''
Chonchanok said.
	   On the other hand, the lack of standardisation of Thai language
software is the major cause of the money wasted in software
development. All Thai software developers have to develop the
entire programme if they want to make software for Thai use. Some
programmes such as word checkers, Thai Optical Character
Recognition, text to speech and Thai structural are essential
components of any Thai software.
	   ''If this software has a set standard, Thai developers will no
longer need to waste time and money duplicating parts of it,'' she
said.
	   The standard for these areas will be introduced for the contest
next year. In addition, the Small Software contest next year will
focus on developing software for educational purposes and for use
by disabled people.
	   ''We try to encourage the development of software for society as
well,'' she said.
	   The software for disabled people in the contest will be
concerned with access to information and support for learning
facilities.
	   This year, Nectec donated around 25 software items which won the
Small Software contest last year to the Office of the National
Primary Education Commission and the Department of General
Education.
	   ''This is the first year that we have donated winning software
to schools for educational purposes. If any school wants this free
software to help in teaching, it can contact both offices directly.
However, distribution of this software for free will be limited to
educational purposes only,'' Chonchanok said.
	   Although the Small Software Project is a minimal project which
contributes only Bt2 million per year, it brings benefit to both
government and private sectors. For examaple, the cost of software
which has been donated to schools works out to only Bt1 to Bt2 per
school.
	   ''We also hope that this project will be the first software
library in Thailand. The software library will help software
developers to develop software which was not completed by other
developers, with no need to start from the beginning,'' she said.
	   Even though it represents only a small move in the development
of IT in Thailand, if supported continually and seriously, it will
result in many advantages to the IT industry in the near and
distant future.
	   
</TEXT>
