w1501 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  VIRTUAL-CAMPUS-ESTABLISH     06-09 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> VIRTUAL-CAMPUS-ESTABLISH sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Virtual campus established, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Virtual campus established, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   To become an international school, Vajiravudh College has set up
a multimedia lab to develop CD-Rom titles while implementing its
own network instead of using traditional paper-based books. Sompit
Potipattanakorn reports.
	   So-called virtual campuses are the centre of attention in the
field of education these days since they are considered to soon be
playing an important role.
	   Apart from establishing electronic networks, CD-Rom lessons are
another aspect of the virtual campus concept.
	   With the hope of becoming an international school next year,
Vajiravudh College, a prestigious government school, plans to
develop CD-Rom titles to replace traditional paper-based books as
well as implementing its own network.
	   ''Our first CD-Rom title, which is to teach English, was
launched early this year,'' said Malcolm Hossick, adviser to the
director.
	   The initiative for developing its own CD-Rom titles was that
most CD-Rom titles available for schools, even from England,
Australia or the United States, are thought to be unsuitable for
Thai students.
	   Therefore the school started to set up the multimedia lab last
year, aimed at developing CD-Rom titles for its students. It was
one year before the lab was finished.
	   The multimedia lab will be responsible for the development of
CD-Rom titles according to guidelines which will be written by
Vajiravut instructors.
	   Its first CD-Rom for teaching English included five titles --
Telling the Time I and II, Calendar, and Opposite I and II, and was
created by the multimedia staff as a trial project.
	   ''Even though the quality of our first CD-Rom is not all that we
would like and it cannot interact with students, it is useful.
However, we plan to develop interactive and animated CD-Roms
soon,'' said Pongpipat Sohsakul, a technician at the multimedia
lab.
	   Hossick added that learning through the CD-Roms will help each
student reach greater objectives. When teaching without CD-Roms, an
instructor cannot concentrate on all students who are at different
levels of skill or intelligence. If the teacher focuses on the less
skilled students, those with higher skills may become bored. On the
other hand, if the teacher concentrates on the students of higher
skills, the others may not be able to catch up.
	   With the CD-Roms, the less skilled students can repeat the
lessons if they fall behind, while the students with higher skills
can go on to the next lesson. Meanwhile, the teacher can monitor
the improvement of each student through a central computer screen.
	   This year the school plans to develop CD-Rom titles about
English for both primary and secondary levels, and then develop
others about different disciplines such as mathematics and science.
	   ''English is our first priority since it is the major problem
for most Thai students and teachers hoping to access information
and communicate with others. If our students have an English
ability, they can access an unlimited amount of information through
the fantastic Internet. If they are not competent in English, they
feel as if they are entering a jungle when going online,'' he said.
	   The company hopes to have CD-Rom titles for all courses in the
next five years. Meanwhile, the school will distribute its CD-Rom
titles to other schools at a discount price, perhaps around Bt30 a
title.
	   ''CD-Rom titles as well as the Internet will play the major role
in education in the future. The Internet is quite simple but
enormously helpful -- anyone can access information from anywhere
around the world almost instantly. The CD-Roms will soon be a
better tool, helping teachers to deal with all students,'' he said.
	   The teacher will continue to play an important role in education
as a facilitator, showing what to learn and how to learn.
	   In the next two years, the school will provide nearly all
lessons through CD-Rom or diskette rather than through traditional
text books.
	   Like many international schools and universities in other
countries, in the future, Vajiravut College students will use only
a laptop computer instead of paper-based books to complete their
courses.
	   ''When that happens, all our students will have to have their
own laptops. All learning processes will be done through laptop
computers,'' he said.
	   Each day, students will carry only their own laptop to their
classes. Any time, anywhere on the school, they will be able to
connect their personal computers to the school's network or the
Internet to access any information they want.
	   Sometimes, students receive assignments from their instructors,
complete the work, and submit it back to the the instructors
through the network or on diskette.
	   In the meantime, lecturers have no paper-based lectures to
deliver since all lessons they plan are stored on the network or a
server.
	   In the class, students just connect their computer to access
that lesson, and learn from the electronic contents while the
lecturer is speaking to the class.
	   With information technology, students are able to learn
independently when ever they want. By just accessing the network,
they find everything at their fingertips.
	   To bring this concept to reality, apart from developing CD-Rom
titles, the school is implementing two protocols to connect with
the Internet as well as servers for recording the CD-Rom titles and
students' information. It plans to provide computer hardware in
every building as well as an e-mail address to all 900 students and
teachers next year.
	   ''Next year our network will be complete. All our classroom
buildings will be linked together. All teachers will use CD-Rom
titles as an aid and they will also write the text to develop their
own lessons,'' Pongpipat said.
	   To encourage teachers to use computers as an aid to teaching,
the school has offered computer training courses to all teachers.
In the meantime, it will encourage students to become familiar with
computers by providing computer courses. The design and technology
department is a trial project.
	   ''The design course using the computer has been available since
early this year. However, it is a sophisticated technology for both
our students and teachers. We have to take time to study to make it
useful,'' he said.
	   However, it is hoped that such courses will help students to use
computers for design work, allowing them to compete other schools,
since computers are a common device for design work these days.
	   
</TEXT>
