<SLUG> CALL-TO-CREATE-JOBS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Call to create jobs to lure back youths who migrated, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Call to create jobs to lure back youths who migrated, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THOUGH satisfied with its infrastructures, Chenderoh residents
hope to see more concerted efforts taken by the authorities to
promote tourism and industrial development.
	   By developing the two sectors they think Chenderoh will become
more attractive for young people who have migrated to towns and
other states to return.
	   Many young men and women had left the area where economic
activities are mainly agriculture-based to seek greener pastures.
Most of them work in factories in Ipoh or Penang while a
considerably large number are in the civil service and working in
other states.
	   If either the Government or the private sector capitialised on
existing resources to develop the two sectors, more economic
activities will be spurred.
	   This will provide opportunities for local residents to
participate in development besides becoming an attraction for those
who had migrated to return.
	   MOHD FAUZI MOHD HANAFIAH, 42, who returned to live in Bukit
Nangka a year ago after many years working with a private firm in
Kelantan said Lenggong town and its vicinity had undergone very
little change in the last decade.
	   ``We have good social and healthcare facilities but what we need
most are industries to spur development in other sectors and
provide jobs to the locals,'' he said.
	   Mohd Fauzi who runs a sundry shop in Lenggong town said many
young people, especially women work in factories in Kuala Kangsar
and Ipoh and they travelled daily to work in factory vans.
	   ``We have only a small garment factory here which recruited some
locals,''
	   he added.
	   Coffee-shopowner FONG YEN AUN, 60 said more development is
needed to attract more people to the area besides providing job
opportunities to the locals.
	   He said in view of the lack of development and job prospects,
many young people have left their kampungs in search of work
elsewhere forcing the older generation to continue with their
age-old occupations like tapping rubber and planting padi.
	   ``Few people stop at this town and as a result, business is
badly affected especially during the current economic situation.
	   ``Perhaps, more tourism projects should be developed to
encourage more people to come for a visit,'' he said, adding that
present tourism projects are mostly confined to Tasek Raban which
is quite far from the Lenggong town.
	   ALIAS MISORI, 53, a boat operator from Kampung Beng said what
his village urgently need is a secondary school so that children
from kampungs on the other side of the Sungai Perak, do not need to
cross the river daily.
	   ``After crossing the river by boat, they have to continue the
rest of the journey to three secondary schools in Lenggong in a
crowded van for another 10km.
	   ``There are more than 90 secondary schoolchildren from three
kampungs including Kampung Beng and a small school would be
sufficient to accommodate them so that they do not have to risk
their lives daily in order to go to school,'' he said.
	   Although there were plans to build a bridge across the river,
the children would still have to take the boat ride as it would be
faster.
	   Besides that there is nothing that the town folk have that we
don't have - like clean water supply provided under the rural water
supply project by the Health Department, electricity and
solar-powered public telephones.
	   SADARIAH ABDUL HAMID, 40, said as rural folks, there was not
much the residents of Chenderoh could complain of because they have
all the facilities.
	   ``The only thing we need is more interaction with our wakil
rakyat so problems could be resolved faster,'' said the lady who
sells goreng pisang at Tasik Raban.
	   On the migration of young people to towns, Sadariah said: ``This
is normal, I too was working at a factory in Penang before I got
married and settled down at Kampung Suak, near here.
	   ``Young people want to gain experience outside their villages
but they will come back when they get older,'' she said.
	   Sadariah believed that many of those who had migrated would
return if there are factories operating in their hometown.
	   She also said that tourism-related activities at existing lakes
like Tasik Raban and limestone hills could be further developed to
boost economic activities.
	   Tailor ABDULLAH MD SAMAN, 66, said four of his children migrated
to work in factories in Ipoh because there was no prospects for
them in Chenderoh.
	   ``They are earning good income at the factories, I think they
will come back to work here if there are job opportunities.
	   ``I heard the rubber estates here are also facing worker
shortage problem because there are no young people around,'' he
said.
	   Abdullah who runs a tailoring shop and lives in Chepor not far
from Lenggong town said there was not much physical development.
	   ``This is a rural area with adequate and comfortable basic
facilities.
	   ``We have good water, electricity, telephone and road facilities
and our problems are always attended to promptly by the elected
representatives.''
	   Kampung Beng headman RODI PUTEH, 50, said some 2,000 residents
of his village are comfortable with the facilities provided by the
Government.
	   ``We would appreciate if the Government can provide a secondary
school for our children who now have to make trips on sampans
across the Perak river to school,'' he said.
	   Rodi said tourism potentials of the Perak river could be
capitalised to promote Perak's tourism industries and also to spur
economic activities for the locals.
	   ``The Government or the private sector should capitalise on the
river and carry out tourism activities.
	   ``Most of the head of families in my village work as rubber
tappers and with new opportunities, they could earn some extra
income,'' he added.
	   
</TEXT>
