w1510 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  WATER-ISSUE-BE-IGNOREDsk     06-09 1905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> WATER-ISSUE-BE-IGNORED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Water issue cannot be ignored, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Water issue cannot be ignored, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   A. Kadir JasinASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SELANGOR Menteri Besar Datuk Abu Hassan Omar may be pleased with
himself for having successfully precipitated the cancellation of
the Federation of Malaysian Consumers Associations' forum on water
shortage planned for Wednesday in Kuala Lumpur.
	   A letter from Abu Hassan's office to Fomca president Professor
Hamdan Adnan asking for it not to be held had suggested that it
``would confuse the public''.
	   The police seemed to have come to his aid by refusing the permit
for the gathering.
	   But Abu Hassan's victory may be short-lived or even deceiving.
Fomca and its supporters have every reason to be more upset with
Abu Hassan than they already are with the Selangor Waterworks
Department for its poor handling of the crisis.
	   The people who are affected by the water crisis, including Umno
members who were invited to the forum, are more likely to be on the
side of Fomca.
	   One wonders what harm such a public meeting can do to the
already low rating the State Government and the JBA are getting for
their handling of the crisis.
	   Even the Sultan had joined others in criticising the department
for ignoring warnings of the impending shortage.
	   One wonders, too, why Abu Hassan, like so many other
politicians, is so afraid of having their performance reviewed.
	   Isn't it better for them to have their performance reviewed
noisily at a forum than silently, but negatively, in polling
booths?
	   We cannot talk about freedom of expression if people are not
allowed to discuss an everyday issue like water. If we cannot
handle a debate on water shortage, how can we debate the larger and
more sensitive issues like the economy, race, religion, culture and
language?
	   Or is Abu Hassan worried that the forum will set the people
thinking more critically about the efficiency of the State
Government and its machinery?
	   Had the public been told of the precarious water situation, say
six months or a year ago, they would certainly not mind having the
supply reduced in stages.
	   Instead water supply had to be cut from 24 hours a day to
nothing for hundreds of thousands of consumers.
	   With bungles by departments like the JBA and others, it is
questionable if the Malaysian public service will ever receive the
ISO certification.
	   More worrying is the talk that some affected foreign-owned
factories may leave Malaysia for other countries.
	   WITH the economy in an unfavourable condition and the recovery
remaining uncertain, it is imperative that we give some serious
thought to non- economic aspects of life.
	   Employment and education are among them. We need better policies
than merely ensuring that the retrenched workers are appropriately
compensated and more places created in institutions of higher
learning.
	   While Human Resources Minister Datuk Lim Ah Lek is doing a
commendable job ensuring that the interests of the retrenched
workers are safeguarded, a broader and more permanent policy is
needed.
	   Unless the economy recovers quickly, the rate of retrenchment,
and consequently unemployment, will increase. Already the level of
hiring has dropped.
	   With tens of thousands of school-leavers and university
graduates entering the job market, the unemployment rate could jump
suddenly. Yet we are being told that the Government had received
applications from the manufacturing and plantation sectors to
employ more than 76,000 foreign workers.
	   Admittedly, it will be difficult to encourage young Malaysians
to take up all the vacancies in the plantation sector. But surely
there must be plantation jobs which may still be attractive to
local workers if properly publicised.
	   Maybe these young workers are not aware that many plantation
jobs are no longer back-breaking. They are not only highly
mechanised but also well paid.
	   WITH only 78,000 places available in the universities and
colleges for this year's intake as opposed to nearly 455,000
students who sat the Sijil Pelajaran Malaysia and Sijil Tinggi
Persekolahan Malaysia last year, the pressure on the job market
will be considerable.
	   Despite the expansion of higher education through the setting up
of more public universities and the introduction of private higher
education institutions, many of the students will still not get a
place despite achieving good grades.
	   While some of those who are offered places may not be able to
take them up due to financial constraints, they will end up in the
job market.
	   A huge number of these school-leavers are more than qualified to
take up jobs in the manufacturing sector which are currently being
offered to foreigners. Maybe a wider publicity by the Government,
industries and employers will attract these young job-seekers.
	   Such a publicity, especially in the Bahasa Malaysia, Chinese and
Tamil media, will help. Many of today's manufacturing and
industrial jobs are better-paying than white-collar or clerical
jobs, and the working conditions are just as pleasant.
	   Also it is time the Human Resources Minister spent less time
ensuring that retrenched workers were suitably compensated and more
on finding ways to discourage retrenchment.
	   This he can do by advising and encouraging workers, especially
union members, to think more favourably of salary cuts rather than
forcing employers to resort to retrenchment.
	   There are many employers who would rather resort to salary cuts
and other cost-cutting measures than retrenching workers.
	   With businesses falling, the cost of funds remaining high and
access to loans curtailed by a tight monetary policy, reducing the
operating costs is the only way to stay alive.
	   Maybe it is better for workers to accept salary cuts than to be
unemployed. They may be initially attracted to the compensation
package.
	   But unless they have been working long enough and their salaries
are fairly high, the compensation money may not last very long.
	   Of course, from the management's point of view, it is easier to
retrench workers even though the company has to set aside a hefty
sum to compensate the workers.
	   The Minister may want to help change the mindset of workers and
employers so that we can put to work the productivity-based reward
system.
	   NOBODY in his or her right frame of mind will dispute Dr Chandra
Muzaffar's argument in favour of professionalism and business
ethics in his letter published by the New Straits Times on
Thursday.
	   But in order to achieve a balance between idealism and
practicality, a measure of pragmatism is needed.
	   Since Chandra cited Bank Negara as an example of an institution
in the public realm that cherishes its professional integrity right
through the present situation and one which, in his view, has shown
that it is capable of sound judgment and competent management of
the nation's finances, it may be useful for us to ask the following
questions: What good is professionalism of Bank Negara and the
banking industry if the economy shrinks by the day, companies edge
nearer to bankruptcy and more workers lose jobs?; and What sort of
professionalism is Chandra talking about when bank managers and
officers who have not spent a day managing businesses or risk a
single sen of their own money doing business can dictate terms to
time-tested entrepreneurs and managers?
	   Perhaps Chandra should have suggested that people working for
Bank Negara and other regulatory authorities should be sent for
training with the private sector so that they understand the
workings of business.
	   Yes, there are pseudo-entrepreneurs and managers who are more
concerned with the engine capacity of their cars and the size of
their corporate suites.
	   But in the current tight monetary regime, which hopefully will
end soon following the setting up of the Asset Management Company
to take over the non-performing loans of the banking sector, even
the best and most prudent entrepreneurs and managers are badly
affected.
	   Their credit lines are being squeezed by high interest rates,
single customer limit and shorter NPL period. They are being
treated no better than the wheeler-dealers who had dumped billions
of ringgit of bad debts on the banks.
	   And what professionalism of the banking system can we talk about
when bank managers dispensed billions of ringgit in poorly-secured
loans to shady companies and characters during good times?
	   And what good is a professionally-run banking system if very few
of its customers are left standing?
	   We are all for professionalism, idealism and non-interference by
the Government. But survival of the economy cannot be less
important than the ego and independence of bank managers.
	   FINALLY, I wonder why after more than three decades, Singapore
is still treating the States of Sarawak and Sabah differently from
Peninsular Malaysia.
	   Take, for instance, the case of the republic's Central Provident
Fund.
	   While it allows Malaysians from Sarawak and Sabah to withdraw
their savings immediately upon permanently leaving the republic,
Malaysians from other States have to wait until they are at least
50 years old.
	   For Malaysians from the peninsula, they are allowed to withdraw
their savings in full only upon attaining 55 years of age and after
leaving the republic permanently.
	   One can also withdraw the savings at the age of 50 if one has
not worked in Singapore for two years before making the
application.
	   It is understandable for Singapore to practise this policy in
the early days of its separation from Malaysia in 1965. But for it
to retain the policy after three decades, especially in the current
unfavourable economic conditions, brings its motive into question.
	   Surely Singapore cannot deny that its economy depends more on
workers from Peninsular Malaysia than those from Sabah and Sarawak.
To disallow them from withdrawing their savings upon leaving their
Singapore jobs and returning to Malaysia cannot be fair. This rule
appears to apply only to workers from Peninsular Malaysia.
	   While the point that the changes in the CPF withdrawal
conditions were discussed within the context of wider co-operation
between the two countries by their respective Prime Ministers is
noted, Singapore does not have to wait for an agreement to be
reached on the entire package of co- operation to relax the rules.
	   As for us in Malaysia, serious thought should be given to making
it compulsory for foreign workers to contribute to the Employees'
Provident Fund or other similar funds not only for their future
welfare but also to increase domestic savings.
	   This is only fair because they enjoy many of the public
amenities and services funded by EPF loans.
	   
</TEXT>
