<SLUG> LAD-PROPOSAL-DRAWS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAD proposal draws deputy minister opposition, NATION
</HEADLINE>
LAD proposal draws deputy minister opposition, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Local Administration Department's move to allow kamnan and
village heads to have ex-officio rights to sit on the board of the
Tambon Administrative Organisation met with resistance Monday from
Deputy Interior Minister Chamni Sakdiseth.
	   LAD Director-General Pramual Rujanaseri admitted that the
department accepted the proposal from the Kamnan and Village heads
Association of Thailand to amend the TAO Act in a bid to maintain
the local leaders' automatic right to sit on the TAO's board.
	   Pramual said the department has submitted the proposal to
Interior Minister Sanan Kachornprasart.
	   Chamni insisted that the LAD's intention to allow local leaders
to wear two hats at the same time would be unconstitutional.
	   ''Although the LAD viewed that the attempt to amend the LAD act
is not unconstitutional, I have a totally different opinion,'' he
said.
	   He said the Local Administration Act stipulated that local
leaders have the responsibility to keep peace, not to manage the
local administration. The new constitution wants members of LAD to
be directly elected from the people.
	   Since the new constitution was being drafted, the local leaders
vowed to fight to maintain their right and threatened mass
demonstration against the move by the draftsmen to deprive their
automatic right to sit on the TAOs' board.
	   Pramual said the department agreed with the local leader'
proposal because it believed allowing them on the board of the TAOs
would improve its operation.
	   ''I am not taking sides but I am concerned about possible
conflicts (between elected TAO board members and kamnan and village
heads). The two need to work closely. If they do not co-operate,
the attempt to reform politics and decentralisation would fail,''
he said.
	   The new constitution gives a 10-year grace period before kamnan
and village heads are required to resign from their posts if they
want to run in the election for the TAO board.
	   
</TEXT>
