<SLUG> ENERGETIC-ZAHID-MAKING sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Energetic Zahid making impact as Youth head, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Energetic Zahid making impact as Youth head, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE latest issue of Pemuda, a glossy newsletter circulated among
members of Umno Youth, has a picture of a pensive-looking Tun Daim
Zainuddin.
	   Daim is part of the cover story on the Youth wing's economic
convention held late last year where the former Finance Minister
and now Economic Advisor to the Government spoke frankly on the
economy.
	   The event was just one of a host of activities that have been
organised by Umno Youth under Datuk Ahmad Zahid Hamidi.
	   In fact, even the most casual perusal of the current and
previous issues of Pemuda is enough to convince most people that
Zahid - he answers to his second name - has been anything but idle
since beating three others to the post in party elections two years
ago.
	   An indication of the breadth of activities: Zahid saying mahgrib
prayers in Jelebu with members of Negri Sembilan Umno; Zahid at a
football match organised by the Larut Youth division; Zahid and his
Youth exco calling on the Pahang Menteri Besar; Zahid leading a
clenched-fist demonstration outside the US Embassy; Zahid and his
boys breaking fast with the Perak Menteri Besar; Zahid meeting the
X Generation of Felda Lembah Klau near Raub, and so on.
	   Even those connected to his previous contenders concede to the
energy that Zahid has demonstrated thus far.
	   Says Md Alwi Che Ahmad, political secretary to Rural Development
Minister Datuk Annuar Musa: ``There have been hundreds of courses
and activities ... more than under any other Pemuda leader.''
	   ``Datuk Zahid is very, very hard-working,'' declares the very,
very loyal Youth executive secretary Saifuddin Nasution.
	   Take the past week. Zahid had slotted in back-to-back meetings
with academicians, special interest groups, NGOs, media
practitioners and State Umno Youth representatives to gather
feedback and material for his policy speech at the coming Umno
Youth Assembly.
	   The chubby and good-natured Youth head is said to have picked up
the consultative method from none other than his mentor, Datuk Seri
Anwar Ibrahim.
	   Another habit Zahid adopted to great effect - this one was
carried over from his corporate sector days - is delegating work.
	   One of the first things he did on assuming the Youth leadership
was to form councils headed by exco members to deal with virtually
every aspect of Malaysian life.
	   There are 23 such councils and they play a sort of ``shadow
Cabinet''
	   role.
	   ``These councils, they are there to monitor the Malay interest
in government policies and issues. It's all part of our struggle
for the Malay agenda,'' says Saifuddin.
	   Indeed, it is the monitoring efforts of these councils that has
enabled Umno Youth to emerge as one of the most on-the-ball and
vocal bodies around. There are very few issues and policies which
Umno Youth does not have an opinion on.
	   These opinions naturally carry a Malay flavour and, more
importantly, carry clout in a way that few other organisations -
even if they spout the same views - do.
	   For instance, says Dr Abdul Rahim Ghouse, who heads the wing's
economic council, Umno Youth took exception to the proposal by the
National Economic Action Council to open up certain key industries
currently held by Bumiputeras to non-Bumiputeras.
	   ``Our stand is: offer them to Malays who can afford to take them
up.
	   Then, if there are no takers, open them to non-Bumiputera
Malaysians.''
	   Incidentally, the most active councils have been the ones on
economic, consumer, religious, education and social issues.
	   ``We have made substantive contributions on very real issues,
issues close to the hearts and pockets of the rakyat, even to the
point of influencing some government policies,'' says Abdul Rahim.
	   A great deal of emphasis has also been placed on training and
Zahid often tells his rank and file that to be a good leader, one
must be humble enough to allow oneself to be trained.
	   ``To some extent, Zahid has turned Pemuda around,'' says Johor
Baru MP Khaled Nordin who heads the education council.
	   ZAHID took over a Youth wing whose public image had been badly
battered by the problems associated with his predecessor Tan Sri
Rahim Thamby Chik.
	   Now, two years later, loyalists like Saifuddin and Abdul Rahim
insist that the wing's image is ``pro-rakyat'' and, more
importantly, plays an assertive role in the ``Malay struggle''.
	   ``Datuk Zahid sees Pemuda as the link between the grass roots
and government. We have been critical ... we declared a jihad
against corruption,'' says Abdul Rahim.
	   The movement also came out strongly on the Agriculture
Ministry's role in food production.
	   ``But, basically, we support the Government,'' Abdul Rahim adds.
	   They admit that not being appointed to any government posts has
been a bit of a disappointment for Zahid (deputy Youth head Datuk
Hishammuddin Hussein is Deputy Primary Industries Minister).
	   ``He feels it a little bit ... he's only human. But, after two
years, he's accepted the fact. Besides, there are many things he
can do because he does not have a government post and it is akward
only at formal functions where a Deputy Minister takes precedence
over a political head,''
	   says Saifuddin.
	   Then there is the difficult question of idealism, something
considerably lacking among the younger generation, including Umno
Youth.
	   This is something easier talked about than done.
	   ``It's something which Zahid should seriously look into,'' says
Kelantan Youth's Md Alwi, a close friend of the Youth leader.
	   ``There is still a gap between the leaders and the grass roots,
especially the rural grass roots. You have leaders zooming around
in Mercedes Benz, wearing Versace belts, Rolex watches and
expensive silk shirts ... worlds apart from the mass of ordinary
Malay youth,'' says Md Alwi.
	   And even while Zahid is seen as having set the Youth wing back
on- course, he himself is occasionally perceived as being slightly
off-course.
	   ``It's the way he says things ... sometimes unnecessary,'' says
a Youth politician from Penang.
	   Some think that Zahid's somewhat impetuous speaking style is a
hang-up from his years as Youth information chief.
	   The most recent incident involved his comments of a plot to
overthrow Selangor Menteri Besar Datuk Abu Hassan Omar. The Umno
fraternity, especially that of Selangor, felt he had spoken out of
turn.
	   Then there was his infamous fiasco over the Lee Kuan Yew
remarks.
	   Many think he should do some homework, even research, before
speaking up. That, as Youth leader, he is among the seven most
important figures in the party and, as such, should be more
thoughtful in his public statements.
	   ``These are things you learn by experience ... thinking before
you speak.
	   But, it won't be held against him,'' says Johor's Khaled.
	   Zahid was also recently embarrassed by the reaction to his
exco's proposal that the two top Youth posts go uncontested next
year although some say the pressure discouraging such a proposal
came from a highly- placed figure within the party.
	   Whatever it was, it did not show up well on him, particularly,
given that he had advocated contests in the Youth wing during the
divisional elections.
	   But, Saifuddin says that the exco proposal, though now aborted,
reflected Zahid's standing in the party.
	   Perhaps one of the most positive impacts of the short-lived
proposal is that it has finally ironed out the last creases in the
relationship between Zahid and his No 2.
	   And according to Saifuddin: ``Hisham(muddin) told me: not even
(President) Clinton will be able to make me do it (challenge
Zahid).''
	   ``They may be on their own when it comes to politics, but
everything is very transparent between them,'' says a Johor
politician.
	   Hishammuddin, on his part, goes out of the way to keep Zahid
informed on his movements and programmes.
	   Since taking over, Zahid has held meetings with close to
two-thirds of the division Youth leadership in the different
States.
	   At every State that he goes to, he meets up with the Menteri
Besar or Chief Minister for breakfast or dinner before a
closed-door session with the division Youth heads. In States where
the opposition is prominent, a ceramah will be thrown in so that
the ordinary Youth members can be involved.
	   Zahid's handling of the Youth wing may not be a roaring success
yet, but it has certainly been impactful and energetic.
	   In the process, he has restored morale for the movement and,
despite holding no government post, established a firm footing for
himself.
	   His supporters say that if he goes on this way, he is heading
for a second term, whether or not he is challenged.
	   
</TEXT>
