<HEADLINE>
Convenience stores becomethe centre ofcommunities, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Convenience stores becomethe centre ofcommunities, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   APART from being consumer retail outlets, convenience stores in
the future will be community places where people can conduct
various public activities and get information remotely and
electronically, said Phanu Limmanont, the assistant vice president
of Retailink, an IT subsidiary of the Charoen Phokphand
conglomerate.
	   He said convenience stores can take advantage of their
nationwide networks to boost their retail businesses by using
information technology to turn the traditional store into an
electronic outlet, allowing people to use public services such as
paying utility bills or getting access to information about their
local community.
	   He said paying utility bills is the first step for convenience
stores to become electronic outlets. CP's 7-Eleven stores now allow
people to pay water, electricity and telephone bills near their
home.
	   The chain has opened utility service counters in 60 metropolitan
outlets. Phanu said the firm plans to expand this service to 100
outlets this year and eventually to every outlet in the 7-Eleven
network.
	   To provide this new service, 7-Eleven has invested Bt25 million
for computer systems in branches and the central office with links
to each utility's office for electronic bill payments.
	   All transactions are collected and sent electronically to each
utility company for updating at the end of each day. Phanu said
there are now around 90,000 transactions a day from all 7-Eleven
utility counters. It's expected that the figure will reach 150,000
per day soon.
	   He admitted that this new service is a value-added aspect of the
7-Eleven retail business. It helps increase customer traffic in the
stores which also helps increase sales volume in the stores.
	   ''We expect that this new service will help 7-Eleven increase
revenue in the retail business by around 30 per cent,'' he said.
	   He predicted that the average 20-square-metre 7-Eleven store
will eventually be equipped with IT to provide other public
services such as information or Internet access, computing services
or even electronic retail banking services.
	   The integration of IT and the outlet's network will change the
role of convenience stores, making them a public centre for each
community where IT service providers can easily deliver their
services to the public.
	   Phanu said in addition, IT also helps increase working
efficiency at the stores themselves. 7-Eleven plans to invest Bt1
billion to implement new back and front-end computer systems to
improve its internal management next year. The new system will help
manage inventory, control stock on the shelves and deliver sales
results. Executives can know the status of each branch and their
sales volume and use this information for future planning.
	   
</TEXT>
