<BODY>
<SLUG> LEARNING-FROM-MISTAKES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Learning from our mistakes, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Learning from our mistakes, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A RECENT remark that people only perceive the environment as an
issue when it really affects their lives no doubt hits the nail on
the head as regards mankind's attitude towards the state of their
surroundings. It is worrisome that as planet Earth observes yet
another World Environment Day two days ago, it is plagued by loss
of biodiversity, global warming, the ozone hole, land degradation
and pollution of international waters with no immediate solutions
in sight. Recent unexpected weather conditions have painfully
brought home the importance of environmental preservation.
	   While the oceanic phenomenon El Nino is unleashing havoc on the
world's weather, bringing snow in Jordan and Mexico, drought in
Southeast Asia and floods in Somalia, extremely warm temperatures
are being felt around the globe. Scientists said three of the past
eight years have been the warmest in the Northern Hemisphere for at
least 600 years and greenhouse gases are the primary cause. In Asia
of late, temperatures of more than 40 degrees Celsius were recorded
in the Indian subcontinent causing deaths from heatwave. In
Malaysia, the weatherman reported that this year's monthly average
temperatures for January and February were the highest recorded for
the past 30 years. Residents have experienced a maximum sweltering
temperature of as high as 38 degrees in the past couple of months.
	   Mercifully, the temperature has come down a bit.
	   The Malaysian experience in seriously preserving the environment
does not have a long history as the Department of Environment was
created just a little over 20 years ago. Undoubtedly, the setting
up of a ministry to look after this vital area shows the Federal
Government's seriousness in tackling the myriad environmental
problems, which will inevitably mount with the country's rapid
development. Unfortunately, the task turns out to be arduous and
frustrating due largely to the reluctance to change by both
industries and relevant agencies and the fact that the ministry
``has the responsibility but not the authority'', as one leader
aptly puts it.
	   Sadly, it takes a major crisis to jolt all concerned into
realisation that it is imperative that they take effective measures
to take care of the environment before it is too late. Last year's
haze experience was said to have done a world of good for the
ministry's hitherto uphill battle to convince the relevant
authorities that they cannot remain unresponsive to moves for a
better environment. The water crisis in some parts of Peninsular
Malaysia, which is still plaguing the Klang Valley, should make the
people more aware of the importance of protecting natural
resources, said the ministry last week. It hopes the awareness
would remain deeply rooted so that water is not taken for granted.
It should also be ``an eye-opener for us not to pollute our rivers
and destroy our catchment areas which are critical elements in our
water supply''.
	   The question remains: will we ever learn? We better do to save
the country from the disastrous environmental problems as
experienced by some countries. Malaysia's fast pace of development
has already seen degradation and pollution of its land, water
sources, seas and the air.
	   Increasingly, the hand of the ministry has been strengthened
with the introduction of legislation and improved regulations to
deal with wrong- doers as well as policies to safeguard the
environment, particularly its rich flora and fauna. Encouragingly,
the Federal authorities' difficult task in creating greater
environmental awareness has been aided by the active role of the
mass media, particularly the print media.
	   But laws alone are clearly inadequate. The awareness campaign
has to be ongoing and far-reaching, including schools, industries
and the man in the street. There is also a need for a firm guiding
hand at the top. As rightly pointed out at a recent global
environment conference, we need to make environmental conservation
a people's movement.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
