<HEADLINE>
Compaq tomodify its strategies, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Compaq tomodify its strategies, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   JIRAPAN BOONNOONASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE US-based computer manufacturer Compaq has repositioned its
PC desktop lines by redesigning its products to cope with the needs
of each market segment.
	   According to the company's research, customers' behaviour in the
Asia Pacific region is changing, with different customers having
different requirements.
	   Compaq Computer (Thailand)'s acting managing director Tan Kok
Hin said small and medium enterprises today want to take advantage
of changes in technology to make the best purchasing decision at
any given time, while large or international enterprises prefer to
buy products that are consistent with their existing systems.
	   The company last week announced a new product repositioning in
Thailand while launching two new desktop PC models -- the Deskpro
EN and EP -- targeted at large or international enterprises and
small and medium organisations respectively.
	   Both models are based on a Pentium II processor at speeds from
266 MHz to 400 MHz with the capability of easily converting from
desktop to minitower.
	   The price for a new Deskpro EN for large enterprises is up to
Bt50,000 while the EP is up to Bt42,000.
	   Hin said the company plans to phase out the previous Deskpro
2000, 4000 and 6000 models. The Deskpro EP will replace the Deskpro
2000 in the small and medium market and the Deskpro EN replaces the
former Deskpro 4000 and 6000 in the large enterprise market.
	   ''We plan to cancel production of the previous Deskpro 2000 to
6000 models in the near future. We hope that we can fully replace
all previous Deskpro models with the new series in the next two
years,'' he added.
	   For the low-end market, Hin said the company last month launched
the Deskpro 1000. This product positioning remains the same.
	   
</TEXT>
