<SLUG> BC-Kazakstan-New Capital </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kazakstan introduces new capital to the world
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos planned &QL; 
 &UR; By BIRGIT BRAUER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ASTANA, Kazakstan (AP) _ Until now, this remote city in northern
Kazakstan has been best known for its inhospitable climate, vicious
mosquitoes and endlessly flat land.
	   On Tuesday, its newly refurbished streets were decorated with
flags and balloons and were full of families celebrating Astana's
new status as capital of the Central Asian country of 17 million
people.
	   President Nursultan Nazarbayev called Wednesday's formal
dedication of Astana a historic event that would show how far the
former Soviet republic has come since gaining independence in 1991.
	   ``The new center of the country will be new energy for the new
state,'' Nazarbayev said on a national call-in TV show. ``We are
showing the whole world what our capabilities are.''
	   Astana _ previously known as Akmola _ became Kazakstan's capital
in December, replacing Almaty, a city of 1.2 million 1,125
kilometers (700 miles) away. Wednesday is the formal unveiling to
the world, a day scheduled to be full of speech-making,
backslapping and cultural events.
	   The city has undergone a remarkable transformation over the past
two years. New government buildings have been constructed, dull
gray apartment buildings along the main street have been
refurbished and painted bright white, green or orange. Store fronts
have new plate-glass windows and flashy neon signs.
	   ``The service has changed for the better,'' said Galina
Zhernonikova, a 48-year-old hospital administrator who has lived in
Astana for 20 years. ``We now have products we didn't have
before.''
	   For the most part, the transfer of the capital has not been very
popular with the Kazak people. Many grumble that the cost of the
move, which has never been fully made public, is money that could
have been spent on overdue wages and pensions.
	   The reconstruction of government buildings, including the
presidential and government offices, parliament and ministries, has
so far cost dlrs 120 million, Nazarbayev announced this week for
the first time.
	   About dlrs 90 million of that came from a fund for the new
capital to which local and foreign companies have contributed, he
said.
	   In an effort to improve the image of the new capital, it was
renamed last month from Akmola _ which means ``white grave'' in
Kazak _ to Astana, which just means capital.
	   ``I think the name Astana is really plain,'' said 19-year-old
Azamat Akhmetov. ``We should have had a renaming competition to
pick the best one. We were never asked about our opinion.''
	   Astana, a city of 130,000, was selected as the new capital in
1994 because of its central location, and because Almaty is
overcrowded, too close to the Chinese border and prone to
earthquakes.
	   One of the unofficial reasons is that Nazarbayev wants to
counter separatist tendencies in Kazakstan's north, which is
populated mostly by ethnic Russians.
	   (str/ls/mr)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Kazakstan-New Capital; CT:i; 
