<BODY>
<SLUG> SMALLER-HOSPITAL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
All's well at smaller hospitals, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
All's well at smaller hospitals, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ahmad A. TalibASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A SMALL hospital can have a big heart. I came across one last
week in the form of the Tanjung Malim Hospital.
	   Its surroundings provide a comforting atmosphere to patients and
visitors alike, and one can rest quite peacefully within its
premises.
	   The hospital is located along the old Kuala Lumpur-Ipoh trunk
road and is not difficult to spot. After passing Tanjung Malim
town, you proceed north and cross the railway gate heading towards
Proton City.
	   Just before the traffic lights, you will see the hospital on the
right.
	   It is sandwiched between a big Hindu temple on its right and the
famous Tanjung Malim teachers training institute on its left.
	   Even as you enter the hospital grounds, you already feel the
serenity of the place.
	   I imagine that the same serenity is found in small hospitals in
other parts of the country.
	   The hospital has a big courtyard in the centre with a
well-manicured lawn. There are two car parks for visitors and they
are seldom full.
	   Motorbikes and bicycles have different sheds, making the
hospital quite user-friendly.
	   Big city hospitals have parking lots, too, but using them is
usually accompanied by a degree of stress.
	   The gardeners were busy trimming the hedges and they went about
with their work efficiently and quietly. This speaks well for the
hospital's general cleanliness and creates a pleasant feeling all
around.
	   The kitchen staff, too, went about their chores speedily and
just as quietly. It gave me the impression that everyone knew
exactly what they were supposed to do with minimum or no
supervision.
	   I spent two days at the hospital visiting a couple of old folks
warded for different ailments. Ward Number One is for male
patients.
	   Visiting hours appear to be quite flexible, but most visitors
come during lunch and tea time.
	   A small signboard hangs on the iron grille at the entrance of
Ward One, advising visitors to refrain from entering the ward when
the doctor is on his rounds, normally in the morning.
	   In a small hospital, the doctor is the most respected figure.
The doctor usually starts his rounds between 8.30 and 9am.
Accompanied by a nurse, whom the kampung folk keep referring to as
`Missy', the doctor goes from patient to patient.
	   I suppose a general practitioner is the most qualified medical
officer to be stationed at a small hospital.
	   His patients are as varied in their ailments as in their ages.
	   At Ward One, a 60-year-old former teacher had just had the
toenails of his left foot removed and had to be warded for a few
days.
	   Next to him was a teenager whose fever had not come down for a
couple of days.
	   At the other end of the roomy ward, an old ustaz had not eaten
solid food for several weeks.
	   His children were very worried as the old man appeared weak and
frail.
	   He had a stream of callers during visiting hours.
	   Visitors to a small town hospital often end up visiting several
patients during a single visit.
	   A village head commonly referred to as Tok Empat walked into the
ward one day and was surprised to see some of his durian-loving
buddies hospitalised.
	   One of them, an old Chinese man clad only in a thin Pagoda
T-shirt and striped boxer shorts, managed a smile and asked Tok
Empat whether his durian trees were fruiting.
	   The old man said he hoped to get out of hospital soon to tend to
his trees.
	   It is normal for a village head to know many people and his
friends thought that he had come to visit them.
	   The fact was, Tok Empat came to visit only one patient, not
knowing that several other friends were also under prolonged
treatment.
	   The patients I spoke to seemed genuinely interested in the
welfare of their fellow mates.
	   After the doctor had finished his morning rounds, the patients
would move about asking each other how they were progressing.
	   The older patients invariably came up with the question: ``Did
the doctor tell you when you could go home?''
	   The doctor spends about 10 minutes with each patient. Taking the
patients' pulse, feeling their stomachs and asking questions about
their ailments, I could sense a certain rapport between them.
	   In a small town hospital, and for folks who cannot afford the
luxury of five-star hospitals and medical homes, a compassionate
general practitioner makes all the difference.
	   Small town hospitals like Tanjung Malim's handle many accident
cases.
	   Seldom does a week pass without its ambulance being called out
to ferry patients from crash sites.
	   One thing I found about the staff of small hospitals is that
they are dedicated, flexible in the administration of wards and
with an ear for their patients.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
