<HEADLINE>
ETC: FCCT hosts talk on Indonesia post-Suharto, NATION
</HEADLINE>
ETC: FCCT hosts talk on Indonesia post-Suharto, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Foreign Correspondents Club of Thailand (FCCT) is holding a
panel discussion tomorrow at 7 pm on a highly topical issue -- the
future of Indonesia post-Suharto.
	   Although Suharto has stepped down, the dust has yet to settle in
this strife-torn country. His successor may be the only hope at
present, but immediate action must be taken to bring back investor
confidence. This means urgent reforms and tough action against
relatives of Suharto who still control most of the country's
economic sector.
	   The panel members have recently returned from Indonesia and will
be screening scenes of rioting, looting and demonstrations.
	   For more information, call 652 0580-1.
	   Shelling out for scientific research TO mark 100 years of
operation, Shell (Thailand) has set up a special centennial
education fund.
	   Under the Shell fund, 20 grants worth a total of Bt2 million
will be awarded for postgraduate research in 1998. The disciplines
covered by the grants are mathematics, physics, chemistry, biology
and computer sciences.
	   All postgraduate students registered in government-run
universities are eligible for entry. Applications are being
accepted until Aug 31.
	   For more information, contact the Education Division, University
Affairs Ministry at 246 1106-14 ext 770.
	   Making the most of your student days DO you know what carpedium
is? If not, then you should consider attending Kasetsart
University's seminar on ''How to make the most of your time at
university'' this Friday from 8.30 am to noon. The venue is the
Sutham Areekul auditorium, Saranithet 50 building, Bangkhen campus.
	   Advising participants on how to make the most of their time
while studying at university are PM's Office's Minister Abhisit
Vejjajiva; Kasetsart University vice president Adisak Buankiyabhan;
former beauty queen and English instructor at Chulachomklao Cadet
Academy, Areeya Sirisopa; and ITV anchorman Kitti Singhapat.
	   Admission is free.
	   For more information, call 942 8181.
	   The importance of good governance THE Oriental Culture Academy
is holding a discussion on ''Good Governance: Why it's important to
people and society and can it be organised in Thailand?'' this
Saturday from 1.30 pm to 4.30 pm at the OCA's headquarters on
Rongmuang Road, Patahumwan district.
	   Panellists are social thinkers Thirayuth Bunmee, Dr Kittisak
Prokati and Anucha Arbhabhirom.
	   Everyone is welcome. Admission is free.
	   Call 216 2826 for further details.
	   Seamo launches maths olympiad THE Seamo Regional Centre for
Education in Science and Mathematics is launching the first Seamo
mathematics olympiad from Sept 14 to 18 in Penang, Malaysia.
	   The olympiad is an academic competition for gifted mathematics
students living in Seamo member states and neighbouring countries.
The competition is open to students who have not formally enrolled
in a university and who are under 18 years of age.
	   Each country team will consist of four students and one team
leader. The team leader should be a mathematics teacher, be able to
communicate in English and translate the examination problems into
the respective mother tongue of each team. Students are permitted
to work and submit solutions in their own languages.
	   The contest will cover all areas of mathematics in the current
upper secondary school curricula of Seamo member countries.
	   This olympiad aims to encourage, develop and challenge
mathematically gifted secondary students as well as foster
international relations and cooperation between students and
teachers from the participating countries. The event will also
create an avenue for secondary school students to apply mathematics
in a challenging and meaningful way, and provide an opportunity for
the exchange of information on school practices throughout the
Southeast Asian region.
	   Certificates and medals will be awarded to the winner and first
and second runners-up. Other contestants will receive certificates
of participation.
	   Seamo will be responsible for room, board and travel expenses
(return flight from capital city or origin to Penang plus
on-the-ground costs) of each country's team leader and two of the
four participating students. For more information and registration
details, call Khun Duriya at the external relations division,
Ministry of Education at 628 5648 or the Seamo secretariat at 391
0144.
	   The closing date for the receipt of completed applications is
June 15.
	   
</TEXT>
