<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Queens, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Defending champion Philippoussis upset in first round
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs; recasts, updates with other results &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ With his power game and huge serve, Mark
Philippoussis was once considered a potential Wimbledon champion.
Righ now, he's playing so poorly he might not even go to Wimbledon.
	   ``This year's been pathetic for me and I just haven't been there
at all,'' the Australian said Tuesday after losing in the first
round of the Queen's Club tournament to Spain's Jordi Burillo 7-6
(11-9), 7-5.
	   Philippoussis, the defending champion and ninth seed in the
prestigious Wimbledon warmup event, has failed to advance beyond
the opening round in five of his 12 tournaments this year.
	   ``I'm actually deciding whether to play Wimbledon,'' he said.
``At the moment I'm not sure. I'm not sure what's going to happen.
I'll go to Florida and talk with my father about it.
	   ``On the court nothing's there for me. I haven't got the desire,
and I can't afford to go out there and give away matches like that.
It's better not going on the court at all.''
	   In another upset, 11th seeded Todd Martin, who beat Pete Sampras
in the 1994 Queen's Club final, lost 6-4, 6-2 to Swiss qualifier
Ivo Heuberger.
	   Australia's Jason Stoltenberg, seeded No. 16, was the only other
seed to fall, losing to Belgian qualifier Laurence Tieleman 3-6,
7-6 (7-5), 6-2.
	   Goran Ivanisevic, the 10th seed and runner-up in 1997, overcame
American David Wheaton 6-1, 7-6 (10-8). Other seeded players to
advance were No. 12 Todd Woodbridge, No. 13 Brett Steven, No. 14
Byron Black and No. 15 Mark Woodforde.
	   American qualifier Doug Flach, ranked 222, surprised the Czech
Republic's Daniel Vacek 4-6, 6-1, 6-3.
	   Philippoussis double-faulted on set point to hand Burillo the
tiebreaker. In the second set, neither player earned a break point
until Burillo broke serve for the match when Philippoussis sent a
wild forehand long.
	   ``I'm just very confused at the moment,'' Philippoussis said.
``I've tried to think about what's wrong, but I don't now what it
is. It's like I'm not hungry any more and it's not a good feeling
at all.''
	   (str/sw)	   
</TEXT>
