<SLUG> BE-ENVIRONMENTALLY-SOUND sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`Be environmentally-sound to be competitive', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`Be environmentally-sound to be competitive', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Hamidah AtanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MALACCA, Sat. - Companies must be environmentally conscious in
their day- to-day operations to stay competitive in today's
marketplace.
	   Sirim Berhad president and chief executive Dr Mohd Ariffin Aton
said the companies must strive to implement the MS ISO 14001
standard, an internationally accepted environmental management
standard.
	   With the certification, the public can be assured of a
well-documented system for identifying, monitoring and managing
environmental impact of their operations and products.
	   More importantly, it indicates commitment to continual
improvement in environmental performance and meeting regulatory
requirements, he said.
	   Speaking at the presentation of the standard to Matsushita
Refrigeration Industries (M) Sdn Bhd today, he however cautioned
that certified organisations are just at the beginning of hard
work.
	   ``They must maintain their systems and strive for continuous
improvement.
	   We will withdraw the certification if they failed to adhere to
the requirements.''
	   Also present was Matsushita Refrigeration Industries managing
director Hiroshi Kawai.
	   Mohd Ariffin added that adherence to the standard would enable
organisations to be more efficient in their business operations and
more environmentally responsible.
	   Mohd Ariffin said 3,458 companies worldwide, in particular the
manufacturing sector, had been certified.
	   ``It is estimated that more than 40 companies in Malaysia have
been certified.
	   ``They are from the oil palm industry, paper products, optical
equipment and plastics industry. Another 50 companies are
undergoing the certification process,'' he added.
	   Matsushita Refrigeration Industries is the third in Malacca to
be accorded the certification.
	   Its personnel and general administration manager Kamal Haslin
Karim said RM2 million was spent on upgrading its waste disposal
treatment facility and landscaping this year.
	   He said Sirim officials would inspect the company's premises
every six months to ensure compliance.
	   The company, which produces refrigeration compressors and
accessories for the export market, has also been awarded the
Canadian environmental standard accreditation.
	   
</TEXT>
