<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Czar's Burial </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian Orthodox patriarch will not participate in czar's burial
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. RECASTS, UPGRADES attribution, UPDATES with details of
funeral, synod decision. &QL; 
 &UR; By MAURA REYNOLDS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The Russian Orthodox Church distanced itself
Tuesday from the lavish state funeral planned for the country's
last czar, deciding that the patriarch will not preside over next
month's ceremony.
	   The church has expressed lingering doubts over the identity of
nine sets of bones recovered in 1991, despite a six-year
investigation and forensic tests in Russia, Britain and the United
States.
	   In light of the doubts, the Holy Synod ruled Tuesday that no
member of the church hierarchy could take part in the solemn burial
service, scheduled for July 17 in St. Petersburg.
	   However, the Synod said in a statement that in accordance with
the church's obligation to officiate over funerals whenever
requested, priests from the St. Petersburg diocese can take part.
	   In an apparent concession to the government, the Synod also said
that on the day of the funeral, Orthodox churches throughout Russia
will hold requiem Masses to ``pray for the repose of the souls'' of
Nicholas II, his family and servants who were executed by a
Bolshevik firing squad in 1918.
	   The announcement brings to an end months of deliberations in
which the government pressured the church to officiate over a
ceremony seen as an act of national repentance for the excesses of
the Russian Revolution.
	   The decision also suggests that President Boris Yeltsin will not
attend, since Russian media have said the president would only take
part alongside the patriarch.
	   The nine skeletons were recovered from a roadside pit in 1991
outside the Ural Mountains city of Yekaterinburg, where the victims
were gunned down by Bolsheviks. Repeated DNA testing has confirmed
their identities as Nicholas, his wife, three of their children
children and four servants.
	   Bodies of two other children have never been found. Those who
disposed of the corpses said they burned two bodies and scattered
the ashes in the woods, but many Orthodox believers distrust any
accounts by Soviet officials.
	   Another cause for hesitation is that the church has started
proceedings that could lead to the canonization of the royal
family. Should they be declared saints, their bones would be
revered as holy relics.
	   The funeral service will be held in the Peter and Paul
Cathedral, the traditional burial site of the Romanovs, who ruled
Russia for 300 years. Hundreds of foreign representatives have been
invited to attend.
	   The director of the Peter and Paul Fortress, where the church is
located, said Tuesday that the government has yet to provide the
7.5 million rubles (more than dlrs 1 million) for the ceremony.
	   Director Boris Arakcheyev said the nine coffins will be placed
in the vault in two rows, with the family members above their
servants.
	   He said the ceremony will be shown live on a large TV screen in
a garden outside, since the church cannot accommodate all the
people invited to attend.
	   (mr/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
