<BODY>
<SLUG> LOOKING-TOWARDS-FUTURE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Looking Towards Future Challenges, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Looking Towards Future Challenges, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   MONGKOL SAHACHUEASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Training students to be competitive in the ever-changing world
is a vital step, especially for a country like Thailand. To achieve
this end, Thammasat University established College of Innovative
Education last year to cope up with the challenge. Mongkol Sahachue
talks the institute's head Naris Chaiyasoot about their vision of
the future.
	   UNLIKE many of his colleagues in academia, Naris Chaiyasoot is
not content to restrict himself to writing dry, theoretical papers
advocating reform; he believes that actions speaks louder than
words. While dean of the Faculty of Economics at Thammasat
University between 1994 and 1996, he won much praise for his skills
as an administrator and launched a number of successful projects
aimed at improving the quality of lectures offered by teaching
staff there and helping students learn more effectively.
	   Today he is the director of the College of Innovative Education
(CIE), established in Pattaya last year by Thammasat University to
prepare the Thai workforce to compete in the high-tech job market
of the next millennium. The CIE currently offers post-graduate
degree courses and training programmes geared towards the needs of
the telecommunications, high-technology and hospitality industries
as well as research and training programmes in food science and
technology.
	   ''International competitiveness requires us to have a more
highly skilled labour force trained in the use of technology and in
other advanced fields,'' says Naris. ''We need to develop new
concepts in educational philosophy as well as in administration and
management.'' Although his background is in economics (he has a PhD
in economics, with specialisation in money and banking, from the
University of Hawaii) and he currently chairs the National Research
Council on Economics (as well as being vice-president of the
Thammasat Economics Association), Naris is enthusiastic about his
work at CIE believing that education is the key to ensuring a
bright future for the Kingdom.
	   - Why did you choose to get involved in the field of education?
There are many ways that people can serve their country.
Politicians play a more visible role but in Thailand a politician
has a very short life expectancy with the constant changes of
government and political affiliation. It's a cruel life with
tremendous pressures and uncertainties, and it kills many good
people before their time. As an educator there is much more
stability; we have a much longer time to develop sustainable and
innovative programmes that will benefit society for many years to
come.
	   - What do you feel is your role as a Thai academic? The primary
objective of an academician should be to provide high-quality
education and training to strengthen our global competitiveness and
instil traditions of democracy, morality, and ethics in the younger
generation.
	   In addition, a university should be concerned about the real
world. Academicians should use their specialised training and
experience to give direction to society. This is a tremendous
responsibility, requiring wisdom and judgement.
	   It is impossible to be an expert in every field, so I try to be
very careful to limit my comments to areas where I have some
training and experience. I strongly believe that expressing
unfounded opinions and giving wrong advice is a sin.
	   - What do you think of the university system in Thailand at
present? Although there are some relatively weak areas such as
English-language proficiency, postgraduate study and research in
certain fields, the university system in Thailand is not that bad;
but nothing to be cheerful about either.
	   Significant progress has been made in recent years concerning
the quality of instruction and the academic training of lecturers.
Additional effort is needed to bring physical facilities -- such as
laboratories, libraries, classrooms, and computer centres -- up to
international standards and to increase access to university
education.
	   Progress has been made, but there is still a lot of room for
improvement.
	   Representatives from overseas universities report that Thai
students perform very well academically. The greatest weakness is
English-language competence. We need to put greater emphasis on
secondary-school English-language programmes and establish more
university-level international programmes and courses offering
English as the language of instruction. With some effort Thailand
could become a centre for regional education in the near future.
	   Thai universities should serve as leaders in society, providing
advice and moral leadership, in addition to their primary role in
education and research. Universities must reach out to society and
cooperate in promoting democracy and social justice. The goals and
values of the university should be consistent with those of the
nation and Thai society.
	   - You're right in both theory and principle. But many people
feel that universities in Thailand have never carried out that
task. Do you agree? I agree that Thai universities have done very
little to serve Thai society. I think that in a crisis like this,
people want to see what direction the academics think is the best
for our society. We academicians should give this matter serious
thought. We have to realise that thinking is our job. We should
listen to people and synthesize ideas; share our ideas with others
and help create better things for society.
	   I feel that many academics in government-run universities today
are narrow- minded. They think they are the best. They train
students in the same way that they were trained many years before.
They have never listened to or cared about what contemporary
society wants. They never watch what the private universities are
doing. If it were possible I'd really like to organise projects
that would bring lecturers and academics from private and
government-run universities together to discuss what we should and
can do to serve our society.
	   - What can CIE do to help solve Thailand's problems? The CIE is
a semi-private institution, a kind of national project, where
educational institutions join with the private sector and
government in providing programmes and services critical for
national development. By working directly with business and
industry, CIE can develop innovative training courses that will
prepare the Thai workforce to compete on an international level and
get jobs in high-technology industries.
	   - What did you accomplish in your first year as director of CIE?
The first year was primarily a year of planning and programme
design. To provide quality, innovative courses it is important to
carefully evaluate the market and create educational programmes
that will meet the current and future human resource needs of the
nation.
	   The CIE and Thammasat appreciate the seriousness of the current
economic situation and have developed a master plan and related
projects to improve infrastructure and increase the country's
competitiveness; not only to meet immediate needs, but also for
long-term development. The plan is divided into two areas.
	   First, production organisation. To reduce weaknesses in the
research-and-development field and in the transfer of technology,
CIE intends to serve as a technology service provider.
	   Secondly, business and industry. To improve the supply and
quality of personnel, CIE will work as a training service centre to
develop human resource expertise both in technology and in the
management of technology. CIE intends to target the immediate
critical needs of society by providing courses such as technology
management, food science, and hospitality management.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
