<SLUG> BC-NATO-Kosovo,0554 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Events in Kosovo unfolding faster than NATO can plan
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JEFFREY ULBRICH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ The violence in separatist Kosovo
province has prompted NATO military planners into considering
``more challenging options, which could include intervention,'' a
senior NATO official said Tuesday.
	   Only a few days ago, the generals were focusing on military
exercises and dispatching troops to help neighboring Albania and
Macedonia deal with refugees and patrol borders.
	   In recent days, entire villages in the southern Serbian province
have been flattened and thousands of people driven from their
homes, making the need for action more urgent if the crisis is not
to erupt into a wider Balkan war.
	   More than 250 people have died in Kosovo since Mar. 1 in
escalating clashes between government forces and the Kosovo
Liberation Army, armed wing of the Albanian independence movement.
	   Ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of the province's
population, are demanding independence from Serbia, the larger of
the two republics remaining in Yugoslavia.
	   The United States and its allies support autonomy for Kosovo but
oppose demands for independence.
	   Earlier, NATO foreign ministers agreed to enhance military
exercises in Albania and Macedonia as a way of increasing the
military presence there. A NATO assessment team is still the region
looking at future options.
	   However, the senior NATO official, speaking anonymously said
that ``with the events of the last week, shoring up the periphery
seems of secondary value.''
	   NATO defense ministers meet in Brussels Thursday and Friday for
discussions certain to be dominated by Kosovo. It is expected they
will order the military to start looking at direct intervention in
Kosovo.
	   The United States and Britain plan to ask the U.N. Security
Council, possibly next week, to approve the use of force against
the Serbs to halt attacks on ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
	   U.S. sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
Americans were also willing to make a direct appeal to Russian
President Boris Yeltsin if they encounter resistence from the
Russian foreign ministry.
	   The Russians oppose NATO troops in the area but have indicated
that they might support a more robust U.N. role. That would require
approval by the 15-member Security Council, where Russia has a
permanent seat and veto power.
	   Exactly what form such action might take is unclear. Some have
suggested air strikes against Serbian forces, or a no-fly zone. But
military moves that may deter the Serbs may not necessary work
against the insurgents.
	   NATO officials say there are other legal bases for conducting
such an operation, but are vague about exactly what they are.
	   ``If we can't get that resolution, we'll have to find another
legal basis to act, if action is necessary,'' said the senior
official.
	   The 15-nation European Union and the United States have slapped
a ban on all investments in Serbia and frozen Yugoslav assets
abroad, though Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic has not
appeared particularly susceptible to sanctions in the past.
	   ``We have learned the Serbs don't respond to pressure unless it
is military pressure,'' said the senior official. 	   
</TEXT>
