<HEADLINE>
Remain united, people advised, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Remain united, people advised, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ALOR STAR, Sat. - The people must continue to be united and
support the Government to enable it to overcome the economic
downturn, former Deputy Prime Minister Tun Ghafar Baba said today.
	   He said the people must not give up helping the Government to
weather the economic problems.
	   ``My fear is that the people might lose their sense of direction
and allow these economic problems to spread and become a political
problem,''
	   he said when opening the State economic development seminar
organised by the State Umno at Bangunan Tunku.
	   Ghafar said the present situation was vulnerable and could
easily lead to chaos.
	   He said before independence, the Malays had only a two per cent
share of the economy. ``The New Economic Policy changed the fate of
the Malays and increased their holding to 17 per cent.
	   ``That holding has now decreased by between two and five per
cent and we may need another 20 years to bring it back to 17 per
cent,'' he added.
	   Ghafar said he felt obliged to contribute towards the revival of
the economy and had offered his services to the Prime Minister to
explain the economic situation to the people, especially the
low-income group.
	   
