<BODY>
<SLUG> FUNDS-CUT-FOR-Y2K sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Funds cut for Y2K, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Funds cut for Y2K, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   SOMPIT POTIPATTANAKORNASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Metropolitan Electricity Authority (MEA) has reduced the
budget for its Y2K Phasell Project from Bt40 million to Bt30
million, according to its deputy governor (business), Kasem
Chaihongsa.
	   The budget will be spent on a new mainframe and upgrading
equipment at its centre on Chidlom Road. In the first phase the
company made an assessment of its inventory and recommended changes
to 40 per cent of its computer tasks including billing and
accounting. Response to the Y2K scare will start in July and the
entire project is expected to be completed in February 1999.
	   ''We guarantee that in January 2000 Bangkok residents will be
able to use electricity as usual, and pay the right bill. The
project will cover all our electronic devices and facilities
including elevators,'' he said.
	   Apart from data tasks, the Y2K problem will not affect other
tasks involved in electricity distribution. Some electricity
sub-stations are controlled manually. The others which are
controlled by computer, called ''Unman Substations'', are said to
be Y2K compliant.
	   He added that the authority had plans to convert more than 100
traditional sub-stations to Unman Substations. However, the idea
has been dropped due to budget cuts.
	   ''This project would have been completed during the Eighth
National Economic and Social Development Plan. However we still
hope to have 30 to 40 sub-stations converted this year,'' he said.
	   Even though the cost of a new substation is high at Bt250
million per station, it will improve the electricity distribution
system.
	   ''If electricity distribution is controlled by computer, there
is less chance of disruption during rain,'' he said.
	   MEA will also implement the Y2K Phasell Project at its internal
hospital. ''Inventory and patients' histories are affected by Y2K
problems, but other medical services will not be affected,'' he
said.
	   MEA's consultant for this project, Pete Galloway, is working
closely with MEA staff and is confident that the project will be on
time.
	   He said several Thai companies don't consider the Y2K scare as a
terrible prospect. However, as a consultant, he hopes that next
year many will be in a panic about the threat of the bug and will
be happy to pay for consulting services.
	   
</TEXT>
