<SLUG> BC-Rwanda-Privatization </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rwanda hopes to raise dlrs 5.3 million for 98 budget through
</HEADLINE>
privatization &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) _ Rwanda hopes to raise 1,600,000,000 francs
(dlrs 5,333,000) for its 1998 budget through divesting, liquidating
or hiring out of state-owned enterprises under a three-year
privatization program, its director said Tuesday.
	   ``From 1998 to 2001, the government expects to have privatized
about 44 public enterprises, sold its shares in six companies and
to have liquidated about five enterprises,'' Director of
Privatization Vianney Shumbusho told the Rwanda News Agency.
	   Among the 44 parastatals to be sold are 25 agrobusinesses,
including nine tea factories and estates and three coffee factories
and estates _ the principal source of Rwandan exports.
	   Through a three-year enhanced structural adjustment facility,
Rwanda is committed to privatizing all state-owned enterprises to
reduce government expenditure and increase revenue through taxation
and sales of parastatals.
	   On May 29, the government earned about 1,003,000,000 francs
(dlrs 3 million) after the cabinet endorsed the sale of two hotels
and two processing factories.
	   (rna/sl)	   
</TEXT>
