<HEADLINE>
Chicken and pasta, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Chicken and pasta, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SECRET Recipe also serves lunch and dinner. The menu may be
limited but there's a good variety. Just a year ago, when I was
there the first time, there was only sandwiches and pasta. Even so,
I was suitably impressed with their lasagne (RM7.50) and spaghetti
(RM8.50) which was full of meaty sauce with a choice of chicken or
beef). In fact, they have opened two more outlets - at Jaya
Shopping Centre and Amcorp Mall in Petaling Jaya.
	   At Secret Recipe, sandwiches are not made with commercial
loaves. Instead, Nicholas himself bakes saucer-sized buns which can
be filled with corn beef or chicken and egg. For RM5.50, you get a
fresh salad to go with it.
	   The extended menu sounds interesting. Priced at RM8.50, all the
main courses are chicken. ``We only use whole chicken legs which
are deboned and skinned - perfect for today's healthy lifestyle,''
says Nicholas.
	   There's crispy barbecued chicken, grilled chicken kebab, fried
chicken wings, Mexican chicken and their best-seller, black pepper
chicken - done just the way I like it - with a fiery pungent sauce
dark from the specks of black pepper.
	   The sauce for Mexican chicken is also a hot, spicy tomato-based
number with a sliced onions, buttom mushrooms and lethal red
chillies. These are served with a cup of aromatic butter rice and
salad with thousand island dressing.
	   
</TEXT>
