<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Gerry Weber Open </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Despite huge crowd, Becker loses at Gerry Weber Open
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HALLE, Germany (AP) _ Boris Becker, trying to decide if his game
is up to Wimbledon, Tuesday fought off five match points but lost
to Hendrik Dreekmann in three erratic sets at the Gerry Weber Open.
	   Becker, showing his rustiness, was beaten by his fellow German,
the world no. 101, 6-3, 5-7, 7-6 (11-9) in a first round match at
the dlrs 875,000 Wimbledon grass court tuneup.
	   It was just the sixth tournament this year for Becker, who is
easing into retirement.
	   Many Germans believed it was a last chance to see their star
play, causing a morning run on tickets. Hundreds were turned away
from the 11,400-seat center court.
	   Becker gave away the match with a double fault after two hours
and 18 minutes and was far from the form that made him a former
world No. 1 and three-time Wimbledon champion.
	   But the 30-year-old offered his roaring fans plenty of
entertainment, blowing a 4-0 lead in the final set tie break, then
warding off one match point after another.
	   Becker, now ranked 58th, displayed little of the coolness under
pressure that marked his prime, despite warding off two double
faults with hard serves.
	   He double faulted to set up one match point and babied a sure
overhead winner that cost him a second. Dreekmann also let him
escape several times with easy errors.
	   For Dreekman, once ranked 39th, the win was revenge for being
publicly dismissed by Becker as talented, but unmotivated.
	   ``Becker has said Wimbledon is his bedroom, but this was mine,''
said Dreekman.
	   Becker said earlier he will announce Friday whether he will play
Wimbledon this year, adding it was dependent on how well he fared
at the event.
	   Although five top 10 players are entered in the Wimbledon
tuneup, the day was dominated by the local German players.
	   Australia's Richard Fromberg upset no. 7 seed Nicolas Kiefer,
Germany, 2-6, 6-4, 6-4, while Tommy Haas beat Belgium's Filip
Dewulf, 6-3, 6-4.
	   The presence of Becker, perhaps the most idolized German, has so
overwhelmed the event that defending champion Yevgeny Kafelnikov
was surprised when he was questioned by a reporter.
	   The 1996 French Open champion and world No. 7 had barely
survived a three-set battle Monday with the Ukraine's Andrei
Medvedev.
	   ``Great, someone noticed I'm still in the tournament,''
Kafelnikov said. ``I thought nobody was aware of it.''
	   French Open finalist Carlos Moya and Alex Corretja are scheduled
to play later Tuesday.
	    &UR; (rk) 	   
</TEXT>
