<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-East Timor-Ramos-Horta,0437 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nobel laureate derides Indonesia's offer on East Timor
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Indonesia-East Timor, BC-Indonesia-East Timor Reaction &QL; 
 &UR; By BRUCE STANLEY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Dismissing the proposal as ``nothing new,'' a
Nobel peace laureate on Tuesday rejected Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie's offer of special status for the disputed territory of
East Timor.
	   ``They are rehashing an old position, which requires first that
the United Nations recognize the illegal annexation of East Timor
by Indonesia,'' said Jose Ramos-Horta, a spokesman for
pro-independence forces in the half-island territory.
	   ``Only then might they consider some wishy-washy 'special
status' for East Timor. This is not a serious proposal, and I am
stating unequivocally that we reject it.''
	   Ramos-Horta is co-winner of the 1996 Nobel peace prize and has
close contacts with the underground resistance movement in East
Timor, which Indonesia invaded in 1975 after the departure of
Portugal's colonial administration. A year later, then-President
Suharto declared East Timor Indonesia's 27th province _ an act not
recognized by the United Nations.
	   Indonesia, the world's largest Muslim nation, is often accused
of widespread human rights abuses in predominantly Roman Catholic
East Timor.
	   Ramos-Horta spoke by telephone from Harvard University in
Cambridge, Massachusetts, where he was attending a seminar at the
John F. Kennedy School of Government.
	   In East Timor's provincial capital Dili, fellow Nobel
prize-winner Bishop Carlos Belo _ the territory's spiritual leader
_ refused to comment on Habibie's proposal.
	   Habibie, in an interview with the British Broadcasting Corp.,
offered East Timor an unspecified special status in exchange for
peace with pro-independence forces.
	   Ramos-Horta said Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas has
argued for years that Indonesia would be prepared to release
certain prisoners and grant some form of ``bogus autonomy'' to East
Timor so long as the United Nations recognizes its control of the
area.
	   ``It is nothing new,'' he said of Habibie's offer.
	   ``The only realistic and honest proposal Indonesia can offer is
that they accept the challenge of an internationally supervised
referendum on the future of the territory,'' said Ramos-Horta, who
resides in Sydney, Australia.
	   ``I am supremely confident that Indonesia can simply not afford
financially, economically and politically to continue the illegal
occupation of East Timor,'' he said.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Indonesia-East Timor-Ramos-Horta; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:ASIA;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
