w1548 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  THE-WORKING-OF-THE-EYEsk     06-09 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> THE-WORKING-OF-THE-EYE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
The workings of the eye, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
The workings of the eye, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE old analogy of comparing the eye to a camera is a good way
to explain the process of how we see things. The eye is attached to
muscles which are used to locate and position an image. Then, a
series of lenses bring the image into focus, while a diaphragm
controls the light intensity.
	   The image is then projected onto a screen, which converts the
image by chemical reaction into electrical signals which are sent
by the nerves to the brain for processing.
	   There are six external ocular muscles that move the eye into the
various `positions of gaze'.
	   In a perfect system, both eyes target the desired scene so that
the focused image falls onto the retina at the back of the eyes.
	   An error in the system can indicate a disease affecting the
nerve connections in the eye and the brain. Sometimes, these
defects may indicate a serious pathology, including tumours and
neurological diseases.
	   The mis-positioning of the eyes by the external muscles is
called strabismus. This can occur if: one or more of the external
muscles is too long or too short; one or more of the muscles are
attached to the eyeball at the wrong position; the innervations
(nerve connections) to one or more of the muscles are defective;
the cortical (brain) processing system is sending incorrect signals
to the muscles, causing misalignment there is an uncorrected
hyperopia (farsightedness).
	   Strabismus can result in the wall-eyed or cross-eyed look.
Stereoscopic (3-D) vision is missing or limited, causing the
focusing system to be slow or inappropriate.
	   Limited depth perception also causes incorrect spatial cues and
may result in problems in learning to walk, eye-hand co-ordination
difficulties, general clumsiness and other problems.
	   Surgery and eye muscle exercises can remedy strabismus. The
length and/or position of the eye muscles can be adjusted through
surgery to create proper alignment. If the problem is minor and/or
associated with a poorly developed or incorrectly nervous system
connection, vision training may be used.
	   Focusing: cornea and lens: The optical lenses consist of the
cornea (the clear window at the front of the eyeball) and the
crystalline lens (just inside the eye and behind the iris).
	   The cornea is a rapidly reproducing and repairable transparent
structure with a constant curvature. It is the main focusing
element of the eye.
	   Chemical exposure and burns, deep cuts and some infections can
cause scars on the cornea which can interfere with vision. If you
experience pain, light sensitivity and tearing, immediate medical
attention is crucial.
	   Badly fitted contact lenses can also affect its health and
structure.
	   After the cornea focuses the image, the light passes through the
crystalline lens. This tissue corrects the focal power for viewing
near objects.
	   As we age, this lens becomes less flexible. The ciliary muscle
weakens and the system fails to adequately focus the image. This is
called presbyopia.
	   Treatment for early presbyopia includes exercises to strengthen
the muscle and flexibility of the lens. Reading glasses are also
recommended.
	   Another age-related condition is cataracts, the term for the
loss of light transmission through the lens. They can also be
caused by certain medications (like prolonged use of
cortcosteroids), metabolic disorders such as diabetes, or can
result from trauma to the eye.
	   As the lens becomes less transparent, vision is affected. The
standard treatment is to replace it with a plastic lens implant.
	   Conjunctiva and Lacrimal (tear-producing system): The
conjunctiva is a thin membrane that covers the sclera (the white-
coloured outer shell of the eyeball) and lines the inside of the
eyelids.
	   Inflammation of this tissue is called conjunctivitis. It can
become damaged, callused-appearing (pinguecula, pterigium) or
inflamed from allergy, bacteria, virus or chemical or physical
trauma.
	   Signs include redness, excessive tearing and discharge (mucus or
cell debris and pus from bacteria or virus). Symptoms range from
itching and watering to burning, pain and grittiness. If the
condition persists for more than three days and is accompanied by
fever, pain or blurred vision, medical attention is required.
	   Tears consists of water, oil, mucus and components designed to
disarm invading pathogens like viruses, bacteria and even pollen.
It also provides moisture and lubrication for the cornea,
conjunctiva and sclera.
	   Deficiency of tears cause dryness and tired, heavy lids. If not
treated, the cornea develops dry spots and areas of dying cells,
causing a gritty feeling, pain and blurred vision.
	   Tear drops can be used to relieve the problem but if it
persists, you should seek medical help.
	   Iris and Uvea: The iris is a disk-shaped muscle with a hole (the
pupil) in the centre.
	   It is responsible for adjusting the amount of light entering the
eye.
	   The uvea is the extension of the iris tissue to the lining of
the inside of the eye. The iris is the anterior part of the uveal
tract.
	   Damage to the iris can cause the tissue to swell and/or disrupt
pupil constriction and dilation, causing angle-closure glaucoma.
Treatment requires the use of drugs to force the iris to constrict.
	   Some disorders affecting the iris include inflammatory
non-rheumatoid arthritis conditions such as ankylosing spondylitis,
reiters syndrome, psoriasis and diabetes.
	   Aqueous and Vitreous: The front chamber of the eye, from the
cornea to the lens, is filled with a fluid called aqueous.
	   Over-production or obstruction of the drainage system causes
fluid pressure and can damage the nerves of the retina. This is
called glaucoma.
	   Treatment for glaucoma depends on the causes and may consist of
oral medications, topically applied drugs (eye drops), laser
surgery or combinations of the above.
	   Retina: The retina is the film of the eye and vision system and
transforms light into electrical signals that travel from the optic
nerve to the occipital cortex of the brain where the information is
processed into the sense of sight.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:THE-WORKING-OF-THE-EYE sked; CT:w; 
