<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Truth Commission </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Parliament give extension to Truth Commission to complete work
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ Parliament on Tuesday gave the
Truth and Reconciliation Commission more time to complete its work,
although the party that ruled during apartheid objected, calling
the commission incompetent.
	   The bill, which passed by 215 votes to 79, will allow the panel
which is probing apartheid-era human rights abuses to submit an
interim report on October 31 this year and enable its amnesty
committee to conduct more than 1,000 outstanding amnesty
application hearings, said Justice Minister Dullah Omar said.
	   Previously, the Truth Commission was to have issued a report in
July. However, the commission has been dealing with a heavy
workload.
	   Once the amnesty committee's work is complete, President Nelson
Mandela will reconvene the Truth Commission so it can complete its
final report.
	   The commission can give amnesty to those who confess fully to
politically motivated crimes committed during apartheid.
	   Parliament deputies from the National Party, which ruled during
apartheid until Mandela's African National Congress won the
nation's first all-race elections in 1994, denounced the
legislation, saying Truth Commission officials were inefficient,
arrogant and incompetent.
	   (aos)
</TEXT>
