<HEADLINE>
New office established in Thailand, NATION
</HEADLINE>
New office established in Thailand, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   JIRAPAN BOONNOONASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IN SPITE of the economic woes, Linksys has established a
representative office in Thailand as its second office in the Asia
Pacific region after Singapore, to sell its networking products.
	   ''Thailand is the greatest potential market among those in Asia
Pacific. Even though it is facing economic turmoil, it will recover
soon,'' Victor Tsao, president and CEO of Linksys, says.
	   He said although China is a huge market, it comes with high
risk. Meanwhile Hong Kong and Taiwan are reaching saturation point.
	   After establishing the Thai representative office, the company
plans to set up offices in Malaysia and Australia. Three branch
offices will report directly to the head office in Singapore. The
head office in Singapore will provide regional sales, marketing,
logistics and technical support to each office.
	   For distribution in Thailand, Surachet Chaikaew, general manager
of Linksys (Thailand) Ltd, said the firm plans to appoint several
distributors in July. One will act as system integrator to focus on
the government market. Another will concentrate on the retail
market while a third will be a value added retailer to cover small
office and home office users as well as small, medium and
enterprise customers.
	   ''We will offer lower prices to customers,'' he insisted.
	   
</TEXT>
