w1555 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  DEALING-TOOTH-INJURYsked     06-09 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> DEALING-TOOTH-INJURY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dealing with tooth injury, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Dealing with tooth injury, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Prof Dr Rahimah A. KadirASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IN the past, an injury to your front teeth was often the result
of fights and probably occurred more often among men. But today,
tooth fractures occur even among toddlers.
	   Often, they are due to falls on hard surfaces. In the process of
learning to walk, they trip and bump into tables, chairs etc. If
they fall face down on hard concrete, chances are their front teeth
gets broken.
	   Studies since the 1970s have shown that tooth injury is on the
increase, ranging from 16 to 40 per cent among five- to
six-year-olds, and about 20 per cent in 12-year-olds. Boys were
twice as prone to tooth injury than girls.
	   Protruding upper front teeth were also found to be at a higher
risk of tooth injury. Most of these were suspected to be due to
falls, fights, domestic violence and child abuse.
	   World wide, the figures seem to imply that in the future, about
every second child will be susceptible to getting an injured tooth
before the age of 12. Local studies also indicate an increase of
tooth injury among teenagers, from two per cent in the 12-year-olds
to six per cent in the 16-year-olds.
	   With the increase in domestic violence and child abuse
incidents, the figures presented may, for all purposes, be an
underestimation.
	   The cost of tooth injury.
	   For many young people, an injured front tooth can pose a
psychological and aesthetic problem.
	   A poor job done on a fractured tooth can affect their self
esteem and confidence. Depending on the nature and extent of the
injury, the age of the child and availability of treatment, the
total cost of immediate and later care of tooth injury can be quite
substantial.
	   Clinically, an injured baby or primary front tooth before the
age of three can have serious implications. In severe cases, it may
cause the loss of the permanent successor located somewhere beneath
the baby teeth.
	   In cases where the tooth is either avulsed or twisted in
position, or came out in toto, dentists will make an effort to
reimplant it. But the success rate of such a procedure in primary
teeth is questionable.
	   Often, to protect damaging the permanent buds, the intruded
tooth is instead extracted. This procedure can be an added trauma
to the child who is already in pain, scared and confused! Before
the age of nine, injuries to the nerves of permanent front teeth
can create complications. Root canal treatment is often difficult
because the root is not fully formed. Complete root formation
usually occurs about three years after the tooth has erupted.
	   Even a slight blow to the tooth can cause nerve degeneration
although it might look normal initially. This can be seen when the
tooth changes colour from yellowish to brownish and black. This is
often accompanied by a tingling, sensitive feeling which can flare
up into persistent pain as the inflammation spreads throughout the
tooth pulp.
	   Prevention is better than cure.
	   Fortunately, the majority of tooth injury can be prevented. Here
are some tips.
	   Make sure you practise home safety to prevent your child from
falling and breaking his front teeth. Do not allow him to jump on
the bed.
	   Supervise his interests in climbing up and down the stairs.
	   Protruded upper front teeth has the highest risk of tooth
fracture when hit. Often, unless genetically influenced, protruded
teeth are associated with detrimental habits like thumb-sucking,
and breathing through the mouth for a long period.
	   Such habits can be controlled if your child felt loved and
secure.
	   Make sure that your child is protected adequately when roller
skating, on skating boards and the like. By wearing safety gears
they are not only protecting their body but also their teeth.
	   Children who play more aggressive games like hockey, rugby,
boxing, martial arts and the like should be encouraged to wear
custom-made mouthguards. Schools should make this compulsory.
	   What do you do when your tooth is injured?
	   After a direct blow or hit - Our teeth are relatively fragile as
compared to other body parts. This is especially true for the four
upper front teeth.
	   Therefore, they may be injured even if they look normal after
being hit because the injury process may be gradual.
	   Many complain of blackened or black-stained teeth several months
and even years after the injury. Others develop a nagging or
excruciating pain around or at the injured teeth long after the
accident has been forgotten.
	   This is because the blood capillaries inside the tooth pulp have
degenerated. These `dead' pulp will then undergo the process of
inflammation at some point in time.
	   Although `dead' pulp can be treated with a root canal procedure,
it is always better to try and save the tooth. Always visit your
dentist immediately after an accident for X-rays and a meticulous
examination.
	   Immediate and appropriate action, which is less costly, can then
be taken.
	   If your tooth fractures - Often your tooth either chips off at
the end or fractures midway after a hit or fall. Visit your dentist
immediately.
	   Your tooth need not be extracted. Instead, your dentist will
have a series of treatment options that will make your teeth look
as good as new.
	   If your tooth is dangling by the root or has dropped out
completely, do not despair. Your dentist can try to reimplant the
tooth. The success of such a procedure, however, depends on the
age, time of injury, your overall oral tissue status, and general
health.
	   Whenever possible, emergency dental treatment should be rendered
at the scene of the accident as soon as possible.
	   If your tooth is severely displaced: Try to reposition it in the
correct position.
	   Hold it in place with your finger, and Rush the child to the
nearest dental clinic as soon as possible.
	   If the tooth is knocked out of the mouth: Ideally, it should be
immediately reimplanted into the socket and proceed as above.
	   If it is dirty, rinse it in water or saline solution. Better
still, immerse it in a cup of milk. DO NOT SCRUB the tooth clean!
Rush the child to the nearest dental clinic.
	   Sometimes it is not possible or practical to reimplant the tooth
back into the socket due to other body injuries. But if the child
can co- operate, ask him to hold the tooth inside the mouth next to
the cheek while he is being transported to the dental clinic.
	   Every school and home should have a First Aid Guideline for
Tooth Injury. The faster you seek dental help, the higher your
chance of saving your tooth/teeth.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
