<HEADLINE>
Israel says it wants Middle East to remain nuclear-free
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A senior Israeli official expressed concern over
Tehran's efforts to acquire nuclear technology during a visit
Tuesday to Russia, which is building a nuclear power plant in Iran.
	   Eitan Ben Tsur, director general of the Israeli Foreign
Ministry, raised the concerns during a meeting with Russian Deputy
Foreign Minister Viktor Posuvalyuk, the Interfax news agency said.
	   Israel and the United States have also accused Iran of trying to
develop a long-range missile with the help of Russian companies and
scientists. Russia acknowledges overtures were made, but said all
were repelled.
	   Ben Tsur said Russian officials reported on their efforts to
crack down on the export of ``dual-use'' technology that can be
used for both military and civilian purposes, Interfax reported.
	   The news agency also quoted Ben Tsur as saying Israel will not
be the first country in the Middle East to acquire nuclear weapons.
	   Former Israeli Minister Shimon Peres last week edged close to
acknowledging that Israel already is a nuclear power, saying the
country pursued a nuclear option to prevent war.
