<BODY>
<SLUG> E-COMMERCE-COMES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-commerce comes from market access, NATION
</HEADLINE>
E-commerce comes from market access, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   SOMPIT POTIPATTANAKORNASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ELECTRONIC commerce in Thailand should be built from market
access, unlike in other countries, according to Department of
Business Economics deputy director-general Thawatchai
Sophastienpong.
	   Worldwide, electronic commerce began with finance, consisting of
customs, taxation and electronic payment; law, comprising a uniform
commercial code, privacy and security; and market access, related
to telecommunications, information technology, content and
technical standards.
	   Meanwhile, he said, market access will be the first step for
Thailand, followed by finance and law.
	   ''Several companies now provide shopping through the Internet,
even though not all the processes are done electronically,'' he
said.
	   However, the department plans to establish a trial
electronic-commerce project this October which is expected to
become a complete electronic commerce project.
	   To achieve this goal, it has set up a committee to set standards
for electronic commerce, including registration and communication,
marketing, consumer protection, taxation, transport and insurance,
as well as payment.
	   In the meantime it hopes to have 100,000 Web sites providing
services and products on the Internet.
	   ''This will help boost the electronic-commerce market in
Thailand,'' he said.
	   Meanwhile the National Electronics and Computer Technology
Centre (Nectec) has set up a committee to draft six laws on
electronic commerce and the Internet, covering data protection,
computer crime, electronic data interchange (EDI), digital
signatures, electronic fund transfers and a law to dovetail with
Article 78 of the Telecommunications Act.
	   The drafting will take around 10 months before it is submitted
to the government.
	   These drafts will be based on a model drafted by the United
Nations and on laws in Germany, the United States, Singapore and
Malaysia.
	   ''We expect that these six laws will be completed and effective
within one year. Then Thailand will be the third country in the
Asia Pacific region with an e-commerce law, after Singapore and
Malaysia,'' said Nectec's director, Pirash Thajchayapong.
	   Apart from Nectec, the Justice Ministry and Police Department
are jointly drafting laws on computer- and information-technology
crime, embracing electronic commerce.
	   ''The final electronic-commerce law may come from both sources.
Electronic-commerce law is vital for every country, since we run
business not only domestically but also internationally,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
