<HEADLINE>
Spice Girls share stage with Pavarotti in Italy
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MODENA, Italy (AP) _ It was a taste of Pavarotti both spicey and
spiked, with a touch of soul.
	   The tenor of his times arranged a live televised song-fest
Tuesday night directed by Spike Lee and co-starring pop performers
like the Spice Girls, Stevie Wonder and Jon Bon Jovi.
	   The Ginger-less Spice group were giving their first performance
since their split with ``Ginger Spice,'' Geri Halliwell, was
announced.
	   The four and Pavarotti joined forces on the program for the song
``Viva Forever.''
	   Proceeds of the fifth annual ``Pavarotti and Friends'' charity
concert were destined to help poor children in the African nation
of Liberia. The show in this northern city was broadcast live on
Italy's flagship state television channel, RAI-1.
	   As the 62-year-old Pavarotti has been making fewer opera
appearances in recent years, his pop career is on the upswing.
	   Also on the roster were Vanessa Williams, Celine Dion, Natalie
Cole, Trisha Yearwood and Italian stars Eros Ramazzotti, Zucchero
and Pino Daniele.
	   At a news conference Monday, Lee was asked whether the group
would be as good without Ms. Halliwell.
	   ``I'm not an expert on the Spice Girls so I don't know if I can
answer that,'' he answered.
	   The other Spice Girls declined to talk about the matter.
	   (djw)	   
