<SLUG> SAD-MEMORIES-FOR-WIDOW sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Award brings sad memories for widow, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Award brings sad memories for widow, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Alex ChoongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sat. - For staff nurse Solhah Mat Sarin, the
posthumous award of Bintang Seri Pahlawan Gagah Perkasa which Yang
di-Pertuan Agong Tuanku Ja'afar conferred on her husband, police
corporal Mohd Nosruddin Che Yeop, brought back sad memories.
	   Talking to reporters after the investiture, she expressed her
gratitude for the award and also her grief that ``the award will
not bring back my husband''.
	   Mohd Nosruddin, 36, was killed during a riot at the Semenyih
immigration detention camp when a group of Indonesian illegal
immigrants resisted deportation on March 26.
	   Solhah, a nurse of Teluk Intan Hospital and mother of three
children aged between 18 months and 10 years, said: ``I am very
thankful to the Government, the police and the Federal Reserve
Unit, Central Brigade, for the help extended to my family and me.''
	   She was the first to accept the award at the investiture on the
occasion of the King's 76th birthday at Balai Rong Seri at Istana
Negara.
	   The citation traced the events leading to Mohd Nosruddin's
death.
	   It stated that Mohd Nosruddin was assigned together with his
colleagues to calm the situation at the camp but they were pelted
with stones by the illegal immigrants who also torched the
buildings.
	   Mohd Nosruddin and others who were in the frontline were
attacked by the rioters with wood, iron pipes, sharpened fencing
posts and knives.
	   He helped his injured colleagues to retreat and faced the
rioters alone only with a cane and a shield. He was stabbed to
death.
	   The citation stated that by rescuing his colleagues and facing
the rioters without considering his own interest and safety, Mohd
Nosruddin made the ultimate sacrifice.
	   Dewan Rakyat Speaker Tan Sri Zahir Ismail, who headed the
honours list, received the Seri Setia Mahkota Malaysia which
carried the title ``Tun''.
	   Sixteen of the 21 recipients of the Panglima Setia Mahkota,
which carries the title ``Tan Sri'', also received their awards
today.
	   Among them were the King's daugther Tunku Dara Naquiah, Deputy
Inspector-General of Police Datuk Norian Mai, DRB-Hicom Group
chairman Datuk Wira Saleh Sulong and Umno veteran Abdul Aziz Tapa.
	   Thirteen of the recipients of the Panglima Jasa Negara, one of
the recipient of the Panglima Setia di-Raja, five of the recipient
of the Johan Mangku Negara and four of the recipients of the Johan
Setia Mahkota also received their awards.
	   Deputy Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim, Ministers and
members of the diplomatic corps also attended the ceremony.
	   
</TEXT>
