<HEADLINE>
Sonia asks Vajpayee to stop move to build Ram Temple, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Sonia asks Vajpayee to stop move to build Ram Temple, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Congress President Sonia Gandhi yesterday asked Prime Minister
Atal Bihari Vajpayee to assure the country that his government is
prepared to uphold the sanctity of the judicial process in She
Ayodhya dispute and stop Gangh Parivar' controlled organisations
from going ahead with the construction of a Ram Temple at the
disputed site. In a letter to Vajpayee, she asked him whether the
whole issue relating to the dispute had to be resolved through the
judicial process which was already under way and was continuing
with the endorsement of the Supreme Court or was it open to any
party to take recourse to actions which had no judicial sanction.
	   Gandhi said the second point was whether the government was
aware that the Vishaw Hindu Parishad or some other organisations
controlled by the Sangh Parivar' were engaged in activities with
the objective of constructing the Ram Temple at Ayodhya even before
the judicial processes already set in motion was concluded. If so
what steps were being contemplated to stop these activities she
queried. The Congress president said 'The country would like to be
reassured that your government is prepared to uphold the sanctity
of the judicial processes and deal firmly with anyone who may
choose to violate the basic tenets that govern the judicial
determination of any issue before a court of law. ``I do hop that
you will take cognisance of this matter which deals with an
extremely serious and sensitive issue having a direct bearing on
the well being of our country .
	   I shall be grateful for an early reply, Gandhi said. In her
letter she referred to media reports about preparations being made
in various part of the country to construct a Ram Temple at the
site where the Babri Masjid structure stood before it was
demolished. Gandhi also recalled the statements made by VHP leaders
that they were ready to go ahead with the building of the temple
within a specified time frame. She said the tragic trail of events
leading to the ``shocking' incident on December 6, 1992, and is
bloody aftermath were still fresh in the memory of the nation. I am
sure you will agree with us that every right thinking citizen in
our country would never like a repetition of these unfortunate
events.'' Gandhi said her party had been raising questions in this
regard in parliament and outside but no satisfactory answer came
from the government.
	   Keeping in mind the recent developments in our country it is
imperative not to allow such divisive issue to come to the fore to
the detriment of the larger national interests she said seeking
government's explanation so that all apprehensions and suspicions
are laid to rest.Meanwhile, Vishwa Hindu Parishad (VHP) yesterday
said no temple construction activity was being carried out anywhere
near the disputed site at Ayodhya. In a statement here VHP
secretary general Acharya Artraj Kishore said the Ayodhya temple
construction work could begin only in amicable and congenial'
atmosphere. Ayodhya temple construction work would go ahead only if
the court gives favourable judgement or the government makes
suitable laws, he said hoping for a favourable court verdict in
this regard. Acharya said my statement regarding Ayodhya temple is
being misquoted every time.
	   
</TEXT>
