<HEADLINE>
HP commits to integration, NATION
</HEADLINE>
HP commits to integration, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   SOMPIT POTIPATTANAKORNASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HEWLETT-PACKARD (Thailand) Ltd is committed to Unix and NT
integration, selling software to run on both platforms, with the
focus on development of software for networks instead of for PCs.
The firm is avoiding competing directly with Microsoft.
	   ''We are committed to endorsing Wolfpack instead of pushing our
Mcserver Guard in order to avoid an overlap in the market.
Microsoft will concentrate on software for offices while we focus
on software management,'' said Kanya Tanphiphat, country manager
professional services organisation.
	   Wolfpack is cluster technology for the Microsoft Windows NT
Server operating system and is based on open specifications and
industry-standard hardware. Openview is the first software that can
run on both platforms. The company also plans to release other
software that runs on two platforms such as Virtual Volt and Smart
Contact.
	   ''These software items are in our lab and they will gradually be
launched in Thai editions,'' she said.
	   The company's managing director, Kim Yu, said integration is a
huge market, and the firm has leasing services. ''The revenue
generated from leasing this year increased 30 per cent over that of
last year. Leasing is usually approved for projects worth
US$100,000 or more,'' he said.
	   Not only does the company offer leasing arrangements to the
private sector, but it also sells assistance to government sectors
as well as state enterprises in terms of training and operational
concepts, as well as consultations on existing computer management.
	   ''The government sector and state enterprises have many older
model computers. We will train their staff to use those computers
instead of purchasing new computers due to budget limits,'' he
said.
	   
</TEXT>
