<BODY>
<SLUG> HANSON-BACK-IN-THE-NEWS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hanson back in the news and that's bad for business, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Hanson back in the news and that's bad for business, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Tony FrancisASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ASKED by Malaysian journalists in Sydney last week about Pauline
Hanson and the seemingly confident march of her One Nation party,
an Australian businessman replied jokingly: ``Pauline who?''
	   His reluctance to acknowledge her was not without reason.
Pauline Hanson is back in the news and that's bad for business.
	   So is the march of her One Nation party which is gathering great
support, giving Prime Minister John Howard's Government the chills
well ahead of next Saturday's Queensland election.
	   The election will be watched with great interest - and concern -
because of Hanson's controversial pronouncements in 1996 on
Aborigines, Asians and migrants whom she blamed for introducing
crime and diseases into Australia.
	   The remarks, made in her maiden speech as an independent MP, had
been labelled as ``racist, deranged and irresponsible''. Not only
did they divide Australia, they also embarrassed Howard who has
been criticised for not rejecting and repudiating her views earlier
and more forcefully.
	   Speaking to Malaysian journalists who were on a special visit to
Australia last week, Foreign Minister Alexander Downer and
Victorian Premier Jeff Kennett were quick to dismiss Hanson and her
racist policies ``as a challenge to be defeated by intellectual
debate and the ballot box rather than anything else''.
	   Downer described her as Australia's wildest political maverick
who should not be taken too seriously.
	   ``Every country in the world has political mavericks - people
who are outspoken with unfortunate remarks, people who are bigots,
people who try to live in the 1930s instead of in the 1990s.
	   ``I make no apology for the fact that Australia is no exception.
We don't judge a country on the basis of its wildest maverick.''
	   Kennett was vitriolic in his criticism of ``that woman in
Queensland'' and said the Asian media was giving her the kind of
prominence she did not deserve.
	   ``By giving her the prominence, you have either ignored or
downplayed the views of the vast majority of Australians,
particularly those of us who have close ties with the Asian
community.''
	   Dr Larry Strange, director of the Asia Australia Institute in
Sydney, does not believe that Hanson and One Nation would pose a
major foreign policy problem for Australia in Asia.
	   ``But she is a vivid example of the negative side of Australia.
While we continue to be unconditionally accepted in the region, she
will always be used against us and we can understand why,'' he
said.
	   ``She is ignorant, she is poorly educated, she is poorly
informed, she does not represent Australian society. In any
society, we have, unfortunately, a small number of people who have
extremely conservative and xenophobic, inward-looking views based
on fear, anger and a dislike of difference.''
	   No matter what, Hanson has already caused a lot of damage to
Australia in terms of internal and external perceptions, said
Michael Wesley a research fellow at the Institute.
	   ``In relation to Asia, the perceptions are particularly crucial
to trade,'' he said.
	   The external perception of Australia is that it is a Western
country, with the White Australian policy still rankling in the
minds of many Asians. The internal perception is on the way the
Government presents the country's relationship with its neighbours.
It is also the way the rest of Australian society feels about how
the country is going.
	   ``Hanson is damaging to both perceptions.''
	   The sudden surge in support for Hanson and One Nation,
especially among the poorly educated blue-collar workers, is
already causing tremors among the ranks of Howard's Government.
	   It was just a year ago that Howard confidently predicted that
the One Nation party, which celebrated its first anniversary in
April, would close shop in the next Queensland election. But he is
not so sure now as recent polls have shown it to be making inroads
in Queensland, and nationally.
	   Said Strange: ``The point about Hanson is if you put a hand in
her crazy shopping bag of policies, you'll pull out every bit of
difficulty in the Australian political system.''
	   For instance, Hanson has been riding high on the back of race
and gun control issues. This week, she continued her assault on
Aborigines with a statement that Australia faced the creation of
Aboriginal States and that a proposed UN declaration on indigenous
rights would spell disintegration for Australia.
	   LAST month, Hanson said her One Nation would relax gun laws,
which were put in place after the Port Arthur massacre in Tasmania
which left 35 people dead.
	   She has also pledged to scrap the registration of rifles and to
re- instate access to self-loading rifles, shotguns and
military-style rifles for gun club members.
	   ``In her bag, she has managed to capture every fear that this
very insecure, conservative, inward-looking part of Australian
society worries about and this is where the Prime Minister's
response, from our point of view, has been so frustrating.
	   ``For example, she has extremely ill-informed views about the
whole reconciliation issue with our indigenous people.
	   ``These views are nonsense and in the current environment, they
are extremely irresponsible and distressing. She actually plays to
groups of disadvantaged Australians who think that as they are
going through hard times, why should Aboriginal people get any
special treatment?
	   ``She plays well on the issue and then you get the Prime
Minister on a talkback radio programme saying he does not subscribe
to the black armband view of Australian history. Howard should have
looked at the experience of the indigenous people squarely in the
face and decide on what to do policy-wise and symbolically, namely
an apology.
	   ``For example, the report on the stolen children - the
experience of Aboriginal children taken from their parents and
often raised by white families and institutions in Australia ...
it's a very distressing document.
	   ``Many political leaders, NGOs and even the governor-general had
very strong views that this required strong symbolic action by
Australian leaders.
	   ``The Prime Minister is very uncomfortable about that sort of
strong symbolic action, so he's saying, `Yes, it's a legitimate
issue but we must make a very measured response to it'.
	   ``This is a perfectly appropriate political option for him but
when these issues are played on Australian talk-radio, it can
actually perpetuate the negative stereotypes in Hanson's shopping
bag when what was needed was comprehensive political leadership.
Talk about it at every turn and bury the misrepresentation at the
root of her party's policy platform.''
	   Wesley feels that Howard was too dismissive towards Hanson in
Parliament.
	   ``When Hanson stands up to ask a question - remember she has
constituents out there who vote for her - Howard's response is so
personally dismissive that it's almost like saying 'I'm not going
to bother to take your opinion seriously'.
	   ``That is not the right way to deal with the problem. A leader
worth his salt, would actually take what she is saying seriously
and attempt to rebutt it. Howard has not attempted to do so when it
is so rebuttable. The things that she said are so stupid.''
	   The upshot to the Hanson episode is that greater emphasis is now
being placed on multi-culturalism in the respective States, with
Kennett saying it was an ``unwarranted political correctness''.
	   It has been reported that ethnic jokes would soon be outlawed in
Victoria under tough anti-racism policy to be introduced in State
schools this year. At present, jokes are exempted under federal
anti- discrimination laws.
	   The policy will ban the voicing of stereotypical views of people
based on national identity.
	   It also covers children picking on others because of differences
such as skin colour or ethno-religious clothing. Teachers and
students accused of racial discrimination will face disciplinary
action under new grievance procedures.
	   The downside is, Australian business, already feeling the
effects of the Asian economic problem, cannot afford further
setbacks.
	   Tourist arrivals from Asia have dipped by as much as 13 per cent
from Southeast Asia and eight per cent from Northeast Asia in the
three months to December 1997 as opposed to the corresponding
period the previous year.
	   No wonder Pauline Hanson is a name most hope would soon
disappear from the Australian political landscape. The sooner the
better.
	   
</TEXT>
