<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Dutch captain may miss first game after injuring ankle
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) _ Dutch captain Frank de Boer may
miss the Netherlands' first World Cup qualifying match after
injuring his ankle in training, Dutch coach Guus Hiddink said
Tuesday.
	   De Boer, 27, twisted his left ankle Monday. He stood on the
sidelines during Tuesday's practice, his injured ankle bandaged.
	   ``We will see how he reacts today and tomorrow,'' Hiddink said.
``He is receiving treatment.'' No decision will be made until
Friday on whether De Boer can play in the Netherlands' opening
World Cup Group E match Saturday against Belgium in St. Denis.
	   A left-footed defender, De Boer missed the Euro 96 tournament in
England with a similar injury. He hobbled off the field at
Amsterdam's Arena Stadium on Monday after falling during training.
	   Barcelona defender Winston Bogarde is De Boer's most likely
replacement alongside Jaap Stam in the center of the Dutch defense.
	   Another injured Dutch player, Arsenal striker Dennis Bergkamp,
went through light training Tuesday as he fought to regain fitness
in the wake of a six-week layoff caused by a hamstring injury.
	   Hiddink said the prognosis for Bergkamp was improving. It had
been feared that Bergkamp would miss not only the Belgium match,
but also the Netherlands' second match, against South Korea June 20
in Marseille.
	   ``I don't have a great deal of faith he will be fit (for
Belgium) but before Korea we have another week so I think it should
be OK,'' Hiddink said.
</TEXT>
