<SLUG> A-PIECE-OF-CAKE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A piece of cake, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
A piece of cake, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 07, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Tan Bee HongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THEY were the underdogs or so they thought. Thus it was hardly
surprising that when they were approached to take part in a
cheescake competition, the Sim brothers - Nicholas, Michael and
Desmond - of Secret Recipe weren't terribly enthusiastic. Nicholas
simply sent one of their regular cheesecakes off the shelf to the
New World Hotel where the 12 judges waited in cosy comfort at the
presidential suite.
	   Secret Recipe was not the only entry and the team was pitted
against 15 other pastry chefs from big, five-star hotels in Kuala
Lumpur. Never dreaming that they would win, the team didn't even
hang around to wait.
	   But win the homeboys did. Yes, it was a case of Malaysia Boleh
and the Sims' Marble Marvel cheesecake took back the Best Overall
Cheesecake award in the competition organised by the Vision Kuala
Lumpur magazine.
	   The judges had a task most of us would die for, devoting a whole
morning to the cream of KL cheesecakes. They `judged blind', not
knowing which cake came from where. But when they were through, you
can bet none of the judges could not look at another cheesecake for
a long time to come.
	   For there were cheesecakes and cheesecakes and more cheesecakes
from establishments like the JW Marriot, Regent KL, Cocomo, Cafe
Citron, Concorde, Sunway Resort, Carcosa Seri Negara, New World,
Istana, Ritz- Carlton, Shangri La, Pan Pacific, KL Hilton and of
course, Secret Recipe.
	   Some had outlandish names too, like Garden of Eden, Lemon Tree,
Strawberry Towers, Little Mermaid and even Gotham City. There were
different categories of awards including the Best Dressed
Cheesecake (New World Hotel), the Most Glamorous (The Regent), the
Most Fun (Shangri La), the Most Sociable (Ritz-Carlton `everyone
loved it'), The Cutest (Cafe Citron), The Most Sinful (Pan
Pacific), Most Authentic Appearance (JW Marriot).
	   ``We really, REALLY didn't think we had a chance,'' says a
modest Steven Sim. ``We didn't even know it was going to be such a
big event. Now we feel so proud that we had beaten the big boys,
namely the big chefs backed by big establishments.When the
organisers called to tell us we had won, we were totally surprised.
	   ``Our 1kg cake is one of the smallest entries. Some of the
others weighed well over 5kg,'' he adds. ``The fact that we sent in
such a plain cake just goes to show that the proof is in the
eating.''
	   No fancy fresh fruit or chocolate figures for Secret Recipe. The
cake they sent was exactly what customers ordered would get at nay
of their outlets. In fact, despite its name Marble Marvel, the only
marbling is merely cosmetic, apologetically skimping the surface of
the cake. The mild chocolate lacework only hints at the flavour.
	   Cut into the cake and you'd find a smooth journey till you reach
the pastry base. There is no side crust. Unlike most cheescakes
which use plain biscuit or cake base, Secret Recipe uses its own
special recipe - made with oatmeal.
	   This gives a nutty flavour to the cake and is lovely to chew on
as it offers a totally contrasting texture to the smooth creaminess
of the cheesecake topping.
	   ``Ordinary biscuit bases are not good enough,'' says Nicholas.
``I feel it would be a waste to have a plain base when we use such
high quality cheese. So we created the oatmeal base (which simply
bowled the judges over).''
	   Baked or chilled? ``All our cheesecakes are baked,'' says
Michael. ``The Marble Marvel is one of our best-sellers.''
	   Nicholas frowns. ``Baked is better,'' he says with all
seriousness.
	   ``Chilled cheesecakes aren't as moist and don't keep well, so it
would be difficult to display it for customers to select.''
	   Not that the Sims worry about how long cakes can keep as they
have yet to ponder over cakes leftover from the day before.
	   ``Keeping the quality of our cakes is very important. Our cakes
are freshly baked daily and we use fresh cream.''
	   The most surprising revelation is that none of the Sims have
been trained overseas. Leader of the pack Nicholas is not saying
but would only let on that he had taken his brothers under his
wing, making them learn the hard hands-on way. The three of them
experiment and continually come up with new recipes to keep
customers happy. Not only that, but the Sims like to keep their
recipes close to the family too.
	   How did they feel about the competition cakes which were
decorated with all manner of fruit from strawberries to mango and
blueberries?
	   Steven laughs (a little sardonically) and says he thinks a good
cheesecake does not need dressing up. ``Cheesecakes with fruit like
raisins etc, especially in the cheese filling, are not true
cheesecakes. Somehow, I feel it spoils the taste,'' he says but
he's not telling what goes into the Marble Marvel except that
there's eggs and cream.
	   Besides the Marble Marvel, new cakes include Chocolate Banana,
Chocolate Chip and Cheesy Chocolate. ``Yes,'' says Steven with a
laugh. ``It's obvious Malaysians like chocolate and we use good
quality Suchard chocolate.''
	   
</TEXT>
