<SLUG> BC-Russia-France </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Official: France's motion on genocide not aimed against modern
</HEADLINE>
Turkey &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The speaker of the French National Assembly said
Tuesday that a motion to recognize the 1915 killings of ethnic
Armenians in Turkey as a genocide was not aimed at modern Turkey.
	   The motion, unanimously passed by the assembly last month,
reflected a wish to show respect to the Armenian people, speaker
Laurent Fabius told a news conference in St. Petersburg.
	   His comments were reported by the Interfax news agency.
	   If also passed by the French Senate, the motion would make
France the first major European country to use the term
``genocide'' to describe the deaths of about 1.5 million Armenians
in Ottoman Turkey between 1915 and 1923.
	   Turkey denies the deaths constituted genocide, insisting they
were the result of a civil war, and strongly criticized the passing
of the motion.
	   Genocide is defined as the systematic killing of, or a program
of action intended to destroy, a whole national or ethnic group.
	   (ad/ls) 	   
</TEXT>
