<BODY>
<SLUG> PARIAHS-OF-THE-PARALLEL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAVEN FORBID: Pariahs of the parallel world, NATION
</HEADLINE>
HEAVEN FORBID: Pariahs of the parallel world, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   Jim AlgieASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   JUST about the lowest of the low in parts of India are those
pariahs who function as undertakers -- laying corpses on top of
funeral pyres, setting them ablaze, and helping them burn.
	   The writers, film-makers, artists and photographers of the
macabre are the same kind of outcasts in the parallel universes of
art and entertainment today.
	   An odd turnabout considering that the blood-line of such morbid
works is the jugular vein in what is the oldest body of
mythological, theatrical and fictional creations on Earth. From
this tradition has sprung Greek tragedy, epics like the Ramayana,
Beowulf , the Bard's Hamlet and Edgar Allen Poe's invention of the
detective story, an early dabbling in science fiction, along with
magical realism and a whole other slew of new authors like Brian
Hodge and Robert Devereaux.
	   So in this monthly column, we will be examining this tradition,
its viral influence, and modern mutations in movies, myths, music
and books.
	   The origins of these stories are shrouded in myth.
	   One of the darkest deities in the world pantheon is the Hindu
goddess of death and destruction, Kali. This black figure's
marrow-freezing appearance (she wears a garland of severed heads or
skulls; her mouth is smeared with blood) is the personification of
death and decay. In fact, her name is derived from a Sanskrit word
for ''time'' which is still used in Thai ( gala ), while galee
denotes something that is particularly odious.
	   In his second ''killer'' novel, Walking Wounded (Dell, 1996),
Robert Devereaux taps into this primal myth of the female as both
nurturer and destroyer (the reason, no doubt, that storms and
hurricanes are still given female names).
	   An energy vortex deep in the womb of Mother Earth, beneath the
home that her friends have built in the Rocky Mountains of
Colorado, has given part-time masseuse Katt a kind of ''magic
touch'' which she can use to cure or bring about the onset of
dormant diseases.
	   The undertow of the novel may be primarily mythical but its
concerns are profoundly contemporary.
	   Even though her 14-year-long marriage to a college professor has
gone flat, Katt comes from an old-fashioned family that does not
believe in divorce. To add fuel to her ire she has discovered that
her husband has been carrying on an affair with a campus colleague
of his.
	   What to do?
	   ''Morality as touted in public was always so black and white,
grey shaded in infinite gradations between them,'' the author
writes. ''She needed her freedom from Marcus or she would die in
spirit. It was that simple.'' What has really reanimated the
moribund corpus of horror is this move away from a
good-against-evil/man-tackles-monster kind of dichotomy, as
evidenced by the books of Devereaux, Kathe Koja ( Kink ) and Poppy
Z Brite ( Exquisite Corpse ).
	   Well, there's that philosophical shift, some inventive prose,
and the injection of a full-bodied sexuality. Gosh, the novels of
Devereaux and Brite are so charged with erotic electricity and
saturated with poetically-wrought sensuality, that they would
probably have made Henry Miller and Anais Nin blush.
	   On a more immediate, gut level, the most frightening bits in
Walking Wounded deal with the omnipotent male violence against
women. In particular, the American author's depiction of the
misogynistic, drill-wielding, serial slayer and his sickening deeds
are very extreme, but so deftly done and relevant they don't seem
gratuitous. Perhaps the novel's most indelible image, however, is
the way that the ex-husband of Marcus' lover branded ''MINE'' on
her back -- shades of what the modern-day troubador Leonard Cohen
called ''man's most ignoble form of real estate.'' Early forms of
drama date back to ancient tribal societies with shamans and
magicians often taking the lead roles. The historical hangover of
such ceremonies, held in praise of various deities, or in order to
ward off their wrath, or bring about a bountiful harvest, can still
be seen every day in Thailand.
	   Down at the Erawan Hotel shrine here in Bangkok traditional
dancers and musicians are paid to perform in honour of the Hindu
god Brahma by grateful supplicants who believe he granted their
wishes. And in parts of Isaan and Laos an ancient fertility rite is
acted out every year at the Bang Fai festival, where wildly
colourful bamboo rockets are launched into the sky so the presiding
deity will bring about a decent deluge for the rice crop.
	   In the West, the Olympic games and early dramas were staged to
honour gods like Zeus and Apollo. The followers of Dionysus, in
particular, were artistic zealots who would get together to drink,
sing songs, and recite folk tales together; until one day in BC 600
when a man named Thespis came out of the crowd to take on the role
of a character. He became the first actor and playwright.
	   The action in the old Greek dramas is frequently horrific. In
what is perhaps the most widely known of all Greek tragedies,
Oedipus Rex , written by Sophocles (BC 496-BC 409), an oracle tells
Laius, the King of Thebes, that the child born to his queen Jocasta
will grow up to kill him and wed his mother. Although the child is
saved and raised by a shepherd, he unwittingly does slay his own
father and then becomes the new ruler of Thebes by solving the
riddle of the Sphinx. In retaliation, the gods bring down a plague
on the city. But what do these vengeful deities really want? For
the murderer to be banished, or, ''the shedding of blood for
blood''.
	   When Oedipus finally begins to realise that he is the actual
slayer being sought, he laments: ''O Zeus. What hast thou willed me
to do?'' And then, near the tragic conclusion of the play, he cuts
out his own eyes and goes into exile.
	   To be continued next month 
</TEXT>
