<HEADLINE>
Back To The Nature, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Back To The Nature, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Wisetpong Wongtip finds out what is the latest on offer from two
leading fashion houses.
	   ON Wednesday, The Nation carried a news item headlined ''Crisis
hits fashion-conscious.'' According to the article, a survey of 391
professional women undertaken by the Thai Farmers Bank's research
centre, revealed that 35.2 per cent of the respondents had stopped
buying new dresses as the effects of the recession begin to bite.
	   Fortunately for both local and international fashion houses,
there is still some money around and connoisseuses of the Hermes
and Les Copains lines turned out in force for the showings of the
Spring/Summer '98 collections.
	   In keeping with budget cutbacks, both houses chose to showcase
their latest offerings at their respective retails outlets in The
Emporium shopping complex. Gone, it seems -- at least for the time
being -- are the days when fashion extravaganzas were held at
city's top hotels.
	   Despite the limited space for both guests and photographers
(most of whom good-naturedly positioned themselves around the
narrow catwalks and clicked away from awkward angles), the two
shows were an outstanding success and proved that when it comes to
imported lines, it can pay to spend on clothes and accessories that
will not only stay in style but also add long-lasting glamour to
your wardrobe.
	   Hermes has declared 1998 as the ''year of the tree'' and the
concept behind the look is the wonders of Mother Nature. The
Spring/Summer collection offers ten designs under the themes
''Beyond the Five Seas''; ''Back to the Land''; ''In the Heart of
the Woods''; ''The Floating Market of Lake Lane''; ''The Tree of
Silk''; ''Three Legends''; ''Silken Sun''; ''Railing''; ''Parasols
and Umbrellas''; and ''Paridaiza''.
	   Perhaps wisely given the current economic climate, Hermes chose
to showcase its flagship product -- the scarf -- and offered a
splendid variety of patterns, colours, sizes and styles.
	   The Hermes silk scarf has an interesting history. It was born in
1937, the fruit of a happy marriage between the Paris-based design
house and the silk merchants of Lyon. It comes in several sizes,
but it is always square. The 35 inch (87.5 cm) square is the
classic; the 18 inch (45 cm) square is known as the ''gavroche''
and the 55 inch (137 cm) square is essentially a shawl.
	   Jean-Louis Demas-Hermes, president of the group and creative
director for the scarf collection, personally reviews each scarf
and a new design is created every three weeks. To date, more than
900 designs have hit the market, many of which have never gone out
of print. The most famous are ''Cles' and ''Brides de Gala''.
	   Before the show, guests were treated to a demonstration of how
to use this classic accessory to its maximum potential. It is, as
Hermes has always emphasised, much more than something that is
simply tied round the neck.
	   The square may be worn under a jacket in place of a blouse or as
a sleeveless body wrap that looks great with casual pants. The
trick is knowing how to mix and match the tones and colours of the
separates. Hermes recommends choosing tones and colours that will
match your existing wardrobe of jackets, shirt and pants.
	   Over the years and to meet the demands of overseas markets,
Hermes has moved away from pure silk and introduced a mix of
quality silk and cotton. These are comfortable in any climate --
including humid Bangkok -- and have the added advantage of being
totally wrinkle-free.
	   As this year's theme is nature, the scarves are patterned with
trees, fruits and leaves. The primary colours in the new collection
are yellow, blue, orange, green, cream, and brown.
	   The second segment of the show featured formal wear for
professional women -- numbers that are suitable for both a day in
the office and evening business functions. The formal black and
dark blue dresses which contrasted sharply with the vivid colours
of the small but eclectic line of casual holiday wear.
	   The simplicity of the cuts and the quality of the fabrics are
such that the buyer knows that she will be able to wear the outfits
from this collection next year and into the next century. Hermes
not only makes clothes to last, but it also retains a sense of
classic modernity.
	   The French label has also introduced a new collection of leather
bags under new line name, Herbag. These offer the added advantage
of being easily adaptable to suit any occasion. Designed in two
modular parts, the Herbag can be taken apart and put back together
in a matter of seconds. It may serve as a briefcase or as a
suitcase for a weekend jaunt. What's more, it easy to modify. Just
slip the nickel framework bar to free the straps -- ditto to put it
back together again. For an extra touch of class, add a polished
padlock.
	   Leading Italian contemporary ready-to-wear label, Les Copains,
also captured hearts and wallets with more than 40 designs in its
new Spring &AMP; Summer Collection.
	   The label has long boasted that it understands the varied tastes
and styles of its customers. Like Hermes, the focus is on
dependability and understated glamour -- a balance between form and
substance that transcends mere fashion.
	   The Italian brand's favourite material -- pure cashmere knit --
was very much in evidence in all the lines on show. But no matter
what the design, it's reassuring to note that all outfits share the
same standard of quality and cut.
	   The ''Classic'' lines weds elegance and luxury through
meticulous design, fine tailoring and high-quality fabrics and is
the ideal companion this season for the fashion-conscious female
aged between 25 and 50.
	   ''Couture'' offers perfect choices for a dress-to-impress
occasion, with stunning long and short evening dresses and delicate
see-through knitted trousers. Gold sequin-embroidered shirts add
the glamour.
	   ''Trend'' is suitable for fashion lovers aged from 18 to 50.
From casual wear and knits to formal suits and evening dresses,
these outfits are light and comfortable.
	   Les Copains' lines for the young were even more interesting and
are likely to be a hit with Thai teens who can afford to spend a
bit more on outfits that last.
	   ''Miss Elleci'' is suited to both energetic teenagers and the
young career women. It is best described as chic and lively, with
the fine cut and tailoring evident in both casual and formal suits.
Also available in this line are T-shirts, dresses, jackets and
trousers.
	   For vacationing or just relaxing, Les Copains suggests ''Blue
Eagle'' -- T-shirts, shirts, trousers and other casuals that boast
a sportier look than ''Miss Elleci.'' The jeans, mostly worn with
sleeveless T-shirts and a casual jacket, received a well deserved
round of applause. The look is elegant but sporty, with colours
ranging from grey, beige, blue through brown and black and
exquisite embroidery on collars and pockets.
	   
</TEXT>
