<SLUG> BC-OAU-Libya </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pan-African body opposes blockade against Libya
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   OUAGADOUGOU, Burkina Faso (AP) _ Heads of state at a pan-African
summit Tuesday rejected a United Nations travel ban on Libya and
asked the United States and Britain to relax an economic blockade
against the North African country.
	   Organization of African Unity spokesman Pascal Gayama said the
29 heads of state at the summit in Burkina Faso's capital had
jointly appealed to the United States and Britain to allow
shipments of humanitarian and religious goods to Libya.
	   The economic blockade was imposed by the two Western powers
after Libya refused to extradite two suspects linked to the 1988
bombing of a Pan-Am Boeing 747 over Lockerbie, Scotland. The attack
killed 270 people.
	   The OAU further decided to support Ghadafi if he breaks the U.N.
flight ban imposed at the same time. Gayama said Libyan leader
Moammar Ghadafi would be welcome if he flew to Burkina Faso for the
summit's closing ceremonies Wednesday.
	   ``As far as the OAU is concerned, there is no travel ban,''
Gayama said. ``He is welcome.''
	   Speculation has persisted that Ghadafi would attend the summit
for the first time in more than a decade.
 &UR; (gam/ids)
</TEXT>
