<BODY>
<SLUG> BROADCASTING-MOVES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Big changes as broadcasting moves towards digital systems, NATION
</HEADLINE>
Big changes as broadcasting moves towards digital systems, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
   PONGPEN SUTHAROJASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SINGAPORE -- The broadcasting industry is in a period of
transition, shifting from analogue systems to digital, said IBM
Global Telecommunications and Media Industries vice president of
broadcasting, cable and sports William Moses.
	   He said that to cope with this change, IBM is offering the
broadcasting industry new digital technologies for production,
distribution and service provision to help them keep pace.
	   IBM has divided digital technologies for broadcasting into three
areas -- content management, content distribution and content
security.
	   Content management uses digital technology to help media and
entertainment executives store and quickly retrieve broadcasting
content in a digital format.
	   An IBM official said that with the IBM digital library and news
archive product, media staff can manage an entire broadcast
archive. With this system, they can quickly store, retrieve, view
and order broadcast content online through a computer system and
can view digital video images remotely, without having to
physically order numerous videotapes. This system will help
increase working efficiency and reduce the time involved in
spooling through videotapes searching for programme content.
	   CBS News now uses this application to manage its broadcast
material. The system helps CBS reduce production and inventory
management costs by increasing the efficiency of its archive
storage and retrieval system.
	   Moses said content distribution is another area which has been
transformed by digital technology. The Warner Brothers network
recently adopted a content distribution system to help expand its
coverage to smaller television sites. With this application,
broadcasters have a digital server to receive video content from a
variety of sources, store it digitally, rearrange the content and
provide multi-stream analogue and digital playback. The official
said the system allows Warner Brothers to manage, distribute and
insert local content and advertisements digitally for its cable
affiliates in more than 100 markets. The system also integrates the
entire broadcast process of sales, traffic, digital encoding,
content storage, data transmission, local insertion, account
reconciliation and billing.
	   Moses added that while the broadcasting industry is going
digital, copyright of their broadcasts is another big issue.
Recently, IBM's research lab in Tokyo succeeded in developing a new
video copy protection technology called Data Hiding. With Data
Hiding, copyright owners can protect their material against
unauthorised copying. The system is designed with special codes
embedded directly in a digital motion picture before distribution
occurs, just like the watermark embedded in a banknote. The special
code allows a digital receiving device to determine whether the
content is authorised for playback or copying. If not, it disables
the device from playing back, copying or both.
	   The official said when someone attempts to make a copy, special
circuits in video recording devices detect the codes to find out
whether the action is permitted by the copyright owners. If not,
the process is stopped. If an unauthorised copy is made, the
circuitry in DVD players detect the original code and prevents
playback.
	   Digital technology is taking the broadcasting industry to the
next level, Moses said. It will help broadcasting production become
more flexible and effective while providing more interesting
interactive services.
	   Broadcasters can create new broadcasting services and deliver
them interactively and digitally. Many new entertainment services
such as interactive television, pay TV, video-on-demand,
information services and home shopping could be provided through
the familiar television set, allowing people to choose programmes
or services whenever they want. 
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NATION all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
