<HEADLINE>
Exam high achievers rewarded, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Exam high achievers rewarded, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ELEVEN children of the Shah Alam Municipal Council's Recreation
Club members received an additional bonus for scoring good grades
in their UPSR, PMR and SPM examinations held last year.
	   They were each presented with an academic excellence award
certificate and a savings account from the MPSA Perwira Affin Bank
branch.
	   Council president Mohamad Adzib Mohd Isa presented the awards
during a presentation ceremony at the MPSA Recreational Hall
recently.
	   Also present were council deputy president Abdul Aziz Hussein
Sazally, councillor Datuk Bakar Abdul Hamid, MPSA Recreation Club
secretary Intanjuddin Ismail, Perwira Affin Bank general manager
Zainal Osman and other council and club members.
	   In his speech, Mohamad Adzib congratulated club members on their
the efforts taken to reward their children who have excelled
academically.
	   ``This award presentation is held to create awareness among the
young on the benefits of savings,'' he said.
	   ``This programme also acts as a motivation to the children in
the club members' family to do well in the forthcoming
examinations.''
	   The UPSR students who scored five As were Fadhilah Hanum Mohamad
Juri, Muhamad Zharif Amir Sharifudin, Siti Nurhafidah Adnan,
Khairul Azlan Abd Aziz and Zarina Abdul Ghani while both Mohd Hafiz
Zawawi and Nurul Faizah Salimi scored four As and one B.
	   PMR students Zaheera Abdul Ghani scored eight As and Mohd Za'im
Shaharudin scored six As and two Bs.
	   Meanwhile, two SPM students, one of them Mohamad Adzib's son,
Mohd Fariz, scored 10 As and the other, Nor Azrita Mohamed Zain,
scored five As with an aggregate of 10.
	   Mohd Fariz received the highest savings account totalling RM300
followed by Nor Azrita who received RM200. The others received
RM150, RM100 and RM75, respectively. Four students unable to
receive their awards were represented by their parents.
	   
</TEXT>
