<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Gerry Weber Open, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Becker loses at Gerry Weber Open; won't play Wimbledon
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; UPDATES, RECASTS thruout with Becker saying he won't play
Wimbledon, ADDS Byline.
 &UR; By ROY KAMMERER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HALLE, Germany (AP) _ Boris Becker Tuesday was beaten by fellow
German Hendrik Dreekmann in three erratic sets at the Gerry Weber
Open, then announced he won't play Wimbledon.
	   Becker fought off five match points, but handed the world No.
101 the first-round match on a double fault, 6-3, 5-7, 7-6 (11-9)
at the dlrs 875,000 grass court event.
	   ``A Wimbledon start would have made sense with a good
performance in Halle, but not with a first-round loss,'' said
Becker.
	   ``This way, the pressure of Wimbledon would be too much for
me,'' added Becker, a three-time champion of the grand slam event.
	   Becker, who is easing into retirement and has played just six
tournaments this year, had changed his mind several times after
announcing last year that his 14th Wimbledon was his last.
	   Many Germans believed it was a last chance to see their star
play, causing a morning run on tickets for his match. Hundreds were
turned away from the 11,400-seat center court.
	   Becker gave away the match with a double fault after two hours
and 18 minutes and was far from the form that made him a former
world No. 1 and a Wimbledon finalist seven times.
	   But the 30-year-old offered his fans, who cheered his every
move, plenty of entertainment. He blew a 4-0 lead in the final set
tie break, then warded off one match point after another.
	   Becker, now ranked 58th, displayed little of the coolness under
pressure that marked his prime, despite warding off two double
faults with powerful serves.
	   A double fault led to one match point, babying a sure overhead
winner cost Becker a second. Dreekmann also let several final
points slip away behind easy errors.
	   For Dreekman, once ranked 39th, the win was revenge for being
publicly dismissed by Becker as talented, but unmotivated.
	   ``Becker has said Wimbledon is his bedroom, but this was mine,''
said Dreekman.
	   Although five top 10 players are entered in the Wimbledon
tuneup, the day was dominated by the local German players.
	   Australia's Richard Fromberg upset no. 7 seed Nicolas Kiefer,
Germany, 2-6, 6-4, 6-4, while Tommy Haas beat Belgium's Filip
Dewulf, 6-3, 6-4.
	   The presence of Becker, perhaps the most idolized German, has so
overwhelmed the event that defending champion Yevgeny Kafelnikov
was surprised when he was questioned by a reporter.
	   The 1996 French Open champion and world No. 7 had barely
survived a three-set battle Monday with the Ukraine's Andrei
Medvedev.
	   ``Great, someone noticed I'm still in the tournament,''
Kafelnikov said. ``I thought nobody was aware of it.''
	   French Open finalist Carlos Moya and Alex Corretja are scheduled
to play later Tuesday.
	    &UR; (rk)	   
</TEXT>
