<SLUG> BC-OAU-Libya,0181 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pan-African body opposes blockade against Libya
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   OUAGADOUGOU, Burkina Faso (AP) _ Heads of state at a pan-African
summit Tuesday rejected a United Nations travel ban on Libya and
asked the United States and Britain to relax an economic blockade
against the North African country.
	   Organization of African Unity spokesman Pascal Gayama said the
29 heads of state at the summit in Burkina Faso's capital jointly
appealed to the United States and Britain to allow shipments of
humanitarian and religious goods to Libya.
	   The economic blockade was imposed after Libya refused to
extradite two suspects linked to the 1988 bombing of a Pan-Am
Boeing 747 over Lockerbie, Scotland, that killed 270 people.
	   The OAU further decided to support Libyan leader Moammar Ghadafi
if he broke the U.N. flight ban imposed at the same time. Gayama
said Ghadafi would be welcome if he flew to Burkina Faso for the
summit's closing ceremonies Wednesday.
	   Speculation has persisted that Ghadafi would attend the summit
for the first time in more than a decade. 	   
</TEXT>
