<HEADLINE>
IFCT approves loan for new plant of President Agri Trading, NATION
</HEADLINE>
IFCT approves loan for new plant of President Agri Trading, NATION &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NATION
   THAILAND
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   AS a way of supporting the export sector, the Industrial Finance
Corporation of Thailand (IFCT) said it had approved a long-term
loan of YEN 187.5 million, or about Bt60 million, to President Agri
Trading Co Ltd to set up a new factory.
	   The IFCT said the loan was sourced from the Export-Import Bank
of Japan and consists of funds which the IFCT has secured and
allocated to domestic industries in order to alleviate liquidity
tightness and assist in project expansion.
	   The business of President Agri emphasises quality selection in
rice sales for both domestic and overseas markets in a
joint-venture with the Chansakulporn family and President Rice
Products Plc.
	   President Agri's business consists of rice milling and sales
while President Rice Products manufactures instant food under the
''Mama'' brand name. The registered capital of President Agri
totals Bt120 million, of which paid-up capital amounts to Bt52.5
million.
	   The company's operational performance in 1997 resulted in income
of Bt1.5 billion and net profit of Bt25 million.
	   New identity for Asia Securities ASIA Securities Trading Plc
(AST) has changed its name to ABN AMRO Asia Securities Plc.
	   But the company's stock code listing on the Stock Exchange of
Thailand remains unchanged as AST.
	   In August 1997, ABN AMRO Asia Holdings Ltd acquired a 35.5-per
cent stake in AST through a public tender offer. In March of this
year, ABN AMRO Asia Investment Research Ltd closed its Thailand
representative office and transferred its staff to AST. According
to George Morgan, managing director of ABN AMRO Asia Securities
Plc, the name change represents the culmination of ABN AMRO's
strategy to integrate its Thai equities business with AST. It also
signifies ABN AMRO's strong commitment to its investment in AST and
a determination to support and develop AST's business.
	   TFAM enjoys successful sale of open-ended fund ONGOING economic
problems have not prevented Thai Farmers Asset Management Co (TFAM)
from enjoying a successful sale of its latest open-ended fund
called Ruang Kao Thanarat I.
	   TFAM said in a statement that the fund, worth Bt1 billion, had
been fully subscribed by May 25 to May 29. The fund marked the
highest sale of unit trusts which invest mainly in government
bonds.
	   The company's deputy managing director Poonpipat Angyureekul
said the fund was very attractive to the public because its planned
investment was well-suited given the current economic situation.
	   Managing director Dayana Bunnag noted that investment risks for
government or state enterprise bonds were relatively low because
they are fully guaranteed, both in principal and interest rates, by
the Finance Ministry.
	   GSB to 'bank for society' THE Government Savings Bank (GSB) has
announced a plan to launch a new project called ''Banking for
Society''.
	   A statement from the bank said the project aims to teach
participants the basics of how banks can help a community, as well
as the responsibility that banks have in society.
	   They will be given on-the-job training to design a project for
the bank. The training project will take 35 days and start on July
13.
	   GSB said applicants have to be under 35 years of age and should
have a bachelors degree with a grade point average of up to 2.5.
Good health and an interest in rural living standards are also
needed. Applications have to be submitted to the bank by Wednesday.
	   Finance Ministry to sell Esso stake by Sept 22 THE Finance
Ministry is expected to finish the sale of its 12.5-per-cent stake
in Esso (Thailand) Plc by Sept 22, according to a ministry source.
	   Krungthai Thanakij Plc, J F Thanakom Finance and Securities Co,
National Finance and Securities Plc and Nava Finance and Securities
Co have been appointed as the ministry's advisers for the planned
Esso share sales.
	   The four financial advisers will appoint four companies to
appraise the value of Esso shares for proposing to Esso's parent
firm Exxon Corp.
	   BOT appoints Ratanakorn THE Bank of Thailand Monday appointed
Ratanakorn Nimwattana, a senior attorney from the office of the
Thai Attorney General, assistant governor responsible for filing
charges against violators of laws governing financial institutions
and monetary policy.
	   Ratanakorn becomes the first central-bank outsider to hold the
rank of assistant governor in eight years. The appointment is part
of a broad reorganisation of the bank's hierarchy undertaken by BOT
governor M R Chatu Mongol Sonakul.
	   Top positions at the Bank of Thailand have generally gone to
officials spending entire careers at the central bank.
	   Meanwhile the Thai Bankers' Association officials will meet a
delegation of the Foreign Bankers Association on tomorrow to
discuss regulations on debt restructuring.
	   It's an ill wind ...
	   FIRST-QUARTER sales of medicine for relief from hyperacidity
have increased by 20 per cent because of the economic recession and
unemployment, according to phamarceutical firm Hoechst Marion
Roussel.
	   Many Thai people have obviously been hit by the economic
malaise, helping to boost the demand for the medicine, according to
the firm's marketing manager, Sakol Damrong Palasit.
	   He said the market was worth about Bt400 million per year with
annual growth of five per cent but sales in the first quarter had
risen 20 per cent from the same period last year.
	   S'pore delegation on its way THE Singapore Confederation of
Industries will lead a business mission to negotiate trades and
study opportunities in joint investment and trade cooperations with
Thai businessmen from June 21 to 24.
	   According to a statement from Thailand's Board of Investment,
the Singapore delegation will comprise executives from more than 20
trade and investment companies as well as financial institutions
that are looking to expand their production bases in Thailand.
	   The Industrial Estate Authority of Thailand will host a meeting
between the Singapore delegates and Thai businessmen at the Laem
Chabang Industrial Estate on June 23.
	   Three state firms face closure A COMMITTEE on state-enterprise
policy, chaired by Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi, has
reaffirmed that three old state enterprises will be shut down, the
Government Cold Storage Organisation, the Preserved Food
Organisation and the Textile Organisation.
	   Meanwhile the Glass Organisation and the Battery Organisation
are to be reorganised as joint ventures with the private sector.
	   
</TEXT>
