<HEADLINE>
BlueWave feels it is better placed for the rough ride, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
BlueWave feels it is better placed for the rough ride, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   JOHOR BARU, Sun. - The Grand BlueWave Hotel is confident of
weathering the economice storm better than others in the industry,
because it is different.
	   Partly owned by the Japan Asean Investment Company of Japan, it
is an all-suite hotel, reputedly the first in the country, targeted
mainly at long-staying guests.
	   At present, Japanese businessmen who stay for more than a year
have taken up about 20 suites, said general manager Fumio Okazaki.
	   The RM90 million hotel opened last year, has 184 apartment-like
guestrooms equipped with kitchenettes.
	   Okazaki said the hotel, which had about 60 per cent occupancy,
anticipated a slight drop this year, but it would be manageable.
	   Besides its all-suite concept which made the hotel relatively
easier to manage, Okazaki said steps had also been taken to reduce
costs.
	   ``For example, we have stopped importing food and have turned to
local supplies.''
	   In addition, the hotel's proximity to Singapore should help
cushion the effects of the slowdown.
	   ``Johor Baru is different from other parts of the country such
as Kuala Lumpur. We have the `Singapore factor' helping our food
and retail business.
	   ``Our restaurant business is doing all right. For example, we
were fully booked during the last Valentine Day,'' Okazaki said.
	   ``Overall, I am a bit optimistic that we will be able to
maintain and survive. Although we do not know if the worst is
here.''
	   Grand BlueWave is managed by Orix Hotels International
headquartered in Hong Kong and owned by Skyline Tower Sdn Bhd,
which is 50 per cent owned by Vikay Development Sdn Bhd. The other
shareholders are the JAIC and a local company.
	   
</TEXT>
