<SLUG> BC-Sports-Greece-Hang Gliding Deaths,0192 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two hang gliders killed during world cup competition
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ Two hang gliders were killed Tuesday
during the Hang Gliding World Cup taking place on Mount Kithairona,
about 50 kilometers (31 miles) northwest of Athens, the Greek
National Air Club said.
	   According to initial information, Michalis Theoharis, 52, and
Alexis Patarias, 25, had been flying for about three hours when
they accidentally entered a storm, said Christos Athanassopoulos,
the air club's spokesman.
	   The two Greeks apparently lost consciousness from the intense
cold in the sudden storm and crashed in the mountainous region.
Other athletes who also entered the storm managed to escape
unharmed, the spokesman added.
	   Weather conditions were good at the beginning of the day, the
air club said in an announcement, adding that it had asked experts
to investigate the exact causes of the accident.
	   Competitions were interrupted for the day. But the week-long
meet, which began Sunday with 103 athletes from 12 countries, will
continue to end as scheduled on June 14, Athanassopoulos said.
</TEXT>
