<SLUG> BC-Qatar-Spy Trial </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Qatari court acquits two convicted of spying
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DOHA, Qatar (AP) _ An appeals court Tuesday overturned the
conviction of two Qataris for spying and reduced the sentence of
another from 10 years in prison to three years.
	   The three-judge court acquitted Khamis Muftah al-Najrani, a
42-year-old army colonel who had been convicted and jailed for 10
years by another court in February for disclosing military secrets.
	   Also acquitted was Mohammed Majid Aman Eid, an army colonel who
was given a one-year prison term in February for failing to report
the crime and failure to prevent it. He never served jail time,
though, because he had already spent more than a year in custody.
	   The court reduced the prison term of Aman Majid Aman Eid, a
relative of Mohammed, from 10 years to three years.
	   The three men were part of a group of seven Qataris accused of
collecting and selling information to alleged plotters of a failed
coup in 1996. The other four were acquitted in February.
	   The emir, Sheik Hamad bin Khalifa Al Thani, ousted his father,
Sheik Khalifa, in a bloodless coup in 1995. The government has
suggested Sheik Khalifa, 65, was behind the coup attempt.
