<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Cell Phones </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Italy awards third mobile phone license to consortium
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ The government on Tuesday awarded Italy's third
mobile phone license to the state electric utility and French and
German phone companies.
	   The consortium of ENEL, Deutsche Telekom and France Telecom,
called Wind, beat out two other groups, led by British Telecom and
Bell Canada International, in the hugely lucrative cell phone
market.
	   Europe's largest market for mobiles is Italy, where there are
some 13.5 million mobile phone users. Some analysts say that market
will be worth about 18 trillion lire (dlrs 10.32 billion) by the
end of next year, and that the third operator can expect to hold
some 2 percent of it by then.
	   Recently privatized Telecom Italia has around 75 percent of the
Italian cell phone market, while Omnitel, controlled by Olivetti
SpA and Germany's Mannesmann AG, has the rest.
	   Wind is 51 percent owned by ENEL, although that stake will come
down when other Italian investors are brought in. Deutsche Telekom
and France Telecom split the other 49 percent.
	   Before the license was awarded, telecommunications minister
Antonio Maccanico told reporters that increased competition would
lead to lower prices and better service.
	   He declined to say whether there would be a fourth license
awarded before the end of the year, as some in the industry have
demanded. The government has only pledged to look into awarding a
fourth license.
	   (dj/djw)	   
</TEXT>
