<HEADLINE>
All systems in place for full scale operations, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
All systems in place for full scale operations, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MALACCA, Sun. - Deputy Transport Minister Datuk Wira Mohd Ali
Rustam said today all systems at the Kuala Lumpur International
Airport in Subang were in place for full commercial operations end
of this month.
	   ``There should be no technical hitches as everything is in
order. There are of course some minor hiccups but on the whole, the
airport is ready.
	   ``We do not anticipate any major problem for this
state-of-the-art airport to go into full-scale commercial
operations,'' Mohd Ali said when met today.
	   He said weaknesses, if any, would be overcome before the
Commonwealth Games in September.
	   ``We have about two months to identify weaknesses before the
start of this world-class event. This should give us ample time to
address the problems.''
	   Mohd Ali said the ongoing trials had also enabled the airport
management to gauge its operations performance and overcome
weaknesses.
	   The first flight trial at the airport was conducted last month
when 340 pilgrims on flight KT35 arrived at 2.25pm.
	   The airport was originally scheduled to begin operation in early
June but this was deferred due to several reasons, including the
recent forest fires near the airport.
	   The Transport Ministry has formed a special committee,
comprising KL International Airport Bhd Malaysia Airports Bhd,
Department of Civil Aviation and the ministry's top officials to
organise the ceremonial opening by the Yang di-Pertuan Agong on
June 27.
	   Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir Mohamad is expected to
deliver the keynote address at the ceremony.
	   Mohd Ali said 100 personnel would man KLIA's control tower.
	   Of this number, 76 are experienced staff and the rest new
recruits.
	   He said 40 control tower personnel underwent a two-week training
at Munich Airport, Germany, recently.
	   
</TEXT>
