<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Northern Ireland </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mowlam seeks police hunt for `sneaky' leaker of government secrets
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SHAWN POGATCHNIK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) _ Britain's Northern Ireland
Secretary Mo Mowlam on Tuesday asked detectives to try to identify
the government aides responsible for leaking sensitive, restricted
documents about peacemaking efforts.
	   ``Leaks are bad for government. It's damaging. We will make
every effort we can to find out who is responsible,'' said Mowlam,
who has had several confidential documents revealed since she
became Northern Ireland's governor in mid-1997.
	   The latest document, passed on Monday to Protestant lawmaker
Jeffrey Donaldson and the British Broadcasting Corp., detailed
conversations Mowlam had with Irish Foreign Minister David Andrews
and the IRA-allied Sinn Fein party about this month's formation of
commission to reform Northern Ireland's police force.
	   Andrews, who had privately complained to Mowlam about her
appointments to the commission, said she was being victimized by
civil servants opposed to the general direction of the Northern
Ireland peace process.
	   ``Sneaky little people in the Northern Ireland Office are not
going to obstruct us in the pursuit of what we all seek to achieve,
a permanent peace on the island of Ireland,'' Andrews said.
	   Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams called for British authorities to
identify the leakers and fire them.
	   ``Those who have leaked those documents are surely in breach of
their vocation, and need to be dealt with and need to be given
their notice,'' Adams said.
	   Also Tuesday, Ulster Unionist chief David Trimble, leader of
Northern Ireland's biggest pro-British Protestant party, launched
his campaign for seats in the province's new legislative Assembly,
the cornerstone of the Belfast peace agreement.
	   The April 10 agreement among eight parties, ratified by voters
in both parts of Ireland on May 22, specified a June 25 election
for the 108-seat Assembly. Its members are supposed to select a
multi-party administration, with Trimble as its most likely head.
	   Trimble urged Protestant voters to back him rather than
hard-liners opposed to the compromise package, which would include
Sinn Fein in the new government and give early paroles to Irish
Republican Army prisoners.
	   ``We must take the opportunity to move into a new era,'' Trimble
said at Belfast's glass-fronted Waterfront concert hall.
	   ``It is absolutely crucial that we elect members dedicated to
progress, not ones who will sit on the sidelines complaining about
everything,'' he said, referring to supporters of the Rev. Ian
Paisley, Trimble's most stubborn competitor for Protestant votes.
	   (sp-scl)
</TEXT>
