<HEADLINE>
White asparagus promotion, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
White asparagus promotion, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   DUBBED the Queen of Vegetables, the white asparagus is being
promoted at the California Grill Restaurant, JW Marriott Kuala
Lumpur.
	   The white asparagus, a delicacy that is highly sought after by
the world's discerning gourmets, is the pride of the Dutch province
of Limburg.
	   In conjuction with the promotion, which will be held till June
26, Dutch master chef Herman Van Ham, who has a vast experience in
preparing and promoting this speciality, also demonstrated his
spectacular creations.
	   Van Ham, who has spent 32 years at the De Hamert, has been
awarded the prestigious Michellin star for 27 consecutive years.
	   He created and introduced the white asparagus cocktail Prince
William Alexander using with chicken meat, orange and light curry
cream.
	   This creation has gained popularity and it is said that most
Dutch would have the cocktail served when they order meals.
	   According to Van Ham, asparagus is prepared the old fashioned
way and should be accompanied by melted butter, hard boiled eggs
and a flaky potato.
	   It can also be served with goose liver sauce with truffles in
salad with crab, shrimp or smoked salmon.
	   Van Ham said the edible part of the vegetable was the sprout
that grew out of the rootstock.
	   ``The sprouts grow in banked sandbeds to keep out the sunlight
so that the asparagus can stay nice and white. It prefers sandy
woodland soil and requires care,'' he explained.
	   ``The seeds alone are costly and no harvest is made until the
third year of cultivation.''
	   
</TEXT>
