w1620 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  HAVANA-HAVENsked     06-09 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> HAVANA-HAVEN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Havana Haven, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Havana Haven, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Magnolia S. SilvestreASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Larry J. Cruz (LJC) restaurant group is never at a loss for
new ideas.
	   This time, they wish to take their patrons to a very unique
destination Havana, Cuba. Cafe Havana is the newest restaurant/bar
to open in the revived Malate Scene.
	   The interior is done in that unique Tropical '50s style that is
so distinctly Cuban -- sunny colors of yellow and green with
elegant wicker chairs, huge wooden fans, and photos of old cars.
	   A special feature of the place is a room where one can purchase
and smoke cigars, named aptly enough as the Hemingway Room, the
author being Havana's most famous resident apart from Fidel Castro.
There is more Hemingway memorabilia at this cafe than Castro, who
nonetheless has a drink named after him -- the Fidel (P125) -- but
then, so does Hemingway, and his is named the Ernest Hemingway
Special (P95).
	   The refreshing Mojito (P85) -- a mix of Bacardi white rhum, soda
water, syrup, and crushed mint leaves on crushed ice -- could be
Cuba's national drink, if there is any. This writer also tried the
aptly named Periodista (P95), made of apricot brandy, Bacardi, and
lime. Of course, the list of drinks would not be complete without a
Banana Daiquiri.
	   The Hemingway Room offers authentic cigars from Havana (as
expected) along with the less notorious (no trade embargoes?)
Mexican, Honduran, nd Manila cigars. Not being a cigar connoisseur,
I chose to evaluate them by price (which I had ignorantly assumed
was by the box until someone more knowledgeable said it was per
cigar!). The most expensive ones on the list include the
Montecristo (P737) and the Punch Punch (P704). At the other end of
the spectrum is the affordable Belinda Coronas (P154), also Cuban.
But the appelatively interesting include the Manila Cigars with
names such as the Double Happiness Sublime (P319) and the Double
Happiness Ecstasy (P286), which sound as if they contain illegal
substances. And for those who can't get rid of the Centennial
fever, there's always the Rizal (P193).
	   Cuban cuisine shares the characteristics of many of its regional
neighbors; it is, in fact, described as a mixture of Spanish and
Carribean. Black beans, plantain bananas, yuca, and garlic are just
some of the common ingredients to be found in many of the dishes.
Banana chips replace the more traditional tortillas as an
appetizer.
	   Cafe Havana, aside from Cuban food, serves nuevo Latino cuisine
as well as an innovation of Spanish and American dishes. Their
pizzas, for instance, have ingredients like chorizo, black beans,
corn, olives, and quail eggs.
	   One of their bestsellers is the Carribean Salmon and Mango Mambo
in Black Rice (P295), an interesting dish which has squid ink. The
salmon is tender and the squid ink rice tastefully complements the
fish's delicate flavor.
	   The blackbean soup has a very distinct flavor which you may or
may not like. The Spareribs Habanera (P285) offers a unique twist
with guava, honey, and pepper glaze on the side.
	   Pleasing both to the eye and the palette is the Smokeless Cigar
(P150), dessert made of chocolate and served with a scoop of
vanilla ice cream on the side.
	   The night scene of Cafe Havana is very much alive because of the
presence of live rhythms during the weekend. Acoustic guitar and
conga drums will be playing Cuban Salsa.
	   Cafe Havana opened last June 3 with a very loud bang (that
fizzled when the crowd couldn't quite jive with the mood that the
affair was supposed to have had). The streets were closed for a
grand celebration, entitled El Carnaval Afrocubano, and there was
Afrocuban music, street dancing, and tropical drinks. The air
smelled of mint and tobacco.
	   There was a cool party crowd, composed mostly of Malate
night-scene revelers, cigar enthusiasts, and celebrities. Among
those who dropped in to join the festivities included all-smiles
Edu Manzano (whose fate as Makati vice mayor is still in limbo -
how are his ties with the American Embassy?); controvery-magnet
Ruffa Gutierrez (who is currently very busy with her
``Roof-A-Child'' Foundation); Ramon Jacinto (hey, thanks for the
free drinks!); noted actress Chin-Chin Gutierrez (resplendent
despite a simple get-up); former Bb. Pilipinas Charlene Gonzales
(who ballroom danced with an almost-violent frenzy during the
latter part of the revelries); singer/public relations officer
Joanne Lorenzana; Indio I band members; writers Danton Remoto and
Joyce Fernandez; chic broadcast journalist Ces Drilon; television
host Franco Laurel (the night may have been too humid for this poor
guy; he was really perspiring); the VIP dancers with their high
priestess Maribeth Bichara; choreographer Eric Edralin; PR whiz kid
Tim Yap and his cohorts; Warp's Ronald Pasyon; scene-stealing,
towering beauty Troy (who almost won the limbo rock contest by
sheer crowd popularity alone); several commercial and ramp models;
businessmen; and (huffing and puffing) expatriates.
	   Acrobats (who were quite short that we had to strain getting a
look at their stunts since everyone in front was standing) in their
colorful, butterfly-like suits, jugglers, and dancers in exotic
Carribean costumes entertained guests - or, so it seemed. (After
they performed, we were like, ``So that was it?'') The main program
of the evening's celebration ended quite abruptly - at around 11
p.m. - but quite a number extended their tropical night in early
June mixing with Che Guevarra and Fidel Castro - or, at least,
people who dressed and smoked like them.
	   [Cafe Havana is located on Remedios St. corner Adriatico where
Bistro Remedios, which has moved next door, used to be located.]

</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
