<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MED-Hypertension Study, HFR,0771 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Study: Drastically lowering blood pressure cuts heart attack risk
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Hold for release at 0200 GMT. Time set by source. &QL; 
 &UR; By JENIFER CHAO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) _ By aiming for a blood pressure
even lower than what doctors traditionally prescribe, hypertension
patients can significantly reduce their risk of heart attack, a
landmark new study reported Wednesday.
	   The five-year international study, led by the University of
Michigan at Ann Arbor, was conducted to help doctors determine just
how low they need to go in treating patients with high blood
pressure and reducing cardiovascular diseases and deaths.
	   Among diabetics, the results were even more promising _
researchers said drastically lowering their blood pressure can cut
in half their risk of major cardiovascular trouble.
	   ``What we've learned is that lowering blood pressure just to the
point where it isn't `high' isn't enough,'' said Dr. Kenneth
Jamerson, associate professor of internal medicine at the
University of Michigan.
	   Doctors estimate 20 percent of people worldwide suffer from the
condition.
	   Results from the study, which involved 18,790 patients ages
50-80 in 26 countries, were being presented at the annual meeting
in Amsterdam of the International Society of Hypertension. The
study was funded by U.S.-Swedish pharmaceutical company Astra
Merck.
	   Researchers said that by lowering patients' diastolic blood
pressure _ the second and smaller number in blood pressure readings
_ to a level even lower than what doctors have been aiming for can
significantly reduce the risk of heart attack.
	   In the past, doctors have generally accepted a diastolic
pressure of 90 as the limit for hypertensive patients. The study
suggests doctors could aim as low as 80.
	   ``People were worried that by reducing blood pressure too much,
there might be adverse effects,'' said Dr. John Hall, chairman of
the American Heart Association's Council on High Blood Pressure
Research. He was not involved in the research.
	   Some doctors feared that pushing blood pressure further could
slow the blood supply to the heart and brain and perhaps even cause
heart attacks or strokes, said Dag Elmseldt, a Swedish professor on
the executive committee of the study.
	   But the study concludes that lowering patients' diastolic blood
pressure further is safe. It found that patients who cut their
diastolic pressure from 105 to 83 can reduce the incidence of heart
attack by 37 percent.
	   Blood pressure is generally considered healthy if the systolic
level _ which measures the pressure of the blood flow when the
heart beats _ is 120 and the diastolic level _ the pressure between
heart beats _ is 80.
	   The study did not specifically examine systolic blood pressure.
Some experts say the systolic level is at least as important, if
not more so, in determining risk of cardiovascular disease.
	   During the study, patients were assigned to diastolic pressure
targets of 80, 85 and 90. Investigators then followed their
progress to see how many strokes, heart attacks or similar deaths
occurred in each group.
	   Among patients whose diastolic pressure was reduced to 90, there
were 84 cases of heart attack, while there were 64 heart attacks
among those in the 85-level group and 61 in the 80-level group.
	   The results, if proven accurate, should encourage doctors to be
even more strict in managing patients' blood pressure, said Dr.
Peter de Leeuw, a hypertension specialist at the University of
Maastricht in the Netherlands.
	   ``We always want to reduce patients' blood pressure as much as
possible, but they don't always reach their goals and they are not
pressured hard enough,'' said De Leeuw, who did not participate in
the study.
	   Getting people's blood pressure to around 80 ``is ambitious, but
not impossible,'' he said.
	   During the study, patients received felodipine, better known as
Plendil, and other blood pressure medications to reach their target
blood pressure level. The therapy is called hypertension optimal
treatment. Plendil is produced by Astra Merck.
	   The study included 1,501 patients with diabetes and found that
the risk of a major cardiovascular incident was halved for those
who reduced their blood pressure to 80.
	   The American Heart Association said the results confirmed what
it has often said: Management of high blood pressure can save
lives.
	   While drug therapy can lower blood pressure, the association
noted that many patients can reduce it through diet, exercise and
restricted salt intake. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-MED-Hypertension Study, HFR; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
