	   Tax Reform Act of 1997
	   Revenue Memorandum Circular 17-98
	   During the latter part of April 1998, a fellow practitioner,
Benjamin S. of Caloocan, called me to inquire about the new
deadline set under the CTRP for the filing of first-quarter income
tax returns for self-employed people and professionals.
	   Under the old tax law, the deadline for filing was every May 15.
This deadline was changed under the new tax law to April 15.
	   Precisely because of poor dissemination of information regarding
the measure, many self-employed and professionals learned about the
deadline only on April 15, 1998, when they filed their 1997 Annual
Income Tax Return (ITR). You will remember that this date was also
the deadline for the filing of the 1997 annual return.
	   Due to many complaint-letters sent to the BIR, particularly on
concerns of taxpayers about the imposition of penalties and
interests, the BIR issued Revenue Memorandum Circular (RMC) 17-98
dated May 15, 1998.
	   RMC 17-98 provides for the waiver of penalties and interest
payments for self-employed individuals and professionals who had
failed to submit their first-quarter ITR for 1998 by April 15,
1998, provided they filed their returns on or before May 15, 1998,
the deadline under the old tax law.
	   The professionals and self-employed welcome the BIR-issued RMC.
Even then, I personally think that the matter of the date should be
studied carefully. Think about it this way. If an accountant
finished recording and closing the books for 1998 just in time for
the filing of the 1998 annual income tax return on April 15, 1999,
how on earth could he finish recording for the first quarter of
1999 also on the same date? Remember that there are quite some
adjustments to be done.
	   Revenue Memorandum Circular 14-98 -- BREAKER Just in passing,
the BIR also issued RMC 14-98, dated April 21, 1998, clarifying the
deadlines for the filing of the quarterly value-added and
percentage tax returns within 25 days following the close of each
taxable quarter.
	   Revenue Memorandum Circular 21-98 -- BREAKER Dated May 25, 1998,
RMC 21-98 extends the grace period for compliance with Revenue
Regulations (RR) 2-98 to May 15, 1998.
	   RR 2-98, dated April 17, 1998, about 74 pages of short bond
paper, is a partial implementation of the rules and regulations of
the CTRP. It confined its coverage, however, only to the
withholding tax provisions of the said Code.
	   Revenue Regulations 2-98 -- BREAKER The important provision of
this RR is the determination of who is required to deduct and
withhold taxes, and what nature or type of payments are subject to
withholding tax.
	   The time of withholding is also vital. Thus, the obligation to
deduct arises at the time the income is paid or payable, whichever
comes first.
	   This might be a lot of work, coordination, and monitoring, as
there are departmental billings which are already due for payment,
but somehow, the processing of the payments has not been made or
forwarded to the accounting department due to lack of, or
questionable, support documents. Sometimes, there are instances
where the Company still does not know the amount of the final bill,
as is the case when the contract is on a per-hour billing basis.
	   The time of filing and payment is still set at the 10th of each
month, except for the month of December, for which the deadline
shall be on Jan.
	   25.
	   In cases of employees whose income does not exceed the statutory
minimum wage or P5,000 monthly, employers are not required to
withhold any monthly taxes.
	   An employee whose annual income will not exceed P60,000, is
given two options - either pay his annual income tax himself (thus
his monthly salary will not be subjected to withholding taxes), or
request that his employer continue to withhold the monthly taxes
(thus he is not required to file any annual income tax ). This is a
new provision. Under the old law, all employers were mandated to
withhold taxes on behalf of their employees, who were given no
options at all.
	   
</TEXT>
