<HEADLINE>
Need to address with determination social ills besetting youths, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Need to address with determination social ills besetting youths, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Shukor RahmanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THERE seems to be an endless string of problems besetting our
youth, and to a certain extent our students, in the last few years.
	   Besides drug addiction, there are social ills such as loafing,
bohsia, illegal motorcycle racing, pre-marital sex, HIV/AIDS,
prostitution, abandoning of newborns, pornography, vandalism and
hooliganism.
	   Discipline has also taken a battering in schools. A group of
Kedah secondary and matriculation teachers who attended a workshop
recently called for tough punishment to check gangsterism in
schools as they felt that mere counselling would be ineffective.
	   In Johor Baru last month, a Form Five male student manhandled
and kicked a woman teacher in the groin when she questioned him for
coming late to school.
	   In Penang, gang fights among students in schools are not only
rampant among boys but also among girls. In April a schoolgirl in
Georgetown, who is believed to be a gang leader, threatened her
teacher with a knife after being reprimanded for being inattentive
in class.
	   Deputy Education Minister Datuk Dr Fong Chan Onn said the
ministry had instructed its State departments to work closely with
the police in curbing gangsterism among students.
	   He said police help was necessary as the problem of
student-gangsterism was linked with ``outside elements''. Many of
these students, he said, frequented entertainment outlets like
snooker centres or nightclubs and are influenced by gangs
controlling these places.
	   Acts of misconduct include students beating up teachers,
fighting, vandalism, smoking, truancy, sexual acts, theft,
extortion and involvement with drugs.
	   National Unity and Social Development Minister Datin Paduka
Zaleha Ismail said children as young as nine years old were getting
involved in house-breaking and other offences such as theft and
gambling.
	   Between 1990 and 1996, an average of 4,000 juvenile delinquents
a year were sent for rehabilitation and development. In 1996, a
total of 4,045 boys and 166 girls between the ages of 13 and 16
were charged in the Juvenile Court for various offences and found
guilty under the Juvenile Act 1947.
	   Zaleha said lack of parental supervision contributed to the rise
in juvenile cases. There have also been cases of girls as young as
12 being forced into prostitution.
	   Deputy Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim said the
Government was worried over serious social problems especially
among Malay youths. He said Malay youths made up 70 per cent of the
200,000 drug addicts while most of those affected by other social
problems are also Malays.
	   According to the National Narcotics Agency, 30 new addicts are
detected each day and more than 10,000 addicts are undergoing
rehabilitation at 27 rehabilitation centres (Pusat Serenti)
nationwide.
	   Many may still remember the furore caused by the circulation of
a videotape showing two youngsters having sex at Kompleks Peruda in
Alor Star in December 1996.
	   In early April this year Kedah police arrested 15 youths
including five girls at a house in Lorong Bayam, Alor Star. The
house was believed to be used for sex orgies and drug abuse
sessions.
	   ``The fact that 2,000 used and unused condoms were seized at
least showed that the culprits believed in safe sex,'' said a local
wag.
	   Less than a week later Kedah police picked up six teenagers -
five boys aged between 18 and 19 and a 15-year-old girl - who were
engaged in group sex at a rented house in Lorong Keriang, Alor
Star, about 4am.
	   Official figures show that the majority of those infected with
the HIV virus in Kedah are between the ages of 15 and 30.
	   Alarmed at the increase in such social ills, the State
Government has directed the State youth and sports department to
set up youth associations in every kampung, and Menteri Besar Tan
Sri Sanusi Junid has asked police to pick up youths found loitering
at shopping complexes in Alor Star to be sent to pick up skills in
canoeing.
	   ``Maybe this is a good way of making use of their time. The
proposal is to help tackle social ills in the State which normally
starts with loafing,'' he said.
	   Penang antique dealer Mohamad Mastan Abdul Rahman, 80, who had a
strict upbringing, described today's youngsters as ``birds leaving
their cages''.
	   ``The old ways of instilling discipline will no longer work in
the present situation and new solutions will have to be found,'' he
said.
	   Trader Mohamad Fadzil Kadir Shah, 36, of Air Itam in Penang,
said the easy availability of hard-core pornographic video tapes
had corrupted the minds of the young.
	   ``Unscrupulous video tape dealers are just out to make a fast
buck and will not think twice about selling pornographic tapes to
underaged schoolchildren,'' he said.
	   Umno Kampung Manggis deputy leader Ramlan Raji welcomed the
tougher enforcement on illegal motorcycle racers and also called
for harsher measures against drug pushers and dealers of
pornographic material.
	   ``Everyone knows that the source of pornographic tapes are the
video tape dealers. Schoolchildren often pool their pocket money to
buy such tapes.
	   Writer Kassim Ahmad called on the authorities to ensure that
adequate library and recreational facilities were provided at
highrise flats to encourage youngsters to spend their time nearer
home instead of loitering at shopping malls.
	   Consumers Association of Penang president S.M. Mohamad Idris
said perhaps the single biggest loss he could see emerging in
modern Malaysia was the weakening of the family institution where
both parents were now going out to work.
	   ``The extended family system which used to provide good support
is also disappearing. If both parents are out working, who brings
up the children?''
	   Idris supported the call to institute compulsory national
service which he said should be constructive and based on
developing and instilling a sense of commitment to society.
	   As MCA president Datuk Seri Dr Ling Liong Sik said: ``If a
nation cannot control social decay, it will lose control of its
economic power. If we want our country to progress we must face our
moral and social ills and find solutions.''
	   
</TEXT>
