<HEADLINE>
Businessman Seeks TRO Vs. Retaking of Bus Company, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Businessman Seeks TRO Vs. Retaking of Bus Company, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Rodel A. AlzonaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Continuing his battle for control over Batangas Laguna-Tayabas
Bus Co. Inc.
	   (BLTB), BMB Property Holdings Inc. owner Benjamin Bitanga
yesterday asked the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) to
stop the Potenciano family from running the bus firm.
	   In an 11-page petition for a temporary restraining order (TRO)
before the SEC, Bitanga said the Potenciano family had
misrepresented themselves as owners of the company, claiming the
stockholders meeting held last May 19 was ``null and void.''
	   During the said stockholders meeting, the Potenciano family
reclaimed the 47.90% shares supposedly sold to Bitanga and secured
control of the BLTB.
	   ``There was absolutely no quorum during the scheduled meeting
since BMB, the shareholder owning the majority 50.26% of the total
outstanding shares of stock of BLTB had not been not represented,''
the businessman said.
	   The petition stated that only Bitanga could have legally
presided and convened the annual stockholders meeting.
	   ``There could be no one else because no vice chair had been duly
elected and the BLTB board of directors had not designated anyone
else to preside,'' the petition said.
	   Bitanga argued that the ``illegal misrepresentation of the
Potenciano family to BLTB employees, creditors, stockholders and to
the general public will cause irreparable damage and ruin the bus
firm.''
	   Currently, BLTB owes Metropolitan Bank and Trust Co., Allied
Bank, Solid Bank, Bank of Commerce and several other financing
firms some P1.3 billion.
	   As this developed, Lorna Potenciano Navarro, chief financial
officer of BLTB, filed an estafa case against Bitanga for allegedly
issuing checks amounting to P33.28 million without supporting
invoices.
	   Among those being questioned were the P20-million representation
expenses by Bitanga; P7.45 million for payment-lease of BLTB's
Sucat property; P2.35 million for the Sucat warehouse; and another
P3.48 million as advance lease of the Sucat property.
	   The Potencianos also claimed that last month's stockholders
meeting was legal as Bitanga was not able to abide by the
memorandum of agreement (MOA) signed by the two parties on the
supposed transfer of 47.90% of BLTB to Bitanga.
	   Currently there are two different claims with both sides
accusing each other usurping the assets of the company.
	   Bitanga claimed the Potenciano family had forcibly taken over
the properties and operations of BLTB.
	   The Potencianos, on the other hand, claimed that Bitanga used
BLTB as a ``cash cow'' as it gave him at least P2 million a day
since December last year.
	   The BLTB minority shareholders control 14% of the company and
both the Potencianos and Bitanga have claimed their support.
	   Bitanga said minority shareholders led by Delfin Yorro had given
their full support to his group, while the Potenciano family
claimed that Yorro talked to them and denied that he had sided with
Bitanga.
	   In a statement, Bitanga said Dolores Potenciano had sold to BMB
the entire holdings of the Potenciano family, representing 47.98%
of the bus company's stocks and that the sale was perfected through
a Deed of Absolute Sale executed on Oct. 28, 1997.
	   He pointed out that Potenciano had even issued a Declaration of
Trust, acknowledging the actual and beneficial ownership of the
shares in question by BMB and summarily waived her right, title,
and interests to the said shares of stocks.
	   Bitanga said Potenciano cannot just rescind a perfected Deed of
Absolute Sale without due process, especially after money has
changed hands as he claimed that Potenciano herself received some
P11 million which was part of the P34,743,364 which was to be
remitted by BMB to Allied Bank to retire some of BLTB's outstanding
debts.
	   He said that BLTB was wallowing in huge financial losses with
debts reaching more than P1 billion at the time BMB was invited to
invest in the bus company.
	   Bitanga said he saw a potential to rehabilitate what was once
the leading passenger bus company in the country through a
restructuring of the firm's financial position and an aggressive
refleeting program to replace the company's dilapidated buses.
	   He said that the credit worthiness of BLTB was restored after
BMB took over the management of the company, adding that Columbian
Motors Corp. had agreed to deliver an initial batch of 30
air-conditioned buses merely on the guaranty of BMB.
	   
</TEXT>
