	   IPOH, Sun. - The three DAP leaders who were suspended and
removed from their posts last Wednesday said they had not objected
to the ``Save Lim Guan Eng'' campaign and had attended several
meetings of the campaign in the Federal Territory.
	   At a joint Press conference today they said they wanted to go on
record on the matter.
	   Liew Ah Kim who was suspended as party vice-chairman said: ``It
is incorrect of (party secretary-general Lim) Kit Siang to accuse
us of sabotaging the campaign and there is no basis for his
allegations.''
	   He said Wee Choo Keong who was removed as national publicity
secretary had openly asked the people of Tangkak, Johor, to support
Guan Eng and fight for justice.
	   Liew, who acted as spokesman for Wee and Fung Ket Wing who was
suspended as treasurer, said the party leaders, including chairman
Dr Chen Man Hin and Kit Siang were confusing members more by
issuing contradicting and misleading statements over their case.
	   ``Their statements create confusion not only for us but also
party members,''he said.
	   The action taken against the three party stalwarts based on
reports by Perak and Malacca DAP, was said to be for ``undermining
party morale, creating confusion, disharmony and disunity among
members.''
	   Despite their case pending an inquiry, the three leaders were
invited to attend a party gathering organised by the Perak DAP in
Manjung last night where they also spoke.
	   The gathering was organised a month ago and were attended by
several national party leaders.
	   Expressing fear of a biased inquiry by the party diciplinary
committee, Liew, Fung and Wee reiterated their request to be
investigated by an independent and impartial committee.
	   ``We demand for an independant and impartial committee to
investigate the allegations,'' he said.
	   ``If we are guilty as alleged by Kit Siang after a fair and
impartial hearing, we are prepared to face the consequences.''
	   
