<HEADLINE>
Israel agrees to give Palestinians two ports, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Israel agrees to give Palestinians two ports, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Israel and the European Union are holding secret talks with
Israel making substantial concessions to the Palestinian authority,
Newsweek International reports in its latest edition. The magazine
without citing sources said Israel had agreed to give Palestinians
a seaport and a working airport to prevent the imposition of EU
sanctions on products manufactured in Jewish settlements. Israel
has reacted with outrage at the European Commission's
recommendation last month that products made in Jewish settlements
in the occupied West Bank Gaza Strip and Golan Heights be denied
tariff benefits. Newsweek says Europe is Israel's biggest market
accounting for more than one third of the Jewish state's 15.7
billion dollars in annual exports.
	   Nearly all the exports are duty free. The US Ambassador to
Israel hosted surprise talks on Sunday between senior Israeli and
Palestinian peace negotiators, Israeli political sources said. The
meeting at the Ambassador Edwrd Walker's home near Tel Aviv focused
on the opening of an airport and industrial zone in Gaza, issues
auxiliary to the handover of more West Bank land to the
Palestinians under interim peace deals, the sources said. The talks
between Israeli Cabinet Secretary Dany Naveh and the Palestinians
Saeb Erekat coincided with media speculation that a deal on further
Israeli troop withdrawal in the West Bank an accord that would
break a 15-month deadlock was near.
	   Naveh and Erekat last met for discussions on the opening of a
Palestinian airport in Gaza and other so-called.Walker said last
week that Washington would decide within days rather than weeks
--whether to press ahead with its Middle East peace initiative. In
remarks to reporters earlier in the day, Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu played down speculation that he was on the verge
of ceding land. We are working towards reaching an agreement. We
are not there yet, Netanyahu said, apparently hoping to ease ferris
of some right wing cabinet members. Invoking biblical names for the
West Bank a statement said he told his cabinet that the territory
of Judea and Samaria is no more dear to anyone than to him and
(Jewish) settlement is no more dear to anyone than it is to him...
Ultra Nationalists in Netanyahu's coalition have threatened to
topple the Israeli leader should be go through with plans to give
Palestinians self rule in the West Bank in keeping with Israeli
peace promises starting in 1993.
	   More than 150,000 Israelis live in Jewish settlements scattered
among more than 1.5 million Palestinians in the West Bank captured
by Israel from Jordan in the 1967 Middle East war. The Israeli
Cabinet statement described negotiations as being at a delicate
stage. The Prime Minster said he could not say we are on the verge
of an agreement, it said. In Jerusalem posters depicting Netanyahu
wearing an Arab scarf under the slogan ``the liar'' appeared on
Sunday, recalling a hate campaign that preceded the 1995 killing of
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin. A Jew shot Rabin dead in
November 1995 to try to stop him from carrying out land-for-peace
deals with Palestinians.
	   Israel's Haaretz newspaper said last week an US draft proposal
envisaged a three-stage Israeli handover of a further 13 per cent
of West Bank land to Palestinians over 12 weeks linked to a
Palestinian security clampodown.Netanyahu has rejected the US
proposals on security grounds. Palestinian President Yasser Arafat
has accepted them. Public security minister Avigdor Kehalani, head
of Israel's Centrist Third Way party was due to meet US peace envoy
Denis Ross in New York on Monday for talks coordinated with
Netanyahu Kahalani's office said.
	   
</TEXT>
