<HEADLINE>
Futures: Bargain buying on the cards, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Futures: Bargain buying on the cards, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   RECENTLY, Bank Negara Malaysia announced that in the first
quarter of 1998, Malaysia's Gross Domestic Product contracted by
1.8 per cent.
	   This is the first quarterly contraction the country has
experienced since the 1985 recession, which was 13 years ago.
	   Although economists and analysts braced for a bad GDP figure, a
1.8 per cent contraction was beyond expectations.
	   Upon the release of this news, the ringgit slipped against the
US dollar in early trading last Monday.
	   The futures began the week on a weaker note, reacting to the
bearish news released by BNM, as well as a weaker ringgit.
	   Against this backdrop, the steep decline in the regional
markets, sparked off by the declining Japanese yen also spooked
players.
	   Amidst this, BNM issued a statement on interest rates policy
late on Monday afternoon.
	   BNMasaid interest rates will remain at current levels to defend
the currency and assist the economic and financial recovery.
	   This announcement was well received by investors. In addition,
the Deputy Prime Minister also announced details of the Asset
Management Company.
	   Investors bought futures in anticipation of the announcement,
resulting in the futures staging a mild recovery in mid-week.
	   However, when the AMC details were announced by the Deputy Prime
Minister, the market gave up most of its gains as the announcement
did not meet the high investor expectations.
	   The selling activity continued, resulting in the futures
finishing the week below the 500.0 level.
	   The June futures ended at 499.5, down 31.5 index points from
Friday's close, with a total of 14,638 contracts traded.
	   The July futures traded 1845 contracts to finish at 492.5. In
addition, the September futures traded 5 contracts to finish at
495.0.
	   The December futures were not traded.
	   The underlying composite index ended at 505.05, down 33.19 index
points from Friday's close.
	   Due to the considerable decline in the futures over the course
of trading last week, we do not rule out the possibility of some
bargain buying this week.
	   
</TEXT>
