<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Gerry Weber Open, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Becker loses at Gerry Weber Open; won't play Wimbledon
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: UPDATES with Moya winning, Corretja losing &QL; 
 &UR; By ROY KAMMERER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HALLE, Germany (AP) _ Boris Becker was beaten by fellow German
Hendrik Dreekmann in three erratic sets Tuesday at the Gerry Weber
Open, then announced he won't play Wimbledon.
	   Becker fought off five match points, but handed the world No.
101 the match with a double fault, 6-3, 5-7, 7-6 (11-9) at the dlrs
875,000 grass court event.
	   ``A Wimbledon start would have made sense with a good
performance in Halle, but not with a first-round loss,'' said
Becker.
	   ``This way, the pressure would be too much for me,'' added
Becker, a three-time Wimbledon champion.
	   Becker, who is easing into retirement and has played just six
tournaments this year, had changed his mind several times after
announcing last year that his 14th Wimbledon was his final one.
	   In his first match since winning the French Open, Spain's Carlos
Moya coasted past France's Guillaume Raoux, 6-4, 6-4.
	   But the man he beat in the Roland Garros final, fellow Spaniard
Alex Corretja, was ousted by another Frenchman, Nicolas Escude,
6-2, 7-5.
	   With many Germans believing it was a last chance to see Becker
play, there was a morning run on tickets for his match. Hundreds
were turned away from the 11,400-seat center court.
	   Becker fought for two hours and 18 minutes against Dreekmann,
but was far from the form that made him a former world No. 1 and a
Wimbledon finalist seven times.
	   But the 30-year-old offered his fans, cheering his every move
wildly, plenty of entertainment. He blew a 4-0 lead in the final
set tie break, then warded off one match point after another.
	   Becker, now ranked 58th, displayed little of the coolness under
pressure that marked his prime, despite warding off two match
points with powerful serves.
	   A double fault led to one match point, babying a sure overhead
winner cost Becker a second. Dreekmann also let several final
points slip away behind easy errors.
	   For Dreekman, once ranked 39th, the win was revenge for being
publicly dismissed by Becker as talented, but unmotivated.
	   ``Becker has said Wimbledon is his bedroom, but this was mine,''
said Dreekman.
	   Although five top 10 players are entered in the Wimbledon
tuneup, the day was dominated by the local German players.
	   Australia's Richard Fromberg upset no. 7 seed Nicolas Kiefer,
Germany, 2-6, 6-4, 6-4, while Tommy Haas beat Belgium's Filip
Dewulf, 6-3, 6-4.
	   The presence of Becker, perhaps the most idolized personality in
his homeland, has so overwhelmed the event that defending champion
Yevgeny Kafelnikov was surprised to be questioned by a reporter.
	   The 1996 French Open champion and world No. 7 Russian had just
survived a three-set battle Monday with the Ukraine's Andrei
Medvedev.
	   ``Great, someone noticed I'm still in the tournament,''
Kafelnikov said. ``I thought nobody was aware of it.''
	    &UR; (rk) 	   
</TEXT>
