<SLUG> EXEC-SAYS-INDUSTRY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Exec Says Industry Too Crowded for Small Banks, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Exec Says Industry Too Crowded for Small Banks, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Arvin P. PanesASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The financial industry is now too ``overcrowded'' to accommodate
the operations of small-scale banks, according to a foreign banker.
	   In a press briefing yesterday, Hongkong and Shanghai Bank Deputy
Chief Executive Officer Paul J. Lawrence noted that the stiff
rivalry among commercial banks have displaced smaller thrift banks.
	   ``There are a lot of big banks competing for the market and this
overcrowds the smaller banks,'' Lawrence said.
	   Currently, there are 55 commercial banks and 800 thrift banks
nationwide.
	   Earlier, investment houses had predicted that thrift banks would
likely be the first casualties of the regional crisis given their
limited resources.
	   The prediction is now seemingly an accurate one after the
Monetary Board, the policy-making body of the Bangko Sentral ng
Pilipinas (BSP), ordered the closure of Commonwealth Savings Bank
due to insolvency last Friday.
	   Richmond Savings Bank and Unified Savings Bank were also
reported to be in financial trouble. Aklan Savings Bank was also
shut down secondary to bankruptcy while Orient Commercial Banking
Corp. which was formerly a thrift bank is still on a holiday up to
now.
	   Meanwhile, Lawrence said Hongkong Bank has yet to find an
investment-worthy financial institution which could become its
subsidiary.
	   Hongkong Bank has applied for a universal bank license with the
BSP but was deferred after the economic crunch took place in the
middle of last year.
	   One major focus of Hongkong Bank, should the BSP grant its
petition, would be the acquisition of a local bank.
	   ``We can go into commercial or retail banking which would be
just like any other business decision. The granting of the license
just raises our options but so far, we have not seen one (bank)
that is attractive,''
	   Lawrence said. 
</TEXT>
