<SLUG> TRANSPARENCY-MUST-REAL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Transparency must be real, not rhetorical, says Umno Youth chief, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Transparency must be real, not rhetorical, says Umno Youth chief, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sun. - Umno Youth chief Datuk Ahmad Zahid Hamidi
today described as ``nepotism'' the practice of big corporations
sub-contracting privatisation projects to related companies or
firms in which they had a personal interest.
	   He said evidence of such practice was available from the
statistics of companies getting such contracts.
	   Asked if the companies referred to were those held by leaders,
he said: ``It depends, but we believe that transparency should
prevail at all times.
	   ``We do not want political connection to be used. We must show
that we are truly transparent in our actions, not only in the
rhetorical sense when implementing a policy.''
	   Ahmad Zahid was speaking to reporters after a congress on
``Strengthening the National Economy'' organised by the Umno Youth
at the Putra World Trade Centre.
	   He said it would be difficult to maintain the nation's economic
and political stability if the interests of the people were
ignored.
	   ``If given an opportunity to profitable business ventures, I
believe even an ordinary Bumiputera entrepreneur can play a
similar, if not better role.
	   ``Like their bigger counterparts, I am sure they will not only
pay their corporate tax, but also not forget their social
obligation like tithe and charity to the less fortunate.''
	   An all-round effort should be made to prevent favourtism.
	   ``By letting such situations continue the ill-practice will
simply mean that we have to sideline justice.
	   ``When we speak of equality, we have to think of, for example,
contractors at the lower level.
	   ``By right, they should be given priority. This is simply
because when a big construction firm faces financial hardship, its
smaller counterparts are likely to be shut down first''.
	   In his speech, Ahmad Zahid said positive elements like a new
management code was needed to fight corruption, nepotism and abuse
of power.
	   ``The current economic hardship is the best period for
self-criticism and re-evaluation of the strength and weaknesses of
our system.''
	   ``The question of wealth distribution can easily trigger
dissatisfaction among the people.
	   ``We are not asking for the Bumiputera entrepreneurs to be
spoon-fed with all sorts of assistance, but only suggesting they
should be given opportunities and priority,'' he added.
	   At the half-day congress which was opened by Ahmad Zahid, a
proposed blueprint titled ``Strategies for the Strengthening of the
National Economy'' was presented by the movement's Economic Council
chairman Dr Abdul Rahim Mohd Ghouse.
	   This was followed by a panel discussion by prominent leaders and
economic experts which included Johor Menteri Besar Datuk Abdul
Ghani Othman, the Bumiputera Manufacturers Association chairman and
MP for Rompin Datuk Dr Jamaluddin Jarjis, L&AMP;G Twintech Sdn Bhd
executive chief director Prof Dr Ismail Salleh and Kompleks
Metrowangsa Sdn Bhd chief executive officer Dr Ghazali Atan.
	   The congress was later closed by the movement's deputy chief
Datuk Hishammuddin Tun Hussein.
	   
</TEXT>
