<BODY>
<SLUG> ASPARAGUS-EPICUREAN'S sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Asparagus: Epicurean's Delight, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Asparagus: Epicurean's Delight, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   How much do you, the average healthy eater, know about
asparagus? Aside from the fact that it makes a great soup, perhaps
not a lot.
	   Asparagus has quite an illustrious history. Everyone from
practically everywhere, from south central Europe to western and
central Asia and northern Africa, has something to say about it.
The Greeks and Romans may disagree on a few things but they share
an opinion when it comes to the fine flavor of asparagus. Old
bas-reliefs also prove the herb was used in Ancient Egypt.
	   Two hundred years before Christianity, Cato described how
asparagus was cultivated, which was not very different from the way
it's done today. It is derived from a wild form still commonly
found in sandy places, woods, and along river banks. There's the
white Argenteuil from France, the purple asparagus from Holland,
the green Bassano del Gappa from Italy, the purple asparagus from
Genoa, the Mary Washington from the Americas, and the White
Asparagus of Baden Wurtemberg, Germany.
	   The White Asparagus, as well as other varieties, is quite well
known as an aphrodisiac. It's an excellent source of Vitamin A and
C, a good source of minerals, potassium, phosphorus, and iron. It
is also suitable for renal, low-sodium, diabetic, weight control,
low-fat, and low cholesterol diet.
	   In Baden Wurtemberg, around Heidelberg in Germany, harvest
season for White Asparagus has started and will end on the 21st of
June. To pay tribute to this ancient delicacy, the Werdenberg
Corp., known for its chain of fine-dining continental restaurants
in Manila, has brought in White German asparagus for local diners
to sample exquisite asparagus preparations.
	   Beginning June 5 until supply lasts, diners can enjoy asparagus
served cold with a choice of vinaigrette dressing; garlic
mayonnaise, chopped egg, herbs, and air-dried ham; or radish cream
dressing and smoked salmon slices, perfect for an appetizer or as
the main course.
	   If you prefer your asparagus warm, you can ask for asparagus
boiled in its own stock with a choice of Hollandaise sauce, Creamy
Cheese sauce, or Herb-Tomato sauce topped with Parmesan cheese.
Should you prefer any of the dishes as appetizers, the chef
recommends you follow them up with these top main courses -
Asparagus and Grilled Salmon with Champignons and Almond-Herb sauce
served with rice or Asparagus and Rump Steak with an
Orange-Flavored Hollandaise sauce and potato crust.
	   Epicureans, as well as the ``epicurious'', can have the best of
asparagus and other prime dishes at Carpaccio's Ristorante Italiano
and Bianca's Cafe &AMP; Vinotek, both located at 7431 Yakal St., Makati
City; Nathalie's Cafe and Vinotek at Unit B Sycamore Bldg., Alabang
Zapote Road corner Buencamino St., Alabang, Muntinlupa; Zucchini's
Grill &AMP; Vinotek at 66 Timog Avenue, Bgy. Sacred Heart, Quezon City;
and The Gold Ranch Steakhouse at 822 Arnaiz Ave., Makati City.
	   
</TEXT>
