w1658 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  NO-MORE-LICENCES-BURNING     06-09 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> NO-MORE-LICENCES-BURNING sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
No more licences for open burning, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
No more licences for open burning, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Esther TanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sun. - The Department of Environment will no
longer issue contravention licences for open burning under
amendments to the clean air regulations.
	   Instead, it will come up with a prescribed list stating clearly
the type of activities for which open burning will be allowed.
	   Even then the exemption will only be given when open burning is
absolutely necessary including for religious and training purposes,
disease control and traditional agricultural practices.
	   Science, Technology and Environment Minister Datuk Law Hieng
Ding told the New Straits Times that plantation companies would no
longer be allowed to carry out open burning for land clearing.
	   This is because the technology for zero burning is available and
plantation companies can afford to use it to get rid of biomass for
replanting purposes.
	   The proposed amendments to the Environmental Quality (Clean Air)
Regulations 1978 are the second stage of DOE's plan to ensure
stringent enforcement to curb local sources of haze.
	   The first step was amending the Environmental Quality
(Amendment) Act 1996 which, among others, saw the introduction of
stiffer penalties for open burning.
	   The Bill was tabled in the Dewan Rakyat on May 13 and passed a
few days later. The Dewan Negara passed the Bill on Thursday and
the DOE is currently gazetting it.
	   Amendments to the regulations do not have to go through
Parliament but the DOE's legal adviser, who is currently drafting
the amendments, will have to submit the draft to the
Attorney-General's Chambers for approval.
	   At present, the regulations allow for contravention licences to
be issued for agricultural practices. There are also clauses which
allow the use of fire for disease or pest control on agriculture
land; research or fire-fighting training purposes; and burning of
garden refuse.
	   Law said all these clauses would be removed and contravention
licences would no longer be issued.
	   ``This means those who carry out open burning for activities
which are not in the prescribed list will be violating the law,''
he said.
	   DOE director-general Rosnani Ibarahim said the amendments would
also remove ambiguities which obstructed effective enforcement.
	   ``The prescribed list will be very specific on types of
activities. For instance, the plantation sector is now lumped under
agricultural activities.
	   ``What we are doing is to come up with the descriptions of
activities for which open burning is allowed,'' she said.
	   Law said traditional agricultural practices including shifting
cultivation would be exempted because they were carried out by
small-scale farmers.
	   ``There is no technology which they can use. Even if there was,
they could not afford it. Moreover, the size of land involved is
not significant,'' he said.
	   When debating the Environmental Quality Bill in Parliament last
month, a few Members of Parliament had urged the ministry to
consider the plight of padi farmers.
	   They said it was common for farmers to burn padi husks and
straws for easy disposal or to destroy pests.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
