<BODY>
<SLUG> MAJORITY-FAVOURS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Majority favours Chuan govt, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Majority favours Chuan govt, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A local newspaper poll published on Monday found 66 percent of
Thais surveyed said they were satisfied with the way Prime Minister
Chuan Leekpai's administration was handling the nation's economic
crisis.The Nation reported 33 percent of 881 voters conducted last
week via the Internet said they were not satisfied with the
government's efforts and 0.4 percent were undecided.But reviewing
Chuan's six months Chuan, it said there was an ``intriguing mixture
of faith and scepticism'' about the way the government was handling
the economic turmoil.
	   Chuan's six-party coalition took power last December after
Chavalit Yongchaiyudh's administration resigned under pressure for
alleged mishandling of the economy.Chuan's administration has been
popular with the markets, given his strong economic team, and
enjoys broad public support.''Sympathisers and supporters still
outnumber detractors as recent polls show,'' the daily said.''But
the gap has narrowed somehow, and whatever remains of his status as
a saviour has been eclipsed by the we-have-no-choice observation
that recognises his indispensability but underlines doubts as to
whether he really has what it takes to solve the country's
worsening problems. ``Gone is the shining armour. After six months
at the helm of a country in its worst economic crisis, Chuan
Lekpai, confounded and politically wounded, looks like anything but
a white knight, depending on one's point of view.''Everyone agrees
on one thing: Chuan's task is not easy,'' it added.
	   The daily said critics complained of the government's failure to
instigate tax reform or establish a fund to help farmer's pay debts
owed the Bank of Agriculture and Agricultural Cooperatives.Critics
also hoped the government would prevent the funnelling of loans for
social programmes from the World Bank and Japan's Overseas Economic
Cooperation Fund into what they said was a corrupt and inefficient
bureaucracy.They sought proper management of the financial sector
debt so repayment would not fall on taxpayers, and wanted the
government to open to public scrutiny the International Monetary
Fund's $17.2 billion bail-out programme for Thailand.The newspaper
said the government's defence was the relative stability of the
baht lately and that it had adhered strictly to the IMF's economic
reform programme. Inflation has been lower than expected with the
average for all of 1998 seen at around 10.5 percent from 11.6
percent projected earlier. Plans to issue $18 billion in global and
domestic bonds would help end severe domestic liquidity, it added.
	   The government also said it had begun reforming the Bank of
Thailand, blamed for the baht's fall by more than 50 percent after
it was floated last July.It said 50 billion baht in funds would be
spent on social programmes and a significant portion of defence and
security spending had been diverted to the farm sector.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
