<SLUG> BC-France-Air France-Strike, 5th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Air France pilots going ahead with strike on eve of World Cup
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs; UPDATES with pilots meeting and deciding to go on with
strike; detail. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By JOCELYN NOVECK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Even as Paris put on the most festive show it could
muster to welcome the world's soccer fans, Air France pilots
decided Tuesday to go ahead with a 9-day-old strike that's left a
threatening cloud over the World Cup.
	   Four unions representing the striking pilots met at Charles de
Gaulle airport for several hours Tuesday evening, and agreed to
continue their walkout.
	   One union, the SNPL-Air Inter, accused Air France management of
``an obvious desire to worsen the strike.'' It called the airline's
``passivity'' since negotiations broke down last Saturday
``stunning and scandalous.''
	   Some union members, meanwhile, said they expected the company's
board to meet in a special session Saturday to consider new
proposals, but management refused to confirm that date.
	   The pilots increasingly are being seen as spoilers of France's
effort to put its best face forward for the World Cup, the gigantic
international soccer fest that begins Wednesday.
	   As the pilots met Tuesday evening, acrobats, dancers, and four
jolly giants filled the capital's streets for a festive World Cup
kickoff. Fans were everywhere, many in kilts; thousands of Scots
have come for the opening game between Scotland and Brazil.
	   But many of the fans who've descended on the capital had to take
alternate means of transport when their Air France flights were
canceled.
	   Only one in four Air France planes was flying Tuesday, and other
carriers were cashing in on the carrier's woes.
	   British Airways estimated it is bringing in an additional 1
million pounds (dlrs 1.6 million) daily as a result of the Air
France strike.
	   Air France is the official carrier of the World Cup, and the
airline has arranged special flights to transport teams to their
destinations.
	   The French transport minister, meanwhile, urged pilots and
management to return to the negotiating table.
	   ``Each moment, each hour, each minute must be used for
discussion and for negotiation,'' Jean-Claude Gayssot told the
French parliament. ``Finding a solution to the conflict is
essential,'' Gayssot said.
	   The pilots are protesting 500 million francs (dlrs 83 million)
in salary cuts. Air France says the cuts are needed to modernize
the airline, which was saved from bankruptcy in 1993 but reported
profits in 1996 and 1997.
	   The airline has offered to compensate the pilots by giving them
stock in exchange for the pay cuts.
	   Meanwhile, bus and subway service was reduced in Lyon, a World
Cup venue, on Tuesday following a drivers' strike there.
	   Another World Cup venue, Bordeaux, may also be hit with a
walkout by bus drivers on Thursday.
	   (parf-dgs-ip-jn)
</TEXT>
