<SLUG> THE-LONG-MARCH sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
The long march, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
The long march, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The elaborately prepared long march by the Bangladesh
Nationalist Party and its allies materialises today. The programme
is organised to oppose the enactment of laws making provision for a
Regional Council and Hill District Council in line with the
Chittagong Hill Tracts Peace Accord. Under the two-day programme
BNP chairperson and Leader of the Opposition Begum Khaleda Zia will
lead the march (automobile procession) from the capital to
Chittagong while the Deputy Leader of the Opposition Professor
Badruddoza Chowdhury will lead the procession from Chittagong to
Khagrachhari.Long march is just another way of staging protest,
though it is an extraordinary way.
	   If it is peaceful and ends peacefully one can find nothing wrong
with it but apprehensions of violence are based on the fact that a
programme like this one has the spirit of mobilisation with the
consequent overheated tempers and frayed nerves. The fears were
somewhat allayed by government announcement that the long march
will not be resisted. The Opposition has also said the long march
will be peaceful but warned of serious consequences if the march is
obstructed. The ruling Awami League is organising peace rallies
during the two days. When both sides make loud protestations of
peace, there should be no cause for anxiety.
	   However, when the mood is one of confrontation and bellicosity,
perception of behavioural line dividing peace from violence is apt
to be blurred. Such a mammoth programme has to rely on
wide-stretched logistics and enlistment with referral links and
activated network over a wide geographical area which as a whole
will remain vulnerable to any provocation. Therefore the whole
nation will have to remain vigilant against any disruption of the
peace. Some irresponsible quarters have given a call for joining
the long march with licensed arms, and we hope the leadership among
organisers of the long march will lose no time to restrain them.
Police have also said that participation in political programme
even with licensed arms is an offence under law. Sabre-rattling and
language of weapons must be discarded at all cost.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
