<SLUG> BC-Sudan-Fighting </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sudan claims it recaptured garrison town in east
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) _ The Sudanese army recaptured a garrison
town in eastern Sudan in fierce fighting that displaced thousands
of people, a government newspaper said Tuesday.
	   The rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army said last week that it
had captured Ulu, 455 kilometers (280 miles) southeast of Khartoum,
after a daylong battle in a region that borders Ethiopia.
	   The town is considered strategic because it is located near the
Roseires Dam, which provides 80 percent of Khartoum's electricity.
	   Government troops retook the town, but clashes continued in the
area, the daily Al-Anba newspaper reported. It did not say when the
town fell, and there was no immediate rebel comment.
	   The fighting forced thousands of families to flee, it said.
	   The rebels have been fighting since 1983 for greater autonomy
from the Muslim-dominated government for the mainly Christian and
animist south. More than 1.3 million Sudanese have died in the war
and famines caused by the fighting.
