<BODY>
<SLUG> GUESS-WHO-PAYS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Guess Who Pays!, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Guess Who Pays!, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   When you next look at the Manila skyline and see all the
high-rise buildings which are under construction, you may well ask
yourself two questions: 1) ``Who will be able to occupy all this
space?'' and; 2) ``Who will pay the bill for this creation of
excess capacity?''
	   Only God knows the answer to the first question and He is not
telling! The horrible truth about the second question is that you
and I will have to pay for all this folly through an accelerated
loss of the purchasing value of our currency.
	   The developers deserve to go into bankruptcy and many of them
probably will, but that does nothing to help pay for the wastage of
resources which they have inflicted on the community.
	   The real cost of all this excess capacity will ultimately have
to be born by every member of our community. We will be made to pay
for this by the simple means of a loss in the purchasing power of
our money, which includes but is not limited to, a decline in the
rate of exchange between our currency and the currencies of other
nations which are less guilty of such wastage of resources.
	   We may well ask if there was ever any attempt by those elected
to be entrusted with the management of our economy to see any
relation between the granting of building permits with any sort of
plan of future needs.
	   Even the least educated housewife is aware of the need to
allocate her financial resources to the actual needs of her family,
but this simple logic appears to be a non-existent within the
realms of government and its huge bureaucratic empire of
certificate and license producers.
	   What is the purpose of requiring a building permit if there is
not going to be some effort to allocate resources to foreseeable
needs?
	   We already have far too much traffic on our roads, but can you
imagine the horrible traffic jams which will develop if ever all
these high-rise buildings are eventually completed and occupied! It
is very difficult to determine that there has been any serious
attempt to allocate the use of land to the available resources of
transportation, wour forests to
the point of extinction, and now we are permitting the equally
senseless construction of bunches of high-rise buildings with
little regard for the services which they require. These are such
things as transportation, water supply, power supply, fire-fighting
capabilities or anything else.
	   Who wants to work in a 31st-floor office in an earthquake or,
for that matter, during a strong typhoon?
	   I don't know about you but I find myself suffering from vertigo
when I look out of the window of my ninth floor office, and I
positively dread the prospects of having to move to a 26th-floor
office as do most of the other people in our office. But I am not
aware of any attempt to measure the general public's attitude to
either living in or working in a high-rise building. No doubt we
shall hear more about that after the next strong earthquake, or
when someone is careless enough to leave a window open during a
typhoon! Imagine being on the 25th floor when a major fire breaks
out on the 15th floor. One day something like that will happen!

</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:GUESS-WHO-PAYS sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
