AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Third National Vitamin A Week began nation-wide last Sunday
to educate guardians about the hazards children face if there is a
Vitamin A deficiency. Lack of this vitamin is responsible for night
blindness. In 1981-82, a country-wide study found night blindness
was prevalent among nearly 3.76 per cent of the total population.
Efforts to improve the imbalance has brought down the incidence of
this eye deficiency to less than one per cent, according to a
number of recent surveys.
	   There is no need to be complacent, however, and this week's
programme highlights that disseminating knowledge of this vitamin's
curative ability especially among the landless poor is essential
for removing the blight of night blindness. Radio has been one of
the most successful means of mass communication in our country. And
NGOs have reached where even the radio is not a constant feature in
the recreational sphere of rural life This is a curable condition,
however. Vitamin A pills or natural food which is rich in that
vitamin can restore normal vision. Among the various dietary
procedures recommended, one is the intake of little Mola fish to
correct the deficiency.
	   Another source is Spirulina, which is a health food.Green
vegetables and green fruits are yet other sources of the vitamin.
There are many plots, small and of veritable minuscule size, which
may be utilised by urban dwellers, even in the capital city for
growing fresh vegetables. In fact, the fear of disproportionate use
of both artificial fertilisers and pesticides by vegetable farmers
has led a number of city dwellers to opt for home-grown fresh
vegetables according to the season.As green vegetables, fruits,
Mola fish and other sources of Vitamin A are available, children
can be fortified against night blindness from the very beginning of
their life. Breast-feeding can also prevent Vitamin A deficiencies.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
