<HEADLINE>
Shipowners Group Oppose New Benchmark Pay Hike, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Shipowners Group Oppose New Benchmark Pay Hike, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Arthur U. SalaganASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The International Shipping Federation (ISF), the international
employers' organization for shipowners, has opposed the plan of the
International Transport Workers' Federation (ITF) to raise the
benchmark pay for able seaman to $1,400.
	   The ITF Council instead reiterated its hardline position that
salary rates should relate to the seafarers' home country and that
the ITF-dictated international wage scales were unacceptable.
	   The current benchmark of $1,200 took effect only last January
this year.
	   The rapid increase in officers' salaries and the continuing
shortage of qualified crews had been major topics during the ISF's
annual meeting held in London last April.
	   ``Pay rates of officers from India, the Philippines and Poland
are catching up with Western pay rates,'' IFS President Juan Kelly
noted. He said the question now is ``where the next generation of
senior officers and shore-based technical managers would be coming
from.''
	   According to Filipino seafarers, some manning agents offer the
higher ITF rates, while others offer Philippine Overseas Employment
Administration (POEA) rates which are much lower.
	   The ISF meeting also focused on new regulations concerning hours
of work.
	   There is still a lot of uncertainty about the subject because of
the discrepancies between the International Maritime Organization
(IMO) requirements now in place and the new International Labor
Organization (ILO) Convention No. 180 which allow various
exceptions to the exact work hour limits.
	   Kelly said: ``It is unclear how port state control inspectors
will establish the actual work or rest regimes applied on
particular ships. Much will depend on the outcome of discussions
taking place in the European Union (EU) which intends to
incorporate the ILO standards into EU law and apply them to non-EU
flag ships visiting EU ports.
	   The ISF is a maritime organization concerned with labor affairs
and manning and training issues at the international level. Its
membership comprises national shipowners' associations from 30
countries representing more than half the world's merchant tonnage.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
