<SLUG> BOMBING-OF-ERITREA sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bombing of Eritrea, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Bombing of Eritrea, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A simmering border dispute between Eritrea and Ethiopia, whose
veterans fought together to bring down the former military dictator
in Addis Ababa, Mengitsu Haile Mariam in 1991, has escalated into
bloody war on three fronts along their 1000 kilometre frontiers and
air-raids that have taken civilian tolls. After thirty-one years of
guerilla war, Eritrea was allowed by Mengitsu's successor
government in Addis Ababa to secede from Ethiopia by a referendum
in 1993.
	   Peaceful talks have been going on all these years about a 400
sq. km. of disputed border territory, which was included in Eritrea
in the maps of colonial administration under Italy, but merged with
Tigre province of Ethiopia under post-colonial administration of
Haile Selassie.As a border war broke out last month, Eritrean
forces repulsed an Ethiopian attack by a counter-attack that pushed
at least 10 kilometres into Ethiopian territory at Zala Ambessa
before declaring the operation nearly over and ``it could be time
to leave.
	   `` Then on Friday last Ethiopia sent four of its warplanes to
bomb the airport of Asmara, the capital of Eritrea, hitting both
civilian and military parts of the complex. One Ethiopian plane was
downed and the pilot captured. A Zambian cargo plane parked on the
ground was damaged. Ethiopia claimed heavy damage has been
inflicted on two planes and infrastructure of the Asmara military
base, and the raid was in retaliation of Eritrean air-attack on
Mekele airport (and a school) in the Tigre state of Ethiopia. The
air-raids took place after diplomats from United States and Rwanda
left Asmara the same day for Burkina Faso to report on the crisis
to a summit meeting of the Organisation of African Unity countries,
and obtain support for their five-point peace plan requiring
demilitarisation of the disputed territory and a third party
observer force pending negotiations.
	   Ethiopia had accepted the plan. Eritrea had declared acceptance
in principle saying ``there are still serious issues of detail and
implementation that need to be worked out.''The USA protested that
the attack on Asmara airport endangered foreign nationals trying to
flee the unsafe capital. The OAU meeting had a stormy session
finding it difficult to reach consensus, but called on both the
belligerents to cooperate with the facilitators, namely, USA and
Rwanda. The UN Security Council has called for ``an immediate
ceasefire,'' which hopefully the parties will honour.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
