<BODY>
<SLUG> DOJ-MOVES-TO-QUASH sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOJ Moves to Quash 'Save Imelda' Petition, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
DOJ Moves to Quash 'Save Imelda' Petition, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Benjamin P. PultaASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Department of Justice Secretary Silvestre Bello III yesterday
said the DOJ was confident the high court would accept government's
appeal to withdraw the petition filed by ousted Solicitor General
Romeo de la Cruz before the Supreme Court seeking the acquittal of
former first lady Imelda Marcos in a graft charge against her.
	   Bello, who was tapped by President Fidel Ramos on Friday to take
the place of De la Cruz, said the DOJ has filed a petition seeking
to quash the ex-solicitor general's appeal.
	   ``Under the rules, we can still withdraw....as any litigant can
always withdraw pleadings,'' said Bello, who added that one of
DOJ's main arguments was De la Cruz's petition was not consistent
with government's ''institutional policy'' on the case.
	   Bello, who is set to step down from office at the end of Ramos'
term on June 30, is not discounting the possibility of seeing
Marcos' lawyers oppose the solicitor general's move to have the
petition withdrawn.
	   ``Anything is possible,'' he noted.
	   Earlier, De la Cruz stood pat on his decision to seek the
acquittal of the former first lady on a graft case.
	   He also remained confident that the Supreme Court would sustain
his plea.
	   ''Since when are cases decided by state policies?'' he asked.
	   Cases, he continued, should be decided on the basis of evidence,
laws and applicable decisions.
	   He added that it was government's option to withdraw his
petition.
	   Civil rights group Philippine Constitutional Association
yesterday criticized Ramos' move to accept the courtesy resignation
of De la Cruz for ''taking Marcos' side in a pending case.''

</TEXT>
