<HEADLINE>
Abdullah: Asean countries still working closely, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Abdullah: Asean countries still working closely, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KEPALA BATAS, Sun. - Foreign Minister Datuk Seri Abdullah Ahmad
Badawi said although Asean countries might take different
approaches in tackling their economic problems, all member
countries were still working closely in many areas including trade.
	   ``Unlike our country, Indonesia, Thailand and the Philippines
are getting assistance from the International Monetary Fund.
	   ``Our approach may be different, but we continue to enjoy a
close relationship,'' Abdullah said today after closing a
traditional cooking and kuih-making contest organised by Kepala
Batas Wanita Umno.
	   Abdullah, who is MP for Kepala Batas, was asked if some Asean
countries affected by the regional financial crisis had diverged in
dealing with domestic problems.
	   ``We are not going about it separately. Malaysia, on its part,
has already given RM250 million in financial aid to Indonesia, and
all Asean members have agreed to carry out trading among themselves
using their respective currencies.''
	   Asked about Cambodia's entry into Asean, he said the matter
would be decided after the country held its general election next
month.
	   ``I foresee no problems. I hope the political situation would
enable the country to carry out its elections smoothly.''
	   He said Malaysia would send eight observers to the elections
which would be held on July 26.
	   
</TEXT>
