<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Italy-Ravanelli, 1st Ld-Writethru,0304 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Italian striker is sick
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with spokesman saying results ``not serious''; status
to be determined tomorrow &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SENLIS, France (AP) _ Striker Fabrizio Ravanelli, suffering from
fever and cough, was taken to a hospital for X-rays Tuesday and
could be dropped from Italy's World Cup team.
	   The 29-year-old Olympique Marseille forward was examined at a
nearby hospital in Creil. Italian federation spokesman Stefano
Balducci said results ``were not serious.'' While not elaborating,
Balducci suggested the X-rays were intended to check for pneumonia.
	   Balducci said Ravanelli's fever and cough persisted, and that
the player was under treatment of antibiotics.
	   Italian officials said a final decision about Ravanelli's status
would be taken by coach Cesare Maldini early Wednesday shortly
before the team's departure for Bordeaux, where Italy plays Chile
in a Group B match on Thursday.
	   Ravanelli's sudden illness could lead to the inclusion of Parma
forward Enrico Chiesa, who has been in camp as a 23rd player.
	   World Cup teams can report to FIFA the replacement of a sick or
injured player up to 1530 GMT Wednesday _ the kickoff time of the
World Cup inaugural match between Brazil and Scotland.
	   Ravanelli's illness was the last bout of misfortune to hit the
Italian team.
	   Forward Alessandro Del Piero has just recovered from a right
thigh strain and is out of the Chile match.
	   Defender Moreno Torricelli bruised his right foot in training 10
days ago and resumed practicing only Tuesday.
	   Chiesa had been put on alert as a substitute for Del Piero first
and then Torricelli. Now he had a third chance to stay with the
team.
	   (pv-jw)
</TEXT>
