<SLUG> BC-NATO-Kosovo, 1st Ld,0440 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Events in Kosovo unfolding faster than NATO can plan
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with U.S. and Britain planning
to ask Security Council to approve use of force. &QL; 
 &UR; By JEFFREY ULBRICH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ Military events in Kosovo are unfolding
almost faster than NATO military planners can plan.
	   Just a few days ago, the generals were focusing on military
exercises and dispatching troops to help Albania and Macedonia deal
with refugees and patrol borders. Now, as one senior NATO official
put it Tuesday, ``We are contemplating more challenging options,
which could include intervention.''
	   More than 250 people have died in Kosovo since Mar. 1 in
escalating clashes between government forces and the Kosovo
Liberation Army, armed wing of the Albanian independence movement.
Ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of the province's
population, are demanding independence from Serbia, the larger of
the two republics remaining in Yugoslavia.
	   The United States and its allies support autonomy for Kosovo but
oppose the rebels' demands for independence and condemn violence on
both sides.
	   In recent days entire villages in Kosovo have been flattened and
thousands of people driven from their homes, making the need for
action more urgent if the crisis is not to erupt into a wider
Balkan war.
	   Twelve days ago, NATO foreign ministers agreed to enhance
military exercises in Albania and Macedonia as a way of increasing
the military presence there. A NATO assessment team is still the
region looking at future options. But as a senior NATO official
said, speaking anonymously: ``With the events of the last week,
shoring up the periphery seems of secondary value.''
	   NATO defense ministers meet in Brussels Thursday and Friday for
discussions certain to be dominated by Kosovo. It is expected they
will order the military to start looking at direct intervention in
Kosovo.
	   The United States and Britain plan to ask the U.N. Security
Council, possibly next week, to approve the use of force against
the Serbs to halt attacks on ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
	   U.S. sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
Americans were also willing to make a direct appeal to Russian
President Boris Yeltsin if they encounter resistance from the
Russian foreign ministry.
	   The Russians oppose NATO troops in the area but have indicated
that they might support a more robust U.N. role. That would require
approval by the 15-member Security Council, where Russia has a
permanent seat and veto power.
	   Exactly what, 8th graf pvs
</TEXT>
