<BODY>
<SLUG> BNP'S-LONG-MARCH sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BNP's long march : Its rationale, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
BNP's long march : Its rationale, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   M. M. Rezaul KarimASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Long march is attributed to the historic march staged by the
great leader and founder of modern China, Chairman Mao, which
continued for decades and traversed thousand of miles of territory.
The purpose was to gain control of territories, consolidate popular
support for the struggle for freedom from feudal and autocratic
rulers and to establish people's rule in China. In our national
context, the term long march was used for the one which, in 1976,
under the leadership of the highly respected octogenarian national
leader Maulana Abdul Hamid Khan Bhashani, went upto the
India-Bangladesh borders at Kanshat near Farakka. It was aimed to
demonstrate the anguish and helplessness of the people of
Bangladesh consequent upon the construction and commissioning of
the Farakka barrage by India on the Ganges, and was purported to
mark as a vehement protest against India's actions.
	   The purpose and rationale of the so-called long march being
staged by the BNP on the 9th and 10th of this month is more akin to
that of Bhashani than of Mao Ze Dong. It is scheduled to start from
Dhaka today, on the 9th, and will go to Chittagong. After
nightfall, it will continue tomorrow morning, on the 10th, and end
its journey in the Chittagong Hill Tracts. People from different
parts of the country will join on the way at different parts of the
rally. The principal objectives are two-fold. Firstly, it would
represent a strong and unequivocal protest against the Chittagong
Hill Tracts Accord and the passing of the 4 acts in Parliament that
are necessary to implement the Accord. Secondly, this would allow
people from different walks of life and regions of the country to
demonstrate their solidarity with the cause through participation
in or support for the march.
	   Finally, this will help provide an awareness in the minds of
many other people of the great harm that would result through
implementation of the accord and its enabling acts.The BNP
forcefully claims that they were not consulted in the conclusion of
the Accord and were not allowed to speak on the relevant bills. The
ruling party stated that in the negotiating team two BNP members
had been incorporated but they did not participate. The BNP
retorted that the two members were taken arbitrarily without
consultation with the Party and could not be accepted as its
representatives. For this purpose the Awami League refused to
formally approach the BNP, which in turn did not suggest any names
on its own.The BNP, on the other hand, pointed out that out of the
9 members of their National Committee, 4 were taken from the
opposition. There was absolute transparency, openness and trust
among political parties in the matter of negotiations during the
BNP time which held three times more sessions with the PCJSS than
during the Awami League rule. But the BNP refused to concede
grounds that harmed national interests and refused to sign an
agreement merely for the sake of signing one.
	   The Awami League acted in haste and signed an accord at any cost
and, in the process, sacrificed vital national interests.National
interests have been curbed in many ways, according to BNP
advocates. The constitution of the newly constituted CHT Parishad
vested with extraordinary authority and marked by undemocratic
composition is not in conformity with the Constitution of the land.
The provision of the Parishad to send a legislative bill back to
Parliament for reconsideration itself impinges on the sovereignty
of Parliament itself. The accord was concluded with the
representatives of the Chakma tribe, which constitutes only 28 per
cent of the CHT population. The Bengali community, which is
composed of 48 per cent of the entire population as well as the 13
other tribes were neither represented at the negotiations nor were
consulted. This is unfair, discriminatory and, therefore, highly
undemocratic.
	   That too is for 0.6 per cent of people for 10 per cent of the
entire land of the nation.Again, it is absurd to assume that we, as
a sovereign nation, have to withdraw our troops, Ansars and even
ill-armed or unarmed village defence corps into far-away
cantonments and towns, leaving the entire countryside vulnerable at
the mercy of local authorities and law enforcing agencies. It is
also interesting to note that the Parishad is empowered to recruit
police and officers, with obligatory preference from among the
tribals many of whom might have been former insurgents. The entire
region being an impassable terrain is likely to go out of the
effective control of the government. If the country adjacent to the
CHT being the traditional patron saint of the tribal insurgents
turns real hostile, sovereignty and territorial integrity of the
nation would be in jeopardy. This would be a matter of the deepest
concern for every patriotic Bangladeshi. All arms, specially the
sophisticated arms, have not been deposited, nor the entire armed
cadre of the PCJSS or Shanti Bahini surrendered themselves.
	   This would pose a dangerous situation and portends ill omen for
the future. It also sounds ridiculous to accept that any tribal can
buy any amount of land anywhere in Bangladesh, but no Bangladeshi
can buy a piece of land in the CHT nor a Bangladeshi can ever be
Chairman of the Parishad. The provision of payment of royalty on
the mineral and natural resources of the CHT to the people in the
region, is discriminatory. It is not illogical to assume that this
and the many other undue concessions granted under the Accord would
only encourage similar demands form other tribal and different
sections of population in Bangladesh.People have often asked if the
accord and the acts are Constitutional, if so, why does not the BNP
send the case to the Supreme Court for consideration and decision.
The answer is that whenever a grave doubt is expressed in many
quarters, it devolves upon the government to seek advisory opinion
of the Supreme Court, lest the Act gets scrapped and this does not
speak well of the government. The country's President has a role to
play in this regard. Such advice has not been sought by the
government.
	   Yet, there is time for some-one to challenge these Acts in the
Supreme Court. Moreover, the issue is fraught with great political
import and should preferably be settled as such.Some people also
ask, and legitimately they do, as to why then this accord got
almost universal acclaim from the international community. The
answer is not difficult to trace. They view that insurgency in the
Chittagong Hill Tracts has cost Bangladesh enormously in terms of
human and material resources over a quarter of century and that any
agreement that pledges restoration of peace would be normally
welcomed by them. The international community, on the other hand,
does not generally possess the requisite information some of which
have been outlined above. As the CHT Accord and the Acts do not
safeguard national interests and even the interests of the majority
of the people in that area who feel discriminated against, it
cannot bring about lasting peace.
	   And, if there is no lasting peace, there could be no final or
decisive settlement.Evidently, many of these points and even more
have been stated by different quarters. Why then the BNP decided to
hold the extraordinary measure of a Long March? It is primarily
because the ruling party quashed a series of BNP demands at every
stage and steamrolled the agreement and the legislation without
allowing others to be heard formally on this vitally important
national issue. BNP demanded that the principal provisions of the
accord be circulated before signing in order to elicit public and
political opinion. This demand was not accepted. Secondly, the BNP
Chairperson led a march of a hundred legislators to the President
to seek his good offices to arrange a dialogue with the ruling
party. The Prime Minister vetoed the move and asked the Opposition
to return to Parliament to hold discussions on the subject.
Accordingly, the Opposition, which so long abstained from sessions
in Parliament for alleged violation by the ruling party of a
previous accord with the opposition party, returned to Parliament
and demanded a general discussion on the Accord.
	   This was also denied by the Speaker, obviously at the behest of
the government.It was then suggested that the discussion would take
place at the time of introduction of the 4 bills relevant to the
Accord. Then, the two BNP members of the parliamentary committee
were not allowed to give their right to dissent on the bills or to
register objections. These were denied on technical grounds of
having been received late, though the Speaker had the discretion to
accommodate. For some strange and inexplicable reasons, the BNP
members had received copies of the bills late.Then came the crux of
the problem. To emphasise paramount importance of the issue, the
Opposition legislators proposed an unprecedented, though an
unreasonable number, several thousand amendments to the 4 bills,
and evidently wanted to speak on them. The Speaker ruled that it
would take several years for holding proper discussions on these
amendments which, by any calculation, is incorrect. He allowed the
Opposition the ridiculous time of a total of only 11 minutes to
speak on these bills.
	   BNP members were allotted only 8 minutes for 8 of its members.
It was estimated that if all the Opposition members were allowed 10
minutes each, it would not have taken more than 3 days to hold a
respectable debate on these bills. But the government retracted its
promises at every stage to the Opposition to allow it to speak.The
very decision of the government to deny the Opposition to talk on
this issue in Parliament prompted the Opposition, the seven party
alliance, to resort to other peaceful means of protests. These
included demonstrations, street rallies, public meetings, hartals
and even fasting. The Long March is being organised as another
means to register public protest. It has been repeatedly stated
that it is a peaceful march and the government should be prudent
enough not to obstruct it, for the sake of avoiding possible
violence and in the greater interest of the nation.Views expressed
in the article are the writer's own. The writer is a member of
Advisory Council, BNP.
	   
</TEXT>
