<SLUG> US-TO-EXTEND-GARMENTS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US to Extend Only Half of $50-M Garments Quota, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
US to Extend Only Half of $50-M Garments Quota, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The United States has offered to extend only half of the $50
million garments quota to local garments manufacturers in 1998.
	   The additional quota was part of the settlement with the US
whose earlier decision to change its rules of origin (ROO) left
local garments manufacturers with heavy losses.
	   US offered only 5% increase in quota instead of 10% given in
1997, triggering protests from local garments manufacturers.
	   ``We cannot settle for that.....we lost that market forever. We
have to have a continuity of that (additional quota),'' said Donald
Dee, president of the Confederation of Garments Exporters of the
Philippines.
	   The United States will be taking back the additional quota in
categories 338, 339, 638, 639, 347, 348, and 847. These categories
include jeans, pants and T-shirts.
	   Philippine garments officials are expected to take the case to
the dispute settlement body of the World Trade Organization (WTO).
	   The row over the ROO started in 1996. US government offered to
settle by giving the Philippines an additional 15% quota in wool
items.
	   The agreement was contained in a memorandum of understanding
signed in 1997.
	   US wanted to take back the additional quota, convinced that
Philippine manufacturers have already adjusted to the changes in
the ROO, The changes made in the ROO were said to have displaced 50
medium-sized enterprises in the country.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
