<HEADER>
w1694 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  GAS-RESOURCE-IMMENSEsked     06-09 1317
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> GAS-RESOURCE-IMMENSE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Gas resource: Immense prospects, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Gas resource: Immense prospects, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Toufiqul IslamASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Bangladesh - a country of more than 120 million, does not have
much resources. Agriculture remains the mainstay of the economy and
contributes a major share to the country's GDP. The population
growth has put tremendous pressure on limited land. So it is
imperative to diversify the country's economy to avoid depending
wholly on agriculture. Jute, known as the country's golden fibre,
is facing stiff competition from the synthetics. The country's
fairly successful ready-made garments' (RMG) industry, that is yet
to build up the necessary backward linkages, would be faced with a
more severe and ruthless competition in the global market as the
new World Trade Organisation(WTO) regime comes into effect, and the
quotas and other preferential systems are done away with. But every
cloud has also its silver linings.
	   Under the earth and off-shore water in the Bay of Bengal, there
is a hidden resource - natural gas, that augurs well for the
resource-hungry nation struggling to cope with overriding poverty
and aspiring for a steady economic development. Indeed, there could
not be any other resource other than oil and gas which could
quickly energise the economy of any nation. Gas is a basic and
versatile energy, it could be used to produce electricity at a
cheaper cost which is a vital factor in industrial production. In
recent years, gas has emerged as the most precious vis-a-vis all
fossil fuels, because of its comparative cleanliness in terms of
toxic emissions. That is probably why it has become the present day
craze for the world's giant hydrocarbon prospectors. Currently,
Bangladesh economy is heavily dependent on its indigenous natural
gas. Today, as much as 72 per cent of the commercial energy
consumption is derived from natural gas. This a positive
development, but without sustained effort to replenish the national
natural gas consumption and reserves, future development in the
sector may suffer stagnation, with wide national implications.
	   At present the national demand for natural gas is about 900
million cft. per day, when the system can supply about 800 MCFD.
According to present projections, demand for natural gas will
increase to about 1225 MCFD in the year 2000, with a supply gap of
about 225 MCFD . The estimated demand-supply gap by the year 2005,
2010 and 2015 are expected to be in the order of 600 MCFD, 1300
MCFD and 2300 MCFD respectively. This indicates the magnitude of
activities required in the sector from upstream exploration to
downstream transmission and conversion to power and other
products.At present, the country has 20 discovered gas fields ,with
total in place gas reserve of around 23 trillion cubic feet, of
which around 13 TCF gas, leaving a net recoverable reserve of about
10 TCF, may sustain the system at current level of consumption till
the year 2015.
	   National gas production has seen an increase from 83 billion CFT
in 1983-84 to about 265 BCF in 1996-97, indicating sharp increase
in consumption. In this perspective, there is no alternative other
than expanding the exploration activities to discover new reserves
of gas and to confirm additional reserves in the discovered fields.
Oil and gas exploration is a capital intensive venture, and risk
capital is now unavoidable mode of investment in the sector. For a
country like Bangladesh with a limited public sector resources such
investment is best bypassed and some effective alternative found.
Bangladesh is following the trend of inviting international risk
capital in the sector through production-sharing contracts. So far,
the response we have received is more than encouraging. To expedite
exploration activities through systematic geological evaluation,
seismic surveys and drilling operations both in known and frontier
areas and to make the environment here investor-friendly,
Bangladesh introduced a new Petroleum Policy in 1993.
	   This policy provided facilities for the international investors
to explore hydrocarbons under competitive terms. To facilitate the
promotional efforts simultaneously with the new policy introduced,
Petrobangla completed compilation of all exploration data available
upto 1992 that relate to occurrence of petroleum in Bangladesh. The
entire Bangladesh territory has been divided into 23 exploration
blocks and offered for PSC. By 1995, 8 such blocks were taken up by
4 companies since then, the PSC terms and conditions were further
liberalised and promotional seminars were held at international
venues to attract foreign oil and gas companies for exploration in
Bangladesh. By July, 1997, 12 of the remaining 15 blocks were
eagerly being sought after by 21 international oil companies (IOC).
In the past, the IOCs were not very keen to explore in Bangladesh
considering it to be a mostly a gas-prone areas.
	   Now with the increased interest in gas, especially, in the Asian
context, and the guarantees of fair gas price paid in US$, the IOCs
now find investment environment in Bangladesh good enough to
explore even for smaller fields. The tremendous interests being
shown for exploration has been unprecedented and certainly we
should give it due welcome and a fair chance. A major participant
in the on-going activities in the gas sector is the Cairn Energ
which is operating two blocks(15-16) under PSC. Cairn was the first
international prospector to start work under the 1993 PSC bidding
round and has already succeeded in discovering the second off-shore
gas field of Bangladesh. They plan to commission this off-shore
field in the mid-June, 1998. It has also identified a number of
other prospective structures in their PSC blocks currently working
at the Halda off-shore structure.
	   In Bangladesh ,the private sector seems to be firm in the
natural gas related activities. A ongoing project is already there
for setting up natural gas fractionation plant in association with
the private sector under the name and style of Ashuganj NGL
Defructionation Plant. It would use NG byproducts and other
unexplored wastes. Additional private sector investments could also
be mobilized in areas such as: bottling ,marketing and distribution
of the LPG produced by this upcoming plant. The private-public
joint ventures should accrue some spin-off benefits to the other
sectors of economic growth. Natural gas - the only indigenous
energy source to date contributes 70 percent to the production of
electricity and chemical fertilizers and could be the base for
promising Petro-chemical industries. Natural gas though a nature's
gifted boon, is not inexhaustible, its use has to be regulated and
new finds have to be mobilized. So, sectoral domestic utilisation
has to be allocated in a planned manner.
	   As we have mentioned already, the power and fertilizer by far
remain and shall remain in the near future the largest gas
consumers accounting for 52 per cent and 26 per cent respectively
of estimated demand by the year 2004/2005.The growing role of
Bangladesh's gas resource makes it imperative for the sectoral
authorities to put it on a solid base and this would require in
turn setting up of a Gas Regulatory Authority with strengthened PSC
division and a Hydrocarbon Unit in the concerned ministry.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:GAS-RESOURCE-IMMENSE sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
