w1695 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SwissBanks-NaziGroups     06-09 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Swiss Banks-Nazi Groups,0727 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Wiesenthal Center: extreme right `saturated' WWII Switzerland
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING to change slug &QL; 
 &UR; By BALZ BRUPPACHER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BERN, Switzerland (AP) _ Pro-Nazi and other extreme right-wing
groups ``saturated'' neutral Switzerland while Adolf Hitler ruled
neighboring Germany, according to the Simon Wiesenthal Center.
	   A copy of a center report to be released Wednesday in New York
was obtained by The Associated Press in Switzerland.
	   ``The extraordinary variety and number of associations and
societies in Switzerland representing the extreme-right _
patriotic, fascist or both _ during the Hitlerian era is most
striking,'' said the 128-page study by the Los Angeles-based
center.
	   He said there were ``well in excess of three dozen'' such groups
and that some ``had cells or chapters in more than 160 cities,
towns and villages.''
	   Swiss President Flavio Cotti reacted heatedly. ``These
representations are untenable and perfidious,'' he said.
	   A Swiss government statement conceded the presence of ``a
variety of small rightist radical groups of all shades,'' but said
they ``never totaled more than 1.5 percent of the voters'' and were
already seriously depleted by the time World War II began in 1939.
	   ``Probably no other country in the whole of Europe was so
thoroughly infested with similar groups in proportion to its
population and geographical area,'' said the report.
	   It was written by Alan Morris Schom, an American specialist in
French history.
	   Last January the center, named after the famed Nazi hunter,
released another report by Schom accusing the Swiss of running
camps where Jewish refugees were used as slave labor and told they
would be handed over to Germany's Gestapo if they complained.
	   Switzerland conceded that some camp commanders had treated
refugees badly, but prominent Swiss Jews and a number of Jews who
lived in the camps said that by and large the country was a safe
haven for many on a hostile continent.
	   The latest Wiesenthal report said the right-wing groups had tens
of thousands of members, most of them working or lower-middle
class.
	   ``These groups thoroughly saturated every one of the country's
21 cantons and the core of Swiss society,'' said Schom.
	   One organization, the Swiss Fatherland Association, ``was
comprised largely of the ruling elite of Switzerland, notably the
officer corps and the political, financial and industrial leaders
of the country.''
	   He described the association as a semi-secret club that pushed
for government discrimination against Jewish refugees and backed
the requirement implemented by the government that the Swiss Jewish
community pay for the care of Jewish refugees, the report said.
	   It said the anti-Jewish sentiment grew out of centuries of
anti-Semitism, including the teachings of Protestant Reformation
leaders Jean Calvin, Ulrich Zwingli and Martin Luther.
	   Rolf Bloch, head of the Swiss Confederation of Hebrew
Congregations, said he thought Schom had overstated the influence
of the association.
	   Bloch said Switzerland's treatment of some Jewish refugees was
``a dark chapter'' in its history, but that the report appeared
``one-sided and exaggerated.''
	   A U.S. government report on World War II issued last week said
Switzerland had a ``mixed record on refugees,'' including its
request to Germany to mark Jewish passports with a ``J'' _ ``which
helped officials turn back thousands.''
	   But, said the report by Undersecretary of State Stuart
Eizenstat, the record ``also included admission of over 50,000
refugees from 1933 until the end of the War, of whom some 30,000
remained and survived in Switzerland during the War.''
	   Eizenstat noted that a Swiss diplomat in Hungary, Vice Consul
Carl Lutz, ``acted on his own initiative to provide letters of
protection that saved the lives of 62,000 Jews and other targets of
Nazi persecution.''
	   Thomas Borer, who heads the Swiss government's task force
reexamining the country's past, said of the report, ``It is so
absurd and wrong.''
	   ``No serious historian will dispute the fact that the great
majority of the Swiss were outspoken democrats and antifascists,''
he said.
	   He quoted Eizenstat as saying, ``The Swiss people were
overwhelmingly sympathetic to the Allies.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Swiss Banks-Nazi Groups; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
