<BODY>
<SLUG> ANWAR-BACK-LEADERS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Anwar: Back leaders who care for the people, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Anwar: Back leaders who care for the people, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Azran AzizASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LIPIS, Sun. - Deputy Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar
Ibrahim has called on the people to continue giving their support
to leaders who have their welfare at heart.
	   ``We have to train and give support to leaders who always think
about how to resolve the problems of the people,'' he said at a
meet-the-people session in Kampung Tanjung Gahai.
	   He said Umno had always emphasised this and elected
representatives from the party had also been subscribing to this
principle.
	   Anwar said this was a positive sign in Umno and in the
leadership of the country.
	   In jest, he said he was ``reluctant'' to come to Lipis as
divisional chief Datuk Omar Othman would enquire a lot about
projects for the people.
	   ``This is not for himself but for the masses such as public
projects and rural developments like schools and bridges,'' he
said.
	   Anwar said he had known Omar ``for a long time'' and he (Omar)
had never asked something for himself. Anwar added that this was
the attitude that should be emulated.
	   He said the Government would continue with efforts to eradicate
poverty and provide development in rural areas despite the lean
times.
	   On a request by community leaders that a bridge be built across
Sungai Jelai, Anwar, who is Finance Minister, assured the villagers
that the Government would implement the project.
	   ``However, we may not be able to build a proper bridge due to
the high cost. I have asked the State Government to come up with a
plan for a medium-cost bridge,'' he said.
	   Sungai Jelai cuts across Kampung Tanjung Gahai and 80 primary
schoolchildren have to use boats to get to their school located
across the river.
	   Also present were Menteri Besar Tan Sri Mohd Khalil Yaakob, his
deputy Datuk Hasan Arifin, State Executive Councillors, State
Secretary Datuk Abdul Ghani Sulaiman and community leaders.
	   Anwar had earlier launched the Cameron Descent '98 Whitewater
Race at Jeram Musuh Karam.
	   
</TEXT>
