<HEADLINE>
Fil-Estate Develops First Golf Course Community in Bicol, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Fil-Estate Develops First Golf Course Community in Bicol, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Full-blast development of the first golf course-residential
community in the Bicol region formally started on June 6 on a
120-hectare property in Naga City, Camarines Sur.
	   Top officials of giant property developer Fil-Estate Land Inc.,
chaired by lawyer Ferdinand T. Santos will lead the groundbreaking
rites for Isarong Hills Residential Estates and Golf &AMP; Country Club
which is a joint project with the landowner families of Antonio
Austria and Rogelio Tormes.
	   Nestled at the foot of cloud-draped Mt. Isarog, the newest
Fil-Estate multi-billion peso flagship project will have the
biggest and most exclusive village clubhouse in Bicol designed to
be the focal point of Naga City's life, and an 18-hole championship
course designed by Golden Bear International owned by golfing
legend Jack Nicklaus.
	   Exclusive to residents, the village clubhouse will be equipped
with a lanai, multi-purpose function rooms, lounge, Olympic-type
swimming pool, tennis court, basketball court, children's pool and
picnic grounds.
	   The golf course amenities will also include a driving range, and
a grand clubhouse with a 120-seat golfer's veranda with dining
facilities, bar, pro shop, men's and ladies' custom-built locker
rooms, and shower rooms.
	   Santos said that Isarog Hills was a major part of the company's
aggressive nationwide expansion program, especially in high-growth
areas where the conglomerate is now concentrating on projects with
high revenue potential.
	   ''We are now giving top priority to projects that are less
capital-intensive but yield more revenues such as residential
subdivisions, as well as golf and country clubs and resorts,''
Santos said.
	   The Fil-Estate chair, however, emphasized that all horizontal
and vertical projects that have been started by the conglomerate
will be completed.
	   ''This is Fil-Estate's commitment to all our buyers and
investors,'' Santos stressed.
	   The Fil-Estate Group recently obtained key government permits
for most of its multi-billion peso projects which should allow the
property giant to start marketing and development of these
township, leisure estates, and tourism centers.
	   Among them are: Harbor Town in Nasugbu, Batangas; Caliraya;
Newport Hills in Lian, Batangas; the Tagaytay tourism estate; the
commercial complex at Pioneer St., Mandaluyong City; and Camp John
Hay in Baguio City.
	   
