<SLUG> SAVING-CHILDREN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Saving children from armed conflicts, THE INDEPENDENT
</HEADLINE>
Saving children from armed conflicts, THE INDEPENDENT &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   THE INDEPENDENT
   BANGLADESH
   ENGLISH
   Feizal SamathASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A top UN official who is armed with a mandate to seek the
protection of children caught in war zones worldwide, has reported
some success in Sri Lanka. Olara Otunnu, UN Secretary General Kofi
Annan's special representative on children in armed conflict, who
was on a week-long visit to Sri Lanka, said both the warring
government forces and Tamil rebels have agreed children should not
be victims of war. 'I hope we can send a message to the world that
children in Sri Lanka, ... (will) not be abused and brutalised in
the manner that conflicts (used to) affect their lives,'' he said
in Colombo, recently, before he left. Otunnu, a former Ugandan
foreign minister and once his country's permanent representative to
the UN, held meeting with President Chandrika Kumaratunga and
parliamentarians from both ruling and opposition parties.
	   In addition, making use of a two-day ceasefire brokered by the
UN children's agency UNICEF, he visited the war zones and talked
with government military commanders, Tamil rebel leaders, community
representatives and children. 'I have seen and heard a tremendous
yearning for peace on the part of everybody in this country and
that has impressed me,'' he told an audience in Colombo of UN
officials, foreign donor agencies, parliamentarians,
non-governmental organisation (NGOs) and child rights activists
before he left. Otunnu said that more than two million children
have died in wars worldwide in the decade up to 1997. In addition,
one million children were orphaned, more than five million disabled
and more than 250,000 children under 18 years used in armed combat.
He said more than 90 percent of the casualties in the big wars this
decade, were civilians.
	   'This is a world upside down. It is a situation where warfare is
being conducted specifically for the purpose of targetting,
humiliating, destroying and annihilating civilian populations,'' he
noted. The UN official said the impact of war on children should be
addressed urgently, and steps taken for their protection like the
creation of fire-free zones in localities where there are
hospitals, schools, school buses and playgrounds. 'We must do
everything in our power to ameliorate the suffering and conditions
of children even as war is raging within a particular zone,'' he
said, adding that women and children would continue to suffer the
psychological and emotional scars of war for many years after the
conflict ends. 'Healing is critical. Healing is important to
reintegrate those who have suffered and make them productive. But
healing is also important because it is the only way to break the
cycle of violence, for those who are abused today could well be the
abusers of tomorrow,'' Otunnu said.
	   The UN official said he was deeply moved by the spirit and the
fortitude of Sri Lankans living amongst difficult conditions in
conflict areas and said he was amazed at 'the incredible courage of
those residents.'' But he stressed that his mandate was purely
humanitarian and ruled out UN intervention in seeking an end to the
15-year war in which Tamil rebels claiming to represent Sri Lanka's
minority Tamil population are fighting for an independent homeland.
'My concern is for the protection and welfare of all children, to
whatever community they belong to, whatever party or whatever side
of the dividing zone,'' Otunnu said in response to reports brought
back by local aid workers that many ordinary people who met the top
U.N official in the war zone had pleaded for U.N or third party
intervention to end the prolonged war. A sudden flurry of visits,
earlier of US ambassador to the United Nations, Bill Richardson,
the Commonwealth Secretary General Emeka Anyaoku, have sparked
speculation that the government and rebels may now be open to
foreign mediation.
	   Both the previous rounds of peace talks were initiated by the
government, but they collapsed before they made any serious
headway. An estimated 50,000 combatants and civilians have died in
the fighting that has devastated Sri Lanka's north and east. At a
news conference that followed his speech, Otunnu said the rebels
had agreed not to recruit children below 18 years in combat, to
allow the free movement of displaced people to areas under
government control, and not to interfere in the distribution of
humanitarian supplies to civilians in war zones. They had also
promised to take review strategies to take care to prevent
civilians from getting caught in the conflict.
	   The Tiger rebels, the world's best trained guerrilla group, has
with chilling results launched several attacks in the capital
Colombo. 'There can be no defence, no justification, no cause that
can justify the deliberate targetting of civilian populations
anywhere within this island,'' the UN official said he told the
government and Tiger political leader Thamilselvan and top
ideologue Anton Balasingham during his talks.Sri Lanka's military
doubts if the rebels could be trusted to keep the pledges made to
Otunnu. Even before the UN official had left, the military had
accused the Tigers of breaking the truce by attacking government
forces in two incidents.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 THE INDEPENDENT all rights reserved as
distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
