	   KOTA BARU, Sun.- Mara is prepared to provide counselling to its
sponsored student detained with three other Malaysians by British
police for alleged involvement in Internet fraud involving
thousands of British pounds, said Entrepreneur Development Minister
Datuk Mustapa Mohamed.
	   ``We assume they are still innocent until the court decides
otherwise,''
	   he said when asked about the arrest of the four Malaysian
students.
	   He said he had yet to receive the full report of the incident.
	   The four were produced before a magistrate's court in Stoke on
Trent, about 240km north-west of London, on Thursday and charged
with conspiracy to defraud.
	   They were identified as Shafiq Rizal Shaaba, 24, Cek Norlie Md
Shah, 23, Riza Musauwir, 23, and Khairul Anwar Ariffin, 24.
	   The three male students are studying at the University of
Staffordshire while the lone female student, who police alleged was
their accomplice, is a student of the University of Liverpool.
	   Shafiq and Norlie are Mara and Public Service
Department-sponsored students while the others are privately
sponsored.
	   
