<SLUG> MEDICAL-UNITY-PROPOSED sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Conversion of Existing Condominiums Into Condotels, Medical Units Proposed, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Conversion of Existing Condominiums Into Condotels, Medical Units Proposed, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   A prominent economists has proposed the conversion of existing
condominiums units into condotels, medical and health care service
units, and offices to ease the glut facing the local condominium
market.
	   In a paper titled Plunge into the Hard Times, Marcelo de la
Cruz, president of the Summit Research and Consultancy Inc., said
that in doing so, the cost of transfer or conversion of existing
buildings will be low and assets will not be highly specialized.
	   De la Cruz cited that the local condominium market faces severe
glut in the coming years, saying that condominium developers will
be affected most since there is a huge number of units that will be
completed in the next few years.
	   ''We predict that close to 8,500 condominium units will be
unoccupied between 1998 and 2000,'' he said. The market demand per
annum is currently anemic at 1,760 units, and market supply is
growing on the average at 3,160 units.
	   De la Cruz explained that the supply of condominium units is
about 61% of what the market can absorb. Absorption rate is
expected to deteriorate below 5% in 1998 when large supply will be
made available. And further deterioration is expected in 1999 and
2000.
	   ''Now that the pace of growth has faltered, the sprouting
skyscrapers seem a symptom less of success than of pain to come,''
he said.
	   Official statistics show that the construction industry's real
gross national product registered a negative 4.4% growth for the
first quarter of this year, a far cry compared to 21.3% growth in
the same period last year.
	   De la Cruz pointed out that fierce competition and price war are
anticipated in this sector. The construction of at least 21
buildings has already been postponed, shelved or stopped, with more
than 4,500 planned units disappearing.
	   About 14,000 condominiums units will be available from 1998 to
2000. Almost three quarters of the units will be located in the
Makati central business district and its adjacent places.
	   ''If developers continue with their plans, the condominium
market will have a tremendous glut. By the turn of the century, the
number of units will total to 32,057,'' he said.
	   Since the second quarter of 1997, De la Cruz noted, the
transaction volumes on this sector have been minimal. The renewed
buying activity on this segment cannot be seen until the interest
rates drop below 20%.
	   With so many condominium units in the market, they will be
choosy.
	   Affordability, quality and right financing facilities are the
crucial factors in pushing the demand higher in the years to come.
	   ''What is happening to the condominium market must serve as a
wake-up call for developers. We would like to bring to their
attention to switch strategy now before its too late,'' he said.
	   De la Cruz stressed that the adage, ''think twice before you
leap'' must be modified for real estate developers. They must not
only think twice, but thrice or even four times before they decide
to pursue a project.
	   Oftentimes, he said, what happens is that developers get caught
up in the euphoria and optimism surrounding the initial phase of a
new construction that they fail to take an objective step
backwards.
	   In this case, the best strategy would be to enlist the support
of the third-party whose opinions of the market and the feasibility
of the project are unbiased.
	   Because the property sector now demands nerve of steel from its
players, this steel might as well be tempered with a healthy dose
of prudence, De la Cruz said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:MEDICAL-UNITY-PROPOSED sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
