<HEADLINE>
Tight credit, high interest rates threaten survival of SMIs, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Tight credit, high interest rates threaten survival of SMIs, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sun. - The credit tightening measure by Bank
Negara in addition to high interest rates have threatened the
survival of small and medium scale enterprises.
	   Umno Youth Economic Council chairman Dr Abdul Rahim Mohd Ghouse
said today, the current interest rate level had not only made it
more difficult for SMIs to obtain loans but had also impeded the
nation's growth.
	   ``We urge the Government to take quick measures to reduce the
current high interest rate which is leaving behind an array of
problems to the various industrial sectors, entrepreneurs and the
public at large.
	   ``About 25,000 small and medium scale enterprises are in
diffcult financial situation due to limited cash flow resulting
from an escalation cost of raw material, labour delay in obtaining
payment and capital restriction,'' he said when tabling a proposed
blueprint entitled the Strategies for the Strengthening of the
National Economy at the Putra World Trade Centre.
	   The blueprint was presented in conjunction with the half-day
Strengthening of the National Economy Congress organised by the
Umno Youth.
	   Apart from underlining the movement's views and proposals on the
roles of the private and public sectors in facing the current
economic difficulties, it also highlights the various means for the
Government to carry out its policy to protect the interest of the
people.
	   Abdul Rahim said while external factors like globalisation,
liberalisation and deregulation were not within the nation's
control, the proposed blueprint recognised the importance of a fair
distribution of the nation's wealth.
	   ``Although non-Bumiputeras can be allowed to acquire the
majority stake at company level, the equity at the industry level
should be clearly spelt out among Bumiputeras, non-Bumiputeras and
foreign investors.
	   In addition to foreign direct investment, the blueprint also
supported the introduction of bonds similar to the one introduced
by Syarikat Perumahan Negara for strategic fields like education,
agriculture and infrastructure.
	   It also called on the Government to fix a benchmark to reduce
the expenditure on the short and long term import of food products.
	   
</TEXT>
