<HEADLINE>
Asian Flu Downs 4th RP Bank, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Asian Flu Downs 4th RP Bank, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Jenniffer D. BaldivinoASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Monetary Board, the central bank's policy-making body, has
closed Commonwealth Savings Bank, the fourth bank to run into
financial problems since Asia's currency crisis hit in July last
year.
	   Another bank - Fortune Savings and Loans Bank - was reported to
be experiencing financial difficulties but monetary officials
refused to comment.
	   Commonwealth Savings, a small thrift bank, was taken over by the
Monetary Board last Friday, said Aurora Baldos, vice president for
claims, receivership and liquidation of the Philippine Deposit
Insurance Corp.(PDIC).
	   Baldos said the takeover team was now conducting an inventory of
the bank's assets and liabilities.
	   PDIC acts as receiver of banks closed by the Bangko Sentral ng
Pilipinas.
	   As a receiver, it gathers, controls and takes charge of the
assets and liabilities of insolvent banks.
	   Commonwealth Savings is the fourth bank in the country to close
its doors since Asia's currencies tumbled, triggering high interest
rates across the region.
	   Orient Commercial Banking Corp., Richmond Bank and Mindanao
Development Bank went on holiday after failing to recover from a
string of bad loans.
	   A central bank official said Commonwealth Savings had been in
the red over the past three years due to a high level of past due
loans that eroded its portfolio.
	   As of the first quarter of the year, the bank's deposit
liabilities have reached P14 million.
	   PDIC has 90 days to come up with a rehabilitation plan before
Commonwealth Savings is offered to potential investors.
	   BSP Deputy Governor Alberto Reyes said the closure of
Commonwealth Savings would have little effect on the local banking
industry.
	   ``The situation is not alarming... The problems were identified
as early as last year,'' said Reyes.
	   Commonwealth Savings is owned by the Yutingco family, majority
owner of the Eyco group of companies. The Eyco group, a
manufacturer of electric fans, has also been declared insolvent by
government regulators.
	   Commonwealth Savings has only two branches in Metro Manila.
	   A company source said the bank's owners had a hard time meeting
the central bank's required capital build-up for thrift banks.
	   The central bank has required thrift banks to put up P200
million worth of capital as of February this year and P250 million
by the end of the year.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
