<HEADLINE>
Cepalco's System Loss Down To 7.47%, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Cepalco's System Loss Down To 7.47%, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Cagayan Electric Power &AMP; Light Co. Inc. (Cepalco) has reduced
its power systems loss to 7.47%, lower than the maximum level
imposed by law at 13.25%.
	   Cepalco said its interruption frequency rate (IFR) was 55.6%
lower than the standard rate, while its cumulative interruption
time (CIT) was 48.76% lower than the standard rate.
	   The company's average time to restore power due to outages was
3.33% faster than the standard.
	   Cepalco is one of the few power utilities with a reserve
capacity supplied by a producer other than the state-owned National
Power Corp. (Napocor).
	   A stand-by power of 25% has helped consumers to avoid the
equivalence of 33 days of the total blackout since the middle of
1995.
	   The power company has also exceeded all reliability and
technical standards prescribed by the Department of Energy (DOE).
Its performances is among the best offered by any power utility in
the country.
	   Records of the technical performances of Cepalco showed that its
interruption frequency rate (IFR) in 1997 was much better that the
national standard set by the DOE.
	   The DOE standard for IFR is five frequencies per annum, while
Cepalco's actual performances last year was only 2.22 times or
55.6% lower that the national standard.
	   Its performance is passed on to all its customers in terms of
quality service, yet its average weighted rate per kilowatt hour
(kwh) of P2.75 is lower than those of the rest of the existing
power utilities in Mindanao.
	   Cepalco's performances has consistently been among the best in
the country, always surpassing all reliability standards prescribed
by the DOE for all electric utilities in the country.
	   The company gets its power supply from the Mindanao Energy
Systems (Minergy) which became operational in July 1995 and
Napocor.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
