<BODY>
<SLUG> BUILD-CARING-SOCIETY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`Compassion, empathy essential to build caring society', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`Compassion, empathy essential to build caring society', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sun. - Young people must be taught compassion and
empathy and a sensitivity to values if the country wanted a more
caring society, said Action for the Betterment of Community
co-chairman Datuk J.
	   Jagadeesan.
	   He said success in instilling these three qualities would be of
great help in human values development among the youth. The end
result would be a more caring citizen.
	   With that in mind, ABC and youth from the San Peng Zone 2 area
co- organised an outing today for 25 children from Rumah Hope, 27
from the Community Rehabilitation Centre and 10 from the Kuala
Lumpur Deaf Society.
	   They were taken to Zoo Negara.
	   The project, it is hoped, will help young people to become
better aware of the presence of others who are less privileged.
	   The San Peng Zone 2 area is identified as one of the most
problematic areas in the city, where drugs and other social
problems run rampant.
	   Project chairman Anthony Arulananthan said the outing was a much
awaited trip for the youth as it ``gives them a reason to go out''
and meet others.
	   He said the experience would give these young people an exposure
to others who were less fortunate, thus helping them to feel more
positive about themselves and their own surroundings.
	   Volunteer Asrul Nizam, 17, from the Sri Selangor Flats said that
to him the outing was an eye-opener as he had never met any
handicapped children before this.
	   ``It is fun to actually get to know the children, exchange
greetings and play with them.
	   ``It gives me a deeper feeling of understanding and caring for
another human being, though they may be strangers at first,'' he
said.
	   Volunteer Zulkifli Nazri, 16, also from the Sri Selangor Flats
said the chance to meet the handicapped and less fortunate children
``touched my heart''.
	   ``Instead of always complaining about the way I live and the
quality of my life, the trip has now changed the way I look at
things,'' he said.
	   The outing was co-organised under the auspices of the Sathya Sai
Central Council of Malaysia, fully supported by the Friendship
Group for Human Values and A Caring Society, the City Hall and the
Social Action Initiative Foundation.
	   The Action for the Betterment of Community is designed as an
experimental programme to see if non-governmental organisations
working wth relevant authorities can help create greater value
consciousness and thus check the decline in negative behaviour in
an area identified as being among the most problem-ridden in the
city.
	   Zone 2 of the San Peng Flats includes the City Hall flats in
Jalan Loke Yew, Jalan Hang Tuah, Sri Selangor, Sri Sarawak, Sri
Pahang, Bukit Kerinchi, Bukit Bangsar, Bukit Kiara, Razak Mansion
and Kampung Muhibbah, Puchong.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
