<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Cell Phones, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Italy awards third mobile phone license to consortium
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with criticism by opposition, Berlusconi
part of losing consortium, winner's projections; no pickup &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ The government on Tuesday awarded Italy's third
mobile phone license to the state electric utility and French and
German phone companies.
	   The consortium of ENEL, Deutsche Telekom and France Telecom,
called Wind, beat out two other groups, led by British Telecom and
Bell Canada International, in the hugely lucrative cell phone
market.
	   Europe's largest market for mobiles is Italy, where there are
some 13.5 million mobile phone users. Some analysts say that market
will be worth about 18 trillion lire (dlrs 10.32 billion) by the
end of next year, and that the third operator can expect to hold
some 2 percent of it by then.
	   The choice drew criticism from opposition politicians, who said
it amounted to expanding government control over the economy.
	   Wind is 51 percent owned by ENEL, which itself is controlled by
the Treasury, although that stake will come down when other Italian
investors are brought in. Deutsche Telekom and France Telecom split
the other 49 percent.
	   The decision is ``the latest demonstration of the (center-left)
government's partisanship,'' said Italo Bocchino, a Parliament
deputy for the right-wing National Alliance party.
	   ``After years of talking about privatization, it is taking the
first good opportunity to put a strategic sector under state
control,'' he said.
	   Wind set goals of more than 8 million clients and revenues of 10
trillion lire (dlrs 5.73 billion) by 2007.
	   Telecom Italia has around 75 percent of the Italian cell phone
market, while Omnitel, controlled by Olivetti SpA and Germany's
Mannesmann AG, has the rest.
	   One of the losers in the decision was Silvio Berlusconi, the
media magnate, former premier and now leader of the center-right
opposition in Parliament.
	   Berlusconi's Mediaset group was part of the British Telecom
consortium, and has long been trying to crack the cell phone
market.
	   Before the license was awarded, telecommunications minister
Antonio Maccanico told reporters that increased competition would
lead to lower prices and better service.
	   He declined to say whether there would be a fourth license
awarded before the end of the year, as some in the industry have
demanded. The government has only pledged to look into awarding a
fourth license.
	   (dj/djw)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Italy-Cell Phones, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
