<HEADLINE>
Hiring of foreign nurses suspended, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Hiring of foreign nurses suspended, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   MUAR, Sun. - In view of the current economic situation, the
Health Ministry has suspended the recruitment of foreign nurses
except those for the critical services.
	   Health Minister Datuk Chua Jui Meng said the 300 foreign nurses
from India, Bangladesh, the Philippines, Myanmar and Indonesia
currently attached to various hospitals were also likely to be sent
home once their contracts expired.
	   He, however, said the ministry would make an exception for
highly qualified and capable nurses.
	   ``The ministry is evaluating their performance to ascertain if
there is a need to retain them,'' he told reporters after opening
the RM400,000 three- storey Zhongtian Temple today.
	   Chua said to ease the shortage of nursing staff in critical
medical services with the departure of foreign staff, the ministry
planned to engage Malaysian nurses working abroad and those serving
with private hospitals in the country on contract basis.
	   ``We are cutting down the hiring of foreign nurses. We have
already sent many of them back. But we will consider extending the
contracts of those whose service records have been excellent.''
	   Chua said the ministry had set up many nurses' training colleges
and centres to cope with the increasing demand for nursing care.
	   He said with some 3,000 nurses graduating every year, the
country would have enough nurses by the year 2003 to fill all
vacancies in hospitals, clinics, and health centres.
	   The ministry, he said, would also continue to promote assistant
nurses to staff nurses once they had completed their conversion
courses.
	   Chua stressed that the Government's austerity drive had not
affected the quality of medical services and nursing care provided
by hospitals and clinics.
	   ``Though the number of patients seeking treatment at hospitals
and clinics is increasing, we will continue to find ways to meet
their needs and provide quality services to all, especially the
low-income wage earners.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
