<BODY>
<SLUG> MOVING-AHEAD-WITH-IT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Moving ahead with IT, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Moving ahead with IT, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Noor AmalASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THESE days, we are seeing a number of words with an ``E''
prefix, such as e- commerce and e-business, mesmerising the world
with promises of erasing geographical boundaries and defining new
ways of doing businesses.
	   However, with the Asia-Pacific region more concerned with
economic stability, is this the right time to talk about building
the E-world?
	   ``It is true we are seeing weaker markets around the region.
Consumer spending have clearly been impacted by the economic
downturn,'' said Hewlett-Packard's corporate vice president, and
Asia-Pacific operations president and managing director Dick
Warmington.
	   He added the region is also experiencing delays in major
information technology (IT) infrastructure projects, but the good
news is that the information age is not going to come to a
standstill because of the economic turmoil. ``The digital economy
is going ahead at full speed - crisis or no crisis. We simply
cannot afford to ignore the trend,''
	   Warmington said at the HP Builds the Electronic World
Asia-Pacific Press Symposium in Sydney.
	   He said some of the driving forces behind the implementation of
IT, even in times of crisis, are fundamental factors in wealth
creation, namely intellectual capital and digitised network
knowledge.
	   Some experts predicted that intellectual capital will be equal
to, if not greater than, traditional factors such as money, goods
and land.
	   Businesses and governments across the world are redefining their
organisations and core competencies to be successful in this new
world.
	   ``If you look around the region, countries like Australia,
Singapore, Malaysia, China, and Taiwan are doing the right thing by
not backing down from major or national IT initiatives,'' said
Warmington.
	   In fact, these countries recognise that if there is a time to
push ahead with IT, this is the time. They see IT as necessary for
pushing national and organisational competitiveness and improving
productivity. At these levels, IT is not a discretionary expense
even though it may come under increased expense control measures.
	   In Australia, the budget that was unveiled just a few weeks ago
provides a generous tax concession for companies to upgrade or buy
new software systems to fix the millennium bug. The package will
cost the Australian government millions in foregone revenue. But
they have recognised the need for businesses to protect and upgrade
their IT environments.
	   In Singapore, there is a strong government commitment towards IT
projects. The Singapore government recognises this period as an
opportunity to differentiate the country as an IT powerhouse in the
region.
	   ``HP, for instance, is providing the infrastructure, products
and services to manage the Singapore government's One Call Project.
HP's solutions integrate knowledge-based systems with interactive
voice response so that the public will always get their phone
answered and a government officer handling enquiries will be able
to access information online and deal efficiently with the call,''
said Warmington.
	   This, he added, is the first step the country is taking to
realising the future vision where members of the public need only
to remember one number to reach any government department.
	   ``Dealing with the civil servants in Singapore will be very easy
and a pleasant experience. This is leadership by example,'' he
said.''Even in Malaysia, a country in the thick of the crisis,
Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir Mohamad has reiterated his
commitment to continue with the development of the Multimedia Super
Corridor (MSC).''
	   Warmington said Malaysia is taking a bold step by offering an
open testbed, unencumbered by existing legislation and regulations
that plagued old environments.
	   ``The Prime Minister realised if Malaysia put the MSC on the
backburner, it will negatively impact the country's future economic
competitiveness.
	   All of these are clear examples where governments are harnessing
the power of IT to help improve the nations' productivity and
competitiveness,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
