<HEADLINE>
Amnesty urges release of Nigerian political prisoners
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) _ Reacting to the death of military
leader Gen. Sani Abacha, Amnesty International on Tuesday urged
Nigeria's new leader to release political prisoners and improve the
country's human rights records.
	   ``Major-General Abdulsalam Abubakar should break with the
country's legacy of repression and give the Nigerian people hope
for the future,'' London-based Amnesty said in a statement received
in the West African country of the Ivory Coast.
	   Among others, the group called for the release of Moshood
Abiola, a leading Nigerian businessman and presumed winner of
aborted 1993 presidential elections.
	   Abiola has been jailed and charged with treason since 1994, when
he declared himself president.
	   Abiola is the most prominent political prisoner in Nigeria.
	   ``Africa's most populous nation cannot fulfill its economic and
political potential if military governments continue blocking the
momentum for reform,'' Amnesty said.
	   The group's call for respect of human rights and democracy
echoed a message from leaders around the world who said Tuesday
they hope Abubakar would honor a transition program aimed at
handing power over to a civilian government.
	   Nigeria's ruling military junta has been accused of widespread
human rights abuses, including arbitrary arrests, torture and
extrajudicial killings.
	   Outspoken journalists and pro-democracy activists are frequently
detained without trials or forced into exile, Amnesty says.
