<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Belarus-US, 5th Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
American, other ambassadors resist Belarus eviction orders
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with State Dept. saying deadline extended. &QL; 
 &UR; By MARINA BABKINA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MINSK, Belarus (AP) _ The foreign minister of Belarus warned
ambassadors Tuesday that unless they vacate a diplomatic complex,
the facility could wind up ``floating in its own sewage.''
	   The U.S. ambassador and others have refused to leave the
compound, which is home to 22 diplomats and their families, saying
the government's eviction orders are a violation of international
law.
	   The Foreign Ministry of the former Soviet republic expressed
regret for the ``inconvenience,'' but insisted the officials must
leave their homes in the 50-year-old Drozdy housing complex on the
outskirts of Minsk to permit urgent repairs.
	   ``There is a danger that Drozdy will float in its own sewage,''
Foreign Minister Ivan Antonovich said Tuesday on Belarusian state
radio. ``We can't endanger diplomats' lives''
	   The ambassadors say that under international law, their
residences are considered sovereign territory and governments have
no right to enter without permission or insist that diplomats
leave.
	   ``These measures are unacceptable and inadmissible,'' French
Foreign Minister spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret said in Paris.
``They are contrary to the Vienna Convention on diplomatic
privileges and immunity.''
	   The United States, Russia, France, Germany and Lithuania have
formally protested the planned eviction. France and Lithuania said
they will recall their ambassadors for consultations if Belarus
persists, and Washington has said it will also take some action in
response.
	   But Antonovich said the issue is not political, it's practical.
And he suggested that foreign countries are overreacting because
they are biased against Belarus, whose authoritarian president has
been criticized in the West.
	   ``There is a tendency to render political coloring to this on
the part of those who are ready to view all events in Belarus only
from political side,'' he said. ``Unfortunately, it is a double
standard.''
	   The dispute began in April when the government served notice
that the ambassadors would have to vacate their homes in the
rambling, wooded housing compound by Wednesday.
	   In Washington, State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said
Belarusian authorities had extended the deadline by one week, to
June 17. He said Ambassador-at-large Steve Sestanovich summoned the
Belarusian charge d'affaires to protest the eviction notices.
	   ``We have pointed out very clearly at a variety of levels to
Belarus that it is not too late to reverse the self-destructive
course the government has chosen,'' Rubin said.
	   Picks up 11th graf pvs, `Belarus says ...'
	   (ls) 	   
</TEXT>
