<HEADLINE>
Rohana Jalil's still hitting it off, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Rohana Jalil's still hitting it off, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Zainal Alam KadirASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FANS of Rohana Jalil brace yourself. One of Malaysia's
longest-serving singers (since the Seventies) is recording a new
album which will include some of her best-loved hits.
	   According to a Press release from her recording company NSR, the
album may include hit songs such as Rintik Rintik Hujan, Cinta Yang
Terbiar, Rayuanku and Perjalananku, all of which will be given new
arrangements and perspectives.
	   The album, expected out by year end, will be produced by Jimmy
Ali.
	   HOW would you like to win prizes lying down, while listening to
the radio? Of course it's possible, especially if you're a metal
maniac who listens to Time Highway Radio (THR).
	   Pony Canyon's bands - Pilgrims, F.T.G and Necromanicide - and
THR invite you to be with them between 1pm and 5pm daily from today
until June 19.
	   If you're lucky to get a line and the right answers to the quiz,
you will win compact discs by your favourite groups. For more info,
tune in to the station.
	   REVIEWS KARMA - Karma (Warner Music): It took seven years for
Azman Warren and his friends, otherwise known as Karma, come out
with this album, but it's worth the wait.
	   The band, once under Roslan Aziz Productions (RAP), took quite a
while to select suitable material. Apparently, the years also saw
several line- up changes, hence the delay.
	   Karma's self-titled debut effort is a mature and rather
unconventional (if you compare it with other Malay rock bands)
effort. All the songs are engaging with meaningful lyrics
(including those by Mukhlis Noor), while the uncluttered and
sophisticated arrangements make the album a winner.
	   Nothing hard-rocking here but who cares? Azman's voice and
singing style is the main strength of the album. Just listen to the
first two tracks and you'll know you're in for a good time.
	   Performance: REDANG - Qasidah Nuraisha (Ambang Klasik): As the
title suggests, expect a lot of fusion work all the genres you
could think of that make up Malaysian music. From traditional
instruments to ethnic sounds, combined with modern sensibility,
this album represents a form of unity.
	   Redang's music has that rather attractive ``dark undertone'',
especially with the overlapping of wails, chants and drones that
create a rather sombre ambience. If you're not into conventional
straight-forward lyrics, this album could be for you. The songs are
laced with ``artistic expressions'' and poetic metaphors.
Occasionally, they do come out rather blur, though. Still, Redang's
debut is a good start for a ``different'' kind of music movement.
	   Performance: VARIOUS ARTISTES - Kenangan Abadi Ilham Seni
Seniman Agung P. Ramlee (Life Records): This is proof that P.
Ramlee's songs are as versatile as he was. These numbers could be
performed by almost any self-respecting singer in different ways.
	   In this album, for instance, we have Hetty Koes Endang's version
of Jangan Tinggal Daku with that certain bossa nova touch, Noraniza
Idris' traditional-feel Jari Jariku Sakit Semua, and Imam S.
Arifin's dangdut version of Engkau Laksana Bulan. The more
``contemporary'' sounds can be heard in Iis Sugianto's light and
jazzy Azizah as well as Domino's a capella version of Ku Rindu
Padamu.
	   Most of the songs are lifted from albums recorded over the years
by a variety of singers. For sentimentalists, this is definitely a
good listen.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
