	   PETALING JAYA, Sun. - Media baron Rupert Murdoch who flew in for
a short visit today held talks with Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr
Mahathir Mohamad and his deputy Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim.
	   The chairman of News Corp - a global film, publishing and
television group - saying he ``was just passsing through'' also
visited the Astro station in Sungei Besi. Astro has a collaboration
with Murdoch's Hong Kong-based Star channel.
	   Met at the Sultan Abdul Aziz Shah Airport in Subang before his
departure to China, Murdoch said he did not discuss anything about
his business interest or the region's economic problems with Dr
Mahathir and Anwar.
	   ``I was just passing through. We talked on world affairs,'' he
said.
	   Asked whether his visit could be a prelude to him acquiring
stakes in local companies to expand his media empire, he reiterated
that this was not the case.
	   Present at the airport to see him off was Tan Sri T. Ananda
Krishnan, head of Measat Broadcasting Sdn Bhd which runs Astro. He
said Murdoch was very helpful and supportive of Malaysia.
	   ``He (Murdoch) says Malaysia is a wonderful place to do business
and invest.''
	   He added that Murdoch also expressed his confidence in the
country's economy, adding that it would recover from the existing
downturn. However, Ananda said Murdoch did not indicate if he was
interested to invest here.
	   
