<SLUG> CONSUMERS-NEED-RIGHTS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`Consumers need to be aware of their rights', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`Consumers need to be aware of their rights', NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ramlan SaidASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sun. - Consumers have every right to complain of
poor utility services arising out of negligence.
	   National Consumer Protection Council chairman Datuk Moehamed
Izat Emir today said consumers must be well-informed and
articulate.
	   Alluding to the water crisis affecting parts of Klang Valley, he
said besides creating awareness, consumer associations could play a
significant role in evaluating the efficiency of services like
roads, electricity, telephone and water supply.
	   Consumer understanding of their rights and protection must be
improved in all areas, and the associations must play a bigger role
than fighting price increases.
	   Commenting on the public forum on water which was cancelled
following police refusal to issue a permit to its organiser, Fomca,
he said: ``It is good and healthy to discuss it so that the service
can improve but if the police cancelled it, they must have a good
reason for doing so.''
	   He felt media coverage on consumer associations gave the
impression that their role was confined to prices of goods and
services.
	   The associations should emulate their counterparts in some
developed nations, which had managed to raise the level of
awareness on consumer rights.
	   ``Take road crashes as an example. Road users, who are
consumers, must be made to realise that are many factors which
could lead to accidents.
	   ``Carelessness or negligence is often cited as the cause; but
there is also the possibility that poor road design or lack of
safety measures could have contributed to the crash.''
	   In developed nations, consumers know their rights better. They
might sue supermarkets for negligence if they fell while shopping
because the floor was wet.
	   Moehamed Izat reckoned the level of consumer protection in
Malaysia was still far from satisfactory, partly because many
consumers left the task of pursuing the matter to consumer leaders.
	   ``Many never bothered to become members. To be strong, consumer
associations not only need a large membership, but also moral
support from society.''
	   Moehamed Izat said the downturn demonstrated how consumer rights
had been neglected.
	   ``Take banks for example. During good times, customers were
regarded as partners. But when times are bad, even the innocent
clients were affected as they are denied funds.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
