<HEADLINE>
Israeli generals visit Temple Mount 31 years after Old City's
</HEADLINE>
capture &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Israel's defense minister and army generals
past and present toured areas of Jerusalem captured by Israel 31
years ago this week and made a rare visit Tuesday to the Temple
Mount, the site of Islam's third holiest shrine.
	   Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai participated in the tour led
by chief of staff Lt. Gen Amnon Shakak. The group also toured parts
of the West Bank which Israel captured during the June 1967 Mideast
war from Jordan.
	   The Temple Mount complex houses the al Aqsa and Dome of the Rock
mosques which are holy to Islam and is believed to sit atop the
site of the ancient Jewish Temple destroyed in A.D. 70. Groups of
right-wing religious Jews who want to rebuilt the Temple often try
to enter the Temple Mount but are turned back by police who fear
their presence will touch of riots with Arab worshipers on the
site.
	   Ibrahim al Sabri, Jerusalem's highest Muslim cleric, said the
generals presence was not viewed as a threat. ``There is no need
for any coordination. The al Aqsa is of course open for the public
and people of all religions,'' Sabri said.
	   Jerusalem is at the center of the Israeli-Arab conflict. Israel
annexed the eastern half shortly after its capture and the
Palestinians want it as the capital of their future state. The
city's future is slated for talks on a final peace agreement
between the two sides.
