<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Paraguay,0362 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Paraguayan goalie bent on scoring in France
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JUAN ZAMORANO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CLAPIERS, France (AP) - Paraguayan goalkeeper Jose Luis
Chilavert has made it clear he's determined to help his team in the
World Cup anyway he can, even if it means scoring a few goals
himself.
	   Chilavert, one of the best goalkeepers in the world, worked hard
under the crossbar in Tuesday's practice session. Then he switched
roles and fired left-footed free kicks from outside the area,
showing off his power and precision for the benefit of about a
hundred cheering fans.
	   Not only a defensive force, seemingly able to blocks incoming
shots at will, he can also score. Chilavert, of Argentina's Velez
Sarsfield, frequently rushes up the field to take free kicks and
penalty shots, and holds the world record for goals scored by a
goalkeeper.
	   ``Everything's possible in soccer,'' Chilavert said. ``Many used
to think a goalkeeper couldn't score goals and I've tallied 35 in
my 17-year career.''
	   He displays the same competitive attitude when talking about
Paraguay's chances of advancing to the second round of the World
Cup, even though it is clearly the weakest team in a group that
includes favorite Spain, Nigeria and Bulgaria. Paraguay and
Bulgaria open Group D play Thursday in Montpellier.
	   ``Many take it for granted that Spain is the favorite, but we
don't think so. Soccer has levelled throughout and Paraguay is not
below anybody,'' he said.
	   Chilavert shrugs away press criticism following Paraguay's
losses in pre-Cup matches to the Cezch Republic, Romania, Belgium
and the Netherlands, the last one a 5-1 rout.
	   ``There are many jealous people in my country, especially
journalists,'' said the outspoken Chilavert, who refuses to speak
to Paraguayan reporters.
	   His relationship with Brazilian-born coach Paulo Cesar
Carpegiani has also been rocky.
	   Chilavert was not called for several friendly matches this year
after he made disparaging comments about Paraguayan president Juan
Carlos Wasmosy. He will undoubtedly set the tone for the team.
</TEXT>
