<SLUG> TO-RESOLVE-TOYOTA-TARIFF sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tariff Body Sets 3 Ways To Resolve Toyota Tariff, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Tariff Body Sets 3 Ways To Resolve Toyota Tariff, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Angel G. AlegreASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The Tariff Commission has come up with three ways to determine
the duty to be levied on the imports of Toyota Motor Philippines
Corp. under the Asean industrial cooperation (Aico) scheme.
	   Emmanuel Velasco, chair of the commission, said government might
retain the 50% margin of preference or discount on existing rates,
set specific rates for different products that would be entered
under Aico or peg a flat 1.5% tariff under the brand-to-brand
complementation scheme and 3.5% on new products that would be
covered by Aico.
	   Velasco said the interagency tariff and related matters
committee would pick out one option that would apply to Toyota
Philippines.
	   Aico is a pan-Asean cooperation scheme that extends preferential
tariffs of between 0% and 5% to joint-venture projects of at least
two firms each in the Philippines, Malaysia, Indonesia and
Thailand.
	   The scheme is aimed at encouraging manufacturers in southeast
Asia to join forces and take advantage of each other's strengths to
come up with a product that can be sold in the region. All imports
under the scheme will be levied duties of between 0% and 5%. It is
considered as the ``accelerated'' version of the common effective
preferential tariff scheme under the Asean free trade area.
	   Aico replaced the brand-to-brand complementation scheme under
the Asean industrial joint venture, which grants a minimum 50%
margin of preference or tariff rate discounts.
	   Toyota wants the 1.5% tariff it enjoyed under the brand-to-brand
complementation scheme restored instead of 3.5% under Aico.

</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed by
WorldSources, Inc. 	   
