<HEADLINE>
Saudi Arabia denies U.S. asked for delay of Arab summit
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) _ Saudi Arabia denied Tuesday that the
United States had pressured it to delay a proposed Arab summit on
the stalled Middle East peace talks.
	   ``There is no truth at all that the United States has asked
Saudi Arabia to delay (holding) any Arab summit,'' the Saudi royal
court said in a statement.
	   Hopes for holding the conference have faded after several Arab
countries expressed doubts about its outcome.
	   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat had pushed for the summit to
put pressure on Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to accept
a compromise of a further 13 percent pullback in the West Bank.
	   But the United States had reportedly asked Arab leaders to
postpone the summit, arguing that it needed more time to persuade
Netanyahu to accept its suggestions.
