<HEADLINE>
Estrada Backs Sumilao Strikers, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Estrada Backs Sumilao Strikers, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Joan B. TanASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   President-elect Joseph Estrada took up the cudgels yesterday for
17 farmers protesting what they termed as government's illegal
takeover of their property in Sumilao, Bukidnon.
	   Estrada, a popular actor known for his pro-poor semantics, had
lunch with the protesters in front of the Department of Agrarian
Reform in Quezon City.
	   The gesture was interpreted as a signal from the incoming Chief
Executive that he wanted a Supreme Court ruling on the Sumilao case
reversed in favor of the protesting farmers.
	   The high court determined in a recent ruling that the farmers
``are not real parties in interest,'' and ruled in favor of another
group of claimants.
	   Estrada said he disagreed with the court's decision, and vowed
to mobilize a legal team to help the farmers in their appeal.
	   He asked the Supreme Court to prioritize the case.
	   Estrada said the appointment of former leftist leader Horacio
Morales should work in favor of Sumilao's farmers. 
