<SLUG> STRAWBOARD-PLANT-PRODUCT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RP's First Strawboard Plant Begins Production, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
RP's First Strawboard Plant Begins Production, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   The first rice strawboard plant in the country, capable of
manufacturing construction panel boards using rice straw as raw
materials, was inaugurated recently in Sta. Barbara, Iloilo by
President Fidel V. Ramos.
	   Landbank officer-in-charge Jesus F. Diaz said locating the
strawboard plant in Iloilo was consistent with the policy of the
Ramos administration to put up processing plants in the countryside
to boost rural industrialization and decongest urban centers.
	   The construction of the P63-million plant was made possible
through the pooled funds of Landbank, the First Iloilo Area
Marketing Co-op, Cooperative Development Authority, and Cooperative
Union of the Philippines, among others.
	   The strawboard technology was provided by the Department of
Science and Technology. Aside from the funding the construction of
the plant, Landbank, the CDA, FIAMCI and CUP likewise extended
institutional assistance to farmer cooperatives involved in the
rice straw project.
	   The project, aside from providing extra income to rice farmers,
will also supply building materials for the housing industry. A
model house using rice straw with a floor area of 36 square meters
costs only about P136,000.
	   The plant has a daily production capacity equivalent to five
housing units of this size.
	   Rice farmers in Central Panay are expected to earn an extra P2
for every kilo of rice straw which they otherwise burn or discard
as waste. With an annual requirement of at least 5,040 tons of rice
straw, farmers will earn P10.1 million from the annual procurements
of the plant. The plant will need at least 2,520 to 5,040 hectares
of ricelands to fill in the requirement.
	   Initially, the project will supply construction materials for
the housing project of the provincial government of Iloilo. A
similar proposal is being considered for the school buildings of
the Department of Education, Culture and Sports.
	   
</TEXT>
