<SLUG> SOLONS-MAKES-LAST-DITCH sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Solons Make Last Ditch Effort to Save Pork Barrel, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Solons Make Last Ditch Effort to Save Pork Barrel, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Maria Mirasol B.NgASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Lawmakers are still determined to make President-elect Joseph
Estrada soften his stand against the so-called pork barrel funds.
	   Outgoing Negros Oriental Rep. Margarito Teves said that instead
of abolishing pork, government should come up with safeguards to
prevent abuses on the use of pork barrel funds, the derisive term
for the Congressional Initiative Allocation and Countrywide
Development Fund.
	   CDF and CIA were seen by many as source of corruption among
legislators.
	   The incoming President has been very vocal against the
allocation of pork barrel funds in the national budget. He bared
plans to adopt a ``line item''
	   budgeting scheme wherein lawmakers would not anymore be involved
in the implementation of their projects but would only identify
them.
	   But the scheme, according to Teves, would not make any
difference because ``temptation to commit abuses in the use of
these funds will only be transferred from the lawmakers to the
agencies.'' Teves said legislators believed the funds should be
channeled through local executives who were ''more transparent,
effective, and accountable.'' In a memorandum to President Fidel V.
Ramos dated June 3, Teves also proposed that reputable
organizations like the Social Weather Station be tapped to conduct
a survey on the people's sentiments on CDF and CIA.
	   The survey results would guide the incoming administration in
its decision on the pork issue.
	   ``We believe that with the safeguards, congressmen and senators
should still be given the responsibility and opportunity to
identify projects to be funded by the CDF and CIA,'' he stated in
the memorandum.
	   Teves also proposed that lawmakers be required to submit a
periodic report to their constituents on how their respective pork
allocations were used.
	   The report would include name of the projects, location, amount,
names of the contractors, date completed, and the standard cost of
each project as certified by the Pre-qualification Bidding and
Awards Committee (PBAC), District Engineer, and Commission on
Audit.
	   ``This will provide the entire nation with a clearer picture on
how Congress as a whole spent the people's money on physical and
social infrastructure projects,'' he explained.
	   Teves likewise lamented that CDFs and CIAs had been used for
projects and expenses that were ``personal'' in nature like
underwriting luncheon or dinner expenses for civic organizations;
channeling funds to privately owned foundations.
	   A periodic report submitted by each congressman, he said, would
show which projects or expenses were personal in nature.
	   The outgoing lawmaker stressed that CDFs and CIAs should be used
exclusively for physical and social infrastructure projects like
irrigation, farm-to-market roads, school buildings, and
scholarships.
	   Meanwhile, outgoing Bukidnon Rep. Jose Zubiri reiterated his
proposal for Estrada to designate a resident ombudsman to oversee
the projects funded through the pork barrel.
	   The ombudsman, according to Zubiri, would prosecute lawmakers
involved in anomalous projects.
	   ``Some congress members, who are honest, are paying for the
indiscretions of some of their colleagues,'' he noted.
	   He also batted for the junking of the present ``lump sum''
approach to budgeting in favor of the more transparent ``line
item'' budgeting which, he said, would make the pork barrel
obsolete.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
