<SLUG> BC-Guinea-Bissau, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Renegade general calls for transition government while neighboring
</HEADLINE>
states send troops to help quash rebels &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with reports that Senegal and the Republic of Guinea
have sent troops to back government &QL; 
 &UR; By BARRY HATTON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ The leader of renegade soldiers locked
in battle Tuesday with government troops in the West African nation
of Guinea-Bissau called on President Joao Bernardo Vieira to step
down, while neighboring states sent forces to back the government.
	   Former armed forces chief Brig. Gen. Ansumane Mane, in a
handwritten statement sent to the Portuguese news agency Lusa, said
a transition government should be installed to prepare for
elections in July.
	   Mane, describing himself as head of the self-proclaimed Military
Junta for the Consolidation of Democracy, Peace and Justice, said
he had no intention of seizing power himself.
	   In a later message to Lusa, Mane offered negotiations if
government forces ended their siege of rebel troops holed up at
military installations in the suburbs of the capital.
	   Without talks, the fighting will degenerate into ``a
bloodbath,'' Lusa quoted Mane's message as saying.
	   Mane's statements came after the government had launched an
unsuccessful pre-dawn attack aimed at dislodging an unknown number
of rebel soldiers from positions they held.
	   Later Tuesday the Portuguese Secretary of State for Foreign
Communities said forces from neighboring Senegal and the Republic
of Guinea had arrived in Guinea-Bissau to back the government
troops.
	   Jose Lello told reporters in Lisbon that the foreign troops had
artillery and armored vehicles.
	   Lusa reported that 1,300 soldiers had arrived from Senegal and
400 from the Republic of Guinea.
	   The general, fired six months ago during an investigation into
arms trafficking with the separatist rebels of Casamance, a
Senegalese region that borders Guinea-Bissau to the north, had
waited until Saturday to officially step down.
	   In his written statement, Mane accused Vieira of corruption and
abuse of power by meddling in parliamentary affairs.
	   Verification of the statements was not immediately possible.
Diplomats said Mane was illiterate and spoke no Portuguese, only
local tribal languages.
	   There was no immediate reaction available from the president,
who had vowed Sunday to ``use all possible means'' to quash the
revolt swiftly.
	   Foreign Minister Fernando Delfim da Silva called Mane's appeal
for July elections ``a joke.'' Delfim da Silva was interviewed by
phone in Lisbon, where he was stuck because of flight cancellations
to Guinea-Bissau.
	   ``Legislative elections are scheduled for this year and
presidential elections are scheduled for next year,'' he said.
``That is when the mandates for Parliament and the president end
and that's when the ballots will be held. We won't be given orders
by the head of a military junta.''
	   Delfim da Silva said the two military sides were ``deadlocked.''
	   ``The rebels are hemmed in. They're not advancing, but we can't
get them out either,'' he said.
	   Heavy fighting could be heard early in the day at two military
installations in the Bissau suburb of Bra and around the army
headquarters in the suburb of Queije, U.S. embassy spokesman Bryan
Hunt said in a telephone interview with the Lisbon bureau of The
Associated Press.
	   Sporadic mortar and automatic weapons fire continued through the
day and some stray shells hit the Russian embassy, causing slight
damage but no casualties, Hunt said.
	   ``The major offensive by government troops ... was unsuccessful
as far as we can tell. The situation is very unsettled,'' Hunt
said.
	   Hunt said it was not clear which side held the army
headquarters, nor were there any credible figures for the number
killed in the fighting.
	   A reporter for Guinea-Bissau national radio, interviewed by
Lisbon radio TSF on Monday, said he counted 30 bodies scattered
around the bases at Bra.
	   The Bra military installation, which includes a barracks and an
arms depot, is 15 kilometers (10 miles) outside the capital.
	   The nearby international airport remained closed. Peace Corps
representatives and U.S. citizens around the country reported there
was no fighting elsewhere.
	   In downtown Bissau, streets were quiet and people were buying
groceries. Security forces ordered people to return home by noon
(1200GMT), Hunt said.
	   The city power supply was working normally, he said.
	   The ruling PAIGC party said in a statement broadcast on national
radio Tuesday that the government remained in control.
	   The PAIGC _ the Portuguese initials for the African Party for
the Independence of Guinea and Cape Verde _ won the 1994 general
election and has 60 lawmakers in the 100-seat National Assembly,
the country's parliament.
	   Guinea-Bissau, a former Portuguese colony, has 1 million people.
Most of them live from farming and fishing.
	   (bh/krt/jt)
</TEXT>
