<SLUG> BC-Canada-Shelter Explosion, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0286 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Blast destroys homeless shelter in Montreal; about 15 hurt
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with one dead; police lowering injury toll, name of
shelter, possible cause. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MONTREAL (AP) _ An explosion, possibly caused by a severed gas
line, shattered a shelter for homeless people in Montreal on
Tuesday, killing one person and injuring at least 15, police said.
Two staff members were missing.
	   Police said the fatality was a woman who died from her wounds
within a few hours of the blast. Five other people also were
seriously injured, police said.
	   The explosion sheared off one entire wall of the three-story
stone building, spilling rubble into the street in historic Old
Montreal. Firefighters were searching through the debris, unsure if
the missing people _ a nun and a volunteer cook _ were trapped
underneath.
	   An official with the city gas company said a private contractor
who was trying to adjust a meter ruptured a gas pipe shortly before
the explosion.
	   ``Apparently he cut a pipe,'' said Stephane Bertrand. ``There
was a gas leak. He called Gaz Metropolitain and we got here as
quickly as possible... It seems he went into the building to urge
everyone to leave.''
	   No one lived in the Accueil Bonneau shelter _ it was used to
provide meals and shelter for homeless people during the day.
	   Authorities initially reported that about 30 people were
injured, but lowered the figure after determining that some were
counted more than once as they were taken to four different
hospitals.
	   The explosion damaged several adjacent buildings, as well as
tour buses parked near the shelter in an area of Montreal popular
with sight-seers. 	   
</TEXT>
