<HEADLINE>
Let PNB Audit Come First Before Privatization: Tanada, BUSINESS DAILY
</HEADLINE>
Let PNB Audit Come First Before Privatization: Tanada, BUSINESS DAILY &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS DAILY
   PHILIPPINES
   ENGLISH
   Ferdinand G. PatinioASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   Quezon Rep. Wigberto Tanada yesterday called for a thorough
audit of the Philippine National Bank (PNB) before subjecting it to
another round of privatization.
	   Tanada also proposed that an inquiry be conducted to determine
the effects of a privatization on funds kept at PNB, particularly
the $280 million Marcos money which was transferred from the
family's Swiss Bank accounts, and intended for human rights victims
during the dictatorship..
	   ``So, where's the money? What will happen to it when PNB is
privatized? What about the claims of the human right victims?'' he
asked.
	   PNB, which is 46%-owned by government will be privatized in June
1999.
	   Tanada added that the regional financial crisis was a
''convenient excuse'' for PNB's problems. Tanada said PNB was
already experiencing difficulties even before the regional crisis
which broke out in July.
	   He pointed out that the bank was having a hard time dealing with
bad loans.
	   He cited for instance the loans to Ramon Jacinto used for the
purchase of the 8,000 square meter prime property in Makati as well
as to Philtranco and Monumento Plaza.
	   ``Its (PNB) quick privatization offers a smooth and quiet
resolution to the problem. But as some of our past privatization
experiences have shown, while assets were privatized, the
liabilities were absorbed by the national government, in short, the
taxpayers,'' the Quezon lawmaker said.
	   ''This is a clear case of privatized gains but the losses are
socialized.
	   This should not be allowed,'' he emphasized.
	   Banking analysts earlier advised PNB management to be
transparent in its operation, particularly to prospective its
buyers.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS DAILY all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
