WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IT'S 4pm on an overcast Monday afternoon, yet dance music is
booming from a discotheque in Penang. Inside its cavernous hall,
the KRU brothers Norman, Yusry and Edry are busy executing slick
dance manoeuvres on the dance floor, accompanied by their
ever-present backup dancers.
	   The music sounds unmistakably KRU. Onstage, a video camera is
rolling, capturing the entire dance routine.
	   IT'S 4pm on an overcast Monday afternoon, yet dance music is
booming from a discotheque in Penang. Inside its cavernous hall,
the KRU brothers Norman, Yusry and Edry are busy executing slick
dance manoeuvres on the dance floor, accompanied by their
ever-present backup dancers.
	   The music sounds unmistakably KRU. Onstage, a video camera is
rolling, capturing the entire dance routine.
	   Welcome to the video shoot of Fobia - KRU's latest single from
the upcoming Silat Lagenda soundtrack album.
	   In between scenes, a gracious Norman readily talks to The New
Straits Times while the makeup lady hovers around, dabbing his face
with powder.
	   ``I don't know whether Fobia is going to be another
controversial song like Fanatik,'' Norman says.
	   ``Fanatik was about society. We were trying to convey our inner
feelings to get people to open up their minds to their
surroundings. Fobia is about KRU. It's about the traumatic
experience that we were put through last year, but here we are
again. It's like we haven't had enough''.
	   Shot on location in Penang, Fobia marks KRU's 10th attempt at
directing a music video. In the RM30,000 video, the brothers are
pursued on land, sea and sky - in stretch limousines, jetskis,
speedboats and a private jet.
	   ``This is the farthest that we have gone for a video shoot.
We've got 20 personnel from Kuala Lumpur here. It is a logistics
nightmare trying to get everybody co-ordinated. Usually, music
video production crews have a maximum of 12 people,'' says Norman.
	   Fobia is among 10 tracks on the KRU-produced soundtrack album
for Silat Lagenda, Malaysia's first full-length animated film
scheduled for release in August.
	   Meanwhile, KRU has succeeded in procuring compositions from a
dream team of songwriters for its self-produced debut English
album. The songwriters - Teddy Riley, David Foster, Babyface and
Diane Warren - have each contributed a song for the album.
	   ``We are going to have 14 tracks for the album. Seven songs are
from foreign composers, including several up-and-coming writers.
The rest of the songs are written by KRU,'' he said.
	   Nonetheless, Norman says the album will retain the KRU sound,
incorporating dance, pop, rap and R&AMP;B music.
	   ``As producers, we have to make sure that the album has
direction and is well co-ordinated. We must be able to have enough
confidence to make some changes to the songs (from other writers).
	   ``As far as the music arrangement is concerned, it is totally
our version of whatever the songwriter has given to us. We maintain
the melody and lyrics, but we have made some changes to the music
arrangement so that the songs blend into the whole album.''
	   KRU is enlisting the assistance of a vocal coach from the US
before laying down the vocal tracks next month.
	   The group is likely to go to Los Angeles in August for the
mixing, and will be able to release the album in October or
November.
	   
</TEXT>
