<BODY>
<SLUG> STARS-CONVERGE-FOR-ALBUM sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Stars converge for album, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Stars converge for album, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Shuib TaibASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   ``THE hardest part was convincing them,'' says Norman, the
eldest member of KRU.
	   ``This is no ordinary compilation album. It is a collaboration
of the work of some of the best talents in the country. So, for the
first time, we roped in superstars, established singers as well as
budding ones.''
	   Norman was addressing the Press at a pre-listening session of
KRU's latest undertaking at its office in Kuala Lumpur. It is the
soundtrack for the country's first animated movie, Silat Legenda.
	   He said while most of the singers were game to work together, it
was initially difficult to secure their participation as they are
signed to different labels.
	   ``This is an industry album, hence it is different from the
usual compilation albums. None of the songs has been released
before, so we are talking about new recording material. On top of
that, it is the first time that we working with top artistes,''
Norman added.
	   The soundtrack features Sharifah Aini (Takkan Melayu Hilang Di
Dunia), Ella (Aku), ex-Search vocalist Amy (Orait), Zainal Abidin
(Ceriteria), Ning Baizura (Bawa Daku Pergi), Elite (Lihatlah
Dunia), KRU (Fobia), Indigo (Istimewa) and Sheila Majid (Setia
Bersama).
	   Interestingly, each song was tailored to suit the vocal ability
of the singers.
	   Sharifah Aini, who needed only 20 minutes to record her song,
sings in asli style. Zainal's Ceriteria is distinctively pop-ethnic
and you can't help but be taken in by Amy's Orait which is so
typically him.
	   ``But what really surprised us was Sheila Majid readily agreeing
to sing our composition. We grew up listening to Sheila's songs and
have been big fans of hers. So it was like a dream come true when
she said `yes' to the project.
	   ``Sheila was certainly the toughest one (to approach) because
hers is a duet with KRU. How do you ask someone of her calibre to
do a duet with us?'' Norman asked.
	   Whichever way you look at it, this album is testimony to KRU's
producing and songwriting skills. Certainly, the project is the
biggest they've had to undertake. It wasn't because it involved a
huge sum of money or anything like that, Norman said, but because
``working with professionals and top artistes does give you the
creeps''.
	   ``I mean, what, for instance, would they think of our
compositions?''
	   Norman said they spent 40 to 45 days in the recording studio.
	   All the artistes were handpicked by the KRU members, bearing in
mind the importance of having a balanced line-up.
	   In the end, they settled for three categories - superstars
(those whose album sales have surpassed the 200,000 mark),
well-established singers (those who have been around for more than
25 years) and new artistes.
	   The singers are from Warner Music, EMI, BMG and KRU Records. EMI
will distribute the album.
	   ``We may have come from various labels but we all have but one
common goal, that is to ensure this album's success.''
	   Norman said for that to happen, they are not sparing anything.
	   ``We are allocating RM100,000 for production while a further
RM200,000 will be put aside for promotions. The line-up of artistes
deserves this kind of A&AMP;P (advertising and promotion) support.''
	   KRU has shot three music videos for the soundtrack album. Two
more will be produced later.
	   Said Norman: ``The soundtrack is released here at the end of
this month.
	   It will also be released in 13 other countries.''
	   And what is the album concept?
	   ``It is unique in the sense that it presents a whole world of
genres. We have rhythm and blues, pop, asli, rock, grunge, etc.
Some of the lyrics do reflect the storyline.''
	   Listening to the album, it is obvious that the boys do know how
to match the singer to the song. Take Zainal's song, for instance.
One listen and you can see his stamp. So too with Amy's Orait,
which showcases his personality (but where is his trademark
``pee...wit!?'').
	   The soundtrack is being released ahead of the film, which only
hits theatres in August.
	   Said Norman: ``We're following Hollywood in that we're releasing
the soundtrack first, followed by the movie. And with the current
situation, we would be happy if the album could sell between 60,000
and 70,000 copies.''
	   Silat Legenda is about five teenagers who come across a mystical
weapon which transforms them into 21st-century versions of
legendary Malacca warriors Hang Tuah, Hang Jebat, Hang Lekir, Hang
Kasturi and Hang Lekiu.
	   
</TEXT>
