<BODY>
<SLUG> BLAME-FOR-PRICE-RISE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bernas: We are not to blame for price rise, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Bernas: We are not to blame for price rise, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Fauziah IsmailASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PADIBERAS Nasional Bhd (Bernas) yesterday dismissed allegations
that it is the cause of the increase in the price of rice over
recent weeks.
	   Its managing director Mohd Ibrahim Mohd Nor, speaking at a press
conference in Kuala Lumpur yesterday, said Bernas supplies only 18
per cent of the rice in the domestic market ``as such, I do not
believe we are able to shake the market''.
	   ``With a such a small market share, is it fair to blame Bernas
for the current price increase? What I know is we make an excellent
scapegoat,'' he said.
	   He was responding to allegations by the Federation of the
Malaysia Consumer Associations (Fomca) which claimed that the price
rises were due to Bernas selling imported rice to its two
subsidiaries, which in turn sell to consumers at a higher price.
	   Ibrahim said he believed that rice wholesalers and retailers are
taking advantage of the situation to jack up prices. There are
37,000 retail outlets inclusive of supermarkets, which are being
served by 1,500 wholesalers.
	   Poor harvest worldwide due to the unfavourable weather
conditions has been identified as the cause of the price
escalations.
	   Prices of home-grown rice shot up by 21 per cent while that of
imported varieties by 52 per cent since May 1.
	   Malaysia imported 65 per cent of its rice from Thailand,
Vietnam, India, Pakistan and Taiwan.
	   Ibrahim, who described Fomca's allegations as ``grossly
untrue'', said Bernas had only increase the price of the imported
rice by not more than 30 per cent beginning May this year. It had,
between September last year and April this year, suffered losses
because it did not increase its rice's price.
	   The rice sold through its B-Mart outlets are also cheaper than
those sold by wholesalers and retailers.
	   Citing an example, Ibrahim said Bernas is selling the Super AAA
Grade at RM30 per 10kg compared with between RM38 and RM40 per kg
sold by wholesalers and retailers.
	   ``We sell the imported rice to BMart at average of 5 sen/kg
cheaper since these are for the B-Mart outlets and BMart sponsored
outlets. The network represents benchmark pricing when Bernas
avoids the middlemen,'' he said.
	   He also denied Fomca's allegations that Bernas is selling 80 per
cent of the 600,000 tonnes it imported annually to its
subsidiaries.
	   Ibrahim said Bernas is selling only 38.6 per cent of the
imported rice to its subsidiaries while the balance of 61.4 per
cent are sold to others.
	   On calls for the Government to liberalise the importation of
rice, Ibrahim said rice is a strategic commodity and as such,
handling the commodity cannot be viewed from one particular angle.
	   Ibrahim said the importation of rice was actually left to market
forces in 1973.
	   ``History showed that when the price and supply of rice
internationally take a vigorous fluctuation due to both national or
economic disasters, the responsibility for importation of rice
cannot be left to an organisation that is driven purely by profit
motive.
	   ``In facing an international market, we are confronted with
international traders and governments the size of which dwarfs even
an organisation like Bernas.
	   ``It is imperative that this responsibility is handled in a
coordinated manner by an organisation, which has the interest of
the consumers, the farmers, the trade as well as the country,'' he
added.
	   Explaining Bernas' business plan, Ibrahim said it takes
cognisance of consumers' interests, farmers' interests as well as
global threats.
	   ``We put consumers' interest as a priority one, it would only be
logical for Bernas to find ways and means to avoid the multi-layers
supply chain and go direct to the 37,000 retail base, if not to the
22 million people who consume rice in Malaysia.
	   ``We opted for a two-pronged approach to bring farmers closer to
consumers. We maintain direct supply to B-Mart and B-Mart sponsored
outlets as a benchmark and the last alternative to consumers as
well as forming joint ventures with some of the wholesalers.
	   ``With access to only half of the total rice supply, Bernas can
only hope to offer an alternative system for both the consumers and
farmers,'' he said.
	   On Deputy Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim's directive
last Wednesday for more medium grade rice to be imported from
countries offering reasonable prices to enable the people to buy
them at affordable prices, Ibrahim said Bernas had done it in 1996.
	   ``We still have stock of the medium grade rice. It has not moved
since two years ago.''
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
