<BODY>
<SLUG> FATE-OF-WESTMONT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fate of Westmont to be decided on Aug 29, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Fate of Westmont to be decided on Aug 29, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Pratap ParameswaranASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE fate of Westmont Industries Bhd (WIB) and its wholly-owned
subsidiary Sabah Shipyard Sdn Bhd (Saship) will be known on August
29 when WIB presents the details of its restructuring proposals to
the High Court.
	   Creditors of the group are expected to vote on the proposals on
the same day. If accepted, the restructuring process will start by
the end of the year, group director Datuk Jaffar Indot told
reporters at a briefing yesterday.
	   He said he is ``reasonably confident'' the group's creditors
will support the proposed restructuring plan, given the encouraging
feedback.
	   WIB and Saship owe its creditors about RM970 million.
	   Of the amount, WIB owes RM66.49 million, of which RM61.09
million is due to unsecured creditors which include financial
institutions, RM869,000 to partially-secured creditors and RM4.88
million to unsecured general creditors, including hire-purchase and
leasing companies.
	   Saship's debt amounts to RM907.3 million, including RM197.91
million owed to WIB and a provision of RM312 million for bad debts.
	   The proposals will be binding on all WIB's creditors if it is
approved by 75 per cent of the creditors in terms of value and 50
per cent in the number of each class of creditors, said Jaffar.
	   ``We have talked to all of them to explain what the scheme is
all about and taken feedback and suggestions from them.''
	   The proposed settlement involves a cash payment, a debt-equity
conversion into new shares in WIB, and a moratorium on debt.
	   Earlier, WIB chairman Datuk Mohd Desa Pachi, reading from a
prepared statement, said the release of WIB's audited accounts for
the financial year ended December 31 1996 to the Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange on Friday marks a turning point for the group and its new
shareholders and management.
	   WIB posted a pre-tax loss of RM664.79 million on a turnover of
RM376.61 million. Group loss after tax stood at RM715.58 million.
	   ``The new board found that the preliminary unaudited results for
the financial year, which was originally announced as a profit
after tax of RM54.9 million, could not be substantiated,'' said
Mohd Desa.
	   The new board was appointed on April 24 1997, four months after
the closure of the 1996 financial year.
	   The High Court had on February 4 1998 granted a restraining
order allowing WIB to proceed with the restructuring scheme.
	   The scheme includes a proposal to reduce 33 sen for each fully
paid-up RM1 WIB share, in order to reduce the balance of
accumulated losses by RM77.7 million. This will be followed by a
restricted issue to WIB's major shareholder, Swascojuta Sdn Bhd -
holding 21.8 per cent - to raise about RM61.15 million.
	   ``Liquidation of WIB is not a viable alternative as most
creditors will not receive full payment while shareholders'
investment in WIB will likely be rendered valueless,'' said Mohd
Desa.
	   The response from creditors is encouraging as the proposal
remains the best alternative for restoring the long-term viability
of WIB and Saship, he added.
	   Saship resumed its shiprepair activities in March after stopping
operatings for two months - which Jaffar said was sufficient to pay
for overheads.
	   In the medium term, Saship will be re-entering its shipbuilding
activities, Jaffar said.
	   The yard is expected to benefit from the estimated 70,000 tonnes
of offshore fabrication work for the next three years and the fact
that it is the only yard in Malaysia's eastern corridor, he added.
	   
</TEXT>
