<BODY>
<SLUG> THE-WHITE-RAP-TRAP sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Running from the white rap trap, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Running from the white rap trap, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Zainal Alam KadirASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   WHATEVER whatever happened to Vanilla Ice, the blonde rapper who
twisted the David Bowie/Queen collaboration Under Pressure into Ice
Ice Baby, a giant hit in the early Nineties.
	   The one who became a star overnight, sold millions of records
and disappeared into oblivion after one movie?
	   Well, the answer to this query is not really important, but it's
fair to say that the novelty of ``pale rappers'' was worn out quite
a while ago.
	   Still, that doesn't seem to bother a certain young man from
Kentucky in the United States who calls himself Trey D. Yes,
Kentucky - not really the ``ideal'' backdrop for rap music, which
seems to thrive in cosmopolitan areas, as well as big urban
districts and ghettos.
	   So, there he was, looking quite awkward on the stage of Beaufort
Hotel's ballroom in Sentosa Island, Singapore, where he was
promoting his music recently.
	   Trey D was backed by a deejay friend who ``scratched and
grooved'' while another cool friend provided the additional vocals.
	   He performed two songs, apparently his own compositions, Mirror,
Mirror and Higher and Higher.
	   The songs were funky and catchy, and the vocals, rather
melodious. The guys exhibited the usual ``yo, yo, yo'' gestures and
the jerk-your-shoulder-
while-your-mouth-shoots-incomprehensible-words action ruled the
day. It was rap, all right.
	   Yet, there was still this fleeting feeling that Trey D was
another Vanilla Ice, a flash-in-the-pan - sell today, sold
tomorrow.
	   Up close and personal the next day, one could not identify the
ordinary young man with the one who was on stage the night before.
	   That raised another question: what was a fine young man like
Trey D (he never told us his real name) doing in the very nasty
world of rap?
	   Couldn't he just sing?
	   ``Yes, I do sing, and I do play some instruments. I listen to
all sorts of music. It's just that I can express myself best in
this genre,'' he explained.
	   He said that he learned a lot by listening often to the radio.
It became his ``teacher'' of sorts, and from it, he learned to
explore his ideas.
	   Trey D said although he was into almost everything, his
favourites are Lionel Richie and Earth, Wind &AMP; Fire. The act that
has made the biggest impression on him is rapper L.L. Cool J.
	   The ideas for his songs are drawn from his own experience or
stories which were related to him by close friends. It seems there
is a moral to each song.
	   Mirror Mirror, for instance, deals with our inner self, how we
perceive things, and our direction in life.''
	   Trey D revealed that he was unsure how long he would be rapping,
and whether he would move on to singing. His priority now is to
explore all the possibilities in the rap world.
	   ``But one thing that I'm quite keen to do is produce. Somewhere
down the road, I see myself running my own company and producing
records. There's so much to learn first, though,'' he said.
	   The singles Mirror Mirror and Higher and Higher are expected to
be out soon. His release album is likely to follow soon after but
no dates have been confirmed.
	   Trey D is represented in Malaysia by Form Records.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
