	   IPOH, Sun. - At least one person per household in Perak will be
trained in first aid by the year 2005, chairman of the Perak branch
of the Malaysian Red Crescent Society Tan Sri Ramli Ngah Talib
said.
	   This will enable mishaps at home to be attended to on the spot.
Since the programme started in 1995, 3,390 people have been
trained, including 1,426 last year.
	   The target is 400,000 by the year 2005.
	   ``We hope to start training programmes in secondary schools,
followed by government departments and the private sector.''
	   Ramli, who is also Menteri Besar, was speaking at a parade to
mark MRCS's 50th anniversary.
	   It was officiated by Sultan Azlan Shah at the Ipoh Padang today.
	   The Sultan inspected a guard-of-honour mounted by 540 members
representing 18 chapters in Perak.
	   He also presented meritorious medals to 14 MRCS members.
	   
</TEXT>
