<SLUG> KODAK-SEES-6PC-INCREASE sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kodak sees 6pc increase in market share, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Kodak sees 6pc increase in market share, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ariff AwangASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KODAK (M) Sdn Bhd expects a 6 per cent increase in its domestic
market share within 12 months following the introduction of an
innovative retail concept, the ``New Kodak Express Programme''.
	   Its general manager of consumer imaging, Mr Richard Fleming said
currently Kodak (M) is ahead of its nearest competitor by 60 per
cent in terms of sales.
	   The New Kodak Express Programme is designed to meet the growing
demands of retail support and provide value-added services and
products to consumers, he said in Kuala Lumpur yesterday at a press
conference to launch the programme in Malaysia.
	   According to him, the programme is the result of extensive
research and a US$1 million (US$1  &QC;  RM3.99) investment by Kodak,
which enables the company to identify key driving factors in
consumer purchasing habits.
	   ``This new retail concept for Kodak Express Stores has already
shown significant success in the US where within 12 months, total
business increased by 62 per cent,'' he said.
	   ``These results indicate that there are vast opportunities to be
tapped in this region and Malaysia especially, if we improve the
retail presentation of Kodak products and services here,'' he
added.
	   Fleming pointed out that in Malaysia, a budget ranging from
RM16,000 to RM20,000 is required for an outlet to set up the
programme. At present there are 350 Kodak outlets operating in the
country.
	   Under the programme, he said, the new visual appeal of the
stores will project Kodak Express as young, vibrant and
professional. Staff will be equipped with the knowledge and
confidence to handle consumer enquiries through Kodak's
personalised training programme.
	   Aside from this, a loyalty programme for customers has also been
created, along with the introduction of other outstanding benefits
namely, Kodak's new point-of-sale system, rebates for members,
exclusive promotions and merchandise to blend in with Kodak's new
look, said Fleming.
	   
</TEXT>
