<HEADLINE>
Mira requires RM25,000 for heart surgery, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Mira requires RM25,000 for heart surgery, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PENANG, Sun. - With the hope of healing heart patients and
saving them from the pain and suffering which she has experienced,
little Mira Natasha Suria, a hole-in-the-heart patient, aspires to
be a medical specialist when she grows up.
	   While most six-year-olds would wish for computers, toys and
sweets, all Mira wants is to have a normal childhood and a chance
to do the selfless deed for people with heart problems.
	   However, her hopes can only be realised if she goes through a
corrective heart surgery costing a hefty RM25,000.
	   Doctors discovered a hole in her heart when she was eight months
old and she has been living with the problem ever since.
	   Her mother Zuraini Ridzuan, a housewife, expressed her thanks to
readers of the New Straits Times for their contributions earlier
which helped improve Mira's condition.
	   Mira went through an operation to enlarge an artery two years
ago.
	   However, without the corrective surgery, she may not be able to
live long and would have to endure suffering for the limited time
that she should live.
	   Her father Suria Majid, a taxi driver, has appealed to the
public for donations to give his daughter a new lease of life.
	   Suria, a father of two, who earns RM800 a month said he brought
Mira to Tawakal Hospital in Kuala Lumpur for check-ups once a year
and it cost RM420 each time.
	   Mira's surgery is scheduled for Aug 18 at the Ampang Puteri
Specialists Hospital.
	   Donations can be sent by way of crossed cheques payable to the
New Straits Times with Mira's name written on the back. Cheques can
be addressed to: Finance/Cashier, The New Straits Times Press (M)
Bhd, Balai Berita, 31, Jalan Riong, 59100 Kuala Lumpur.
	   
</TEXT>
