<BODY>
<SLUG> NEW-HOONG-FATT-CLOSES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New Hoong Fatt closes at RM2.95 for 15-sen premium, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
New Hoong Fatt closes at RM2.95 for 15-sen premium, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Roziana HamsawiASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   AUTOMOTIVE replacement parts manufacturer New Hoong Fatt
Holdings Bhd ended its maiden day on the second board of the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange with a premium of 15 sen yesterday.
	   With an offer price of RM2.80, the counter closed the day at
RM2.95 after hitting a high of RM3.06 and touching a low of RM2.88.
Some 169 lots were traded.
	   The stock earlier opened at RM3.06 with 10 lots traded in the
first minute.
	   ``We are quite satisfied with the (opening) price. Actually, we
are not bothered by it ... we will continue with our business as
usual,'' said its managing director Kim Lang Fatt.
	   New Hoong Fatt is involved in the manufacture, marketing and
trading of automotive parts and accessories. It has three
subsidiaries - New Hoong Fatt Auto Supplies Sdn Bhd, NJ Metal
Stamping Sdn Bhd and Jhi Soon Auto Metal Sdn Bhd.
	   NJ Metal Stamping and Jhi Soon Auto Metal manufactures
automotive replacement parts under the brand names of NJ and JS,
respectively.
	   New Hoong Fatt Auto Supplies markets, distributes and trades the
automotive replacement parts manufactured by its subsidiaries.
	   ``As of now, we are already expanding our export market and we
have been doing that for the last two years,'' said its exective
director Chin Jit Sin after New Hoong Fatt's listing ceremony at
the Exchange Square yesterday.
	   He added that the company hopes to increase its exports to 30
per cent of its turnover this year from the current 20 per cent.
	   ``For this year, we have invested RM10 million to expand our
plant in Klang and purchase new manufacturing equipment which uses
robotics technology,'' said Chin.
	   He said despite the slowdown in the economy, the company's plans
to expand its export market is not affected.
	   ``In fact, the depreciation of the ringgit has been quite
beneficial to us, in terms of our exported products while our
operating costs have not gone up as the costs are still in
ringgit,'' he said.
	   At present, New Hoong Fatt exports its products to Australia and
Thailand. It expects to tap into West Asian, South American and
African market in the near future.
	   
</TEXT>
