<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Arrest, 6th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Head of Russian statistics service accused of helping tax cheats
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to ADD comment from prime minister, edits
thereafter to conform. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo MOSB105 &QL; 
 &UR; By LESLIE SHEPHERD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The two top officials of the Russian statistics
service have been charged with helping big companies evade taxes,
raising fears that figures used to make government policy and
collect other taxes were falsified.
	   Investigators said they arrested Yuri Yurkov, head of the State
Statistics Committee, his deputy, Valery Dalin, and up to 20
alleged accomplices on Monday after a yearlong investigation.
	   More than dlrs 1 million in cash was found in Yurkov's
apartment, said government spokesman Alexei Volin said. Another
dlrs 500,000 and a large amount of jewelry was seized from the
others.
	   Tax evasion is a major problem in Russia, from ordinary citizens
to large corporations. The government's inability to collect tax
revenues has hobbled efforts to boost the economy.
	   Yurkov and the others were accused of manipulating economic data
to hide the real output of companies and reduce their tax
liability, and with selling classified information about rival
companies' performance.
	   The arrests could have far-reaching economic implications if it
turns out that data government officials rely on to make policy and
collect taxes was falsified. Yurkov has been head of the statistics
agency since 1993.
	   The Russian Prosecutor General's office said more than 20 people
were involved in the scheme, including the head of the agency's
data processing center, Boris Saakyan.
	   ``They have distributed roles among themselves making every
member of the criminal group earn money,'' it said in a statement.
	   It said that Yurkov and Saakyan made statements pleading guilty
to the charges. Yurkov is one of the highest-ranking Russian
officials to be arrested in recent years.
	   Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko said the arrests highlighted
government efforts to battle economic crimes.
	   ``I do not think that today's arrest of Yuri Yurkov is a
misfortune,'' he said, according to the ITAR-Tass news agency. He
said the arrests were a combined effort of the Russian security
service and the prosecutor general's office.
	   Meanwhile, Russia's new tax enforcement chief, Boris Fyodorov,
pledged once again to enforce the law equally against all tax
dodgers.
	   ``I've been told to collect taxes.'' he said at a news
conference. Because he intends to do so, ``People are hysterical.
It's like 1937, the year of the Stalin purges.''
	   In a country of 150 million people, only 3.2 million tax
declarations were submitted last year, Fyodorov said. He said his
first targets will be rich Russians and foreigners.
	   ``For years, the government has been pretending to collect
taxes, and people have been pretending to be paying them,''
Fyodorov said.
	   (pvs/ls/mr)	   
</TEXT>
