<BODY>
<SLUG> CAPITAL-POSITION-STRONG sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hwang-DBS: Capital position strong, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Hwang-DBS: Capital position strong, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Elena ShamsuddinASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HWANG-DBS Securities Bhd's financial position will not be
strained after it forks out RM70 million to reimburse Omega
Securities' clients as it has a strong capital position.
	   Currently, the stockbroking company has some RM300 million in
fixed deposits, said Hwang-DBS executive chairman Datuk Hwang Sing
Lue, adding that the setting up of a branch in Shah Alam is timely
despite the current bearish sentiment.
	   Speaking at a press conference organised by the Securities
Commission (SC) yesterday, Hwang said, the Penang-based
stockbroking firm has always been keen to expand its operations
into the Klang Valley.
	   ``It is the opportunity we have tried for so many years but
without success ... As far as we are concerned, we feel that it is
the right time to start a branch,'' he said.
	   The branch, he said, is expected to be operational as soon as
possible with the cooperation of the relevant authorities.
	   Last Friday, the SC announced that Hwang-DBS has agreed to
participate in a reimbursement scheme, which effectively sees
Hwang-DBS forking out RM70 million to reimburse qualified clients
of Omega Securities (whose licence has been revoked) the net
amounts owing to them upon closing their accounts with Omega.
	   Under the scheme, a willing stockbroking company deemed fit by
the SC will undertake to reimburse clients of stockbroking company
whose licence has been revoked.
	   In Omega's case, it was placed under trading restrictions for
failing to fulfill prudential and business conduct standard of the
securities laws and Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) rules.
	   It was then directed by the SC to come up with a restructuring
exercise, but failed to do so, which caused a show-cause letter to
be issued by the SC to the compaof most of Omega's remisiers ``who are performing.''
	   ``As far as the staff of Omega are concerned, we have to go
through the list and decide later,'' he added.
	   Meanwhile, SC chairman Datuk Dr Mohd Munir Majid stressed that
the reimbursement exercise does not entail Hwang-DBS taking over
Omega's assets and liabilities as it is not a takeover.
	   The assets and liabilities of Omega are really of no concern to
Hwang- DBS, said Munir, adding that the company's involvement goes
as far as offering Omega's clients recourse to claim the net amount
owing to them.
	   On whether Hwang-DBS would be keen to set up another branch,
Hwang said, the firm plans to ``take one thing at a time,'' but
added that it is not keen to open a branch in Sabah or Sarawak.
	   Meanwhile, under the reimbursement scheme, Hwang-DBS will send
out letters to eligible clents by June 15 1998, informing them the
details and procedures of the payment.
	   Eligible clients who opt to accept the payment under the scheme
will be required to return the reply slip to Hwang-DBS before June
30 1998 and those who dispute the net amount must clarify in person
with the KLSE's staff at the office of Omega before the same date.
	   Payments will be made by the KLSE between July 13 1998 and July
17 1998 from 9am to 5pm and eligible clients will be required to
produce their original identity cards or passports and other
requisite documents as stipulated in the letter.
	   Eligible clients who fail to submit their replies to Hwang-DBS
on or before June 30 1998 will no longer be eligible to the payment
under the scheme and will have to claim against the KLSE's
compensation fund.
	   
</TEXT>
