<SLUG> INTERNAL-SYSTEM sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Internal system has weaknesses: Anwar, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Internal system has weaknesses: Anwar, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   DEPUTY Prime Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim said yesterday
Malaysia should accept the fact that its internal system has
weaknesses and should be rectified particularly during the current
economic slowdown.
	   ``If firm measures are necessary, we will take them. If such
measures are necessary to guarantee the strength of our financial
institutions, we will adopt these measures so that they do not
become paralysed,'' he said when opening the Johor Umno Convention
at the Sibu Island Resort in Mersing.
	   Even though Malaysia remained firm in calling for reforms to the
international monetary system and uncertain market conditions, it
also needed to realise that not everything that was happening in
the countries of this region was the result of an unjust financial
system.
	   ``There are also internal ills and problems that needed to be
corrected.
	   If we refuse to accept the facts just like the past leadership
of Indonesia, which refused to accept, then the people will rise
and demand for changes in a harsh way,'' Anwar said.
	   Anwar, who is also Finance Minister, said Malaysians should be
grateful that the country need not have to seek help from the
International Monetary Fund as the Government had already taken the
necessary measures to handle the economic problems.
	   ``Hence, Malaysia is demanding for justice in the international
financial system as well as reforms and more transparency,'' he
said.
	   ``We should make the corrections with determination and continue
reforming the culture of our society in dealing with the question
of the economy and management,'' Anwar said.
	   He said the Government would step up efforts to ensure
confidence particularly among investors in economic revival so that
the economy would move forward more rapidly.
	   ``While we demand for changes and reformation in the
international financial system, the nation should also defend its
policies which had served it well and also make appropriate
renewals and changes so that it did not deviate from the principle
of justice,'' he said.
	   Anwar said the international monetary system's present form and
methods favoured the rich nations making it possible for the
currency trading system to be manipulated and speculation to occur
and small and developing nations had to put up with the present
regulations.
	   ``We should not budge from our stand that part of our problems
and that of developing nations stemmed for an uncertain and unjust
financial and market system,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
