<HEADLINE>
CSA has its corporate doctrine to thank for increase in earnings, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
CSA has its corporate doctrine to thank for increase in earnings, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   David Ong-YeohASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   AT A time when most companies are announcing depressing results,
Computer Systems Advisers (M) Bhd (CSA) is enjoying an increased
turnover, profits and cash reserves, and the secret, says managing
director Chuah Tai Eu, is spreading its exposure at every level.
	   None of CSA's customers contributes more than 2 per cent to the
group's total turnover while not more than 30 per cent is sourced
from a single supplier.
	   It is a corporate doctrine that has worked for CSA even in these
troubled times - cash reserves stand at over RM15 million, low
borrowings and results for the first quarter of 1998 are better
than for the same period in 1997.
	   For the financial year 1997, the integrated computer systems
company achieved a 22 per cent jump in group pre-tax profit to
RM19.3 million on a turnover of RM370 million.
	   Chuah attributes all that to a good cash position, wide customer
base and a good balance of business activities.
	   ``We don't just depend on one or two companies that give 10 or
20 per cent of our business,'' said Chuah after CSA's annual
general meeting in Petaling Jaya yesterday.
	   It already command about 7 per cent of the RM4 billion Malaysian
IT market, making it one of the single largest IT companies in
Malaysia.
	   ``We just need to increase our market share by 1 per cent and we
can grow more than 10 per cent.''
	   For this year, Chuah says results will be ``about the same''
from a base of over 2,000 customers; each expected to contribute a
few million each.
	   Nevertheless, CSA has not been untouched by events and Chuah
said the results would have been much better off if not for the
economic crisis.
	   What has helped is hedging and that most of its suppliers deal
with CSA in ringgit with only about 20 per cent dealing in US
dollars, which has helped take the edge off high exchange rates.
	   Although some 20 per cent of CSA's turnover comes from the large
banks, Chuah said he is not overly concerned with their
non-performing loan levels as again, not more than 2 per cent of
turnover comes from each bank regardless of how large it is.
	   A spinoff from that is lower borrowings as a result of the
smoother cash flow.
	   Also, indications are that IT expenditure is the last thing
banks can afford to cut back on, even in these difficult times, if
they want to stay competitive.
	   Another 15 per cent comes from securities companies, 20 per cent
from its wholesaling operations and the rest comes from the
manufacturing and oil and gas sectors.
	   Other revenue opportunities for CSA are the looming Y2K problem,
service and maintenance operations as companies prefer to maintain
existing hardware to save money.
	   ``Service and out sourcing will be a main contributor to revenue
this year,'' said Chuah.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
