<SLUG> HALT-THE-PUNISHMENT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Halt the punishment of innocents, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Halt the punishment of innocents, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   GOING by Baghdad's claims, the eight-year sanctions by the
United Nations (UN) against Iraq have succeeded in murdering more
people than the invasion of Kuwait did. President Saddam Hussain,
who incurred the wrath of the US, its allies, and the world in
general for the 1990 invasion, said that 1.5 million Iraqis have
died from malnutrition and a lack of medical supplies during the
past eight years.
	   Whether or not the claims can be substantiated is not the main
issue.
	   And eight years may or may not be a long period of punishment
for what Iraq inflicted upon Kuwait and its people. However, if
people in Iraq are dying because of the sanctions, it is the duty
of the international community to investigate. If Baghdad's claims
are true, the UN must take urgent measures to stop this human
rights violation. The sanctions are meant to teach the Government a
lesson, not to kill civilians who had no part in the Kuwaiti
invasion, or deny Iraqi children their basic rights such as
education and medical care. If the people continue to elect Saddam
as their leader, it is not up to anyone outside Iraq to try and
change their ways by denying them food and medicine. The UN must
investigate Saddam's claims since the UN's food-for-aid deal ought
to have supplied enough food and medicine to care for the ordinary
Iraqi. If people are dying, is it a question of not enough or is it
because help is not reaching the people it is intended for?
	   The UN should be concerned because something could really be
amiss here.
	   According to a news report, a Russian plane that landed at the
Al-Rashid airbase last month carried three crew members, a
five-member delegation and just 20 kg of medicine. What can a few
cartons of medicine do for 22 million people and how can a few
tonnes of flour feed 7 million hungry children? Under its
food-for-aid deal with Iraq, the UN has allowed Baghdad to sell
US$2 billion (US$1  &QC;  RM3.99) of oil every six months for the last
year and a half and buy urgently needed food and medicine with some
of the revenue. If these figures are correct, people in Iraq should
not be dying of hunger or from the lack of medical care. The UN has
been more generous for the coming half-year, allowing Iraq to sell
up to US$4.5 billion worth of its oil in exchange for food. That
should really make the UN oil-rich.
	   Failure on the part of the world body to act on Saddam's claims
will, once again, confirm the double-standards being applied on
countries, depending on whose side one is. It is for humanitarian
purposes that Malaysia and other countries have been pressing the
UN to free Iraq from a social calamity. But it is sad to note the
existence of bigots in the UN.
	   The US, which was the dominant power when Iraq was ousted from
Kuwait in 1991 (and still is), wants to see Saddam punished further
at the expense of the Iraqi people. By playing up the issue of
Iraqi chemical weapons, Washington has adopted a harsh stance
against Baghdad. In fact, its strong aversion towards Iraq deters
any effort by the UN to lift the sanctions.
	   Some US allies in the UN are backing Washington's move for
further sanctions on Iraq. It is not that the UN has been pressured
by other members to lift the sanction but as usual, it is the
minority veto owers who have the ultimate say. This has been the
manner in which the UN always falls into the US' clutches. It would
seem as if it is not the UN which oversees world's affairs but the
US.
	   What has happened to the egalitarianism in the UN Charter? While
the principle of equal rights has been the foundation of the UN, a
few countries are allowed to practice elitism. Never has the UN, it
its five decades of existence followed the rule of majority. And as
long as the minority rules, the Iraqi people will not have the
chance to re-build their lives. Should the sanctions remain, Iraq
will become history by the next decade. Or is this what the US and
its allies actually want? The Iraqis cannot afford to continue
living in this manner. People in a tight corner will do anything to
survive, whether the UN likes it or not. It's for the UN to decide.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
