<HEADLINE>
New competitors different from old timers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
New competitors different from old timers, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   BESIDES being one of Malaysia's ranking competitive off-roader,
Norman has been in the motor service and maintenance industry since
completing his diploma in diesel engineering at the Federal
Institute of Technology, Malaysia, in 1978.
	   The Penang boy has never looked back since then - starting as an
apprentice at a performance tuning workshop, and then working his
way through some of the finest performance tuning workshops and 4x4
centres in Malaysia.
	   Before his stint at Traction Motors, he was at Speedworks in
1989, which does things like putting combo turbo-chargers and
superchargers in Range Rovers.
	   In 1991 when Speedworks boss Toh Soon Hing joined hands with Ken
O'Keefe to set up Ultimate Offroad Centre in Petaling Jaya, Norman
was assigned full-time to the Speedworks 4x4 division.
	   Ultimate Suspensions is a pioneer in Australian after-market
heavy duty off-road suspensions for four-wheel drives.
	   His experience with 4x4s began in 1986 with a Daihatsu Rocky.
	   In a competition, he was driving for Dunlop and subsequently
went on to win the team class in the 1996 Rainforest Championship.
For this event, he replaced the Lada-Niva's original suspension
with the Australian-made Tough Dog brand.
	   The other makes in the Dunlop team were two Suzukis and one
Pajero.
	   As a seasoned campaigner in major Malaysian competitive offroad
events, he reckons there is a big difference in the new offroading
generation.
	   ``When I competed in those days, I also had to double as
mechanical back- up. Look at the new drivers (competitors) today,
they still lose to us old members in recovery skills. And when the
going gets tough, they (the competitors) start to quarrel with the
officials.
	   ``Pressure ... they (the competitors) can't take it.
	   ``Last time, we did not sleep for two to three days and we could
still joke. Now, they just drive to the campsite and then
compete,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
