<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Croatia barely beats French third division team
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By TONY CZUCZKA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VITTEL, France (AP) _ Davor Suker missed one penalty kick but
drove home another to give Croatia a hard-fought 2-1 victory in a
practice match against a third division French club Tuesday.
	   Five days before Croatia's World Cup debut against Jamaica, the
Real Madrid striker saved his team from an embarrassing draw with
the 43rd-minute goal.
	   The Croats showed little enthusiasm in the match, played before
a friendly crowd of 7,000 in this bucolic town in the eastern
French hills, where they have set up their training camp.
	   ``Today wasn't important,'' said Croatia's captain Zvomimir
Boban.
	   Mario Stanic opened the scoring for Croatia in the 4th minute,
blasting the ball in from close range.
	   But the locals leveled eight minutes later when Christophe
Violant duped the Croatian defense in a solo run.
	   Croatia's stars played only in the first half but even they were
regularly fooled by the local in offside traps.
	   Suker missed his first chance to put Croatia ahead in the 32nd
minute when he had his penalty shot fisted away by the opposing
goal keeper.
	   Croatia replaced most of its first-choice players in the second
half half, which ended goalless.
</TEXT>
