<HEADLINE>
Jaya Jusco confident of higher profit, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Jaya Jusco confident of higher profit, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Zety Fazilah BaharuddinASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   JAYA Jusco Stores Bhd, after recording a net loss of RM14.44
million in its last financial year, is confident of achieving
higher net profits of RM4 million for the year ending February 28
1999, despite the current economic slowdown.
	   Jaya Jusco's confidence hinges on the retail chain's
anticipation of success in the shifting of its business strategy
from being a traditional retail shopping complex to a
smaller-scaled Neighbouring Shopping Complex (NSC), serving
residential areas.
	   ``We foresee the NSC business would be more profitable as it
will be located in residential areas, which will provide
convenience to our customers,''Jaya Jusco's managing director Mr
Masaaki Toyoshima said after the group's annual general meeting in
Kuala Lumpur yesterday.
	   NSC's will be located at the main area like Klang Valley and
Johor Bahru. The group is looking at areas with between 50 per cent
and 60 per cent matured populations.
	   The group plans to open 14 NSC's by 2002 and 50 by 2010, and the
first NSC is expected to be opened in 1999. Jaya Jusco will invest
some RM15 million for each store.
	   The investments will be funded through the group's internal
funds and strategic alliances with developers. Through the
alliances, Jaya Jusco will come up with the building design and
will lease them for 20 years once its completed, while developers
will develop the land at their cost.
	   ``His will help us to minimise the initial investments and speed
up expansion,'' he said.
	   Asked whether Jaya Jusco plans to seek loans, he said that the
group has no plan to do so as it now trying to reduce its gearing
ratio which currently stands between 0.51 and 0.73 times.
	   The group also has total loans US dollar loans amounting to
US$42.17 million. (US$1  &QC; RM4.00) US$16.87 million is due for
repayment over the next 12 months.
	   Meanwhile, Jaya Jusco has deferred opening two of its new
megamall - Bayan Bay in Penang and Seri Alam Shopping Centre in
Johor Bahru - due to the projects' slow progress.
	   The group is currently expanding its Taman Maluri outlet in
Cheras and Melaka Shopping Centre in Malacca, and the expansion
exercises are expected to be completed in March 2000 and July this
year respectively.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
