<HEADLINE>
Directors should be aware of liabilities, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Directors should be aware of liabilities, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Jai ShankarASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   COMPANY directors need to be aware that their liabilities
arising from the millennium bug or Year 2000 (Y2K) problem are
significant. This is because the problem has been clearly
identified and the solutions are made available.
	   Their liabiliies are compounded due to the immense publicity
that the problem has generated.
	   Among others, the failure to act on the problem may leave the
directors liable to shareholder action for damages. This was
disclosed by Philip Chan, lawyer from the firm Azalina, Chan and
Chia, during a recent seminar related to the Y2K problem.
	   The seminar, titled Insurance Day, was organised by Unisys (M)
Sdn Bhd.
	   ``The legal implications of the Y2K problem range from
liabilities of directors and officers, drafting of remediation
contracts, liabilities of insurers and liabilities of vendors and
computers,'' Chan elaborated.
	   He said company officers hence have the onus to hire experts and
ensure that the problem is rectified.
	   However, Chan remarked, they should not be passive and rely
totally on experts alone.
	   ``They must conduct their own due diligence in informing their
ownselves of the qualifications of the experts and the merits of
the business decisions.''
	   Chan also reminded company directors that the Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange authorities require companies to disclose in 1998 and 1999
their annual reports of the efforts and actions taken by each
company to ensure that they are Year 2000 compliant. ``As such, the
directors are also advised to seek assistance of Y2K experts in
drafting the statements in the annual reports,'' he said.
	   Tips on handling Y2K problem Educate themselves about the issue
and establish a committee to oversee the project. Encourage
employees to attend conferences, purchase books, subscribe to
publications and on-line services, etc.
	   Direct that an inventory of software used by the enterprise be
compiled, including source code, object code, operating systems,
utilities, file archives, third party applications and tools.
	   Conduct a risk assessment and produce a statement of impact to
report on the effect the Year 2000 would have on the enterprise.
	   Have the nature of the problem and the actions necessary to
address its communicated to all levels of the enterprise.
	   Develop a detailed plan to address the problem including all
resources necessary, a budget and critical path analysis.
	   Execute the plan on a timely basis, including work plans for the
period, work completed during the period, problems that arose and
solutions that were implemented.
	   Consider all approaches in addressing the problem, including
external consultants, specialised training, deferring
implementation of new systems to address current systems and
advancing the implementation of new systems to retire legacy
systems.
	   Source: Philip Chan
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
