<SLUG> WEAK-YEN-WILL-HAVE-DEEP sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Weak yen will have deep impact on Asia: Mier, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Weak yen will have deep impact on Asia: Mier, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE impact of the weakening yen on the Asian region will be deep
and far- reaching, economists said yesterday.
	   Executive director of the Malaysian Institute of Economic
Research, Dr Mohd Arif said a weaker yen means a weaker Japanese
economy.
	   ``The Japanese economy is stagnating. If it remains stagnant, it
is not good news since Japan is one of our most important trading
partners. Japan is also a very important Asian player and the
softening of the yen will have a deep impact on the region,'' he
told Business Times in a telephone interview.
	   Dr Arif added that as the yen is weakening now (at a time the
Asian region is facing an economic and financial crisis) indicates
the crisis is going to be global.
	   ``Due to the crisis in Asia, a lot of capital has moved out of
the region and into the US and Europe. Now that this has happened,
it is just a matter of time before it hits them as well since the
world is so `borderless' now,'' he said.
	   When asked about the strength of the Japanese economy, Arif said
the Japanese domestic economy is much bigger than what it seems.
	   ``In spite of the trade surpluses Japan has been recording, the
export sector only contributes about 10 per cent to the economy.
	   ``The problem is Japan needs a lot of economic reforms. The
interest rates for instance are way too low. It is less than 1 per
cent. In addition to that, the Japanese economy is over-regulated
and highly protected,'' Arif said.
	   Meanwhile, Ratings Agency of Malaysia (RAM) manager for
Economics and Market Research, Dr Yeh Kim Leng said a strong yen is
needed to increase exports for the entire region.
	   ``A softer yen will mean that Japanese goods and services will
be more competitive. Competition with Japan will be more difficult
despite the weakness of the other Asian currencies.
	   ``It would also mean fewer Japanese investments into the region.
	   Therefore, it is better for Asia as a whole for Japan to have a
stronger yen,'' Yeh said.
	   He added that the collapse of Japan's domestic demand means the
country is liquidity strapped.
	   ``Interest rates are very low. Businesses and consumers are not
spending and the Japanese Government has tried very hard to
stimulate spending.
	   However, consumers and corporations are not responding and
domestic consumption has fallen considerably.''
	   Yeh explained that most large economies are two-thirds
domestic-driven.
	   ``They cannot export their way out of the economic gloom. The
region is hoping that Japan will be the engine leading to economic
recovery for the region (like the US was for Mexico)... but Japan
is not likely to be the locomotive here.
	   ``We have to wait for the Japanese economy to pick up ... we
have to wait for measures to filter through the economy,'' Yeh
added.
	   Japan announced in April a record 16.6 trillion yen (100yen  &QC; 
RM2.90) stimulus spending package but markets are yet to be
convinced that it will have a long-term impact on the economy.
	   He said since Japan has been in an economic slump since the
early 1990s, it stands a better chance of recovering.
	   Meanwhile, head of research at Kenanga BNP PrimeEast, Mr Seow
Choong Liang said the impact of the falling yen on the region's
currencies is clear-cut.
	   ``The yen is being held by some countries in their reserves.
Therefore, the devalution of the yen could have a direct affect on
the region's currencies.
	   ``The devaluation of the yen could also make Japanese goods more
competitive and thus other countries in the region would have to
devalue currencies if they want to remain in the game,'' Seow said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
