<BODY>
<SLUG> WORLD-CLASS-STANDARDS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Wilken pushes for world-class standards, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Wilken pushes for world-class standards, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   REMEMBER actor James Dean, the rebel without a cause? Well, meet
a rebel with a cause - Leo Burnett Advertising Sdn Bhd's chief
operating officer and managing director, Peter Wilken.
	   His cause is to push the level of the local advertising industry
to consistently achieve world standards.
	   And he wants Leo Burnett to be the pioneer, the catalytic player
in upping the quality ante of the local advertisement industry.
	   Only by constantly seeking improvement, he said, agencies ensure
that they survive the ever-increasing competition from other firms
and management consultants.
	   As such, Wilken stated, it's high time that the industry's
leading agencies see beyond the national landscape and produce
world-class products.
	   According to him, if this challenge requires them to
unreasonably demand changes in the attitude of all industry players
and of rules regulating the industry, then so be it.
	   Like the true advertising man that he is, Wilken backs his
position by quoting George Bernard Shaw, who once said, human
progress is usually achieved by the unreasonable person and not by
the reasonable one.
	   Achieving quality by engaging in change management is something
that this 37-year-old Briton has done before.
	   He did this when he headed Ogilvy and Mather Philippines where
he transformed the agency from a low-profile outfit into an
award-winning, all within a time frame of within two years.
	   And hence it comes as no surprise that he has embarked on a
programme to reinvent the agency since coming on board in December
last year. This he believes, would play an instrumental role in
helping the agency to better conform to the dictates of the
marketplace. However, in doing so, Wilken does not intend to
compromise Leo Burnett's main asset - its people. That would
explain their on-going recritment exercise.
	   Currently, Leo Burnett is one of the largest privately-owned
companies in the world. The agency handles many of the world's top
brands, including the top three, namely McDonalds, Coca-Cola and
Marlboro.
	   Managing and nurturing creative people Q: You have experienced a
wide and varied career. How has this prepared you in helming Leo
Burnett at this particular juncture?
	   A: I am lucky that the first five of the nine years that I have
been in Asia was spent playing a pan-regional role. This gave me
the opportunity to work in many different markets, cultures and
scenarios.
	   Prior to that, I had the experience to live through one of the
worst economic recession in Europe.
	   If anything, I believe these experiences have taught me to stick
to my principles, especially in defining what you are as a person
and what your company believes in.
	   In other words, never lose sight of what your goals are and
always look long term.
	   Furthermore, we have to retain emotional commitment to our
partners.
	   As such, Leo Burnett will not be rattled by short-term pressures
and will only react according to long term perspective. As such,
Leo Burnett for example, will not be pulling out of the industry,
unlike one agency which did so recently just because the economy is
presently not doing well.
	   Q: Can you explain your vision for the company?
	   A: My own personal vision will reflect the corporate vision,
it's a shared vision.
	   But during a recent management meeting at Terengganu, we reached
a watershed decision.
	   We decided that after being a leading player in the local
advertising industry for the last few years, we should expand our
horizons and seek global recognition.
	   We intend to make advertisement campaigns that can be recognised
on a worldwide basis. This is because now people work and shop on a
worldwide basis, for example, someone from Chicago can come and
engage our strategic expertise.
	   Malaysia should be one of the top places to provide such
services and at the moment we are doing a disservice to the country
in allowing our competitors from Thailand, Singapore and Taiwan
steal a march on us.
	   But instead, in a recent CNBC-Media Asian Advertising industry
poll, Malaysia was placed quite lowly in terms of the most creative
countries to work in.
	   And in this survey, Thailand topped the list.
	   This is surprising since in terms of creative manpower, both the
countries are similar. It is actually attitude and some constraints
placed on the industry, like the Made-in-Malaysia policy.
	   Although, Leo Burnett is doing in isolated cases some world
class work, but this is not done in a consistent manner as it
should be done rightly so.
	   I intend to achieve this in two to three years' time.
	   Q: How do you ensure that your employees embrace your vision and
work in tandem to it?
	   A: You can't force feed a vision, at best you can only encourage
them to take it on.
	   It's a bit like learning, they should make the effort to absorb
what is being taught.
	   They have to know that the company intends to be world class in
what we do and work towards it.
	   Q: What is the difference between managing an advertising agency
and managing any other company?
	   A: The difference is that agencies don't physically produce
anything except ideas.
	   So we can't measure ourselves on a physical basis, so that's the
main challenge.
	   Furthermore, we are dealing with extremely bright and
independently minded people.
	   And generally, creative people, tend to be much more free
spirited and don't respond well if they're placed in straitjacket.
	   However, they still need some sort of boundaries.
	   So managing people and creating an environment to this effect is
absolutely important, especially so as it's a delicate thing that
needs to be constantly nurtured.
	   Q: Can we expect Malaysians to head the company anytime soon?
	   A: Well, our chairman, Ali Mohamed, is a Malaysian and it's a
fact that Leo Burnett has one of the lowest expatriate to Malaysian
ratio for an international agency. But, I believe that nationality
should be secondary to ability and talent. If we had an Eskimo who
is capable, we will hire him or her - it won't make a difference.
	   Q: Leo Burnett prides itself for low employee turnover. How did
the company achieve this?
	   A: Actually, manpower turnover is an interesting question.
Although generally it is treated as a good development, it does not
have to be so all the time.
	   Sometimes, it means that the company is not being aggressive
enough in promoting change within its organisation.
	   Advertising agencies are especially slow in the way they do
business and hence need dramatic change.
	   Changes not only in the way they are structured but also in
competing effectively in the marketplace.
	   To succeed against management consultancies, for example,
agencies need to hire people with absolutely leading edge strategic
capabilities.
	   But of course I'm not implying that to raise manpower quality,
an infusion of new blood is all that is required. We also rely
heavily on our own internal resources for this.
	   Q: How do you ensure that you have a ready supply of creative
people?
	   A: Creative training is really difficult although many people
still try it.
	   You can educate people to a certain extent like in the areas of
art direction but I don't really think that we can teach
creativity.
	   One way to encourage creativity is to push for the creation of
better advertising campaigns by using the world's best as the
benchmark.
	   Q: Management wise, how is Leo Burnett different from other
companies?
	   A: Well, we don't really do anything really radically different
but I would say that we do some of the simpler things in our
business exceptionally well.
	   Q: You speak much about change management. How will it affect
Leo Burnett organisationally?
	   A: I would like to create smaller companies within companies.
	   They will run with much autonomy and responsibility but infused
with the same spirit as its parent company.
	   Q: The first casualty during times of economic distress is the
advertising and public relations budget. Any comments?
	   A: Well, this is evidently occurring. Apart from few, usually
the larger multinationals, many companies don't actively invest
during these times.
	   It is happening simply because advertisement budget is the most
easiest and flexible budget that can be cut without an immediate
counter backlash.
	   Furthermore, many of the people who are working on the
advertisement budget don't have to live with the consequences as
the average life-cycle of a marketing manager is about three years.
	   Unfortunately, the long-term damage is not taken into account.
	   The impact of a large sustained budget cutback will not be seen
for about three to four years.
	   But then, the process of recovering market position too will
take an almost same amount of time.
	   Nevertheless, it is hard to argue with clients who are fighting
to retain their employees to make a choice between their
advertising budget and their people.
	   Advertising is something that is intangible, and people will
always argue for something that is tangible, like retaining their
employees.
	   Nevertheless, anyone who takes 10 minutes to read the various
literature abound on why advertising is key for long-term survival
will understand the need for continued advertising.
	   Additionally, this is the ideal time to kill off smaller
competitors.
	   Thus, the situation provides huge possibilities for companies
with foresight to invest.
	   Q: Do you think advertising takes a backseat because it is seen
as a luxury and not a necessity?
	   A: What many companies say and do are different. Many claim that
they know that advertising is important. However, figures
conclusively show that Malaysian companies tend to cut advertising
during recessionary times.
	   
</TEXT>
