<HEADLINE>
Ministry to probe rice price hike, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Ministry to probe rice price hike, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ainon MohdASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Sun. - The Domestic Trade and Consumer Affairs
Ministry will meet Padiberas Nasional Bhd to discuss allegations
that it is the cause of the price increase in the Super grade rice.
	   Its minister, Datuk Seri Megat Junid Megat Ayob, said the
meeting was to find ways to stop spiralling prices, and to ensure
that no party would take advantage of the high market demand by
marking up the prices of super grade rice which is not
government-regulated.
	   The meeting, he said, would also include rice importers, millers
and wholesalers.
	   ``We have to check whether these allegations are true. This is a
staple food and an important item ... profits should not be the
only criterion,''
	   he said when asked to comment on allegations by the Federation
of the Malaysian Consumer Associations that Bernas had sold
imported rice at a high price.
	   He was speaking after the launching of Pemadam Kawasan Parliamen
Segambut.
	   Megat Junid who did not deny that some traders took advantage of
the situation to mark up the prices of super grade rice, said his
ministry and the Agriculture Ministry were studying ways to
overcome this situation.
	   ``The Government is likely to decide on whether to control the
price of super grade rice,'' he said adding that at the moment, the
Government would let market forces determine the price instead of
making it a controlled item.
	   The only control on super grade rice is on its quality in that
it should contain not more than 25 per cent of low quality rice
(beras hancur).
	   Standard Grade is a local produce which contains broken rice,
rice from unripened padi and permissible foreign bodies while
Premium Grade is local rice of moderate quality.
	   Megat Junid said studies showed that many prefer Super grade
rice compared to standard and premium grades.
	   Super grade, he said commands a 90 per cent market of the total
consumption nationwide, making it profitable and more favourable
for millers.
	   The lowest price of super grade rice with five per cent broken
content was RM2.52 per kg, those for packs with 10 to 15 per cent
broken content were lower at RM1.80.
	   The retail price of premium grade rice is fixed at RM1.05 per kg
while there is virtually no demand for standard grade rice.
	   Megat Junid said both ministries would continue enforcement to
ensure that prices of super grade rice would remain reasonable.
	   He said the Government could take action if traders and
retailers increased the prices of premium and standard grade rice
but could not do so for super grade rice although the contents must
conform to specifications laid down by the Government.
	   Megat Junid said the prices of domestic and imported rice had
increased by 21 per cent and 52 per cent respectively compared to
previous price since May.
	   He said the price of rice had become expensive while the demand
had increased due to the declining production caused by the El Nino
weather phenomenon.
	   ``Indonesia which used to have a surplus of more than three
million tonnes of rice is facing a decline in its production which
had inevitably caused a shortage in the supply of rice to this
country,'' he said.
	   Earlier, Megat Junid, who is Pemadam president, said the 10
parliamentary constituencies in the Federal Territory must set up a
branch to provide after-care services to reformed addicts.
	   
</TEXT>
