<HEADLINE>
500 companies taking part in expo to promote local products, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
500 companies taking part in expo to promote local products, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Eirmalasare BaniASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SOME 500 manufacturing companies of local products and services
will take part in the `Love Malaysia Consumer Fair 1998', an
exposition, said to be the biggest in the country.
	   Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir Mohamad is scheduled to
officiate at the event, which will be held at the Mines Exhibition
Centre for a period of 10 days, from July 10 to July 19.
	   Announcing the details yesterday, Transport Minister Datuk Seri
Dr Ling Liong Sik said the event is to promote local products and
services, as part of efforts to overcome the current economic
problems.
	   ``When you love Malaysia, you buy Malaysian goods. This can help
our factories to strengthen their positions and ensure the
permanence of their employees,'' he told reporters in Kuala Lumpur.
	   Besides buying local products, he said, Malaysians should also
use local services and save with local banks, study at local
universities and holiday at local tourist spots.
	   ``It improves the national resilience. This is what `Buy
Malaysia' means,'' he said.
	   The exposition is jointly organised by the Kuala Lumpur and
Selangor Chinese Chamber of Commerce and Industry (KLSCCCI) and the
Love Malaysia Action Committee. Its main sponsor is the Country
Heights Group of Companies.
	   The event demonstrates the loyalty and sincerity of Malaysian
Chinese businessmen in overcoming current economic woes, said
KLSCCCI president Lim Guan Teik.
	   To date, 300 companies have confirmed their participation
including the Taiwan Manufacturers' Association and some foreign
companies which manufacture here.
	   On whether other entrepreneurs such as Malays and Indians can
take part in the exposition, Ling said ``This is a national effort.
All are invited and no one who wishes to participate will be left
out.''
	   Besides promoting products and services, some companies will
also offer special prices during the promotion period.
	   
