<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Tajikistan,0400 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Annan protests law banning religious parties in Tajikistan
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROBERT H. REID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Secretary-General Kofi Annan told
Tajikistan's president Tuesday that a new law banning religiously
based political parties could undermine the 1997 peace accord
between the government and the largely Muslim opposition.
	   The agreement guaranteed posts in a coalition government to the
United Tajik Opposition. But the UTO's largest component, the
Islamic Revival Party, would presumably be banned under the new
law, adopted by the Tajik parliament May 23.
	   Annan met Tuesday with Tajik President Emomali Rakhmonov to
express ``serious concern that this decision would remove one of
the main pillars of the General Peace Agreement,'' the United
Nations said in a statement.
	   The agreement provided for the legalization of banned political
parties following the public declaration by the UTO that it had
disbanded its armed wing.
	   ``The secretary-general voiced the expectation that the
conciliation commission established by President Rakhmonov will
resolve this matter in the spirit of the general agreement signed
by the Tajik government with the United Tajik Opposition,'' the
statement added.
	   There was no comment from Rakhmonov, who was in New York to
attend the U.N. General Assembly special session on drugs, which
opened Monday.
	   Approval of the law banning such parties is among several recent
developments which have led to warnings from the opposition about
the prospect of renewed, largescale fighting in the former Soviet
Central Asian republic.
	   Last month, Tajik opposition figures also denounced a new
partnership among Russia, Uzbekistan and Tajikistan to curb the
rise of Islamic fundamentalism in the region.
	   The opposition said the partnership would ``seriously jeopardize
the divided Tajik society. Russia, Uzbekistan and Tajikistan formed
the partnership to work to end the violence that has erupted twice
this year in Tajikistan, killing dozens of people.
	   Uzbek President Islam Karimov also said the new partners should
work together to revive Tajikistan's economy and oppose aggressive
Islamic fundamentalism in both Central Asia and the North Caucasus
regions.
	   Tajikistan has been troubled by sporadic violence despite the
peace accord ended a five-year civil war.
</TEXT>
