w1903 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  FAREWELL-TO-AN-INDUSTRYs     06-09 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> FAREWELL-TO-AN-INDUSTRY sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Farewell to an industry pioneer, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Farewell to an industry pioneer, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Lim ChongASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IT wasn't the kind of news that grabbed too much attention and
the impact was probably felt more among those involved in computer
journalism. After 23 years, one of the computer industry's most
respected publications, Byte, is closing down.
	   Started in 1975, the magazine practically grew up alongside the
personal computer (PC) industry and was at one time regarded as
``the technology magazine''. It was known for its serious, in-depth
reporting on technology, as well as for its editorial independence
and influence on the computer industry.
	   Byte was seen as the benchmark and there were no serious
competitors then. It was always the first to report on the new
trends and the noteworthy in technology. But in recent years,
circulation has fallen, along with advertising revenues. Long-time
readers would notice the drastic cut in pagination of what was once
the thickest computer publication around.
	   Finally, it was bought over by CMP Media which decided to
suspend publication after the July issue. Though the company has
announced plans for a revamped version, many are sceptical. It also
appears to be doubtful as 74 of the 85 staff members were being
laid off.
	   Why buy a magazine and then suspend it?
	   An explanation offered by John Dvorak, the well-known columnist
of PC Magazine, was that CMP still perceived Byte to be a serious
rival of its own flagship Windows magazine. ``The sad thing is that
Byte is a symbolic and historic publication that should not have
met with such an ignominious finale. It's a crime,'' Dvorak
commented.
	   I remember Byte from way back because it was the favourite
computer magazine of the late Mah Swee Aun, who was also a pioneer
of sort, being the first sub-editor to work on Computimes. He used
to point out the interesting articles in each issue, and the crisp
writing style and easy- to-follow layout and design that
journalists should learn to emulate - a guide to the new age of
inIT journalism. However, Mah wasn't so forthcoming when anyone
wanted to borrow his copy of Byte.
	   Still, the magazine's abrupt end does come as a surprise. One
reason given was that Byte was not consumer-oriented but geared
more towards serious computer users. It doesn't focus on any niche
market segments like PCs or networking but attempts to be
wide-ranging, covering practically everything that was
computer-related. It was crammed with technical details about
hardware and software, a treasure trove for the computer
enthusiasts.
	   Perhaps, it tried to do too much, and failed to notice the
changes taking place around the industry. In recent years, the
computer magazine market has become rather specialised and a
general interest publication tends to find the going tough while
looking to retain readers and advertisers.
	   For Byte, the shutdown came after 10 years of sharp declines,
even though various attempts were made to revamp the magazine and
made it more relevant to readers and industry. Unfortunately, these
were not successful or maybe too late.
	   The demise of Byte also marked the end of Jerry Pournelle's
Chaos Manor user column, regarded as the longest-running,
continuously published feature in computer journalism. Another
milestone.
	   For those who were involved in computer publishing long before
computers were as ubiquitous as they are today, the end of Byte is
seen as the end of an era. Possibly, there are lessons to be
gathered from the demise of a once-prominent pioneer.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:FAREWELL-TO-AN-INDUSTRY sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
