</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> TECHNOFISH-HAS-A-WINNER sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Technofish has a winner in the aquarium, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Technofish has a winner in the aquarium, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   TECHNOFISH Sdn Bhd has proven that the aquarium fish business is
lucrative and probably yields the fastest returns among the various
pisciculture activities.
	   The company exports 98 per cent of its fish to countries like
Singapore, the US, Japan, the UK, Germany, France, Italy, the
Netherlands, Spain, Belgium, Taiwan and South Korea.
	   ``There is great potential in this industry due to the high
demand overseas,'' said managing director Raymond Cheah.
	   Technofish, which started 12 years ago as a pioneer status
company, breeds and sells wholesale about 40 species and 60
varieties of aquarium fish commercially on its eight-hectare fish
farm at the Senai Industrial Estate.
	   It invested between RM50,000 and RM100,000 on each 0.4-ha of the
farm.
	   Each plot consists of about 20 to 200 earth ponds, areas for
hatchery, nursery, growout, grading, quarantine and packing.
	   ``The sales value for every hectare ranges between RM5,000 and
RM20,000 per month,'' Cheah said.
	   Besides fancy carp, scientifically known as cyprinus carpio,
other varieties include ramirez (apistogramma ramirezi), tiger barb
(barbodes tetrazona), goldfish (carrassius auratus), managuense
cichlid (cichlasoma managuense), dwarf gourami (colisa lalia),
kissing gourami (helostoma temmincki) and angel fish (pterophyllum
scalare).
	   Cheah said among the best selling were the tetras such as
penguin tetra (thayeria obliqua) and glowlight tetra (hemigrammus
erythrozonus), barbs and gouramis. The company breeds its own fry
from imported parent stock from countries in Southeast Asia,
Australia, China, India, Mexico, Colombia, Brazil, Argentina,
Congo, Zambia and Madagascar.
	   Technofish also prepares its own feed, carries out in-breeding
and hatchery experiments as well as supplying fish fry to other
farms.
	   These fry are cultivated in the farm until they reach marketable
size.
	   Cheah, who is also the Johor Aquarium Fish Breeders Association
vice- president, said the aquarium fish industry had the fastest
returns compared with other agriculture-related ventures.
	   Technofish also provides training courses for Fisheries
Department staff and Universiti Putra Malaysia students.
	   Johor produces about 62 per cent of the country's total export
of RM60 million worth of aquarium fish last year.
	   There are more than 400 fish breeders in the State, scattered
over Jemaluang, Layang Layang, Ulu Tiram, Pontian, Kulai, Kluang,
Kota Tinggi and Kempas.
	   Cheah said the State Fisheries Department's constant support had
contributed to the success of the industry.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
