	   SINGAPORE's benchmark stock index closed 3.4 per cent lower
yesterday as the falling yen forced Japanese investors to dump
shares and pull down South-East Asian currencies.
	   The Straits Times Industrials index ended 39.89 points down at
1,128.57.
	   The broader All-Singapore index fell 9.66 points to 314.55.
	   Falling stocks outnumbered those rising 272 to 38 with 281
unchanged.
	   Turnover fell to 137.511 million shares valued at S$244.975
million, from 112.97 million shares worth S$207.6 million.
	   Following the yen's fall past the 140 level to the US dollar,
the Singapore unit weakened to around 1.7095 to the dollar.
	   Among the most heavily traded stocks was DBS Land Ltd, with 8.58
million shares changing hands before closing 10 cents lower at
S$1.58.
	   Top gainer was NatSteel Broadway Ltd which rose 19.5 cents to
S$1.00, while the biggest loser was City Developments Ltd which
shed 62 cents to end trading at S$2.28.
	   
