<HEADLINE>
Shares ease across the board, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Shares ease across the board, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   SHARES on the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) ended
yesterday's trade broadly lower as investors dumped stocks on
worries over the declining ringgit, said analysts.
	   The gloomy regional markets yesterday also contributed to the
weak sentiment as the Japanese yen continued to fall against the US
dollar.
	   The KLSE Composite Index (KLCI) breached the psychological
500-point level yesterday to end the day 7.26 points or 1.44 per
cent down at 497.79 after touching a low of 497.44 at 3.48pm. Big
capitalised stocks were under selling pressure yesterday as foreign
funds, in reaction to the weakening ringgit were shorting the
stocks in thin volumes.
	   Yesterday, the ringgit closed at 3.9950/005 to the greenback as
against 3.9700/900 last Friday.
	   A weak ringgit would raise the external debt of the country's
corporations and raise the price of imported goods, they said.
	   The Second Board index closed 0.36 points lower to 109.05 while
the broader-based Emas Index was down 2.09 points at 128.46.
	   The scoreboard showed losers outpacing gainers 430 to 128 with
159 counters remained unchanged.
	   The broad-based BT Ordinaries eased 2.07 points to 121.78 while
the 30- share New Straits Industrial Index slid 34.96 points to end
at 2,988.05.
	   On the KLSE yesterday, total turnover was 99.290 million shares
valued at RM225.384 million compared with 106.763 million shares
valued at RM279.069 million last Friday.
	   Turnover on the main board was 82.729 million shares worth
RM214.948 million while trade on the Second Board was 5.504 million
shares worth 8.216 million yesterday.
	   Maybank was the most active counter with 13.259 million shares
traded followed by Berjaya Singer TSRs with 5.653 million shares
and TNB with 4.547 million shares dealt.
	   
</TEXT>
