<SLUG> CARLSBERG-LAUNCHES sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Carlsberg launches a new brand of beer, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Carlsberg launches a new brand of beer, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   CARLSBERG has launched Carl's Reserve, which was initially
introduced for a limited period as a festive beer during this
year's Chinese New Year.
	   The new product is crystal-filtered, giving it a lively and
distinctive taste and less bitter than other regular beers.
	   Carlsberg Malaysia Managing Director Datuk Jorgen Bornhoft said
overwhleming market response during its launch, and subsequent
positive findings from consumer research led to the decision to
launch Carl's Reserve as a permanent brand.
	   The beer, which is aimed at the upper segment of the market,
will be initially available in small bottles only. There are plans
to introduce cans in the near future.
	   The product will also be distributed selectively in hotels,
clubs, pubs, restaurants and major supermarkets.
	   ``We in Carlsberg are very optimistic of the many opportunities
that exist now for entrenching Carl's Reserve solidly in this
market, even in these trying times.
	   ``We are going to invest substanially in a long-term brand
building programme rather than short-term sales driven activities,
which clearly demonstrates our faith in Malaysia as well as our
confidence in the future of Carl's Reserve,'' Bornhoft said.
	   During a Press conference after the launch, Bornhoft said Carl's
Reserve would be priced around RM5 in the retail market. It was
aimed at the younger generation.
	   When asked about the future prospects of the beer market, he
said, despite the economic problems the market was doing reasonably
well.
	   ``I do not agree with the notion that more people are drinking
beer because of the economic downturn. The Malaysian beer market
has always been supported by people who enjoy their drinks
especially those who drink moderately in the company of friends.
	   ``As such the trend is continuing. Furthermore there are also
those who are switching from expensive hard liquor to beer during
these times,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
