<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Yassin, 1st Ld-Writethru,0557 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hamas: Sheik Yassin to return within days
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with Yassin comment, Israel barring family
of another Hamas official from entering Gaza; ADDS Byline &QL; 
 &UR; By IBRAHIM BARZAK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip (AP) _ Sheik Ahmed Yassin, founder and
spiritual leader of the radical Islamic group Hamas, will return to
Gaza within days, a spokesman said Tuesday.
	   Mahmoud Zahar, a Hamas spokesman, told The Associated Press that
Yassin _ who has been on a 3 1/2-month tour of Muslim countries
raising millions of dollars and drumming up support for Hamas _
will ``most likely'' come back to Gaza on Saturday.
	   Israel's security establishment and political leaders have been
debating for weeks whether the sheik would pose a greater danger
from outside or inside Gaza. Israel, which controls Gaza's borders,
could keep Yassin out if it wished.
	   Meanwhile, Israel barred the wife and children of another Hamas
official, Mousa Abu Marzouk, from entering the Gaza Strip from
Egypt Tuesday. Abu Marzouk was released last summer from a U.S.
jail and sent to Jordan where he lives now, after promising not to
get involved in terrorism.
	   ``This morning, my brother's wife Nadia and her five children
were refused entry into Gaza by the Israeli border police, even
though they traveled on American passports'' Abu Marzouk's brother
Mahmoud said.
	   He said it was the first time Israel had ever refused her
permission to visit and that the family had asked the Palestinian
Authority to intervene on their behalf. Mrs. Abu Marzouk returned
to Cairo, her brother-in-law said.
	   Regarding Yassin's return to Gaza, Israeli leaders appeared
Tuesday to be leaning toward allowing him back, in part because
keeping him out could set off an explosion of violence by backers
of Hamas.
	   ``The choice is not between what is good and better, but between
what is bad and worse,'' Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu told
Israel radio.
	   Yassin was quoted by the Sudan News Agency in Khartoum where he
is visiting, as saying he would return.
	   ``I did not sneak out through a window and I am going back home
through the door sooner or later. i am going to live among my
people leading the jihad there,'' Yassin said.
	   State-owned Israel TV reported that Israel's internal security
agency, Shin Bet, submitted its recommendation to the government
that Yassin's returned be allowed and coordinated with the
Palestinian Authority. Not other details on the recommendation were
available and the secret agency does not have a spokesperson.
	   Hamas opposes peace with Israel, and its military wing has
killed more than 100 Israelis in scores of attacks in recent years.
	   The group's popularity in the Palestinian lands, especially
Gaza, is seen as a growing threat to Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat's authority.
	   Yassin's fiery comments on his tour, such as his description of
suicide attacks as ``holy missions,'' have been widely reported in
Israel.
	   Yassin was freed from an Israeli jail last fall to buy the
freedom of two Israeli Mossad agents captured in Jordan during a
bungled assassination attempt on another Hamas leader.
	   On Monday, Netanyahu's inner security Cabinet debated the Yassin
question, but did not reach any decision.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Israel-Yassin, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:INDI;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:ASIA;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
