<HEADLINE>
Formation of AMCs quite common in the West, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Formation of AMCs quite common in the West, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE formation of asset management companies to manage
non-performing loans is quite common in the West - an example that
is being followed by the Government in establishing Pengurusan
Danaharta Nasional Bhd.
	   Time will tell of the success or failure of this courageous
undertaking by the Government.
	   In its website, Bank Negara has included case studies of
countries such as the US, Sweden and Mexico, which have formed such
asset management companies following concerns on the solvency of
local banks.
	   The central bank said from 1980 to 1991, about 1,400 banks in
the US failed or received government assistance. During the same
period, 1,100 thrifts (retail savings and loans insitutions)
failed.
	   The US legislature then created the Resolution Trust Corporation
to help troubled thrifts.
	   The RTC's brief was to take over the non-performing loans of
failed thrifts, and actively manage these assets to maximise value
pending eventual disposal.
	   Formed in 1989, the RTC had at its peak assets totalling about
US$1 trillion (RM4 trillion). All these assets have been
successfully disposed of and the RTC ceased operations in 1996.
	   Another form of an asset management company set up by the US
Congress way back in 1933 was the Federal Depositors Insurance
Corporation which, among other things, acquired NPLs of banks
facing insolvency.
	   In what is termed as ``bulk sales,'' the FDIC, said Bank Negara
in its website, acquired NPLs as well as performing loans and sold
them in bulk to interested parties through a closed bid process.
	   Loans bought in bulk sales have common characteristics and are
packaged according to criteria such as loan size, quality, type,
collateral and location.
	   These packages are offered to interested parties and the
successful bidder takes on all the risks of the acquired loan
package from FDIC.
	   Bid packages forwarded to interested parties offer a specific
loan portfolio including loans information spreadsheets, invitation
and instruction to bid, loan sales agreements and other important
documents.
	   The FDIC finances its operations through the issue of bonds.
	   Bank Negara said in its website that the Mexican Government
received financial assistance from the US, the World Bank and the
Inter-American Development Bank.
	   This allowed the Government to provide support for banks through
the Bank Fund for Savings Support, Fondo Bancario para Proteccion
del Ahorro (FOBAPROA).
	   The FOBAPROA is a trust established by the Banco de Mexico to
provide ``preventive support'' to problem banks.
	   Its existence predates the 1994-1995 Mexican banking crisis.
FOBAPROA's stated mission is to cover all bank liabilities, except
subordinated debt.
	   FOBAPROA has generally acted as the lead agency in resolving
bank problems since the peso crisis.
	   One of the major FOBAPROA assistance programmes implemented was
the purchase of impaired loan assets from banks at net book value
(on the basis of the Mexican rating system) in exchange for a
requirement for the bank in question to raise new equity.
	   The FOBAPROA instituted this programme on a case by case basis:
in some instances, the FOBAPROA purchased US$2 of loans for every
US$1 of equity injected; other cases have run as high as 5 to 1.
	   In the case of Sweden, two banks were taken over by the
government, which formed asset management companies to acquire
these banks' non- performing assets.
	   This happened during the years 1991 to 1993 when several banks
were facing insolvency, Bank Negara said.
	   The Swedish government's initial step was to guarantee the
safety and soundness of the banking system, stating it would stand
behind the banks.
	   The government adopted legislation creating a comprehensive
programme to restructure the banking system. Its support led to the
private sector recapitalisation of the banks.
	   Four other banks in Sweden were encouraged to form their own
similar asset workout vehicles to take over problem real estate
loans.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
