<SLUG> WAT-ER-WAY-TO-PULL-DOWN sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Wat-er way to pull down the economy, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Wat-er way to pull down the economy, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   K.H. LimASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IT is now official: Malaysia's economy contracted 1.8 per cent
in the first quarter but all is not lost as pronouncements since
then have given us hope.
	   Leading the chorus was Bank Negara Governor Tan Sri Ahmad Mohd
Don who duly noted that growth was picking up early in the second
quarter. At a recent briefing where the negative Gross Domestic
Product figure was announced, Ahmad and his team tried their best
to assure the Press that the economy was picking up steam.
	   However, the central bankers stopped short of saying whether
second quarter GDP growth would be positive. At best, there was an
impression of the second quarter hitting zero growth.
	   This column had warned in the third quarter of 1997 that if all
sectors of the economy were to cut costs, led by the Government
itself, there was a danger of the economy going into a tailspin
from which it would be extremely difficult to recover.
	   The concern then was that people in the private as well as
public sectors might go overboard in cutting costs rather than
cutting waste.
	   Cutting waste trims the fat and makes organisations more lean
and mean.
	   Cutting costs per se may be self-defeating. With everyone
cutting costs, domestic demand will shrink and the economy will
risk coming to a standstill.
	   Among the voices of hope was that of Deputy Prime Minister and
Finance Minister Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim. He had said March
actually saw pick-up and the first quarter results were pulled down
by January and February.
	   With this, there is hope that the second quarter may be flat or
slightly positive and Malaysia can avoid a recession which,
technically, is two successive quarters of contraction.
	   February has traditionally been a ``quiet'' and under-performing
month.
	   Activities slow down for the festive season and will take time
to gather speed again.
	   However, this time, the incompetence of the authorities
responsible for water has added to our woes. And the
``authorities'' here do not mean just the Selangor Waterworks
Department.
	   There is a strongly-held view that the first quarter GDP figures
might not have been negative if there was no water crisis. What do
you expect the data to show when factories had to cut down on
production?
	   At a time when the nation needs every productive sector to bring
in the badly-needed foreign exchange, we hear of electronics
factories cutting production by 30 to 50 per cent.
	   One cannot avoid looking at the situation with the benefit of
hindsight.
	   Yes, the Waterworks engineers had recommended early plans for
water supply schemes but the State authorities had other
``agendas.''
	   Yes, there is now a contingency plan but does anyone monitor it
to see whether it works? Does the rationing system work? At best, a
sympathetic review will show that the rationing only brings to the
fore the inherent weakenesses of the reticulation system.
	   One wonders if the Waterworks staff actually know which valve
controls which area and how long it takes for water to reach
particular areas.
	   How else can Waterworks explain why factories, including the
largest single user of water in the Klang Valley, did not get water
for five days at a stretch while others within the rationing zones
got water every day at the same time?
	   Waterworks can now deny this but no amount of denial can erase
the sad fact that these factories, including the single largest
user, have given the Government an ultimatum.
	   If the worst happens and these factories relocate, the country
will lose more than their investments in terms of ringgit and sen.
We will have lost our image as an attractive investment
destination. We will have told the world that in a country with
abundant rainfall, we are unable to assure investors of sufficient
water supply.
	   Errant and incompetent Waterworks staff must be punished if they
fail in their duties. The ``bad apples'' should not drag down the
thousands of diligent, hardworking and solution-driven
professionals in the department.
	   The work culture there has to shift to a higher plane. They
cannot adopt a tidak apa attitude of not attending to pipe leaks
and mains bursts. When we do not even produce enough for our needs,
let us conserve every drop we manage to put into the system.
	   (As I pen these lines, I cannot help but mention the tale of a
leaking tank near my house. Countless complaints, including one
directly to the district engineer in October, have brought no
solution. Action there was: sometime in November, a Waterworks
employee in a gleaming 4WD vehicle stopped by to check and told me
he had no ladder to do a proper check! (At that time, there was
only one leak detected. Another tank has since then also sprung a
leak and there are now two leaking tanks! My neighbours and I get a
free reminder each time supply resumes in our area due to the
racket caused.) As for the Selangor State Government, it cannot
shirk its responsibilities or pass the blame to others. The State
has failed to implement the water supply schemes that Waterworks
engineers had recommended as early as 1990.
	   To be fair to the current Menteri Besar, he inherited a
situation which inevitably turned into a crisis. The person who was
supposed to ``press the button'' several years ago is no longer
around.
	   Let us make the best of the situation and make sure everyone
gets their fair share of water, especially industrial users.
	   TALKING POINT: The Government, right up to the highest
authority, must now pull out the stops and make sure these
factories DO NOT leave. It is a matter of national honour.
	   
</TEXT>
