<HEADLINE>
E-commerce to help Customs cut costs, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
E-commerce to help Customs cut costs, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Adeline OngASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Royal Customs and Excise Malaysia spends some RM7 billion
annually on paper and document processing but electronic commerce
(e-commerce) will cut costs significantly and prove beneficial to
the Government, Deputy Finance Minister Datuk Dr Affifuddin Omar
said yesterday.
	   ``It will save a large amount in terms of money and e-commerce
will also enable the department to be more efficient. However, this
procedure is still at an early stage ... and therefore, it is
rather difficult to say how much can be saved by paperless
international trade,'' Affifuddin said.
	   He was speaking to reporters after opening the Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation (Apec) Customs-Industry Dialogue in Kuala
Lumpur yesterday.
	   It is estimated that in Japan, paper and document processing
costs US$12 billion (US$1  &QC;  RM4.000) a year, while it costs Apec
countries some US$46 billion.
	   E-commerce through the Internet is poised to boom over the next
few years with the value of transactions reaching US$300 billion by
the year 2001 from virtually zero at the start of 1990 and less
than US$10 billion today.
	   He also said the Customs Department will need to be more
transparent.
	   ``Through electronics, the department can be more transparent.
Currently, the files are kept in file cabinets in offices. When
people want to collect data, they have to follow specific rules and
regulations.
	   ``With the use of electronics, it is all there ... just a mouse
and a click away. It is not that it is not transparent now ... it
is just the nature of the administration and management of Customs
that makes it seem to be non-transparent,'' he added.
	   
</TEXT>
