<HEADLINE>
`Right move to build airport when ringgit was strong', BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
`Right move to build airport when ringgit was strong', BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PRIME Minister Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir Mohamad said the
Government had made the right move by building the RM9 billion KL
International Airport at Sepang when the ringgit was still strong.
	   ``Some people didn't understand why we wanted to build the
airport and they claimed it was too costly to build a new one.
	   ``However, if we did not build it then, and had we been forced
to do this later or even now, we would not have been able to build
such an airport at RM9 billion,'' he told newsmen after a two-hour
visit of the airport yesterday.
	   Work on the airport, including earth works, started four years
ago.
	   With the depreciation of the ringgit against the US dollar, Dr
Mahathir said the cost of building an airport of such size would
escalate.
	   ``The KL International Airport was built at the right time when
the ringgit was strong. It cost about RM9 billion, which is
equivalent to about US$4 billion (currently US$1  &QC;  RM4.00), at that
time.
	   ``Now, the cost (to build such airport) will be more due to the
appreciation of the US dollar against the ringgit. The RM9 billion
will be equivalent to about US$2.4 billion now,'' he added.
	   The ringgit closed easier at 4.0000/100 against the greenback
yesterday compared with Friday's close of 3.9700/900.
	   At a cost of RM9 billion, Dr Mahathir said this was considered
cheaper than in other countries. ``Other countries have built
smaller airports but at a higher cost,'' he said.
	   Dr Mahathir also did not dismiss the possibility that the second
phase of the KL International Airport project would be delayed due
to present economic problems.
	   ``It may or may not (be delayed)... that is beyond our control.
If people are not flying (to the airport), it will be meaningless
to build a new terminal.
	   ``But, I think even if there is a delay or not, it will not be
for too long,'' he said.
	   Located about 50km from Kuala Lumpur, the KL International
Airport is scheduled to start operations on June 29, with the Yang
di-Pertuan Agong Tuanku Ja'afar scheduled to officially open the
airport on June 27.
	   The KL International Airport is a four-phase project designed to
cater to the passenger and air cargo demands of Malaysia in the
next century.
	   Initially, the airport is expected to handle some 25 million
passengers a year, and this may increase to 35 million by the year
2008, and 45 million by year 2012.
	   
</TEXT>
