<BODY>
<SLUG> PM-CONFIDENT-KLIA sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PM confident KLIA will be opened on schedule, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
PM confident KLIA will be opened on schedule, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Kamarul YunusASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   PRIME Minister Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir Mohamad said he is
confident the KL International Airport in Sepang will be opened on
schedule.
	   Speaking to reporters after a two-hour tour of the new airport
yesterday, he said he had several private visits a few weeks
earlier, and he was worried that the airport might not be able to
be completed on time.
	   After the tour, Dr Mahathir described the progress of the
airport as ``good, the quality high, and the total airport
management systems did not pose problems.''
	   The Prime Minister toured the main terminal building, the
satellite building and the ``Bunga Raya'' complex, a special
arrival and departure complex for the VVIPs.
	   He was given a briefing on the operations of the airport by KLIA
Bhd, the company overseeing the construction of the airport.
	   He congratulated KLIA Bhd for completing the construction of the
airport within a short period. The company took four years for the
airport to be completed - one year for earthworks and three years
for building construction.
	   The earth works of the airport project, which was undertaken on
a build- operate-transfer concept, commenced in 1995. The Prime
Minister himself officiated at the ground breaking ceremony of the
first package of the construction of the main terminal building on
March 27 that same year.
	   He described this as a record of sort, explaining that it would
require quite considerable management skills to manage such a large
and complex development that required 25,000 workers and more than
300 contracts.
	   Following the completion of the new airport, Dr Mahathir said
the country has succeeded in developing expertise for future
construction of major projects.
	   Dr Mahathir also said there was no compromise on the quality of
the construction in spite of the short time it took to complete the
airport.
	   ``You can see for yourself, the quality is very good,
construction work is very good, the finish is very good and the
designs are very innovative,'' he said, adding that the furniture,
which were locally made, are also of good quality. In fact, he
said, ``practically everything is local.''
	   On complaints that signages at the airport are too small, Dr
Mahathir said adjustments have been made earlier to the signages
but stressed that the relevant authorities will make corrections if
there is a need for them to do so.
	   ``I had received comments on that matter and adjustments were
made earlier but there is still dissatisfaction. If that (signages)
is not good enough, we will make corrections ... we are open to
criticisms,'' he said.
	   On the Sultan Abdul Aziz Shah Airport in Subang, Dr Mahathir
said it will not be left idle as the Royal Malaysian Air Force base
is situated there.
	   ``Other than that, the airport will also be used for servicing
and repairs ... we may also use the airport for general aviation
and others relating to aviation such as handling the Tabung Haji
flights,'' he added.
	   Asked if he was satisfied with the fares for public transport to
the new airport, Dr Mahathir said: ``For the time being, there is
going to be a lot of complaints, but one has to remember that when
one upgrades a certain thing, we have to pay a higher price.
	   ``There is no way we can afford to have better facilities but
(at the) same price. In Malaysia, we always want better things but
we want to pay less,'' he said, adding that this is ``a bit
difficult''.
	   On suggestions that it would cost a taxi passengers more to go
from Kuala Lumpur to the airport than taking the taxi from Kuala
Lumpur to Ipoh, Dr Mahathir said they can then travel by road.
``There is no point really, travelling south 60 miles in order to
go north ... that is why we built good roads,'' he said.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 BUSINESS TIMES all rights reserved as distributed
by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
