<BODY>
<SLUG> AN-ALL-IN-ONE-SOLUTION sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
An all-in-one solution with SuperDisk Drive, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
An all-in-one solution with SuperDisk Drive, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Muhammed AzharASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FLOPPIES of 1.44 megabytes (MB) don't get much respect nowadays.
It worked fine in the Eighties, when files and computer programs
were small in size.
	   You could cram your annual expenses, company reports, a yearly
budget and everything else under the sun yet still have enough room
to spare for a computer game that you can play on the go.
	   But when the Nineties came, it brought along the Internet, and
with the Internet comes shareware, freeware and the likes. It also
brought about a boom in the computer industry.
	   Computers got faster, programs got larger in size and personal
computers experienced SOS - suddenly obsolete syndrome - where a
new PC today will be a prehistoric monster tomorrow. However, the
1.44MB, 3.5-inch floppy disk and drive somehow eluded evolution.
Hence it became the target of verbal abuse and jibes when someone
wanted to hand out a 5MB sound file to a friend or a 16MB file of
the latest freeware to a fellow techie.
	   Seeing this problem, the computer industry responded with
numerous solutions. One of the viable solutions is the emergence of
``super floppies'' - diskettes with capacities exceeding 1.44MB. Up
until now Iomega Corp was the obvious popular player in this league
with its Iomega Zip drive.
	   However, Mitsubishi Electric is set to change that. Its product,
the LS- 120 SuperDisk Drive has garnered support from notebook and
desktop PC manufacturers. Compaq, Hewlett-Packard, Gateway 2000,
Acer, IBM, NEC and Hitachi have announced that they would offer an
option of a 120MB Mitsubishi SuperDisk Drive with their computers.
More computer manufacturers are expected to follow.
	   The Mitsubishi LS-120 SuperDisk Drive is based on the LS-120
standard, developed by Imation Corp, Compaq Computer Corp,
Matsushita-Kotobuki Industries Ltd and OR Technology. It offers 83
times more storage space than the 1.44MB floppy and 20MB more than
its closest competitor, the Iomega Zip. The drive reads and writes
your ordinary, seen-and-used everywhere 3.5-inch disks as well as
the 120MB floppy disk, which looks and feels like an ordinary
floppy.
	   These characteristics make the LS-120 SuperDisk Drive a perfect
candidate to replace the already anaemic 1.44MB floppy disk and
drive. In case you are wondering how 120MB of data can be crammed
into a disk that has the same dimensions as an ordinary 1.44MB
floppy, the secret actually lies in the way the disk is
manufactured.
	   Basically, a unique manufacturing process is used to increase
the data track density on a 3.5-inch diskette from 135 tracks per
inch to 2,490 tracks per inch. This means that any unused gaps in
the floppy is fully utilised, and that data is stored much closer
together. This type of space conserving technique allows more data
to be stored in the same amount of space.
	   Since the track arrangements are different compared to a
conventional floppy, data is read using a special read/write head
that is accurately positioned using a laser servo motor. This head
also has the ability to read ordinary 3.5-inch diskettes as well,
hence boosting the reputation of this drive as a truly ``backward
compatible'' drive.
	   Installing the Mitsubishi LS-120 SuperDisk Drive was easy. All
we had to do is to place the drive in an empty bay in the PC,
connect the integrated drive electronics (IDE) cable from the back
of the drive to the motherboard and plug in the power cable to the
back of the drive. After that, we started our PC and Windows 95
detected the drive as a ``3.25-inch floppy'' and assigned it as an
E:\ drive.
	   According to the local distributor Metro Information Products
Sdn Bhd, the drive is supported by several motherboard
manufacturers such as Asus, Mitac and Trend. These motherboards
normally run on an Award Software Inc basic input output system
(BIOS).
	   Our review set was devoid of a proper installation manual, since
it is targeted at the original equipment manufacturer (OEM) market
or people who are comfortable with their way in and out of
computers. Therefore, installation of this product should be left
to people who know exactly what they are doing. The drive performed
file transferring from and to the PCs hard disk with amazing speed.
It took less than a minute to transfer a 10MB file from the hard
disk to the drive, and another minute or so to transfer the same
file back to the hard disk.
	   With such impressive speed, the SuperDisk Drive is perfect for
transferring, archiving or backing up files as long as the files do
not exceed the 120MB disk quota. However, this drive may not be the
perfect solution if you are talking about high-capacity back-ups.
	   You might be better off with devices such as Iomega's Jaz or
SyQuest's SyJet 1.5-gigabyte (GB) which offers higher storage
capacity with a faster transfer rate and shorter seek time. When we
reviewed Imation's External LS-120 SuperDisk Drive some time ago,
we found it has compatibility problems when an ordinary 1.44MB
diskette is formatted in it and then used in an ordinary floppy
drive. Apparently, data stored in that particular diskette cannot
be read by the ordinary floppy drive. We were wondering if
Mitsubishi's LS-120 SuperDisk Drive had the same problem.
	   To find out, we fully formatted a 1.44MB floppy disk using the
SuperDisk Drive and another disk using an ordinary floppy drive. We
then transferred three joint picture experts group (JPEG) image
files with a total file size of 100-kilobytes and a Microsoft Word
97 document 45 kilobytes (KB) in size into both the 1.44MB disk in
the SuperDisk Drive and the floppy drive. The 1.44MB disk that was
in the SuperDisk Drive was then placed in the floppy drive and vice
versa. It seems that Mitsubishi's SuperDisk Drive did not suffer
the compatibility problem Imation's drive had.
	   The SuperDisk Drive had no trouble at all displaying the images
and opening the Word document. In fact, it did the job smoothly and
without much fuss. The SuperDisk Drive is a bit noisy when compared
to the floppy drive though. The motors emitted some grinding and
clicking noises whenever the drive is accessed.
	   Mitsubishi's SuperDisk Drive looks like the perfect replacement
for your 1.44MB floppy disk drive. It offers a large storage
capacity and is able to read your old 1.44MB floppies as well. It
can also serve as a back-up tool for your data as long as it does
not exceed the 120MB storage limit the disk has.
	   This drive offers an all-in-one solution at a very low price.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:AN-ALL-IN-ONE-SOLUTION sked; CT:w; 
