<SLUG> AM-US-Nigeria </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US hopeful as new Nigerian leader takes over
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ The U.S. government praised Nigeria's new head
of state Tuesday, calling him a well respected professional soldier
who is capable of guiding his country toward democratic rule.
	   Spokesman James P. Rubin said Abdulsalam Abubakar, an army
general named to replace the late Sani Abacha, ``has a historic
opportunity to open the political process and institute a swift and
credible transition to civilian democratic rule.''
	   That process, Rubin said, should include freeing political
prisoners, ensuring respect for freedom of press, speech and
assembly and the return of the Nigerian military to the tasks of
defending the constitution and civilian rule.
	   ``We want this transition to make it possible for there to be a
return to civilian democratic rule by October 1, 1998,'' Rubin
said.
	   Rubin said a high-level U.S. mission may travel to Nigeria to
convey that message. Such a mission was supposed to go to Lagos
last week but Nigeria imposed conditions that the State Department
could not accept.
	   Abacha died on Monday after almost five years of repressive
rule. At the time of his death, he was maneuvering to perpetuate
his rule by being the sole candidate in elections set for August.
	   Abubakar, who received military training in the United States,
had served as Army chief of staff before assuming his new duties.
</TEXT>
