<SLUG> UMNO-COUNCIL-EXTENDS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Umno council extends V-P's leave, BUSINESS TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Umno council extends V-P's leave, BUSINESS TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   BUSINESS TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Fadzil GhazaliASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE Umno supreme council last night extended the leave of party
vice- president Tan Sri Muhammad Muhammad Taib.
	   Umno president and Prime Minister Datuk Seri Dr Mahathir Mohamad
said Muhammad's leave of absence has been extended until the court
makes a decision on the case.
	   ``The supreme council holds the opinion that Muhammad cannot
assume his duty as a Umno vice president. Furthermore, there is
news that he will be taken to court again.
	   ``As such, he is not yet allowed to assume his duties as the
vice president. His leave of absence will be extended until the
court makes a decision on his case,'' he told reporters after
chairing a three-hour Umno supreme council meeting in Kuala Lumpur
last night.
	   Dr Mahathir said Muhammad had met him yesterday morning to
submit a declaration on his assets.
	   ``I am now checking to find out when he last made such a
declaration ...
	   I was busy today so I did not check it properly,'' he added. The
Prime Minister visited the Kuala Lumpur International Airport in
Sepang yesterday morning.
	   Asked whether Muhammad's series of court cases, of which one was
in Australia, had caused any damage to the party, Dr Mahathir said:
``I do not know whether there is any damage or not. It just goes to
show that we have always adopted a stand that if any party member
does anything that warrants a case being taken against him, we will
not stand in the way.
	   Dr Mahathir said this has been the history of Umno, which had
seen several Menteris Besar facing court action, adding that: ``We
do not protect the guilty parties but if the person is innocent, we
will defend him.''
	   On the status of Negri Sembilan State Executive Councillor Datuk
Waad Mansor who was charged last May with five counts of
corruption, Umno deputy president Datuk Seri Anwar Ibrahim said the
supreme council had received his resignation last month.
	   ``He is now on leave of absence until after the court decision
is made on the charges,'' he added.
	   To a question on the main theme of the upcoming Umno assembly,
Dr Mahathir said the economic problems would most likely be the
main theme.
	   ``This is not surprising. I myself would be doing injustice if I
do not talk about the economic problems during the meeting,'' he
added.
	   Asked whether corruption and nepotism would also be raised at
the meeting, Dr Mahathir said it is up to party members to do so if
they felt that the matters needed attention.
	   On the opposition's call for a roundtable meeting with other
political parties to discuss the economic situation, Dr Mahathir
said: ``We do not want to politicise this issue. The opposition had
said that they will win more seats because of the economic
downturn. To them, it is a political issue which will benefit them.
	   ``So it is up to the people to accept whether it is proper to
make use of the country's misfortune to improve their (the
opposition) fortune,'' he said.
	   Dr Mahathir also said the supreme council will discuss in detail
the Indonesian economic situation, and the lessons that could be
learnt from the republic's experience.
	   It also discussed the criticisms made towards the New Economic
Policy.
	   
</TEXT>
