<HEADLINE>
Useful features in OmniBook 3000, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Useful features in OmniBook 3000, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Martyn GreenASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   WITH its OmniBook 3000, Hewlett-Packard looks set to kill the
competition.
	   The OmniBook 3000 comes with a Pentium 200-megahertz or 233MHz
MMX processor, an easy-to-read (13.3-inch) diagonal 1,024 by 768
extended graphics array (XGA) thin film transistor (TFT) active
matrix display screen with up to 65,536 colours for what HP says
are true-to-life colour presentations and graphics.
	   With two megabytes of (MB) video dynamic random access memory
(VDRAM) and a 128-bit NeoMagic video graphics controller, the
system allows for a ``Zoomed Video'' port within its personal
computer (PC) card slot.
	   This means that a 32-bit PC card is able to directly access the
graphics and audio systems - it writes directly to graphics memory.
This gives smooth-motion real-time video for more interesting
presentations and engaging entertainment.
	   Perhaps, most important of all in these days of increasing
``miniaturisation'' (almost to the point of absurdity with the new
palmtops) - the OmniBook still has an industry standard, 87-key
keyboard with full- size key spacing. There is also an embedded
numeric keypad and 12 function keys.
	   The OmniBook has a number of useful features. Apart from its
large 2.1- gigabyte or 4GB removable enhanced-IDE hard disk (with
hardware-based password), and standard 16MB of extended data out
(EDO) DRAM (expandable to 144MB), it also has a video out, a
universal serial bus (USB) connector, and a four megabits per
second (Mbps) wireless infra-red IrDA port.
	   The infra-red port allows for easy transfer of data to desktop
machines equipped with a NetbeamIR Ethernet Access Point.
	   The suspend-resume facility allows you to get to work whenever
and wherever inspiration strikes without re-booting - and will
allow you to continue for a lot longer than it is likely to last as
it has a (lithium- ion) battery life of up to 2.5 hours.
	   The battery can be recharged in less than 2.5 hours, even with
the computer on and with battery operation, there is a two-minute
low-battery warning before a controlled shutdown. There is also a
dual battery option so that for instance, when you want to work on
a long-haul flight, you can, HP claims, keep going for up to five
hours at a stretch.
	   For those occasions when you are feeling particularly sociable
and would like to ``talk'' to your computer (rather than shout and
scream when you realise you just exited a program without saving
your file!) the OmniBook has a built-in microphone along with Sound
Blaster Pro-compatible sockets for external mike/stereo line in and
both headphones and stereo speakers.
	   This means that, for instance, with IBM's Via Voice speech
recognition program (which you can install with the optional
slim-line, low-power 14X CD-ROM drive) and 16MB of additional
memory, you can dictate memos and letters straight into your
computer or use voice commands instead.
	   On earlier OmniBook models, HP fitted its well-known built-in
``mouse''
	   device. Bearing a strange resemblance to a small paper stapler,
it popped out from the side on a plastic rod. Some users liked it,
others preferred the Trackpoint used on other OmniBooks.
	   On the OmniBook 3000, HP installed a TouchPad pointing device.
	   Inevitably, each system just takes getting used to.
	   With earlier models, there wasn't even an external mouse port,
so unless you wanted to use up the only serial port, you more or
less had to learn to adapt. On the OmniBook 3000, HP have sensibly
made a very welcome addition - a combined keyboard/mouse port
(PS/2). Thus, for those who have found the OmniBook's integrated
keyboards a trifle ``stiff'' (such as this writer), there is at
last an answer.
	   Computer users inevitably find that they can never really get
all they want in one notebook - for instance, earlier OmniBooks did
not have a built-in CD-ROM drive, keyboard/mouse port or S-video
port. And the keyboards certainly could have done with a lighter
touch. But most of those issues have been addressed in the OmniBook
3000.
	   And when there's a choice of central processing unit (CPU)
speeds as high as 200MHz and 233MHz, ``road warriors'' will find
that they can not only easily run their ``killer aps'' - the
enhanced speed of the fastest 233MHz chip kills the pain of waiting
for them to load.
	   True, the industry's newest machines with Intel's 266MHz MMX P2
chips do offer about 10 per cent increase in performance. But it's
a trade-off since such raw power inevitably means shorter time
before batteries die.
	   It's a killer, isn't it?
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
