<BODY>
<SLUG> HI-TECH-SPACE-COMBAT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hi-tech space combat in BattleZone, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Hi-tech space combat in BattleZone, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Huong Chia HiangASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IN 1952, a meteorite crashes into the Bering Straits. American
and Soviet scientists scrambled to investigate the incident. A
strange new type of metal is discovered. Intelligence reports the
metal is of extra- terrestrial origin. Both American and Soviet
forces are trying to gather as much of it as possible. Conflict
escalates into one of the biggest cover-ups in the 20th century,
covert hi-tech space combat. Does any of those ring a bell?
	   Well if it does, chances are you have played or at least have
seen an advertisement or two about BatttleZone. That's right, the
old arcade classic that was the first of its kind, featuring
three-dimensional wire frame-based graphics is back. Well, sort of,
anyway.
	   BattleZone again?
	   Activision has totally revamped BattleZone and has just recently
re- released it. Wait, before you say ``Oh no not another lousy
revamp with spruced up graphics?'', just let me say a few things.
	   This current release of BattleZone looks and plays very
different; I'm quite surprised that Activision would just call it a
re-release. In my honest opinion, it is a totally new game that
just has an old label plastered on its box. The main difference
that clearly separates it from the original classic would be its
gameplay.
	   Besides the ``point and shoot until it blows'' part of the
original is being present, Activision has also added strategic
elements into the game that would have been thought of as a
first-person-perspective shoot-'em-up game.
	   Resource management has also become an important issue. This is
simply because just like in any other strategy games, you will be
given a base and is responsible for gathering resources needed to
manufacture key structures and units.
	   In the game, you are the field commander (be it American or
Soviet). At your disposal are various types of vehicles; each with
its own functions and specialities. For instance, on the American
side, the basic assault vehicles are the Razor (a fast scouting
unit), Grizzly (a heavy assault tank), Bobcat (a light assault
tank) and the list goes on. Do not be mislead by the term tank
here; these vehicles definitely do not operate in the same way as a
normal tank would. Instead of travelling on threads, these vehicles
travel by means of some sort of anti-gravity propulsion.
	   Piloting these vehicles is quite similar to playing a helicopter
simulation. Forward to advance, backward to reverse, left and right
to rotate. There are even additional booster rockets to accelerate
or to jump over high terrains. The combat controls seem to have
been taken from Quake in the sense that both keyboard and mouse are
utilised. This might be a little awkward to those who are new to
it, but I believe Quake players should have little trouble in using
it.
	   Selecting units for command could not have been any simpler as
BattleZone employs a high-intuitive interface. Important keys used
to access unit functions are highlighted, unit functions are
brought up as soon as they are in your targeting reticle. Even with
all that on a screen, it still remains quite uncluttered. If you
think all this is complicated, do not worry as BattleZone comes
equipped with some basic tutorial missions that will get you up and
rejoicing over the scraps of some enemy battle-tanks.
	   The strategic side of the game centres upon gathering bio-metal
to produce defence structures, utility structures and manufacturing
structures. In order to gather bio-metal, you will need to
manufacture scavenger units. Scavenger units would look for
bio-metal deposits or scrap from destroyed units and send it back
to a recycler (a type of light factory). The recycler is used for
manufacturing defence turrets and light units. It is also used to
manufacture ammo and repair kits which can be picked up by touch. I
guess this is the only other similarity it has with the original
classic.
	   Other than that, the various units in the game and their
different capabilities also contributed to BattleZone's
semi-strategic nature.
	   Activision has also redefined the degree of virtual movement in
this release. Players are not given a chance to pilot vehicles but
roam around on foot as well. Sure, Activision is not the first to
do it, but no other game has ever done it this well (one reason why
you probably never have heard of it in other games). Just picture
this and you will know how cool this feature is.
	   Your vehicle gets blasted to smithereens but you managed to
eject. It is quite fortunate that the enemy does not notice you
slowly floating to the ground. Now what do you do? Either you could
walk back to base and get into another vehicle, or you stay around
to wreak more havoc. Using a sniper rifle (yeah, a rifle that comes
complete with a liquid crystal display sniping scope) you take out
the pilot of the nearest enemy vehicle and climb into it (a really
unpleasant tactic in multi-player games). Then you... (oh you get
the idea).
	   The only thing anyone may complain about this feature is that
while roaming on foot you only have two types of weaponry. However,
I would say it is definitely more realistic this way; I seriously
doubt that carrying more than four different types of heavy
weaponry alone in a near zero gravity would be practical.
	   It is getting hot out here In line with most of its recent
releases, Activision has done a lot in ensuring that BattleZone has
an intense gaming atmosphere. Radio chatter is aplenty and it is
not just to make the game look good but also serves to give you
insights into your mission objectives as well. That, plus the
voice-overs of the unnamed hero (that would be you) in the
single-player missions adds to its well-thought out game design.
The music itself is a little spooky and gloomy; hmmm, which covert
operation on the dark cold extra-terrestrial surfaces would be the
same without it, eh?
	   As with any other game, one of the key components in enhancing
the gaming experience would be the graphics. Graphics-wise,
BattleZone is really something to behold. It definitely has the
best looking Direct3D graphics I've seen in any 3-D accelerated
game in a long time. It's so detailed, the graphics are not any
different from the graphics found in BattleZone's rather impressive
introduction.
	   The terrain is something to behold as it appears before your
very eyes.
	   As you travel around, your craft will bob up and down following
every single detail of the terrain. It gets so real that at times
you may get a little nauseated. Unlike other Activision releases,
the highly customisable Instant Action/Skirmish feature is sorely
missed here.
	   There may be an empty playground for you to fool around with,
but there is hardly anything challenging to do on it. Another thing
I would like to bring up would be the lack of multi-player spawned
games. This means each of the participants of a multi-player game
must have a BattleZone compact disk.
	   Conclusion What are you waiting for now? Yes, I am now out of
breathe, honest. So unless you think your machine will not be able
to do justice to the BattleZone experience, go out and get this
``revolutionary action-strategy''
	   (as mentioned on the box) game from Activision.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:HI-TECH-SPACE-COMBAT sked; CT:w; 
