<SLUG> IT'S-TOO-VIOLENT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
It's too violent a movie for Mother's Day, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
It's too violent a movie for Mother's Day, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   L.K. HungASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE movie Natural Enemy with a ``U'' rating, as indicated in the
TV programme section of NST on May 23, was shown the same evening.
	   After viewing it, I felt that there was an error in its
classification.
	   For by virtue of the film's story and violent contents - there
are four murders plus an attempt on the life of the villain's
natural mother - it should be classified under 18SG (for 18+ with
non-excessive violent/horrifying scenes).
	   Indeed, the film may not even pass for a 18SG rating, but at
least this would be more appropriate, as viewers would be
forewarned about its contents.
	   Worse still, the error was compounded by airing it as a Mother's
Day Special. Generally, a Mother's Day Special movie would have a
theme with an ending that warms the hearts of the viewers.
	   I wonder if that night, after viewing the film, parents and
children could go to bed with peace and happiness in their hearts.
	   The film had a chilling and disturbing effect on me. Surely, TV2
is not so short of good, wholesome films that it had to air Natural
Enemy as a Mother's Day Special.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
