r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  HOW0TO-KEEP-NET-HOAXERSs     06-09 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> HOW0TO-KEEP-NET-HOAXERS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
How to keep Net hoaxers away, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
How to keep Net hoaxers away, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Maria O'DanielASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THERE are a lot of hoaxes around on the Internet. How do you
avoid them?
	   Learn to read with scepticism! Look for these following
tell-tale signs.
	   Please pass along this message to 10/12/65 million people: Any
message which asks you to pass it along to more people is suspect.
The most famous of these is the Little Craig letter. This hoax asks
you to send an electronic mail (e-mail) to a dying child who
purportedly wants to be in the Guinness Book of Records or who is
exceptionally lonely. Don't fall for it! Little Craig was ill - in
1989. However, he is now 18 years old and a recipient of 16 million
cards and was included in the book of world records. Also, Craig
has been cured of cancer but still receiving five bags of mail a
day, which goes directly to the recycling depot.
	   A similar hoax is now being distributed but it tells people to
send business cards instead. A different version of this is the
``Cookie story''
	   where a few people claimed to have been charged a fortune for a
cookie recipe and is now making it publicly available out of
revenge. This here's-how-I-was-ripped-off-and-now-want-revenge
story starts off with ``....a true story of justice in the good old
US of A. Thought y'all might enjoy this; if nothing else, it shows
Internet justice, if it can be called that''.
	   There's a virus in your e-mail: Any e-mail message warning you
not to read e-mail is a hoax. It is not possible to catch a virus
from just reading an e-mail message. However, it is possible to
catch a virus from a document or program attached to an e-mail
message. Macro viruses, the most prevalent type of virus at the
moment, are often passed along over networks via e-mail
attachments. It is also possible to catch a virus if you set your
software package to read attach documents or run attached programs
without checking them first. So to be safe, read all your e-mail
and before opening attachments check them for viruses. If you buy a
new program, check for viruses. And always, always make sure you
back-up all your files. Names of these hoaxes are varied but they
include: Goodtime, PenPal, Deeyenda, PKZ300, Irina, and Ghost.
	   Please change your computer's configuration/send me your e-mail
account password: Some people think it's funny to have people
destroying their own computers. If you receive any message telling
you to change your account or send a file or message over the
network, call or e-mail your Internet provider or check with a
known expert! Forward this mail and it's worth money to someone:
Ignore any message that act as a chain letter. Whether it is Bill
Gates testing a product and offering you thousands of dollars for
sending on his message or a little boy who tells you that for every
message forwarded some charity will receive money.
	   Chain letters are always hoaxes. There is no way of tracking the
forwarded messages as they are sent.
	   And he woke up in a bath full of ice: The urban legends going
around about the sailor/business man going into a foreign
country/bar/brothel and finding his kidney/testicle being stolen
for organ transplant are a myth.
	   These people who designed these urban legends are always careful
to present a nice little moral tale with a horrific end for the
hapless victim. Don't humour these rumour mongers by sending these
messages around. If you receive any stories involving organ theft,
people being sucked up in planes and thrown out over forest fires,
etc, go and check http://www.urbanlegends. com/. Remember, if this
were to happen even once, it would be No. 1 television and radio
news item within hours.
	   Make money fast: Never send money in response to e-mail. E-mail
from so-called charities are faked. No charity asks for funds using
e-mail, so don't be fooled. Pyramid schemes don't work. The people
who send them out know this and are committing a crime which can
land them in jail in most countries. If you receive a pyramid offer
or asked to send money, forward the e-mail with the complete header
to your Internet service provider or contact MYCERT. Look at it
this way; if there are ways to make money quickly why would anyone
offer it to you over the e-mail for nothing? So, stay safe and
remember: Just because it is written doesn't mean it's true.
	   The more urgent a message, the more suspect it is. Don't be
rushed into a response! Never, ever send anyone money! Never, ever
send any personal information such as your telephone number,
address or password.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:HOW0TO-KEEP-NET-HOAXERS sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
