<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Blatter Angered,0333 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nasty FIFA presidential campaign hasn't ended yet
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By BRIAN TRUSDELL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ FIFA's presidential election is over, but things
are still nasty between winner Sepp Blatter and challenger Lennart
Johansson.
	   Blatter issued a press release Tuesday night through FIFA
``categorically'' denying rumors ``of a manipulation of the vote''
that gained him the post.
	   ``Mr. Blatter vehemently refuted the allegations and said he
would investigate the source of such malicious reports,'' the
release said. ``He stressed that he reserved the right to take
legal action against those seeking to defame him.''
	   Rumors apparently were fed by a story in the International
Herald Tribune on Tuesday which quoted Johansson, the president of
UEFA, possibly indicating that Monday's vote wasn't fair.
	   ``Something happened somewhere,'' Johansson was quoted as
saying. ``I had so many promises of votes that I am, to put it
mildly, surprised and disappointed to be beaten so
comprehensively.''
	   Blatter didn't get the necessary two-thirds majority on the
first ballot, but led 111-80, more than enough to win a simple
majority on the second vote. Johansson conceded before a second
vote could be held.
	   A FIFA source, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said one
rumors that reached Blatter Tuesday involved the buying of votes.
	   Many had hoped the election would restore peace to soccer's
governing body after a bitter 2 1-2 month campaign rife with
personal attacks and name-calling.
	   Both candidates exchanged friendly statements following the
election, but Johansson clearly was upset.
	   ``The result is there, consequently he is the winner and we will
have to cooperate for the good of the game,'' Johansson said. ``But
we're not dropping our program. I'm loyal to the president but I'm
not going to obey everything he says.''
	   (bt/jw)
</TEXT>
