</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> THINGS-TO-KNOW-CHAT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Things to know about chat room, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Things to know about chat room, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Ng Ken BoonASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   AFTER reading through my last article I noticed that I did not
thoroughly explain the concept of the chat room as clearly as I
would have liked.
	   Allow me to draw an analogy between a hotel and a chat site.
Imagine a chat site as a hotel if you prefer. Inside the house
there are many rooms.
	   Now imagine that inside every room there are people chatting
about various subjects. As you walk through the hotel, you notice
that there are titles on the door of every room.
	   These titles indicate the char topics in the rooms. Thus, in a
room called ``Computer Talk'', for instance, one would naturally
find that the people in the room are talking about computers.
	   Likewise, in a room called, say, ``Casual Chat'', one would
expect the people in the room to be participating in a well, casual
chat, or to paraphrase the recently-ended (and sorely missed)
television series Seinfeld, a chat about nothing. So, it follows
that in a room called ``Teen Talk'', there would be teenagers
talking about mostly teenage issues.
	   If you enter a room titled ``Flirt'' for instance, you would
find a lot of people appearing to flirt with one another. The
ability to flirt with one (or more) participant in a chat room
appears to be one of the more controversial uses of the Internet
relay chat (IRC) service.
	   There have been many untoward incidents (some of which are
extremely interesting) that have been reported in the media... but
I digress.
	   We will return to the subject of flirting on the IRC in a later
article.
	   To continue, let us return to our earlier analogy (that of a
chat site being very much like a hotel).
	   In order to enter a room, you would first have to select the
room that you would like to chat in.
	   This can be done, of course, by walking down the corridor of the
hotel and looking at the room titles one by one until a particular
room title strikes your fancy.
	   Once it is done, you would then open the door and immediately be
surrounded by the chatters who arrived before you.
	   Now that you can not only hear the chatter, but also participate
in it by taking part in one of the discussions already started,
starting a new discussion, or by making a remark to someone (or
even no one in particular).
	   In our hotel analogy, you can see that it is easy to leave the
room (for instance, if you found nothing of interest or even
decided to visit another room) and travel down the corridor in
search of another one.
	   (Actually, due in part to the multi-tasking capabilities of most
modern operating systems, it is now possible to be in more than one
room at a time - just think of it as having cloned yourself.) All
this talk about rooms and corridors are all very well, but what
does this have to do with IRC? Well, now that the concept of sites
and rooms has been thoroughly explained, let's revisit the analogy.
	   In order to visit a hotel, you would first have to get to where
the hotel is.
	   Similarly, in order to use a chat site, you would first have to
log on to it. The process of logging on differs from one chat
client to another chat client.
	   Usually, however, to get logged on, one would need to have the
IRC server name the port to connect to (usually a number) a
username (sometimes called a ``nickname'' in IRC), and optionally,
a password. For instance, the server name for TalkCity is
chat.talkcity.com, port number 6667.
	   The username is, as stated in the earlier article, the name that
you like to be referred to in a room. This also serves to identify
you, but not all the time, as we shall see below.
	   Some servers enforce what is usually called ``username (or
nickname) registration''.
	   Username (or nickname) registration means that the server allows
a user to ``register'' a name. It then becomes exclusively his (or
hers) to use, and is protected by a password.
	   Another user trying to log on using the same name but without
supplying the password (or supplying an incorrect one) would
usually be informed that the username is already registered.
	   The user would then be instructed to choose another nickname
(one that is not registered).
	   This (username registration) is usually done to prevent
imposters from ``stealing'' an identity.
	   For example, assume user A has the username ``UserA''. After
some time spent in certain chat rooms, user A has become a
``regular'' and is thus known and recognised by many other
``regulars'' from the same chat room.
	   Now assume that user B logs on with the username UserA. With the
username registration in place, user B will simply be told that the
name UserA has already been registered and will be instructed to
select another username.
	   Without the registration procedure, user B will be able to pose
as UserA.
	   This would lead everyone in the chat room to believe that user B
is in fact user A. User B is now free to wreak havoc on user A's
reputation since everything he types will be attributed to user A.
	   User B, logged on as UserA, could start abusing all the regulars
(or even all the participants) and all this would be blamed on user
A. As a result, user A could find himself being ignored (or even
abused in return.) the next time he logs on.
	   This would probably cause no end of confusion as user A tries to
make sense of what he has been so unjustly accused of.
	   Shakespeare once made a mention of this: ``He who steals my
purse steals trash... but he who steals from me my good name steals
that which does not make him any richer, but makes me poor
indeed''.
	   Because of this, one would expect the use of nickname
registration to be more prevalent among chat-facilitating
companies, but sadly, the reverse appears to be true.
	   The main reason for nickname registrations lack of popularity is
widely said to be due to the difficulty of programming and
implementing such a facility. Let us all hope that in due time,
such an important and valuable facility becomes easier to write and
implement, and hopefully more popular.
	   The are other ways (albeit somewhat limited) to ``sniff out''
imposters.
	   We will discuss this, among other things, in the next article.
Until then, happy chatting.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:THINGS-TO-KNOW-CHAT sked; CT:w; 
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
