<BODY>
<SLUG> WHY-FRIENDS-IS-A-HIT sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Why `Friends' is a hit, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Why `Friends' is a hit, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Errol OhASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   FRIENDS: SERIES 1 EPISODES 1-24 (US, 1994/95) Directed by James
Burrows and others Starring Jennifer Aniston, Courteney Cox, Lisa
Kudrow, Matt LeBlanc, Matthew Perry, David Schwimmer Running Time:
Approximately 90 minutes each Rating: 1/2 Distributor: Movie Magic
(03-9836688) IF The X-Files represents the acme of television
drama-suspense, Friends (and probably a few other series) is its
comedy counterpart.
	   The strong characterisation and continuity of this series about
six twentysomethings are big pluses. It sounds trite, but Friends
has a huge following because viewers care about the characters.
	   Of course, Rachel (Aniston), Monica (Cox), Phoebe (Kudrow), Joey
(LeBlanc), Chandler (Perry) and Ross (Schwimmer) form an attractive
group, even if they do little but sit around nursing oversized cups
of coffee and jawing away.
	   They are portrayed with broad quirks, yet they interact and
develop onscreen with naturalness and charm.
	   The scripts are consistently sharp and relevant. The stories are
a mixture of trivial misadventures in everyday life and compelling
season- long sagas.
	   Every episode - each cutely titled The One With/Where... - is a
fine example of ensemble acting. Chances are the show will
eventually fade, but right now, it's great, funny television.
	   The first season of 24 episodes has been packaged into these six
videos.
	   Watch how the show quickly gained momentum after wobbling
briefly at the start.
	   TOMORROW NEVER DIES (UK, 1997) Directed by Roger Spottiswoode
Starring Pierce Brosnan, Jonathan Pryce, Michelle Yeoh, Teri
Hatcher, Joe Don Baker, Judi Dench Running Time: 113 minutes
Rating: 1/2 Distributor: Movie Magic THE James Bond franchise is so
laden with formulae that it's increasingly difficult to appreciate
each successive instalment, even with the frequent retooling and
personnel changes. Very rarely is the template measurably
stretched.
	   Tomorrow Never Dies is more of the same. Sure, you can debate
endlessly about Brosnan's take of 007 as compared with the previous
Bonds, but it all boils down to how differently he orders his
Martini, beds his women and wipes the floor with the baddies.
	   In Tomorrow Never Dies, the villain is a media baron (Pryce) who
wants to - quick, take a wild guess - rule the world. His chosen
method is to manipulate and control global news. The evil deed of
the movie is his attempt to fool the Chinese and British into
sparking off a war.
	   Bond gets a tough Chinese agent (Yeoh) as an ally and has a
bedroom encounter with Hatcher, an ex-lover and Pryce's wife.
	   The stunts and gadgets are typically wonderful, but the
familiarity of Tomorrow Never Dies may gnaw at you.
	   OUT TO SEA (US, 1997) Directed by Martha Coolidge Starring Jack
Lemmon, Walter Matthau, Dyan Cannon, Gloria De Haven, Brent Spiner,
Elaine Stritch Running Time: 102 minutes Rating: Distributor:
Wawasan Videovan (03-7049125) THE Lemmon-Matthau pairing is
becoming a geriatric gimmick. In the past, their odd couple act
worked because the duo were excellent comedians who can carry far
the chalk-and-cheese routine. They're still great actors, but their
recent movies together have shown that their age - both are
septuagenarians - overshadows lots of things.
	   Admittedly, this is difficult to sidestep. Matthau, in
particular, seems to be physically labouring in Out To Sea, a
seaborne Grumpy Old Men.
	   He plays Charlie, a shiftless gambler who belatedly decides that
his ticket to a good life is to marry into money. Lemmon is
Matthau's brother- in-law who refuses to embrace life since being
widowed years ago.
	   Matthau dupes Lemmon into going with him on an all-expense paid
luxury cruise. In truth, the former has signed them up as dance
hosts. After Lemmon discovers the lie and the ensuing squabbling
subsides, romance comes on. Matthau pursues Cannon and her wealth,
while Lemmon and De Haven take turns blowing hot and cold.
	   Lemmon and Matthau deserve a better vehicle than Out To Sea, one
that's less predictable and more genuine in its story and laughs.
	   The fine acting overall is of some consolation. As usual, Lemmon
and Matthau are utterly at ease in their combination. Spiner (Data
of Star Trek: The Next Generation) slips comfortably into the skin
of the ambitious, control freak of a cruise director. Watch and
cringe as he croons - yes, croons - the Santana hit, Oye Como Va.
	   STARSHIP TROOPERS (US, 1997) Directed by Paul Verhoeven Starring
Casper Van Dien, Dina Meyer, Denise Richards, Jake Busey, Neil
Patrick Harris, Patrick Muldoon, Michael Ironside Running Time: 110
minutes Rating: 1/2 Distributor: Berjaya HVN (03-9826688) WHEN it
comes to thrilling moviegoers, you've got to hand it to Dutch
director Paul Verhoeven. He wields his tools - violence, special
effects, sex, hardware, humour - with impressive dexterity and
efficiency. The trouble is, the substance of his more recent
efforts lag hopelessly behind.
	   Based on Robert A. Heinlein's futuristic sci-fi novel, Starship
Troopers is supposed to have some cerebral elements in its story of
Earth engaged in a war against intelligent, destructive alien bugs.
	   Van Dien, Meyer, Richards and Harris are schoolkids who enlist
in the campaign and quickly mature as the toll mounts. All the
components of a war drama are here: love, bravery, loss and
triumph.
	   The ``depth'' comes by way of political overtones such as the
fascist- style indoctrination in school and the media - a citizen,
we are intermittently told, is a notch higher than a civilian.
	   However, these are seldom anything more than background noise.
There's really no pause for thinking when the awesome SFX and
almost cartoonish goriness overpower all else. You'll probably be
swept along by the action and adventure. But it's equally likely
that you'll experience the weird aftertaste of pointlessness.
	   THE VERY BEST OF STING &AMP; THE POLICE (US, 1997) Running Time: 70
minutes Rating: 1/2 Distributor: Berjaya HVN WHETHER you should get
this depends on the kind of fan you are. If you're ravenous about
amassing everything to do with The Police and/or Sting, the video
store has probably kept aside your copy of this tape.
	   For those who admire - but not rabidly so - the defunct
three-man band and/or its high-minded frontman, this may not be of
much importance.
	   The Very Best is a video companion to yet another greatest hits
album.
	   The 17 music videos here are not in chronological order and the
amount of fresh material is negligible. Perhaps, the only
noteworthy thing is that The Very Best gives a glimpse of the
musical and stylistic evolution of an influential rock group.
Sting's post-Police career is patchy, but his music videos are
always visually interesting.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
(PROFILE
(WS SL:WHY-FRIENDS-IS-A-HIT sked; CT:w; 
