<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   IN the last article, we saw several methods of enhancing the
ClipArt picture. One can add frames and background fill effects to
provide a printed look. It is possible to add various textures and
hues to improve this background. Today we will look at fine-tuning
this background, i.e.
	   the hypothetical space between the outline of the picture and
the frame that surrounds it.
	   In order to study the background effects, you must first insert
a ClipArt picture into the document. Then click on the picture so
you can see the handles around it. Invoke Format -) Picture. Click
on the Colours and Lines tab. Study the pulldown menu in the Fill
Colour item by clicking on the arrowhead to the right.
	   Choose: Fill Effects. You will see a dialogue box with four
tabs, namely Gradient, Texture, Pattern and Picture.
	   The Gradient dialogue box allows you to choose from several
combinations of hues. At the top of this dialogue box, you will see
an area labelled Colours with the options One Colour, Two Colours
and Preset. Below this, you will find two areas labelled Shading
Styles and Variants.
	   The options in the Colours menu, the Shading styles menu and the
Variants menu are linked. When you click on the One Colour option,
for example, a pulldown menu labelled Colour 1 appears to the right
of the dialogue box. This allows you to choose a colour of your
choice. A sliding bar appears below this.
	   The sliding bar allows you to change the intensity of the hues
that you see in the variants. The colours in the variants will
change, depending on your choice in the Colours menu.
	   The options in the shading styles area allow you to choose a
particular alignment of hues. Basically, the fill effects comprise
a certain colour (assuming you choose the one colour option) moving
in intensity from dark to bright.
	   If you were to choose the Horizontal option, then the upper
portion of the variants box will have a lighter hue and the lower
portion will take on a darker hue. Alternatively, the upper portion
can be darker and the lower portion lighter.
	   A third variant of this pattern is a dark middle portion
followed by lighter upper and lower edges. The final variant is a
light middle portion with darker upper and lower edges. You can
choose the variant that appeals to you from the Variants area.
	   The light and dark hues become horizontally placed, if you were
to choose the Horizontal option in the Shading Styles menu. If you
were to choose Vertical, the hues will occur in vertical lines.
	   The Diagonal up option causes the hues to occur in diagonal
lines, stretching from the bottom left corner to the top right.
	   Diagonal down has similar patterns of hues, but the alignment of
diagonals is now from the top left corner to the bottom right
corner.
	   The From Corner option gives interesting results. The dark
shades commence from one corner of the ClipArt picture and spread
out into lighter shades as they reach the opposite corner. The four
possible variants indicate the dark hues commencing from each of
the four corners of the picture.
	   The From Centre option has only two variants. In one of the
variants, the dark shades begin from the centre of the picture and
spread out in brightening hues. In the next variant, the light
shades occur at the centre and become darker as they spread out
towards the edges of the picture.
	   If you were to choose the two colours option, the menu to the
right of the box will change to show two pulldown menus labelled
Colour 1 and Colour 2 respectively.
	   You can add exciting colour combinations to the background of
your ClipArt picture via these menus. For example, if you want hues
of red and blue instead of light and dark hues of a single colour,
you can choose blue in the Colour 1 menu and red in the Colour 2
menu.
	   You can choose to have these hues aligned vertically,
horizontally, diagonally or emerging out from a centre by choosing
the appropriate options in the Shading Styles menu.
	   You should experiment with different colours and the From centre
option to get a feel of the attractive effects possible.
	   The third option in Colours is labelled Preset. When you click
on this option, you will get a pulldown menu labelled Preset
colours. This menu allows you a pre-determined combination of
colours. The names of these preset combinations are meant to be
user-friendly, and include titles such as Early Sunset
(representing bright colours of dawn), Nightfall (darker hues
associated with dusk) and so on.
	   I find Fire interesting. You might want to try out Brass if you
want a sombre, metallic background.
	   These preset backgrounds can be used in conjunction with the
various shading styles.
	   You must be careful when choosing a background, make sure that
it goes well with the ClipArt picture that you have chosen for the
foreground.
	   For example, if you have a picture that has darker colours at
the top and lighter colours below (for example, a boy with dark
hair wearing white shoes), you will want to choose a shading style
that gives light background colours at the upper half of the
picture and dark background colours at the bottom half of the
picture. The fill effects feature allows you to add a professional
touch to your ClipArt-based work.
	   However, the large number of choices that are possible sometimes
make it difficult to choose a particular background. It helps to
remember: generally a light background works well with a dark
foreground picture, and the converse is also generally true. In
addition, you must always check the final printed copy, especially
if you are using a colour printer. The colours on the printed copy
may look somewhat different from the copy on the screen.
	   The writer is academic head of the American Degree Programme at
Metropolitan College. He can be contacted at ananda &LR; metropolitan.
edu.my.
	   
</TEXT>
