w1986 &Cx1f; wstm-
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  IF-SOMEONE-HAS-DESIGNSsk     06-09 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> IF-SOMEONE-HAS-DESIGNS sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
If someone has designs on you, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
If someone has designs on you, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Susanna CheckettsASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   NOW, take a good look at yourself. Are you a designing person -
a fashion designer, for example, or an architect, an engineer or a
draftsperson?
	   Perhaps the boot is on the other foot, however. In other words,
has some designing person got designs on you? If the anwer is yes,
then you must be looking good. It may be, of course, that you are
actually wearing a designer label, though I do hope that you are
wearing the clothes as well.
	   A designer label, if you stop to think about it, would not
exactly cover very much.
	   I would recommend several banana leaves to keep you decent
rather than the traditional but skimpy fig-leaf.
	   Needless to say, if somebody has designs on you in the idiomatic
or traditional sense, they are assuredly not decorating you with
such things as watered silk, polka dots, sprigging, or even batik.
	   (Watered silk, in case you are wondering, is neither damp nor
diluted, but a silk patterned with discreet shiny patterns, while
sprigging usually consists of regular patterns of tiny flowers or
buds.) No, they are more likely to be eyeing you with a view to
making a profit, or to putting their mark on you. To put it another
way, having designs on somebody often means planning to get money
or goods out of the victim, or else it can mean planning to do harm
in some way.
	   For example, while on holiday in the UK, I was recently sitting
in my mother's garden when the robin came along. This is the
red-breasted bird that you often see on British Christmas cards,
rather than Robin Hood, though this particular bird qualifies to be
called the Prince of Thieves.
	   The nearest Malaysian equivalent would be the perky
black-and-white Magpie Robin, while the most likely bird to grab
your roti canai would probably be the audacious Lesser Mynah.
	   Anyway, this robin had designs, not on me, but on my French
stick, and it actually took a beakful of bread before I could even
say `Hop it!' So do be careful with your French stick, especially
in your compound.
	   Some marauding cat, bird, or sneak thief may have designs on it,
and then you will be left without your daily bread.
	   In a slightly more positive, if jokey, sense, ``having designs
on someone'' can mean that some interested party, male or female,
is hoping to get together with you.
	   This could mean that they wish to put their mark on you in the
time- honoured way and that wedding bells are in their eyes (though
I always feel that they really ought to go to the optician if this
is the case).
	   On the other hand, it could mean that they are marking up
another conquest, rather as sportsmen mark up a score on on the
scoreboard - in which case they ought to be playing cricket, and
possibly you ought to be making a run for it.
	   As I said before, the design may be literal, and it may take the
form of a designer label - but here I have to say that I am not at
all keen on being labelled, myself.
	   Nor does it seem too discreet or elegant to have labels
plastered over my front, back and sides, or any other visible part
of my anatomy.
	   As my friend Kathy remarked, far too many people these days are
``designered'' - a nice invention which somehow reminds me of verbs
such as blinkered and scuppered.
	   The superficial similarity is obviously the ``er'' at the end of
the verb, though these two verbs have the same ending for rather
different reasons.
	   As you might guess, ``blinker'' is a combination of the verb
``blink'' with one common ending for English nouns, the suffix
``er'', which often suggests action or a particular use for
something.
	   Horses traditionally wear blinkers (British English) or blinders
(American English) to prevent them from seeing scary things out of
the corners of their eyes.
	   So, if a human being is blinkered, he or she can't or won't see
something that is obvious, or perhaps is narrow-minded and can't
accept new ideas.
	   (Since American horses need to be blinded where British ones
appear only to close their eyes momentarily, you may well feel that
US equines are more sensitive than those in the UK - but that may
be just a mare's tale.) When it comes to being scuppered, the
Titanic is the all-time great example. Scupper comes from the Old
French verb escopir meaning to spit, though this seems slightly
inadequate for the torrent of water that rushes in when a hole is
made in a ship.
	   In this case, the ``er'' ending indicates that it has come
through French from a Latin original.
	   A scupper was not accidental in the beginning; it was a
deliberate hole, allowing water to drain off a ship's deck.
Metaphorically, if your plans are scuppered, you can imagine what
happens - they sink without trace, and you have to start all over
again.
	   Of course, the other similarity which connects ``designered'',
``blinkered''
	   and ``scuppered'' is that they all have negative connotations.
	   This is not to say that designer garments are bad in themselves.
On the contrary, they can be most attractive things but what
worries me a bit is that they are all too often seen as status
symbols, and they say very little about the real personality behind
the fancy clothes. The label sometimes seems to count for more than
the actual design.
	   Just a look at the word ``label'' itself, while we are at it, as
this is another word with a common ending or suffix.
	   ``El'' is a diminutive from Latin, so that a label is actually
lab + el - a little fold, or a little ribbon.
	   The related Old Norse word leppr seems to have meant a ``rag'',
so we are back to the idea of fashion, design, and glad rags -
otherwise known as your best clothes, or your party outfit.
	   (This is not to be confused with your birthday suit, since this
is even more of an exposure than wearing just a designer label or a
fig-leaf - it consists of the skin you were born with.) Rags, as
you may be aware, are not really the sort of thing you want to be
seen wearing, while ``a rag'' describes a cheap and sensational
tabloid newspaper - the connections are mostly negative.
	   By the same token, if you are ``labelled'' in English, the
chances are that it's a negative description of some kind.
	   For example, these days you could be labelled a ``wimp'' if you
seem to be feeble, over-sentimental, or physically unenterprising.
	   The kinds of label I should prefer are the more positive
professional and personal ones. I can label myself a ``lecturer'',
``writer'' and ``poet''
	   quite accurately, but I can only hope for pleasant labels from
other people, and I should here like to thank the many readers who
have sent me e-mails on my ``interesting'', ``useful'' and
``enjoyable'' Tongue Tip column.
	   Your appreciation, as well as your positive criticism and
comment on specific points, is something which helps me to design
these articles, and it also helps me to maintain a sense of humour
- something which we all need in trying times, or our tempers may
be in rags by the end of the day.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
