r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Soccer-US     06-09 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-US,0636 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
World Cup: Eight years later, Wynalda tries to shake bad boy rap
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With AP Photo XSF104 &QL; 
 &UR; By RONALD BLUM &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAINT-JEAN D'ARDIERES, France (AP) _ Eight years later, Eric
Wynalda is still trying to shed the bad boy rap.
	   One day after his 21st birthday, he was on top of the soccer
world, in the starting lineup as the United States played its first
World Cup game in 40 years.
	   Then, eight minutes into the second half, he became Eric the
Red, ejected for pushing a Czechoslovak player right in front of
the referee.
	   Ever since then, it's been a scarlet card on his back, an image
stuck to him like the defenders who follow his every move on the
field.
	   ``When I first came on to the national team, it was difficult
because I knew I was a volatile player. But I think I have changed
a great deal,'' he said Tuesday as he reached the somewhat wiser
old age of 29.
	   Time has changed him. And perhaps success, too.
	   It's his third World Cup. Now he's a leader and he knows it, the
top scorer in United States history.
	   He can relax a little _ oh, and perhaps please his coach by
working hard on defense, too.
	   Still, he's the one player Steve Sampson says provides
``brilliant moments.''
	   ``Eric has the ability to be very deceptive on the dribble, to
create that little space for him to pass or shoot. That first step,
when he's in form, is very hard to defend,'' Sampson said.
	   His status for the American opener against Germany on Monday has
been in doubt since April 16, when he had arthroscopic surgery on
his left knee. He's played just 74 minutes in games since then,
trying to work back to 100 percent.
	   On Tuesday, he played 45 minutes in a scrimmage against the
French club FC Gueugnon, a 4-0 U.S. victory. He didn't score, but
pronounced himself ready.
	   ``I believe that I'm healthy enough, I'm definitely healthy
enough,'' he said.
	   He has 32 goals in 100 international games, a Ruthian figure for
U.S. soccer, where the No. 2 scorer has just 21.
	   And, perhaps more importantly, he has some experience against
the Germans, the European champions. In the fall of 1992, he went
to Germany and scored nine goals in his first 10 games with FC
Saarbruecken of the Bundesliga. He spent three seasons in Germany,
scoring 21 goals in 57 games for Saarbruecken, and then scored two
goals in 23 games for VfL Bochum in 1994-95, when he was slowed by
a broken leg just before the midseason break.
	   ``I've had some bad injuries, some little injuries,'' he said.
``I never had the opportunity to heal up. The last few weeks have
been brilliant for me, not having the pressure from the club to
play when I'm not 100 percent.''
	   He came back to America for the start of Major League Soccer,
scoring 10 goals for San Jose in 1996, five last year and three
before the knee injury this season. Still, with a good World Cup,
he hopes to end up back in Europe, but not Germany.
	   ``When I said I'd never play in Germany again, that wasn't
saying that Germany was a bad place to play. I had some good times
and bad times in Germany,'' he said. ``My thinking is I'd like
another experience. I'd like to play in England or Spain.''
	   His agent keeps trying to tell him about opportunities in
Europe, but Wynalda doesn't want to hear it until after the
tournament. He may not start _ Sampson may go with Roy Wegerle or
Brian McBride because of the injury _ but Sampson says Wynalda will
see significant time.
	   ``This World Cup will really be the opportunity to make my
mark,'' Wynalda said. ``This World Cup is the most important of the
three, not just for myself, but for the team. This is our chance to
do something special.''
	   (rb/jw)	   
</TEXT>
