<HEADLINE>
Go into aquaculture, MB advises fishermen, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Go into aquaculture, MB advises fishermen, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Mimi Syed YusofASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   TAPAH, Mon. - Fishermen have been urged to venture into
aquaculture to supplement their income and help boost the State's
fish production for the domestic and foreign markets.
	   Menteri Besar Tan Sri Ramli Ngah Talib said fishermen should not
only depend on fishing from the sea, rivers or lakes, but should
also look into other ways to earn a living.
	   He said fishermen could go into large or small-scale commercial
aquaculture ventures.
	   Speaking to reporters after visiting a fish breeding project in
Chenderiang today, Ramli said through aquaculture, fishermen could
be assured of a continuous supply of fish.
	   He said fishermen were now dependent on the weather. While on
good days, they may have a bumper haul, they may return home
empty-handed on rainy days, he added.
	   The fish breeding project at a four-hectare site in Chenderiang
is being carried out by Bright Aquatic Sdn Bhd, a joint venture
between Johanif Abdul Rahman, 38, and Mohd Khairizam Abdul Majid,
41.
	   It produces freshwater fish fry including varieties like
catfish, tilapia merah and lampam jawa.
	   Accompanying the Menteri Besar was State Agriculture Committee
chairman Datuk Ramly Zahari and State Fisheries director Mhd Shah
Abdul Hamid.
	   Ramli said the State Government, through the Fisheries
Department, was willing to assist those interested in aquaculture.
	   ``The department will also provide expert advice on the matter
to help increase fish production.
	   ``Aquaculture activity is not difficult as many government
agencies have come up with scientific methods to increase fish
production and ensure the quality of produce.''
	   Currently, Perak produces 5,000 tonnes of fresh-water fish and
3,500 tonnes of brackish-water fish every year through aquaculture
activities.
	   
</TEXT>
