</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria, 1st Ld-Writethru,0929 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nigeria's Abubakar takes office that many hope he'll quit
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with Abubakar appearing on state-run
television, says he will honor transition to civil rule, an appeal
to the international community; EDITS to conform and tighten. &QL; 
 &UR; With Nigeria-Africa-Reax, Nigeria-Economy
 &UR; AP Photos NY190, LON102, 104, PAR107 &QL; 
 &UR; By TIM SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Clad in a khaki army uniform and a beret,
Nigeria's new military ruler went on state-controlled television
Tuesday to pledge his support for a transition process that aims to
end army rule in favor of democracy.
	   ``We remain fully committed to the social-political transition
program of Gen. Sani Abacha's administration,'' Gen. Abdulsalam
Abubakar said, reading from a prepared statement. ``We will do
everything to ensure its full and successful implementation.''
	   Abacha, a ruthless dictator by any standards, died Monday of a
heart attack. He had long promised hand power over to the army but
never fulfilled his vow.
	   Hours after emerging as Abacha's sucessor, Abubakar was almost
immediately met with a barrage of calls from at home and abroad for
democracy to replace military autocracy.
	   Nigerians, weary after years of army rule, have long called for
democratic reform.
	   ``The people were sick of military dictatorship,'' exiled
Nigerian playwright and Nobel laureate Wole Soyinka said in
Jerusalem. ``So it's up to the military to recognize this.''
	   Abacha seized power in a 1993 coup and went on to become one of
Nigeria's harshest dictators. About 7,000 government critics and
dissidents have been locked up during his rule.
	   He was unmoved by international appeals, the threat of sanctions
and condemnation for his internal security policies, which human
rights groups say included torture and killings.
	   His successor is a 55-year-old career soldier who trained in the
United States early in his career and in 1981 served with Nigerian
troops assigned to a U.N. peacekeeping force in Lebanon. Abacha
appointed him chief of defense staff in 1993.
	   One after another, members of the international community
acknowledged Abacha's death, but more poignantly called it an
opportunity for democracy for Nigeria.
	   In the United States, White House spokesman Mike McCurry said
President Bill Clinton's administration was interested in Abubakar
surrendering power to democratic rule.
	   ``Our hope, among others, would be, at this moment of
transition, that an accountable civilian government ... will emerge
from what has been a very horrific episode,'' McCurry said.
	   Overshadowing condolences for Abacha, similar calls for
democracy in Nigeria came from France, Britain and members of the
British Commonwealth of nations.
	   In his televised statement, however, Abubakar appeared to hold
out an olive branch to a scornful international community. He also
called Nigeria's diaspora of self-exiled expatriates to return home
to rebuild help their country.
	   ``My servant appeal also goes to the international community for
their understanding and cooperation,'' he said. ``Nigeria demands a
fair hearing and constructive engagement and not isolation.''
	   Abubakar, meanwhile, faced the daunting task of rebuilding a
country eroded by years of corruption and economic mismanagement.
	   Up to 80 percent of the population lives in poverty, government
figures indicate.
	   From the sprawling commercial hub of Lagos to countless
countryside shanties, most Nigerians live without clean water,
reliable electricity or even basic health care.
	   The world's sixth-largest oil exporter, Nigeria can't even fill
its own gas tanks. Corruption and bureaucracy have put the
country's refineries out of business.
	   ``Do you see people crying in the streets?'' said government
clerk Musiniu Bakare after Abacha's death. ``People are rejoicing
now that he is gone, this man who ruined the economy.''
	   At home, leaders of various groups in Nigeria's pro-democracy
movement _ the political opposition, civil rights activists,
journalists and clergy _ were meeting Tuesday in hope of forging a
unified coalition to give strength to their demands for democracy.
	   Few were willing to speak on the record about their discussions,
saying they first wanted to hear from Abubakar, a career soldier
and close ally of Abacha.
	   But Edetaen Ojo, who runs the watchdog group Media Rights
Agenda, said he had few hopes for the new government.
	   ``I really don't think we're going to have much of a change,''
he said. ``He must have maneuvered himself in some way to get into
that position, so he must also want a taste of power.''
	   But like the world leaders who called for the transition to go
forward, Ojo said the sudden change was an opportunity that should
not be wasted.
	   ``This is a crucial moment,'' he said.
	   He also called for the release of jailed politician Moshood
Abiola, the presumed winner of 1993's annulled presidential
elections.
	   But opposition leaders and diplomats say they doubt the
transition can proceed as scheduled: with Aug. 1 presidential
elections and an Oct. 1 handover to civilian rule.
	   Most obviously, there aren't even any presidential candidates
left. Abacha, who never committed to running, was the only legal
candidate _ nominated by all five state-approved parties.
	   Amid many unknowns in post-Abacha Nigeria, one thing is clear:
Opponents are glad Abacha is gone.
	   ``Thank God that he's gone,'' said radical Lagos lawyer Gani
Fawehinmi. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Nigeria, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
