<BODY>
<SLUG> MINISTRY-OF-HEALTH sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ministry of Health should look into issues pertaining to doctors' welfare, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Ministry of Health should look into issues pertaining to doctors' welfare, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 09, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   D.A.WASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   THE way the Health Ministry handles transfers and postings of
medical officers is really a disappointing affair to doctors. A
recent incident involving the posting of my spouse who is a
Master's student further illustrates the point.
	   My spouse and I applied to a local university for the Master's
programme in medicine late last year. We were required to fill up
various forms and we clearly stated our marital status. Both of us
were accepted into the programme.
	   However, to our dismay, we later found out that both of us were
posted to different hospitals which were several hundred kilometres
apart. Calls to the ministry proved futile and instead we were told
to send in an appeal.
	   When we inquired why this had happened despite informing them of
our marital status, we were told that the data was not furnished by
the particular university.
	   What did we fill up the form for then? We haven't heard from the
ministry with regard to our appeal but my spouse is already
considering quitting the programme and even the public sector.
	   Ironically, a similar incident happened to a relative of ours
who got married recently. Both husband and wife are working and are
separated by land, river and sea. An appeal for a transfer was
submitted to the ministry early this year but it was rejected
without any reason.
	   Imagine the newly-weds meeting over the weekend and that too if
the spouse is not on call duty.
	   Many doctors who are married and currently serving the ministry
are subjected to this trauma every year. Despite complaints and
written appeals to the ministry, no changes have been seen or noted
in the system.
	   We are told to be a caring society, but how can we instil such
an attitude when the ministry has little regard for the welfare of
its doctors? Due to this factor, many doctors leave the public
sector and we are seriously considering this in view of the many
foul-ups by the ministry.
	   I seriously urge the Minister to look into this and many other
issues pertaining to the welfare of doctors before it is too late.
	   
</TEXT>
Copyright 1998 NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES all rights
reserved as distributed by WorldSources, Inc. 	   
