<HEADLINE>
HP mulls business potential in MSC, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
HP mulls business potential in MSC, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
   Noor AmalASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   HEWLETT-PACKARD Co is exploring potential business opportunities
in the Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC), and identifying the areas
that could thrive within the environment.
	   HP's corporate vice president and Asia-Pacific operations
president and managing director Dick Warmington said the company is
also looking at whether its involvement in the MSC will be
meaningful in supporting its operations within Asia-Pacific.
	   According to him, HP has already established a presence in the
corridor through Prolin, an MSC-registered company which it has
acquired.
	   ``We are also looking at expanding some of our software
activities in that framework,'' he said at the HP Builds the
Electronic World Asia- Pacific Press Symposium which was held in
Sydney last week.
	   Warmington reiterated that HP is committed to the region, and
looks upon the current period of economic turbulence as an
opportunity to use information technology (IT) to propel nations
and corporations forward.
	   The company is also taking the opportunity to strengthen its
presence in the region for the long haul. ``We feel we have a very
real opportunity to gain greater leverage from investments around
the region,'' he said.
	   Late last year, HP announced an additional RM1 billion
investment in Malaysia to expand the company's present operations
in Penang and develop a new centre of excellence in the
manufacturing and testing of microwave components.
	   HP's plant is the largest single foreign investment in Penang
since the beginning of the State's industrialisation initiative in
1972. Its investment will be spread over a period of five years.
	   ``Actually, we are bringing some of the crown jewel technology
of our microwave instrumentation into Penang and the capability to
build the semiconductor components for our telecommunications
instruments,'' said Warmington.
	   HP's other investments in the region include Indonesia, Korea,
the Philippines, and Singapore.
	   In Indonesia, the company opened a business centre in Jakarta
late last year to provide IT consultation and customised-computing
solutions to small and medium-sized enterprises.
	   In Korea, the company recently announced an investment of up to
US$250 million (RM950 million), of which around US$100 million of
this would be infusion of working capital for the management of HP
operations in Korea.
	   ``About US$70 million has already been forwarded to Korea. Part
of the investment is to set up an HP financial operation to provide
Korean customers and partners with flexible financing and IT
equipment management services,'' said Warmington.
	   HP announced recently that it had purchased from Samsung
Electronics the 45 per cent shareholding in HP Korea.
	   In Singapore, the company has just established the first
regional part centre to speed up the supply of parts for repairing
and servicing HP's equipment in the region.
	   In January, HP announced in the Philippines the parts
distribution centre in Manila, along with 46 service centres
throughout the country to support its customers and partners.
	   HP also recently set up a centre of expertise to develop HP's
test and measurement electronics manufacturing solutions in Taiwan.
	   ``And the list goes on and will continue. While we are
experiencing a business slowdown in this region, we believe the
fundamentals remain in place to support Asia's long-term economic
growth,'' said Warmington.
	   He added that reforms currently underway in many of the affected
countries, though painful in the short term, will provide the free
market forces that should support high growth in the future.
	   
</TEXT>
