<SLUG> PALM-OIL sked </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Palm oil, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
</HEADLINE>
Palm oil, NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES &QL; 
   June 08, 1998
   NEW STRAITS TIMES-MANAGEMENT TIMES
   MALAYSIA
   ENGLISH
ASIA WorldSources, Inc. 201 PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE, S.E., 2nd Floor

<TEXT>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20003 Tel: 202-547-4512 Fax: 202-546-4194
COPYRIGHT 1998 BY WORLDSOURCES, INC., A JOINT VENTURE OF FDCH, INC.
AND WORLD TIMES, INC. NO PORTION OF THE MATERIALS CONTAINED HEREIN
MAY BE USED IN ANY MEDIA WITHOUT ATTRIBUTION TO WORLDSOURCES, INC.
	   CRUDE palm oil (CPO) futures on the Kuala Lumpur Commodity
Exchange are likely to trade higher this week with sentiments to be
inspired by the currency factor.
	   The ringgit which weakened further last Friday (quoted at 3.97
to the US dollar against 3.86 the previous week), prompted
technical buying in the market.
	   Local trading house JF Apex Futures Sdn Bhd forsees the upside
potential in the near term with the three-month August contract
expected to test the RM2,419 level.
	   The week just ended featured a bullish report on Tuesday,
stating that India will retain its import duty of 25 per cent for
edible oil, while on Thursday, the US agricultural attache
estimated that Malaysia's palm oil stocks for end-June would ease
to 525,000 tonnes from 790,000 tonnes in the same month last year.
	   Talks that the State Trading Corporation of India will issue a
new tender soon, spurred interest for the local palm oil on
Thursday.
	   Palm oil exports were estimated to increase to 565,000 tonnes
against PORLA's exports for April at 530,385 tonnes.
	   
