<DOCNO> APW19980609.1553 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 06/09/1998 17:12:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2028 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Eritrea-Ethiopia 5thLd-Writethru   06-09 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Eritrea-Ethiopia, 5th Ld-Writethru ,0777 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede ASMARA, Eritrea
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eritrea, Ethiopia clash again at border; foreigners flee &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with color, quotes, foreigners leaving;
CHANGES byline, dateline. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos ASM103-105 &QL; 
 &UR; By JEAN-MARC BOUJU &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ZALA AMBESSA, Ethiopia (AP) _ Eritrean and Ethiopian troops
pummeled each other with shell and rocket fire along their disputed
border Tuesday, while diplomats and hundreds of frightened
foreigners flew out of the Eritrean capital.
	   The Eritrean army advanced along a jagged front line up a steep
mountain south of Zala Ambessa, pushing from 8 kilometers (5 miles)
to 15 kilometers (9 miles) into Ethiopian territory.
	   Each side accused the other of starting the fighting at dawn,
before morning mists cleared from the valley.
	   ``Everytime they attack us, we'll strike back and push them back
even farther,'' said Eritrean commander Capt. Afwerki, who uses
only one name.
	   Ethiopian government spokeswoman, Selome Taddesse said the
Eritreans had attacked Ethiopian positions south of Zala Ambessa
for the fourth time Tuesday afternoon. She added that the
Ethiopians had repulsed them, taking several prisoners and
inflicting heavy casualties. No further details were available.
	   Eritrean forces last week seized the border town, whose 15,000
civilians swiftly cleared out as the deafening roar of battle
began. Dozens of Eritrean troops were wounded and some were
evacuated in slings improvised from bloodied bedsheets and tree
branches.
	   In the Eritrean capital of Asmara, 105 kilometers (65 miles) to
the northwest, German and Russian diplomats boarded evacuation
flights after closing their embassies.
	   The Israeli and Danish governments last week closed their
diplomatic missions, fearing more bombardments by Ethiopian
warplanes, which hit Asmara's military-civilian airport on Friday
and Saturday. Ten remained open.
	   ``We are leaving with mixed feelings,'' German Ambassador
Wolfgang Ringe said after lowering the flag at his embassy.
	   A U.S.-chartered plane left for Cairo, Egypt, with 50 diplomats
and dependents, 120 naturalized Americans born in Eritrea, and 80
others including Russians, Swedes, Norwegians and Djiboutians.
	   ``This is the one chance I've got to get out. If I don't take
it, I'm afraid I'll be trapped here,'' said Gabriel Ephrem, an
Eritrean whose home is in San Diego.
	   Also aboard were a handful of Ethiopian diplomats, ordered out
by Eritrea in retaliation for the expulsion of its diplomats from
Addis Ababa last week. Two diplomats remained in each capital.
	   Commercial flights and most ships have stopped coming to Eritrea
because Ethiopia has said it cannot guarantee their safety. Eritrea
on Tuesday demanded that the international community force Ethiopia
to lift its threat.
	   ``World leaders should tell them, `You can fight on the front,
but you can't hold the capital hostage,''' said Yemane Gebremeskel,
presidential spokesman.
	   The government welcomed a plan debated by iplomats at an
Organization of African Unity summit to send a six-president
delegation the two Horn of Africa countries, he said.
	   In a message sent to the meeting in Burkina Faso, Eritrean
President Isaias Afwerki said, ``The real stumbling block to peace
is Ethiopia's logic of force and spiral of measures that have begun
by blowing the problem out of proportion and have ended up
escalating the conflict to the brink of full-scale war.''
	   Isaias renewed his calls for an end to all hostilities, full
demilitarization of the border, and direct talks between Eritrea
and Ethiopia in the presence of high-level mediators.
	   In a terse statement, Ethiopia refused direct negotiations.
	   ``We have made it clear since the beginning, unless they
withdraw from areas they have occupied, we cannot sit down for any
talks, direct or indirect,'' Taddesse, the Ethiopian government
spokeswoman, said.
	   The northeast African nations are engaged in a battle over their
border. Ethiopia is resisting attempts by its smaller, northern
neighbor to control territory it says is wrongly held by Eritrea.
	   Eritrea claims its forces are within internationally recognized
borders drawn by Italy in the late 19th century. Eritrea, an
Italian colony from 1885 to 1941, was annexed in 1962 by Ethiopia,
against whom it later fought a 30-year war for independence.
	   The United States and Rwanda have crafted a peace proposal that
would require Eritrea withdraw to positions it occupied prior to
May 6, when border skirmishes broke out. Ethiopia has accepted the
plan, but Eritrea says it is sketchy.
</TEXT>
