r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Nigeria-Economy     06-09 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Economy,0379 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New Nigerian leader inherits shattered economy
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ Nigeria's new military leader, Gen.
Abdulsalam Abubakar, inherits a shattered economy, ravaged by years
of endemic corruption.
	   But with Abubakar promising to honor plans to hand over power to
a civilian government later this year, analysts say the country may
be making its first tentative steps toward recovery.
	   ``The key question is who takes over and how that shifts the
balance of power between those who want to hang on to power, and
those who want to return to the barracks,'' said Jean Francois
Mercier, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney.
	   Moving toward an elected, democratic government could help build
investor confidence and creditor confidence here, he said.
	   Abubakar's predecessor, Gen. Sani Abacha, who died Monday of a
heart attack, is widely blamed for allowing the country's
potentially powerful economy slip into disarray during his five
years in power.
	   Under Abacha's rule, Nigeria became an international pariah, and
his government was accused of widespread human rights abuses and
rampant corruption.
	   Although Nigeria is one of the world's largest exporters of
crude oil, which earns this West African country more than dlrs
4.45 billion in annual revenues, up to 80 of the population live in
poverty, government statistics indicate. Nigeria's bounty was
largely believed squandered, pilfered or spent propping up the
country's ruling army.
	   So anemic is the economy that even in the heart of the vast oil
fields in the Niger Delta, the government either is unable or
unwilling to offer to help to poverty-stricken communities.
	   Laden with debt and marked as a risky credit prospect, Nigeria
is struggling just to keep afloat amid this latest political
turmoil.
	   Bringing itself more into line with the International Monetary
Fund and World Bank reform recommendations is crucial for Nigeria
if the West African country is to negotiate relief from its
crippling dlrs 35 billion external debt.
	   Although negotiations for additional IMF and World Bank loans
continue with Nigeria, both lending bodies insist that the country
must take measures to bring spending under control, while
increasing government revenues. 	   
</TEXT>
