<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OAU-Mandela-Abacha </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mandela bids farewell to Abacha, pan-African summit
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   OUAGADOUGOU, Burkina Faso (AP) _ President Nelson Mandela bade
farewell to his last pan-African summit Tuesday after paying
tribute to his former political enemy, Nigerian dictator Gen. Sani
Abacha, who died Monday of a heart attack.
	   Mandela, 79, was whisked in a black limousine from the three-day
Organization of African Unity on Tuesday afternoon in Burkina
Faso's capital shortly after telling reporters in brief impromptu
remarks that Abacha's death was a great loss for Nigeria and
Africa.
	   The South African leader later flew out of the capital,
officials said, ending Mandela's farewell appearance at the OAU
summit before retiring from politics next year.
	   Mandela was echoing a statement made by South Africa's foreign
ministry praising Abacha for his country's role in ousting junta
troops in Sierra Leone. Nigeria led a multi-national force that
restored the country's elected government in February.
	   The conciliatory remarks came despite persistent tensions
between Nigeria and South Africa under the rule of Abacha and
Mandela.
	   Relations chilled between the two countries after Mandela called
for Commonwealth sanctions against Nigeria in retaliation for the
military execution of environmental activist Ken Saro-Wiwa and
eight fellow activists in 1995.
	   Last week, Abacha accused South Africa, Ghana and the U.S. of
working together to destabilize Nigeria.
	   In his parting speech to the OAU on Monday, Mandela urged
African leaders to work together for peace and development instead
of acting like ``superstars.''
	   He was warmly embraced and praised by other African leaders,
several of whom supported him while the 79-year-old walked , during
an informal photo session later in the day.
	   (gam) 	   
</TEXT>
