<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-President,0467 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mexican president wants open primary for ruling party
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CLAUDE E. ERBSEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Mexico's president said Tuesday that he favors
an open primary to elect the ruling party's next presidential
candidate, after decades of the president choosing the candidate to
succeed him.
	   In a meeting with a small group of news media executives in New
York, President Ernesto Zedillo said he would prefer a ``wide
open'' primary for the candidate of the Institutional Revolutionary
Party, or PRI.
	   The PRI ``has understood the need to be more competitive,''
Zedillo said.
	   It was unclear whether he was advocating a primary limited to
PRI members or open to all registered voters.
	   Since the party was founded in 1929, all Mexican presidents have
been from the PRI. Party officials have honored the outgoing
president's choice of a candidate to succeed him _ effectively
letting him name the next president.
	   But in recent elections opposition parties have presented real
challenges to the PRI because a series of reforms have made
elections more fair.
	   Zedillo was elected with just over 50 percent of the vote in
1994. In past decades, the PRI often improbably claimed 90 percent
of the vote.
	   Zedillo predicted that some form of primary would select the
candidate for the 2000 elections and said he personally preferred
an open primary to a smaller one in which PRI activists would
select a candidate.
	   Asked if he thought he might have to follow the tradition of
selecting the candidate himself _ a practice known as the
``dedazo'' or ``big finger'' _ he said: ``fortunately not.''
	   The party expects to hold a national convention this year to
decide on the mechanism for choosing a candidate.
	   Asked about a U.S. money-laundering investigation that has hurt
relations between the United States and Mexico, Zedillo said he was
not bothered by the failure of U.S. authorities to inform their
Mexican counterparts.
	   ``We also keep secret some of our anti-drug efforts,'' he said.
	   But he said Mexico's attorney general's office must determine
whether U.S. agents violated any laws in its investigation that led
to the arrest of dozens of Mexican banking officials.
	   He added that he and President Bill Clinton agreed during a
meeting Monday ``on the principle that no Mexican law should be
violated when applying U.S. laws.''
	   Zedillo said growing street crime in Mexico is not a by-product
of drug wars, not attributable to the economic situation. He said
that blaming street crime on the economy would be to accuse the
poor of a propensity to crime.
	   He said the ``inefficiency of our institutions'' was more to
blame for the growth of crime and the government's failure to
control it.
</TEXT>
