r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Mexico-Chiapas     06-09 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Chiapas,0665 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mediator's resignation raises questions for Mexico conflict
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By TRINA KLEIST &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico (AP) _ Nearly two years after
peace talks between the government and Indian rebels broke down, a
key mediator's resignation is signaling that the government wants
to resolve the conflict on its own terms.
	   Roman Catholic Bishop Samuel Ruiz, claiming growing government
``aggression'' against his church, on Sunday ended his efforts to
mediate an end to the uprising by the Zapatista National Liberation
Army. The mediation commission he led also disbanded.
	   The controversial bishop had led efforts to end the conflict
since it erupted on Jan. 1, 1994. The first talks in early 1994
were held here in his cathedral.
	   Nominated for the Nobel Peace Prize by supporters, his critics
accused him of causing the rebellion by preaching social activism
to the region's impoverished Indian communities. Some Zapatista
rebels are former church layworkers.
	   On Tuesday, masked men _ presumably Zapatistas or their
supporters _ ambushed six government supporters in the village of
Los Platanos, 50 kilometers (30 miles) north of San Cristobal. One
man was killed and five were injured _ four of them seriously.
	   While there is no evidence Ruiz has advocated violence,
President Ernesto Zedillo last week issued a veiled warning, saying
that ``those who promote the theology of violence... should correct
their errors.'' Officials have repeatedly denounced Ruiz and his
diocese.
	   Supporters said Ruiz's sympathy with rebel goals helped convince
the suspicious Zapatistas to talk with the government.
	   ``What has happened is nothing positive,'' historian Lorenzo
Meyer of the Colegio de Mexico in Mexico City said of Ruiz's
resignation. ``It polarizes the situation in Chiapas even more.
Now, the Zapatistas and the government are virtually alone.''
	   Zedillo seems to want it that way.
	   Government officials for months have questioned the need for
mediators, saying they want direct contact with the Zapatistas. As
part of its strategy, the government also is turning up the
pressure on the Zapatistas and their supporters.
	   At least 40,000 federal troops patrol the region. The government
has been accused of links to vigilante groups that have clashed
with Zapatista supporters, including a band that massacred 45 rebel
sympathizers in the town of Acteal late last year.
	   Officials have interrogated foreigners who sympathize with the
rebels at immigration checkpoints on roads to Zapatista-held areas,
and more than 150 foreigners accused of meddling in politics have
been expelled.
	   The government has raided at least two self-declared rebel
municipalities and has encouraged members of others to abandon the
rebels.
	   Meanwhile, dozens of Ruiz's rural layworkers have been charged
with crimes by local officials and his diocese says local
pro-government officials have used intimidation to close 33 Roman
Catholic churches.
	   The new government tactics come nearly two years after talks
broke down.
	   Government and rebel representatives spent 17 months in talks
that resulted in agreements on rights for Indians nationwide.
Sympathetic Congressmen proposed a law that the Zapatistas
accepted. The federal government ultimately rejected the measure
and offered its own, less sweeping version _ one that the
Zapatistas didn't like.
	   The rebels reacted by withdrawing from talks in August 1996,
accusing the government of reneging on its pact. Now, even the
once-voluble rebel military leader, Subcomandante Marcos, is being
unusually silent.
	   Signs are that circumstances are swinging in the government's
favor, Meyer said.
	   ``The federal government ... has the Zapatista army
surrounded,'' Meyer said. ``It is making life impossible for its
(village support) bases and is pouring out money to support ruling
party adherents in the appearance of a social program.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Mexico-Chiapas; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
