<HEADLINE>
Histadrut labor union boss re-elected to second term
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) _ The leader of Israel's largest labor
union was expected to win a landslide victory to a second term
Tuesday, according to exit poll results.
	   Israel TV exit polls showed Amir Peretz leading with 72 percent
of the vote one hour after polls closed around the country at 22:00
(19:00gmt). Final results were not expected before Wednesday 04:00
(0100gmt).
	   Peretz, a member of Israel's Labor party, has led some 600,000
Histradrut workers in several massive generals strikes over the
past two years mostly to protest a government proposal to roll back
on a pension agreement plus the plans to privatize state-owned
corporations.
	   Peretz, who ran on an ``anti-capitalist'' platform, ran against
one other candidate, Maxim Levy, a lawmaker with the small Gesher
party and brother of David Levy, who resigned as Israel's foreign
minister earlier this year over the stalled Mideast peace process.
