<SLUG> BC-Hungary-Chess,0139 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Polgar defeats Karpov in chess battle of the sexes
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) _ Hungary's Judit Polgar, the world's top
female chess player, defeated World Chess champion Anatoly Karpov
on Tuesday in the first day of their four-day series of speed
matches.
	   ``I think some of my moves made him pause, they were not what he
expected,'' said Polgar, 21. ``With only 22 seconds to go, he made
a wrong move and gave up.''
	   Karpov fought her with the Carokan defense but quit after the
50th move.
	   The first match, with Judit playing black and using the Bennoni
defense, ended in a tie after the 33rd move.
	   Karpov, 47, is the reigning champion of the World Chess
Federation, known by its French acronym FIDE, although fellow
Russian Garry Kasparov is considered the true world champion. 	   
