<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Martin-PGA,0623 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Martin rises to the moment again
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RON SIRAK &QC; 
 &UR; AP Golf Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Great athletes are at their best when it means
the most. It is almost the definition of a champion.
	   By qualifying for the U.S. Open _ in a playoff no less, and
after nearly blowing it with a double bogey on the last hole of
regulation no less _ Casey Martin strengthened his credentials as a
great athlete.
	   ``Know what?'' Martin said after he made a birdie on the second
extra hole Monday to get the final qualifying spot in Cincinnati.
``I grew up hitting Whiffle ball shots around my yard thinking I
was in the Open. I guess it's going to come true.''
	   When Martin tees up a real ball at The Olympic Club in San
Francisco on June 18 he will represent all those who ever dreamed
of playing in the U.S. Open while knocking around a Whiffle ball.
	   And when he becomes the first person to ride a cart in a U.S.
Open he will represent all those who overcame great odds to live a
dream.
	   But to think of Martin merely as a role model for the disabled
is to do him a disservice. He is _ perhaps above all else _ a
golfer and a competitor who can rise to the occasion.
	   Twice this year Martin has played his best when it meant the
most.
	   The first time was in the opening event of the year on the Nike
Tour. Riding in a cart because of a temporary court order and while
anticipating the upcoming trial in his suit against the PGA Tour,
Martin won the Lakeland Classic.
	   ``A total weight has been lifted,'' Martin said at the time.
``All the stuff about the court and all the talk about me playing
in a cart, it weighs on you emotionally. Just to win is an amazing
relief.''
	   Martin went on to win that case against the PGA Tour _ a
decision under appeal _ and then was overwhelmed with offers for
public appearances and endorsements.
	   As happens with many players, he found that success creates
demands on one's time, making top-level golf difficult.
	   After winning his first start out of the blocks, Martin missed
the cut in three of his next five tournaments, and in 10
consecutive events he shot only one round below 68 and never
finished in the top 10.
	   ``I'm wearing down, there's no question,'' Martin, 25, said in
early May.
	   ``I'm getting a little more worn out every week,'' he said. ``If
it weren't for the carts, I wouldn't be able to play at all by
now.''
	   But as the U.S. Open neared _ the tournament he dreamed about in
all those imaginary rounds in his back yard _ Martin got his game
back. For a second time, he played his best when it meant the most.
	   He shot a 67 and a 64 last weekend at the Miami Valley Open in
Ohio, and his opening 67 in the U.S. Open qualifier put him in
position to be able to get into the playoff for the final spot.
	   ``I'm just kind of stunned,'' Martin said. ``I was so
disappointed after I finished (the 36th hole) that I kind of wrote
it off. I'm shocked that I'm here.''
	   Martin wouldn't have needed to endure the playoff if he had made
only a bogey on the 36th hole.
	   ``On the last hole, I just hit six bad shots, took a double and
was crushed,'' he said.
	   That he was able to rally after that miserable hole was
testimony of his competitive nature.
	   In a large sense, it was that competitive nature that led to his
suit against the PGA Tour. A circulatory defect in his right leg
was not about to stop him from being a professional golfer.
	   ``I realized if I win, that would open the way,'' Martin said
after the trial in Eugene, Oregon. ``That's something to feel good
about. I'd like to be a role model. Hopefully, I'll do a good
job.''
</TEXT>
