<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turks and Caicos-Haitian Refugees,0369 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police fire at Haitian refugee sloop; 30 believe drowned
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RAYMOND HAINEY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HAMILTON, Bermuda (AP) _ Authorities in the British Turks and
Caicos Islands fired at a sloop jammed with 100 Haitian boat
people, capsizing it and perhaps drowning as many as 30 people,
according to reports Tuesday.
	   John Kelley, deputy governor of the archipelago, said in a
telephone interview that there were claims the police hit the boat
when they tried to shoot warning shots over its bow on Monday.
	   The sloop flipped over and catapulted its passengers into the
ocean.
	   The bodies of six drowned Haitians were recovered Monday, and
rescuers searched Tuesday without success for 24 missing people,
Kelley said.
	   Kelley said that firing warning shots was a routine way to stop
suspect boats and capture some of the thousands of Haitians who try
to reach the Turks and Caicos illegally each year.
	   But he added, ``There is no evidence that the police officers'
shots hit the boat, and the six dead did not suffer bullet
wounds.''
	   He said they had asked Bermuda, another British territory, to
send Creole-speaking police to help interview the 70 survivors and
to investigate the charges that police bullets hit the vessel.
	   If true, the incident could be the worst ever caused by
authorities fighting to stem illegal immigration in the Caribbean.
The Turks and Caicos Islands, located between Cuba and the Bahamas,
are a popular tourist destination.
	   Investigators were expected to raise the sunken vessel to
examine it for bullet holes.
	   ``What the police try and do is to get aboard a boat and try and
see if it's carrying illegal migrants. If it is, it's escorted into
port and the illegals are flown back to Haiti,'' Kelley said.
	   It's not known how many Haitians flee their poverty-plagued
island and make the journey north to Providenciales, the most
populated of the Turks and Caicos islands, which have about 15,000
citizens. In 1996, the local government estimated Providenciales
had 7,000 legal residents _ including 1,000 Haitians with work or
residence permits _ and 6,000 illegal Haitians.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Turks and Caicos-Haitian Refugees; CT:i; 
