<BODY>
<SLUG> AM-US-Au Pair, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0688 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede LONDON
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Woodward lawyer says she resigned weeks before firing &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: LEDES thruout with lawyer claiming she quit case; ADDS byline &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBIN ESTRIN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BOSTON (AP) _ A former lawyer for Louise Woodward said Tuesday
she had told her fellow attorneys she wanted out of the
controversial case six weeks before the British au pair announced
she had fired her.
	   Elaine Whitfield Sharp told The Associated Press she gave her
resignation notice on April 20 because she ``wanted out.''
	   Ms. Whitfield Sharp, who was fired from the case last week,
declined to elaborate.
	   ``At this time, I will not talk,'' she said, indicating she may
provide details for her desire to quit the case.
	   Ms. Woodward was convicted of second-degree murder and then had
that jury finding reduced to manslaughter by a judge in the case in
which she was charged with the death of an 8-month-old baby in her
care. She is awaiting the result of appeals by both prosecutors and
the defense.
	   Ms. Whitfield Sharp said she sent an e-mail notice of
resignation to Ms. Woodward's three other attorneys, Barry Scheck,
Andrew Good and Harvey Silverglate, on April 20, and a letter by
certified mail on April 21.
	   After discussing her resignation plans with the other attorneys,
Ms. Whitfield Sharp said she agreed to wait until the state Supreme
Judicial Court makes its decision on appeals in the case. A
decision could come any day.
	   ``In deference to Louise, I didn't withdraw and decided to hold
off, but there was to be a mutual parting of the ways,'' Ms.
Whitfield Sharp said.
	   Reached by telephone at his office Tuesday, Silverglate would
not comment.
	   ``We're not answering any questions about Elaine Sharp ... not
now,'' he said.
	   In a scathing statement to the media June 1, Silverglate and his
partners said Ms. Whitfield Sharp had been fired by Ms. Woodward.
The lawyers described Ms. Whitfield Sharp as displaying ``an
aberrant pattern of behavior.''
	   The firing came after Ms. Whitfield Sharp allegedly told a state
trooper who arrested her for drunken driving that she now believes
Ms. Woodward is guilty.
	   Asked why she didn't disclose her intentions to resign last week
after her colleagues said she was fired, Ms. Whitfield Sharp
indicated the timing was inappropriate. She denied it was a case of
sour grapes.
	   ``I've been crucified,'' she said in her first public comments
since the firing.
	   The lawyer said she decided to make her resignation plans public
to correct false media reports that her relationship with the
Woodwards deteriorated after her May 22 arrest.
	   Ms. Whitfield Sharp's statements come one day after her husband,
Dan, accused Ms. Woodward's mother of forging a housing bill to
squeeze money out of the au pair's legal defense fund.
	   Susan and Gary Woodward stayed at the Sharps' Marblehead home
while their daughter was on trial for the death of 8-month-old
Matthew Eappen.
	   Ms. Woodward, 20, lived at the Sharps' for several months after
her second-degree murder conviction was overturned and she was
sentenced to the 279 days she had served in prison since her
arrest.
	   Dan Sharp said the Woodwards created a phony bill for dlrs
15,400 that purported to charge them for housing and living
expenses during their stay. The Sharps said they didn't charge the
Woodwards anything.
	   The relationship between the Woodwards and the Sharps seems to
have been deteriorating for months. The 20-year-old moved out of
the Sharp home more than two months ago.
	   Last month, a London tabloid, The Mirror, reported a taped phone
conversation in which Ms. Whitfield Sharp allegedly says Ms.
Woodward lied to her and negotiated secret book and newspaper deals
about the case.
	   Meanwhile Tuesday, trustees of the Louise Woodward Appeal Fund
rejected allegations that the former au pair's mother defrauded the
fund.
	   At an emergency meeting, the trustees said Ms. Woodward's
parents ``have always acted in an honest and straightforward
manner'' and unanimously pledged to continue to support the family.
</TEXT>
