<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-World Cup-Incidents </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rowdy soccer fans cause disturbances along Champs-Elysees
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Police used tear gas Tuesday to disperse inebriated
soccer fans who threw beer bottles and tried to knock down a
phalanx of policemen during festivities kicking off the World Cup.
	   Police gave an early count of 15 policemen slightly injured by
the bottle-throwing.
	   About a dozen people were arrested in several incidents on the
famed Champs-Elysees, which lasted about an hour.
	   In the earlier incidents, dozens of fans threw beer bottles at
the helmeted police, who responded by charging at them. The fans
dispersed.
	   But about an hour later, just after midnight, several hundred
people, led by young fans armed with security barriers as battering
rams, tried to break through a line of policemen on the
Champs-Elysees.
	   This time police charged them and used tear gas. The fans
quickly dispersed.
	   While the police were clashing with the youths, tourists and
passers-by, in the area to soak up the post-parade atmosphere,
snapped pictures or filmed them with minicams.
	   (parf-jn) 	   
