<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Cuba,0382 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cuba says U.S. embargo and certification harmful to fight against
</HEADLINE>
drugs &QL; 
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Cuba said Tuesday the U.S. embargo was
harming its efforts to fight drug trafficking and rejected as
illegitimate the U.S. procedure of certifying countries as allies
in the drug war.
	   ``The developing world,'' said Justice Minister Roberto Diaz
Sotolongo, ``is where the flow of the resources required to
confront the challenge posed by this evil is most necessary.''
	   Speaking to a U.N. General Assembly special session on drugs,
Diaz Sotolongo said there was political will in Cuba to prevent
using Cuban territory for moving drugs.
	   Cuban authorities prevented 95 million doses of cocaine from
being consumed in other countries between 1994 and 1997, he said.
	   ``Cuba is carrying the battle forward in difficult economic
conditions, further aggravated by the presence and strengthening of
the unjust and unilateral blockade which has lasted for nearly 40
years,'' said Diaz Sotolongo, who is also president of the national
drug commission.
	   The U.S. embargo has been strengthened by legislation, known as
the Helms-Burton act, which seeks to punish foreign companies that
invest in the communist island.
	   Diaz Sotolongo said Cuba rejected U.S. certification policies
``for they are illegitimate and contrary to international law.''
	   The certification program requires the U.S. president to certify
annually whether countries that feed illegal drug markets in the
United States are cooperating in anti-drug efforts. Countries that
fail certification are denied aid, unless the president waives
penalties in the national interest.
	   Cuba doesn't receive any federal U.S. aid, but it is not alone
in its condemnation of the policy.
	   On Tuesday, Mexican Attorney General Jorge Medrazo denounced the
procedure, saying Mexico didn't accept judgement of its efforts
``not from the United States or any other country.''
	   While some U.S. officials have defended it, the administration's
chief anti-drug official, retired Gen. Barry McCaffrey, has
criticized the certification process as building resentment in
Mexico and impairing anti-narcotics cooperation between the two
countries.
</TEXT>
