<SLUG> BC-Cuba-Italy,0232 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Italian foreign minister in Cuba
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP photos HAV101-102 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   HAVANA (AP) _ With Cuba expressing concern about a recent U.S.
pact with Europe, Italy's foreign minister met Tuesday with Cuban
officials to express interest in continuing ties with the communist
island.
	   Lamberto Dini, who arrived Monday, was making the first visit by
a European Community foreign minister since the United States
imposed a tougher new version of its Cuba embargo in March 1996.
	   Cuban foreign minister Roberto Robaina, who met Dini on Tuesday,
said Monday that he was confident Europe continues to oppose the
U.S. law known as the Helms-Burton Act, which authorizes U.S.
sanctions against international companies that deal with Cuba.
	   President Fidel Castro and other Cuban officials have expressed
concern about an agreement announced last month by European and
U.S. officials to ease the impact of the law on European companies.
	   Under the agreement, European companies agreed to discourage
investment in expropriated U.S. properties in Cuba, while the
United States said it would not take legal action against European
companies that now use such property.
	   Dini expressed interest in the economic development of Cuba.
There is about dlrs 200 million in yearly trade between the two
countries and Italy is a major source of tourists for the island.
</TEXT>
