</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Caribbean-Death Penalty,0387 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Officials: rights groups ``ganging up'' on Caribbean over death
</HEADLINE>
penalty &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   GEORGETOWN, Guyana (AP) _ Human rights groups are ``ganging up''
on Caribbean nations to force them to abandon the death penalty,
local justice ministers complained during a forum in Guyana.
	   They urged each other to openly oppose pressure by the United
Nations Human Rights Committee, Amnesty International, Caribbean
Rights and Human Rights Watch to curb their use of capital
punishment.
	   ``This is a fundamental issue that we must address because we
have a number of international organizations ganging up against
us,'' Radford Hill, Antigua's legal affairs and justice minister
said during the meeting last week. ``The better thing to do is for
us to come up with a harmonized approach to the issue. There is
strength in numbers.''
	   Britain has been pressuring many of its former colonies in the
Caribbean to abandon the death penalty, and the efforts have drawn
support from many human rights groups.
	   Caribbean countries counter that they need capital punishment to
deter murders related to drug trafficking, a problem they claim
other countries do not fully appreciate.
	   During the meeting, Guyanese Attorney General Charles Ramson
said the U.N. committee ``is insensitive to the normative behavior
and conditions'' in Guyana and other countries. Eliminating capital
punishment ``would have far-reaching negative effects and would
affect the safety of citizens,'' he said.
	   Representatives from Trinidad and Tobago, Jamaica, Guyana and
the Bahamas accused European countries of trying to impose their
culture on the Caribbean. Together, those four countries have more
than 130 people on death row.
	   Jamaica withdrew in October from a U.N. panel that hears death
row convicts' appeals, claiming the appeals were delaying
executions. Ramson has said Guyana will simply ignore the U.N.
panel's recommendations.
	   Trinidad and Tobago withdrew from the 1969 American Convention
on Human Rights, a human rights accord enforced by the Organization
of American States, on May 26. It accused the organization of
dragging its feet on death penalty appeals.
	   The move drew quick criticism from Amnesty International and
Human Rights Watch.
</TEXT>
