<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-Africa-Reax, 1st Ld,0335 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Africans praise Abacha the man, scorn the policies
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs with Mandela comments at OAU summit. &QL; 
 &UR; By AMBA DADSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) _ African leaders, diplomats and
dignitaries on Tuesday ignored late Sani Abacha's harsh domestic
politics, opting instead to praise the man who defended democracy
abroad while squelching liberty at home.
	   From the Ivory Coast to South Africa, carefully worded tributes
marked Abacha's death _ tributes that also carried a message
calling for change in Nigeria.
	   ``He was quick to recognize that prosperity in the region
depends on the capacity of countries in West Africa to foster peace
and stability,'' Ghana's Vice President John Atta Mills said.
	   At home Abacha crushed dissent, jailed opponents and refused his
people freedom and democracy.
	   But elsewhere in West Africa, Abacha's soldiers were ironically
welcomed by villagers as champions of democracy as they drove out
villains and despots to help restore elected governments.
	   At a meeting of Africa's top political body, the Organization of
African Unity, South African President Nelson Mandela paid tribute
to Abacha, his former political enemy.
	   Mandela, 79, who is serving his last term as president, told
reporters in brief impromptu remarks that Abacha's death was a
great loss for Nigeria and Africa.
	   The South African leader later flew out of Ouagadougou, Burkina
Faso, officials said, ending Mandela's farewell appearance at the
OAU summit before retiring from politics next year.
	   The conciliatory remarks came despite persistent tensions
between Nigeria and South Africa under the rule of Abacha and
Mandela.
	   Relations chilled between the two countries after Mandela called
for Commonwealth sanctions against Nigeria in retaliation for the
military execution of environmental activist Ken Saro-Wiwa and
eight fellow activists in 1995.
	   Sierra Leone's, 6th graf pvs 	   
</TEXT>
