<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Argentina-Arrested General,0212 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former military junta leader is arrested
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) _ A member of the military junta
that ruled for seven years was arrested Tuesday on kidnapping
charges linked to Argentina's ``dirty war,'' officials and news
reports said.
	   Former president and commander-in-chief Jorge Rafael Videla, who
took power in a 1976, was detained on orders by a federal judge,
said Interior Minister Carlos Corach.
	   According to local news reports, the 71-year-old Videla was
arrested on charges of child kidnapping, in a case brought by
children whose parents ``disappeared'' during the military regime.
	   As the chief of the military, Videla presided over death squads
that waged a ``dirty war'' of torture and murder against political
opponents, mainly leftists from 1976-1983.
	   The Argentine government claims 9,000 people disappeared during
that time, but human rights groups put the figure at 30,000.
	   The Army chief was sentenced to life in prison in 1986 for human
rights abuses that occurred during the dictatorship. He served
several years before he was pardoned.
	   In 1990, Videla, along with all middle and senior-ranking
officers, was pardoned as part of a decree by President Carlos
Menem.
</TEXT>
