<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup-Incidents, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police use tear gas to disperse bottle-throwing fans
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with background on festivities. ADDS byline.
 &UR; By JEAN-MARIE GODARD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Police used tear gas to disperse drunken soccer
fans who threw beer bottles and tried to knock down a phalanx of
policemen during festivities kicking off the World Cup.
	   Police gave an early count of 15 policemen slightly injured by
the bottle-throwing late Tuesday and early Wednesday.
	   About a dozen people were arrested in several incidents on the
famed Champs-Elysees, which lasted about an hour and a half.
	   The incidents marred the festive atmosphere of the meticulously
planned pre-World Cup events. Four 60-foot-tall robots made their
way through the city to the Place de la Concorde, where tens of
thousands watched a spectacle involving acrobats and dancers in
fanciful costumes.
	   The World Cup begins on Wednesday, and thousands of fans have
been pouring into Paris.
	   At about 10:30 p.m. (2030 GMT), dozens of fans threw beer
bottles at the helmeted police, who responded by charging at them.
The fans dispersed. The incident was repeated several times.
	   About an hour later, just after midnight, several hundred
people, led by young fans armed with security barriers as battering
rams, tried to break through a line of policemen on the
Champs-Elysees.
	   This time police charged them and used tear gas. The fans
quickly dispersed.
	   While the police were clashing with the youths, tourists and
passers-by, in the area to soak up the post-parade atmosphere,
snapped pictures or filmed them with minicams.
	   (parf-jn) 	   
</TEXT>
