w2176 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PeopleandPlaces     06-09 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-People and Places,0859 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
People and places in the news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Luciano Pavarotti and the Spice Girls,
French cops on rollerblades, Britain's Queen Mother, Japan's
tabloids and a memorial service for Linda McCartney. Some items may
also have moved as separates. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MODENA, Italy (AP) _ The newest Spice is ... Luciano Pavarotti?
	   The Ginger-less Spice Girls teamed up Tuesday with the famed
tenor for their first performance since announcing their split last
week.
	   The charity song-fest, ``Pavarotti and Friends,'' was directed
by Spike Lee and co-starred pop performers Celine Dion and Stevie
Wonder. Proceeds were to benefit poor children in the West African
nation of Liberia.
	   The four Spices and Pavarotti joined forces for the song ``Viva
Forever,'' their first performance since the departure of Ginger
Spice, Geri Halliwell.
	   The 62-year-old Pavarotti has been making fewer opera
appearances in recent years, but his pop career is on the upswing.
Tuesday's show in this northern city was broadcast live on Italy's
flagship state television station, RAI-1.
	   Also on the program were Vanessa Williams, Natalie Cole, Jon Bon
Jovi, Trisha Yearwood and Italian stars Eros Ramazzotti, Zucchero
and Pino Daniele.
	   At a news conference, Lee was asked whether the all-girl group
would be as good without Ms. Halliwell.
	   ``I'm not an expert on the Spice Girls, so I don't know if I can
answer that,'' he answered.
	   The other Spice Girls declined to discussed the split.
	   ___
	   PARIS (AP) _ French cops on rollerblades made their first
appearance Tuesday on Paris streets, only hours before World Cup
festivities kicked off with a parade down the Champs-Elysees.
	   Clad in helmets, kneepads and windbreakers, an eight-man brigade
skated through Paris, which is being invaded by thousands of soccer
fans.
	   The special squad _ expected to grow to 30 in the next few weeks
_ was picked on the basis of skating ability, and trained by a top
French speed skater.
	   The idea was actually developed before the World Cup, to help
keep order on weekends. On weekend evenings, some 5,000 Parisians
gather at the Place d'Italie before skating through the city.
	   French Interior Minister Jean-Pierre Chevenement said the
brigade was not a publicity stunt, but was designed to allow police
to intervene ``with more flexibility'' on the sidewalks.
	   Several U.S., Canadian and Dutch cities have experimented with
cops on rollerblades.
	   ___
	   CAMBRIDGE, England (AP) _ The Queen Mother, undaunted by her 97
years and hip surgery less than five months ago, inaugurated a new
rowing boat at Cambridge University on Tuesday, but skipped the
usual champagne launch.
	   At Queens' College, the women's rowing team and sundry VIPs
gathered on the lawn to watch the mother of Queen Elizabeth II
unveil the boat's name _ the Patroness.
	   It was the 50th anniversary of her becoming the college's
patroness, and the 550th anniversary of the college's foundation.
	   The traditional breaking of a bottle on a new ship would damage
a glass fiber boat. So, after the Queen Mother left to have lunch,
the rowers held another brief ceremony to pour a glass of champagne
over the top of the boat for good luck.
	   ___
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Accusing Japan's ribald tabloids of going too far,
police said Tuesday they issued warnings to two newspapers for
publishing pornographic photos.
	   The warnings, made separately in recent months, were the first
in decades in which police took exception to material published in
Japan's often risque daily tabloids.
	   On March 9, Tokyo Sports published a photo downloaded from the
Internet showing female nudes that _ according to police _ were
insufficiently blurry.
	   Two months later, Nikkan Gendai printed a color photo of a
couple having sex _ again, only slightly blurry.
	   Neither paper will be charged with any crime because both
publishers pledged not to release such photographs again, the Tokyo
police said.
	   ``But we will not stop publishing sex-related materials,'' said
Yasuo Sakurai, chief editor of Tokyo Sports. ``Sex is a universal
interest of human beings, and we believe many readers like to read
what we publish.''
	   ___
	   LONDON (AP) _ A day after an emotional memorial service for
Linda McCartney in London in which 700 guests sang the Beatles song
``Let It Be,'' Paul McCartney announced Tuesday that a second
service would be held later this month in New York City.
	   The former Beatle said he and the couple's children would attend
the June 22 service, at New York's Riverside Church.
	   The entire McCartney family has been surprised and touched by
the outpouring of support from fans and fellow animal lovers over
the past few weeks, he said in a statement. Mrs. McCartney was a
staunch campaigner for animal rights and vegetarianism.
	   After the service in London, at St. Martins-in-the-Fields
Church, McCartney thanked the hundreds who paid tribute to his
wife's memory, saying, `The kids and I thank them all for coming.
Although Linda's not here, she's in our hearts and her spirit and
her message will live on forever.'' 	   
</TEXT>
