<HEADER>
w2190 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Soccer-WorldCu     06-09 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Briefs,0977 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
staying home to watch the World Cup; betting; Haitian electricity
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Includes items on times of goals; Ronaldo's earring; Brits
shortage &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ It took only 94 years to do it, but the people who
run soccer have finally come up with a definite way to tell time
during a match.
	   For the first time at a World Cup, FIFA is introducing a
standardized system of timing goals, fouls and substitutions.
	   For decades, there have been two generally accepted ways of
marking such incidents.
	   For example, if Ronaldo had scored a goal 26 minutes, 15 seconds
into a match, some scorekeepers would say it came ``after 26
minutes'' and record it as ``Renaldo (26).''
	   Others would say it was ``in the 27th minute,'' writing it as
``Renaldo (27).'' FIFA says this is the system that will be used at
the World Cup.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   PARIS (AP) _ Even the Brazilians are looking for more of an
edge.
	   Two-time FIFA Player of the Year Ronaldo probably doesn't need
it, but he's decided to wear an enamel earring, sent to him by a
female admirer, on his jersey as a good luck charm during Brazil's
World Cup games.
	   The shaven-headed 21-year-old megastar received the jewelry in
the mail, of which Ronaldo receives more than a 100 pieces a day _
most on the team.
	   The item still must meet FIFA approval. To wear on his jersey,
Ronaldo must present the amulet to the referee before the match,
who will have to decide whether it poses a safety threat.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   LONDON (AP) _ More than one in four men in Britain will take
time off from work to watch the World Cup, with some admitting they
are already planning to call in sick, according to a survey.
	   The survey of 1,200 people by the Institute of Personnel and
Development revealed that 28 percent of men and 8 percent of women
in England, Wales and Scotland plan to take time off work to watch
World Cup matches on TV.
	   Over half of those will take paid leave, one in four will take
advantage of flexible hours and 16 percent will take unpaid leave.
	   Around 3 percent admit they will take a sick day to watch games.
	   Some employers are taking steps to allow their staff to follow
the action.
	   At the Cadbury's Factory in Bourneville, near Birmingham, live
radio coverage will be piped in for the 4,000 employees to keep up
to date.
	   In Scotland, shifts have been changed and television screens are
being brought into some offices.
	   Production at the Coca-Cola and Schweppes plant in East Kilbride
will be stopped during each of Scotland's first round games against
Brazil, Norway and Morocco.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   LONDON (AP) _ Not surprisingly, the money is pouring in for the
World Cup favorites at bookmakers in England.
	   One fan walked into a Coral betting shop and placed 20,000
pounds (dlrs 32,700) on the Netherlands to win it all.
	   ``He'll never need to go Dutch again if Bergkamp and Co. win the
World Cup,'' Coral spokesman Simon Clare said.
	   Even so, the Netherlands remained at 8-1 to win the tournament.
Brazil was the 3-1 favorite, followed by France at 6-1. Italy and
Germany were both 7-1, with England joining the Dutch at 8-1. Iran
was the distant outsider at 400-1.
	   Rival bookmaker Ladbrokes had similar odds, with defending
champion Brazil as 3-1 favorites and France at 11-2. Italy was
third at 6-1, and both Argentina and Germany were 7-1 picks.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   SAINT-JEAN D'ARDIERES, France (AP) _ Attendance for Tuesday's
U.S. soccer scrimmage: 0.
	   The U.S. Soccer Federation barred reporters, fans and everyone
other than staff from Stade de Fetan in Trevoux for its 4-0 victory
over Gueugnon 4-0.
	   Why all the secrecy? After all, the stadium was open Monday in
Nice when Germany defeated a Cote d'Azure selection of young
professionals 2-1.
	   ``I want to have the ability to determine what I say after the
game, so I make the conclusions, not everyone else,'' U.S. coach
Steve Sampson said. ``If I open it to the American press, I have to
open it to all press. We all know there are certain connections in
the German press to the German national team coach.''
	   Brian McBride, Cobi Jones, Brian Maisonneuve and Ernie Stewart
scored for the Americans, who hadn't played a game since a
scoreless tie against Scotland on May 30 in Washington.
	   Each goalkeeper played 30 minutes, with Brad Friedel starting,
Kasey Keller following and Juergen Sommer finishing.
	   Marcelo Balboa (infected foot) and Chad Deering (ankle pain)
were the only players who didn't get in.
	   ___ &QC; 
	   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ To bring World Cup matches live to
soccer-crazed Haitians, the state electricity company plans to
boost power to the capital that suffers 12-hour-a-day blackouts.
	   It comes at a price, however. The Nouvelliste newspaper reported
Tuesday that residents are being asked to turn off their
refrigerators, air conditioners and electric water pumps during
soccer matches.
	   Haitians have adopted the teams of Argentina and Brazil, the
defending champions who open the World Cup finals in France on
Wednesday. While Haitians have started flying Argentine and
Brazilian flags from their homes and cars, they appear indifferent
to Jamaica, only the second Caribbean team to make it to the finals
since Haiti broke the barrier in 1974.
	   Tuesday's Nouvelliste quoted Electricity of Haiti officials as
saying that they would boost power to Port-au-Prince from 55 to 100
megawatts during the World Cup. Even that will not guarantee
unbroken coverage since they city needs 115 megawatts daily,
according to officials who appealed to residents to turn off other
electrical appliances.
	   Probably fewer than a third of Port-au-Prince's 2 million
residents own television sets.
</TEXT>
