w2194 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Venezuela-OilSpill     06-09 0232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Venezuela-Oil Spill,0232 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
7,000 barrels of diesel fuel spill into Caribbean Sea off Venezuela
</HEADLINE>
coast &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) _ Seven thousand barrels of diesel fuel
spilled from a tanker into the Caribbean Sea, causing an ecological
crisis off the coast of Venezuela, officials said Tuesday.
	   The cause of Monday's spill in the Bay of Carenero, 100
kilometers (60 miles) east of the capital, Caracas, was not
immediately known. However, RCR radio reported that a hose sprung a
leak while transferring the fuel from the tanker to shore.
	   A diesel slick stretched 1.5 kilometers (1 mile) into the ocean,
and some of the fuel contaminated the shoreline, the state-run oil
company Petroleos de Venezuela said in a statement.
	   Workers were at the scene Tuesday trying to clean up the spill,
the statement said.
	   The affected area is a popular Venezuelan tourist destination
and home to a large number of mangrove plantations. Seven thousand
barrels is the equivalent of 1,059,884 liters (280,000 gallons) of
diesel.
	   ``We found out about the spill today,'' Alberto Colmenares, a
local representative for the Environment Ministry, told The
Associated Press Tuesday. ``They have not been able to contain all
of the fuel that was spilled.''
	   Petroleos de Venezuela uses a facility at the Bay of Carenero to
distribute diesel fuel to local markets inside Venezuela. 	   
</TEXT>
