w2199 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WorldCup-PartyTime     06-09 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-World Cup-Party Time,0623 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AP Special Correspondent
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MORT ROSENBLUM &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ A fantasy pageant to open the World Cup descended
into a drunken party that spilled across Paris in the early hours
of Wednesday, with police battling fans on the Champs-Elysees.
	   On Tuesday evening, crowds watched four 60-foot (18-meter)
robots depicting the world's races lumber into the Place de la
Concorde to meet around the ancient Egyptian Obelisk, done up as
the World Cup.
	   The spectacle ended in a swirl of color and sound, but the
gaiety was dampened by zealous security officers who forced crowds
behind a maze of barriers, often brusquely ignoring official
passes.
	   Near midnight, several hundred soccer fans of mixed nationality
began heaving bottles at the police. One group seized a metal
barrier and rammed it into a line of riot troops.
	   Police charged the fans, swinging batons and firing off tear
gas, chasing them up the broad avenue. At least a dozen were
arrested, and 15 policemen were treated for injuries.
	   In the heart of Paris, partying visitors jammed almost every
place that serves alcohol _ no small number in this town _ as they
waited for Wednesday's opening game between Brazil and Scotland.
	   Most seemed pretty relaxed, chanting their team's fight songs or
dancing impromptu sambas to Brazilian rhythms. Hundreds wore
football shirts emblazoned with ``Ronaldo,'' Brazil's star.
	   Brazil is favored, but not by the 20,000 Scots who crossed the
Channel for the opening game.
	   ``We'll win, 1-0, for certain,'' declared Eric Muirhead, in a
kilt and bare chest, as he wavered unsteadily at the edge of the
Place de la Concorde.
	   Neither he nor his friends seemed to notice the swarm of
costumed dancing figures: from bobbing baobab trees and women in
evening dress to silver creatures that looked like Ninja aardvarks.
	   Paris awoke on Tuesday to find the four giants _ an African, an
American Indian, an Asian and a European _ planted near their most
familiar monuments.
	   Blaring ethno-techno music and escorted by 4,500 costumed
extras, the robots took separate routes toward the Concorde.
	   ``We want to show that football is accessible to everyone and
belongs to no one,'' said Jean-Pascal Levy-Trumet, who designed the
``Fete du Football'' show. ``The grand theme is universality in a
single world.''
	   Moussa, the African, was the first to stir in the evening, near
the Eiffel Tower, standing up and opening huge eyes to wild
applause.
	   He symbolized man in a new world, and he rose up to see dancing
odd-shaped baobab trees and termite hills. Six ostriches _ actually
men on stilts _ bobbed among women dressed as stylized giraffes.
	   ``Amazing,'' said Florence Farriaux, as she hurried her three
kids home so their father could take them to Concorde, where Moussa
would meet the three others. ``I loved it.''
	   On the Pont Neuf over the Seine, Ho, the Asian, stood up in a
fantasy world of balloons shaped like flying fish and dancers
dressed as tropical sea creatures.
	   Pablo, the Indian, rose from a crouch under the Arc de Triomphe
and strolled down the Champs-Elysees to see the animated trees,
snakes and bugs that depict nature.
	   Romeo, the European, had been snoozing outside the Opera
Garnier. His theme was love, and along his route he bowed to a
sculptor's conception of the Urban Woman, a mere 4.5 meters (15
feet) tall.
	   David Quill, a Scottish engineer who came for no-nonsense
football, found himself carried away by the spectacle. ``This
brings together the four worlds,'' he said. ``I really liked it.''
	   But another Scot, Eric Blackley, just shrugged. ``It's all
right, I suppose,'' he said. ``But it's not what I came here for.''
</TEXT>
