<SLUG> BC-UN-Kosovo,0484 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. seeks Russian endorsement of strong measures against Serbia
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS; LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Yeltsin saying he will
meet with Milosevic himself, but rebuffing military action.
 &UR; With Yugoslavia-Kosovo &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT H. REID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ U.S. President Bill Clinton is prepared to
talk to Russian President Boris Yeltsin himself, if necessary, to
get Moscow's support for tougher measures to stop the violent Serb
crackdown in Kosovo, senior U.S. officials say.
	   The Americans and Britons plan to ask the Security Council,
possibly next week, to authorize the use of force against the Serbs
to halt attacks on ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, diplomatic sources
said Tuesday.
	   Both they and the U.S. officials spoke on condition of
anonymity.
	   In Bonn, Germany, Yeltsin pledged Tuesday to use his influence
with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to end police and army
attacks in Kosovo, but remained firmly opposed to any Western
military intervention.
	   Yeltsin said he would try to meet Milosevic in person, and made
clear he prefers friendly diplomacy over any military threats or
economic sanctions to resolve the conflict that has killed at least
250 people this year.
	   ``The more softly I speak the better the chances of a meeting,''
Yeltsin said at a news conference following two days of talks with
German officials. ``We will meet and discuss the question of how to
get out of this situation without getting into a big war.''
	   The Russian president said any military deployment in Kosovo
would be ``very dangerous'' and could spark a wider Balkan
conflict.
	   NATO defense ministers, who meet in Brussels on Thursday and
Friday, are expected to order NATO military commanders to draw up
plans for possible direct military intervention in Kosovo.
	   Such proposals could include a ``no-fly'' zone similar to one
imposed on Bosnia during the war there, or expanding the 750-member
U.N. peacekeeping force in nearby Macedonia. Nearly half that force
is American.
	   The Russians _ allies of the Serbs _ oppose NATO troops in the
area but have indicated they might support a more robust U.N. role.
That would require approval by the 15-member Security Council,
where the Russians have a permanent seat and veto power.
	   Diplomats said the Britons and the Americans are waiting to see
what NATO foreign ministers decide before circulating any draft
resolution.
	   In the past, however, strong council action on Kosovo and other
issues, notably Iraq, has been blocked by Russian Foreign Minister
Yevgeny Primakov.
	   To get Moscow's backing on Kosovo, the United States is trying
to show flexibility on other issues, including Iraq, in which
Moscow and Washington differ. The Americans have indicated they may
accept a scaling-back of U.N. inspections of Iraqi nuclear
facilities in the coming months. 	   
</TEXT>
