<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup Roundup,0901 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Scotland dispenses with niceties; 18-meter monsters kick off World
</HEADLINE>
Cup &QL; 
 &UR; By BRIAN TRUSDELL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ It's easy to tell the opening kickoff of the World
Cup is getting closer _ the tone is getting more desperate.
	   ``We must go for the throat,'' Scotland's Gordon Durie said
Tuesday.
	   The 33-year-old striker and his teammates was expecting the
world to watch when Scotland takes the field against four-time and
defending champion Brazil in Wednesday's opening match of France
'98.
	   ``If we sit in and try and defend, they have players who can
destroy you,'' Durie said.
	   On the final day before the opener, World Cup activities
officially got underway Tuesday with a parade of four 18-meter
(60-foot) mechanical giants and 4,500 costumed extras through the
middle of Paris.
	   The Champs Elysees was awash with Brazilians in yellow,
Argentines in sky blue and Scots in all kinds of tartan kilts.
	   The FIFA presidential election, however, lingered a day more
than expected with Sepp Blatter, the winner, ``categorically''
denying rumors and reports that he bought the election.
	   ``Mr. Blatter vehemently refuted the allegations and said he
would investigate the source of such malicious reports,'' he said
through a FIFA release. ``He stressed that he reserved the right to
take legal action against those seeking to defame him.''
	   Rumors apparently were fed by a story in the International
Herald Tribune on Tuesday which quoted Johansson, the president of
UEFA, possibly indicating that Monday's vote wasn't fair.
	   ``Something happened somewhere,'' Johansson was quoted as
saying. ``I had so many promises of votes that I am, to put it
mildly, surprised and disappointed to be beaten so
comprehensively.''
	   Meanwhile, Brazil and Scotland, along with Morocco and Norway,
who were to play Wednesday night in the tournament's second match,
made final preparations for their debuts.
	   ``We must understand this moment,'' Brazilian midfielder
Leonardo said. ``I want to make history.''
	   Scotland was the team in position to create shockwaves, having
never advanced past the first round in eight trips to the finals
and won only four of 20 matches.
	   ``We have to lift ourselves to another level and show we can
compete against Brazil,'' said midfielder John Collins, who will
earn his 50th cap when the match kicks off at 5:30 p.m. (1530 GMT).
``We will need a superb performance that night as well as in the
other two games if we are to progress.''
	   The second Group A match of the day was a much-lower profile
affair, featuring two teams that both were bounced from the United
States after the first round in 1994.
	   However, the match was considered anything but a game between
equals.
	   Norway went into the match unbeaten in its last 14 games and
having outscored its last three opponents by a combined scored of
13-2. The ``Drillos'' are being picked by most experts to be the
second team that advances out of Group A with Brazil.
	   Morocco, conversely, will be a major surprise if it gets past
the first round.
	   It struggled to a 1-1 draw in its final prep match against Chile
on Thursday, allowing the equalizer in the 90th minute on a header
by Marcelo Salas.
	   To start it all, the French lived up to their artsy reputation
Tuesday with a ``Festival of Football'' through the streets of
Paris reminiscent of the opening ceremony for the 1992 Winter
Olympics in Albertville.
	   Ho, the Asian; Pablo, the American Indian; Romeo, the European;
and Moussa, the African, strode down the main avenues of Paris with
human-sized bugs and plants for escorts before meeting at Concorde
at the base of the Champs Elysees in a five-hour extravaganza.
	   Unlike the Olympics, soccer usually provides its own spontaneous
pageantry at matches, and is not accustomed to the scripted shows
more associated with the Summer and Winter Games.
	   It won over a few converts who came strictly for the matches.
	   ``This brings together the four worlds,'' Scottish engineer
David Quill said. ``I really liked it.''
	   Elsewhere, other teams still fretted about injuries.
	   Nigeria, Italy, the Netherlands and Germany all dealt with
various infirmities.
	   The Africans learned that starting defender Jero Shakpoke had
broken his collarbone and would be out for the tournament, and
forward Daniel Amokachi was felled by a twisted right knee.
	   Amokachi hurt himself about an hour into Tuesday's training
session when his foot got caught in the damp turf as he attempted a
shot. An assistant team trainer said it would Wednesday before the
extent of the injury was known.
	   Italy seemed to have good word on Alessandro Del Piero and
Moreno Torricelli, but Fabrizio Ravenelli, who was suffering from
fever and a cough, was taken for X-rays to determine if he had
bronchitis.
	   Dutch captain Ronald de Boer twisted his left ankle in training
Monday and didn't practice Tuesday. His status for the Netherlands'
opening World Cup Group E match Saturday against Belgium in St.
Denis was still to be determined.
	   And in the German camp, midfielder Christian Ziege missed his
third day of training with a fever and defender Thomas Helmer sat
out a second day with a thigh injury.
</TEXT>
