<HEADLINE>
Author Richler in `stable condition' after kidney surgery
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MONTREAL (AP) _ Novelist Mordecai Richler was reported in stable
condition after undergoing surgery at a Montreal hospital.
	   ``The doctors have said that the surgery went very well and he
is resting in stable condition,'' Montreal General Hospital
spokewoman Chantal Beauregard said Tuesday. ``I understand he's
spending the night in the recovery room.''
	   She would not confirm that the celebrated Canadian writer had
had kidney surgery_ as he had indicated in an newpaper interview
Monday.
	   ``Mr. Richler really wants to keep his personal life personal,''
said Beauregard. ``I think we have to respect his wish for privacy
at this time.''
	   Beauregard added that she did not know how long Richler would be
in hospital.
	   In in telephone interview Monday with the Montreal Gazette from
his hospital room, Richler said his general health was ``terrific''
and he expected to be home in a week.
	   ``I need to have something done about my kidney,'' said Richler,
67. ``It's not a life-threatening operation. It's done pretty often
and I'll just have a difficult week.''
	   Richler, the author of The Apprenticeship of Duddy Kravitz and
St. Urbain's Horsemen, has just published Barney's Version. He is
also an internationally known newspaper and magazine columnist. 	   
</TEXT>
