<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. dollar slightly higher, Tokyo stocks lower in early trading
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar edged higher against the yen early
Wednesday as traders awaited the outcome of a meeting of G-7
finance officials later in the day. Tokyo stocks edged lower.
	   The dollar bought 140.56 yen at the start of morning trading, up
0.20 yen from late Tuesday in Tokyo and above its late New York
level of 140.30 yen overnight.
	   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
slipped 9.79 points, or 0.06 percent, to 15,520.38 at the start of
Wednesday's trading. On Tuesday, the average rose 235.46 points, or
1.52 percent.
	   The dollar hovered above 140 yen as all eyes turned to Paris,
where deputy finance ministers of the Group of Seven top industrial
nations are meeting. Officials could announce a joint effort to
prop up the yen later Wednesday, traders warned.
	   The dollar had gained steadily against the yen in recent weeks
as investors shifted more and more funds out of Japan's lagging
markets and into the robust U.S. economy.
	   Concerns about the Japanese economy drove the dollar to a
seven-year high of 141.35 yen on Tuesday.
	   Such concerns also weighed on stock prices, offsetting optimism
the stronger dollar would boost the earnings of Japan's exporters.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section fell 1.14 points, or 0.09 percent, to 1,207.54. The
TOPIX closed up 10.32 points, or 0.86 percent, the day before.
	   Stock prices remained little changed as investors watched if G-7
officials in Paris would intervene in currency markets.
	   Without some move to support the yen, analysts cautioned foreign
investors will likely keep selling their Japanese holdings. That's
because a weakening yen erodes the dollar value of Japanese stocks.
	   ``The weak yen is good for exporters, but our concern is that it
will hurt the sentiment of foreign investors,'' said Tsuyoshi
Nomaguchi, a strategist at Daiwa Securities Co.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond stood at 1.200 percent, down from Tuesday's 1.210
percent. Its price rose to 112.02 yen from 111.96 yen.
 &UR; (mef-dj) 	   
