<SLUG> BC-Sweden-New Peace Concept, HFR,0367 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Nations urged to rethink concept of peace
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; For release at 0800 GMT, Wednesday June 10. Time set by source.
Will be updated from news conference after report released &QL; 
 &UR; By JIM HEINTZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) _ Governments should enter the 21st
century understanding that peace means more than countries arming
themselves so heavily that no one will attack them, a respected
research institute said Wednesday.
	   ``The security agenda ahead must be founded on a new political
philosophy, encompassing a common, institutionalized system of
standards and shared values rather than concepts based on the
balance of power,'' the Stockholm International Peace Research
Institute's yearbook said.
	   SIPRI's annual report is regarded as a definitive assessment of
global security issues.
	   The yearbook covers 1997, before the balance of power issue took
a worrisome turn with longtime foes India and Pakistan each
demonstrating its nuclear weapons capacity with a series of test
blasts last month.
	   ``One of the top priorities must be the complete elimination of
nuclear weapons,'' the institute urges in the yearbook's
introduction. Other parts of the report indicated a mixed prospect
for whether agreement on that scale is feasible.
	   On the favorable side, the report noted developments such as
last signing of the international treaty on banning anti-personnel
mines and the ratification by Russia, China and the United States
of the Chemical Weapons Convention.
	   But it noted ``the START II treaty remained in limbo in 1997,
despite agreement between Presidents Clinton and Yeltsin on a
series of measures to boost its chances of being ratified by the
Russian Parliament.''
	   Among the report's other conclusions:
	   _ World military expenditure declined by about one-third from
1988 to 1997 and is estimated to be about dlrs 740 billion for last
year.
	   _ Russia's military expenditure in 1997 was less than 10 percent
of what the Soviet Union spent a decade earlier.
	   _ Peace accords last year in Liberia, Tajikistan and Bangladesh
can be considered ``major successes in armed conflict resolution.''
</TEXT>
