<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Sumitomo Life, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Insurer to form Japan's biggest asset management firm
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with confirmation from Sumitomo, ADDS name of largest
existing company in 3rd graf &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Sumitomo Life Insurance Co. plans to form Japan's
largest asset management company early next year, a company
spokesman said Wednesday.
	   Sumitomo will create a subsidiary out of an affiliated company
that will manage some 10 trillion yen (dlrs 71 billion) in assets,
said Sumitomo spokesman Hitoshi Yamanaka.
	   That would be more than twice as large as Japan's biggest
existing asset management company, Nomura Asset Management.
	   Sumitomo aims to launch the company in January after a revision
in the country's insurance law allowing subsidiaries goes into
effect in December, he said.
	   Sumitomo is the world's third largest insurer.
	   The new company will establish offices in New York, London, Hong
Kong and Singapore and hire about 30 asset management experts from
overseas companies.
	   Banks and other financial institutions are scrambling to form
new alliances with both domestic and overseas companies in line
with major reforms _ known collectively as the ``big bang'' _ aimed
at increasing competition in Japan's financial industry.
 &UR; (kgo-tz) 	   
</TEXT>
