<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Fire </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rescuers at burned shopping center expecting to find dozens dead
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS and UPDATES previous; some Indonesians use one name &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos staffing
 &UR; By ALI KOTARUMALOS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PALEMBANG, Indonesia (AP) _ Hampered by smoke and ashes still
smoldering after two days, rescuers returned to a burned out
shopping center and movie theater complex Wednesday expecting to
recover the bodies of dozens of victims trapped inside.
	   Fire swept through the Megahira shopping center Monday night. So
far only 19 bodies have been recovered. But firefighters and police
fear many more died when choking black smoke filled the building.
	   Witnesses said stores in the center had been shut for several
hours when the fire started.
	   Police said at least 54 people were known to have been in three
movie theaters inside. Dozens more were playing pool in an adjacent
amusement center.
	   ``Many victims are still inside,'' police chief Brig. Gen. Dedde
Janrigadi was quoted as saying by the Sumatra Espres newspaper.
	   The cause of the fire has not been established, he said.
	   Police spokesman Lt. Col. Sardjo Sadjat said 19 people were
injured, 14 of them treated in hospitals in the city, 460
kilometers (285 miles) northwest of Jakarta.
	   Survivors said panic broke out when the building was engulfed
with smoke. None said they saw any flames.
	   One man told the newspaper Republika that people ``trampled on
one another'' to get out.
	   ``I think no one can survive,'' said Djaieni, a fire department
official.
	   The shopping center, in Palembang on the island of Sumatra, was
built in 1976. It was rebuilt after fire destroyed much of it in
1985, when one firefighter was killed.
	   Last month several shopping malls were set afire during riots in
the capital, Jakarta. Hundreds of people died, mostly looters
trapped inside. 	   
</TEXT>
