<SLUG> BC-Canada-Toxic-Spill ,0402 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Canadian experts say no cyanide contamination in Kyrgyzstan
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SASKATOON, Saskatchewan (AP) _ Canadian experts have found no
signs of cyanide contamination in soil or water near villages in
central Asia where a huge spill took place last month, says a
spokesman for the Foreign Affairs Department.
	   The findings appear to back up Cameco Corp., which has
repeatedly denied that it poisoned anyone with its May 20 spill
into a river that supplies several villages.
	   The Kyrgyz government insists the spill killed two people and
affected at least 2,500 others.
	   Valerie Noftle of the department said Tuesday that two federal
government scientists found contamination only at the actual
accident site since they arrived in Kyrgyzstan last Friday.
	   Noftle said the scientists will make test kits available to
local people to test their soil and water.
	   ``The test methods that were used have won the approval of the
local leaders,'' she said from Ottawa. ``They've been reassured by
the immediate and easily available results of the method.''
	   Bernard Michel, president of Cameco, blamed poor crisis
management by the Kyrgyz government for the panic that has seen
thousands of people go to hospital in the central Asian republic.
	   ``The government has been faced with a crisis that instead of
managing, it let go,'' Michel said Tuesday at a news conference at
the company's Saskatoon headquarters.
	   Michel said it is possible a few people ingested small amounts
of sodium cyanide in the first few days of the spill but ``we have
never seen any of those people.''
	   A report by the World Health Organization released Tuesday
confirmed cyanide wouldn't cause the high number of reported
illnesses because cyanide breaks down quickly in the body.
	   The report didn't comment on the deaths that have been
attributed to poisoning or the effects on people immediately after
the spill.
	   A commission of scientists from Russia, U.S., Canada, Kyrgyzstan
and WHO also agreed Tuesday to examine the aftermath of the spill
to figure out why so many people were made sick.
	   One Russian physician has proposed the theory that people were
made sick by a virus transmitted by chickens. Kyrgyz government
officials say more than 5,000 people from five villages sought
medical attention after the accident.
</TEXT>
