<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Argentina-Arrested General,0434 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former military junta leader is arrested for child kidnapping
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous to update and clarify. &QL; 
 &UR; By DANIEL ZADUNAISKY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) _ A former Argentine president has
been arrested and charged with kidnapping children born to parents
who were killed during the nation's ``dirty war,'' officials said.
	   Jorge Rafael Videla, who led the military junta that took power
in a 1976 coup, was detained Tuesday on orders by a federal judge,
Interior Minister Carlos Corach said.
	   Videla, 71, was arrested on charges of child kidnapping and
falsifying identity documents, a spokesman for the court told The
Associated Press in a phone interview.
	   Videla was held at a police station awaiting questioning by
federal judge Roberto Marquevich, who was urged by human rights
groups to investigate allegations that some children of dissidents
who were slain were handed over to members of the military, who
raised them.
	   Videla is accused of being involved in five such cases,
including those of two children given to Norberto Bianco, a former
military doctor who fled to Paraguay after democracy was restored.
	   He was extradited to Argentina and jailed on kidnapping charges.
	   The two children have grown and married and reside in Paraguay.
No immediate information was available on the other three children
mentioned in the charges.
	   As chief of the military, Videla had final authority over death
squads that waged a ``dirty war'' of torture and murder against
political opponents, mainly leftists, from 1976-1983.
	   The Argentine government claims 9,000 people disappeared during
that time, but human rights groups put the figure at 30,000.
	   The army chief was sentenced to life in prison in 1985 for human
rights abuses during the dictatorship. In 1990, Videla, along with
all middle and senior-ranking officers, was pardoned as part of a
decree by President Carlos Menem.
	   Human rights advocates hailed his arrest Tuesday as a victory
for justice.
	   ``This is the result of more than twenty years of struggling for
justice,'' said leftist Congressman Alfredo Bravo, who was jailed
and tortured during the dirty war.
	   Hebe Bonafini, president of the Mothers of Plaza de Mayo, said,
``We are glad he is in prison, though he should serve time for all
of his crimes, not just baby kidnapping.''
	   Since 1977, the Mothers march every week around the Plaza de
Mayo facing the presidential office building in downtown Buenos
Aires to demand justice for their missing children.
</TEXT>
