<HEADER>
w2239 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Nigeria     06-09 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria,0854 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New Nigerian ruler promises return to civilian government in first
</HEADLINE>
speech &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous &QL; 
 &UR; With Nigeria-Economy, US-Nigeria &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos LAG2, LAG101-102,NY190,LON102-104,JRL102 &QL; 
 &UR; By TIM SULLIVAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) _ In his first address to the nation,
Nigeria's new military ruler has vowed to support a transition to
civilian rule and said the country's many political exiles were
welcome to return home.
	   But Gen. Abdulsalam Abubakar went into no details on how the
transition would be carried out, leaving up in the air just how
such an enormous shift could be accomplished by Oct. 1, the date
the program was to be completed.
	   Abubakar was speaking hours after he was appointed by the ruling
military junta to replace Gen. Sani Abacha as ruler of this West
African nation, rich in oil reserves but torn by ethnic divisions.
Abacha died Monday of a heart attack after a five-year
dictatorship.
	   Speaking on national television Tuesday night, Abubakar said his
government was ``fully committed to the social-political transition
program of Gen. Sani Abacha's administration.''
	   ``We will do everything to ensure its full and successful
implementation,'' Abubakar said Tuesday night.
	   Earlier Tuesday, Air Vice Marshal Mohammed Alfa, a senior
military junta aide, told reporters that Abubakar would turn the
country over to an elected civilian government by Oct. 1 _ but gave
no details.
	   Abubakar, a career soldier and long a close ally of Abacha, also
called on Nigeria's political exiles to return to the country.
	   ``I invite all Nigerians in self-exile to return home to join
the process of reconstruction and reconciliation,'' said the
general, who remained stone-faced throughout the five minute
speech.
	   Such well-known exiles as Wole Soyinka, a writer and Nobel
laureate, have warned that the military must give way to civilian
leadership.
	   ``I'm afraid that if the military does not bow to the will of
the people, armed insurrection becomes inevitable,'' he said in
Jerusalem, where he was lecturing. ``The signs of it are already
there.''
	   Also Tuesday, many civil rights groups called for the release of
jailed businessman Moshood Abiola, the presumed winner of the 1993
annulled presidential elections.
	   Abacha, a dictator well-known for his brutality, had long
promised that his transition program would end military rule in
Nigeria. But he was also widely seen as manipulating the system to
have himself transformed into a civilian ruler. Though he never
officially declared his candidacy, he was the only person nominated
by Nigeria's five registered political parties for Aug. 1
presidential elections.
	   Abubakar, who was named as chief of defense staff under Abacha
in 1993, made no comment on the election date or lack of
contestants.
	   Abubakar has not been welcomed warmly by Nigeria's pro-democracy
supporters.
	   ``We are under no illusion that by Abacha's death, military rule
has come an end,'' the United Action for Democracy said in a
statement, adding ``the struggle against military rule in all its
guises will be renewed with vigor.''
	   Many other groups declined to comment, though, as they met to
discuss forging a stronger pro-democracy alliance.
	   But countries around the world added their voices to the call
that the military, which has ruled Nigeria off and on since the
country achieved independence from Britain nearly 40 years ago,
finally step aide for good. Abacha himself seized power in a 1993
coup. During his years in power about 7,000 government critics and
dissidents were imprisoned.
	   In Washington, White House spokesman Mike McCurry said the
Clinton administration hoped that Abubakar would soon surrender
power. Similar calls for democracy in Nigeria came from France,
Britain and members of the Commonwealth of former British colonies.
	   Still, several nations in West Africa praised Abacha for making
his military a regional peacekeeper. Sierra Leone President Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah was returned to power earlier this year as a direct
result of Nigeria's military intervention.
	   And Liberian President Charles Taylor called for a national day
of mourning for Abacha _ whose troops helped to implement peace
accords that ended seven years of civil war in Liberia.
	   In Lagos, which was officially in mourning over Abacha's death,
there were few signs of tears over the death of Abacha.
	   ``There's no reason to be upset,'' said Kehinda Suleiman, a
40-year-old Lagos resident. ``We're happy he's gone. He was not
such a good leader.''
	   Abacha's leadership problems are visible everywhere in Lagos,
from the lines for gasoline that stretch for blocks to the
flickerng electricity and the phones that can't call across town.
His years in power were marked by accusations of jumps corruption
and mismanagement that completely crippled much of Nigeria's
infrastructure. Nigeria's economy, once the pride of West Africa,
is now an utter mess. Up to 80 percent of Nigeria's 115 million
people _ Africa's most-populous nation _ live in poverty.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Nigeria; CT:i; 
