<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Cartel Arrests,0344 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Attorneys seek release of Mexican drug suspects after two charges
</HEADLINE>
dropped &QL; 
 &UR; By ISAAC GUZMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GUADALAJARA, Mexico (AP) _ A judge has cleared two brothers
believed to lead Mexico's biggest methamphetamine cartel of two of
the three charges they faced. Their attorney said he is seeking
their release from jail.
	   But the attorney general's office said Tuesday that it would
seek proceedings to have the brothers, Luis and Jesus Amezcua
Contreras, extradited to the United States.
	   Judge Jose Nieves Luna Castro cleared the brothers of one count
each of criminal association and money laundering, saying they had
been charged under statutes that were not in effect at the time of
the alleged crimes. He ordered them held for trial under a separate
money laundering charge.
	   Defense attorney Everado Rojas Contreras said he is seeking a
court order that would free his clients and prevent their
extradition.
	   ``The attorney general's office hasn't offered a single piece of
evidence that, in my opinion, is worthwhile,'' he said.
	   In announcing the arrests of the Amezcua brothers last week, the
attorney general's office said that Mexico's largest
methamphetamine and amphetamine trafficking cartel had been broken
up. He said police had seized dozens of businesses in three states
and found chemicals used for producing the drug.
	   The U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration said the Amezcua
brothers' organization was the largest methamphetamine and chemical
trafficking gang known to U.S. law enforcement agents.
	   But the Amezcua brothers were not charged with drug violations.
In a statement Tuesday evening, the attorney general's office said
it is continuing its investigations linking the brothers to drug
trafficking and organized crime.
	   Methamphetamine _ a highly addictive synthetic drug also known
as crank, ice or crystal _ has gained popularity along the U.S.
West Coast and central states, surpassing usage of crack and other
drugs in many communities.
</TEXT>
