<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-New Zealand-Insurance-Snow </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Snow `property' damaged by ash fall, judge rules
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) _ Falling volcanic ash damaged the
snow ``property'' of a ski slope operator, a judge has ruled in a
landmark case sparked by eruptions that ruined two ski seasons.
	   The High Court has ordered State Insurance to pay ski slope
operator Ruapehu Alpine Lifts U.S. dlrs 2.6 million (5 million NZ
dollars) for profits lost during the Mount Ruapehu eruptions of
1995 and 1996 in central North Island.
	   Justice Warwick Gendall ruled Tuesday that the company should be
paid for the ash damage to its snow property.
	   He said snow was tangible, capable of being used, shaped and
harvested and ``by its very essence'' was used in the business.
	   Gendall said he had been unable to find any case covering snow
as property, but being a product of nature did not exclude it from
being defined as ``property.''
	   The payout is for losses suffered by the operator due to the
slope closure caused by volcanic ash damage to the snow.
	   State Insurance had earlier paid U.S. dlrs 750,000 (1.5 million
NZ) to the company for damage to plant and equipment, and an extra
U.S. dlrs 550,000 (1.1 million NZ) for interruption to business by
the 1995 eruption.
	   Local business, from farming and market gardening to tourism and
ski slopes, lost an estimated U.S. dlrs 5 million (10 million NZ)
in profits as a result of the eruptions.
	   State Insurance spokeswoman Jackie Curtis said the company was
considering an appeal against the ruling that snow was property.
	   Mount Ruapehu, meanwhile, continues to rumble occasionally and
spit steam from vents at the bottom of its crater lake.
	   Vulcanologists maintain a Level One alert on the mountain, the
alert used when a minor local eruption is in progress. It is the
lowest alert rating. 	   
</TEXT>
