<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia,0559 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian president offers special status to East Timor
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous &QL; 
 &UR; With Indonesia-Troubled Territory &QL; 
 &UR; By IRWAN FIRDAUS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Signaling a possible easing of
Indonesia's tight control, new President B.J. Habibie said he's
ready to grant special status to East Timor in exchange for peace
in the disputed territory.
	   In an interview with the British Broadcasting Corp., Habibie
also said Tuesday that he had signed a decree to release 10 East
Timor rebels jailed by Indonesia, which invaded the former
Portuguese colony in 1975 and annexed it the next year.
	   The new Indonesian leader emphasized, however, that special
status did not mean political autonomy, and he said that imprisoned
East Timorese rebel leader Xanana Gusmao would remain behind bars.
	   Indonesia regards Gusmao as a criminal, saying he has committed
violent acts in his fight against Indonesian rule. He is serving a
20-year prison term in Jakarta's Cipinang Prison.
	   East Timorese activists said Tuesday's gesture was not enough
for them to end their long-running guerrilla war against Indonesian
rule.
	   ``They are rehashing an old position, which requires first that
the United Nations recognize the illegal annexation of East Timor
by Indonesia,'' said Jose Ramos-Horta, a Nobel Peace Prize-winning
independence activist for East Timor.
	   ``This is not a serious proposal, and I am stating unequivocally
that we reject it,'' Ramos-Horta told The Associated Press in a
telephone interview from Harvard University's John F. Kennedy
School of Government.
	   Habibie's comments on East Timor appeared to be a significant
change from the policy of former President Suharto, who steadfastly
refused to consider granting any special status or any form of
local autonomy to East Timor.
	   Weeks of massive student and worker protests, fueled by alleged
government corruption and Indonesia's worst economic crisis in
decades, forced Suharto to step down last month after 32 years of
autocratic rule.
	   More than 150,000 people fled Indonesia when those deadly riots
broke out, a newspaper reported Tuesday.
	   Some 70,837 Indonesian citizens and 81,526 foreigners left
between May 14 and May 20 from airports and seaports on the islands
of Java, Bali and Sumatra, the Jakarta Post quoted immigration
chief Pranowo as saying. He said more than 51,000 people returned
in subsequent days.
	   Habibie's recent promises of economic and political reforms
weren't enough to prevent more anti-government protests Tuesday.
	   Student mobs protesting alleged local government corruption
threw rocks and smashed bank windows Tuesday in Tegal, a coastal
town about 300 kilometers (185 miles) east of Jakarta. No injuries
or arrests were reported. Three peaceful protests also were
reported elsewhere in the capital.
	   Regarding East Timor, a Habibie aide, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said predominantly Muslim Indonesia would grant some
form of recognition to the territory's culture and Roman Catholic
religion.
	   Other parts of Indonesia with special status include Jakarta,
the deeply Muslim province of Aceh in north Sumatra Island, and the
sultanate of Yogyakarta in Central Java.
	   Their local governments enjoy a few, mostly symbolic, privileges
and powers. 	   
</TEXT>
