<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Israel-Palestinians,0285 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Palestinians call for Security Council action on settlements
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Palestinians called Tuesday for Security
Council action against Israel for approving construction of 58
homes for Jews on east Jerusalem land where an Arab girls' school
was to have been built.
	   ``It is imperative for the international community to take
measures in order to confront these Israeli policies and actions,''
the Palestinian's U.N. representative, Nasser al-Kidwa, wrote in a
letter to the current Security Council president, Antonio Monteiro
of Portugal.
	   There was no indication the council was prepared to act on the
issue. The United States has long sought to keep Arab-Israeli
issues from reaching the council, and in the past has vetoed
resolutions criticizing Israel for its settlement policies.
	   In the letter, which al-Kidwa gave to Monteiro in a meeting
Tuesday, the Palestinian representative said the Security Council
``as the body responsible for the maintenance of international
peace and security, should formally consider the situation with a
view of taking the necessary actions in this regard.''
	   He called the decision by the Israeli interior ministry to
approve the construction ``yet another example of the pursuit by
the government of Israel of an intensified expansionist policy for
the colonization and judaization of Arab Jerusalem.''
	   The United States has asked Israel for a time-out in settlement
construction to help restart Israeli-Palestinian peace talks,
stalled since Israel began another settlement project on a disputed
east Jerusalem hilltop in March 1997.
</TEXT>
