r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UN-Sweden     06-09 0188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Sweden,0191 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sweden calls for an end to ``massive'' pro-drug propaganda
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Sweden called Tuesday for an end to the
``massive propaganda'' machine that makes drug use appear
fashionable and safe to young people.
	   Margot Wallstrom, Swedish minister of health and social affairs,
urged participants at the U.N. General Assembly special session on
drugs to undertake effective international cooperation to counter
the marketing she said was most often aimed directly at the young.
	   ``Such messages are transmitted worldwide in a matter of seconds
and tend to be embedded in a cultural context, accompanied by music
and fashion,'' she said.
	   ``Risks associated with drug abuse are played down and _
unbelievably _ cannabis and some of the synthetic drugs are
portrayed as totally safe and harmless.''
	   She acknowledged that trying to reverse this trend will be
difficult and expensive. ``But we, the political leaders of the
U.N. member states must make it very clear that we will not allow
ourselves to be influenced by those who promote illicit drugs.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
