<SLUG> BC-Sports-Basketball-Teikyo Post-NKorea,0219 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. basketball team invited to North Korea
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   WATERBURY, Connecticut (AP) _ The Teikyo Post men's basketball
team is planning a historic trip this summer, becoming the first
U.S. sports delegation to visit the communist nation of North
Korea.
	   The school announced Tuesday it has accepted the invitation from
Intersport USA Inc., a non-profit sports exchange program. The
11-day trip begins Aug. 1 and includes a stop in China before
heading to the North Korean capital of Pyongyang. The country has
been a communist nation since the 1950s.
	   ``Teikyo Post University is the ideal institution to undertake
this endeavor because of the international flavor we have,'' head
coach Tom Curle said.
	   The Waterbury school is affiliated with Teikyo University in
Japan. The basketball team is a member of the NAIA and the
Collegiate Atlantic Collegiate Conference.
	   The Rev. Philip Cascia, president and founder of
Connecticut-based Intersport, said the program visits countries
that, historically, have had strained relations with the United
States.
	   Since 1988, Intersport has taken athletes to goodwill
tournaments in the former Soviet Union, China, Vietnam and Cuba and
has plans to visit Iran in the future.
</TEXT>
