<SLUG> BC-Japan-Parliament </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan's ruling party seeks extension for vote on economic stimulus
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan's Parliament will vote Wednesday to extend
its current session by eight days to complete passage of a 16.6
trillion yen (dlrs 119 billion) economic stimulus package, an
official said.
	   The extension would keep Japan's Parliament, which was scheduled
to go into recess Wednesday, in session until June 18, a lower
house spokeswoman said.
	   The ruling Liberal Democratic Party wants the extra time to
finish cobbling together the largest economic stimulus package in
Japanese history, which is aimed at reviving an economy on the
brink of recession.
	   Opposition party members are expected to counter by seeking a
vote of no-confidence against Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto for
his handling of the economy, Japanese media said. Such a measure
would be unlikely to pass.
	   The extension will mean that upper house elections scheduled for
this summer will likely take place between July 8 and 18, Kyodo
News reported.
	   Parliament passed Tuesday a bill to streamline nation's
bureaucracy.
	   The new law will trim the number of agencies and ministries to
13 from 22 within five years. It will cut the number of public
employees by about 10 percent and strengthen the prime minister's
control over policy making.
	   The new law was a key policy objective of Hashimoto, who has
promised to cut costs and rein in Japan's powerful ministries.
 &UR; (mef)
</TEXT>
