<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. dollar slips, Tokyo stocks fall
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with midday trading &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar slipped against the yen Wednesday
morning as traders waited for the outcome of a meeting of G-7
finance officials later in the day. Tokyo stocks fell in light
trading.
	   The dollar bought 140.63 yen in late morning trading, up 0.16
yen from late Tuesday in Tokyo and above its late New York level of
140.30 yen overnight.
	   The dollar's relative strength from its New York level followed
some buying on speculation that deputy finance ministers of the
Group of Seven will not issue a statement after their meeting in
Paris.
	   ``After all, no one knows what will come out of the G-7 deputy's
meeting and people are nervous,'' said Yasuhisa Morikuni, assistant
vice president at Bank of America.
	   Morikuni and other traders said the dollar would likely remain
in a narrow range for the rest of the Asian day as players were
avoiding making significant moves prior to the G-7 meeting and
congressional testimony by U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan, also later Wednesday.
	   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average
fell 107.79 points, or 0.69 percent, to 15,422.38 at the end of the
morning trading. On Tuesday, the average rose 235.46 points, or
1.52 percent.
	   The dollar had gained steadily against the yen in recent weeks
as investors shifted more and more funds out of Japan's lagging
markets and into the robust U.S. economy.
	   Concerns about the Japanese economy drove the dollar to a
seven-year high of 141.35 yen on Tuesday.
	   Such concerns also weighed on stock prices, offsetting optimism
the stronger dollar would boost the earnings of Japan's exporters.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section fell 5.70 points, or 0.47 percent, to 1,202.98. The
TOPIX closed up 10.32 points, or 0.86 percent, the day before.
	   Analysts said foreign investors will likely keep selling their
Japanese holdings, if the yen keeps weakening. That's because a
weaker yen erodes the dollar value of Japanese stocks.
	   ``The weak yen is good for exporters, but our concern is that it
will hurt the sentiment of foreign investors,'' said Tsuyoshi
Nomaguchi, a strategist at Daiwa Securities Co.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond stood at 1.210 percent, unchanged from Tuesday's
finish. Its price was marginally lower at 111.95 yen, down from
111.96 yen.
 &UR; (mef-km-dj) 	   
</TEXT>
