<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-World Cup-Party Time,0894 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Parisians catch the spirit at ``Festival of Soccer''
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By MORT ROSENBLUM &QC; 
 &UR; AP Special Correspondent &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Four jolly giants _ an African, American Indian, an
Asian and a European _ strode through Paris like good-guy Godzillas
on Tuesday, symbolizing the spirit of a World Cup that France hopes
will loom large in history.
	   Blaring ethno-techno music and escorted by 4,500 costumed
extras, the 18-meter (60-foot) robots took separate routes toward
the Place de la Concorde, the heart of a citywide tournament
kickoff party.
	   ``We want to show that football is accessible to everyone and
belongs to no one,'' said Jean-Pascal Levy-Trumet, who designed the
``Fete du Football'' show. ``The grand theme is universality in a
single world.''
	   As crowds watched the pageant end, however, several hundred
soccer fans hurled bottles at police on the Champs Elysees,
provoking an angry response from riot troops.
	   The fans fled, chased by police firing tear gas, and no arrests
were immediately reported.
	   Parisians awoke Tuesday to find the dozing giants at familiar
monuments, along with throngs of strangely dressed tourists from
the 31 nations joining France in the planet's biggest sports
tournament.
	   Moussa, the African, was the first to stir in the evening, near
the Eiffel Tower, standing up and opening huge eyes to wild
applause.
	   He symbolized man in a new world, and he rose up to see dancing
odd-shaped baobab trees and termite hills. Six ostriches _ actually
men on stilts _ bobbed among women dressed as stylized giraffes.
	   ``Amazing,'' said Florence Farriaux, as she hurried her three
kids home so their father could take them to Concorde, where Moussa
would meet the three others. ``I loved it.''
	   On the Pont Neuf over the Seine, Ho, the Asian, stood up in a
fantasy world of balloons shaped like flying fish and dancers
dressed as tropical sea creatures.
	   Pablo, the Indian, rose from a crouch under the Arc de Triomphe
and strolled down the Champs-Elysees to see the animated trees,
snakes and bugs that depict nature.
	   Romeo, the European, had been snoozing outside the Opera
Garnier. His theme was love, and along his route he bowed to a
sculptor's conception of the Urban Woman, a mere 4.5 meters (15
feet) tall.
	   David Quill, a Scottish engineer who came for no-nonsense
football, found himself carried away by the spectacle. ``This
brings together the four worlds,'' he said. ``I really liked it.''
	   As dark fell, the four giants met at the Concorde around the
famed Obelisk from ancient Egypt, which had been transformed into a
towering replica of the World Cup, topped by video screens.
	   At their feet, in a swirl of color, danced the full range of
costumed escorts, from ladies in body-length white wooden wigs to
silver-clad creatures that looked like Ninja aardvarks.
	   The vast plaza was jammed with fascinated Frenchmen and soccer
tourists. But at the edge, a cluster of Scottish fans, already
staggering drunk, hardly seemed to notice the show.
	   Heavy overnight rains had not dampened the mood, but they washed
off Ho's loincloth, made of rubberized-plastic, exposing the
midriff of his articulated steel skeleton. Workmen pinned it back
on.
	   The 38-ton giants were powered by small trucks hidden in their
feet. They moved one after the other, as if the giants were
walking. Huge heads moved, eyes rolled, and fingers wiggled.
	   During the day, Parisians paid less attention to the four
colossi than the real characters in their midst. Clusters of soccer
fans roamed the streets in outlandish outfits and gaudy colors.
	   For once, passersby paid more attention to skirts on men rather
than women. Perhaps 20,000 Scots came across the Channel for the
opening game with Brazil on Wednesday. Most wore kilts.
	   Scott Wallace, a fishmonger, and his housepainter friend, Gerry
Shiels, sat behind tankards of lager at the Cafe Montecristo, each
with bare knees and Highland feathers towering above their hats.
	   ``I think we'll beat 'em, 2-1,'' Wallace said, a little
hopefully. ``Aye,'' Shiels agreed. ``And if we do, it'll be some
party.''
	   From the looks of things Tuesday, there'll be some party,
anyway.
	   Still, an Air France strike and soccer ticket foulups have left
many fans furious.
	   Crowds pushed their way into the France 98 shop to buy World Cup
paraphernalia: polyster T-shirts, caps, crowd-parting cologne,
fuzzy stuffed versions of the goofy-looking rooster mascot named
Footix.
	   Visitors seemed to show more interest than the French. Jacques
Lambert, head of the organizing committee, complained of an evident
lack of fervor among the general public.
	   A block off the Champs-Elysees, Emmannuel Delhomme painted a
banner on the awning of his bookshop, the Livre Sterling: ``Good
news, ladies. This store will be open during all of the games of
the World Cup.''
	   Delhomme, no soccer fan, said he was a little wary of the
snarled traffic, the armed police and boisterous visitors.
	   ``But, after all,'' he concluded, ``it's a good thing. Parisians
are so sad, so stressed, and this is a change. All these people in
colors and a happy mood. It is something new to talk about.''
</TEXT>
