<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Opera House Eyesore </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government won't pay to remove Sydney's eyesore building, says
</HEADLINE>
Howard
 &UR; AP Photo available &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Prime Minister John Howard said
Wednesday he despises the building that eclipses the Sydney Opera
House as much as anyone else but ruled out paying for it to be torn
down.
	   Public outrage has been growing over the structure, a more than
230-room apartment building at Sydney's Circular Quay, culminating
in calls for it to be razed before it is ever occupied.
	   The building has been dubbed ``The Toaster'' by expatriate
historian and art critic Robert Hughes because of its blocky, glass
and steel facade.
	   It is the first of three buildings planned for the eastern side
of the Quay, the site of the first British landing in 1788 and a
popular tourist stop.
	   The source of most ire is that the building blocks the view of
the Sydney Opera House, one of the city's most famous landmarks and
recently listed by Time magazine as one of the top architectural
achievements of the century.
	   Hughes, the art critic for Time, has led calls for the
building's destruction.
	   Howard said Wednesday he could not justify using government
money from the U.S. dlrs 590 million (Australian dollars 1 billion)
Federation Fund to buy the building.
	   ``As a citizen of Sydney I'd like to see it disappear, but I've
got to ask myself should I really divert money that I could
otherwise spend on facilities for people in need,'' Howard told
Australian Broadcasting Corp. radio.
	   ``I just don't think I can justify switching funds from those
sorts of things.''
	   He blamed city and New South Wales state officials for granting
planning approval for the development, which he agreed was ugly.
	   The New South Wales government has estimated it would cost about
U.S. dlrs 118 (Australian dollars 200 million) to demolish the
building and buy back the land from its Hong Kong owners. 	   
</TEXT>
