r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-China-Technology     06-09 0237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Technology </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China announces plan to promote science, technology and education
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Premier Zhu Rongji has set up a group to plan
China's strategy for developing science, technology and education _
fields seen as crucial to the country's economic development,
state-run media reported Wednesday.
	   The government plans to pour more money into science and
research that can help promote development, the Xinhua News Agency
quoted Zhu as saying.
	   ``We must work out an overall plan for development of science,
technology and education in tandem with the growth of the national
economy,'' Zhu said at the first meeting of the group, which is
also led by vice premier Li Lanqing.
	   China's current generation of leaders, most of whom have a
background in engineering, say the country must boost technology if
it is to compete in world markets.
	   During the first three decades after the Communists took power
in 1949, political campaigns and central planning caused China to
fall far behind other industrialized countries in many areas.
	   Antiquated equipment and production technology are seen as major
reasons for the inability of most state-owned enterprises to
achieve profitability.
	   Premier Zhu, who took office in March, and other top leaders
hope to make up for lost time by investing more in education and
research and by attracting more high-tech foreign investment. 	   
</TEXT>
